<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE DAZZLED BY PHLLIES, WITH SCHILLING NEXT
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Sweat listened on every face and arm at Veterans
Stadium Monday night, but the heat seemed to have a special effect
on the Yankees. They played most of the game as if they had been
locked in a sauna for half the day, and they are in jeopardy of
getting kicked in the teeth by the Phillies this week.
</P>
<P>
   The hustling, scrappy Phillies survived a ninth-inning rally to
win the first game of the three-game interleague series, 6-5, with
a favorable pitching match-up for Philadelphia to come Tuesday.
Paul Byrd, a former Met who has perfected his ability to change
speeds, pitched eight strong innings in the humid 92 degrees and
improved his record to 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, called a team meeting after the
game and noted how the Phillies had thoroughly beaten them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it to us, they played us off the field,'' Torre told
reporters. ``They were very confident and we were flat-footed.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Derek Jeter: ``We didn't really step it up until the ninth
inning. We've got to play hard for nine innings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went 2 for 13 with runners in scoring position and
for the second consecutive day, they missed a chance to move into
first place in the American League East. The Yankees are 32-23, a
half-game behind the Boston Red Sox who lost in Montreal Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling, who ranks among the National League leaders in
almost every significant pitching category, spent much of Monday
afternoon studying videotape of the Yankees, giving off the
distinct impression that he is more than serious about his start
Tuesday night. Schilling's opponent will be Hideki Irabu, who has
been more baffling to his manager and coaches than to the hitters
he faces.
</P>
<P>
   At only one juncture before the ninth inning of tonight's game
did it seem as if the Yankees were the predators, rather than those
preyed upon, and a baserunning gaffe cost them a chance for a run.
Joe Girardi was on third base and Chuck Knoblauch on first with two
out in the sixth inning, Yankees trailing 2-0, and Jeter hooked a
ground ball down the third base line, the ball bounding past the
bag and toward the left field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi scored easily, while the left fielder Ron Gant moved
toward the corner, assuming the ball would roll there. But it
turned and bounced off the facing of the stands, rolling back
toward the infield, away from Gant, and in Torre's mind, Knoblauch
should have at least had a chance to race home and tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch had slowed as he rounded second and eased into
third, believing he had no chance to score. ``I guess I made a
mistake,'' said Knoblauch, ``by using my own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill grounded out to end the Yankees' rally, and on the
very first pitch thrown in the bottom of the sixth by Andy Pettitte
after that discouraging sequence, Scott Rolen smashed a home run _
a devastating 1-2 punch.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees closed to 3-2, but Jason Grimsley allowed five walks
and three runs over the next two innings, his last pitch going all
the way to the backstop on the fly, and as the ninth inning
started, Philadelphia led, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Gomes, who took over for Byrd, walked three batters,
Rolen made an error, a passed ball scored a run and O'Neill hit a
run-scoring single with two out. Bernie Williams then batted with
runners at first and second and a chance to give the Yankees a
lead. But Williams grounded into a game-ending force at second
base.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Torre had said the Yankees would not experience
a let down after the weekend series with the Mets. But then he
watched Philadelphia take it to the Yankees. The Phillies are young
and athletic and play hard, and there were moments when the Yankees
looked as if they were merely foils for a Philadelphia exhibition;
the Washington Generals for the Harlem Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   One came after Jeter smacked a one-out triple in the fourth
inning. O'Neill chopped a ground ball to third and Jeter broke for
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rolen gloved the ball, threw homeward, and Jeter stopped about
40 feet short of the plate, intent on getting himself into a
rundown and allowing O'Neill to reach second base. Mike Lieberthal,
the Philadelphia catcher, charged up the third base line with the
ball in hand, operating the rundown expertly. When Jeter headed
back to third, Lieberthal zipped a throw to Rolen, who had come
down the line to close the gap on Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' third baseman slapped a tag on Jeter, whirled and
fired to second, where Kevin Jordan dropped his glove on the
sliding O'Neill. Double play, end of rally, end of inning, so crisp
that it should have been accompanied by ``Sweet Georgia Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Yankees did let down, Torre mused afterward. ``They
beat us, and they beat us soundly,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
