<SLUG> BC-BBO-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRO RISKS ARE IGNORED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Now we know why Mark McGwire cries at press
conferences and crusades on behalf of abused children. It's the
androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   A scientific study conducted by researchers at Iowa State
concluded the controversial weight-training supplement favored by
McGwire leads to higher levels in the blood of the female hormone
estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, if it were only that increased levels of estrogen in men
produced no side effect worse than an uncontrollable urge to shout
directions from the backseat or, in McGwire's case, a compulsion to
ask every opposing batter who reaches first base, ``Do you think
these pants make me look fat?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, higher levels of estrogen in men can increase the risk
of heart disease and pancreatic cancer and decrease their store of
HDL, or ``good'' cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   That was the conclusion drawn by the Iowa State researchers at
the end of their eight-week study of 19 men. Their results were
published last week in the ``Journal of the American Medical
Association.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, their sampling is as small as the strike zone. It
wouldn't shock us if any given major-league organization has that
many players taking andro. These days, you buy into ``The Natural''
at your naivete's own peril.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire isn't the only user, just the only one careless enough
to keep a bottle of the stuff in his locker where a reporter could
see it.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the criticism McGwire has had to field (including in
this space), we'd be surprised if any other andro users in the
major leagues step forward. They might be foolish, but they're not
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   They're also perfectly free to use the stuff. That's because
major-league baseball, which is in the process of conducting its
own research on the substance, hasn't followed the lead of the IOC,
the NFL and the NCAA in banning andro.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Nutrition Business Journal'' has estimated that 80,000
people tried andro in 1998, many of them no doubt drawn to it after
getting an eyeful of McGwire's bulging biceps and Herculean home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusions drawn from one laboratory in America's heartland
aren't going to sway the muscle-bound believers. If you think
otherwise, we've got a beauty pill we'd like to sell you.
</P>
<P>
   Angels outfielder Tim Salmon spoke the plain, sad truth over the
weekend when he said, ``There's always going to be people out there
doing things at all costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Players blinded by ambition aren't likely to see the health
risks. Football player Lyle Alzado spread the message that steroids
kill, and countless others have taken up his drumbeat since
Alzado's death in 1992. And yet, Salmon said, ``I can remember
talking to guys in the minor leagues who said, `If taking steroids
guarantees I'll get to the big leagues, I'll do it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If ballplayers are inclined to use steroids, which are illegal,
what's to stop them from taking andro, which is not? Probably
nothing short of a death or a few deaths. If that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it this way,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros said.
``If somebody is willing to take that risk in the first place, I
would imagine studies that show that it may be harmful aren't going
to have much of an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a point.
</P>
<P>
   There are caveats posted about tobacco in both clubhouses at
Dodger Stadium. On Friday we walked into the visiting clubhouse and
there it was, plain for all to see. A sign that read, ``Due to the
increased health risks, tobacco products (cigarettes, chew and dip)
will not be available.''
</P>
<P>
   A few yards away, Angels slugger Mo Vaughn was reaching for his
smokeless tobacco. Never mind all the former chew and dip users _
ex-Dodger Brett Butler among them _ who have battled throat cancer,
Vaughn can't step into the batter's box without the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to have something in my mouth when I swing,'' Vaughn
said. ``Otherwise I grind my teeth. Bubble gum? I've tried it.
Doesn't work. I bite my tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, we bit ours. Vaughn, who has endured many a lecture by
the likes of ex-catcher and anti-chew propagandist Joe Garagiola,
shrugged as if to say, ``I know, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Vaughn said. ``I only chew during the season.
And I'm always getting my mouth checked out. As long as the doctor
tells me I'm OK, I don't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Skyrocketing salaries and swollen ERAs? Double-digit scores?
Pete Rose's status? If today's players aren't careful, those things
might turn out to be the least of baseball's concerns. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
