<HEADER>
A6766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-08 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was a time when he could have gloated. A night when the Junkyard
Dog could have barked at all of the names and faces he had left
behind in Houston, when he could have chewed on leftover grudges
like they were an old bone.
</P>
<P>
   While the high-profile, big-name Rockets are nothing but a
long-forgotten playoff memory, Mario Elie is heading back to the
NBA Finals with the San Antonio Spurs. But instead of a sneer,
there was a smile. In the place of anger and ill feelings, there
was forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to come to terms with what happened in the past,''
Elie said in the aftermath of the Spurs' Western Conference finals
sweep of the Portland Trail Blazers. ``I've got to let all of that
stuff go now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some great years in Houston, some great experiences, and
I can't let the way it all ended ruin those memories.''
</P>
<P>
   You see him on the court _ his expressive face always speaking
louder than even the virtually nonstop barrage of words that comes
out of his mouth _ and he looks like the same scrappy, fearless
competitor who helped make up the guts of those two Rockets
championship teams in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But talk to him away from the games these days, and he is
different. Aged. Changed. Grown to realize that carrying a grudge
is a burden that can weigh a man down and make for an unfulfilling
present.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to leave Houston, I'll admit that,'' he said.
``I felt like I was a big part of the things we accomplished, and
after going there and finding a home, I didn't want to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems I had at the end all came from when they tried to
make me part of that trade to Toronto for (Damon) Stoudamire. I
have always told myself through all my years of trying to make it
in the NBA that I realized the game was actually just a business,
that business-type decisions had to be made, and you just had to
live with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when that trade situation came around, I'll admit that I
forgot all that, and I took it personally. I didn't handle it well.
I didn't handle myself the way I should have. Now that I look back
on it, my own attitude was the thing that made me bitter and left
me with a bad taste about those final few months last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blessed to have a chance to play with the Houston
Rockets, and I want to thank Rudy (Tomjanovich) and the coaching
staff for helping me with my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know that I was wrong about the way I left. I shouldn't
have let it all build up inside and make me so angry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a hurt that festered throughout the longer-than-usual
offseason and a grudge he carried with him to his new team in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   There is little coincidence that Elie chose his moment just
prior to the Spurs' March 2 game in Houston, when San Antonio was
struggling with a 6-8 record, to stand up in the locker room and
tell his teammates that he expected more out of each of them.
</P>
<P>
   And there was no hiding the vengeful spirit that erupted from
him April 18 at the Alamodome when the Spurs rallied from 23 points
down and scored an emotional 86-83 victory over the Rockets on
Elie's dagger-in-the-heart 3-pointer just ahead of the final
buzzer. He pointed at the Rockets. He taunted them. He shouted in
the TV cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was like the volcano finally erupting,'' Elie said.
``When I hit that shot, when I won that game, that was all of the
emotion and disappointment and the anger about what happened coming
out. I did feel a real sense of accomplishment. It was a statement
that I had been wanting to make all season long.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when that game was over, I kind of got a new outlook on
things. It was like the pressure was off, and it was time for me to
let go of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   His role with the Spurs is no different than it was with the
Rockets. He is the last offensive option on a team that has so many
of them, and he scored just two points in the Game 4 clincher at
Portland. He is in the game to clamp on the defense like a bear
trap, and he kept the Blazers' explosive Isaiah Rider from ever
going off in the series.
</P>
<P>
   He was brought into the Spurs' locker room to provide a spark, a
ferocity that always had been lacking in this team. He was
recruited to San Antonio by Avery Johnson, another mile-a-minute
mouth who wanted help in pushing and prodding the other Spurs to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to Mario,'' said David Robinson. ``He's been there.
He helps us.''
</P>
<P>
   As they have helped him come to grips with the past.
</P>
<P>
   Two championship rings with the Rockets and a different kind of
ring with fiance Gina Gaston in Houston. Now a third trip to the
NBA Finals in San Antonio. And a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no reason to be mad at anybody,'' said Mario Elie.
``Texas has been good to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
