</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS EVEN SERIES WITH A 90-78 VICTORY OVER KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Knicks' pocket of miracles was empty as the
Indiana Pacers left nothing to chance by taking over Monday night's
game early and keeping their edge to the end of a 90-78 victory in
Game 4 of the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers tied the four-of-seven-game series, 2-2, and will
play the Knicks in Game 5 on Wednesday night in Indianapolis. It
was not the outcome the Knicks had hoped for when Latrell Sprewell
was given the start.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to score in the halfcourt around the likes of Chris
Mullin and Jalen Rose, Sprewell finished his first start of the
playoffs with 12 points. Sprewell was not the only starter to fade
into the background as Game 3's miracle worker, Larry Johnson,
finished with 11 points and hit just 1 of 7 from 3-point range.
Marcus Camby led the Knicks with 18 points and had 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither Rik Smits nor Reggie Miller scored in the first
half, the Pacers rode the edge of Mullin, Antonio Davis and Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Rose had 19 points, Mullin 18 and Davis 16 coming off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers shot 50 percent to the Knicks' 41 percent and made 22
of 30 free throws to the Knicks' 9 of 14.
</P>
<P>
   There were only a few minutes of uncertainty in this game. The
Pacers took a 14-point lead as the Knicks imploded at the hands of
tentative shot-taking by Johnson and the shocking inability of
Sprewell to win his matchup with Mullin. But as the Knicks have
done all season, they did not give in to a Pacers team that was
winning with its bench play.
</P>
<P>
   Camby shrugged off whatever rough treatment he was receiving
during the game and came up with a steal at midcourt on a Mark
Jackson pass and turned it into a soaring, one-handed dunk to pull
the Knicks within 7, 71-64, with 7 minutes 23 seconds left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point, the Knicks were just able to trade baskets
with a Pacers team that took every punch Chris Childs delivered _
as he drove on Mark Jackson for two consecutive layups _ and
returned the favor with firm reactions. Rose came up with a wild
running layup with 4:28 left and drew a foul for a 3-point play to
put the Pacers up by 81-70.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed unthinkable for the Pacers to grab a 45-32 lead at the
break without either Smits or Miller scoring in the first half.
Smits had two fouls in the first 30 seconds and immediately
retreated to the bench for the rest of the half. Miller, who was
also called for two quick fouls, played a quiet 11 minutes and was
0 for 3 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   In stepped the Pacers' role players to provide the kind of depth
the Knicks have no answer for without the injured Patrick Ewing.
Reserves like Rose and Antonio Davis _ even Fred Hoiberg _ came off
the bench and supplied a total of 24 points, overwhelming any
lineup the Knicks had to offer.
</P>
<P>
   That included a starting lineup with Sprewell. Coach Jeff Van
Gundy's experiment did not work well in the first half. Close to
the time he would have normally come into the game off the bench,
Sprewell was leaving the floor with two fouls and 6:41 left in the
first quarter. He finished the first half 3 for 11, part of a
Knicks starting lineup that was 6 for 22 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took a deep breath in the locker room and opened the
third quarter with an ounce more determination. Allen Houston and
Sprewell began to force the action and take the ball to the basket,
and the Knicks cut the Pacers' lead to 8 points in the first four
minutes of the third. The Pacers did not get flustered and found
Miller for a 3-pointer, then Mullin came up with a jumper to give
them a 55-42 lead with 6:47 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake-prone Knicks then came up with a doozy when Charlie
Ward fouled Mullin on a 3-point attempt. Mullin made all three free
throws. Three minutes later, Johnson did the same thing to Miller,
who hit two of three free throws to put the Pacers up by a healthy
62-49.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were melting down at this point, countering their
good plays with mindless mistakes. Sprewell was the ringleader of
this by allowing Mullin, his former teammate from Golden State, to
fluster him on the defensive end and then beat him on the offensive
end. The Knicks were better off without him and went on an 11-6 run
to close within 9, 66-57, when the third quarter ended.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Sprewell was too eager in his first playoff start, too
pumped up by the introduction at the Garden. Out of control,
Sprewell was unable to slip around a slow but crafty Mullin, who
was winning a matchup that was expected to be in the Knicks' favor.
Sprewell was unable to break the Pacers' defensive code in the
halfcourt before halftime. His few successes came on the fast
breaks, which were kept to a minimum by a Pacers team that got back
quickly to defend. The plan was to beat the Pacers with the Knicks'
small but quick lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing went according to plan for the Knicks in the first
half. Johnson, the hero of Game 3 with his 4-point play, was
tentative with every move into the paint, fumbling the ball and
passing up open looks from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' guards were no help, either. Houston, who was faced
with chasing Miller and then forced to guard Rose, was frayed
around the edges as he shot 1 for 4. Together, Sprewell, Houston
and Johnson were 6 for 19 in the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
