<HEADER>
A6772 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-WATERSUPPLY-COX     06-08 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WATERSUPPLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $100 million buys supply for growing population
 &HT;    By Chuck Lindell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The City of Austin and the Lower Colorado River
Authority will announce today a $100 million water agreement that
would provide a drought-proof supply for the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   For a city that has suffered two destructive dry spells in the
past three years, that guarantee carries a lot of weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a turning point in Austin's history,'' Mayor Kirk
Watson said. ``The strength of our economy and the strength of our
quality of life are going to be based on the supply of water.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's agreement in principle would ensure Austin's water
supply _ even during a repeat of the decade-long drought of the
1950s _ as the city's population doubles to an estimated 1.6
million by 2050.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot of money, but it's a lot of water guaranteed for
a long time,'' said Mark Rose, LCRA general manager.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for the $100 million deal, water rates would rise 10
percent by 2006, adding $28 a year to the average residential
customer's bill. Expect a 4 percent increase next year, followed by
smaller rises in following years.
</P>
<P>
   Austin will get a 30 percent discount on its water by paying for
it in advance _ $25 million the first year, followed by annual
payments of $6 million to $7 million over the next 20 to 30 years.
The payment schedule must be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The savings amount to almost $40 million over the life of the
contract, said Randy Goss, head of Austin's water utility.
</P>
<P>
   What else does Austin get for its $100 million?
</P>
<P>
   _The city will boost its water supply by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is entitled to 250,000 acre feet of Colorado River water
a year, or about 81.5 billion gallons, enough to last until the
mid-2030s. The new contract would add 75,000 acre feet, enough to
serve 375,000 a year while extending the city's supply to 2050.
</P>
<P>
   _Austin won't need to dip into that extra 75,000 acre feet until
the mid-2030s, but by reserving the water now, Austin is assured
that no other city or industry will swoop in to reserve the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to sell the water to anybody who asks for it,'' said
Paul Thornhill, engineering manager for the LCRA's water division.
``Once it's reserved, we can't sell it.''
</P>
<P>
   _The city will extend its contract with the LCRA until 2050,
with the option of deciding whether to extend its terms another 50
years. Austin's current contract with the LCRA can be voided by
either party as early as 2023.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement _ a memo of understanding reached after 10 months
of negotiation _ may be signed as early as today by Austin City
Manager Jesus Garza.
</P>
<P>
   Final details will be negotiated over the summer, and city staff
hopes to have a contract ready for City Council approval in August.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the memo of understanding will be circulated
among the city's boards and commissions. Presentations also will be
made to neighborhood associations and other interested groups.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract will replace a 1987 agreement that was part of
a hard-fought water-rights settlement among the City of Austin,
LCRA and state water officials.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gave Austin the right to pump 250,000 acre feet a
year from the Colorado River _ the first 150,000 acre feet for
free, the rest at the LCRA's fee of $105 per acre foot.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the agreement has favored Austin. After all, the city
doesn't expect to cross the 150,000-acre-foot threshold for another
two or three years, providing almost 15 years of free water.
</P>
<P>
   But with time, the 1987 deal began to look shaky from Austin's
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is a clause that enables either the city or the LCRA
to void the contract as early as 2023 _ a situation that would
leave Austin in a predicament. Without the LCRA's water stored in
the Highland Lakes, Austin would run short during the dry years.
</P>
<P>
   That's because all of Austin's water rights are ``run of river''
rights _ meaning the city can pump water that would normally be
flowing down the Colorado River. During dry spells, the normal flow
of the Colorado doesn't come close to providing enough water to
quench Austin's thirst for green lawns, swimming pools and clean
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Without water stored behind the Highland Lakes dams, for
example, Austin would have fallen almost 33 percent short on water
during the 1996 drought, Goss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this historic agreement . . . there could be times of
the year, especially under drought conditions, when Austin would
have little or no ability to take water out of the river,'' Rose
said. ``That is not a good circumstance for anyone in Central
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed agreement and extension option, Austin could
ensure access to Highland Lakes water until the 22nd century.
</P>
<P>
   The city also would keep its annual right to pump 150,000 acre
feet for free but will pay the going rate _ $105 per acre foot _
for the next 51,000 acre feet. That water will cost about $36
million and is projected to last until 2021, after which Austin
will pay whatever water fee the LCRA is charging at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Austin also will pay about $64 million to reserve its additional
75,000 acre feet of water in the Highland Lakes. The normal
reservation fee would be $104 million over 50 years, but the LCRA
offered a discount to cement the deal and because Austin will
prepay in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The LCRA will spend the money to modernize its dams, improve its
flood-warning system and to pay for newly purchased water rights _
avoiding debt and saving on interest payments, Thornhill said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also would allow the LCRA to avoid a planned
increase in water rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for Highland Lakes water, frozen at $105 per acre foot
since 1992, are due to rise 5 percent annually for the next four
years to pay for this year's $75 million purchase of the Garwood
Irrigation Co.'s water rights.
</P>
<P>
   If a final contract is worked out, the LCRA can delay rate
increases for at least four years, Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin plans to pay its first $25 million installment with money
from water-wastewater department projects that came in under budget
or were delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The $6 million to $7 million annual payments will be paid from
rate increases, Goss said.
</P>
<P>
   The city's memo of understanding will allow the LCRA to create a
``water bank'' to sell Austin's unused water in short-term
contracts. Austin, which must approve the sales, would be repaid
with future water or money.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides also agreed to negotiate provisions that would allow
Austin to scale back the contract if growth demands fall short.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a new contract providing 325,000 acre feet of water a
year, Austin will still fall 25,000 to 35,000 acre feet short of
its needs in 2050.
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to make up for the shortfall with an aggressive
campaign to encourage conservation and use treated wastewater for
irrigation. To meet its goals, Austin will have to almost triple
the amount of water it currently saves through conservation (4,250
acre feet per year) and reused wastewater (6,500 acre feet).
</P>
<P>
   Though ambitious, Goss believes the city can turn reused
wastewater into a third city utility that provides water to local
golf courses and other irrigators.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas include stepped-up rebates for water-saving devices,
such as underground watering hoses that reduce evaporation.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Lindell writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
