<HEADER>
A6774 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-RICE-CWS-HNS &LR;      06-08 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-RICE-CWS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The question drew a belly laugh from Rice baseball coach Wayne
Graham.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would the Owls consider forfeiting their first game in the
College World Series against Miami on Friday so they could begin
their mental preparation for winning the tournament through the
losers bracket?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Graham said after he recovered. ``We've been behind the
eight ball long enough. I'd like to get out from behind it and feel
what that is like.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the question wasn't serious, it wasn't all that absurd.
Rice lost its first game in the double-elimination NCAA regional in
Lubbock and had to win four games in the losers bracket to move on.
Then, after dropping the first contest in their best-of-three super
regional against Southwestern Louisiana at the Astrodome, the Owls
won two games in a row to advance to the College World Series for
the second time in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls were eliminated in two games in their previous CWS trip
in 1997. But Graham believes Rice's return to Omaha is going to be
special for his program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have a feeling that you belong when you go your
second time,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls had hoped to play at 12:30 p.m. Saturday in the game to
be telecast by CBS. But network officials chose the Texas
A&AMP;M-Florida State game for that slot, ostensibly because the large
state schools have more public recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee went with what CBS selected,'' said NCAA
Division I Baseball Committee chairman Dick Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   The first CWS gme pairs Alabama and Oklahoma State at 2:30 p.m.
Friday. Rice and Miami follow at 6:30 p.m. in a game to be telecast
by ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State and A&AMP;M open the second day of action, with Cal
State Fullerton taking on Stanford at 7 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The four teams playing Friday will be in one bracket, playing a
double-elimination tournament among themselves to determine a
winner. The same goes for the four teams that begin play Saturday.
The winner of each bracket will then play a winner-take-all CWS
championship game June 19.
</P>
<P>
   As Rockwell noted, the committee seeded the invitees before the
64-team NCAA tournament field was announced, and seven of the top
eight seeds made it to the CWS. Oklahoma State's defeat of Baylor
prevented the Omaha field from containing all of the top-seeded
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically are patting ourselves on the back,'' Rockwell
said. ``Any time you can seed at the beginning and get seven of
eight, we think we did a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said the feedback resulting from the new 64-team format
has been mostly positive. The only negative has dealt with the fact
that some teams within the same conference had to meet in super
regionals. But with the NCAA's commitment to placing teams in
geographic proximity, it might not be helped, Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some (things to consider), but I don't think there
will be any serious tinkering,'' he said of the regional/super
regional format, which replaced the 48-team tournament that put six
teams in eight regionals. ``I think we have a foundation to improve
college baseball. It proved that all the criteria we used _
including the RPI _ worked. I think it's something that we will
continue to build on for the betterment of college baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's seedings went against the college baseball
polls. Miami was seeded No. 1 by the NCAA committee and Rice was
seeded No. 8, based on the Ratings Percentage Index. The RPI takes
into account a team's record, opponents and record of opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Before last week, Rice was No. 1 in the Baseball America poll.
The Owls fell to No. 4 this week after losing one of their super
regional games. Rice is No. 1 and Miami No. 2 in the Baseball
Weekly/ESPN poll, which was not updated this week. Miami remained
No. 1 in the Collegiate Baseball poll, with Rice No. 2, as it was
before the super regionals.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said the Owls can compete with anyone in the CWS,
regardless of ranking or RPI, because of their depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are solid enough and mature enough to have a shot
at anyone we play,'' Graham said. ``What gives me real hope is the
way we competed with the bat this weekend (against Southwestern
Louisiana). We are not going to face pitching that is much tougher
than what we faced this weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one thing Graham would like to rectify.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked Miami before the season started to win the national
championship,'' he said. ``They've got talent, but they've kind of
had an up-and-down year. I'll have to rethink my position. I think
we have a shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
