<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-08 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ It started with Joe Nieuwendyk. Pretty soon, Dave Reid was
getting into the act. Lately, Jamie Langenbrunner has been testing
the mettle of headline writers, and in Game 7 of the Western
Conference finals, it was Mike Keane who took center stage.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What, you might ask, of Mike Modano, Brett Hull or Jere
Lehtinen, three of Dallas' more celebrated Stars?
</P>
<P>
   They've been busy doing battle with the Peter Forsbergs, Joe
Sakics, Theo Fleurys and Claude Lemieuxs of the NHL world, matchups
in which just breaking even can be bigger than it seems. That, in
turn, has left plenty of room for other Stars to shine in these
playoffs, and none has taken better advantage of the situation than
Nieuwendyk, Reid and Langenbrunner, a second line that is putting
up statistics worthy of a No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been a plus for our team all year,'' said winger Pat
Verbeek as the Stars got ready for Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals
at 7 tonight at Reunion Arena. ``We really rely on our depth, and
we count on other people to score.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``other people'' have done just that, which is a major
reason Dallas is just four wins away from claiming hockey's most
coveted prize.
</P>
<P>
   Through 17 postseason games, Nieuwendyk has nine goals
(including a pair of game-winners in the Colorado series) and nine
assists. After watching most of the fun from the stands when he
suffered a severe knee injury in the opening playoff game against
San Jose a year ago, the 32-year-old center has been an enormous
part of Dallas' Stanley Cup run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Missing out last year really hurt him and in the end hurt the
team because the depth was missing,'' Modano said. ``He's made up
for lost time.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Reid has managed his time pretty well, too. He
may have totaled just 17 points (six goals) in 73 regular-season
games, but eight points in 17 playoff outings have elevated his
profile considerably.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is in the playoffs,'' Reid said. ``The top
lines are going to wash each other out. It's important for
everybody else to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner, who won't turn 24 until next month, clearly got
the memo as well. Following a disappointing regular season in which
he scored only 12 times (in addition to 33 assists), he took over
Game 6 in Colorado with a pair of goals, then opened the scoring in
the decisive Game 7 on a picture-perfect feed from Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Langenbrunner has nine postseason goals, three of them
game-winners. And all this comes from a fellow who lit the lamp
only once in last year's playoffs, that one coming on something of
a fluke as a long slap shot was badly misplayed by Detroit's Chris
Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner realizes his work is hardly done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our line is going to be expected to contribute because of the
guys who check Mike's line,'' Langenbrunner said. ``We're going to
have to pick up the pace again.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Stars will be trying to pick up Peca, as in
Michael, the Buffalo star who likely will occupy much of Modano's
time. If Dallas can play the Sabres' top line to a draw, the hope
is that superior depth will favor the Stars as the series
progresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see,'' said Modano. ``It takes some of the heat
off us.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Colorado, those other lines helped wear out three-time
Stanley Cup-winning goalie Patrick Roy. Dallas now tries to find a
crack or two in the wall that is Dominik Hasek, the Buffalo goalie
who is allowing just 1.82 goals per outing in these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to outwork him,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``If you let a goalie discourage you, that's when you're in
trouble. You've got to outwork him.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Cup finally in sight, Dallas hopes to do just that.
Hitchcock would be perfectly happy to see a Modano or a Hull catch
fire and make these Finals his own, but more likely the heroics
will come from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the search began as the Stars and Sabres met the press
in the Star Club, adjacent to Reunion Arena. While the usual
suspects drew the customary attention, the Nieuwendyks, Keanes,
Langenbrunners and Brian Skrudlands found themselves surrounded by
tape recorders and minicams as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about the playoffs is that anyone can step up,''
said Keane. ``It seems like every night, there's a new hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The Strs look for four more to answer the call. At this point,
they aren't particular about whom they might be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
