<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-08 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE SWINGMAN COMES OUT OF THE DOGHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Larry Bird was surrounded by reporters on Monday
morning. The buzz of the day was that Jeff Van Gundy, the Knicks'
head coach, had scrapped a monthlong winning formula and elevated
Latrell Sprewell to the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   How would Bird counter? Would Bird counter at all?
</P>
<P>
   Larry Legend wasn't budging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into playing matchups with Jeff Van
Gundy,'' he said with just a hint of disdain. ``I don't want to get
into this chess match where if he makes a move, I've got to make a
move.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the move that Bird was forced to make may have
saved the day _ and the series _ for the Pacers. Earlier in the
morning, Bird learned that Travis Best, the backup point guard,
would miss Monday night's Game 4 at Madison Square Garden with a
pulled groin muscle. Suddenly, Bird, one of the great clutch
players of all time, had to put his faith and Pacer dreams on the
shoulders of Jalen Rose, the 6-foot-8-inch guard/forward who has
been in and out of Bird's doghouse this season. He is out now.
</P>
<P>
   Bird is wise enough to know that Rose is also the Pacers' most
versatile player in a series where versatility has become a
premium. So with 4 minutes 37 seconds left in the first quarter,
Reggie Miller disappearing _ once again _ Rose went in for Miller.
The spirit changed immediately. Rose hit a running jumper over
Allan Houston and then a tough twisting jumper over Houston, then
made a tough, in-your-face jumper over Houston at the buzzer. Not
only did Rose play the point but _ at various times in the half _
he also defended Marcus Camby, Houston and Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Rose ended the half with 10 points and 4 rebounds. More than any
statistics could show, Rose and Chris Mullin steadied the reeling
Pacers, refocused his team on the prize and inched closer to
securing Bird's trust.
</P>
<P>
   Rose finished with a team-high 19 points, and his 12th and 14th
were daggers. After Kurt Thomas pulled the Knicks within 69-62,
Rose hit a jumper for the left corner that silenced the crowd. Then
Camby brought the house down with a thundering dunk, Rose working
against Larry Johnson, a nasty jumper that that gave Indiana a
73-64 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rose wasn't finished. After Chris Childs pulled the Knicks
within 76-68, Rose, now handling the point duties, drove then
dished out to Miller who scored. The next time down the court, Rose
drove on Houston, scored off the glass and drew the foul. The
3-point play gave the Pacers an 81-70 lead and send fans to the
exits. Indiana would win, 90-78, tying the series at two games
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Trust comes a lot faster when a team's back is against the wall.
For the last three games, Rose has battled Sprewell and done what
few have been able to do: he forced turnovers, blocked shots and
generally made his good friend trip over himself.
</P>
<P>
   Rose and Sprewell became friends in 1993. They met when Chris
Webber, Rose's teammate at Michigan, was drafted by Golden State.
Sprewell had joined the Warriors a year earlier. ``I was out there
that whole summer working out with the team with Chris Mullin years
ago, so we've been friends since then,'' he recalled. Rose followed
Sprewell's career and the now fabled incident at Golden State when
he choked his coach, P.J. Carlesimo.
</P>
<P>
   Rose had his own problems with Larry Brown, then his coach at
Indiana. While the problems didn't lead to a physical
confrontation, they left Rose with the hard-to-clean ``attitude
problem'' label. While Sprewell played with ferocious abandon and
ultimately forced the coaching staff to put him in the starting
lineup, Rose has taken a more moderate approach to proving himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Latrell's drive, but I'm in a little different
position than he is,'' Rose said. ``I knew coming into the season
that we were going to do the same thing this season that we did
last season. Regardless of how I felt about it, regardless of any
improvement to my game or our team, I was prepared to deal with the
circumstances that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come in thinking that, regardless, I may find a way
to get them to change how they're doing things. I knew coming in
that was not going to happen. I'm going to go out and play my butt
off every night and whether it's for 20 minutes or for 48 minutes,
whatever they asked me to do, I made up my mind, coming into this
season, I was going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose was now walking to the Pacers' bus and saying how happy he
was for Sprewell's success. Later that night he would compete
furiously against his friend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rose said there was something neat about the way New York has
generally embraced Sprewell. For Rose, the embrace says something,
not simply about people liking a winner, but about the deeper
nature of the city that appreciates toughness, persistence and
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's about opportunity,'' he said. ``New York is like
Paris, a city where everybody's doing their own thing; it's not
revolving around one person or one place. This is a town of
fighters. This is a town where you can be a multimillionaire, but
you walk a mile to work. So they respect a fighter. Latrell comes
here, they see this guy who has a lot of people taking shots at him
and had his back up against the wall. He's shown them that he has
the fortitude.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before he climbed onto the bus Rose added: ``He's taken them to
the Eastern Conference finals. Now they embrace him. Spike Lee had
to take off his Ewing jersey and put on a Sprewell jersey.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Knick fans had nightmares about No. 5. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
