r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LAD     06-08 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WORD ON PARK'S STATUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers awaited word of right-hander Chan Ho
Park's eminent suspension Monday in vain. Such word never came.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers are anxious to hear from National League
president Leonard Coleman, not only so they'll know Park's status,
but also so they can plan their starting rotation for the next week
or so.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials said they're expecting Park to be suspended
for five to seven games. If that's the case, don't expect Park to
appeal the decision, several Dodgers officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule is set up in the favor of the Dodgers to handle the
suspension without a starter needing to pitch on short rest or
without needing to summon Jamie Arnold from the bullpen for a spot
start.
</P>
<P>
   Park's next turn to pitch would be Thursday, which is an off day
for the Dodgers. It would allow lefty Carlos Perez to open the
three-game series in Oakland on his normal four days rest and for
Ismael Valdes and Darren Dreifort to pitch on their regular rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also have off Monday, which would give the Dodgers
another round of starts before needing a fifth starter. If a
verdict was handed down today, the Dodgers wouldn't need a fifth
starter until June 19 against Philadelphia. The Dodgers would play
nine games by then.
</P>
<P>
   Park faces the suspension after getting into a fight with the
Angels' Tim Belcher on Saturday. After being tagged out by Belcher
along the first-base line, Park hit Belcher with a forearm to the
face and then bashed a charging Belcher with a flying scissors-kick
before the benches emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley OK: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said he's ready to
return from the wrist sprain that's forced him to miss the last
four games. He took batting practice before Monday's game and
didn't experiences any discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hundley is aware of manager Davey Johnson's style and
wouldn't be surprised if he was given today off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're ready to go, he gives you one more day,'' Hundley
said. ``I can handle it. I'm learning to go with the flow, to
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley sprained his left wrist Wednesday in Pittsburgh in a
collision at home plate. But the Dodgers throw Dreifort tonight
against the Texas Rangers, and the movement of his pitches figures
into Johnson's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught Perez's warm-ups (Sunday),'' Johnson said, ``but
that's not quite like catching Dreifort.''
</P>
<P>
   Draft signings: The Dodgers signed 11 of their 50 picks from
last week's amateur draft, including three of their top 10 and
seven of their first 15.
</P>
<P>
   Top pick Jason Repko, a shortstop from Hanford High in West
Richland, Wash., signed during the weekend. It included a $700,000
signing bonus. He was the 37th pick overall and will arrive in Vero
Beach, Fla., today for minicamp before heading to Great Falls
(Mont.) for rookie ball in the Pioneer League.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' fourth pick, shortstop Joe Thurston of Sacramento
City College, and their ninth pick, right-handed Jonathan Berry of
Newberry College, also signed.
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: During the weekend series with Anaheim, Johnson
returned to using Eric Young in the leadoff spot in place of Devon
White. The eight-game experiment of hitting Young second is over
for now. ``(Young) is the sparkplug,'' Johnson said. ``He's been
struggling a little bit, but it's what happens in this game. He's
our best leadoff guy, head and shoulders. Devo, it was a little
more strain on him to lead off. He's a little more comfortable down
in the lineup.''... Johnson was hired Oct. 23 to manage the
Dodgers, and at a get-together after Sunday's game he met Rupert
Murdoch, chairman and CEO of The News Corporation, the parent
company of the Fox Group, which owns the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
