<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO BOOS, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So now that the Knicks have surrendered the
home-court advantage they worked so hard to get, the only logical
assumption is that they have the Indiana Pacers right where they
want them: thinking they are going back home, in the clear.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the essence of this crazy, shortened season, hasn't
it? The Knicks making everyone believe they are about to go away,
and then reappearing, like Marcus Camby, flying from nowhere,
making people change their shot and next week's plans.
</P>
<P>
   That is what the pro basketball playoffs are about in a larger
sense, staying loose and flexible. Rethinking. Remapping.
Re-energizing, which is what the Pacers did on Monday night,
bumping and grinding their way back into the Eastern Conference
final with a 90-78 victory at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers knew they were one defeat from the unofficial
countdown to a New York-San Antonio championship series, and they
played with that kind of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mullin played like it was 1985, any old St. John's game on
the same Garden floor, finding too many seams in the Knicks'
defense. Reggie Miller didn't terrorize Spike Lee, or anyone else,
but he mustered enough second-half offense after an embarrassing
scoreless first half. Most of all the Pacers, as promised, made the
lane a far less friendly place.
</P>
<P>
   But come on. Boos for the Knicks as they walked off the floor
trailing by 45-32 at the half? Saturday night may as well have been
1973. It was so quickly forgotten that no rational soul in the area
had the remote notion one month ago that the Knicks might make the
finals. And contingencies are still being made.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, Michelle Musler, planned a lot of business for the
last two weeks of June and is scrambling around in the event her
presence in the first row behind the Knicks' bench is required.
Many news media outlets in the area are busily rearranging their
travel budgets. As for me, I've been looking forward to the
second-week matchups on the Wimbledon lawn, but what the heck, the
San Antonio Riverwalk is lovely and the burritos taste better than
strawberries and cream.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose this series, Camby, more than anyone, has become the
embodiment of the Knicks' evolution. The elasticity of his body,
the dancer's lightness with which he moves, gives the Knicks a
chance in this series as they depart for Indianapolis and Game 5 on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Grunfeld said he made the Charles Oakley trade to better
meet the athleticism of Indiana's Davises, Antonio and Dale. By
now, you know the whole convoluted saga, and even Dave Checketts
will have to admit soon that Grunfeld was right.
</P>
<P>
   After looking golden most of the season, it is Glen Grunwald,
not Grunfeld, who has to explain why the tall, young acrobat he
gave up on in Toronto is eliciting praises such as ``dominant'' and
``outstanding'' from Jeff Van Gundy, the coach who didn't want him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus was always a great talent,'' Grunwald, the Raptors'
general manager, said by telephone on Monday. ``His problems were
injuries and consistency. We needed veteran leadership, and that's
what we got. Marcus needed a chance to play in an environment that
would bring the best out in him. New York's a pressure cooker. You
burn up or turn into a diamond.''
</P>
<P>
   Toughened by a short season in our pro sports cauldron, Camby is
glistening in the national spotlight. But Grunwald said, ``I don't
regret the trade at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What else could he say? News media opinions are like a coach's
cliches, plentiful and disposable, but these men have careers on
the line. For the deposed Grunfeld, there is bitter irony in
Camby's becoming a major player in the 180-degree turnaround that
has saved Van Gundy. To put it in basketball terminology, Checketts
was in the process of taking a shot at Phil Jackson, but Camby
appeared from the weak side to swat it away.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was supposed to be in big trouble on Monday night, as
Larry Bird said the big, bad Davis boys were going to plant some
serious elbows in in his scrawny chest. Well, Camby wasn't the
dominant player he was Saturday night, but he didn't exactly run
for the exit, either. His hustle, in fact, got the Knicks and crowd
out of a third-quarter stupor, impassioned for the fourth. Not
enough shots fell this time.
</P>
<P>
   Please, though, no boos. The Knicks are not out of this, by any
means. They have won twice in Miami this playoff season, twice in
Atlanta. This has the look, smell and feel of seven games. Just
when you think these Knicks are done, they come back. Wingspan
travels. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
