<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER STILL ANGRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Pitcher Tim Belcher spoke to reporters Monday
for the first time since his fight Saturday with Dodgers pitcher
Chan Ho Park, who attempted a flying kick at Belcher, spikes and
all.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was still angry over the incident, and didn't think the
explanation that tae kwon do _ a form of martial arts _ is commonly
taught in Park's native Korea was a good excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy knows tae kwon do. So what?'' Belcher said. ``I like
to hunt, but I didn't take a shotgun. There's a time and place for
everything. If you get rolled by a thug on the street, and he tries
to steal your kid and beat your wife, whip out everything you've
got.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain unwritten rules on the baseball field that
he doesn't understand _ and he should. There are cultural
differences, and he might have that as a legitimate excuse. But if
he can be taught the language, he can be taught the customs.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher didn't talk about the incident Saturday or Sunday,
instead issuing a statement both days, because ``it makes better
sense to let something like that calm down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotation update: Although manager Terry Collins said before the
game he had not made a final decision, Belcher said he'd be able to
pitch Wednesday on three days rest.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is Omar Olivares' turn in the rotation, but he won't
be able to go because of a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who made only 81 pitches Saturday, said he doesn't need
to be held to a limited pitch count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't tell Terry I could go Wednesday if I wasn't going
to approach it like a normal start,'' Belcher said.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus honored: Third baseman Troy Glaus was named American
League co-Player of the Week (with the White Sox's Frank Thomas)
for the week of May 31-June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus had a league-high 22 total bases and hit .550 (11 for 20)
with three homers, two doubles and six RBI in six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key for me is to keep it simple,'' said Glaus, who
entered Monday's game hitting .258 with nine homers and 27 RBI.
``Just hit it and don't worry about where it goes. Put a nice pass
on it and whatever happens, happens. It's a matter of putting your
work in and knowing your swing is going to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Right fielder Todd Greene had to leave Monday's game in
the second inning with tightness in his right hamstring. Greene
doubled in the top of the second before being replaced by Orlando
Palmeiro in the bottom of the inning.... Ex-Angel J.T. Snow wasn't
in the Giants' starting lineup because the Angels threw lefty Chuck
Finley. Snow, formerly a switch hitter, bats only left-handed now
because he struggled hitting right-handed. Snow, though, has been
successful against the Angels in interleague play the past two
seasons, hitting .379 (11 for 29) with five homers and 12 RBI.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
