u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKN-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-08 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SHOULDN'T BE UPSETTING TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-RYAN COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Want to hear something ridiculous? The Knicks were
booed off the floor at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   OK, they were pretty bad in the first 24 minutes. They were down
by 13 at the half (45-32) and their offense was your basic chicken
excrement. But boos? After what this team has done for the fans and
the city in the past three weeks?
</P>
<P>
   We can really be a bad race of people sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem very likely is that the New York Knicks are now
burdened by absurdly unrealistic expectations. They arrived at
Monday night's Game 4 with the Pacers thanks, frankly, to some very
nice breaks. Does Allan Houston and Miami ring a bell? Does drawing
the pathetically impotent Atlanta Hawks in the next round ring a
bell? Does Larry Johnson making two gimme-a-break 3-pointers
earlier in the game and then getting an NBA-only ``continuation''
call to augment a 3-pointer at the end of Game 3 ring a bell?
</P>
<P>
   So what's the point? The point is that the Knicks are what the
Knicks are, which is a highly flawed team now playing without its
inspirational 7-foot leader. What the Knicks have done to get this
far is very laudable. Anything they do beyond this is gravy, icing,
you name it. Extra. A bonus. Unnerstan?
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks lost a 90-78 decision to the Pacers Monday night, and
in so doing they looked very bad. Perhaps I'm just an outside
cynic, but should anyone be surprised? Did anyone halfway
intelligent really think the Knicks were some wonder team?
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that the Pacers have got to be ecstatic heading
back home. They pulled even in the series after what could have
been a devastating loss Saturday. They could have pulled a Portland
and allowed one big play to ruin their season. They did not. Even
better, they won this big road game despite receiving a minimal
offensive contribution from Reggie Miller and a negligible
all-around contribution from Rik Smits. Want more? OK, they
rediscovered a valuable sixth man in Jalen Rose (19 points) and
welcomed back an offensive MIA in the person of Chris Mullin, who
scored 18 points in the first three games and 18 in the first 31
minutes of Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really ready for a breakout game,'' smiled Mullin, who
has struggled in each of the last two playoffs when being
agressively guarded by younger, quicker athletes, which is to say
just about any conceivable opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked extremely hard to get open tonight, and we didn't
guard him,'' said a very unhappy Jeff Van Gundy. ``It was a
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullin hurt the Knicks early with some cuts and slashes to the
hoop and he really knifed them in the third quarter with both
outside shooting and an ability to find his way to the free throw
line. All this represented a completely new dimension for Larry
Bird, who has been running the proud Mullin out there for two
playoff seasons hoping to get at least one such game out of his
ancient warrior. If Monday night turns out to be the only Mullin
moment, so be it. The Pacers had to have this game, and they
wouldn't have nailed it down without Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy had drawn pregame attention with a significant
coaching decision. He let the world know Sunday that he would
replace Kurt Thomas in the starting lineup with Latrell Sprewell,
over whom the New York press and basketball-loving public have been
salivating of late. It has become rather chic in New York to refer
to Sprewell as ``the best player on the team,'' and so, as if
yielding to public opinion, Van Gundy gave in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was talking about Sprewell starting,'' pointed out
Bird. ``It was a big burden on Chris's shoulders, and that is a
tough matchup for him. But we thought if Chris could get free at
the other end and loosen up, he might score, and that's what he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was all over the newspapers the day before this game,
calling on Miller to step it up and wondering aloud just how much
his team would be affected by the surreal ending of Game 3. The
Johnson shot even took place a few feet from where Larry himself
was standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little suprised how we played tonight,'' Bird
acknowledged. ``We really took a hit the other night. But after we
practiced on Sunday, I could see we were loosened up, and we really
came in here and played well tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bird lavished praise on his troops, Van Gundy blasted his
boys for atrocious defense and rebounding. They weren't as bad as
Van Gundy suggested, of course, but to say otherwise would be to
admit just how marginal his team is.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get it straight. The Knicks have been on a roll, but no
one should confuse that spurt with greatness. They might just be
like Charismatic. We may have already seen all they've got to give.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
