<HEADLINE>
STUDENT, 15, GOES THE EXTRA MILE FOR SCHOLARSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ROBERT MONROE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lynisha Perkins watches the sun rise and set every
day through the windows of a school bus that crawls 90 minutes each
way along a route between her home in South Central Los Angeles and
Granada Hills High School.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year-old said she is willing to go so many extra miles to
get the education she wants.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, she was rewarded for her tenacity: Lynisha and five
other Los Angeles Unified students each received a $16,000 college
scholarship from former Secretary of State Warren Christopher and
his Los Angeles law firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed that they were only going for the best and the
brightest, and I never thought of myself like that,'' she said.
``Maybe now that everybody's saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said he was struck by the story of the long bus
ride, her life in a single-parent household and Lynisha's poise and
self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I met her, I felt very much reassured that we had made a
sound choice,'' said Christopher, who has returned to the
sponsoring law firm, O'Melveny and Myers, as the senior partner.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-grader with a 3.7 grade-point average received a plaque
Monday and will get the $16,000 scholarship when she finishes high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 50 high schools in the Los Angeles Unified School
District nominated one candidate. Christopher, a committee of law
firm members, district representatives and the California Community
Foundation selected the six winners. The other nominees get $500
each.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said the law firm chose to award the scholarship six
years ago to recognize students in the firm's base city.
Christopher himself is a graduate of Hollywood High School. The
firm also wanted to focus the winners early _ they are all
10th-grade students _ on the goals they can achieve with the
financial help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many tragic situations where students drop out of
high school, having been discouraged by their prospects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher added that no recipient has failed to finish high
school, though the firm will get the students mentors if they
falter.
</P>
<P>
   According to her teachers, Lynisha isn't likely to buck
tradition. Pat Givant, coordinator of the Granada Hills/California
State University, Northridge, Math Science and Technology Program,
said Lynisha is a strong candidate for a program allowing her to
take classes at CSUN. Givant said there are lots of students who
take the bus to get to the magnet program, but that Lynisha has an
extra quality that made her stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going in that direction where she's not only willing to
be challenged here but taking whatever's available to her,'' Givant
said. ``Usually when you get a student who gets involved right
away, you know you have someone who is motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynisha had already chosen the San Fernando Valley as a place to
go to school as a middle school student. She followed her brother
Maurice, now 18, to a magnet program at Nobel Middle School in
Northridge. She saw going to Granada Hills, with its magnet program
and the friends she had made, as a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools out where I lived weren't all that great,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Perkins, Lynisha's mother, said Granada Hills also had
the music program her daughter, a piccolo and flute player, was
looking for. When Lynisha gets home at dusk from school, she is
coming from the band room where she spends three hours after class.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Perkins said she has never had to play the role of
motivator even though the day starts at 5:30 a.m. It's occasionally
a hurdle for the mother, who is part-time taxi driver to her
daughter on especially late nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult with her getting up early and with her getting
up early, her mom is getting up early,'' Deborah Perkins said.
``She has high standards, and she has set goals for herself, and
she's very focused.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lynisha's college plans, Stanford has yielded to the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology as her first choice. What's
important to her and her mother is not the place but the
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that she's exposed to as many positive
experiences as possible,'' Deborah Perkins said. ``I guess she can
get used to the cold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
