</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-MULLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULLINS ANSWERS THE CALL IN STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was supposed to be too old and too slow, a relic
of a player who could give the Indiana Pacers nothing against the
high-rising, fleet-footed New York Knicks. A 35-year-old former
Olympic Dream Team member and five-time All-Star, Chris Mullin was
said to have little value in this series. Why, some observers
wondered, did Coach Larry Bird continue to start him?
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, still moving as if his sneakers had glue on their soles,
answered that question on Monday night, scoring 18 points to lead
Indiana to a 90-78 victory over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Schooling the sleeker Latrell Sprewell in the craft of spin
moves and head fakes, Mullin kept the Pacers from falling into an
abyss on a night when their two top guns, Reggie Miller and Rik
Smits, played more like 12th men.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Smits, the Pacers' two leading scorers, totaled 16
points, 14 below their combined average of 30 points in the first
three games of this series. They went scoreless in the first half,
as Smits played only a minute _ and not because of foul trouble _
and Miller missed all three of his field goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with Antonio Davis (12 points), Jalen Rose (10) and
Mullin (8) picking up the slack, Indiana took a 45-32 lead into the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The third quarter belonged to Mullin, who reminded Madison
Square Garden's fans how he used to play when he was a star at St.
John's. Hitting 3 of 5 shots and three free throws, he scored 10
points in a four-minute span that pushed Indiana's 47-38 lead to
60-46 midway through the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Mullin scored 7 straight points for the Pacers.
After Miller followed a Mullin 3-pointer with a 3-pointer of his
own _ it was Miller's first basket of the game _ Mullin sank a
20-footer, drew a foul on Charlie Ward while attempting a
3-pointer, hit the three foul shots and then spun around Sprewell
for a driving layup. He had all his points by the end of the third
quarter, when the Pacers led, 66-57.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin was one of the least likely players to even this series
at two games apiece and return the home-court advantage to Indiana.
He had been no factor in the first three games, averaging 6 points
on woeful 37.5 percent shooting. Mullin had been so bad that Bird
was playing him just 18 minutes a game. A defensive liability no
matter who he guarded, Mullin was expected to see his impact lessen
as the series went on.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 was going to be Miller's revival, his return from the odd
comatose state he had been in for most of this series. Even if his
lauded jump shot was not falling, Miller was going to be different
from the deferring, disengaged player he had been for the better
part of this matchup with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Bird had challenged him to be more aggressive, even selfish,
demanding that Miller display the superstar qualities he is reputed
to have. Miller himself had promised to enter the game in attack
mode, vowing to be a ball hog and attempt as many as 25 shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the loud-talking, pressure-loving Indiana guard backed up
his words about as well as he created his own shot. Rather than
light up the Knicks and the Garden crowd, Miller played his most
unproductive game of this post-season, finishing with 12 points on
3-of-10 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Making good on his promise to carry aggression into the game,
Miller got a little too wild. His first jump shot bounced high off
the rim and over the backboard and he committed his second foul
less than five minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird wanted desperately to get his best player going, though, so
he left Miller on the floor. But three minutes and another Miller
miss later, Bird substituted Rose for Miller. The score was tied at
10 and the Pacers were presumably in for a long night. But Rose did
what Miller could not.
</P>
<P>
   He beat Knicks defenders off the dribble and ignited the Pacers,
scoring 6 points in the final 2 minutes 46 seconds of the first
quarter as Indiana surged to take a 23-20 lead into the second.
With Miller on the bench in his warm-ups, the Pacers' roll
continued as Davis, Rose and Mullin did what Miller and Smits could
not in the first half. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miller finally broke out a bit in the second half, however. He
scored 5 points in the third quarter and another 7 in the fourth
quarter as the Pacers evened the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
