<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SPREEWELL GETS A START BUT DOESN'T PRODUCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He was blazing downcourt, ahead of everyone, trying
to get Chris Childs' attention before the series was tied, the
home-court advantage lost and the questions began all over again.
Cutting along the baseline, behind the Indiana defense, Latrell
Sprewell finally saw the ball headed in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Inches from the basket and without a moment to spare, he caught
a bullet pass, and fumbled it before he could ever get a shot. Two
Pacers recovered in time to knock the ball out of bounds, but it
was yet another blown opportunity for Sprewell, heavenly sixth man,
hellish starter.
</P>
<P>
   The idea seemed as necessary as it was simple: insert the most
talented offensive player on the team into a starting lineup sorely
in need of points. The sixth man would get his wish, the coach
would get the production he wanted, and the fans at Madison Square
Garden would get to see more of their favorite new player.
</P>
<P>
   But when the experiment involves the supremely talented and
equally erratic Sprewell, the answers are never that easy. On a
night when the Knicks needed a player to take over Game 4 of the
Eastern Conference finals and put the Indiana Pacers into a deep
rut, Sprewell could not deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell played 33 minutes, finished with 12 points and never
got on track in the open court. His ability to change the tempo was
curtailed by Indiana's transition defense. The rest of Sprewell's
ineffectiveness was taken care of by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had an abysmal first half, shooting 3 for 11, picking
up two fouls within nine seconds of each other in the first quarter
and accomplishing little to merit his first start in more than two
months. It was not so such the misses but the quality of shots he
was taking. Ten-foot runners off one foot with defenders clinging
to him. Pull-up jumpers over Chris Mullin, who cannot guard
Sprewell when he drives toward the goal.
</P>
<P>
   With less than nine minutes left in the game and the Knicks
trying to crawl back in, Sprewell tried an aggressive spin move and
ended up mowing over Reggie Miller for an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   He was not alone in failing to carry the team. Larry Johnson
stood out beyond the 3-point line all night, failing to exploit the
matchups inside that had served him so well in the first three
games of the series. Allan Houston, who did not give Sprewell any
help in Game 3, gave him even less in Game 4 with 14 points on
5-of-16 shooting. And let's not even get into the lackluster play
of the point guards.
</P>
<P>
   For all those reasons, Sprewell needed to demonstrate that he
was the first and best option in Patrick Ewing's absence, a player
who could perform under pressure without having to come off the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to take Sprewell's performance and turn into a
referendum on his gradual adjustment in New York. But it was one
game, and being the guinea pig in so many situations this season,
he gets a pass over the short haul. But this was his wish. To
start.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeff Van Gundy began telling his bosses last year that
acquiring Sprewell was worth the risk, he drew distinct parallels
with a young and spry John Starks. The athleticism, the ability to
score in bunches, the raw, unbridled passion. And, of course, a
knack for slowly driving mad anyone for whom they played.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching Starks took Van Gundy most of three seasons, and even
then the coach was unsure what his most unpredictable player would
do in crucial situations. Reaching Sprewell, figuring out what
makes him tick on the floor, is a drawn-out process as well.
</P>
<P>
   All the cold stares from the bench toward Van Gundy, all the
times he honestly _ and petulantly _ answered, ``Jeff knows I want
to start'' were nearly forgotten before the game.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no bickering this night. The most headstrong
offensive player in the National Basketball Association _ Sprewell
goes to the right harder than Jesse Helms _ and the equally
stubborn coach would coexist in their own little playoff world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe he may have had a problem with me, but I have
no problem with him,'' Van Gundy had said. ``That's the bottom
line. I always told him I was doing what was best for the team. He
said he wants to start, but there's been no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sprewell: ``I think I just like starting; that's what I
feel comfortable doing. We'll see how I perform. That's one thing I
get up for. In a way, it's like I come out ready and focus and I'm
bringing all the energy from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   It never happened. Another Sprewell experiment had gone awry,
and now the Knicks need to win at least one game in Indianapolis to
advance to their first finals in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy had to make the call. Still, Sprewell looked awfully
good coming off the bench the other night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
