<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALK EXPERT'S CREDIBILITY ASSAILED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The prosecutor in the Scott Falater murder trial
accused an expert defense witness on Monday of having asked a
technician to falsify the data on tests that measured the sleep of
the former engineer, who claims he was sleepwalking when he stabbed
his wife 44 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were asking (the technician) to falsify or change her
numbers,'' assistant county attorney Juan Martinez said in an
aggressive cross-examination of Janet Tatman, who has endorsed the
sleepwalking defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' came the taut response from Tatman, a
psychologist and sleep disorders specialist who administered four
nights of tests on Falater's sleeping patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining her calm under the prosecutor's barrage, Tatman said
it was he who was distorting the tests. She said he did not
understand the science that was behind her analysis of Falater's
brain waves.
</P>
<P>
   But Tatman acknowledged that the technician had sharply
disagreed with her approach and that ``an air of mistrust''
developed between them. She said the technician had clung
stubbornly to a technique that had been developed 30 years ago and
had been superseded by later sleepwalking research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be foolish to discount everything that science has
learned,'' said Tatman.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is expected to revisit the issue next week, when he
calls the technician to testify as he rebuts the defense case. But
in the meantime, internationally renowned sleepwalking expert Dr.
Roger Broughton began his defense testimony on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lead defense attorney Michael Kimerer asked the Canadian
physician and researcher the core question of the defense case,
which is based on case law that says no one is criminally
responsible for an act he committed involuntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Did Broughton believe Falater was sleepwalking when he attacked
his wife in January 1997?
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion he was,'' said Broughton, who directs a sleep
disorders center in Ottawa. He has written in medical journals
about his research on violence by sleepwalkers.
</P>
<P>
   The balding, silver-bearded and bespectacled Broughton said his
appearance in the Falater case was only the second time he had
testified in a defense case based on sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   His only other testimony came in a 1988 trial of a Canadian man
who was later acquitted of the charge that he had murdered his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Under Kimerer's questioning, Broughton put on a slide-show
seminar on sleepwalking. He explained that sleepwalking episodes
almost always occur during the first hours of sleep, when the
subject falls into a deep sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That timing is important because Falater's defense claims he had
been working on a defective pump on his backyard pool immediately
before going to bed. Falater slept for about a half hour before
sleepwalking back to the unfinished task, his attorneys say.
</P>
<P>
   Broughton, like Tatman, testified that sleepwalkers often engage
in purposeful activity, particularly related to unfinished tasks.
</P>
<P>
   While the experts helped the defense lay out its case,
prosecutor Martinez used his cross examination of Tatman to narrate
the complex series of events that Falater undertook when he claims
to have been unaware of what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   Relying mostly on the account of a neighbor who began looking
into the Falater yard after the attack, Martinez said Falater:
stabbed his wife 44 times, stashed his bloody clothes in his Volvo,
put on a pair of gloves, dragged her to the pool, held her head
under water, went inside, put on a bandage and changed into pajamas
and a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The complex sequence did not budge Tatman, who endorses the
defense theory that Falater attacked his wife when she came out to
the pool pump to steer him back to bed. Sleepwalkers sometimes
engage in highly complex activities and often lash out at those who
interfere with their movements she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behaviors by themselves don't tell us _ unfortunately _
whether (a sleepwalker) is conscious or not,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of Tatman's testimony, Judge Ronald Reinstein allowed
the jurors to submit written questions for the witness. Asked if
the cold water of the pool would have jolted Falater out of his
sleep, Tatman said research has shown that sleepwalkers' senses are
often dulled.
</P>
<P>
   But Tatman had no ready answer for the juror who wanted to know
how she explained Falater's use of the bandage. ``It may have been
a reflex action to take care of a cut,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tatman said some of Falater's behavior made no logical sense, a
circumstance she called common among sleepwalkers. For example, she
said, rolling his wife, Yarmila, into the pool, where police found
her body floating in crimson waters, ``would seem a pretty
nonsensical thing to do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
