<SLUG> BC-HONEYWELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONEYWELL, ALLIEDSIGNAL EMPLOYEES AWAIT MORE DETAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICCARDO A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The planned merger of AlliedSignal Inc. and Honeywell
Inc. sent shock waves from Wall Street to Minneapolis to Phoenix,
and all points in between.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after Monday's announcement, about 17,500 Valley
employees working at the two companies were anxiously awaiting
details about the new company _ including how it would reduce
overlapping jobs and shed 4,500 jobs worldwide by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive officer of the proposed new company
maintained that the cuts would have little impact on the jobs based
in the Valley. Among the reasons: Phoenix is to be the headquarters
for the new company's aerospace division and its largest business
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combined technological investment we have there represents
$10 billion in revenue,'' said Michael Bonsignore, who is to be
chief executive officer of the new Honeywell. `We are after the
intellect of all the engineers there.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions about layoffs are not expected to be made until after
the new company does a three-month review of its businesses
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday, AlliedSignal and Honeywell said they were uniting
to form a $25 billion Fortune 50 company to take advantage of their
complementary aerospace technologies, products and services used on
airplanes. The new company is to retain the name Honeywell, but be
based in AlliedSignal's hometown of Morristown, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell expects to shed at least 1,000 positions in
Minneapolis when it pulls up stakes and relocates its headquarters
to Morristown.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately half of AlliedSignal's 10,000 employees in Arizona
work in its aerospace business, which manufactures airplane engines
and collision-avoidance systems at its facilities in Phoenix.
AlliedSignal also makes such consumer products as Prestone
antifreeze, Fram auto filters and Autolite spark plugs.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell, maker of cockpit controls and global positioning
equipment, employs about 7,500 in the Valley. Its businesses are
divided into three segments: Home and Building Control, Industrial
Control and Space and Aviation Control. The latter two are based in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two companies compete on several fronts, their
businesses have little overlap. Robert Johnson, currently president
and chief executive officer of AlliedSignal Aerospace, said there
is no local overlap in the products.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who is to be the new Honeywell's chief operating
officer and executive vice president for aerospace, said
AlliedSignal Aerospace currently cuts metal and makes engines and
jet propulsion devices at its Phoenix facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, adding Honeywell technology, would be able to
produce entire integrated systems, including cockpit systems
consisting of communication, navigation and surveillance equipment
to customers looking to outsource more of the aircraft's systems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the motives behind AlliedSignal's planned acquisition of
Honeywell is that aircraft makers are reducing the number of parts
suppliers they work with, and demanding that those suppliers
provide complete solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new company is to produce integrated cockpits
systems for its customers, the focus of AlliedSignal's Chairman and
Chief Executive Officer Lawrence Bossidy will be on integrating the
two corporate cultures. Bossidy will stay on as chairman of the new
company until his planned retirement on April 1, 2000. At that
time, Bonsignore is to assume the additional title and
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore said integrating the cultures should be easy because,
despite being somewhat different, they are action-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Bossidy said, ``We are both successful, growth-driven technology
companies who are intensely focused on performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger still requires regulatory approval in Europe and
America, and from stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators are expected to review the merger carefully, but
according to Bonsignore, AlliedSignal and Honeywell only overlap in
two areas: collision avoidance systems and weather radar, which
account for about $250 million in annual sales, or a little more
than 1 percent of the combined business. &QL; 
Riccardo A. Davis can be reached at (602) 444-8894 or at
riccardo.davis(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; The Associated Press
contributed to this
article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
