r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE WHITE, GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It had been a full game _ nearly two if you piece
together parts of games from other days _ and no incident of injury
or fisticuffs from the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The way it's been going this season, they were due.
</P>
<P>
   So we bring you the outfield situation, already tenuous, tedious
and thin. And then center fielder Devon White leaves with a sore
right leg after the third inning of a 3-2 loss to the Texas Rangers
on Monday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   White missed seven games with a strained right hamstring in
mid-May, and his availability for the next two games against the
Rangers is in question.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves the Dodgers in a precarious spot once again. Todd
Hollandsworth is on the disabled list with a torn oblique muscle on
his right side, so the club is carrying four outfielders. If White
isn't available, that number gets chopped to three. The way it
worked against Texas was Dave Hansen, upon pinch-hitting in the
eighth, played right field in the ninth and Raul Mondesi moved to
center.
</P>
<P>
   If White is going to miss a few days but not long enough to be
placed the disabled list, it puts the Dodgers in an interesting
situation. Though Johnson has talked about needing a fifth
outfielder, the Dodgers don't have the type Johnson is looking for
_ a left-handed hitting outfielder _ at Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   The White conundrum overshadowed the rest of the day for the
Dodgers, the lowlight of which was an inability to hit the usually
ineffective Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (6-4) had allowed at least four runs in four of his last
six outings. He allowed two runs on five hits in seven-plus innings
against the Dodgers. Rangers closer John Wetteland pitched the
ninth for his major-league-best 20th save.
</P>
<P>
   As it's been most of the season, the Dodgers had the pieces in
place to tie it in the eighth. Eric Young singled to start the
inning and knock Sele out, and Gary Sheffield walked with one out
against Jeff Zimmerman. Mondesi reached on a 10-foot infield single
to load the bases. Eric Karros then lined out to left to score
Young and pull the Dodgers within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But Hansen popped out down the right-field line in foul
territory to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the seventh inning the offensively inept Dodgers
got to Sele, and there was help on Texas' part.
</P>
<P>
   Trenidad Hubbard, White's replacement, led off the inning with a
double that popped off center fielder Tom Goodwin's glove near the
wall. Hubbard moved to third on catcher Ivan Rodriguez's errant
pickoff throw to second with none out.
</P>
<P>
   Leading 1-0, Texas played the infield in and Adrian Beltre
grounded to second for the first out. Angel Pena grounded to
shortstop and Hubbard broke for the plate. Instead of trying to get
Hubbard, Texas' Royce Clayton threw to first and allowed Hubbard to
tie the score 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   It mattered for a moment but not much longer. The Rangers
responded with a pair of runs in the eighth inning to ruin what was
turning into a dandy start for Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McLemore started the eighth with a leadoff single. Rusty
Greer flied out, Juan Gonzalez walked and Rafael Palmiero singled
to right to score McLemore and give the Rangers a 2-1 lead.
Rodriguez followed with a single to right to score Gonzalez and
make it 3-1 and chase Valdes (5-4) from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Mills relieved and walked Todd Zeile before getting Clayton
to ground into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Before the eighth, the only Ranger who seemed to have Valdes
figured out was Zeile, the former Dodger. He had three hits and
drove in Texas' first run.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the reigning AL MVP, led off the second with a single
to right. He moved to second on Ivan Rodriguez's groundout to first
and scored when Zeile hit a ground-rule double to right-center
field to give the Rangers a 1-0 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
