<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS     06-08 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ On the heels of one of the most crushing defeats in
franchise history, the Indiana Pacers came out Monday and crushed
the New York Knicks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pacers finally flexed their muscles and hammered the Knicks
90-78 in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference finals before 19,763 at
Madison Square Garden. The victory evened the best-of-seven series
at 2-2, with Game 5 on Wednesday in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any concern that the Pacers would be flat after the
shocking end to Game 3, when Larry Johnson nailed a four-point play
in the waning seconds to give the Knicks an improbable victory,
Indiana dispelled any such notions right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Game 3, the emotion can take the steam out of
a team,'' said the Pacers' Reggie Miller, who was held to 12 points
Monday. ``But this team has been there. Maybe not like that
(Johnson's shot), but we've had our backs to the wall many times.
We know what it takes to come back from that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   They certainly appeared to be Monday night, which is why New
Yorkers will no doubt be discussing this game almost as much as
they did the Knicks' miraculous Game 3 win.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because New York coach Jeff Van Gundy, apparently thinking his
team needed a shakeup, decided to start sixth man Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Up a game and wanting to get a stranglehold in the series, Van
Gundy was hoping Sprewell would put pressure on the Pacers with his
quickness and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his surprise move served as a wake-up call for the
Pacers, and Van Gundy will no doubt spend the interim answering
questions about his moves.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the decision gave the Knicks a front line that had
6-11 Chris Dudley flanked by 6-7 (wink, wink) Larry Johnson and the
6-5 Sprewell, a frontcourt that rivaled in size those from the
mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why the Knicks' point total was similar to those of
that era.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make changes, you're susceptible to
second-guessing,'' Van Gundy said. ``So if it doesn't work, then
some people are going to second-guess you. I don't worry about
that. I know this is the way we have to go to have a chance to win
this series. We're going to stick with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mullin will be thankful for that.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling in the first three games, averaging six points,
Mullin went off for 18 points. Freed from the burden of guarding
the 6-9 Kurt Thomas, Mullin's matchup against the shorter Sprewell
allowed him to concentrate on offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to take him out,'' Indiana coach Larry Bird said
of Mullin. ``I wanted to leave him in there all night. Chris had a
big burden on his shoulders because he knew Sprewell was going to
start, and everyone was talking about him not being able to defend
Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a tough matchup for Chris, but on the other hand we
feel that if Chris could get loose and hit some shots, then that's
very important for our team. We had to get some scoring out of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially since they were getting next to nothing from Rik
Smits (four points in 13 minutes) and Miller (3-of-10 shooting),
both of whom were saddled with early foul problems.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Jalen Rose, who ripped the Knicks for a game-high 19
points while delivering several clutch baskets down the stretch.
And with backup point guard Travis Best out with a strained groin,
the 6-8 Rose was inserted at the point and manhandled the shorter
Knicks guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jalen played extremely well,'' Bird said. ``Jalen loves to
play the point, and he just proved to me that he's capable of doing
that. He had two big baskets in the fourth quarter to kill (New
York) rallies. He just played awesome tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Antonio Davis, who, more than anything else, wanted some
way to make amends for his gaffe that gave the Knicks Game 3. It
was Davis who fouled Johnson on his late 3-pointer, and he wanted
to make up for that mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Davis scored 16 points and grabbed eight rebounds to help ensure
that there would be no last-second heroics in this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful I got an opportunity to play well tonight,''
Davis said. ``It was tough for me after the last game, but I just
wanted a chance to contribute to a win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it seemed as if the goats were heroes in this one, and
the heroes were goats.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who appeared to be off-stride from the outset, got
just 11 points (on 5-of-15 shooting) from Johnson and 12 points
from Sprewell. Throw in Allan Houston's meager production (14
points on 5-of-16 shooting), and you can see where the offense
suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Only Marcus Camby (18 points, a game-high 14 rebounds) had
anything even approaching a decent offensive game.
</P>
<P>
   The positive for the Pacers is that they have managed to tie the
series with Miller yet to have a big game. The negative for the
Knicks is that they haven't been able to capitalize while Miller
has struggled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer this series goes, the time is going to come when I
feel better and better,'' said Miller of his offensive woes. ``It's
almost like an overflowing dam. It's getting to the top, and it's
ready to burst. When it does, it's going to flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hourglass is slipping, especially for this team. We're one
of the veteran teams in the league, so we have to seize the moment
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
