<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY'S ERROR HURTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly all of Chuck Finley's pitches Monday
night were thrown with impeccable accuracy, but it was a throw in
the opposite direction that cost the Angels pitcher in a 5-2 loss
to the San Francisco Giants before 13,661 at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   A potential double-play comebacker to Finley instead wound up
rolling in the grass in shallow center field and led to four
unearned runs in a four-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out, the Giants' Brent
Mayne hit a one-hopper back to Finley, who fielded it with no
problem, but his throw to shortstop Andy Sheets covering second was
wide. Sheets dived to his right and got a glove on the ball, but it
caromed into center field, allowing Stan Javier to score the first
run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, F.P. Santangelo hit one of Finley's few (begin
ital)pitching(end ital) mistakes of the game over the fence in left
field for a three-run homer and a 4-0 Giants lead.
</P>
<P>
   In six innings, Finley (4-6) allowed only three hits and was
coming off a strong outing his last time out _ one run in eight
innings in a victory over the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   He started out fine Monday, allowing one hit through four
innings. After he got the first out in the fifth, Javier singled
and Rich Aurilia walked, setting up Mayne and the fateful play of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Russ Ortiz (7-4) shut out the Angels for six
innings on two hits, but the Angels got something going in the
seventh. Orlando Palmeiro singled with one out and went to third on
a single to right by Troy Glaus. Palmeiro then scored and Glaus
took second on a wild pitch. After Matt Walbeck singled Glaus to
third, Andy Sheets grounded out, Glaus scoring to cut the Angels'
deficit to 4-2. Jeff Huson, pinch-hitting for Finley, walked,
spelling the end of the night for Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Giants reliever Jerry Spradlin entered the game and hit Randy
Velarde with a pitch, loading the bases. Giants manager Dusty Baker
then went to his bullpen again, summoning lefty Rich Rodriguez to
face Darin Erstad, who grounded out to second to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants increased their lead to 5-2 in the seventh when
Javier singled and scored on a double to right field by Mayne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
