<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ARENA LEASE. NO ORGANIZATION. NO PLAN. HERE COMES WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Amid the gee-whizzing at Monday's news conference
announcing that the WNBA was coming to Seattle, the feeling was
that the whole enterprise just fell out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to know much beyond the fact that Seattle was one
of four new expansion franchises awarded Monday by the Great
Omniscience, the NBA, for the summer (not winter) of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   No KeyArena lease. No organization. No ticket plan. Only the
vaguest acknowledgment of the WNBA's requirements, including the
fact that the franchise award is conditional, not guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was there any sense of irony that the reason the event was
happening at all was because the NBA had helped put its rival _ the
American Basketball League, including the Seattle Reign franchise _
out of business last winter.
</P>
<P>
   The loopiness at the Sonics practice facility was captured best
by none other than the esteemed mayor of Seattle, Paul Schell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to celebrate. Negotiate tomorrow,'' said Schell,
offering a slogan that certainly works for me if I'm in a toga and
he's the head of Animal House. But I thought mayors worked more
deliberately when turning over public facilities to private
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, what the heck. It's women's hoops, so standards of logic and
civic protocol tend to get suspended.
</P>
<P>
   The laudable eagerness to re-establish the game as a
professional beacon for female athletes certainly was palpable.
City Council member Tina Podlodowski, whose charge is to protect
the public interest in the incomplete KeyArena deal, excitedly and
repeatedly offered Monday to buy the first 10 season tickets, never
mind the conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could anyone explain how it was that Seattle was deemed a
hotbed for women's hoops when its franchise and league had died for
lack of widespread interest _ during a lockout of the NBA men's
game, no less _ and attendance at the much-admired University of
Washington women's program fell to a six-year low.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did anyone really know how the team was going to meet the
league-mandated minimum season-ticket sales of 5,500 by Oct. 15 in
a busy sports market in which the Reign never sold more than 2,000.
Even the Reign's three-year average attendance of less than 4,000
at Mercer Arena was suspect. ABL co-founder Gary Cavalli told the
P-I last November that 25 percent of the attendance counts in the
league's first two seasons included complimentary tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the predictable lamentations were issued over the
demise of the Reign, no twinge of anxiety was detected at sliding
into the sack with the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Richard Blumenthal, the Connecticut attorney
general, issued a subpoena to the NBA after an investigation into
whether the league conspired to monopolize women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said he had information indicating that the NBA
actively hastened the collapse of the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's evidence the NBA used sharp economic elbows to exclude
the ABL ... from fair play _ including access to essential
financial rights like TV and product sponsorships,'' Blumenthal
said.
</P>
<P>
   None of these matters were derailing the politicians and Sonic
bosses Monday from joining other NBA teams in their singular and
noble purpose for the WNBA enterprise:
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring arena filler.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the ABL, which seemed sincere in its desire for
grass-roots growth of the women's game, and paid good salaries, the
WNBA is mostly a way to fill dates in buildings owned by the
franchises. The WNBA typically makes money by paying its players
store-clerk entry salaries and doubling the work of staff from the
men's franchise.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonics' business arm, Full House Sports and
Entertainment, the women's franchise is the same economic racket as
the SeaDogs, which I believe was a men's indoor soccer team _
though witnesses are few _ that folded a couple of summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   This region is littered with the carcasses of sports franchises
besides the Reign that began with lofty ambitions: the original
Sounders, Storm and Tacoma Tides (men's outdoor soccer); Tacoma
Stars (men's indoor soccer); Smashers (volleyball); Cascades
(tennis); Totems (hockey); and Rainiers (the longtime Class AAA
Pacific Coast League baseball team, plus a Class A version that
died in 1976).
</P>
<P>
   One difference between those failures and the impending
psychological assault by the WNBA was explained, inadvertently, by
Full House's president, John Dresel.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success, he said, was ``selling the game before the
season starts.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, relentless, remorseless hype, as only the NBA
can do. Armed with a willing network lap dog in NBC, the NBA knows
if it screams loud and long enough and insists that hipness is
nigh, the gullible American sports public will show up to watch a
tire-pumping tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic operatives at the moment might be almost clueless about
what just landed on their doorstep. But by next summer, this
junior-varsity team and calendar-stuffer will be affixed to the
local sporting consciousness like a Rodman tattoo, no matter how
many people didn't request it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6823 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-WNBA-SEATTLE-SPI &LR;      06-08 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE `THIS CLOSE' TO NETTING WNBA FRANCHISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Pending a successful season ticket campaign, women's
professional basketball will return to Seattle next summer. The
Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA) awarded Seattle one
of four expansion franchises Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The new team _ not yet named _ will be operated by the Seattle
SuperSonics and begin play in the summer of 2000, providing it
secures pledges for 5,500 season tickets by Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Also awarded expansion franchises for next year were Portland,
Indianapolis and Miami. The four expansion sites were chosen from
among 14 NBA cities interested in attracting the country's only pro
women's basketball league.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers would boost the women's league to 16 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities we came up with reflect the best mix of being in
parts of the country we're not currently represented in and in
being with (NBA) teams that are well-developed in basketball with
good top management and high-end facilities,'' said WNBA President
Val Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   NBA sources say Denver was the only other serious contender for
the 2000 expansion, but the pending sale of the city's NBA Nuggets
may have complicated its WNBA bid.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman noted Seattle's interest in women's basketball
``particularly by the University of Washington's teams and the fan
base laid by the ABL team'' _ the Seattle Reign, which ceased
operations when the American Basketball League folded last
December.
</P>
<P>
   But as optimistic as Ackerman is, Seattle's WNBA deal
technically is not completed. The Sonics lack a signed lease for
use of city-owned KeyArena, and, in addition to selling the
required number of season tickets, Seattle, like all the new
franchises, must:
</P>
<P>
   -- Secure a broadcast deal for local radio and TV coverage. At
least six games must be televised locally.
</P>
<P>
   -- Set up a staff exclusively for the WNBA side of operations.
</P>
<P>
   -- Make a substantial financial commitment for top-rate
promotions, advertising, marketing and team operational spending.
It would also include an undisclosed ``franchise fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Full House Sports and Entertainment, which will run the Seattle
WNBA team, announced Monday that KJR (950-AM) will handle the
team's radio broadcasts. And although the group hasn't priced
season tickets yet, a $50 deposit will secure a season ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is the season ticket pledges,''
Ackerman said. ``Beyond that the teams are now probably going to
start doing some civic ground-laying, reaching out to local media
and tapping into the fan base that's been most fertile for the WNBA
_ and that's family.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's previous women's pro team, the Seattle Reign played
two and a third ABL seasons before the league went bankrupt in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Ackerley, co-chairwoman of the Ackerley Group that owns
the SuperSonics, called NBA Commissioner David Stern when the ABL
folded, to find out how she could secure a WNBA franchise for the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Reign left, this city was absolutely grieving,'' said
Ackerley, who will serve as chairwoman of Seattle's WNBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think many of us realized how much the Reign meant to
this community until after the team left.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the community's support of women's basketball will
decide the team's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Playing at Mercer Arena, the Reign drew more fans for each of
its seasons, but the final figures were only about 1,900 season
ticket holders and an average attendance of 4,013.
</P>
<P>
   The new WNBA team will play at KeyArena, which seats 17,072.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved with the WNBA expansion franchise say that
selling 5,500 season tickets for a summertime basketball schedule
will be the team's first big hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Tina Podlodowski challenged the area's
``high-tech millionaires'' to buy tickets and donate them to local
children if that's what the city needs to meet its quota.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerley said she's not ``terribly concerned'' about meeting
season ticket obligations, saying, ``This basketball is exciting.
Some people just don't know it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Full House has promised an aggressive marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our immediate access to a large base of basketball fans is
right there because of the Sonics,'' said Full House President John
Dresel. ``We've been in the basketball business for 16 years, and
hopefully that experience will help us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Full House is still negotiating the KeyArena lease deal with the
city, but both sides characterized the discussions as friendly.
Dresel and Mayor Paul Schell refused to give any details, but
Dresel said the deal could be finalized later this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Ackerley group last month, Schell offered
concessions to a start-up WNBA franchise using KeyArena. He offered
to lower the rent for WNBA games; let Full House retain all ticket,
concession, merchandise and sponsorship revenue; and give the
organization the same scheduling rights it has to Sonics games.
</P>
<P>
   All parking and admission tax revenue from WNBA games would be
retained by the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the issues we've had are being taken care of,'' said
Podlodowski, who also insisted she was supremely confident in the
upcoming season ticket drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle group will meet with Ackerman next week, and then
team officials hope to announce a timetable to hire a general
manager and come up with a name and logo.
</P>
<P>
   The Reign hasn't been ruled out, but the team hasn't decided how
or when it will pick a name.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's not the name or the logo, it's the tickets and the
question is when can I get them,'' Podlodowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
