<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVITZ, BROAD DISCUSS JOINING FORCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The two groups competing and sometimes clashing
for the Los Angeles NFL franchise met for the first time this
weekend to discuss possibly merging their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Neither would discuss specifics of their Sunday-morning meeting
but plan to talk again within the next 10 days to further explore
joining forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at that hard,'' said Eli Broad. ``There is a
desire to do it, we've got to work out how you do it. There are a
lot of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The Broad and Ed Roski Jr. group has been competing with the
rival Michael Ovitz and Ron Burkle group for ownership of the NFL's
32nd franchise, which has been tentatively awarded to Los Angeles
and the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz had proposed an entire new stadium for the city of Carson
and had less than six weeks to develop a design for renovating the
76-year-old Coliseum after the NFL announced in April it had been
selected the expansion site.
</P>
<P>
   The former Hollywood superagent's splashy design for the
Coliseum impressed owners when they met in Atlanta two weeks ago.
But commissioner Paul Tagliabue, concerned whether the plan could
get local approvals, said the NFL was encouraging the two sides to
merge in a unified Los Angeles effort.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz previously had been offered an opportunity to join the
Broad-Roski group but said he wanted to pursue his own Coliseum
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday morning, Ron Burkle and I met casually with Eli
Broad and Ed Roski,'' Ovitz said in a statement. ``Our meeting was
cordial.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have said all along, my ownership group's top priority is
to bring professional football back to Los Angeles, and we are
willing to explore any ideas that increase Los Angeles' chances
with an NFL franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, an Ovitz adviser, said the four leaders of the two
groups met at Burkle's home. Broad called Sunday's meeting
``preliminary'' and said he came away neither encouraged nor
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the middle,'' Broad said. ``We both have the same
thoughts, but there are a lot of things to be ironed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good meeting, but nothing was concluded and we're
going to meet again. There is a lot to talk about when you do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups' separate redesigns of the Coliseum would each cost
approximately $300 million, but to meet the NFL demands, Ovitz's
original plan called for parking garages around the stadium with
27,000 spaces that could cost an additional $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   The five parking garages, which would likely require public
funding, drew immediate criticism from public officials. The
recommended Broad parking proposal includes one $67.5-million
garage and using parking at USC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
