<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, June 8.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BIRTH (Mexico City) _ Like many old-style Mexican
matriarchs, Emma Castro Amador bore so many children that she can't
keep their birthdays straight, but all 14 of her children say they
are determined to limit their own families to two or three. The
national birth rate is down from an average of 7 to 2.5 and that
means a lot, for the entire continent. Next year, Mexico's
population is projected to reach 100 million, and the contrast
between Mrs. Castro's family and those of her children illustrates
the extraordinary changes under way in the country's population
patterns. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STUN-BELT-PRISONS (Undated) _ A California case and a report to
be issued by Amnesty International on Tuesday are focusing
attention on stun belts, electrical shocking devicees that are
attached to some inmates in federal and state prisons and local
jails across the country, and some prisoners when they are taken to
court. Some critics question the legality of the belts. By Williams
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL _ Members of the House of Representatives return
from a recess to confront a looming battle over gun control that
has already become more fraught with political anxiety than it was
before they left. Increased tensions over new gun control measures
partly reflect the activity of the National Rifle Association,
which used the recess to rally its supporters, lobby lawmakers and
sprinkle the radio airwaves with ads. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-WHITMAN (Trenton, N.J.) _ As she prepares to run for the
Senate, Christie Whitman finds herself in a political squeeze
between conservative and moderate Republicans. By Jerry Gray.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-BLACKS-TAXIS (Miami) _ Society Cab has become more than a
taxi ride in some of Miami's black communities. In a part of the
city where taxi drivers must carry change for a quarter because
even a dime is more than most people can tip, the drivers are the
only ones who regularly answer calls in Miami's harshest
neighborhoods. Now, a piece of county legislation may do what
gunfire could not: do away with older cabs like the ones in
Society's fleet of 23. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON _ President Clinton will soon propose revamping
the Medicare program to offer prescription drug coverage to all
beneficiaries, and he will contend that such coverage can actually
save money for the government by reducing the need for hospital
stays and nursing home care, administration officials said on
Monday. By Robert Pear.
</P>
