<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Falls among older people and the
resulting injuries that can cause long-term disability and even
death are rising in epidemic fashion. In a study published last
month in the Journal of the American Medical Association, Finnish
researchers documented an alarming increase in the number and
incidence of falls sustained by people over 50 since 1970. By Jane
E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPERM-SUPPLEMENT (Undated) _ With a bit of fanfare but
limited hard evidence, a Maryland pharmaceutical company has begun
marketing a dietary supplement said to improve sperm quality to
couples having trouble conceiving. By Eric Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EXERTION-SYNDROME (Undated) _ Chronic exertional compartment
syndrome, a problem that most frequently occurs in the legs of
runners and soccer players, is growing, particularly among women
who in greater numbers are becoming athletes. But the condition is
also frequently misdiagnosed as shin splints. A new procedure now
is alleviating the pain. By Janis Graham.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRINCETON-FUSION (Undated) _ In its heyday the Princeton
Plasma Physics Laboratory was a palace among physics laboratories,
with an enviably fat budget, ample support staff and the prestige
that comes to research institutions working at the cutting edge in
solving global problems. But today, it is still a leader in
hydrogen fusion research and is so short of cash that it can no
longer afford even a receptionist. But that may be changing.
Specialists in the field are banding together in the hope that
progress toward the elusive goal of harnessing thermonuclear
fusion, the process that drives the sun and hydrogen bombs, to
produce unlimited energy on Earth, will soon regain momentum. By
Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUSION-HARDWARE (Undated) _ Scientists have developed a
variety of devices and systems in which they hope to be able to
compress hydrogen to the densities and temperatures needed to
sustain thermonuclear fusion reactions. A run down of seven
devices. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FREE-HEROIN-PROGRAM (Undated) _ Taking a bold approach to
drug addiction, researchers at Columbia University are offering
free heroin to addicts and paying them to use it under a federally
authorized program aimed at finding a cure for their addictions.
Two trials involving heroin injections are among six related
drug-addiction studies being conducted at Columbia's College of
Physicians and Surgeons, all of which focus on the role existing
medications can play in defeating drug addictions. By Christopher
S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-RESEARCH (Washington) _ The director of the
National Institutes of Health has touched off a passionate debate
by proposing that scientists disclose and disseminate on the
Internet the results of biomedical research, so the full text of
their reports would be available at no cost to anyone with a
computer anywhere in the world. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TUMOR-DRILL (Undated) _ A delicate but destructive machine,
a kind of molecular power drill deployed by tumors to punch their
way through the body's compartments, has been visualized for the
first time by biologists at Sweden's Karolinska Institute. The
power drill exists not for the benefit of tumors, though they
exploit it, but for normal remodeling of the tough walls that
surrounds the body's main organs and tissues. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FINCH-FEEDBACK (Undated) _ Among songbirds, the zebra finch
is a one-hit wonder. It learns a tune in its youth, and then is
condemned to repeat it forever, like an aging pop star on the
oldies circuit. A young zebra finch learns through auditory
feedback, listening to its own sounds and comparing them to a song
in its head until it gets it right. Little has been known about how
a mature finch, a ``closed learner'' (compared to a canary, for
example, which learns new tunes all the time) maintains its song.
But recent studies with deafened adult finches have suggested that
they use feedback as well. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-STARGAZING (Undated) _ In speeches to astronomical
meetings in Chicago last week, NASA Administrator Dan Goldin
announced that he would apply the ``cheaper, faster, better''
philosophy that has revitalized planetary exploration to deeper
studies of the origin and structure of the universe, and challenged
the stargazing community to dream up innovative bold ideas. By John
Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OBSERVATORY (Undated) _ Items on turbocharged lizards, an
explanation for the extensive damage of Hurricane Mitch and
wind-borne pollution. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ A researcher has injected neural stem
cells into the brains of fetal monkeys and found that the stem
cells spread out and evolved into the right kinds of tissue in
various parts of the brain. This is the scenario that stem cell
researchers who envision using these pliable cells to replace
damaged organs have been hoping for. The results are not directly
applicable to humans, since the monkeys were still in a fetal
stage, but they allow the researchers to study how the stem cells
migrate around in the brain and evolve. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ESSAY (Undated) _ Medical science can measure most things
these days, but one quantity remains eternally, enragingly
imprecise: how long doctors should take to do their work. The
single feat dangling permanently out of reach of the biomedical
revolution seems to be how to make the whole magnificent enterprise
run on time. By Abigail Zuger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
