<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6828 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ASTROS-WHITESOX-H     06-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ASTROS-WHITESOX-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CHICAGO _ Jose Lima hadn't made his way back to the visitors'
clubhouse when his merengue music was heard blasting away.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's baseball custom that the pitcher gets to select the music
after a victory. The way Lima has pitched this season, the compact
disc is in place. All the Astros have to do is push the button.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny part is he isn't even in the clubhouse, and we have
his music going,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``We're
starting to understand what's going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the rest of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Lima became the National League's first 10-game winner and the
Astros rebounded from one of their most humbling showings of the
season to defeat the Chicago White Sox 8-2 Monday night at Comiskey
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Lima (10-2) matched the club record for reaching double-figure
wins in the fewest appearances, accomplishing it in 12 starts. In
1964, Dick ``Turk'' Farrell went 10-1 in his first 12 games for the
Colt .45s.
</P>
<P>
   Does Lima believe he has been slighted when it comes to national
attention?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody mentions Jose Lima,'' said Lima, who won 16 games last
year but didn't post his 10th victory until Aug. 1. ``I only hear
about everybody else. That's OK. I don't want anybody saying
anything about me. I'm going to stay quiet and keep winning games.
I'm going to keep taking care of business.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lima isn't making any friends on Chicago's south side. The
righthander pumped his right arm after getting Frank Thomas to hit
a comebacker to end the fifth inning and was booed by the crowd of
16,881. Lima tipped his cap as he walked to the dugout, drawing
more boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, and I'm sure his teammates don't like it,''
said Chicago designated hitter Paul Konerko, who matched a career
high with three hits. ``It's fine to be emotional, but you don't
show up a player like Frank. I'm surprised he does that in the
National League, because he has to bat. I'd be surprised if he
doesn't have bruises all over his back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, White Sox reliever David Lundquist threw a ball
inside that sent Craig Biggio heading for the dirt and drew a
warning from home-plate umpire Jim Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't a brushback (pitch),'' Chicago manager Jerry
Manuel said. ``That's not our style. He was just pitching him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima allowed eight hits, walked one and struck out three in his
third complete game of the year. And as long as he continues to
win, his teammates don't plan on changing any of his routines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White Sox haven't seen him, but everybody through our
league knows how he is,'' Bagwell said. ``I'm not a big proponent
of it usually, but I know Jose, and he's the same way tonight as he
will be tomorrow and the next day and the next day whether he wins
or loses. I don't have a problem with that, because he's an
emotional guy. He doesn't mean any harm. If you listen to him out
there, he's yelling at himself, not at anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago starter John Snyder (6-5) had cause to yell at himself,
failing to make it out of the fourth inning. Snyder allowed six
runs (five earned) and 10 hits in 3 innings, his second-shortest
outing of the season. During his four-game losing streak, Snyder
has allowed 22 earned runs in 19 innings _ a 10.42 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who were drubbed 13-6 the day before at Minnesota,
finished with 17 hits, one short of their season high set May 11
against Pittsburgh. Bill Spiers had three hits and drove in two
runs, Derek Bell hit a two-run single in a five-run fourth inning,
and Tony Eusebio went 3-for-5.
</P>
<P>
   Every Astros starter had at least one hit, and the top four
hitters _ Biggio, Spiers, Bagwell and Bell _ went 9-for-19 with
five runs and six RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros batted around in the fourth inning, with the first
five hitters reaching base safely. With the game tied at 1,
designated hitter Daryle Ward led off with a single, Eusebio
doubled, and Ricky Gutierrez broke the tie with an RBI single.
Biggio then reached on an error by White Sox shortstop Mike Caruso
that allowed Eusebio to score, and Spiers doubled in Gutierrez.
After Bagwell lined out, Bell cleared the bases with a single to
center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek and I started to swing the bat a little better,'' said
Biggio, who had two hits after entering the game batting .206 on
the road trip. ``In order for us to score a lot of runs, Derek and
I have to get on base. If one of us isn't doing the job, the other
has to do the job. Everybody really contributed today.''
</P>
<P>
   In seven of Lima's 12 starts, the Astros have supported him with
at least a half-dozen runs. Does it have something to do with the
music?
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked one of the coaches before the game, `Do you think we
get ready for the game better by taking infield practice or by
coming in here and listening to that (merengue) music?''' Dierker
said. ``I think the consensus was the music was better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
