<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS, HALAMA BOOST MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ This isn't football, so the prize for a job well done
is not a game ball. More appropriate is a handshake, a cold one and
a small sense of pride lasting only until the next day.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts like the one Russ Davis gave Monday night would seem
to deserve a bit more. At least, Alex Rodriguez thought so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, the ball for this game goes to Russ Davis,'' said
the Mariners shortstop, after several standout plays by Davis
ensured a 4-2 win over the Colorado Rockies. ``He didn't want it,
and I was just messing around with him. But that's how you win
games. He played great, great defense, and that's more valuable
than four hits. He must have saved four runs for us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman's efforts helped John Halama (4-2) win his
second consecutive start, another sterling effort in which he
worked quickly, used all his pitches and lasted deep into the game.
He struck out one and did not walk a batter until the last one he
faced, Larry Walker, with one out in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Halama needed 91 pitches to get 22 outs; the day before at Coors
Field, Rockies starter Pedro Astacio had needed 153 pitches to get
23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really couldn't care less about strikeouts,'' Halama said.
``If I could repeat this performance throughout the whole year, I'd
be very happy. I had one strikeout, who cares? Strikeouts are just
for statistics. I would rather get the hitters to swing in the
first two or three pitches and get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Halama's pace _ he had three seven-pitch innings _ helped the
defense behind him. That was about all Davis would say, sticking to
his rule of just playing, ignoring any criticism or praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys are throwing strikes and going after guys, your legs
feel a lot fresher than when you're standing out there for 45
minutes in one inning,'' Davis said. ``It's a heck of a lot easier
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Davis made a diving stab down the line to
hold Darryl Hamilton to a single, stopping the lead runner at
second. He ended that inning with a belly-flop grab of a ground
ball by Walker, throwing him out to leave two runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   Davis started a double play to erase a leadoff single in the
sixth, then doubled up Dante Bichette with the bases loaded in the
eighth inning, preserving the Mariners' two-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw him two sinkers, because I was looking for the ground
ball double play,'' said Jose Paniagua, who induced the grounder
after relieving Halama. ``That's the pitch I use all the time with
one out and a right-handed hitter. That's exactly what Lou told me
when he gave me the ball: `Throw (it) inside and jam him.'''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella has gotten that kind of performance from
Paniagua since last August, when the right-hander was called up
from Class AAA Tacoma. What he's not used to seeing is such solid
defense. The Mariners came into Monday night's game fourth in the
American League in defense, and tied for first in double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' turnaround has been exceptional. At this point last year,
he had 14 errors, on his way to a franchise-record 34. So far in
'99, he has made only five, and just one since April 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played very well defensively,'' Piniella said. ``That's
the biggest improvement in our ballclub over last year. We have
really picked up the pace with the glove. We're turning more double
plays, and really helping our pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Another improvement: the Randy Johnson factor. At this point in
'98, Johnson was 5-4. The two starters Seattle acquired when they
traded Johnson to Houston, Halama and Freddy Garcia, are a combined
11-4 in '99.
</P>
<P>
   And they're also hitting. Garcia contributed a broken-bat,
run-scoring single to his victory in San Diego Sunday, and Halama's
opposite-field double to left started the go-ahead rally in
Seattle's two-run fifth Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Halama scored on a double by Rodriguez, which gave the M's a 2-1
lead. Rodriguez then scored on the first of two RBI singles by
Butch Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That proves (I had) a lot of luck,'' said Halama, who was on
base three times, of his first major league hit. ``That's all that
proves. It's a case of the ball hitting the bat, because I just
swung as hard as I could. I was so late. I felt so out of place out
there from a hitting standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times last year when Davis looked out of place from a
fielding standpoint. But not this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of him getting his confidence,''
Rodriguez said. ``I've always complimented him on his good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   When a guy doesn't want a game ball, a compliment will have to
do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
