</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE WHITE, GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One Dodger was injured, another didn't come up
with (begin ital)the(end ital) hit that could change the game, and
there was a lot of optimism afterward as to when this season will
begin to take the shape it was already supposed to take.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, just another Dodgers game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers lost to the Texas Rangers 3-2 Monday at Dodger
Stadium to keep fresh their rhythm of inconsistency. They've lost
the last two games to fall to 28-28 after they'd won two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're going to hit, sometimes you're going to
pitch, and the good teams put it together,'' Dodgers reliever Alan
Mills said. ``We're not doing that. Whenever you have a team with
the talent we have, it's going to draw attention and expectations.
But I don't think it's late enough in the season for anybody to
push a panic button.''
</P>
<P>
   On this particular occasion, the injured party was center
fielder Devon White. He left after straining his right groin while
chasing former Dodger Todd Zeile's RBI double in the second inning.
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he doesn't anticipate White
playing in the next two games against the Rangers. White missed
seven games with a strained right hamstring in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   It makes the already tenuous outfield situation, which was
tediously dissected for the past two weeks, again unstable and
without options. Todd Hollandsworth is on the disabled list with a
torn oblique muscle (right side of rib cage) so the club is
carrying four outfielders. With White unavailable, it leaves
Trenidad Hubbard, Raul Mondesi and Gary Sheffield as the healthy
bodies and means Johnson is limited on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   It was to the point against the Rangers where the Dodgers' top
pinch hitter, Dave Hansen, played right field in the ninth. It was
the first outfield stint of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope nobody else gets hurt,'' Johnson said. ``We got Hansen
and Tripp (Cromer) out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's been brilliant as a pinch hitter this season (9 for 21)
but popped out foul in his chance to tie the game or give the
Dodgers a lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were unable to produce any offense against the
usually hittable Aaron Sele, who yielded two runs in seven-plus
innings. It was the fewest runs he's allowed since April 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers chased Sele (6-4) in the eighth after Eric Young's
leadoff single, but after loading the bases with one out, scored
only on Eric Karros' sacrifice lineout to left that made it 3-2.
Hansen, pinch hitting for Hubbard who replaced White, popped out to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers closer John Wetteland pitched a perfect ninth for his
major- league-best 20th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens like that,'' Mills said. ``Take the ball Karros hit
to give us our second run. A little more right, a little more
left.... Right now, as a team, we're not clicking. I just think
it's a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the Rangers came up with the big hit and the big
pitch in crucial situations. Before reliever Jeff Zimmerman got
Hansen to pop out, Rafael Palmeiro (3 for 4) singled in a run in
the top of the eighth off Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes (5-4) to
give the Rangers a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought he was going to hang another curveball to
(Palmeiro), I would have hooked him,'' Johnson said. ``Three times
he did the same thing. It was a great effort. If he wasn't throwing
the ball really good, I'd have hooked him. I had people ready for
(Palmeiro). It was his to win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez followed with his RBI single as Texas went ahead
3-1. Those hits, coupled with the pitching from Zimmerman, show why
the AL West-leading Rangers (34-22) have won 11 of their last 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this stretch, we've played a lot of games like this,''
Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``We didn't have too many games
like that in our first 30. They were 9-8, 14-3.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
