<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY'S ERROR COSTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Nearly all of Chuck Finley's pitches Monday
night were thrown with impeccable accuracy, but it was a throw in
the opposite direction that cost the Angels pitcher in a 5-2 loss
to the San Francisco Giants before 13,661 at 3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   A potential double-play comebacker to Finley instead wound up
rolling in the grass in shallow center field and led to four
unearned runs in a four-run fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out, the Giants' Brent
Mayne hit a one-hopper back to Finley. He fielded it with no
problem, but his throw to shortstop Andy Sheets covering second was
wide. Sheets dived to his right and got a glove on the ball, but it
caromed into center field, allowing Stan Javier to score the first
run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, F.P. Santangelo hit one of Finley's few (begin
ital)pitching(end ital) mistakes of the game over the fence in left
field for a three-run homer and a 4-0 Giants lead.
</P>
<P>
   Finley was coming off a strong outing his last time out _ one
run in eight innings in a victory over the Twins. In six innings
Monday, Finley (4-6) allowed only three hits, walked two and struck
out four.
</P>
<P>
   Finley allowed one hit through four innings, but after he got
the first out in the fifth, Javier singled and Rich Aurilia walked,
setting up Mayne and the fateful play of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw it away, man,'' Finley said. ``The bottom line is I
threw the ball into center field, and I pretty much threw the game
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Angels' season? Are they throwing it away,
too? It's more than a month before the All-Star break, but their
7{-game deficit in the AL West is the largest in manager Terry
Collins' two-plus years with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really getting any better right now,'' Finley said.
``You try to hold on, hold on until you get guys back in the
lineup. Keep playing hard and not let anybody get so far ahead they
get so small you can't make 'em out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get hot sooner or later. But 7{ games out, we
don't have many games to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Russ Ortiz (7-4) shut out the Angels for six
innings on two hits, but the Angels got something going against him
in the seventh. Orlando Palmeiro singled with one out and went to
third on a single to right by Troy Glaus. Palmeiro then scored and
Glaus took second on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After Matt Walbeck singled Glaus to third, Sheets grounded out,
Glaus scoring to cut the Angels' deficit to 4-2. Jeff Huson, pinch
hitting for Finley, walked, spelling the end of the night for
Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Giants reliever Jerry Spradlin entered the game and hit Randy
Velarde with a pitch, loading the bases. Velarde remained in the
game despite being hit with a 95-mph fastball in the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Giants manager Dusty Baker then went to his bullpen again,
summoning lefty Rich Rodriguez to face Darin Erstad, who grounded
out to second to end the threat. Erstad, who went 0 for 4 and saw
his average fall to .227, stranded six baserunners Monday,
including four in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Finley) pitched a great ballgame, but once again it was one
of those things where you just can't make any errors,'' Collins
said. ``And we didn't give him anything to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the offense continues to struggle, Finley refused to
share any blame for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to doing what you're supposed to do,'' he said.
``It was an easy double play and I screwed it up. I knew when I
threw it. I was hoping Andy was late getting to the bag, but he had
all his momentum going to second.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants increased their lead to 5-2 in the seventh when
Javier singled and scored on a double to right field by Mayne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
