<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES0     06-08 0238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Aglow with civic ardor
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton has formed an exploratory committee. Every
candidate forms exploratory committees these days. Mrs. Clinton's
exploratory committee will advise her whether to run for U.S.
Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will tell her it's OK. When was the last time you
saw an exploratory committee say the mere idea is a nightmare?
Exploratory committees, in their simplicity, want to give their
hearts away.
</P>
<P>
   As a candidate, you can't let them. You've got to think where
uncomplicated ardor might lead, like imprudence. A candidate cannot
be seen virtually adrool for public office. A candidate is to be
summoned from private life by citizens driven by civic interest.
Then, having heard their plea, you can announce your candidacy
three or four times without the press keeping count.
</P>
<P>
   The press, flighty as ever, will have turned its attention to
thinking up trick questions. In Mrs. Clinton's case, what was Pee
Wee Reese's uniform number? A: 1. Where is Mark Twain buried? A:
Elmira. Do you like your corned beef sandwich on rye or white? A:
Rye _ with mustard.
</P>
<P>
   Shows you're serious.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
