<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN09-CO     06-08 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC chief offers Web horse sense
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt
talked recently about electronic investing in the next century, he
summoned up the old-fashioned wisdom of folk singer Pete Seeger:
``Education is when you read the fine print. Experience is what you
get when you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   His point was that successful investing will always require
detailed and demanding study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ease and speed of the Internet have made trading _ not
investing, but trading _ easier than ever before,'' he said. ``But
in no way does it absolve investors of their basic responsibilities
to invest in a way that is consistent with their goals and risk
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt was speaking to a crowd of 6,000 at the Los Angeles
Times' annual investment conference. He pointed out that nobody at
all traded on the Internet before 1994. Now an estimated 10 million
investors buy and sell stocks electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day, I was driving behind a bus that advertised a
financial Web site,'' he said. ``I remember when buses used to
advertise the local newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt, now in his second term as boss of the federal
government's chief watchdog over the investment markets, draws
mixed reactions from people who care about his work.
</P>
<P>
   Some market insiders _ meaning the industry leaders who make the
big bucks _ admire his work. But one market official fumed in a
trade publication that Levitt's SEC has gone from tinkering to
``full-on socialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Among investors and their partisans, the range of opinion is
just about that wide. Some complain that Levitt talks a good game
but tilts toward serving the industry before the public.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is a first-rate teacher, and he was a big hit in Los
Angeles, dropping down from the suited elegance of a big-time
market professional to the shirt-sleeve level of everyday
investors.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about using old-fashioned horse sense in the 21st
century marketplace. Here are some of his tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't assume your buy and sell orders are executed instantly.
``The process is usually seamless and electronic,'' Levitt said.
``It is not, however, guaranteed. Lines may clog, systems may
break, orders may back up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's especially worrisome when everybody wants to buy or sell
a company's stock at the same time. To protect themselves,
investors should consider a limit order. It directs your broker,
human or electronic, to buy or sell only at the price you specify.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't assume your order is canceled when you hit the
``cancel'' button. It's executed only when it gets to the market.
In one recent case, Levitt said, a major brokerage couldn't process
20 percent of its cancellation orders on a fast-breaking initial
public offering.
</P>
<P>
   One customer later told regulators she canceled an order to buy
2,000 shares, then placed a second order for 1,000 shares. She
wanted to invest about $18,000, Levitt said, but she ended up owing
her broker more than $250,000 for 3,000 shares. ``I urge you to
contact your firms to see how they can ensure a cancellation order
actually worked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do your homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest mistake investors make is that they invest
emotionally,'' Levitt told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He recommended, for starters, reading corporate annual reports
and mutual fund prospectuses. He pointed out _ no surprise _ that
the SEC itself provides much more information on its own Web site,
www.sec.gov.
</P>
<P>
   A major attraction there is EDGAR, the commission's humongous
database. It gives investors ready access to the last five years of
filings by most public companies.
</P>
<P>
   You can find, among many other things, whether a company's
auditors have spotted any problems, whether officers and directors
have chosen to buy stock in the company and whether insiders are
buying or selling. It's a treasure trove.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask your broker exactly how he or she is paid. Often the
biggest commissions are paid for selling favored stocks or the
mutual funds operated by the brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the government's job to decide how brokers should be
paid,'' Levitt said. ``But I personally think it is wrong for a
brokerage to pay a higher fee for selling its own in-house
securities. The better firms are stopping this practice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't fall for old scams in new packages. ``Just recently, the
SEC took action against an individual who told investors through
his Web site that a tax-free island would emerge from the sea floor
of the Caribbean,'' Levitt recounted. ``He sold so-called New
Utopia `government' bonds promising returns of 200 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site had gotten more than 100,000 hits before the SEC
stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the cardinal rule of investing: If it sounds too good
to be true, it probably isn't true. Let me add another one here
today. If it sounds crazy, it almost definitely is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Be very cautious about stock tips gleaned from Internet chat
rooms. Too often, the tipster has an interest in the stock, or is a
con artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chat rooms have been compared to a high-tech version of
morning gossip or advice at the company water cooler,'' Levitt
said. ``But at least you knew your co-workers at the water
cooler.''
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
