<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFANT-BEDSHARING09-C     06-08 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFANT-BEDSHARING09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Infant siblings gain comfort, health benefits
from `co-bedding'
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The baby triplets clearly don't like being apart.
When one of them is left alone in the bed they all share, it won't
be long before she'll start moving around and fussing. She seems to
be reaching out for her sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always have to be touching each other, and they'll
smile,'' says their mother, April Lenz. ``When you look at them
together, you can just see the peace that they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The limited research on premature babies who share a bed with
their siblings suggests it's more than just comforting to stay
close with their buddies from the womb as soon as practical after
birth. They also gain weight faster, begin maintaining body heat
earlier and nurse sooner on more nutritious breast milk, says Linda
Lutes, an infant-development specialist and the country's foremost
advocate of what she calls co-bedding.
</P>
<P>
   It all makes sense, certainly. They stay warmer together, and if
the companionship keeps them calmer, Lutes says, ``they'll sleep
for longer periods of time so they're able to grow more.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, twins, triplets and other multiple-birth babies can
leave the hospital sooner. That has been the experience at the
Children's Medical Center in the year it has been co-bedding. It
costs less, the babies are healthier and everybody's happier.
``Nobody likes their baby to cry,'' Lutes says.
</P>
<P>
   So why is this such a new concept? Swedish hospitals have been
bunking multiples together as soon as they can breathe on their own
for more than a generation, but Lutes began introducing the idea to
this country only eight or nine years ago, and other Western
countries were even slower to start.
</P>
<P>
   There have been two main concerns, which still prevail in many
newborn intensive-care units. One is that it would be too easy to
mix up the babies' medications if they were in the same bed. The
other is that the close proximity would make them more susceptible
to infection, which is especially dangerous for a preemie.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough to keep the medications straight by
color-coding everything, Lutes says, and it's turning out that
preemies who share a bed have a lower infection rate ``because
everybody is so careful.'' Which leaves one other obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't sure if this works,'' Lutes says. She
understands that. Doctors don't tend to take anything on faith, and
there isn't much scientific data from her three years of research.
The first study, at Good Samaritan Hospital in Cincinnati, simply
showed sharing beds wasn't harmful. The second study established
success in growth rates, body heat and breast-feeding, but it
involved only seven sets of pre-term twins in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question is how early it's safe to put the preemies
in the same bed. Lutes says as soon as they're breathing without a
ventilator and don't have a catheter in the umbilical line, which
could cause serious bleeding if it came loose.
</P>
<P>
   Bethany and Becca were sharing a bed without Brittany five days
after they were born April 2, at 10 weeks premature, each within
three ounces of three pounds. Brittany, the smallest, joined them
11 days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``They suck on each other's fingers,'' Lenz says. ``That was the
first time one of them nursed, when Brittany had put one of her
fingers in Becca's mouth so she was already sucking.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenz and her husband, Jeff, had decided to bed their babies
together at home simply because their Springfield, Ohio house
wasn't designed for the five children they now have. But they were
planning to put some sort of dividers in the crib ``so it would be
like three little beds,'' she says, until someone gave her a book
that told about bedding triplets together.
</P>
<P>
   In the hospital, the babies were snuggled tightly at first in
one blanket, their hands free to touch each other's faces and
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do that, they immediately will hold hands and embrace
and then go to sleep,'' Lutes says. ``Within five minutes, if you
look at their monitors, their heart rates and breathing rates will
be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiple-birth babies simply develop differently, she says. Even
if they don't share the same sac in the uterus, they touch each
other constantly. Lutes has seen ultrasound images of one fetus
appearing upset and the twin sister offering her thumb to suck, or
stroking his face or holding his foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of them gets the hiccups, all three get the hiccups,''
Lenz says of her babies. ``If one monitor goes off, all three go
off. It's uncanny. One time they were checking the babies' eyes and
before they got to the third one, she was covering her eyes. They
say triplets can feel each other's pain, and it's just amazing to
watch how that works.''
</P>
<P>
   Lutes started figuring this out as a grade-school teacher where
she lives in suburban Oklahoma City. It used to be automatic that
twins were assigned to separate classrooms, but Lutes started
arranging with other teachers to bring both twins into the hallway
for a few minutes if one was having a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't take much. Maybe the upset one would get a hug or a
back scratching or an empathetic look or even a quick
``get-a-grip'' lecture. The other twin always knew what to do,
``and it would just turn their day around,'' Lutes says.
</P>
<P>
   Now 44, she eventually taught sick kids in hospitals, and bed
sharing made even more sense to her. ``There was a time when they
did it, but only when the babies were about ready to go home,'' she
says. Now she hears from hospitals across the country and in much
of Europe that want to start co-bedding earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The children often stay in the same bed until kindergarten or
first grade, she says, but even after that, they're likely to go
back to share a bed again on the night before something exciting or
stressful, from Christmas to the first day of school.
</P>
<P>
   As infants, one of the best things for the Lenz parents is that
they can spend time with all their babies at once. ``I don't have
to count the minutes I spend at each bedside,'' their mother said.
</P>
<P>
   The triplets went home May 21, all of them together even though
Brittany still needed to be hooked up to a monitor. Separating them
at that point wasn't even an option, April says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been together for so long. We can't always be there.
The nurses change. But they don't. They're the only consistency in
each other's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   CONTACT Linda Lutes by e-mail: LU2682(AT)ionet.net
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
