   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TAXIS-CAMERAS (San Francisco) _ Taxis in San Francisco soon be
equipped with tiny infrared digital cameras that photograph drivers
and their passengers under a safety plan to be considered by the
San Francisco Taxicab Commission. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ELEMENTS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ Scientists have discovered two
new elements, the heaviest ever seen. Unromantically dubbed 116 and
118, they were created inside a cyclotron or ``atom smasher'' at
Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory near the UC-Berkeley campus.
By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY (San Francisco) _ Forget it. Stop dreamin'. Save your
buck. You're not gonna win that $65 million SuperLotto jackpot on
Wednesday night. Because Jeff Davis will. How come? Because that's
the way life is. This is California's biggest SuperLotto jackpot in
about a year. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-Y2K (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Albany International Airport
has a Y2K contingency plan that includes hiring high school and
college kids to carry baggage to arriving passengers if the luggage
carousel fails on Jan. 1. By CAROL DeMARE.
</P>
<P>
   YUPPIE-HOAX (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco weekly newspaper
gleefully admits to fabricating a news event and tricking major
media outlets, including the San Francisco Examiner, into covering
it. SF Weekly editor John Mecklin said he and his staff created a
fake advertisement for a pro-Yuppie rally that was to take place on
Sunday afternoon, hoping that the media would take the bait and
cover the non-existent rally. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE-ORGANIC (Berkeley, Calif.) _ One of life's simple
pleasures may soon become increasingly complex. If Mayor Shirley
Dean has her way, city departments will be required to buy only
organic coffee produced under fair trade conditions. Previous
Berkeley initiatives prevent the city from buying Salvadoran coffee
beans or serving beverages in styrofoam cups. By ROBERT SELMA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDITATION-HEALTH (Albany, N.Y.) _ Every afternoon, Edward Koch
sits in a chair in his home and meditates. He had a heart attack in
1994 and health experts at Kaiser Permanente encouraged him to
improve his diet, exercise and meditate to help with his recovery
program. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ADIRONDACK-CHAIRS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The Adirondack chair did
indeed originate within the Adirondack forest preserve in New York.
This sturdy classic features a sloped back and seat angle that is
just as comfortable as an upholstered club chair, making it a
mainstay in outdoor furniture across the country. By FRANCES
INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-PRESERVE (Tory, N.Y.) _ The Albany area can be a
daunting place for an architect because there is a sense that it's
all been done before. But that's good news for preservationists,
whose job it is to keep the past alive. Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute hopes to draw on that past with a new degree program in
architectural renovation, to begin this fall. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader wants to know what kind of
plant that he has. It looks like a spider or airplane plant.
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-MONEY (San Francisco) _ For 20-somethings who haven't
sprained their brains yet on matters financial, here's some
beginner's advice from Dan Goldie: Forget that sizzling start-up
firm or initial public offering (IPO). Most starry-eyed young
investors hear of the occasional high-tech workers who strike it
rich. They don't hear about the many horror stories, the
bankruptcies, the financial failures. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FARMING (San Francisco) _ Following a less than fruitful
1998 season, California farmers can look forward to a more
profitable crop in 1999, according to a survey conducted by Bank of
America. By BOBBY McGILL.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-POISONING (Undated) _ Food safety quiz: What does a
hamburger teeming with sickening amounts of bacteria taste like?
Answer: A hamburger. That's the problem with most food poisoning _
the bacteria that cause the misery of stomach cramps, diarrhea,
nausea, and vomiting cannot be tasted, seen, or smelled, according
to an article in the July issue of Redbook magazine. And what may
cause you a few days of feeling yucky can be a serious, even
life-threatening, illness for your child. By STEPHANIE YOUNG.
(Filed June 4 for release Wednesday, June 9.)
</P>
<P>
   With BC-SWIMMING POOLS and BC-IF-GET.
