   Others range from the white garden, planted in deep ravines that
cut through the estate, to the butterfly garden, named for its
shape and planted with vintage camellias and azaleas, to a topiary
garden.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth a visit to Bayou Bend simply to stroll through the
grounds. People with small children may have to do just that since
those under the age of 10 are not admitted on the house tours,
which are limited to six.
</P>
<P>
   Led by well-informed docents, the tours take visitors through
the two floors of the house into 28 separate areas dedicated to
tracing the evolution of style in America from Colonial days to the
Victorian era.
</P>
<P>
   Each docent, a museum-trained volunteer, provides an individual
touch, going beyond telling visitors what they're looking at, to
discuss how history influenced the furnishings and decorative arts
from each period.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Pine Room, a paneled former library with a bay
window, fireplace and two John Smibert portraits, is described as
typifying the Baroque period; a variety of chairs in the room _
William and Mary to Queen Anne _ are used to trace an emerging
Asian influence on furnishing styles.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the change, visitors learn, is that when Charles
II became King of England, he married a Portuguese princess, which
opened doors to trade in Asia. (Much of American furniture at this
time was still heavily influenced by English styles.)
</P>
<P>
   Miss Hogg started her collection with a simple maple chair made
in New England in the mid-1700's, purchased in 1920 from Collings &AMP;
Collings in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of the museum are a Queen Anne japanned
high chest, circa 1730-1760, one of a handful existing today; a
Newport block front desk and bookcase, one of 11 existing, and the
only John Henry Belter parlor set _ a highly ornate Rococo Revival
suite of two armchairs, two side chairs and a sofa in laminated and
carved rosewood _ with an original bill of sale.
</P>
<P>
   It is also fun to look at some of the more whimsical items, such
as Staffordshire transferware plates commemorating various
historical events, or a 1758 blue and white delft English ceramic
punch bowl with the words ``Fill the Other Bowl Boys'' painted in
underglaze blue on the inside bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Bayou Bend, which depends primarily on donations for
acquisitions, continues to add to the collection, this year
purchasing a pre-Revolutionary Charleston great chair, the earliest
piece of Charleston furniture known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent purchase is a Chinese porcelain stand, such as a
gravy boat might be set on, from George Washington's personal china
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't under the bell jar,'' Mr. Warren said of the
collection, ``so it definitely continues to grow and improve.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, does the Museum of Fine Arts continue to expand its
decorative arts collection. On May 1, the museum opened Rienzi to
the public. This River Oaks estate features 18th-and 19th-century
European furniture, paintings, precious metals and objets d'art. It
is just minutes from Bayou Bend.
</P>
<P>
   House tours, gardens, plus a detour worth a stop
</P>
<P>
   Bayou Bend, at 1 Westcott, (713) 639-7750, is 10 to 15 minutes
from downtown Houston. There is a story with every room, and guided
tours are offered Tuesday through Friday; hours vary. It's best to
call for reservations (a week or two in advance during the school
year).
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, there are self-guided audio tours only, also open
to children, from 1 to 5 p.m. (third Sunday of the month free,
unless special events are scheduled); only audio tours offered in
August. Admission: $10 for tours of the house and gardens; $5 for
ages 10 to 18; under 10, free; $3 for the gardens only.
</P>
<P>
   Rienzi, with its fine collection of 18th- and 19th-century
European decorative arts, is less than a mile from Bayou Bend, at
1406 Kirby Drive. Open Monday, Thursday, Friday and Saturday from
10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Sundays 1 to 5 p.m.; guided tours only (by
reservation). Admission $6; children allowed Sunday only.
Reservations: (713) 639-7800.
 &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Whitaker is a writer living in Houston.) &QL; 
