<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-SCHOOL-$ADV13-CO     06-08 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-SCHOOL-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NO COPIER, FEW BOOKS AND DESKS, SCHOOLING DECLINES IN IRAQ
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With IRAQ-SANCTIONS-$ADV13.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ With their sneakers, cartoon-clad backpacks and
pony tails, these girls would fit in at any American school.
</P>
<P>
   But, when visitors enter classes at the Hidayeh (Enlightenment)
Elementary School in Baghdad, the students rise together with
smiles and shout, ``Welcome and long live the leader, Saddam
Hussein!''
</P>
<P>
   There's something else different about schools in Iraq. This
one, with about 1,200 girls, has one telephone and no copying
machine. Lights are often out in the school, and many students sit
on the floors for lack of even a broken-down desk.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the girls start their studies by erasing the
penciled-in work in last year's workbooks so they can be re-used.
</P>
<P>
   Serious Samar Khatab, a 13-year-old fifth-grader, sums up the
problem saying, ``It is because of the sanctions. The enemy
countries want to take everything from us because we were rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Saddam Hussein invaded Kuwait and the world
slapped economic sanctions on Iraq, aid officials are worried about
the degradation of a generation of students like Samar.
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions supporters will note that there is money squandered in
Iraq. Despite the sanctions, Saddam has opened palaces worth tens
of millions of dollars. Near this school, a couple of bulldozers
scrape at the site of the Saddam Hussein Mosque, planned to be the
biggest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But aid groups say even the money for those projects would not
reverse the overall degradation of this country of 22 million
people. Especially for its children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the most progressive countries in the Middle
East. Today it is in a state of disrepair and dilapidation that is
having a formative effect on the youth,'' Hans von(CQ) Sponeck, the
United Nations Humanitarian Coordinator in Iraq, said in a recent
interview with Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   It is leading, he said, ``to a generation deprived of
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   In America, children are getting hooked into global learning
through computers and the Internet. When a visitor asked children
at Hidayeh Elementary who among them knew what a computer was, only
a few hands were raised.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, these children are lucky to be in school. Enrollment
from first grade through college has dropped from 56 percent in
1990 to 42 percent today. Many children live and beg in the
streets. Other children work.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are in short supply because salaries have dropped to
around $4 a month.
</P>
<P>
   At Hidayeh, a school in a lower-middle class area of central
Baghdad, many classes have more than 55 children. They often show
the lethargy expected in a country where almost a quarter of the
children are undernourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, it will affect their future,'' says deputy school
director Talia Ali Hussein. ``If they are suffering now, how can
they build a society in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
