<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MUSIC-NYTSF     06-08 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MUSIC-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AN EQUAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   By Vikram Seth.
</P>
<P>
   381 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books. $25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; QUARTET FOR FIVE
</P>
<P>
   BY NICHOLAS CHRISTOPHER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of writing fiction about music and musicians has
so often been remarked that it has become a kind of self-fulfilling
observation.
</P>
<P>
   Having to ``describe music'' is said to present countless
difficulties. In an author's note to his new novel, ``An Equal
Music,'' Vikram Seth writes: ``Music to me is dearer even than
speech. When I realized that I would be writing about it I was
gripped with anxiety.'' Because it was dear to him -- or were there
other sources for his anxiety?
</P>
<P>
   In remarks intended for Goethe, Beethoven famously observed:
``Music, verily, is the mediator between intellectual and sensuous
life. . . . Tell him to hear my symphonies and he will say that I
am right in saying that music is the one incorporeal entrance into
the higher world of knowledge which comprehends mankind but which
mankind cannot comprehend.'' Seth seems to understand that writing
about an artist usually means exploring the circumstances of his
art. So he concentrates on the dynamics of the string quartet on
which he centers his book and captures well the backstage theatrics
of a musical performer's life, the intricacies of concert
preparation, the tedium of life on the concert circuit (hotel
rooms, meals, dead time) and the complicated interactions of
musicians and their booking agents and record companies.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to people -- to the specific personal and
professional interrelationships within the quartet -- the novel
falters. In tone and content, the musicians' many conversations
veer between the mundane and the hyperbolic. And predictability and
cliched feelings undermine the romance at the heart of the book.
</P>
<P>
   The plot elements are themselves problematic: a restless,
querulous violinist re-encounters his long-lost love, who is now a
wife and mother. She is a concert pianist -- with the added twist
that she is going deaf. A musician losing her hearing over the
course of a novel, like a painter going blind or a ballerina
succumbing to gradual paralysis, perilously skirts the bathetic.
Which is a pity here, for Seth's violinist, Michael Holme, and his
pianist, Julia McNicholl, are in many ways appealing and
interesting characters.
</P>
<P>
   Michael is a member of the Maggiore Quartet. His partners are
Billy, Helen and Piers. When they play music, Seth is inclined to
give us canned catalogues of their responses and actions: ``Today
we are running through a couple of Haydn quartets and a Brahms. . .
. We love Haydn, and he makes us love each other. Not so Brahms. He
has always been a cross for our quartet. I feel no affinity for
Brahms, Piers can't stand him, Helen adores him, Billy finds him
'deeply interesting,' whatever that means.'' Here is the quartet
again, during a long curtain call one night: ``Helen and I are
grinning from ear to ear, Piers is trying to look statesmanlike and
Billy gets in a couple of sneezes.'' And again: ``All three of us
turn on Billy. 'No way,' say I. 'Ridiculous!' says Piers. 'What?'
says Helen.'' After many such encapsulations -- some unintendedly
comic -- one begins to anticipate them with dread, for they do not
enhance, but rather subvert, the textual power of the music that we
ought to see animating these performers.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Seth deftly delineates Michael's teaching session
with a pupil, Virginie. He allows them to speak clearly about the
score they are working through, and gives us a concise glimpse of
Michael thinking intelligently about both the music and the
frustrations of teaching. One looks in vain for that same concision
when we are presented with Julia and Michael's relationship, the
evolution of their musical careers and the travails of the Maggiore
Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   In his author's note Seth also thanks ``a number of friends''
who ``generously agreed to read the first draft of the manuscript
-- a task I can hardly bear to do, even for my own work.'' This is
a strange admission for any writer, and an unfortunate one in the
case of this book. A more careful reading of his manuscript might
have enabled Seth to eliminate much of the overbaked interior
monologues, gratuitous description and endless patter that
substitutes for dialogue. In reporting the back-and-forth
discussions of the quartet in rehearsal, he offers up not
revelations but seemingly interminable banter:
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Why don't we plan a structure around the tunes?' Billy
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Well, it sort of lacks tunes,' I say. 'Not melody exactly,
but melodicity. Do I mean that? What's the right word?'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Melodiousness,' says Helen. 'And, incidentally, it doesn't
lack tunes.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'But what do you mean by that?' says Piers to me. 'It's all
tune. I mean, I'm not saying I like it, but. . . .'
</P>
<P>
   ``I point my bow at Piers's music. 'Is that tune? I doubt even
Brahms would claim that was tune.'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Well, it's not arpeggio, it's not scale, it's not ornament,
so . . . oh, I don't know. It's all mad and clogged up. Bloody
Edinburgh. . . .'
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Stop ranting, Piers,' ``says Helen.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``mad and clogged up'' is how much of the
dialogue feels in ``An Equal Music.'' We find other examples in a
telephone call Virginie makes to Michael to cancel a lesson; in the
extended, unpleasant debate between Michael and a flight attendant
about the color of a sandwich wrapping; and in the page-long
discussion of the time of day between Michael and Julia as they
wake one morning. The book is also filled with passages like:
``Last year I heard a snatch of Bach, in a taxi of all places. I
rarely take cabs, cabs rarely play music, any music they do play is
rarely classical.'' After a while, they numb the reader and sap the
efficacy of both the love affair and the musical relationships that
the story chronicles.
</P>
<P>
   Vikram Seth is a talented writer who has published books of
poetry and translation in addition to an inventive light-verse
novel, ``The Golden Gate,'' and the sprawling, multitiered novel
``A Suitable Boy.'' He was rightly praised for the fine detail,
clear voice and witty style that marked ``The Golden Gate,'' and
one only wishes he had infused ``An Equal Music'' with more of
those same qualities.
</P>
<P>
   ----- Nicholas Christopher is the author, most recently, of
``The Creation of the Night Sky,'' his sixth book of poems. His new
novel, ``A Trip to the Stars,'' will be published in February.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7116 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     06-08 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BY MARILYN STASIO
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ian Rutledge, the shellshocked Scotland Yard detective in
Charles Todd's haunting post-World War I mysteries, takes his
troubled conscience to a Dorset village in SEARCH THE DARK (Thomas
Dunne/St. Martin's, $24.95) to investigate the death of an unknown
woman and the disappearance of her two children. Although the
victim was beaten beyond recognition, public opinion has it that a
deranged veteran (a ``shabby stranger with frantic eyes'') killed
the entire family in a fit of insane grief, because they reminded
him of the loved ones he lost in the war. Only Rutledge, himself
heavily burdened with survivor guilt, has the compassion to
recognize the man's innocence and the insight to search for the
true murderer among the locals, a striking collection of insular
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dorset countryside in 1919 is pictured as a place
of quiet healing, the secretive people who live there are buffeted
by ``passion, hot and raw,'' and the very air is poisoned by their
deceit, suspicion, malicious envy and calculated cruelty. Todd
works these volatile elements into a remarkable village mystery,
classically constructed around a central puzzle but driven by
characters of great psychological complexity. ``We all walk with
shadows,'' one tormented soul confides to Rutledge, who is
honorable enough to let his own ghosts choose the path of his
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to go wrong with a story that opens with a bunch of
nuns huddled around an empty grave in the dead of a Montreal
winter. Kathy Reichs follows up that first, eye-catching scene of
DEATH DU JOUR (Scribner, $25) with more Gothic jolts, from a fire
that yields two mutilated babies among the dead to the chewed-up
corpses of college students attacked by dogs. In one cop's laconic
understatement: ``Just when you think you've seen it all, you learn
that you haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   This sequel to ``Dej Dead'' is not as grisly as it sounds,
largely because the analysis of these atrocities is entrusted to
Temperance Brennan, like the author a certified forensic
anthropologist who teaches in North Carolina and moonlights for the
Province of Quebec in a police lab in Montreal. Sanitized by the
scientific paraphernalia in the morgue (and reanimated by Tempe's
lively table talk during autopsies), the body parts lose their
grotesque horror to become puzzle pieces in the arcane but
fascinating practice of reading bones. All the same, Reichs does
manage to go wrong: by hitching these realistic procedures to the
bizarre doings of a sinister religious cult, by stuffing the story
with so many characters that even the living ones seem half-dead,
by kicking the bloated plot back and forth between Montreal and
North Carolina and by weighting the carcass with too many
coincidences to get it to float.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Wallander, the melancholy detective in Henning Mankell's
Swedish policiers, takes it personally when a crime is committed on
his turf. In SIDETRACKED (New Press, $25), the work of a serial
killer who dispatches his victims with an ax (and carries off their
scalps as trophies) throws him into a deep depression. ``For a
brief moment he felt an indescribable sorrow inside'' is how
Mankell describes Wallander's state of mind when he realizes that
an entirely foreign kind of violence has surfaced in Ystad, his own
fair city on the Baltic Sea. ``The world had both shrunk and
expanded at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mankell observes local police routines in close detail, while
taking a parallel path to follow the insane logic and precise
methods of the killer. But it is Wallander's anguished voice,
delivered from the bottom of an emotional well in Steven T.
Murray's pensive translation, that captures us. While all of Sweden
is following World Cup soccer and preparing for its collective
summer vacation, this sober cop can't get over the girl who torched
herself in a farmer's field. (``She kept running and running. And
burning and burning.'') Brooding on the alienation of the young,
the fragmentation of families and the ``great loneliness'' that
attends this breakdown of modern society, Mankell's philosophical
hero vows to make it up to the coming generation while he still
can.
</P>
<P>
   Two pages into Stan Jones's WHITE SKY, BLACK ICE (Soho, $22),
you can feel the bite of the west wind that comes screaming across
the Alaska tundra and sense the isolation of the Inupiat Eskimos
who live in this desolate part of the far north. Nathan Active, the
state trooper who brings much of the warmth to this stark debut
novel, has kept his distance from Chukchi, the miserable little
town where he was born and from which he thought he'd escaped when
he was adopted by a white family in Anchorage. But a job
reassignment drags Nathan (a nalauqmiiyaaq, or half-breed, to his
old neighbors) back to face a rash of suicides and hints of trouble
at the copper mine that has brought hope to the hard-luck
community. The crimes that come to light are nasty, but nowhere
near as interesting as the cycles of life in this fierce climate,
or as appealing as the Inupiat characters who speak in a
``stripped-down village English'' that after a while starts to make
real sense to Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   With its fine churches and stately homes, its new industries and
bustling downtown, South Bend, Ind., in 1900 looks like paradise to
Hilda Johansson, a young Swedish maid who keeps house for the
prominent Studebaker family and makes a spirited amateur sleuth in
DEATH IN LACQUER RED (Walker, $22.95), by Jeanne M. Dams. In her
first adventure, Hilda finds the battered body of a missionary
lady, the sister of the grand political personage who lives next
door, and takes it upon herself to solve the crime before people
look for a scapegoat among the city's immigrant population. The
detection work is catch as catch can, because as Hilda sensibly
points out: ``Me, I can talk to other servants, I can learn things.
. . . What I cannot do is go far, or talk to people I do not
know.'' But Hilda loves life, and the joy she takes in the simple
pleasures of Sunday picnics and summer holidays and a loud, lusty
hymn is treat enough for now.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
