<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BOUTROS-NYTSF     06-08 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BOUTROS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 UNVANQUISHED
<TEXT>
<P>
   A U.S.-U.N. Saga.
</P>
<P>
   By Boutros Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE UNMAKING OF A SECRETARY
</P>
<P>
   BY BARBARA CROSSETTE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Boutros Boutros-Ghali, hounded out of office by the Clinton
Administration in 1996, the only United Nations Secretary General
ever to be denied a second term, sets out in this book to tell his
side of that miserable tale.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, the account is an act of self-justification.
Boutros-Ghali, an erudite Egyptian who served the United States
well during the boldest years of peacemaking between Israel and
Egypt, can now, two decades later, portray himself as a wronged
international civil servant who got in the way of American
politics. Perfidious Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Unvanquished,'' Boutros-Ghali does not limit himself to
that part of the story, however. Rather, he surveys in detail and
from an international perspective how the Clinton White House
operated during years of crises in Somalia, Rwanda, Bosnia and
beyond. Appearing as it does now, in the shadow of a Balkan war and
as historians begin to assess the Clinton record in foreign
affairs, the book is likely to be mined for its revealing if
anecdotal portrayal of a politically thin-skinned and often
indecisive President.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Boutros-Ghali says, he was warned against
rattling the president by Secretary of State Warren Christopher and
Madeleine K. Albright, who was Washington's chief representative at
the United Nations before moving to the State Department as
Christopher's successor.
</P>
<P>
   They bluntly told the Secretary General where not to travel,
what envoys to appoint, whom to avoid meeting and what to say or
not say in speeches. He was advised to keep his distance from
Congress, where the Republican leadership had painted him as a
threat to American sovereignty and made sport of his name.
Americans would not take orders from ``Boootrous Boootrous-Ghali,''
Bob Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   On a visit to Washington during the Somalia crisis, the
Secretary General was asked not to meet the editorial board of The
Washington Post and not to mention the $1 billion-plus American
debt to the United Nations in a speech to the United Nations
Association, a private citizens support and research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Boutros-Ghali, a strong-willed man very conscious of his
self-image (``not the easiest person to deal with,'' as he himself
says), ignored most of these demands, adding to the friction that
ultimately cost him his job. Even his associates admit that he
veered between contempt for his adversaries and a highly developed
sense of victimization when things went wrong. In any event, he
continued to seek meetings with the President or other high
administration officials to clarify what seemed to him by 1994 to
be an ``utterly confused'' foreign policy, or to put forward his
own ideas. He was usually rebuffed, or at best treated with
disdain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from a developing country, I was trained extensively in
international law and diplomacy and mistakenly assumed that the
great powers, especially the United States, also trained their
representatives in diplomacy and accepted the value of it,''
Boutros-Ghali writes bitterly after describing a particularly
unpleasant exchange with Christopher and Albright. ``But the Roman
Empire had no need for diplomacy. Neither does the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   No administration officials, except some in the Pentagon, come
off looking good. Boutros-Ghali says that his relations with
Albright began well. ``I was puzzled, however, by what seemed her
desire to strike attitudes rather than address substantive
issues,'' he writes. Her warmth, he soon discovered, ``turned to
fury the instant problems surfaced.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Christopher proved to be hard to get to know and appeared
at times to be in the dark about conflicts within the
administration. In Haiti, for example, Boutros-Ghali's
representatives discerned deep differences between the Central
Intelligence Agency and the State Department over the reliability
of the deposed president, Jean-Bertrand Aristide. Christopher
seemed surprised and annoyed to hear this.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1993 Somalia crisis, created in no small measure by
the United States -- although Boutros-Ghali does accept some of the
blame for allowing Italy, the former colonial power, to send troops
with their own agendas to the conflict -- the Secretary General
thought that both Christopher and Albright ``seemed unsure of their
roles.'' The subsequent deaths of 18 American Army Rangers in
Mogadishu, although under United States and not United Nations
command, poisoned the atmosphere for future American participation
in peacekeeping, most tragically in Rwanda the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Boutros-Ghali's anger over the Clinton Administration's pattern
of voting for tough Security Council resolutions and then refusing
to support the action called for, epitomized most clearly in
Bosnia, is often disguised in a deadpan writing style that allows
the reader to draw the intended conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The former Secretary General now spends most of his time in
Paris, where he was educated at the Sorbonne, writing and running
an international organization of francophone countries. An intense,
scholarly diplomat prone to answering casual questions with
lectures on history, art or geopolitics, Boutros-Ghali never tried
to mix into American social life. His aloofness and intellectual
arrogance, as well as his championing of the third world, were
widely held against him among politicians and policy analysts
alike.
</P>
<P>
   In the light of this, it is interesting to note that his
successor, Kofi Annan of Ghana, the Clinton Administration's
choice, has not fared too well with Washington either. Annan, a
graduate of Macalester College in St. Paul, is very much at home in
America. But he has also been short-changed by the White House and
stonewalled by a Congress demanding virtual control over the United
Nations, adding credence to Boutros-Ghali's sense that the problem
is not Republican or Democrat, but American.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one great gap in this book, it is Boutros-Ghali's
failure to analyze rigorously why so many other nations, among them
his soul mates, the French, are letting this happen. He ventures
only to suggest that American power overwhelms all in its path.
``Single-superpower hegemony is a transitory phenomenon, but
globalization is an irreversible force on a scale heretofore
unseen,'' Boutros-Ghali concludes. Globalization introduces
unfamiliar problems, and ``the only truly global mechanism for
addressing them is the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Crossette is the United Nations bureau chief for The New
York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
