<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ADOPTION-NYTS     06-08 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ADOPTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ADOPTING ALYOSHA
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Single Man Finds a Son in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   By Robert Klose.
</P>
<P>
   University Press of Mississippi. $22.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; FROM RUSSIA, WITH LOVE
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVE EGGERS
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, some of them valid, we're suspicious
of single men with young boys. Being a single male parent means
occupying the lowest spot on the totem pole of parental
preferability. If a child must have only one parent (and that
parent is not the star of a breakthrough television dramedy), the
mother is preferred over the father. If that single parent is
neither mother nor father, a female relative is preferred over a
male one. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   This partly explains why adoptions by single men are rare, and
why Robert Klose's account of the long, grueling road he took to
adopt a child is so often enthralling. Klose, an associate
professor of biological science at University College of Bangor, in
Maine, is intelligent, well spoken in matters of child care and
financially secure. In the early stages of his adoption process, he
clears all hurdles with ease. But even after his local agency
approves him for adoption, his climb up what he calls ``the greased
flagpole'' has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   As with many hopeful adoptive parents, his chances of adopting a
foreign boy are much greater than those of adopting an
American-born child. But even then, most countries have their own
idiosyncratic restrictions. Thailand disallows any adoptions by
single parents. The Polish agencies prefer Roman Catholics. The
Peruvians reportedly ``will let anyone adopt,'' but at the time of
Klose's search their programs were closed as the result of
political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with multiple agencies and intermediaries, Klose
ricochets between promises made and hopes repeatedly dashed. One
day he's on the verge of adopting a 7-year-old in Guatemala.
Another day, a 3-year-old in Honduras. The conversations, like this
one with a woman handling Bolivian adoptions, sound eerily like
negotiations for the purchase of, say, stereo equipment:
</P>
<P>
   ``They have three boys, all in the age group you're approved
for: Johnny and Jose, both 6, and Daniel, who's 5.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And they'll definitely allow a single man to adopt?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely. These boys are ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't pan out. Much of the time, the process is ridiculous,
given the gravity of the task at hand. One organization is run out
of the home of a woman in California who works with someone named
Jorge, an orphan-finding partner in Guatemala. Klose, trusting and
desperate, invests $3,000 with the organization, which is sent to
Jorge, who promptly disappears with it.
</P>
<P>
   That $3,000 is a fraction of what many agencies want --
adoptions from Hungary, Klose writes, cost as much as $20,000 --
and he ends up spending more than $12,000. Indeed, the issue of
money begets some of the book's most unintentionally disturbing
passages. ``The only way to satisfy them,'' Klose writes of one
agency, ``seemed to be to throw myself at their mercy and take
whatever child they could come up with. But I had no interest in
satisfying them. I wanted to satisfy myself. . . . I am the
consumer. . . . I am the consumer. . . . I am the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   As we follow his progress, for a time ``Adopting Alyosha'' reads
like a thriller. We forget the outcome made clear in the book's
title and get caught up in wondering which boy will come to live in
the bedroom Klose has already decorated. But once the adoption of
Alyosha is imminent, the book loses steam and focus -- the suspense
over, the second half seems like filler. Eleven pages are devoted
to Klose's plane ride to Russia, including dubious commentary on
the airport bathrooms in Shannon, Ireland. As much as we liked
Klose in the first half -- his passion and tenacity endear him to
us -- we lose patience with him in the second. The minute-by-minute
accounting of his time in Russia is excessive, and his observations
(``Chekhov is far and away my favorite Russian author'') are
increasingly banal.
</P>
<P>
   Described by the publisher as the first book to be written about
a single man adopting from abroad, ``Adopting Alyosha'' might be
considered requisite reading for anyone planning to do what Klose
did. (If it was this difficult for a well-educated, financially
solvent heterosexual man, God knows what the average hopeful has in
store.) It might even be worthwhile for single women, or even
couples, hoping to adopt foreign children. As casual reading for
anyone else, it rarely transcends its guidebook flavor, though in
offering further proof of the innumerable ways one can (and often
must) make a family, ``Adopting Alyosha'' is instructive. And we
can always use such instruction.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Dave Eggers, the editor of McSweeney's Quarterly, is finishing a
book that is in part about being a single parent.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
