<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7120 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LOCAL-NYTSF     06-08 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LOCAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LOCAL GIRLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Alice Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   197 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   G. P. Putnam's Sons. $22.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; ISLANDERS
</P>
<P>
   BY SARAH FERGUSON
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lightning strikes, a cat talks and Grandma's ghost sabotages a
family dinner in ``Local Girls,'' Alice Hoffman's collection of
stories set in a sleepy Long Island suburb. Arranged in
chronological order over the course of a decade or so, the stories
center on -- and are frequently narrated by -- Gretel Samuelson,
who first appears as a precocious adolescent with a deadpan
delivery that brings to mind the baton-twirling delinquent played
by Sissy Spacek in Terrence Malick's ``Badlands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was humid and warm; every mosquito in town seemed
to have hatched, and each one was hungry for blood,'' she says in a
typical burst of backyard portentousness. ``It was the sort of
night that feels like a dream, when you're suddenly about to do
things you only thought yourself capable of imagining. Before you
know it you're inside of something that feels as unavoidable as
destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Franconia, Gretel's hometown, is the sort of place where the
summer air smells like cut grass and people sit outside on their
front porches at night, their conversations punctuated by the
chirping of cicadas. Naturally, all hell is breaking loose inside
those picture-perfect little houses, and Gretel's got a nice way of
pointing out the dark side of the so-called good life -- the nut
jobs hanging around the luncheonette, the head of the P.T.A. who
gets hustled off for shock treatments, the divorced woman who cooks
with such passion ``you'd have thought it was the heart of her ex
she was sauteing instead of mushrooms for a strudel.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretel's mother's health is failing, her parents are squaring
off for a messy divorce ``like pit bulls trapped in an L-shaped
living room'' and her brother is about to throw away early
admission to Harvard for a job in the deli department at the Food
Star and a blossoming drug habit. Basically, whatever can go wrong
has -- or is just about to. Even that never-ending cicada song,
Gretel says, ``could lead you to believe little bombs were going
off on your neighbors' front lawns.''
</P>
<P>
   Told in alternating voices, the stories form a scrapbook of
pivotal moments in the lives of Gretel and her nearest and dearest.
In ``Rose Red,'' Gretel and her best friend, Jill, are 12, ``that
unpredictable and dangerous age when sampling shades of lipstick
and playing with dolls seem equally interesting.'' As the stories
unfold, Gretel and Jill trade in their dolls and candy for boys and
beer. In ``True Confession,'' 17-year-old Gretel falls head over
heels in love with the local amphetamine dealer, a smooth talker
who drives a brand-new Camaro and gets her to let him ``do things
she didn't even know people did.'' In ``Fate,'' Jill gets pregnant,
drops out of the 11th grade and marries her dimwitted boyfriend,
Eddie, ``the boy that everyone wanted, but not for keeps.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd mystical moments crop up now and then as Gretel, starved for
miracles, seesaws between wonder and sorrow. In ``Dear Diary,'' she
swears she heard Jill's cat say ``Let me out!'' as it stood at the
kitchen door. In ``How to Talk to the Dead,'' she's positive she
saw her Grandma Frieda's ghost sabotaging her dad's diet by
slipping sticks of butter into his new wife's cooking. Supernatural
walk-ons like these seem calculated to infuse Hoffman's sad-sack
chronicles with a hint of magic realism, but for the most part they
feel forced and out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Originally published in Ladies' Home Journal, Redbook,
Cosmopolitan and Kenyon Review, among others, the stories suffer
from a debilitating overlap when they're read as a collection. As
in a soap opera, where any episode may be the viewer's first,
background information is repeated and characters are reintroduced
ad nauseam, leaving the reader trapped on what feels like a
never-ending receiving line, making the acquaintance of the same
loop of oppressed suburbanites. It's as if Hoffman felt compelled
to back up her car and nose it down the Samuelsons' driveway over
and over again. After a while, you start to wish she knew some
other people in the neighborhood, or at least knew the Samuelsons
well enough to stay a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ferguson is a writer and critic who lives in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
