<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7121 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DUBLIN-NYTSF     06-08 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DUBLIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   44
</P>
<P>
   Dublin Made Me.
</P>
<P>
   By Peter Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   Viking. $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; MY HEART BELONGS TO DA
</P>
<P>
   BY TOBIN HARSHAW
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   I guess it shouldn't be a surprise that an Irishman, especially
one who happens to be a man of the theater, would begin his book
with a small fib. The subtitle of Peter Sheridan's memoir states
that he was ``made'' by his hometown, Dublin, where he was raised
in a small house near the River Liffey, at 44 Seville Place. But
Sheridan could have grown up in a yurt on the Mongolian steppe and
he wouldn't have turned out any differently, so long as he grew up
with his Da. For his father is the black hole by which all energy,
expression and thought in the Sheridan household are consumed,
digested, deconstructed and, most important, judged on their
merits, or conspicuous lack thereof. Luckily for Peter Sheridan --
and the reader -- Da is neither a bitter tyrant nor a drunken sod.
He may be a braggart and a blowhard (``God the Father on the
throne, a bottle of stout for his crozier''), but he is also that
rarest of birds in this age of victimography, a decent man.
</P>
<P>
   As befits the memoir of a leading Irish stage director and
playwright, ``44: Dublin Made Me'' takes a theatrical form. It is a
series of set pieces, all peaking with a bout of hilarity or
aggression or sorrow; and although these sketches never deliver the
emotional climax they strive for, it's still a good deal of fun
never quite getting there. The kitchen of 44 Seville Place is an
ideal proscenium: it's crowded yet comfortable and has a steady
stream of siblings, boarders, neighbors, priests, salesmen and
refugees from the Troubles in Ulster -- in other words, plenty of
character actors against which father and son can play out their
drama.
</P>
<P>
   The lodgers are sufficiently motley. There's Mossie Thomas
Sullivan, a pudgy country bumpkin who walks ``like a farmer
struggling through a wet bog'' but who seems to know when the fix
is in at any race track in Ireland; Noel Dargan, a hulking soldier,
a veteran of the Congo with a 30-inch scar on his leg; Noel's
brother, Liam, who is ``a plasterer, was never anything else, but
wanted to be a drummer in a show band''; and Mahony, an idler who
oversees Da's racing ledger. (``He was as committed as the monks
who created the first Bibles. If it worked out as well as he and Da
hoped, it would be more useful and more valuable than the Book of
Kells.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although he is the second boy among seven children, Peter is
favored over his introspective older brother, Shea (who would grow
up to become the film director Jim Sheridan), and gets to play a
sort of moppet Hermes to his father's tin-pot Zeus. He delivers his
father's meticulously worded notes to shopkeepers. (``He used
bookies' paper for notes because he thought people would take pity
on him and charge less.'') He helps dig up the garage in search of
clogged water pipes and then, after the discovery that the
blueprints have been misread, helps dig it up all over again. He
risks death to install a television antenna on the roof, and later
is nearly demolished by a wayward chimney pot.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a mother in all this. And she is as saintly
as one would expect. But such mothers spend little time at center
stage, and Sheridan's inability to illustrate her full complexity
is most evident when death strikes the family. Her mourning never
takes on the poignancy of Da's overwhelming grief. Even in their
mutual silence, he drowns her out.
</P>
<P>
   Much to Da's chagrin, the 60's will not be dissuaded from
happening, and the attendant cultural shift corrodes his iron grip
over the family. He can only howl Lear-like into the wind,
insisting that the Beatles are charlatan poseurs, lip-syncing their
way to a fortune. Reconciliation comes when the boys discover the
theater; it is the only one of his sons' interests that Da can't
resist. After all, he raised them to it -- and not even Da could
argue with that.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin Harshaw is an editor with the Op-Ed page of The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
