<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LAYOVER-NYTSF     06-08 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LAYOVER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LAYOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Lisa Zeidner.
</P>
<P>
   268 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $24.
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; HEARTBREAK HOTELS
</P>
<P>
   BY KAREN KARBO
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Claire Newbold, the rather obviously named heroine of Lisa
Zeidner's subtle, astute new novel (her fourth), is a 41-year-old
medical supplies saleswoman who, after the death of her 3-year-old
son in a car accident and her husband Ken's subsequent short-lived
affair, just fails to come home after a business trip. Claire has
developed a passion for swimming in hotel pools, and one afternoon
simply swims too long and misses her flight. It's a baby step from
here to spending an extra night in her room, even though the front
desk has already automatically checked her out:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a hard-core wage earner of the type hotel ads target. My
husband was a cardiothoracic surgeon. My wallet was a garden of
credit cards budding possibility, the holographic birds' wings
glinting as if poised for flight. No one would ever suspect me of
fraud, though I knew enough about the rhythms of that hotel, the
staffs' frenzies and downtimes, the secret pockets, to take
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Claire is content to see how long she can squat in a
hotel room without getting caught. She cozies up to the
housekeepers, hatches stories about forgotten keys, snacks on room
service leftovers. Once, the inevitable happens, and she wakes up
late in the morning to see ``a chubby, chinless man in his 50's
with lots of hair'' staring down at her while she sleeps. '' 'I'm
sorry,' he said. 'There must be some mistake.' He held up his key
card, as if to prove that it had admitted him to the room.'' Claire
is amused, unafraid: this is simply one more aspect of her unlikely
voyage to the bottom of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Claire's willful refusal to go home to her husband, her lack of
interest in keeping her appointments, answering her phone messages,
pages, E-mail, are initially liberating. It's relatively easy to
root for her: you go girl! But after she's seduced Zachary, an
18-year-old soon-to-be premed student at Brown, in the pool of the
Four Seasons in Philadelphia -- in part by telling him that she,
and not her husband, is a surgeon -- Claire becomes, even to this
captivated reader, the stereotypical difficult woman. And that's
when ``Layover'' really begins to soar.
</P>
<P>
   There are few aspects of a novel more compelling than watching
the writer go out on a limb, wondering how dare she. Claire's
odyssey of lust, seduction, desire, control -- young Zachary is
just the warm-up -- never veers from what we think of as classic
male acting out, which forces us to examine why we would more
easily accept such behavior in a bereaved father than in a bereaved
mother. Even though the child for whom Claire would be required to
perform her maternal functions is dead, she is still, always, a
mother, which brings up the questions: Why isn't she grieving in a
more acceptable manner? Why isn't she home organizing support
groups or raising money for a preschool scholarship fund endowed in
her deceased child's name? Why isn't she sitting on a bench at a
playground discreetly weeping into her shredded Kleenex?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Claire hatches schemes to seduce strangers, lies for
days on her bed in her hotel room half-asleep, brooding in a
self-absorbed manner about the connections between sex, maternal
love, disease. She won't return her worried husband's phone calls.
She angles a dinner date with Zachary and Margot, his bitter mess
of a divorced mother, and in a devilishly perfect scene, as rich
and satisfying as the expensive meal the three of them are
consuming at the most exclusive French restaurant in town, Claire
explains it all for Margot:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mar. May I offer a piece of advice? As a still-married woman?
If what you want . . . is to be tenderly held, I can tell you that
you're going about it the wrong way. . . . Certainly you must know
that. Talking so much is one thing. . . . But the neediness! It's
stultifying! Where do you expect to get, presenting yourself like
this? If you think the problem is your body -- your thighs, your
wrinkles -- then work on your body. Lift weights. Do some low-rep
sets two, three times a week. Build bone density. Build
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   People who think about such things differ over which human
condition is the most difficult to write about convincingly.
Religious conversion, quote unquote heart-stopping terror, romantic
love that lasts -- these are all tough, but my vote goes to grief,
particularly the grief of a parent over the loss of a child. What
is there to say other than it's so sad? There is no chance for a
happy ending, ever, when a child has died.
</P>
<P>
   Zeidner knows this, and is both wise and shrewd in depicting her
grief-stricken bad girl, a powerful one-two punch that makes
``Layover'' work. After the death of a child, nothing matters, and
if nothing matters, anything goes. Even if you're a middle-aged,
middle-class woman with good sense and a well-paying job. Or,
perhaps, especially if you're one:
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken and I hadn't gone out much. Without discussion, it had
been clear to both of us that it was pointless, too trashy a
consolation. Nothing like grief to turn to dust the dry, weightless
world of things. Vases, cars, clothes? All husks. Exotic fish and
game in ambrosial sauces, baby greens and out-of-season fruit flown
in with the kind of care reserved for donated organs? Who cares.
Who cares.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it may seem that Claire's voyage is a simple
sexual one, when in fact it's a story of possibilities: what's left
in the world after death? Still, the novel rocks with a lot of
great, sexy scenes, in which Zeidner's fine writing is on glorious
display. There are the expected lyrical erotic bits, but also very
funny moments that roller-coaster from the peak of hilarity to the
low loop of plain truth. When Claire and Zachary are back at her
hotel room after their swim, ostensibly to pick up her running
shoes to go for a run in the park across from the hotel (she
doesn't have any, but invented a pair to get him into her room),
she observes:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in bathing suits, so the journey to bed shouldn't take
long. I was aware of trying to be perfectly clear about the
invitation, while at the same time hanging back enough so that I
didn't scare him, or repulse him -- I feared that with Let me be
perfectly clear I could seem, coming at him for the kiss, like
Richard Nixon through a fisheye lens, old and hairy, tremulous.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH ``Layover,'' Zeidner joins the ranks of Doris Lessing,
Margaret Atwood and Fay Weldon, all of whom have written in the
women-spiraling-into-madness genre. But Claire is something new.
Unlike would-be female nut cases from an earlier time, she doesn't
set off on her journey needing to shuck her good-wife persona -- as
early as page 17 she admits: ``I was no longer, in some sense, even
a woman. I'd buried myself in work as a man would . . . and
rejected everything frilly, decorative. So I was no longer fragile.
In fact, I felt almost armor-plated, and that's a shame, because
grief at least ought to make you empathetic.'' Not to mention that
she's in her 40's; yet we never for a moment question either her
allure or her own accurate sense of it.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zeidner attempts to tantalize the reader with the
suggestion that Claire may collapse into madness, or even terminal
illness, never to reclaim herself or her life -- there is some
unpersuasive business about a cancer scare near the end, drummed up
by Claire during the height of her disconnectedness -- one of the
most satisfying parts of the novel is the thin line that the author
manages to tread so adroitly. Zeidner pulls no punches; Claire errs
and errs. She is on the verge of being patently insufferable.
Still, we have faith that any woman who is this clever, this smart
about the nature of despair, will somehow pull through. Claire has
gone off the deep end, but we never doubt that she can swim.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Karen Karbo is the author of two novels. Her latest nonfiction
book, ``Notes From Ex Isle,'' will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7123 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-KING-NYTSF     06-08 1911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KING-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HANNIBAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Thomas Harris.
</P>
<P>
   480 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Delacorte Press. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; HANNIBAL THE CANNIBAL
</P>
<P>
   BY STEPHEN KING
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room, there are flowers and candlelight and
harpsichord music -- ``If Love Now Reigned,'' composed by Henry
VIII in 1510. A woman enters, dressed in a long dinner gown of
cream silk and wearing emerald earrings. Her companion is casual
but elegant in his dark trousers, white shirt and ascot. ``What are
we having?'' the woman asks. Her host, Dr. Lecter -- known in some
quarters as Hannibal the Cannibal -- raises his finger to his lips.
``You never ask,'' he replies. ``It spoils the surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. And what is true of gourmet meals and cannibal feasts is
equally true of the suspense novel: knowing too much beforehand
spoils the surprise. The worst thing I could do is summarize this
novel in any detail, and were I the book's editor, I would argue
very strongly for flap copy consisting of only three words:
</P>
<P>
   ``HERE IT IS.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely that would suffice for Thomas Harris's fans, who have
waited 11 years for the rematch between Clarice Starling, intrepid
F.B.I. agent (``cornpone, but with a little taste''), and Hannibal
Lecter, the great fictional monster of our time. Most of Harris's
devotees have read his entire oeuvre, and why not? Until now it
consisted of only three novels. In a culture where a handful of
popular novelists pump out a book or two a year, producing them
like hormone-juiced hens laying eggs, Harris's rare appearances in
the marketplace make him a singularity: a novelist whose work can
be grasped entire not just by English department profs and
tenure-bound grad students but by the humble folk who entertain
themselves with novels on airplanes and in overcrowded waiting
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is not for all these people, of course -- I don't think
many of the Danielle Steel crowd will be rushing out to buy a book
in which one character is eaten from the inside out by a ravenous
moray eel -- but for those who like what Harris can do so
brilliantly, no book report is required. The readers who have been
waiting for ``Hannibal'' only want to know if it is as good as
``Red Dragon'' and ``The Silence of the Lambs'' (we can exclude
Harris's other novel, a terrorist thriller called ``Black Sunday,''
from this discussion; it seems to have been written before the
author himself clearly understood what he was up to). It is a
pleasure to reply in the negative. No, not as good. This one is
better. It is, in fact, one of the two most frightening popular
novels of our time, the other being ``The Exorcist,'' by William
Peter Blatty. Sequels are usually lame ducks, poor things that are
unable to keep up with their predecessors. ``Hannibal'' is really
not a sequel at all, but rather the third and most satisfying part
of one very long and scary ride through the haunted palace of
abnormal psychiatry.
</P>
<P>
   In the books that form the Lecter trilogy, we see the doctor
take form slowly, advancing from a minor, almost incidental
character in ``Red Dragon'' to a major player in ``The Silence of
the Lambs,'' where his evil and intelligence quickly overshadow the
less interesting presence of Jame Gumb (a serial killer known as
Buffalo Bill because he is reputed to skin his victims), to the
central figure in the book that bears his name. In a late-century
literary landscape where most psycho-villains are little fellows in
rubber masks, armed with knives and burdened with cumbersome sexual
kinks, Dr. Lecter casts a long shadow indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact,'' Harris writes in his carefully measured prose,
``there is no consensus in the psychiatric community that Dr.
Lecter should be termed a man. He has long been regarded by his
professional peers in psychiatry, many of whom fear his acid pen in
the professional journals, as something entirely Other. For
convenience they term him a 'monster.' '' So the word is out, and
it's le mot juste. If Hannibal Lecter isn't a Count Dracula for the
computer-and-cell-phone age, then we don't have one.
</P>
<P>
   HARRIS, the Thomas Pynchon of the popular novel in terms of both
his low visibility and his sparse production, is in charge of his
story and his material from the book's opening: ``Clarice
Starling's Mustang boomed up the entrance ramp at the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms . . . a headquarters rented from the
Rev. Sun Myung Moon in the interest of economy.'' It seems so much
as if he has never been away, even in this first sentence, that one
wonders just why he has been. And, perhaps, where he has been.
</P>
<P>
   If one mourns for the books that might have been during those
years when we have had to put up with pale Lecter-substitutes (one
good rule of thumb for book buyers might be never to buy a novel
with ``In the tradition of'' on the cover), one must also
acknowledge that Harris's antihero has gained an even darker aspect
as a result of his long wait offstage.
</P>
<P>
   No character in popular fiction is as fragile as the monster, or
so prone to losing his pants in his later appearances. Freddy
Krueger is authentically terrifying when he first flashes his
scalpel fingernails in ``A Nightmare on Elm Street,'' but by the
third installment of the series he has become a pal and by the
sixth he has become a joke. In 11 years Hannibal Lecter's notoriety
has grown rather than lessened, and he is no joke -- although, like
all great monsters, he is not without a certain soulless sense of
humor. Barney, his old attendant, recalls Dr. Lecter once saying
that ``whenever it was 'feasible,' he preferred to eat the rude.
'Free-range rude,' he called them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hannibal'' is a novel full of rough bumps and little insights
as sharp as one of the doctor's own needles; Harris observes
America with a cultured civility and perfect grasp of Southern
idiom that only Tom Wolfe can match. And Harris understands plot as
well as language. The result is a book as insightful as ``A Man in
Full,'' but rather more successful; there is never the feeling that
the author is carrying his story on his back like a heavy piece of
furniture, teeth gritted and cords popping out on his neck.
``Hannibal'' is a balloon Harris bats steadily onward, probably
with a grin on his face. The balloon happens to be full of poison
gas and bad dreams, true, but as has been previously suggested,
Harris is not writing for everyone. This is authentic witch's brew,
eye of newt and haunch of redneck, not chicken soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hannibal'' is a full-out, unabashed horror novel, in other
words. One erstwhile patient of Dr. Lecter's describes how the
doctor persuaded him to peel off his face with a piece of mirror
glass, then feed it to his dogs. This isn't horrible, only gross.
The horror comes when the patient adds, ``They got my nose back
when they pumped the dogs' stomachs at the animal shelter, but the
graft didn't take.'' Yet Harris is also capable of turns of phrase
you won't find in the latest Patricia Cornwell. ``He . . . carried
the scars of a man who, in the haste and fear of his ambition, once
seized his gift by the blade,'' Harris writes of the unfortunate
Florentine policeman who tries to collar Lecter for the reward. Nor
is Harris unaware or unmindful of what our own interest in such
dark fare may mean for our culture and our civilization: ``Now that
ceaseless exposure has calloused us to the lewd and the vulgar, it
is instructive to see what still seems wicked to us. What still
slaps the clammy flab of our submissive consciousness hard enough
to get our attention?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Hannibal Lecter does, for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Two mountains are likely to arise this summer in the generally
flat topography of the Great American Masscult: George Lucas's
fourth ``Star Wars'' movie and this third episode of Harris's smart
and scary retelling of ``Beauty and the Beast'' (a character in
``Hannibal'' actually notes this similarity, although in an
unfairly dismissive fashion). Lucas's space cadets will most likely
rule the box office, and Harris's lunatics (these include Dr.
Lecter's old friend Sammie, who once put his mother's head in the
church collection plate) will most likely rule the best-seller
lists. Of the two, the novel is the more finely nuanced: ``It was
Krendler's nature to both appreciate Starling's leg and look for
the hamstring.'' It is also the one in which a man is eaten alive
by a pig. In ``The Phantom Menace'' there is mention of the dark
side of the Force; Dr. Hannibal Lecter is that dark side.
</P>
<P>
   IN ``Dracula,'' a singular work of genius by an otherwise
untalented writer, Bram Stoker has the wit to present the count in
one scene as a figure of absurdity -- dressed in a great floppy
planter's hat to ward off the hateful rays of the sun, he appears
at the London docks to personally direct a shipment of the boxes of
earth that will become his bedrooms. The dockworkers pay him and
his gesticulations very little mind, noting only that he speaks
much of ``bloom'' and ``blood.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hannibal,'' Thomas Harris gives us an equally brilliant
scene as Dr. Lecter -- dressed in a Toronto Maple Leafs hockey
jersey and sneaking back into North America as part of an airborne
tour group -- prepares to dine. After years in a maximum security
cell, he is able to live with his cramped quarters at the rear of
the jumbo jet, and he has trained his mind to deal with the
proximity of so many people (it is their smells that principally
trouble him), but he is unable to bear the thought of eating the
airline food, ``freezing-cold sandwiches of slippery meat.'' He has
thus provided himself with a meal from Fauchon, the Paris caterer:
pate de foie gras and Anatolian figs. He waits ``with the patience
of a python'' for the other passengers to fall asleep, then
stealthily pulls the catered meal out from under his seat and
unties the silk ribbons that hold the box shut. At this point a
little boy, who has been observing him all the while, cozens the
monster out of his meal, mistaking the pate for a liverwurst
sandwich without the bread and gobbling it down greedily. It is a
wonderful moment, a comic ray of light that makes the darkness of
Dr. Lecter's heart and mind all the blacker.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the end for the doctor and the F.B.I. agent? Harris is
crafty enough to leave the door to a fourth installment open, but
just a crack. I hope with all my heart that he will write again,
and sooner rather than later -- novels that so bravely and cleverly
erase the line between popular fiction and literature are very much
to be prized -- but I would rather see him bar this door and go
down a different corridor. Familiarity, even with a monster, breeds
contempt. As it is, I like to think of Dr. Lecter in his Maple
Leafs warm-up jersey, losing his carefully husbanded gourmet meal
to the little boy. He takes the loss quite well, I might add. Even
genially. Why, a man like that could steal your heart. Not to
mention your liver . . . your sweetbreads . . . your.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Stephen King's most recent novel is ``The Girl Who Loved Tom
Gordon.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
