<HEADER>
A7125 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WALLS-NYTSF     06-08 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WALLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 HADRIAN'S WALLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Robert Draper.
</P>
<P>
   321 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; LOCAL JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   BY SARA MOSLE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Now, here's a premise for a novel. In the early 1970's, a boy
named Hadrian Coleman fatally shoots a powerful judge in East Texas
and then scratches the dead man's eyes out with a broken whisky
bottle. The crime is so heinous that the boy, although just 15
years old, is tried as an adult, convicted and sentenced to 50
years in the state penitentiary. A decade and a half later, he wins
parole, but a few weeks before his release, he commits another
murder, this time of a fellow inmate. Afraid of spending the rest
of his life behind bars, he escapes from the most secure prison in
Texas, embarrasses the state's correctional system by eluding a
manhunt and is on the lam for eight years.
</P>
<P>
   So far so good. Then, however, Hadrian is suddenly pardoned,
while still at large, by the governor of Texas _ this in a state
with perhaps the harshest criminal justice system in the country _
at the apparent behest of Sonny Hope, the head of the Hope Farm
state penitentiary, who it just so happens, in a secret to no one,
was the escaped convict's best childhood friend. In other words, in
a deal that stinks to high heaven. It would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   No governor _ certainly no governor of Texas _ would ever risk
looking so ridiculously soft on crime by pardoning, out of the
blue, an escaped two-time murderer, and certainly not to appease
some two-bit state official with no campaign money to donate and no
constituency to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the novel opens with Hadrian picking up his pardon papers at
Sonny Hope's mansion, where he's welcomed with open arms and asked
to recount his escape by gleeful prison officials. Hasn't anyone in
these parts ever heard of the appearance of impropriety?
</P>
<P>
   But if you can get past this gargantuan leap of logic, Robert
Draper's first book, ``Hadrian's Walls,'' is actually a deft,
occasionally ingenious novel, doing for sadistic prison officials
what Donna Tartt's ``Secret History'' did for murderous college
cliques: making them seem, if only momentarily, far more appealing
than you ever thought they could be.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, a reporter gets nosy about the goings-on in
Shepherdsville, a fictional stand-in for Huntsville, a prison
community of 35,000 north of Houston, on the edge of East Texas'
Pine Curtain.
</P>
<P>
   The pardon, at first glance, appears to correct an earlier
injustice: Hadrian killed the judge to defend Sonny, whom the judge
had tried to seduce and then murder when his advance was spurned.
But Sonny inexplicably let his friend take the rap for the murder
without providing exculpatory testimony. (There's a homophobic
assumption underlying the plot: Sonny couldn't afford even an
unwanted association with homosexuality or his life would be
ruined.)
</P>
<P>
   Sonny's father, who is the prison warden before Sonny succeeds
him, tries to make it up to Hadrian, as he serves his time, by
giving him a work detail in his mansion.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys _ one free, one not _ grow up together and,
stretching all credulity, remain friends. Sonny courts and marries
a gorgeous local girl, whom Hadrian also loves. Pained by his
proximity to freedom, Hadrian finally forgoes his mansion
privileges to live like any other convict.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sonny, revealing his true character, becomes
warden after betraying his father. Later, he wants Hadrian to repay
the favor of the pardon by killing for him again _ this time, Ricky
Tempesta, a sleazy former con who is threatening to run Sonny out
of business by opening a private prison next door in Trust, Tex.
(Some of the novel's most hilarious bits involve Tempesta's
marketing of his prison: ``Why We Need Trust.'')
</P>
<P>
   More than half the novel is devoted to Hadrian's tedious
agonizing over whether he owes it to Sonny to commit the murder.
It's hard figuring out why Hadrian has ever felt any loyalty to
Sonny _ particularly after serving 15 years' hard time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, everyone's devotion to Sonny _ his father's, the girl's,
other prison officials' _ is pretty inexplicable. Even in Draper's
sympathetic portrait, he comes across as completely odious.
</P>
<P>
   Draper has found a modern Texas subject that is fresh and
fertile: the exponential growth of the state's prison system and
the rise of towns whose entire economies depend, with creepy
exploitation, on incarceration. Draper covered the Texas prison
system for Texas Monthly, and the novel borrows heavily from a long
piece that he wrote for the magazine on Andy Collins, the former
director of the Texas Department of Criminal Justice, who was
ousted for corruption and is an obvious model for Sonny Hope.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, however, goes wrong precisely where it departs from
the real story. In the Texas Monthly article, Collins comes across
as something of a buffoon: a glad-handing, frat-boy bureaucrat with
all the charm of a used car salesman. In the novel, however, Draper
is gunning for more significance, for literature with a capital L.
He wants Sonny to be a kind of Governor Stanton, a tragic, flawed
figure who still inspires epic loyalty. But such men usually don't
end up as lifers in the Texas Department of Corrections. Hadrian,
in turn, is less a Texan than the Southern innocent, displaying a
wide-eyed navete that is completely incongruous with his
circumstances. The guy, after all, rather gratuitously gouged a
man's eyes out and then was raised by the state pen. Hasn't Draper
ever read ``The Executioner's Song''?
</P>
<P>
   Draper is guilty of a kind of Texas Uncle Tomism: playing up to
the literary establishment's stereotypes of what Texas regional
color should be. But he never gets past the cliches to conjure up a
real place and time. His descriptions are mostly stock images from
Southern literature. There's the wild, untamed nature: ``The river
exists in no postcard. Even on the calmest of evenings, it froths
and flails like the devil's own handmaiden.'' There's the emphasis
on patriarchy and the hammy folk wisdom: ``But your daddy, 'course
you know, if pure stubbornness is strength why then he's stronger'n
Nellie's breath.'' There's even the obligatory lesson about race.
At one point, Hadrian's father invites his young son onto the
family porch to shame some Ku Klux Klan members with his innocence.
The scene is straight out of ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   There's tragedy in the Texas prison system, but Draper doesn't
find it here. The novel's best bits are his sharp satire of
Tempesta and Trust, and the whole prison industry. Indeed, there's
a great comic novel struggling to get out of ``Hadrian's Wall,''
but instead Draper gives us an implausible thriller. He wants us to
believe that prison officials have the grandeur of ``The
Godfather.'' But these guys are the Sopranos.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Sara Mosle is an editor at The New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
