<HEADER>
A7126 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MOORE-NYTSF     06-08 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MOORE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BEFORE HIS TIME
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Untold Story of
</P>
<P>
   Harry T. Moore, America's First Civil Rights Martyr.
</P>
<P>
   By Ben Green.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Press. $25.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; FIGHTING JIM CROW
</P>
<P>
   BY ADAM NOSSITER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Before Medgar Evers and Martin Luther King Jr., there was an
obscure black civil rights campaigner in rural Florida who worked
in little towns like Live Oak, Titusville and Groveland, and who
believed fervently in equality and democracy. Like those men and
many others, Harry T. Moore paid with his life, killed in a bombing
attack on Christmas Day, 1951, that was never solved.
</P>
<P>
   Almost completely forgotten by posterity, Moore was a victim
twice over. He doesn't even figure on the Civil Rights Memorial in
Montgomery, Ala., although he was every bit as courageous as those
who do. Ben Green, a freelance writer, speculates in ``Before His
Time'' that Moore came along too early, before the country's
attention was focused on civil rights. Perhaps. But the legacy of
this upright schoolteacher may also have been diminished by his
context: a state that, partly thanks to experienced self-promotion,
is not usually associated with the worst excesses of Jim Crowism.
</P>
<P>
   That reputation is only half deserved. Moore, the N.A.A.C.P.'s
first full-time, paid state executive director in the country, was
operating in a tough, dark place. Florida was third in the country
in lynchings, after Mississippi and Georgia; the Ku Klux Klan had
infested the ranks of local politicians, businessmen and police
officers; and the state's leaders were hardly sympathetic to civil
rights complaints. It may not have been Mississippi, but for a
black ``troublemaker'' like Moore, it was a place where nighttime
car rides easily became something worse.
</P>
<P>
   So we can only share the author's admiration for his subject's
singular achievement. In the late 1930's and 40's, Moore was
putting himself bravely on the front line, suing to get equal pay
for black teachers, starting voter registration drives (by the time
of his death Florida's black registration was years ahead of that
of other Southern states) and firing off angry letters to the
state's governor about the latest atrocity. Unlike those civil
rights leaders who came after, he had no national media to
publicize his cause and no sympathetic Northern whites to help
finance him. And in the end he was abandoned even by his own
organization, the N.A.A.C.P., as the author makes plain.
</P>
<P>
   Like Evers, Moore was inspired by his country's fight in World
War II, goaded by the terrible gap between the ideals of democracy
and the reality of the Jim Crow system. True to the N.A.A.C.P.
tradition, Moore was no radical. He was reassuring to the few
whites bold enough to ally themselves with him. One wrote to Gov.
Millard Caldwell that Moore was a ``sane, conservative, intelligent
Negro . . . and is as far from Socilistic [sic], Communistic or
radical beliefs as either you or I.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was he killed? In the years before his death, he had played
an outspoken role in a kind of Florida Scottsboro case, in which
several young blacks accused of rape were brutally beaten, and he
had helped get a more sympathetic county commissioner elected in
Brevard County, where he lived. Ominously, a neighboring county
seethed with Klansmen, including a county commissioner, a city
manager and numerous police officers. There were plenty of people
with ample motive to place a bomb under the house of the
``troublemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Green has performed a valuable service in bringing attention
once more to this courageous man. He does a good job of conjuring
up the bug-infested, sweaty towns that are the backdrop. The story
is dramatic because of its very obscurity. But this book is flawed
by a tendency toward hyperbole (starting with the subtitle: it
seems unlikely that Moore was America's ``first'' civil rights
martyr) and cliche. Mobs are ``unruly'' and poverty is
``grinding.'' And Green, in researching his book, has spent too
much time listening to doubtful theories about Moore's death in the
furtive world of former Klansmen, whose entire reason for existing
is to get drunk and talk.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Adam Nossiter is the author of ``Of Long Memory: Mississippi and
the Murder of Medgar Evers.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
