<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A BETTER WAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Unexamined Victories and Final Tragedy of America's Last
Years in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   By Lewis Sorley.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt Brace &AMP; Company. $28.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; UNSUNG VICTORIES
</P>
<P>
   BY JEFFREY RECORD
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Sorley believes that the United States had won the Vietnam
War by the end of 1971. ``Not only was the internal war against
subversion and the guerrilla threat won, so was that against the
external conventional threat -- in the terms specified by the
United States.'' Those terms were continued American financial and
logistical assistance to Saigon and, once American ground forces
had departed, renewed air support of South Vietnam's ground forces
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Better War'' is a comprehensive and long-overdue examination
of the immediate post-Tet offensive years, perhaps the most
fascinating years of the war. A first-rate historian and a
third-generation West Point graduate who served in Vietnam, Sorley
focuses on what was indeed the remarkable military improvement of
the South Vietnamese after Tet.
</P>
<P>
   Two main keys, he says, unlocked progress in what until mid-1968
had been a stalemated war. The first was a new American military
strategy devised by Gen. Creighton Abrams, who succeeded the
discredited William Westmoreland as commander of United States
forces in Vietnam. Abrams, who recognized the inseparability of the
war's political and military dimensions, replaced his predecessor's
stupid and wasteful attrition strategy with one that concentrated
on population protection. The second key was a reorganized and
accelerated pacification program directed by William Colby.
</P>
<P>
   Working closely with President Nguyen Van Thieu of South
Vietnam, Abrams and Colby crushed what remained of the Vietcong and
their political and military infrastructure after the Tet
offensive. It was an impressive triumph, perhaps even
extraordinary, given its accomplishment against a backdrop of
capricious White House oversight, relentless United States troop
withdrawals and collapsing public support for further American
involvement in Vietnam. One wonders what course the war might have
taken had Abrams been appointed military commander in 1964 instead
of Westmoreland, whom Sorley rightly tags as a major contributor to
``the squandering of literally years of substantial support from
the American public, Congress and even media.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanoi, however, had an obvious alternative to its defeated
guerrilla option in the South: a straightforward conventional
invasion. And it was this option that it pursued in 1972 and again
in 1975. The first invasion, the so-called Easter offensive, was
finally stopped largely by a huge United States aerial
counterattack. The second invasion, which the Communists called
``Our Great Spring Offensive,'' decisively defeated South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Yet how does one explain Saigon's fall when, according to
Sorley, we had won the war by late 1971? He blames the United
States, more specifically Congress, for defaulting on Nixon's
secret pledges to Saigon of continued military assistance,
including air strikes. But, surely, there was more to it than that.
First of all, the war that Abrams and Colby won was not the
conventional war to come, but rather the original insurgent war.
Second, no American President can or should expect unconditional
Congressional support for a costly, seemingly endless war fought in
a remote place on behalf of largely abstract objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Most important was South Vietnam's political illegitimacy and
military weakness. From its inception, the Republic of Vietnam
could not escape its identity as a cold war creation of the United
States. Ultimately, probably no amount of American air power and
arms assistance could have saved a Government that by 1975
consisted of little more than a professionally feckless oligarchy
of corrupt senior military officers masquerading as a sovereign
state. When the end came, the South Vietnamese armed forces, with
almost $6 billion worth of American weapons, simply broke and ran.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Record, who served as a civilian adviser in Vietnam in
1968-69, is the author of ``The Wrong War: Why We Lost in
Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
