<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7128 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DESIRE-NYTSF     06-08 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DESIRE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BETWEEN MEMORY AND DESIRE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Middle East in a Troubled Age.
</P>
<P>
   By R. Stephen Humphreys.
</P>
<P>
   University of California Press. $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE PROMISED LAND
</P>
<P>
   BY MAX RODENBECK
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Iran's Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance narrowly escaped
impeachment last month. Religious conservatives were out for his
blood, accusing him of allowing ``perversion and filth'' to spread
in the Islamic Republic. The Minister's winning defense was simple.
Although Iran's 1979 constitution forbids the undermining of
Islamic principles, he said, legislators have never defined what
exactly those principles are.
</P>
<P>
   This would surprise the many Americans who tend to regard Islam
as a monolithic faith with inflexible rules. It would not surprise
R. Stephen Humphreys. The clash between ideals of Islamic
governance and the practical difficulty of applying them is exactly
the sort of Middle Eastern conundrum he neatly exposes in this
refreshingly forthright collection of essays.
</P>
<P>
   A professor of Islamic history at the University of California,
Santa Barbara, Humphreys brings a historian's deep and
dispassionate perspective to the modern Middle East. In ``Between
Memory and Desire,'' he poses incisive questions, elaborates
convincing arguments and does not shy from tackling the prickliest
of topics. All this is achieved with an eye for telling detail and
a concise style that is rare in academic writing.
</P>
<P>
   Students of the region will find little that is really new here.
What they will find is an admirably succinct exposition of key
issues. These range from the failure of Arab state building to the
failure of Arabs and Israelis really to come to terms to the
failure of modern Islamists to forge a practical social and
political program.
</P>
<P>
   That is a lot of failure, and indeed the picture that emerges is
a somber one. ``Life is full of surprises,'' Humphreys writes,
``but a betting man would wager that the Middle East will be living
with the current legacy of rapid population growth and economic
frustration for decades to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Few who know the region would seriously dispute this judgment.
Levels of unemployment are dangerously high, even in relatively
successful economies like Israel's. Such vital resources as arable
land and water are scarce. A lack of popular legitimacy makes most
governments shaky and intolerant of dissent. Middle Eastern states
are only just beginning to adopt policies likely to stimulate rapid
economic growth, which is ultimately the only way they will manage
to accommodate the thousands of youths entering the job market
every year.
</P>
<P>
   What Humphreys might have added is that the Middle East's
frightening population growth rates have plummeted in the past
decade. In fact, the region is experiencing a profound demographic
transition. Recent research has shown that similar transitions
helped fuel economic booms in both 19th-century Europe and east
Asia during the 1970's. Not only will fewer students be entering
the Middle East's overburdened educational systems, but the
proportion of working-age people to dependents will rise, creating
a far more productive balance. The countries where these trends are
most pronounced -- Morocco, Egypt and Tunisia -- are already
attractive emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   But if demographic pressures are easing, there is still plenty
of room for pessimism. The region's most serious challenges lie
less in economics than in perceptions, habits and attitudes. This
is the realm ``between memory and desire,'' the apt phrase
Humphreys has borrowed from Eliot's ``Wasteland.'' It is on this
intangible plane that the author is at his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memory in the Middle East,'' Humphreys says, ``tends to be
embodied in myth rather than history.'' Excepting the very new
school of Israeli revisionist historians, the region as a whole has
made only feeble efforts to scrutinize its own past objectively.
The absence of a solid understanding opens history to manipulation
and distortion -- a very serious thing considering that memory,
according to Humphreys, is what identifies goals and purposes for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Arab memories, for example, are often consumed by a sense of
having fallen from grace, of having declined ever since Islam's
spectacular efflorescence in the seventh and eighth centuries. The
politicization of Islam in recent years has exaggerated this
feeling, since fundamentalists hold the early years of Islam to be
a perfect model for society in all ages. Scholars who seek to probe
and challenge this construct are now exposed to charges of
betraying their faith. Without free investigation of Islam's
history, Humphreys suggests, there can be little hope of either
renewal or reform.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the historical memory of both Israelis and
Palestinians is so clouded by their own national tragedies that the
two peoples rarely pause to consider how to accommodate each other.
As Humphreys observes of the Israelis, much of their ``memory'' of
injustice is simply misdirected toward their neighbors. Zionism is
strictly a product of European conditions, he says. Far from being
grounded in age-old hatreds, the Arab-Israeli struggle ``is
decisively a 20th-century conflict, and biblical or Koranic texts
are relevant only insofar as they are used to sanctify ideas and
standpoints whose roots lie in modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys is equally dismissive of many Western myths regarding
the Middle East. The idea of mad dictators driven by irrational
rage is one such shibboleth. In a persuasive series of analyses, he
shows how seemingly self-destructive policies are nearly always
founded in perfectly rational choices. For example, Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini's support for the students who held hostages at
the United States Embassy for 444 days may have isolated Iran in
the world, but it also enabled Khomeini to clinch his grip on power
at a critical juncture in the Islamic revolution. While admiring of
such tactics, Humphreys is hardly sentimental. Khomeini, he says,
was ``militant, vindictive, sure of Islam's enemies but not of what
he hoped to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Humphreys concludes his demolition of the mad dictator myth in
typically pithy fashion. ``The problem for us is not that the goals
of Middle Eastern leaders are impenetrable; most of the time they
are quite transparent. The problem is simply that these goals are
not the ones that we want them to have.'' A wealth of observations
like this place Humphreys's work in the best tradition of writing
on foreign cultures. Objective yet sympathetic, scholarly yet
accessible, his book ends up revealing as much about our own
society as about those it describes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Max Rodenbeck, who writes on the Middle East for The Economist,
is the author of ``Cairo: The City Victorious.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
