<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-REMARKABLE-NY     06-08 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-REMARKABLE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 GETTING USED TO NOT BEING REMARKABLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Michael Foley.
</P>
<P>
   306 pp. Chester Springs, Pa.:
</P>
<P>
   The Blackstaff Press/Dufour Editions. Paper, $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; TAKE MY WIFE, S'IL VOUS PLAIT
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID SACKS
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Defiantly wordy yet sensible in its message, the very title of
Michael Foley's eloquent novel hints at the flaws and strengths
within. The plot of ``Getting Used to Not Being Remarkable''
involves three powerful themes: (a) the grind and compromises of
midlife vs. the proud expectations of youth, (b) the tension of
being Irish in England and (c) adultery. Foley's treatment of them
proves by turns poignant, funny, informative and annoyingly
evasive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a low opinion of schoolteachers,'' his narrator, Martin
Ward, tells us at the outset. ``I was a schoolteacher. Also a
scientist trained in logic. From early youth my head teemed with
syllogisms -- but still I was incapable of drawing an obvious
conclusion. It was a long time before I developed a low opinion of
myself.'' Martin is full of contradictions. Arrogant, aloof, yet
obedient and conformist, he finds both safety and shame in being
underemployed, teaching science at a (vividly sketched) Roman
Catholic girls' school in London, circa 1979. Equally discontented
is Martin's wife, Clare, who looks after their two small children
and works part time as a private nurse. Harried and cash-poor, the
couple squabble.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has rejected the promising future he once faced as a
brilliant, cocky physics student in Northern Ireland in the 1960's.
In his family's convention-bound, middle-class Catholic enclave, he
had seemed destined for a plum corporate research job or a
prestigious post as a university lecturer. Instead, as he puts it,
``the great Martin Ward'' became ``a teacher like everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   For escape, he reads 19th-century decadent French poets,
particularly ``the Magnificent Seven -- Baudelaire, Flaubert,
Rimbaud, Lautreamont, Huysmans, Barbey d'Aurevilly and Villiers de
l'Isle Adam.'' They excite him with their hatred of authority,
exaltation of individualism and variously extreme reactions to the
church. The novel is sprinkled with brief translations from the
Seven, representing Martin's glosses on his momentary feelings, on
what's happening around him.
</P>
<P>
   It's not long before we've seen enough of Martin's peevish
self-absorption to sympathize with Clare -- and to understand why
she falls into bed with a rebellious Londoner named Nick. And when
Martin gives the affair his blessing, we also understand that he's
trying to follow the Seven's subversive ideals, with Clare as his
Emma Bovary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Martin secretly exults in Clare's infidelity: ``I too
was free. We could both cut school. . . . If I had had a fling it
would have shattered Clare's frail confidence and plunged her into
despair. She, on the other hand, could take us both along on her
freedom dash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Used to Not Being Remarkable'' combines two
alternating narratives. The ``now'' thread presents Martin's crisis
in London, over the course of about seven months. The ``then''
thread spans his hopeful teen-age years and coming of age in
Londonderry. This back-and-forth tactic can yield wonderfully
bittersweet results. For example, we see the young Martin at a
dance, first meeting a mysterious, knowing 15-year-old Clare, and
then, a few pages later, we see Clare, the disenchanted wife,
admitting that she's grown more serious about Nick. The Northern
Ireland sections also offer local color and a telling portrait of
Martin's high-toned, anxious mother, who inspires his fear of
intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Foley, despite his obvious gifts, has assembled
too many elements to create a gripping plot. The novel's most
arresting feature -- a cynical husband facing unconventional
choices in dealing with his wife's adultery -- goes neglected amid
Martin's overheated daily perceptions, accounts of his youthful
adventures and digressions on French poets. Despite two splendidly
eerie scenes revealing Clare's deft manipulation of her cuckolded
husband, the whole adultery story line stays reined in. Martin's
reactions remain passive, his feelings shallow. We're told that he
is angry, but he seems to worry more about his thwarted marital
rights than about the possibility of losing his children.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the author is poking fun at, even punishing, Martin
for his ineffectual pride. As the two narratives move toward twin
resolutions, there emerges in each a more mature Martin, ready for
the next stage of life. ``I was not a remarkable person,'' the
adult Martin touchingly concludes. If only he could have been given
a more remarkable way of getting there.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   David Sacks is the author of the Encyclopedia of the Ancient
Greek World.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
