<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PRINCE-NYTSF     06-08 1851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PRINCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE NEW PRINCE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Machiavelli Updated for the Twenty-first Century.
</P>
<P>
   By Dick Morris.
</P>
<P>
   252 pp. Los Angeles:
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Books. $22.95.
 &UR; THE END OF UTOPIA
</P>
<P>
   Politics and Culture in an Age of Apathy.
</P>
<P>
   By Russell Jacoby.
</P>
<P>
   Basic Books. $26.
</P>
<P>
   ---------
 &UR; AS THE FOCUS GROUP GOES, SO GOES THE NATION
</P>
<P>
   BY ANDREW SULLIVAN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``When a man can take a poll and tell what everybody is
thinking, that means nobody is really thinking anymore,'' Marshall
McLuhan wrote back in 1951, recapitulating Gertrude Stein. McLuhan
never knew Dick Morris, but he laid the basis for understanding
him. Morris's candid book about the machinery of professional
politics is premised on an absence of thought deeper, though, than
McLuhan -- or indeed anyone only a decade ago -- could have
predicted. Morris's sense of history extends to a psephological
grasp of the last 50 years of domestic politics, and his broader
learning amounts to a smattering of Churchill quotations and
homilies from the musical ``Annie.'' His philistinism, by which I
mean his complete unconcern for the highest goals of any society,
is so complete it is fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Take the substance of what Morris has helped turn our politics
into. This is what Morris calls ``issues.'' According to ``The New
Prince,'' issues -- not spin, not character, not charisma -- get
candidates elected and keep them in power. What the issues are,
however, has nothing to do with a judgment of what the country
needs, what history demands or what a politician's accumulated set
of principles intimates. What the issues are is determined
primarily by polling: ``The icons of the past relied on political
instinct. Now, Presidents can use scientific polls and focus
groups. I fail to see the difference.'' The use of the right issues
in the right way enables a President to stay popular, and this is
important because, without popularity, he is not really President:
``An elected executive -- whether President, governor or mayor --
needs a popular majority every day in his term. . . . When he dips
below 50 percent, he is functionally out of office.'' So much for
elections, electoral colleges or, for that matter, the
Constitution. What matters, when one peels away the political
onion, is the nightly tracking poll.
</P>
<P>
   The actual content of the issues is as irrelevant as the formal
powers of the Constitution. ``Take whatever position you want, but
do take a position, because once you do, ample money awaits you on
either side,'' Morris advises would-be candidates. (Someone should
inscribe that sentence on Bill Clinton's Presidential library.) The
only indispensable thing is flexibility. The key for those on the
right, Morris argues, is to co-opt the strongest issues of the
left, whatever they may be at the time. And the key for the left is
to neutralize the strongest areas of the right, whatever they may
be. So we end up with a millennial race in which Tweedle-A and
Tweedle-B distinguish themselves by careful platitudes that are
determined in advance by the wrists of wired focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   This, Morris argues, is an entirely good thing. And it does not,
he protests, lead to apathy. Although 40 percent of the electorate
couldn't care less about politics, the 60 percent who are involved
-- the retired C-Span addicts, readers of Brill's Content and
surfers of the Drudge Report -- are more sophisticated than any
electorate in history. This means that the politician must be
forever inventive (``The roaches have developed an immunity to this
year's roach spray,'' in Morris's felicitous metaphor), but it also
means that the future of America's direct democracy -- a kind of
plebiscitary Internet chat room -- is, in Morris's eyes, bright.
The premise in all this is that liberal democracy succeeds when it
most perfectly reflects the will of the majority. What is new in
our politics is merely the technical means to discern that will
with ever greater precision at any given moment. The notion that
liberal democracy might be concerned with the minority, or the
individual, or even the rule of law, does not seem to have occurred
to Morris.
</P>
<P>
   But if Morris's book is sometimes chilling, it is also often
acute. Many of his micro-observations, like many of his master's
micro-policies, are on the mark. He is underwhelmed by the power of
special interest groups, and he doesn't buy the notion that the
sound-bite culture inherently degrades political discourse (``There
is literally no such thing as an idea that cannot be expressed well
and articulately to today's voters in 30 seconds''). He's
persuasively dismissive of the powers of spin (take that, George!)
and imaginative when it comes to policy prescriptions, even though
they are generally of the metal-detectors-in-schools variety. But
he has no clue about foreign policy -- he thinks Americans will
support interventions only if they are geared to protecting
children. And the amoralism is ubiquitous. Morris eschews racism,
for example, as an electoral tactic not because it is beneath him
but because it ``doesn't work.'' Oh well, times change.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it no longer surprises that this kind of politics was
perfected by a Democratic President and defended by the Democratic
Party. The merit of Russell Jacoby's new book is that it asks us to
place the politics of Morris's Clinton (and Clinton's Morris) in
the context of the intellectual collapse of the left. Jacoby, a
social historian, clearly thinks the two phenomena are related. And
he has something of a point.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby's premise is that the American left has had the stuffing
knocked out of it by the last 10 years. The implosion of Communism
has deeply undermined milder forms of redistributionism, and the
stagnation of the social democratic countries in Europe has robbed
liberals of any real alternative to Rubinomics. The result is a
capitulation to conservative social and economic policy in both
Britain and the United States. Jacoby is right, if unoriginal, in
pointing out how thorough an abandonment of liberal utopianism this
represents. But he is smartest in seeing how the liberal
intelligentsia accelerated the process.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S refreshing to read ``The End of Utopia'' because the kind
of left-wing tradition Jacoby revels in -- a defense both of high
culture and of a genuinely democratic politics -- is, to all
intents and purposes, extinct. His disgust at the shallowness of
``multiculturalism'' is matched only by his frustration at the
alleged end of ideology. His hero is Matthew Arnold, the Victorian
inspector of public schools, the defender of sweetness and light
but the opponent of aristocratic privilege. ``That people are equal
and should be treated equally,'' Jacoby argues, ``is one matter;
that their thoughts and activities are equal is another.'' The way
in which academic liberals have come to fetishize popular culture
and relativize morality strikes him not as an evolution of
liberalism but as its disintegration. Obscurantist cultural studies
and the blather of communitarianism are, for him, merely two sides
of the same pitiful decline.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby is particularly sharp on the leading liberal political
theorists -- thinkers like Richard Rorty and Charles Taylor --
whose avowed relativism, he believes, leads to their inability to
say anything robust at all. Because they cannot uphold what was
once thought of as absolute truth or universal reason, they have no
zeal for the utopianism that once animated liberals across the
globe. They represent, Jacoby charges, a kind of ennui of the
liberal political soul, a lassitude that can only allow the likes
of Morris to prevail. And such intellectuals, to Jacoby's horror,
even acknowledge their complicity. Rorty himself has argued that
``it is not something we can remedy by a firmer resolve, or more
transparent prose, or better philosophical accounts of man, truth
or history. It is just the way things happen to have fallen out.''
</P>
<P>
   THE problem, of course, is that the liberal predicament Rorty
points out is a real one. There is a good reason why at the end of
the 20th century utopias, especially leftist utopias, are hard to
believe in, and why both political and philosophical skepticism has
followed the political horrors of the last century. And by far the
weakest part of Jacoby's analysis is his attempt to deny this. He
believes ethnic hatreds and territorial disputes have taken far
more lives in this century than utopianism gone awry. But what has
surely marked the 20th century -- from Stalin to Milosevic -- is
not ancient hatred but the toxic fusion of such hatred with modern
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Jacoby refuses to see this because he needs an unsullied
utopianism. He needs it because without it, he believes, liberalism
cannot thrive: ``A left constituted the liberal backbone; as the
left vaporized, the backbone went soft.'' There is unfortunately no
proof of this postulate in the book. The collapse of the left and
the decline of liberalism have indeed been coincidental, but Jacoby
provides no causative link between the two. One might equally well
argue that it was the left's triumph in the late 1960's that did in
liberalism, and that the left's demise in the 1990's, far from
being a cause of liberalism's extinction, is an opportunity for its
revival. This is why Jacoby's book works far better as a lament
than as an argument. He has diagnosed the problem and made some
worthwhile enemies in doing so. But he is less effective at
providing a solution than even Morris is. At least Morris intuits
the collapse of liberal conviction and exploits it. Jacoby merely
misses Arnold and Mill.
</P>
<P>
   But is Jacoby right that a liberalism without utopia is
unimaginable? Surely not. Is it not truer, in the spirit of Isaiah
Berlin, that it is the abandonment of utopia that makes liberalism
possible? This liberalism is not the same as Morris's bankrupt
acquiescence in the status quo, and it is more realistic than
Jacoby's romanticism. It is a liberalism concerned with pluralism,
fairness and freedom, and it is not hard to see what it would
amount to today. For all the talk of the end of ideology, there are
still plenty of causes. There is genocide again in Europe; there is
economic inequality at home; civil rights are not assured for all
Americans; civil liberties have had a terrible decade; the racial
question remains and festers. For liberals, there may be polls to
be taken, and utopias to be left behind, but there is also work to
be done. It is perhaps the clearest legacy of the current President
that he has done so little of it.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Sullivan is a senior editor at The New Republic and a
contributing writer for The Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
