<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NANNY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE NANNY AND THE ICEBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Ariel Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   358 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $25.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; BLAME IT ON CHILE
</P>
<P>
   BY SHASHI THAROOR
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Ariel Dorfman -- Chilean expatriate and American
writer, refugee from Pinochet's death squads and professor at Duke
University -- has written movingly and often brilliantly of the
cultural dislocations and political fractures of his dual heritage.
Poet, playwright (``Death and the Maiden'') and essayist, Dorfman
has, in an impressive body of work, done justice to the two
languages that have battled for his voice and the two countries
that claim his allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   He has written of torture and suffering, of cultural imperialism
(``How to Read Donald Duck,'' with Armand Mattelart) and freedom of
the press, of exile and rediscovery (most memorably in his recent
autobiography, ``Heading South, Looking North'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Nanny and the Iceberg,'' his sixth novel, Dorfman
reflects some of these concerns in the story of a callow
23-year-old Chilean exile in New York, Gabriel McKenzie, returning
to a homeland recovering from dictatorship, a land obsessed with
sex, politics and cultural identity.
</P>
<P>
   The novel, except for a coda, takes the form of a long suicide
note, e-mailed in installments by Gabriel to an American
girlfriend, Janice. When Gabriel and his radical mother, Milagros,
fled to America in the wake of the Pinochet coup, his father,
Cristobal McKenzie, an expert at tracking down runaway boys, stayed
behind. Cristobal is a larger-than-life Latin lover; he makes a bet
with his best friend, Pablo Baron, that he will have intercourse
with a woman every day of his life until his 50th birthday.
Cristobal, in his wife's words, ``swore to live only for that
moment when you copulate''; his axiom is that he exists because he
fornicates.
</P>
<P>
   Cristobal manages to maintain his daily dose of sex, finding
partners at wakes and even among the nurses in the maternity ward
where his wife delivers Gabriel. But Cristobal's prodigious
carnality is the cause of his son's impotence: his father was there
ahead of him every time he tried, Gabriel writes, ``as if his organ
were in her before mine could even begin to rise up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel grows up in America under the looming shadow of his
mother's idol, Che Guevara -- the revolutionary, now reduced to a
poster above his bed, whose death brought his parents together --
waiting for the restoration of democracy in Chile so that he can
seek amatory advice from his father. Soon after his return he too
makes a vow, ``that I would only make love to a woman who had not
tasted the fruits of my father's tongue.'' This leads him to pursue
the beautiful teen-age daughter of Pablo Baron, Amanda Camila, the
only female he is sure hasn't fallen to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo, now a minister in Chile's post-Pinochet democratic
Government, wants to tow an Antarctic iceberg, 70 tons of it and 30
feet high, to the Expo '92 world's fair in Seville, Spain,
commemorating the 500th anniversary of Columbus's voyage to
America. The idea is to market a new image of Chile: not a tropical
third world country full of dark-skinned indigenes, but ``the New
Zealand of Latin America.'' However, Pablo has received a note from
the mysterious ``Comandante You-Know-Who'' threatening the iceberg,
and he persuades the McKenzies, father and son, to take the case on
and save the project.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel realizes he came to Chile searching for ``even the shoal
of a father to wreck myself on.'' His mother wanted to save the
country, his father wanted to save runaways, ``and neither of them
seemed interested in saving me.'' Fortified by the wisdom and the
cooking of his mother's 80-year-old nanny, a native descended from
an extinct Patagonian tribe, Gabriel comes into his own and
Cristobal finally gives Gabriel the parental advice he has been
waiting for. Before the novel's end Gabriel himself is sounding
worldly-wise: ``Women want two things from men: they want a father
to protect them and they want a son to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   Some readers may find the incessant priapism tiresome, but ``The
Nanny and the Iceberg'' sustains interest by keeping you guessing:
Who is threatening the iceberg and why? Who will win the notorious
wager? Who is really whose father? And will Gabriel finally fulfill
his threat to blow himself and the iceberg up in Seville? The novel
is overladen, though, with direct, and sometimes crude, discussions
of physical intimacy, whose effect is not always engaging. When
Pablo's daughter Amanda is born, Cristobal presents him with a
condom -- the one he'll never use, a token of his commitment not to
sleep with his friend's daughter. Pablo carries it around in his
wallet as a good-luck charm. This episode encapsulates the novel's
singular attitude toward sex and friendship. Pablo tells Gabriel:
``Friendship is more important than sex. Sex passes -- a few
thrusts in, a few thrusts out, a spasm of pleasure and then it's
over. But friendship. That lasts, and that's what we live for.
Lasts longer than anything we have with women, with their big
breasts and their small brains.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a Latin American novel written in English, and its
sensibility is a cross between the macho masculinism of the barrio
and the street smarts of New York. The author never quite manages a
settled narrative voice for his young protagonist, who veers
between lyricism in the finest Latin American tradition and its
opposite. Passages of confidence and grace, like a section
describing a search in Antarctica for the vital iceberg, alternate
with similes of adolescent shallowness (``She flirted as if she had
learned the technique at Vamp University''). Poetic prose is too
often undermined by jarringly crude language. If Joseph Conrad is
right in demanding that a work of art should carry its
justification in every line, then ``The Nanny and the Iceberg''
does not quite measure up to the standards we are entitled to
expect from Dorfman.
</P>
<P>
   Cristobal tells his son about the first time he made love to
Milagros: ``I began to understand, and understood it even better
when I finally got inside her and I lost and found myself there,
that this was what life was about, its meaning for me, the only
meaning that really fit into this only life that had been given to
me.'' My only problem with ``The Nanny and the Iceberg'' is that it
does not offer any greater meaning than that, and we know that the
intelligent, subtle and gifted Ariel Dorfman could have given us
one.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Shashi Tharoor is the author of ``The Great Indian Novel'' and,
most recently, of ``India: From Midnight to the Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
