<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TIDE-NYTSF     06-08 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TIDE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 AGAINST THE TIDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Battle for America's Beaches.
</P>
<P>
   By Cornelia Dean.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 279 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University Press. $26.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; ON THE BEACH
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVID RAINS WALLACE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Americans love the seashore. A growing majority of us (including
this writer) live within an hour's drive of it. What is the source
of this allure? Natural beauty and fresh seafood play a part, of
course, but the main attraction probably is the beach. The
pleasures of congregating in seminudity on hot sand are somehow
vital to modern civilization. Cornelia Dean's ``Against the Tide''
warns, however, that Americans may not have beaches much longer or,
at least, the public beaches that defined so much of 20th-century
culture may fade as upkeep becomes more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   America's seashores are in trouble. Hundreds of miles are
urbanized, wildlife is dwindling or contaminated and the
destruction has accelerated since the trouble became obvious in the
1960's. Yet the environmental journalist who opens this Pandora's
box faces a daunting task trying to describe it. Where to begin?
Water pollution? Fisheries destruction? Wetlands loss? Dean, the
science editor of The New York Times, addresses the problem
adroitly by concentrating on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Beaches are so important as social milieus that they may not
seem natural, but they are. Dean does an excellent job of
explaining how they evolve and function. Beaches are among the most
dynamic geological phenomena, their workings so massive and subtle
that scientists have yet to understand them. We know that they form
as coastal currents transport sand flushed from river mouths and
deposit it along the shore. The currents, and factors like tides
and storms, remove sand from shores as fast as they deposit it, so
beaches must be continually replenished by more sand eroded from
the land.
</P>
<P>
   On the Pacific coast, where colliding tectonic plates push the
land upward, most beaches form in bays between steep headlands. On
the geologically more quiescent Atlantic and gulf coasts, most form
at the seaward edge of long barrier islands. In all cases, they
function as buffers between land and sea, protecting terrestrial
habitats from flooding. Storms can destroy them overnight, but
newly deposited sand quickly rebuilds them under natural
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Wide beaches prevailed on North America's coasts when Europeans
arrived. Dean's descriptions of them -- they lasted into the late
19th century -- are like something from another world. Long
Island's were ``spectacular expanses of fine-grained, light gray
sand, hundreds of yards wide, backed by grass-covered dunes as much
as 15 or 20 feet high.'' Many stretched for scores of miles, and
often were the main travel routes for settlers. Beaches began to
dwindle, however, as urban Americans discovered the shore. The
reason is simple and ironic. Beaches depend for existence on
wide-open natural processes, but people cannot live in large
numbers on the shore without interfering with those processes.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal processes include violent events such as storms, and
burgeoning coastal communities quickly encountered terrifying
situations. Dean makes the terror graphically clear in her first
chapter, on the destruction of Galveston in 1900. The thousands who
died in a September hurricane were strewn across the Texas coast so
gruesomely that military authorities had to force laborers at
gunpoint to collect them. Communities responded by ``armoring'' the
shore, protecting houses and streets with sea walls, jetties,
groins and other structures. But that armoring interrupted the flow
of beach-nourishing waters -- not only coastal currents that bring
sand to beaches but tides and waves that rebuild them. Starved of
sand, beaches melted away. Where hundreds of feet of dry sand once
separated communities from the surf, high-tide lines crept to the
bases of sea walls, and strollers now must clamber over obstacle
courses of concrete and steel.
</P>
<P>
   Americans responded with more technology, replacing lost sand
artificially. Dean shows that many beaches where sunbathers
congregate today are man-made, their sands pumped from elsewhere.
Artificial beaches are vulnerable to the same erosion that destroys
natural ones, so we are faced with a costly cycle of repeatedly
replacing beaches. Storms can snatch away not only a new beach but
the machinery that made it. The situation is heart-rending for
hundreds of coastal communities, and Dean tries to be evenhanded
about its complexities. Indeed, she cites so many specific cases
that her narrative occasionally slows under the weight of detail.
The upshot seems clear: America can't expect to preserve its
beaches if it keeps destroying them with coastal construction --
especially at a time when a projected sea-level rise from global
warming compounds the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The only lasting solution to loss of beaches will be a halt to
(or even a reversal of) urban growth along them. Dean points to
some hopeful trends. Communities and conservation groups are buying
beaches to stop owners building on them. Ten national seashores
protect several hundred miles of beach. (Only one is on the West
Coast, unfortunately.) Government is less willing to subsidize
beach development or bail out property owners. Insuring beach
structures is getting harder.
</P>
<P>
   Yet conservation lags far behind growth, and the prospect of an
urban withdrawal from the beach seems distant. As Dean points out,
the consequences of wholesale coastal urbanization could be
ghastly. If a ``worst case'' Category 5 hurricane hit southern
Florida, for example, the havoc wreaked by Hurricane Andrew in 1992
would be small by comparison, since that weaker, Category 4 storm
missed downtown Miami. ``Hurricane Andrew should be remembered as a
narrow escape, a warning about what can happen when people
overdevelop the coast,'' Dean writes. Hurricanes constitute only
one threat. Dean overlooks a Western one -- tidal waves or tsunamis
from earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Impending disasters point up a limitation of Dean's strategy of
building her case against coastal urbanization around beaches.
Controlling urbanization on beaches would save beaches, money and
lives. It would not prevent huge destruction in a big hurricane or
tsunami, since such events can reach well inland. Saving beaches
will not save the coasts if urban proliferation continues unchecked
nearby. Beach conservation could be a keystone for building a
coastwide conservation system, but not the whole edifice.
</P>
<P>
   Such limitations probably are unavoidable, however, at a time
when environmental problems have receded from the public's
attention. Dean has done a first-rate job of making coastal
conservation interesting. ``Against the Tide'' would be good beach
reading.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   David Rains Wallace's most recent book is ``The Monkey's Bridge:
Mysteries of Evolution in Central America.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
