<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-THINGS-NYTSF     06-08 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-THINGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LAST THINGS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jenny Offill.
</P>
<P>
   264 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $23.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; OH MOM, POOR MOM
</P>
<P>
   BY NANCY WILLARD
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Jean Piaget observed that scarcely any question seems absurd to
a child, but he was silent on the question of absurd answers from
adults. In Jenny Offill's remarkable first novel, ``Last Things,''
7-year-old Grace Davitt watches her mother, Anna, descend into
madness and tries to make sense of the claustrophobic world that
Anna has created for her. The child has been plucked out of school
for behavior problems and is being educated at home, in a small
town in Vermont on Lake Champlain. Her father, Jonathan, is a
chemistry teacher; her mother is an ornithologist who decides to
teach Grace the history of the world in a room she has painted
black and decorated with glow-in-the-dark stars: ``In one corner
was a desk and a small blackboard. On the wall behind them, my
mother had painted some words in white. 'It's the cosmic calendar,'
she said. 'Everything that's happened since the beginning of time
compressed into just one year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Grace's unsentimental education is anything but rational, and
this is no ordinary coming-of-age novel. Her mother's downward
spiral takes center stage. Demonstrating a lively knowledge of both
science and magic, Offill shows Anna stuffing her daughter with
answers that veer from the scientific to the fantastic. Yet the
child accepts every absurdity because it comes from a higher
authority:
</P>
<P>
   '' 'Once,' my mother said, 'there was no true darkness. Even at
night, the moon was as bright as the sun. The only difference was
that the light was blue. You could see clearly for miles and miles
and it was never cold. And this was called twilight.' 'Why twi?' I
asked. 'Because it rhymes with sky,' my mother said. 'It's a code
word for blue.' Code blue was what they said when someone died, I
remembered, and this, too, had to do with the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Important cosmic events, dated and noted like entries from the
earth's diary, are interspersed throughout the narrative. But
applying the rigorous methodology of science to the imagination is
like putting a dream on dialysis, and the cosmic calendar, with its
succession of vanishing species, casts a terrible shadow over
Anna's faith in her own survival. ``My mother said that stones were
last things and would be around long after people were gone. Other
last things were oceans, metal and crows.'' The child translates
her mother's pronouncements into practical magic: ``I thought that
if I filled a birdbath with seawater and dropped a coin in it, I
might glimpse the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace ponders the mysteries revealed in the Encyclopedia of the
Unexplained (a gift from her mother) and sees herself as a
detective, keeping lists of words and facts in her notebook. ``I
had an idea that someday someone would come to me with a mystery
and I would open up the notebook and all the clues would already be
there.'' Ordinary communications are fringed with codes, signs,
questions and disguises. Grace's eccentric baby sitter, a
16-year-old genius named Edgar, suggests that ``everyone around you
might be an ingenious robot and you're the only one that's not.''
Uncle Pete, her father's twin brother, plays Mr. Science on a
television show for children. When he runs off with one of the
show's writers, Grace's father easily steps into the role, playing
his brother playing Mr. Science. Anna is fluent in Annic, her own
secret language, invented by her father.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances are not only deceiving, they are baffling. Who can
one trust in such a world except a cryptozoologist?
``Cryptozoologists were detectives who specialized in finding
hidden animals. . . . This was the sort of detective my mother
wanted me to be.'' For ``hidden,'' read ``endangered,''
``legendary,'' ``vanished,'' ``extinct.'' Make no mistake.
Hide-and-seek is not child's play. Offill gives us journeys within
journeys: the earth keeping time, the light sent eons ago from a
dead star, Anna's harrowing cross-country drive with Grace, which
ends in a California desert.
</P>
<P>
   Offill does not succumb to the familiar tug-of-war between
science and religion; her characters, not their ideas, are her
major concern. The child's nonjudgmental point of view and deadpan
accounts of people caught in the thrall of their convictions make
``Last Things'' an unexpectedly funny book. Grace's father wants to
protect her from religion. Her mother wants to do no harm to the
natural world. When Anna receives a collapsible iron from her
husband for Christmas, her query reminds us that to one who voyages
in the imagination pressed clothes are as useless as traveler's
checks:
</P>
<P>
   ``My father didn't believe in Christmas, but still we celebrated
it. It was like not believing in God but still you prayed. My
mother said it was a shame to cut down a tree, so instead we chose
one in the forest and tied a ribbon around it so we could find it
again. . . . We opened our presents all at once because it was too
cold to take turns. . . . My mother folded and unfolded the iron;
then she ran it across the snow. 'How marvelous,' she said. 'What
do you suppose its purpose is?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The novel is crisply written, economically constructed and so
inventive that you read without a clue as to what anyone will say
or do next. Offill's fresh voice, endearing and quirky, makes you
willingly suspend disbelief. Underlying the surprises is a
carefully constructed pattern of motifs -- water, animals,
darkness, unsolved mysteries -- that cluster into metaphors for
what happens to Grace's mother, which is not described directly.
The reader understands it as Grace does, through various clues.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few chapters, Grace takes her first steps toward a
life of her own, though scarred by her mother's emotional
detachment. The final chapter, filled with lyrical speculation
about Anna, has the power of a dream carried not in the head but in
the heart.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Publishers Weekly, Offill talked about the
origins of the novel: ``It occurred to me that a child would be a
very good companion for a madwoman.'' This idea is also central to
Marilynne Robinson's ``Housekeeping,'' although Robinson's novel,
narrated by an adult looking back at childhood, is faithful to
memory in what it includes: landscape, characters, personal
reflections. In contrast, Offill's is faithful to the child's point
of view in what it leaves out -- a circumscribed telling indeed.
But if ``last things'' means things that will last, then Offill's
novel is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Willard's books include ``Telling Time: Angels, Ancestors,
and Stories'' and an anthology, ``Step Lightly: Poems for the
Journey.'' She teaches literature at Vassar College.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
