<HEADER>
A7136 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FIRE-NYTSF     06-08 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FIRE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ELEMENTALS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories of Fire and Ice.
</P>
<P>
   By A. S. Byatt.
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $21.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; RUNNING HOT AND COLD
</P>
<P>
   BY FERNANDA EBERSTADT
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   One of the more energetic and magisterial of contemporary
British writers, A. S. Byatt is part of a generation of
novelists-cum-academics from the provinces -- the 20th-century
heiresses to George Eliot -- whose strong intellects won them
entrance to the great universities and for whom, consequently,
academia betokened not crabbed shelter but the freedom of noble
company. It's no coincidence that a collection of her criticism is
entitled ``Passions of the Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Ruskinian tradition, Byatt's particular mental passion
inhabits that place where esthetics and moralism fuse. Her
fictional protagonists are frequently painters or art historians or
artisans. Like the Victorian writers she recalls, Byatt has a bent
for fairy tales -- fertile ground for lovers of both artifice and
ethics, for storytellers who happen to be interested in what one of
her characters calls the ``ambages and sinuosities'' of their
craft.
</P>
<P>
   There is an episode in an earlier volume of short stories, ``The
Djinn in the Nightingale's Eye,'' that reveals the highly conscious
duality of Byatt's fiction. In the title story, a middle-aged
``narratologist'' uncorks a genie from an antique-shop phial. When
the genie, a giant of intoxicating male sexuality, demands a
secret, the narratologist tells of her discovery that a glamorous
friend of her youth grew up in a suburban home stuffed with knitted
tea cozies and featuring a ``three-piece suite in moquette.'' The
genie, who has regaled her with memories of Suleiman the
Magnificent and the Queen of Sheba, is puzzled by the triteness of
her revelation. ``All English stories,'' she explains wearily,
``get bogged down in whether or not the furniture is socially and
esthetically acceptable. This wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The disjunction between the priapic genie and the ``three-piece
suite in moquette,'' between art's wide enchantment and a snobbish
parochialism, is central to Byatt's writing. ``Elementals,'' her
latest collection of short fiction, combines what a story called
``Crocodile Tears'' describes as the ``world of mythical
absolutes'' with an inhibiting concern for the esthetically
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the acid precision with which ``A Lamia in the
Cevennes'' begins: ``In the mid-1980's Bernard Lycett-Kean decided
that Thatcher's Britain was uninhabitable, a land of dog-eat-dog,
lung-corroding ozone and floating money, of which there was at once
far too much and far too little. He sold his West Hampstead flat
and bought a small stone house on a Cevenol hillside.'' Like many
British expatriates fleeing to the Mediterranean countryside,
Byatt's artist hero becomes obsessed with his swimming pool: 1.
How, after Hockney, to capture its seraphic blue? and (more
crucially) 2. How to deal with its clogged purification system?
Unlike most expatriates, he discovers that the pool is haunted by a
serpent-woman, or Lamia, who explains that she can be freed from
her snake body only if she marries a mortal. Bernard finds the
Lamia's female portions even more repulsive than her ``coils,'' but
manages to fob her off on an unwanted houseguest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crocodile Tears'' also involves a Londoner's escape to the
south of France. Patricia Nimmo's husband, Tony, drops dead on the
floor of a Bloomsbury art gallery after a tiff with his wife over
whether or not a small English seascape is ``banal.'' Patricia, a
middle-aged businesswoman with an unrealized appetite for mystery,
steps over his corpse and onto a train to Nmes. There she meets a
fellow northerner, a Norwegian schoolmaster who seeks to cure her
of her guilt-induced ``indifference'' by introducing her to the
ancient city's honeyed cult of ``blood and death and ritual.'' (The
incomplete nature of Patricia's emancipation is suggested when,
visiting the grave that her children have raised for their father,
she pronounces, ``This is vulgar.'')
</P>
<P>
   Many of the stories in ``Elementals'' -- confirming its
subtitle, ``Stories of Fire and Ice'' -- do indeed involve
northerners who are either imprisoned or revived by the brutal
south. The loveliest is an unalloyed fairy tale entitled simply
``Cold,'' which tells of an ice princess wedded to a desert prince
who constructs an elaborate cave palace of spun glass to keep her
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The besetting sin of Byatt's ``inexpressive northerners'' is an
unwillingness to be moved. Patricia in ``Crocodile Tears,''
visiting Nmes during the bullfighting season, refuses to look at
the matadors' ``absurd deathly dance''; the narrator of ``Jael''
examines the biblical story from the book of Judges, a feast day of
intricacies and reversals of expectation, and remembers only its
``shocking morals.'' Opposing these blinkered prigs are Byatt's
artist guides, counseling curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated message of ``Elementals'' is stated clearly in a
short fable, reminiscent of Isak Dinesen, entitled ``Christ in the
House of Martha and Mary,'' in which Velzquez, staying at a grand
Spanish house, teaches a gifted but bad-tempered cook not to resent
her languidly indifferent masters. ``The divide,'' he informs her,
``is not between the servants and the served, between the leisured
and the workers, but between those who are interested in the world
and its multiplicity of forms and forces, and those who merely
subsist, worrying or yawning. . . . The world is full of light and
life, and the true crime is not to be interested in it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Elementals'' is similarly full of light and life, the
throwaway gleams of a writer at the height of her powers. Byatt's
prose is capacious yet exquisite, and it is proof of her ample
gifts that she can rivet us in a story like ``Crocodile Tears''
with what, from a less unified talent, might feel like a
travelogue, a restaurant review or art criticism. But Byatt is also
an angry writer, drawn to explore the violence that bursts out of
modestly circumscribed lives. In ``Elementals,'' it is the rage of
her unappeasable northerners, these latter-day ``berserkers'' on
southern holiday, that lingers long after the exhortation to be
``interested'' in life.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Fernanda Eberstadt's most recent novel is ``When the Sons of
Heaven Meet the Daughters of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
