<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MARQUIS-NYTSF     06-08 1881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MARQUIS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE MARQUIS DE SADE
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Life.
</P>
<P>
   By Neil Schaeffer.
</P>
<P>
   567 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $35.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; THE EPONYMOUS SADIST
</P>
<P>
   BY MIM UDOVITCH
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Reviled in his own lifetime and resurrected in the latter half
of this century, the Marquis de Sade, Richard Seaver writes in his
introduction to Sade's ``Letters From Prison,'' today ``enjoys a
measure of respect far greater than he ever could have imagined in
his wildest dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the nature and content of the wildest dreams of Sade's
imagination and their various methods of measuring respect, this is
really saying something. Not that Seaver doesn't have a point _ the
much-written-about Marquis has slowly but surely become something
like the Madonna of arts and letters: a reliably controversial and
safely daring subject that speaks to a paradoxical, voyeuristic
desire to see what you don't want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Still, following hot on the heels of Francine du Plessix Gray's
``At Home With the Marquis de Sade'' and Laurence L. Bongie's
``Sade: A Biographical Essay,'' Neil Schaeffer's biography, ``The
Marquis de Sade: A Life,'' enters such an unusually crowded field
that in some respects it is already out of date. (For example, what
Schaeffer deems the only extant piece of correspondence written by
Sade's mother is supplemented in ``Sade: A Biographical Essay'' by
several letters newly discovered by Bongie.)
</P>
<P>
   However, especially given that most readers will not be sitting
down with all three books, Sade's life is, to put it mildly,
sufficiently interesting to sustain several retellings and numerous
approaches. He is, at the very least, surely the only man in
history to have imprisoned a prostitute and forced her to listen to
him prove the nonexistence of God all night, after which, and who
is to blame her, she went straight to the police.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the recent biographies neatly cover the spectrum of
negative to the point of prosecutorial (Bongie); to tolerantly,
moderately sympathetic (du Plessix Gray); to practically poleaxed
by devotion (Schaeffer).
</P>
<P>
   The bare, undisputed outlines of the life of
Donatien-Alphonse-Franois de Sade are as follows: He was the only
surviving child, born in 1740, of Jean-Baptiste de Sade and his
wife, who was born Marie-eleonore de Maille. He was descended on
his father's side from an ancient and noble Provenal family, who
claimed among its ancestors Laure de Noves, a plausible candidate
for Petrarch's mysterious muse, Laura. Through his mother, a
distant cousin of the Prince de Conde, he was collaterally related
to the Bourbon kings, a point of pride in the Sade family to this
day. (``How could you not want to know about the Marquis de Sade?''
the current Comte de Sade, who, unlike some of his more immediate
forebears, owns the connection freely, asks du Plessix Gray. ``He's
descended from King St. Louis!'')
</P>
<P>
   Sade's father, an improvident roue, was briefly a minor
diplomat; his mother was a lady-in-waiting to her cousin through
marriage, the Princesse de Conde. After spending his first four
years with Marie-eleonore at the Conde palace, the young Donatien
was raised by his father's family in Provence, primarily by his
uncle, the rakish Abbe de Sade.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in Paris at the Jesuit college Louis-le-Grand,
Sade entered an elite military academy at 14, and eventually an
elite cavalry regiment, from which he was demobilized in 1763, at
the end of the Seven Years' War. The same year, he was hustled by
his cash-poor father into a marriage with the well-connected,
well-off but relatively not well-born or well-favored Renee-Pelagie
de Montreuil.
</P>
<P>
   After an escalating series of sex-related offenses, in 1777 Sade
was imprisoned by royal fiat more or less at the behest of his
mother-in-law, who was enraged by his seduction of her younger
daughter, Anne-Prospre. Freed by the Revolution in 1789 and
separated from a finally fed-up Renee-Pelagie, he lived without
major mishap until his authorship of the scandalous ``Justine'' in
1791 led to his commitment 10 years later to a mental hospital,
where he died in 1814.
</P>
<P>
   His work and his reputation, as reviewed and interpreted by
writers and thinkers such as Simone de Beauvoir, Michel Foucault
and Roland Barthes, to name but a few, have been in a state of
habitual comeback ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Sade is, of course, best known for the set of sexual
predilections associated with those he details in his fiction and
that have come to bear his name. In most of his novels, these
alternate about equally with a philosophy that can be fairly
completely summarized as: There is no God; nature is all;
self-interest and the will to pleasure are natural; and it is
therefore unnatural to resist desire, which is inherently dark and
destructive, so may the worst man win.
</P>
<P>
   His formal writing (his letters are delightful) is blunt and
repetitive, and even most of his loyal adherents don't make much of
a claim for him on strictly literary grounds. Like, say, William
Burroughs, Sade is a writer whose work functions more as a sort of
place card for a body of thought than it does as an entity of
independent value. As an aristocrat who lived through the ancien
regime's last gasp, a physical prisoner whose primary subject was
conceptual freedom, a seductive charmer who favored force and a
male sexual tyrant whose life was ruled by powerful women, Sade by
definition is an argument in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer, a professor of English at Brooklyn College, enters
this fray with the sense of urgency peculiar to Sade studies. His
primary focus is on Sade's psychological development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Sade's conscious fantasies turned to erotic violence,
especially directed against women, we may ask where and why those
underground rivers of rage and sexuality met,'' he writes after
quoting from a letter in which Sade describes a dream vision he had
of his ancestress, Laure de Noves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where was the first abandonment, disappointment, even betrayal
that lurks behind the beautiful, compassionate Laure of the
dream?'' You guessed it, Freudians. Mothers certainly do come in
for brutal treatment in Sade's novels, and motherhood itself is
repeatedly asserted to be meaningless. But since Sade's
relationship with his own mother is barely documented, this avenue
of inquiry is largely speculative; the consensus (disputed by
Bongie) is that she was remote and rejecting. In fact, Sade's
childhood in general is rather minimally documented; explanations
of his temperament as a child, his separation from his mother and
his departure for Provence when he was 4, for example, are based
almost entirely on a presumably autobiographical passage from his
novel ``Aline et Valcour, ou le Roman Philosophique'' describing a
fight with his slightly older cousin, the Prince of Conde, as a
result of which he was banished from the palace.
</P>
<P>
   (One of Bongie's newly found letters from Sade's mother confirms
at least that such a quarrel took place.)
</P>
<P>
   Because of this minimal documentation, the early parts of ``The
Marquis de Sade'' are the weakest. Proceeding from the not
unreasonable assumption that trauma occurred, but without any one
particular thing from which to infer it, Schaeffer tends to cover
all eventualities by depicting everything in Sade's childhood as
traumatic -- the move to Provence, the move from Provence, the
stress of academic expectations, war and marriage are all suggested
as motivators for what is after all only a presumed personality
type, the shy and angry loner who believed that ``if he became an
object of discipline, this meant that he was not alone in an
indifferent world.''
</P>
<P>
   In spots, Schaeffer's attempts to penetrate Sade's psychological
character are more earnest than they are astute. Occasionally they
are silly. ``Our two horses are giving us some trouble: his is off
his feed, and is lame (somewhat); he claims it's out of spite,
since, when he gets a chance to run off, he skips like a goat,'' a
traveling companion writes of the young Sade during his time in the
cavalry, in a letter to the Marquis' father.
</P>
<P>
   Schaeffer posits that this seemingly rather commonplace
rhetorical pleasantry describes ``a small instance of Sade's
characteristic paranoia: Sade somehow came to believe that his
horse was persecuting him with a feigned injury.''
</P>
<P>
   The part of Sade's life that seems the most obviously related to
Sade's literature is the period after his marriage but before his
imprisonment in 1777 _ that is, the period during which the sexual
exploits that got him locked up took place.
</P>
<P>
   Sade's staunchest supporters usually offer a sort of cos fan
tutti defense, and Schaeffer does likewise: sodomy, though illegal,
was common; flagellation was a standard practice among prostitutes,
etc. (This could also be termed the plus ca change argument: women
of loose morals wouldn't scruple to lie; he's rich and they just
want to hold him up for money, etc.) Leaving aside the fact that in
two of the incidents the women in question did not agree with Sade
that they were prostitutes, and given that this was an era in which
the King of France had a private brothel custom stocked with
adolescents because his official mistress, Mme. de Pompadour,
didn't like sex and there was, du Plessix Gray says, a young woman
reputed to be ``the official whipper of the Count of Binheim'';
even given that in an age of formal class distinction definitions
of consent were not what they are now, and granting the virtue of
all principles of sexual libertarianism, this argument is off
point. What made Sade's actions problematic was not the nature of
the sexual action but the fact that he tended to kidnap, imprison,
drug or threaten to kill the other parties. By the time Sade was in
his early 20's, the chief of the Paris vice squad was warning
brothels not to let him take women off the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Schaeffer is probably not wrong when he writes
that Sade's ``sexual life would find a modern equivalent among a
great many film and rock stars. Their public expect and vicariously
enjoy their escapades. There is always an actual or an imagined
privileged sexual class, and individuals who think they belong to
such a class usually can get away with a great deal if they are
careful and lucky. Sade was neither.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the weirder demonstrations of the degree to which
puritanical and pornographic attitudes toward sex coincide, Sade's
sexual life was vicariously enjoyed in his day, by a public who
followed it in the yellow press and by Louis XV and Mme. de
Pompadour, who followed it in the Starr Report equivalent of the
age, the vice squad chronicles of illegal sexual activities
submitted to them by the police for nominally righteous purposes.
Cos fan tutti, and, actually, plus ca change.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Mim Udovitch is a contributing editor for Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
