<HEADER>
A7138 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FRY-NYTSF     06-08 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FRY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MOAB IS MY WASHPOT
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen Fry.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 364 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Random House. $24.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; OVER EDOM WILL I CAST OUT MY SHOE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BY RANDY COHEN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In 1775, Samuel Johnson contemplated the English educational
system and concluded, ``There is now less flogging in our great
schools than formerly, but then less is learned there; so that what
the boys get at one end, they lose at the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred years later, when Stephen Fry attended school,
enthusiasm for thrashing as a pedagogical method had diminished but
not disappeared, and each master preserved his own style: ``Angus
in his day beat me many times, always with gentle sorrow. Mid Kemp
sliced me from time to time with a rather mad, rather frightening
glazed boredom. Cromie beat me more than anyone since his reign as
proper headmaster coincided with my rise from infancy to boyhood,
from naughtiness to wickedness. When he beat me it was always with
a glum resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre world of the English boarding school is the setting
for ``Moab Is My Washpot,'' Fry's engaging memoir of his boyhood,
and it is as curious a culture as anything you'd encounter up the
Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what you see there may frighten and confuse you _ the
odd clothes, the incomprehensible slang, the bellicose games, the
complex social hierarchies, the revolting food and the bewildering
erotic customs whereby any boy might have sex with another boy but
only certain boys are branded ``queer.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all good anthropological expeditions, this one begins with
a railway journey. Fry sends himself off to school and us off into
his life with wit and charm: ``After one of those squealing,
juddering, stomach-dropping false starts with which trains so
tactlessly articulate human emotion, we pulled ourselves out of the
great shed of Paddington and steamed west.''
</P>
<P>
   Fry has a knack for depicting childhood's unhappiness, but
because we know, in effect, how the story will come out _ Fry the
adult will become a fine and successful comic actor _ it is
tempting to dismiss each transient episode of teen-age torment. But
of course young Fry had no knowledge of the agreeable adulthood
awaiting him, and even if he had, he wouldn't have been comforted.
Like many unhappy adolescents _ i.e., adolescents _ he is fiercely
loyal to his misery, denouncing any future happiness as a betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Fry at 16: ``I tell you now that everything I feel now,
everything I am now is truer and better than anything I shall ever
be. Ever.'' This was not to be read until he'd forgotten youthful
truth in his decrepitude at the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
   Fry's juvenile self-absorption is apparent when he writes of
love. Despite his claim that his schoolmate Matthew was the hub
around which his adolescence turned, that position seems occupied
not by this paragon but by Fry himself. Nothing wrong with that.
His is a story of adolescence, and narcissism is a privilege of
that age. But if Fry wants to assign that place to his beloved, one
wishes Matthew were more vividly present.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew does come to life in ``The Liar,'' Fry's 1991 novel, in
the guise of a character called Cartwright. In a kind of laboratory
experiment, many of the events Fry presents as memoir he'd
previously rendered as fiction, often to greater effect.
</P>
<P>
   In the memoir, he sometimes succumbs to the temptation to
reflect on the meaning of things, to provide an overview, to speak
in generalities. But in his novel he is specific, and a few
sentences, a brief scene rich with detail, convey the texture and
turbulence of his school days more movingly than whole sections of
the memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Spend enough time with someone in close quarters _ a long car
trip, a lengthy memoir _ and an unimportant mannerism can become
infuriating. In Fry's case it is list making. Time and again,
rather than selecting the one word to convey his meaning, he tosses
a dozen onto the page. It's not padding; it's exuberance, it's
riffing, it's an ill-advised generosity. And it's more annoying
each time he does it. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a word which still means much to the English and
which was for many years a rod for my back, a spur to prick the
sides of my intent, a Fury from which to flee, a nemesis, an enemy,
an anathema, a totem, a bugaboo and an accusation.'' (The word, by
the way, is ``healthy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Fry lists people who are old, winter activities, insights easily
achieved through LSD, songs commonly sung at the piano, songs often
played on record, effects that can be achieved by language,
unpleasant things he'd rather do than seem to admire intelligence,
expressions used by schoolmasters, things that seem to be camp but
are not and foods that are tasty but not strictly necessary for
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Fry's voice grows stronger as his story builds _ or
perhaps disintegrates _ to his youthful breakdown when, at 18,
having flunked out or been thrown out of several schools, he is
arrested for stealing and using a credit card. When he lands in
jail, Fry finds it not so bad because he'd been well trained for
life behind bars. ``Life in prison was a breeze for me, because at
that point I'd spent most of life at boarding school.'' And of
course in prison, he was much less likely to be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Randy Cohen writes the Ethicist column for The Times Magazine
and the News Quiz for the on-line magazine Slate.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
