<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-NONFICTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION
 THERE'S NO SUBSTITUTE FOR FIELDWORK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY SUZANNE MACNEILLE
</P>
<P>
   The pioneering Polish ethnographer Bronislaw Malinowski had an
ambivalent attitude toward photography, which, he said, ``I hate
above all other things.'' Yet he photographed extensively as part
of his fieldwork in Kiriwina, one of the largest of the Trobriand
Islands in the South Pacific. Beginning in 1914, Malinowski
documented in five monographs, including the classic ``Argonauts of
the Western Pacific,'' the beliefs, rituals and quotidian habits of
the islanders. With great aggravation, he lugged around his
ungainly photographic equipment -- a monstrous cross on the
Golgotha of life.'' Nonetheless, Malinowski found photography to be
an indispensible tool and took more than 1,000 pictures of the
gardeners and animists whose traditional sula -- the inter-island
trade of shells and other goods -- became, in academic settings, a
widely used paradigm of traditional economic exchange. ``No other
anthropologist of Malinowski's generation made photographs work so
hard,'' Michael W. Young writes in MALINOWSKI'S KIRIWINA: Fieldwork
Photography 1915-1918 (University of Chicago, $40). Nearly 200
previously unpublished photographs are arranged in 14 visual essays
with headings like ``Magic'' and ``Mortuary Rites and Exchanges.''
Perhaps the most alluring sequence is ``Masawa Canoes and the Kula
Quest,'' which depicts rituals associated with the shell trade and
the construction of the islanders' boats, with their graceful sails
of dried pandanus leaves sewn with awls of flying fox bone.
Undoubtedly, this book will be of primary interest to those in the
social sciences, but the engagingly written text and colorful
quotations from Malinowski's letters, diaries and books will make
it a pleasure for the general reader. Young, senior fellow in the
Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies at the Australian
National University, makes the point that his book is, in many
ways, less an objective study of the islanders than a portrait of
Malinowski and ``his vision of his Trobriand world.''
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT BLOOM
</P>
<P>
   A MEMOIR.
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Cappello.
</P>
<P>
   Beacon, $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not really sure it's possible for me to look at anything
directly,'' Mary Cappello confesses midway through ``Night Bloom,''
as if to excuse the myriad metaphors in her sometimes colorful,
frequently meandering memoir. Cappello, who teaches English at the
University of Rhode Island, shifts between past and present tenses
to reconstruct the experiences of her immigrant forebears and to
chronicle her own grim childhood in a working-class Philadelphia
suburb. Much of what she describes is chilling: the murder of a
neighbor, her father's explosive temper, the erosion of her
grandfather's faith in the possibility of prosperity in the United
States. Amid this somber landscape, however, Cappello finds reason
to rejoice. In particular, she relishes tending flowers; the
ephemeral blossoms of the cereus, for example, offer her a respite
from hardships both current and remembered. She regards her desire
to write as a legacy from her grandfather and interweaves fragments
from his writings. Unfortunately, the frequent interruption of
pop-academic musings weakens this memoir significantly. By
introducing discussions of ``systems of oppression'' and the
``poetics of loss,'' Cappello overintellectualizes the otherwise
gripping memories she describes. Moreover, her penchant for seeking
hidden meaning in just about everything, from a pair of scissors to
birthday candles, quickly grows tiresome. She disregards her
concern about becoming ``metaphor-crazed,'' and this predilection
makes portions of her memoir downright unintelligible. But when
Cappello restrains herself from such overindulgence, her writing
shines and, like the flowers she cherishes, offers fleeting
glimpses of beauty. _ Sara Ivry
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HER BODY THOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   A Journey Into the Shadows.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Griffin.
</P>
<P>
   HarperSanFrancisco, $24.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Griffin's book is like an old car: it's clunky and awkward
at the start, but once it gets going, it more or less works. An
amalgam of genres -- memoir, cultural criticism, political
argument, historical investigation and spiritual meditation -- What
Her Body Thought'' centers first on Griffin's own illness. More
than a decade ago, before it was recognized by the medical
community, she became afflicted with chronic fatigue immune
dysfunction syndrome. The simply but stiffly described details of
her sickness read heavily, as she repeatedly walks her reader
through symptom after symptom, both physical (numbness, loss of
concentration and memory, nausea, insomnia, muscle ache) and mental
(initial denial of her affliction, loneliness, a sense of
abandonment). But once she looks outside her own condition, she
begins making complex and highly opinionated connections between
the individual mind and body and society, and her tone becomes
decidedly more authentic. New Age enemies (and grammarians),
beware: Griffin thinks nothing of throwing out vague holistic
sentiments like ``Turning my attention toward sense, movement,
sensation, taking in the great breadth and complexities, the
intricacies of physical experience, I feel a kind of relief in
response and then gratitude, as if flesh were glad to be known, a
steady stream of what feels like love saturating the substance of
my existence.'' _ Alexandra Hall
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA GOTHIC
</P>
<P>
   A Story of Adultery and Murder in an American Family.
</P>
<P>
   By Pope Brock.
</P>
<P>
   Nan A. Talese/Doubleday, $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   A woman has an affair, and a child, with her brother-in-law, who
is shot on the street by her enraged husband. Pope Brock has turned
this tawdry tale of his great-grandfather Ham Dillon's murder, and
the betrayals that he spun and that spun around him, into ``Indiana
Gothic,'' which nimbly illuminates the stain of adultery spreading
disaster across so many lives. In his turn-of-the-20th-century
setting with a turn-of-the-21st-century sensibility, Brock winks at
the weird science of the medicine (electricity cures), psychiatry
(alienists abound) and law (with plenty of ``knotty and fractious
testimony'') of the time. ``Instead of going up to Michigan, for
the cornflakes and magic shows, you chose to enter the heart of
darkness,'' the prosecuting attorney says to the avenging husband,
Link Hale, who, until he pulled the trigger, had been a depressive,
obsessive mope on his way -- and out of his wife's way -- to John
Kellogg's Battle Creek Sanitarium for a ``cure.'' Brock has a gift
for making a reader shift sympathies. Is murder simply a question
of law, or is blame assessed on the basis of who hurt whom the
most? A freelance magazine journalist, Brock knows how to tell a
good story -- perhaps one that is too good. His unveiling of the
inevitable affair and the just-as-inevitable murder is as elegantly
wrought as the finest of fiction. He has reimagined and rendered
whole and human the way his family members thought, felt and acted
more than 90 years ago. ``Indiana Gothic'' is being sold as
nonfiction, even though parts of it have clearly been invented. But
whatever it is called, it is well worth reading. _ Andrea Higbie
</P>
<P>
   WAITING FOR APHRODITE
</P>
<P>
   Journeys Into the Time Before Bones.
</P>
<P>
   By Sue Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We humans are a minority of giants stumbling around in a world
of little things,'' Sue Hubbell writes in ``Waiting for
Aphrodite,'' which begins when she gives up her bee farm in the
Missouri Ozarks to move onto five acres in coastal Maine. On land
and sea, the invertebrates make up the largest and most diverse
phylum of animal life, ranging from sponges to spiders, from the
honeybee to the lobster. They could all get along nicely without
us, as they did for millions of years; but we could not survive
long without them -- about a third of the food we eat depends upon
pollination by insects. Hubbell is a master of the science writer's
necessary art of explaining -- what is taxonomy, cladistics,
punctuated equilibrium (or ``punk eek''); what distinguishes an
animal from a plant. In the realm of small things, the smallest
details are significant: when Martha, the last passenger pigeon,
expired, two species of lice became extinct with her; while we
humans favor the spider's orb (like Charlotte's web), the common
cobweb is more efficient at entangling prey, and therefore marks an
evolutionary advance. Such odd and colorful bits fill the book, but
Hubbell's message is one that all biologists today repeat: that the
diversity of life -- with its 370,000 known and 10 million
estimated species of beetles, its million or more varieties of
ocean life -- is essential to the stability and endurance of our
own lives. _ David Walton
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
