<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-NYTSF     06-08 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
 OUT OF THE MOUTHS OF BUBBAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BY BRUCE BARCOTT
</P>
<P>
   ``My South,'' Tom Franklin writes in the introduction to
POACHERS (Morrow, $22), his debut story collection, ``is lower
Alabama, lush and green and full of death, the wooded counties
between the Alabama and Tombigbee rivers.'' It's territory
populated with good ol' boys down on their bad ol' luck. Franklin,
a son of Alabama who has never felt at home there, brings together
an engaging collection of sympathetic losers caught in tough
situations and almost-interesting jobs. A series of bad bets turns
a factory foreman into his bookie's indentured servant. An
alcoholic who lives off his successful younger brother is asked to
do little bro' a favor: kill his sister-in-law's cats while she's
on vacation. A ground-water contamination inspector, instead of
shutting down a leaky gas station, conspires with the owner to
cover up the mess in exchange for the pump jockey's stuffed dead
rhino. In this last story, ``Dinosaurs,'' Franklin takes a Southern
cliche -- the chain-smoking, oily-overall-wearing cinder-block
station owner -- and turns him into a memorable character with just
a few lines of dialogue. The old man answers the young inspector's
remark about doing good for the environment with an incredulous
snap: ``The environment?'' he says. ``Take you a good long look out
the window yonder at the environment.'' With all these bad
husbands, ne'er-do-well buddies and frayed marriages, it's as if
the author kidnapped Raymond Carver's characters and set them loose
in the Deep South. Franklin isn't challenging Carver's mastery yet,
but with this satisfying collection he establishes himself as one
of the region's more interesting emerging voices.
</P>
<P>
   DOORS
</P>
<P>
   Stories.
</P>
<P>
   By William Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   University of Missouri, paper, $17.95.
</P>
<P>
   If journalists are pesky gnats, then short-story writers, as
defined by William Hoffman, are observant flies on the wall. In
``Doors,'' his fourth collection of stories, Hoffman flits among 10
houses, most of them in the fictional town of Tobaccoton, Va.,
absorbing the kind of detail about character and class -- from
white-collar to redneck -- that both illuminates the heart of the
matter and burrows in the brain. When a woman owns a black satin
painting of Willie Nelson holding a banjo, ``his face giving off
sunbeams and favoring Jesus,'' we don't have to wonder if she's
ever been bowling. Throughout, Hoffman explores the secret
yearnings of his characters, the lengths they go to in putting on
appearances and how they handle the temptation to cross lines of
color, circumstance and creed to find the passion and truth that
elude them. The black businessman of ``Stones'' offers friendship
to a white teen-ager who is too blinded by racism to accept it; the
pathetic farmer of ``Winter Wheat'' finds chilling meaning in the
Bible when his wife takes a lover. The majority of Hoffman's tales
don't so much end as fade away, leaving the reader aching for the
resolution of ``Tenant,'' a tense interplay between an ambitious
couple and the convicted murderer in their employ. Still, Hoffman's
grasp of the subtleties of human nature and his lyrical use of
language make Tobaccoton an attractive, if offbeat, destination. _
Alanna Nash
</P>
<P>
   SNOW MAN
</P>
<P>
   By Carolyn Chute.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt Brace, $23.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Chute has written good novels (``The Beans of Egypt,
Maine'') and bad ones (``Merry Men''), but nothing in her past work
quite prepares you for ``Snow Man,'' an absurd and rather ugly
political thriller that asks you to sympathize with a Maine militia
member who murders a United States senator. Class resentment has
always simmered below the surface of Chute's work, and here that
resentment is transformed into rage. Robert Drummond, this novel's
violent working-class hero -- he is described as a ``pure human
being'' and a ``beautiful ordinary man'' despite the swastika
that's tattooed on his arm -- is a member of the Snow Men, a
pro-gun, anti-corporate backwoods sect. When Drummond murders a
senator in Boston and is wounded himself, he improbably takes
refuge in the home of another senator, whose wife and daughter
surreptitiously nurse him back to health. (Drummond seduces both
women, cartoonish liberals who urge him, in bed, to do his ``ugly
bear'' thing and his ``Mr. Right Wing thing.'') Chute uses the
killer's extended stay to evoke the plight of Maine's working poor
-- Drummond has lost his farm, his family lacks health insurance --
and to deliver scattershot rants about the sorry state of the
Government. These rants are not subtle: the dead senator is likened
to ``a maggot in a brimming garbage can''; the First Lady is
described as an ``arrogant bitch broad femmie-Ms. wifey.'' The
crude sermonizing in ``Snow Man'' makes it plain that the activist
in Carolyn Chute has, for now, silenced the novelist in her. _
Dwight Garner
</P>
<P>
   MY PHANTOM HUSBAND
</P>
<P>
   By Marie Darrieussecq.
</P>
<P>
   New Press, $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   When a beautiful young woman's husband unaccountably disappears
on a domestic errand one evening, the terror of her nights and the
disorientation of her days produce hallucinatory images, gory
speculations and manic-depressive actions. In her second novel,
translated from the French by Esther Allen, Marie Darrieussecq
writes chiseled, brightly faceted sentences that evoke her
heroine's contrasting emotional temblors and peculiar perceptual
glints -- e.g., that the physical objects of a shared living space
are ``solidification of void.'' Some readers will dismiss this kind
of exercise as claustrophobic and overintellectualized; others will
admire a confidently original writer's kaleidoscopic analysis of
spiritual crisis. The latter may especially appreciate
Darrieussecq's crafty exposition. Even as her bluestocking heroine
flirts with madness, we learn solid truths about her chilly
marriage to a real estate agent and her relationships with a
distant mother and a vulgar friend. In the outside world that may
explain the heroine's passivity, a 20th-century city is built from
such details as sea lions exploding in a mined harbor and an exotic
underclass with blue-tinted skin. At the same time, the heroine's
cosmic imagination links, in startling conjunctions, discoveries of
contemporary science -- from hermit crab anatomy to an experiment
in quantum physics. Eventually, the heroine learns what Nathaniel
Hawthorne wrote in ``Wakefield,'' his short story on a similar
theme: ``It is perilous to make a chasm in human affection.''
Whether her husband left or was taken from her, she gains balance
enough to write her story, thus validating her new singularity and
letting deep water close over him. _ Charles Flowers
</P>
<P>
   KING
</P>
<P>
   A Street Story.
</P>
<P>
   By John Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Pantheon, $20.
</P>
<P>
   John Berger has been paring down his style. His novel ``To the
Wedding'' (1995) was composed with language that sounded timeless,
as if recited by an ancient bard. In his new book he's sparer yet,
and less successful. The setting is a homeless encampment by a
freeway near an unnamed city. We are in an allegorical world
reminiscent of Troy, the ``global city'' in Berger's earlier novel
``Lilac and Flag.'' The dump's inhabitants have polyglot names like
Joachim, Corinna, Saul and Liberto. The events of a single day,
which turns out to be the last day for the little community, are
narrated by a dog named King. He guards the ramshackle huts, and he
lives with Vico and Vica, an old couple who once had another life,
full of laughter and books and enough money to keep out ``the first
hopelessness'' that ``begins when you cannot imagine anything ever
being dry again.'' Vico tells King the same stories over and over
because, aside from a thick coat, they are his only valuable
possessions. On this day, Vico goes to town to sell some radishes
he's grown on stolen soil, and Vica, accompanied by King, wheels a
grocery cart to the gas station, where she fills her cans with
water. Rumors float around the camp about the city's plans to raze
it and develop the site into a stadium. That night, as everyone
sleeps, King sees them coming: the jeep, the soldiers and, worst of
all, ``the massive engine'' and ``the noise of stones being torn
like linen.'' Witness and bard, King resembles the Aesop-like
chronicler of ``To the Wedding'' and the Greek-chorus narrators of
``Lilac and Flag.'' His nonhuman gaze of pity and mourning for
people treated like garbage, his gnomic judgments, create a formal
distance between the reader and the characters. Although the
individual portraits of Vica, Vico and the rest are beautifully
drawn, we're constantly reminded that King really is a pet, who
goes around sniffing at hermit crabs and mushrooms. It's just too
hard to believe in a poetic dog. _ Brigitte Frase
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
