<SLUG> BC-ADIRONDACK-CHAIRS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADIRONDACK CHAIRS HAVE ROOTS IN THE FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Adirondack chair did indeed originate within
the Adirondack forest preserve in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This sturdy classic features a sloped back and seat angle that
is just as comfortable as an upholstered club chair, making it a
mainstay in outdoor furniture across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The first Adirondack chair, with its 4-inch-wide arms for a
drink or book, was designed in 1903 by Thomas Lee for his home in
Westport, N.Y., according to Ann Stillman O'Leary's book
``Adirondack Style'' (1998, Clarkson Potter, $37.50). It was
originally called the Westport chair.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, owner of the famous Westport Mountain Spring, suggested
that a carpenter friend named Harry Bunnell make a few of the
chairs to sell, according to O'Leary, and Bunnell applied for the
patent. Bunnell's chairs were all signed, made of hemlock and
stackable.
</P>
<P>
   As with any popular furniture design, designers and craftsmen
soon began putting a spin on the original model, such as doubling
them in size and adding rockers to modifying the shape of and
design of the back.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Adirondack chair is manufactured in several woods:
pine, oak, cedar, mahogany, cherry and teak. Most come unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   Adirondack chairs originally cost less than $4. Today, depending
on their condition, original Adirondack chairs are worth $1,250 or
more, according to Ted Comstock of Ithaca, N.Y., who is an
appraiser of antique Adirondack items. When he worked for the
Adirondack Museum, Comstock curated the museum's first exhibit of
rustic furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   Rustic furniture includes both twig and Adirondack types, but
the former may use bark and roots while the latter is made solely
of pine.
</P>
<P>
   The price for Adirondack chairs depends on the size, age,
condition and original finish and whether it is a signed Westport,
Comstock said. Original colors were green or a medium dark brown.
</P>
<P>
   New Adirondack chairs vary in price and design. Jerry Amerine in
Speculator, in Hamilton County, N.Y., makes several varieties, from
a Westport style to the High Peaks style. His Westports sell for
$70 unfinished, but new Adirondack chairs can cost $200 or more,
according to retailers.
</P>
<P>
   If that's more than you want to spend, green plastic copies sell
for $14.99. They are so popular that they are already back-ordered
at stores such as Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
