A7150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-PROFILE-EVIL-HNS     06-08 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-PROFILE-EVIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-G-MAN PROFILES A LIFETIME ANALYZING CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the book ``The Evil That Men Do,'' profiler Roy Hazelwood
relates his first FBI case: the recovery of a vacuum cleaner,
vanished for five years from a naval base.
</P>
<P>
   Discovering that the Navy personnel who borrowed the vacuum
simply gave it away, piece by piece, Hazelwood traced everyone
connected to the missing cleaner. Showing up on doorsteps with the
pronouncement, ``I'm with the FBI. Do you have a piece of this
vacuum cleaner?'' Hazelwood gradually reassembled the cleaner, and
presented it, with a few choice words, to his supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Hazelwood, his FBI career would lead to more
fascinating cases. Among the approximately 10,000 serial murders
and rapes, mutilations, explosions and other mayhem, Hazelwood
helped investigate the Atlanta child murders; also the notorious
assault allegations of Tawana Brawley, who a grand jury determined
made up the racially inflammatory story; and the turret explosion
aboard the USS Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But the case of the missing vacuum cleaner illustrates
Hazelwood's methodical approach to criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood spent 16 years of his 22-year FBI career in the
bureau's Behavioral Science Unit, investigating and researching in
particular violent sex crimes. A profiler, or crime analyst,
Hazelwood assembled portraits of unknown offenders from behavioral
clues left at the crime scene. The BSU's work became widely known
through the novel and subsequent movie, ``The Silence of the
Lambs,'' and profilers are featured on two current television
series.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen G. Michaud, the Dallas writer perhaps best known for
interviewing notorious serial killer Ted Bundy for the book ``The
Only Living Witness,'' is the co-author of ``The Evil that Men Do''
(St. Martins Press, 256 pages, $25). He credits Hazelwood with
several significant research breakthroughs at the FBI Academy at
Quantico, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood explored the accidental deaths resulting from
autoerotic asphyxia, when people purposely cut off their own oxygen
flow to achieve a high and supposedly to enhance sexual arousal. A
sex-crimes instructor, Hazelwood ``typed'' rapists by motivation
and, thus, level of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood helped built a system for the behavioral approach to
criminal investigation, according to Michaud.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy is remarkably quiet and self-effacing about his
achievement and what he does,'' Michaud said. ``Outside of the
law-enforcement circle, before our book was published, he was
hardly known and I think he liked it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood, a man quick to laugh but careful in speech, does not
set profilers apart as select people operating on an inaccessible,
intuitive plane. The qualities of a profiler _ maturity, curiosity,
common sense and open-mindedness among them _ in fact sound like a
prescription for leading a rich, sensible life. Quoting Nobel
Prize-winning biochemist Albert Szent-Gyorgyi, Hazelwood summarizes
profiling: ``Discovery is looking at what everyone else has seen
and thinking what no one else has thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood, whose slight youthful rebellion in small-town Texas
and family dysfunction did not spell future crime expert, first
became fascinated by sex offenders as a young officer in the
Military Police Corps. Harvey Glatman, the ``Lonely Hearts
Killer,'' had just been executed for the rape and murder of women
he met through a lonely-hearts club.
</P>
<P>
   This was the late 1950s and early 1960s, and the sexual offense
was largely unexplored investigative territory. Crime specialists
could not explain Glatman's elaborate killing ritual, including the
elaborate bondage with which he secured his victims.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood wanted to know, and the case set him on a quest to
understand the mind of the sex offender, whose rituals during the
crime are so connected to their self-gratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Evil that Men Do'' is an annal of human depravity _
behavior that can't be as easy to mentally set aside and
compartmentalize as, say, the stress caused by an irritable boss or
a job deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But Hazelwood says his work depressed him only once when, having
just completed a report on a series of couples murdered while
hiking, he learned of yet another couple who had just been killed.
</P>
<P>
   He took two weeks off, and painted his house. ``At that point in
time, I made a decision, which was: This was not my life, this was
my work. If it becomes part of your life, you become part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood, now 61, retired from the FBI in 1994 and now is an
associate of the Academy Group, a private forensic consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hazelwood weighs in on a recent wave of crime: school violence.
Sounding a call for parental involvement in children's lives,
Hazelwood, a father of five, said the violence is occurring in an
increasingly shameless society that has lost a sense of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to project the blame on all of these outside sources.
. .. We then have to look at the individual as being responsible
for what he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
