<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLAG-DAY-HNS &LR;      06-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLAG-DAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA THE BEAUTIFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUBY MASCHKE  
 c.1999 Huron Daily Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAD AXE, Mich. _ Last week we observed Memorial Day on May 31.
Next week we will honor the flag on Flag Day, June 14.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to think of Memorial Day without thinking about
the American flag. It would be equally hard to think of the
American flag without thinking of all the men and women who fought
and died defending our country. This column is a bridge between
those two noteworthy days.
</P>
<P>
   I looked up some of the prose and poetry written by patriotic
persons.
</P>
<P>
   But even as I read each poem and each article, the words of one
person kept weaving in and out of my reading. The words were those
of Katherine Lee Bates, who wrote ``America the Beautiful.''
Perhaps that most patriotic and descriptive gem needs a close-up,
line-by-line scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``O beautiful for spacious skies''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the temperature is more agreeable, I've resumed my
habit of early morning coffee outdoors, watching the sunrise in
those spacious skies. Not sky, but many skies, each one different.
Sometimes gorgeous shades of pink, sometimes fluffy white clouds
rimmed in rose, sometimes gray-smoke ribbons that form and reform
at the wind's whim. Sometimes patterned by a vee of migrating
geese. An always beautiful sky.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``For amber waves of grain''
</P>
<P>
   A field of wheat, ripe heads bent in submission to the
harvester.
</P>
<P>
   Silken heads of barley rippling in a summer breeze. Grain that
is lovely mellow gold. Grain that means bread for the nation. Once
Jesus said, ``Unless a kernel of wheat falls to the ground and
dies, it remains only a single seed. But if it dies it produces
many seeds.'' A field of grain is a million miracles.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``For purple mountain majesty''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most awesome and majestic mountains are those in our
own United States of America. My first view of the Grand Canyon
brought tears to my eyes. Purple, beige, rose, indescribable
striations of color. A helicopter flight revealed unending miles of
purple mountains and deep-sculpted canyons, so awesome my heart was
filled with wonder.
</P>
<P>
   God must have smiled when He created such majesty.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Above the fruited plain.''
</P>
<P>
   Fly across our great country. See the farmland, brown fields
ready for planting, green fields of alfalfa and corn and grain, the
bounteous blessings of many kinds of crops _ all included in the
``fruited plain.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``America! America! God shed His grace on thee''
</P>
<P>
   Bates wrote those words as she viewed the lofty and graceful
Grand Tetons in Wyoming. They were so beautiful, so scenic, she
must have felt the grace, the undeserved love of God for this
country.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``And crown thy good with brotherhood, from sea to shining
sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Name any country of the world. Somewhere in this vast and
wonderful United States of America _ somewhere between the shining
Atlantic and Pacific oceans _ there is someone from any country you
can name. Some people die trying to get to this land of
opportunity, this land of untrammeled freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Verses two and three of the song speak of ``pilgrim feet'' that
``a thoroughfare for freedom beat across the wilderness for heroes
proved in liberating strife, who more than self their country
loved.''
</P>
<P>
   The last verse begins with the words`
</P>
<P>
   _ ``O beautiful for patriot dream that sees beyond the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The far-seeing men who wrote the Constitution were patriots in
the best sense of the word. They pledged their fortunes and their
very lives to gain freedom from British tyranny. They wrote a
document that has served to guide this great country for more than
200 years. Their patriot dreams certainly did reach beyond their
years!
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Thine alabaster cities gleam''
</P>
<P>
   Some people do not care for cities, but many people prefer the
urban life. There are art museums, concert halls, theaters, sleek
shining office buildings _ edifices for entertainment and business
and learning.
</P>
<P>
   At night, look down on a city from high up. Lights sparkle like
jewels tossed across the Earth. A lighted city truly gleams after
dark.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Undimmed by human tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever sing well-known words without really thinking about
their meaning? What did Katherine Bates have in mind when she wrote
that line? Certainly not the absence of sorrow, for where there are
people, there is sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   We can only guess at her thoughts. Our country _ this sprawling
and mighty U.S. of A. _ has never shed tears because another
country rained destruction on our cities. Our gleaming buildings
stand tall. Perhaps that was the author's thought. I'm sure there
are other interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   The last four lines of this last verse are like those of the
first, a reminder once more of the blessedness of our country. Walt
Whitman wrote a poem about the diversity of America, titled ``I
Hear America Singing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear America singing, the varied carols I hear,
</P>
<P>
   Those of mechanics, each one singing his as it should be blithe
and strong
</P>
<P>
   The carpenter singing his as he measures his plank or beam,
</P>
<P>
   The mason singing his as he makes ready for work, or leaves off
work,
</P>
<P>
   The boatman singing what belongs to him in his boat, the deck
hand singing on the steamboat deck,
</P>
<P>
   The shoemaker singing as he sits on his bench, the hatter
singing as he stands,
</P>
<P>
   The woodcutter's song, the plowboy's on his way in the morning,
or at noon intermission or at sundown,
</P>
<P>
   The delicious singing of the mother, or of the young wife at
work, or of the girl sewing or washing,
</P>
<P>
   Each singing what belongs to him or her and to no one else,
</P>
<P>
   The day what belongs to the day _ at night the party of young
fellows, robust, friendly,
</P>
<P>
   Singing with open mouths their strong melodious songs.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ruby Maschke lives in Bad Axe. Her column has appeared each
week in the Huron Daily Tribune for the last 40 years. Write to her
at the Huron Daily Tribune, P.O. Box 10, Bad Axe, Mich. 48413.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
