</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTSERRAT-BOX-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONTSERRAT: AT A GLANCE
 &HT;    With MONTSERRAT-VOLCANO-$ADV06.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTSERRAT
</P>
<P>
   Population: About 4,500 (down from 12,000 before volcano
eruption).
</P>
<P>
   Area: 39 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Location: 350 miles southeast of Puerto Rico, just off the
Caribbean islands of Antigua and Nevis.
</P>
<P>
   History: Columbus spotted Montserrat in 1493, naming if after an
abbey of the same name in Spain. Irish Catholics settled on the
island in the mid-1600s after leaving their uneasy base on the
Protestant island of St. Kitts.
</P>
<P>
   Volcano's history: The Soufriere Hills Volcano erupted in July
1995 after nearly four centuries of dormancy. By 1997 it had killed
at least 19 people, forced two-thirds of the population into exile,
and rendered most of the island unsafe for human habitation. The
volcano is still active, though it is becoming dormant.
</P>
<P>
   Government: A British dependent territory, Montserrat has a
representative government with a ministerial system. Queen
Elizabeth II is head of state and is represented by a resident
governor, now Tony Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: The East Caribbean dollar, although most people accept
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Language: English.
</P>
<P>
   To get travel information: Call the Montserrat Tourist Board at
1-664-491-2230.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; tad-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTSERRAT-EXPATS-$AD     06-08 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTSERRAT-EXPATS-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNDER MONTSERRAT'S VOLCANO: Thousands fled, many Americans
stayed behind
 &HT;    600&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With MONTSERRAT-VOLCANO-$ADV13.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETER'S, Montserrat _ To hear Nancy Burke tell it, this
island's string of natural disasters began with the flash floods of
1981. Those were followed by the earthquake in 1985, followed by
Hurricane Hugo in 1989, followed by the eruption of the Soufriere
Hills volcano in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this tiny island has had more than its share of bad
luck, so much so that some Montserratians believe God is trying to
tell them something.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even an erupting volcano hasn't been able to persuade Burke
and her husband, Richard Hermany(CQ), to permanently abandon their
comfortable villa here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing left is fire or locusts,'' reasoned Burke, 57.
``But we love it here. We couldn't afford to live like this back in
the states.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke is a chatty, one-time belly dancer from Manhattan. Her
husband earned a living on Broadway, performing in shows such as
``Hello Dolly!'' with Ginger Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   The pair bought their spacious abode, which includes a 42-foot
swimming pool -- as well as a guest house and another swimming pool
-- in 1992 for less than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here trust one another completely,'' Burke said. ``You
never even have to lock your doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing lacking? ``A good dentist,'' claimed Hermany, 71.
</P>
<P>
   Before the volcano, this island was an upscale tourist
destination that supported 12,000 people. It also was a popular
spot for American retirees. Whereas other islands have had cricket;
Montserrat has had golf.
</P>
<P>
   Then the volcano unexpectedly sprang to life, killing at least
19 people, forcing two-thirds of the population into exile, and
rendering most of Montserrat unfit for human habitation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what's often been called the Emerald Isle, in part
because of its lushness, has remained a powerful magnet for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps hundreds of expatriates either spend winters here, or
live here year-round, mostly in a northern ``safe zone'' that
encompasses about a third of this 39-square-mile British territory.
</P>
<P>
   An American couple, Robert and Beverly Kleeb from Howell, Mich.,
are the only people to openly defy a government order to leave the
so-called ``danger zone'' near the volcano.
</P>
<P>
   They say all their money's tied up in their $800,000 villa,
perched high atop a cliff above the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   They refuse to abandon their property, powered by a generator,
even though the volcano is still active, spewing hot gases into the
air.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see the island's appeal, however.
</P>
<P>
   Too small and friendly to be intimidating, roads snake passed
shingled cottages that bear cutesy names such as ``Chez Mango,''
and are shaded by breadfruit trees and smothered in mostly pink and
yellow bougainvillea.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seems to know and care about everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers greet passers-by again and again with a wave and a quick
``toot-toot'' of their horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans have always liked Montserrat because it's like
living in a small town,'' said Pam Arthurton, owner of Carib-World
Travel, who grew up in Montserrat. ``There is no crime, or drugs,
but there are plenty of good fruits and vegetables.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Mitchell was a vice president for Georgia-Pacific Corp.
before buying a house here with his wife, Marcia, in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started coming here in 1989 and every time we would stay
longer and longer,'' he said. ``We have coffee in the morning and
look out over the ocean and it's spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchells' home has a long veranda overlooking crystal-clear
sea, which they say is perfect for snorkeling. A waterfall just
outside their bedroom window lulls them to sleep each night.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans say they were drawn to Montserrat by pure
economics: a population explosion on many of the Caribbean's larger
islands had made it increasingly difficult to find unspoiled,
reasonably priced property in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Montserrat's so popular: labor is cheap, with
maids costing $3 to $4 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   This island was first colonized in the mid-1600s by Irish
Catholics who came over from the neighboring, but mostly Protestant
island of St. Kitts. Even now, St. Patrick's Day is a national
holiday, and passports here are stamped with a bright, green
shamrock.
</P>
<P>
   Volcanic in origin, this pear-shaped island has hot mineral
springs. Americans insist the water here's so clean and tasty that
it should be bottled and sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One of these Americans is David Lea, from Warren, Ohio, who
moved his family here in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Clover, and their three sons, live in a
treehouse-like dwelling that looks like something straight out of
``The Swiss Family Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no shortage of hammocks or fresh flowers, a look David
Lea describes as ``well-done hippie.''
</P>
<P>
   There's even a hot tub on the deck with sweeping views of the
sea, and a hydroponics garden, where vegetables grow in
nutrient-rich solution, rather than soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure the kids still play with their Game Boy, but they also
swing on ropes,'' David Lea said. ``Our children use their
imaginations, just like I did when I was growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
