<HEADLINE>
BANK FORECAST SEES GOOD YEAR FOR FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Following a less than fruitful 1998 season,
California farmers can look forward to a more profitable crop in
1999, according to a survey conducted by the Bank of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If production conditions prove favorable for the remainder of
1999, the value of the state's final agricultural output and net
farm income should rise,'' Vernon Crowder, an agricultural
economist at the Bank of America, said in a statement accompanying
the release Monday of the bank's 1999 Agricultural Outlook report.
</P>
<P>
   The study also foresees a good year for dairies, which should
benefit from low feed costs. Increased demand for California
products in the previously depressed markets of Asia also bodes
well for the state's farmers, according to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a good year,'' said Marilyn Watkins, a
spokeswoman for the California Tree Fruit Agreement in Reedley,
which represents about 2,000 California growers.
</P>
<P>
   The optimism is welcome after a poor year for the state's
agribusiness industry. In 1998, according to the Bank of America
report, lower market prices and lower yields because of heavy rains
reduced net farm income by 43 percent to $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The report found the cotton industry was hit hardest by last
year's downturn. The drop in net income for this industry, as well
as others, was due in part to weak global markets. Just the same,
Mother Nature gets a big chunk of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins agreed with the Bank of America assessment: ``The main
problem last season had to do with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank remains bullish on farming, despite more harsh weather
this season _ primarily lower temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Freezing December temperatures in the San Joaquin Valley damaged
more than 80 percent of the citrus crop, according to the report.
Stormy, cold weather in March and April also reduced the yield for
numerous grape, vegetable, tree fruit and nut crops.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the overall damage to the harvest has been
moderate, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the weather that was so bad for citrus trees was
actually a boon for other fruit trees, particularly peaches,
nectarines and plums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold weather in the winter actually has a good effect on our
fruit. It gives it good flavor,'' Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of America report focuses solely on the financial
outlook of agribusiness and means little to consumers, Watkins
said. She said prices should be about the same as they were last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
