<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR 20-SOMETHINGS: INVEST EARLY AND WISELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For 20-somethings who haven't yet sprained their
brains on matters financial, here's some beginner's advice from
financial adviser and author Daniel Goldie: Forget that sizzling
start-up company or initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Most starry-eyed young investors hear of the occasional
high-tech worker who strikes it rich. They don't hear about the
many horror stories, the bankruptcies, the financial failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good analogy is my tennis career,'' said Goldie, a senior
financial adviser for RWB Securities Inc. in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're sports fans, they may know about me, but they
rarely hear about the thousands of tennis players who never made it
to the college or professional level.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldie, who is co-author of ``The Prudent Investor's Guide to
Beating Wall Street at Its Own Game'' (McGraw-Hill), learned his
money lessons the hard way. He grew up in McLean, Va., where his
parents divorced when he was 13, and he and his bookkeeper mother
stretched to live on one salary.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, at Stanford University, Goldie developed into
a world-class tennis player. He was the National Collegiate
Athletic Association singles men's champion in 1986, then turned
pro, made the Wimbledon quarterfinals and earned a No. 27 world
ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with cash at an early age, Goldie was forced to make tough
decisions. Dive into spending sprees and flirt with bankruptcy like
many young pro athletes? Or buckle down and invest in his future?
He chose the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a high-spending lifestyle _ I learned early on
to keep my expenses down,'' said Goldie, 35, who lives on the
Peninsula with his wife and two young boys. ``The returns on my
money have been great.''
</P>
<P>
   He offers this advice to younger people:
</P>
<P>
   _ Start saving early for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Delayed gratification pays off. Those who commit money early for
retirement _ even if it's 50 years away _ will be grinning when
they hit their golden years.
</P>
<P>
   At a 10 percent annual return, if you start saving $5,000 a year
at age 25, you'll have $2.2 million when you retire at 65. Start at
35, and you'll accrue $822,000. Start at 45, and you'll end up with
only $286,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year you delay, it costs you a lot of money,'' Goldie
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn to invest wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Too many young people invest based on hot tips from financial
gurus. Or they trade like mad, trying to time the market. Or they
imagine themselves to be the next high-tech employee who cashes out
big on stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Goldie said they need to return to the foundations of investing.
Among other principles, that includes balancing their portfolios,
carefully choosing mutual funds and understanding risk vs. returns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tone down those high expectations of the bull market and
diversify your portfolio to reduce risk.
</P>
<P>
   Many giddy 20-somethings and young baby boomers have experienced
only the raging bull market. Sooner or later, a bear market will
hit, Goldie said.
</P>
<P>
   During good or bad times, it pays to balance one's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Look at one of Goldie's former clients, a Silicon Valley manager
who owned hundreds of shares in a sizzling software company. The
stock had a great run, earning 20 to 30 percent returns over
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Goldie strongly recommended that the young man sell some of
those holdings and spread out the risk among other strong stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The man ignored the advice. A few weeks later, the software
company's stock got crushed, plunging 70 percent. The man lost more
than $1 million, Goldie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't understand the difference between
investment strategies that make them enormous wealth _ and
investment strategies that keep their wealth for them,'' Goldie
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A heavily concentrated position in a high-growth stock makes
their wealth,'' he said. ``But if they want to keep their wealth,
they need a well-diversified portfolio. To keep their wealth, they
need to reduce their risk.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Save for home-buying.
</P>
<P>
   Even party-hardy 20-somethings will want to start a family and
buy a home one day, Goldie said. That time will come sooner than
they think.
</P>
<P>
   After putting money into retirement vehicles such as
tax-sheltered 401(k)s, 403(b)s and IRAs, they should save up to 10
percent of their paychecks for a big house down payment. That money
should sit in a short-term bond fund or other safe place, Goldie
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy disability insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Many young people carry health, auto and life insurance, but few
look at disability insurance, Goldie said. A young worker's
greatest asset is his or her earning power over the next 40 years.
A good disability package _ covering, say, 70 percent of those
wages _ will protect that asset if he or she is unable to work.
</P>
<P>
   Private disability insurance goes far beyond the meager payments
from the state workers' compensation program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you're hurt at work and you lose all of your
income,'' Goldie said. ``For a young person, injury is the highest
risk _ not death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
