<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDISTRICTING MEANS END OF BIPARTISANSHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush was hugging Democratic and
Republican lawmakers alike on the closing day of the Texas
legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   He knew each side had contributed significantly to tax cuts,
teacher pay raises and other successes that he will largely claim
as his own when he finally takes his presidential campaign out of
state this week.
</P>
<P>
   The large tent on Bush's front lawn, where he hosted a fajita
luncheon for legislators, was clearly big enough for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   But there were clouds on the horizon that portended a much
stormier session for lawmakers the next time they get together _ in
2001 _ with or without Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican governor was praising the virtues of
bipartisanship, leaders of the Republican and Democratic parties
were tearing it down.
</P>
<P>
   The different reactions were not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   Bush needed the help of Democrats to get most of his program
through the Legislature. And although he will be running for the
nation's highest office in a partisan election system, he will
welcome _ and receive _ the support of many Democrats in his quest
for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of political parties, meanwhile, have much simpler and
easier jobs. They don't have to govern. They just have to be
partisan. And not to disappoint the expectations of their
followers, Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm and her
Republican counterpart, Susan Weddington, fired broadsides.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm said that Democratic legislators, not the governor, were
the true leaders, and Weddington issued a six-page statement
extolling the virtues of Republican leadership and bemoaning the
fact that GOP lawmakers had to share the statehouse _ or the
planet, for that matter _ with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's praise of bipartisanship notwithstanding, next year's
legislative races may be more contentious than ever, and the 2001
session may spatter political blood all over the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   While the just-completed legislative session was dominated by
Bush's presidential race, the next session and the legislative
elections leading up to it will be dominated by that most partisan
of all legislative endeavors, redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   During the 2001 session, the Legislature will have the task of
redrawing legislative and congressional district boundaries to
reflect changing population patterns determined by the 2000 federal
census.
</P>
<P>
   The new legislative district lines will be particularly
important because they will help determine the partisan makeup of
the Legislature for the next decade and perhaps longer. That's why
Republicans and Democrats both attach a lot of importance to the
partisan affiliation of the lawmakers who draw the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have never had in modern times a majority of either
the Texas House or the state Senate during a redistricting session,
which normally occurs every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now have a 16-15 majority in the Senate, but at
least two Senate seats _ and maybe more _ will likely be highly
contested next year. Democrats are expected to make a strong run at
the seat held by Sen. Drew Nixon, R-Carthage, and Republicans are
expected to mount a strong challenge of Sen. David Cain, D-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to erase a political liability, Weddington last week took
the unusual step of publicly urging Nixon _ a member of her own
party _ not to seek re-election. Nixon served time in jail a couple
of years ago for illegally carrying a handgun after he was arrested
in a prostitution sting in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the election year action will be focused on the House,
where Republicans once again will try to capture a majority. They
have been inching closer in recent elections, but Democrats still
hold a 78-72 edge.
</P>
<P>
   If they were to capture a House majority next year, Republicans
also would try to elect one of their own speaker in 2001 _ if they
could agree on a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   It's way too early, obviously, to predict how the 2001
redistricting effort _ with or without a Republican House majority
_ will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   If partisanship keeps the Legislature from finishing the job,
the Republicans would have the upper hand. Last year's GOP sweep of
statewide offices gave Republicans a majority of the Legislative
Redistricting Board, which would draw the lines if lawmakers don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too early, however, to predict that the redistricting
process will be contentious _ and very partisan. It also may prove
to be so distracting that it will be extremely difficult to pass
other major legislation.
</P>
<P>
   If so, Bush, if he is still here, or Gov. Rick Perry may be
hosting a food fight, rather than a bipartisan luncheon, at
session's end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
