<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKING IRIS PLANT MAKES ATTRACTIVE BASKET SUBJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have an unusual plant that looks like a spider or airplane
plant. It has done well in its basket. It has long runners with
baby spiders but, to my surprise, these babies have flowers
April-May. The blooms have three large white petals with three
small curled violet petals in the center. There are tan markings
near the base of the petals. I was told it could be a walking iris.
What say you?
</P>
<P>
   A: I say walking iris, ``Neomarcia gracilis,'' an evergreen iris
relative that matures to a height of about 2 feet. The glossy green
fans are attractive, especially when the plants are allowed to mass
in a flower bed. But as you see, this plant makes an attractive
basket subject.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers are 2 inches wide and are white with yellow and
brown markings and blotched blue. As each bloom fades, a plantlet
forms, and as this grows larger and therefore heavier, the stalk
bends until the plantlet reaches the ground and roots: therefore,
the name walking iris.
</P>
<P>
   This perennial thrives in filtered or partial sun and prefers
water while growing. Protect from freezing temperatures with a
layer of mulch. The top may burn back during harsh cold, but the
roots are usually hardy.
</P>
<P>
   This is an easy-to-care-for plant that is fun to share with
friends.
</P>
<P>
   There is another iris in this genus, Neomarica longifolia, that
is equally easy. While the plant produces plantlets where blooms
fade, the stalks do not bend, so the plant does not walk. However,
new fans will pop up near the mother plant over time, and, of
course, you can remove the plantlets, as you would a daylily pip,
and plant them.
</P>
<P>
   The late spring through summer blooms on this evergreen are
yellow and mottled with brown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I planted three climbing roses this spring. They are growing
vigorously, but are not producing any buds. The tag says they
should produce in the first season. Also, something is eating
nickel-size holes in the leaves. Any ideas as to what this could
be?
</P>
<P>
   A: Climbing roses can take a while longer than shrub roses to
bloom. However, too much nitrogen can sometimes cause overly
vigorous growth at the expense of blooms. Since your plants are
growing well, just try to be patient. (I assume your roses are
repeat bloomers, rather than only in spring.)
</P>
<P>
   If those holes are circular and at the edges of the leaves, I
bet leafcutting bees are at work. The bees use the leaf parts in
their nests. These insects are important pollinators, and I've
found do only cosmetic damage to the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have a Norfolk Island pine purchased several years ago as
a living Christmas tree. It is now quite large and too heavy to
move frequently. Is it possible to transplant this potted tree into
our garden to preserve it as an outdoor specimen?
</P>
<P>
   A: In their native habitats, Norfolks can reach 50 feet. Here we
find a Norfolk will eventually outgrow its use as a house plant,
and we're faced with finding it a home in a building with an atrium
or moving it to the patio, where it is subject to freeze damage in
winter. Generous layering of blankets will help during a hard
freeze, but the plant may suffer damage.
</P>
<P>
   You could plant your tree in the garden, but when there is harsh
cold, you would need to take extra precautions to protect it.
</P>
<P>
   Many try to prune too-tall Norfolks, but in doing so, ruin the
natural shape. Rather than top it in such a manner, you can take a
foot or foot and a half off the top and root this cutting to
produce a new plant. While this still results in a rather misshapen
plant, it may not look quite as bad. The top cutting should include
two tiers of lateral branches. Remove the bottom branches before
planting the cutting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents replies to all unpublished letters. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
