</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDITATION-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS FIND A DOSE MEDITATION MAY HELP HEART PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NISKAYUNA, N.Y. _ Every afternoon, Edward Koch sits in a chair
in his home and meditates.
</P>
<P>
   He had a heart attack in 1994 and health specialists at Kaiser
Permanente encouraged him to improve his diet, exercise and
meditate to help with his recovery program.
</P>
<P>
   Of all those lifestyle changes, meditating proved to be the most
simple yet the most challenging for Koch, then a 64-year-old
researcher for the General Electric Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, `Am I doing it right? Am I leaving something out? Why
aren't I levitating off the ground?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Koch has yet to levitate but through daily meditation he has
experienced a sense of peace and inner strength against the
distractions and stresses of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In traffic, I didn't have that urgency or road rage. My wife
seemed to notice I was a lot calmer. I think it's helped me fight
this heart disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A growing body of research shows that meditation does just that,
by reducing heart rate and blood pressure, improving immune
function and decreasing stress-hormone levels.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dr. Dean Ornish's Program for Reversing Heart Disease,''
meditation is given the same importance for improving heart health
as diet and exercise.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 panel at the National Institutes of Health found ``strong
evidence'' that meditation and other relaxation techniques are
effective at treating a variety of chronic conditions, from heart
disease to migraines, lower-back pain and arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any form of stress management is helpful,'' said Dr. David
Armenia, the medical director of Cardiac Rehabilitation and the
Intensive Care Unit at Ellis Hospital in Schenectady. ``The problem
is that getting most people to do something like that is
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are plenty of reasons not to try it: time constraints,
skepticism and boredom at the idea of sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   Koch was one of those skeptics. When he first started
meditating, he felt fidgety and his mind jumped around, flitting
from thought to thought. ``At first, I didn't think too much of it
... but I did it because it was part of the program.,'' he said.
``I look forward to it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Bodian, a longtime practitioner and teacher of
meditation and the author of a new book, ``Meditation for
Dummies,'' tells his students not to worry about that initial
restlessness.
</P>
<P>
   Meditation takes practice and it's the process of practicing
that makes it so helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to know that there's really no wrong way to
meditate,'' Bodian said from his office in Marin County, Calif.
``It's to make a shift from thinking and planning to just being.''
</P>
<P>
   As he points out in his book, we let our minds stress us out by
replaying negative conversations, hashing over worrisome scenarios
and creating inner dramas based on events of the past or the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Such constant mind chatter not only raises the level of stress
hormones in the body, but also distracts us from enjoying the
present moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the regular practice of meditation, you can reduce
your suffering and stress by stilling and ultimately dissipating
the confusion and turbulence inside you,'' Bodian writes in his
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``As one Zen master put it, `If your mind isn't clouded by
unnecessary things, this moment is the best moment of your life.'''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a Buddhist, or a subscriber to any kind of
thought system, to appreciate that insight. Nor do you need any
fancy equipment, tapes or the ability to sit cross-legged on the
floor to meditate. ``I just sit in a chair and repeat, `Relax, let
go,' and I kind of form a visual picture in my mind of somebody
cutting a rope with knots in it. That's the tension letting go,''
Koch said.
</P>
<P>
   As Bodian points are, there are dozens of ways to meditate.
Count your breaths, focus on an image, whatever you feel
comfortable doing. Start with five minutes and gradually increase
your time. If you feel your mind wandering, return your focus to
your breathing.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you do it, remember the most important step is the
doing: ``Don't get stressed out about it,'' Bodian said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
