<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURAL-PRESERVATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE PROGRAM TO FOCUS ON ARCHITECTURAL RENOVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute hopes to draw on
the rich architecture of New York's capital region _ from the Dutch
colonial influences to the marble megaliths of the Empire State
Plaza _ with a new degree program in architectural renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Northeast, we are built out,'' said Alan Balfour, dean
of RPI's school of architecture. ``We're increasingly focused on
maintaining what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The new program, to begin this fall, is emblematic of a national
trend. In 1996, the American Institute of Architects projected that
a few years into the new millennium, building rehabilitation will
overtake new construction as a percentage of the total construction
projects in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrored on RPI's successful Executive MBA Program, the Master
of Science in Building Conservation is geared toward working
professionals. Courses will be offered on weekends. Students and
their families will be encouraged to commune at a nearby hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows access to this discipline for people who can't
afford to quit their job for two years while they get a master's,''
said Michael Lynch, vice president of the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities in Boston and a member of
the advisory committee for the new program.
</P>
<P>
   The degree is currently slated as a pilot, pending approval by
the state Department of Education. Seven students are enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch described the area around Albany, the state capital, as an
ideal place to launch such a project, with its rich architectural
choices.
</P>
<P>
   What few realize, he added, is that the area is also home to
some of the nation's premier preservationists _ architects like
John Waite, who handled the renovation of the Lincoln Memorial and
the homes of George Washington and Thomas Jefferson in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Almost unheard of three decades ago, historic preservation as a
distinct architectural specialty grew out of the excesses wrought
by urban renewal and the massive expansion of the highway system in
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   While much of urban America underwent an economic development
boom at the time, the Albany area lagged behind. This was bad news
for almost everyone but historic preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting irony: Poverty is the best preservation
tool,'' said Lynch, who until recently was a senior preservation
coordinator with the state of New York. ``Albany never seemed to
get the economic development pressure that cities like Boston and
Philadelphia got. Yeah, we got urban renewal. But we still have
hundreds, thousands of wonderful, old buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the science of renovation, students in the RPI
program will learn preservation law and how to apply for grants. In
New York alone, more than $8 million is available through the
preservation grants system.
</P>
<P>
   Preserving the past takes time. Waite said that one of his
projects, a British army barracks in Trenton, N.J., took more than
20 years to fund and restore.
</P>
<P>
   But he believes that's the direction his profession is headed.
``There is a huge emphasis on restoring existing buildings right
now,'' he said. ``The field of architecture has turned upside
down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
