A7310 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-08 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(nk) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Bonn, Germany) _ Eight nations including
Russia agree on a U.N. Security Council resolution authorizing a
peacekeeping force for Kosovo with NATO at the core of the
operation. ``We got what we came for,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ A look at the involvement of Russia's
military in peace efforts. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Somewhere in Kosovo) _ An escorted visit to
Kosovo. By Steven Erlanger. With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Morini/Kukes, Albania) _ Latest on the Kosovo
Liberation Army. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Belgrade, Yugoslvia) _ Yugoslavia is making a
bid to retain some control of its borders by vetting who will
return from among the refugees, a Yugoslav foreign ministry
spokesman says at a news conference. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ White House reaction to U.N.
resolution on peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Finnish president meets with Chinese
leaders, speaks optimistically of getting a U.N. resolution. Jiang
and Yeltsin talk by phone. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ Talking to the Chinese Government is a
little difficult these days, but trying to figure out the best ways
to apologize over the Chinese Embassy bombing have tied the varying
teams of the administration into knots. A mission of some officials
may go to Beijing by the end of the week, with hopes of settling
the World Trade Organization matter. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPY-CASE (Washington) _ Examining the case of the nuclear
weapons scientist suspected as a spy for China, focusing on
ambiguities in the evidence and difficulty of bringing any charges.
By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ After snubbing Pakistan offer,
India offers to hold talks with Pakistan on Saturday. By John
Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SCANDAL (Mexico City) _ On a Zedillo campaign finance
scandal. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Jakarta) _ Slow election returns left
Indonesia in suspense Tuesday about the shape of its political
future. But whatever the outcome of Monday's vote, a fundamental
shift in power already seemed to be taking place: people were
choosing their leaders. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (Also see INDONESIA-ECON in financial news.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TREATMENT (Phoenix) _ A dozen years after the national
alarm over crack speeded the discarding of drug treatment in favor
of punitive laws that helped create the world's largest prison
system, drug policy is taking another turn. Treatment is making a
comeback, driven largely by a grass-roots revolt. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-PORTLAND-JOBS (Hillsboro, Ore.) _ The Portland area is so
intent on controlling growth that it has just completed a
tax-incentive compact with its largest private employer, Intel,
under which Intel will pay a penalty if it creates too many jobs.
By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ House unity challenged again, with
reports from Republican conference where Hastert tries to assert
control. In the Senate, things are going much more smoothly, and
the defense spending bill should pass. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-PLANE-CRASH (Washington) _ The runway at Little Rock, Ark.,
where an American Airlines jet crashed on June 1, narrowly avoided
having to add a 1,000-foot safety zone in precisely the area where
the MD-80 hit heavy steel stanchions, broke up and caught fire,
because of the way the Federal Aviation Administration's airports
division wrote its regulations. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TEENS-IDS (Washington) _ Young teen-agers will need photo
ID's (and, as always, an accompanying adult) to get into R-rated
movies. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS-JUVENILES (Washington) _ Developments on juvenile justice
bill. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATHOME-EXCITE (Redwood City, Calif.) _ Several of the big cable
companies that control At Home are now dropping hints that the
acquisition of Excite Inc. was a mistake. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Undated) _ A look at the impact of President
Clinton's proposal to require Medicare to offer prescription drug
coverage to all beneficiaries. Will this kill the Medigap insurance
business? Will it sharply restrict the ability of pharmaceutical
companies to set drug prices as high as they would like?
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ECON (Jakarta) _ Despite uncertainty over the winner
of the Indonesian elections, the peaceful conditions surrounding
the voting has produced near euphoria and a sense of optimism about
the Indonesian economy. The stock market jumped 12 percent Tuesday
and was in the forefront of stock gains throughout Asia. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (Also see INDONESIA-ELECTION in international news.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-BNY (Detroit) _ The General Motors Acceptance Corp. will pay
$1.8 billion to acquire BNY Financial, the Bank of New York's
asset-based lending and factoring unit. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELEMENTS-DISCOVERED (Undated) _ Two new elements _ with atomic
numbers 118 and 116 _ have been discovered at Livermore Berkeley
Labs by crashing a beam of krypton atoms into lead atoms. By
Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   HORMONE-BREAST-CANCER (undeate) _ An article in the Journal of
the American Medical Association reports on a new study of the
relationship between hormone replacement therapy taken during
menopause and the woman's chances of developing breast cancer. By
Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (undated) _ ``Liberties'' by Maureen Dowd.
</P>
