<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COFFEE-ORGANIC-HNS &LR;      06-08 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COFFEE-ORGANIC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAN COUNTERS MAY GET NEW ORDER: ORGANIC COFFEE ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ One of life's simple pleasures may soon
become increasingly complex.
</P>
<P>
   If Berkeley Mayor Shirley Dean has her way, city departments
will be required to buy only organic coffee produced under fair
trade conditions. Previous Berkeley initiatives prevent the city
from buying Salvadoran coffee beans or serving beverages in
Styrofoam cups.
</P>
<P>
   But Dean, who admits her proposal is largely symbolic because of
the small amount of coffee the city actually buys, said the new
restrictions wouldn't inconvenience employees and might help
preserve the environment and improve conditions for coffee growers
in developing nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Berkeley people are really passionate about coffee, and
organic coffee is gourmet and also allows people to do something
for the environment that is socially responsible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certified organic'' coffee beans, according to Dean's office,
are grown without heavy use of pesticides and other chemicals,
certified as such by a third party. ``Shade'' organic coffee has
the additional benefit of being grown in the shade of taller jungle
trees, thereby preserving forests and bird habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Organic coffee has been widely available since the early 1990s,
but still makes up only about 5 percent of the gourmet coffee and 1
percent of all coffee sales in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it still only makes up a small percentage of the coffee
sold, organic coffee is the fastest growing segment of the coffee
market and is growing by about 18 to 20 percent a year,'' said Dave
Griswold, owner of the organic coffee bean wholesaler Sustainable
Harvest in Emeryville.
</P>
<P>
   Fair-trade coffee, Griswold said, are beans for which growers
are guaranteed a certain price regardless of the sometimes volatile
swing of the coffee commodities market. The theory goes that
because prices are guaranteed, workers are typically assured of
receiving a living wage.
</P>
<P>
   As in manufacturing athletic shoes and other clothing, Griswold
said, producing coffee beans is an endeavor in which unskilled
workers in developing countries often receive a disproportionately
small share of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   Dean, who said she drinks six to 10 cups of coffee a day, said
she had gotten the idea for the purchasing restriction from the
longtime West Berkeley wholesale coffee distributor Uncommon
Grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been selling organic and conventional coffee
since 1984, but has seen the demand for organic jump in the past
few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like wine in California in the '60s,'' said Uncommon
Grounds general manger Kim Moore. ``To most people it was just red
or white and came in a big jug, but then people got smart about it
_ that's what's happened with coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley Finance Director Fran David said the city typically
spends about $6,000 a year on coffee.
</P>
<P>
   David said there was no citywide coffee buying policy, and most
departments handled it on their own. However, she said similar
policies have been implemented in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have restrictions against Salvadoran beans, virgin redwood,
companies that do business with Nigeria, Burma and Tibet, and any
company engaged with the nuclear industry, including IBM and
Motorola,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Styrofoam cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
