<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE-OIL (New York) _ California olive oils have come far in
the last 10 years. Not only can some brands stand up to the best
that Italy exports, in the judgment of discerning buyers in this
country. But they also command such dazzling prices that they are
best used as a condiment, like that dainty drizzle over fish. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-TOMATOES (Undated) _ Anyone who is panting for the local
tomato season to begin has already missed its opening. For true
tomato fans, the season begins when the first green tomatoes arrive
at the markets. And they have. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-ALEHOUSE (Norwich, Vt.) _ To cosset their guests, some
innkeepers bake their own bread, make their own jams or grow their
own mesclun. Tim Wilson, an owner of the Jasper Murdock Alehouse at
the Norwich Inn in Norwich, Vt., brews tasty, full-bodied beers _
from hoppy pale ales to thick, creamy stouts. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BASQUE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews ``The
Basque Kitchen'' by Gerald Hirigoyen (HarperCollins). With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The Minimalist: Grilled butterflied
leg of lamb. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (Vouvray, France) _ The last time I was here, 14 years
ago, the railroad was planning to run its new high-speed train
through the town's vineyards. The winemakers were up in arms and
one of them, Gaston Huet, explained it all to me over a bottle of
his 1947 Vouvray, an unforgettable wine the color of burnished
gold. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ Capsule review of Monthelie Les Champs
Fulliots 1996, Bouchard Pere et Fils, Burgundy.
</P>
