<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TB-CURE-LUNG-NYTSF &LR;      06-08 2589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TB-CURE-LUNG-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRUTAL CURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By LISA BELKIN  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Operating room No. 5 at University Hospital in Denver is chilled
almost to the point of refrigeration, but already the team of
surgeons is sweating. The noxious scent of burning flesh fills the
air as a cauterizing instrument slices through the skin. Next comes
the snapping sound of bone, first one rib removed, then another,
until finally the target is in view.
 &HT;    ``His lung looks awful,'' says Dr. Marvin Pomerantz, one of a
small fraternity of surgeons in the world who would even attempt
this operation. ``I always hope it will be better than expected,
but it never is.''
 &HT;    The young man on the table has tuberculosis. His is a sinister
strain, resistant to all known medication, and his right lung, or
what remains of it, shows the devastation of the disease. A lung
should be pink, nestling in the chest like a delicate balloon. This
one is mottled and marbled, a red so dark it is almost black.
Beneath it, unseen, is the heart. As it beats, the lung jumps,
looking dangerous and angry.
 &HT;    The scarring from both the illness itself and the techniques
used to fight it have left the landscape of this chest cavity
scrambled beyond recognition. ``Nothing,'' Pomerantz explains, ``is
where it should be.''
 &HT;    This is less a surgery, therefore, than an excavation, as the
surgeons chip their way through the anatomical debris. The
operation began at 9 a.m.. More than two hours pass before
Pomerantz finds something familiar. ``Here's the edge of the
diaphragm,'' he says, his eyes dark with concentration over his
surgical mask. ``This is my first good landmark.''
 &HT;    The digging and snipping will go on for six hours, and Pomerantz
grows tired as he works. ``I'm a dinosaur,'' he says, and that is
exactly why he is here.
 &HT;    Medicine is supposed to march forward. Drugs, therapies,
surgical procedures _ they are all expected to become ever simpler
and more effective. That, by definition and historical precedent,
is scientific progress. But while the past decade has brought
hurtling advances, it has also brought a growing awareness that
medicine cannot always maintain its slim lead.
 &HT;    Not all that many years ago, doctors had declared victory over
infectious disease. Then the plague of AIDS appeared from nowhere
and, at the same time, bacteria that had been considered drugged
into submission mutated anew into a formidable threat.
 &HT;    ``The ancient Greeks warned of this,'' says Dr. Michael Iseman,
a pulmonologist at the National Jewish Medical and Research Center
in Denver and one of the country's leading experts on tuberculosis.
``It was hubris to believe our own press notices. We thought we
were going to conquer tuberculosis just as we thought we were going
to conquer infectious disease. But DNA wants to replicate itself,
it wants to live on and it will mutate and survive in a Darwinian
way.''
 &HT;    The same can be said of modern medicine, which is undergoing its
own unexpected counter-evolution. While still looking forward for
answers, investing in ideas that are new and untried, science is
also beginning to look back, reinvesting in ideas that have long
been abandoned. Removing all or part of a lung to stop tuberculosis
was the treatment of the 1950s.
 &HT;    Even then it was seen as a drastic and brutal approach, and by
the early 1960s a powerful generation of medications made the
surgery obsolete. Now, more than three decades later, Pomerantz
this year will perform about 30 lobectomies (partial lung removals)
and pneumonectomies (complete lung removals) on patients with
incurable microbacterial infections (a total of 350 since he began
anew in 1983).
 &HT;    ``Drugs put us out of business,'' Pomerantz says. ``Drug
resistance brought us back.''
 &HT;    Pomerantz gives his age as ``more than 60, less than Medicare.''
While he was completing his residency at Duke University Medical
Center between 1959 and 1967, TB was still a part of his training.
 &HT;    But his was the last group of surgeons to learn their trade in
the era of TB wards and sanitariums, and when surgery was later
resurrected to fight TB, Pomerantz called his own former mentor,
now a retired octogenarian, for advice. Then he tried to teach what
he remembered to a generation of young surgeons who have never
navigated their way through a TB-marred chest.
 &HT;    This return to the old ways has its notes of vindication. ``It
reminds us not to devalue the types of treatments that came
before,'' says Dr. Barron H. Lerner, a physician and medical
historian at the Columbia University College of Physicians and
Surgeons and the author of ``Contagion and Confinement,'' a history
of tuberculosis. ``Generally, people look back at these types of
procedures with disdain. They were seen as the types of things
people did when they didn't know what they were doing. But it's
really fortunate that there are people around who can still do
these operations.''
 &HT;    Pomerantz takes no satisfaction from the new premium being put
on his old skills, nor from this new awareness that medicine is not
a straight road but a looping and meandering one.
 &HT;    ``Don't think for a minute that I want to be doing this,'' he
says. ``It would be better if the drugs worked for everything _
cancer, heart disease, TB, but drugs will never be the 100 percent
answer. It's time we stop believing in a magic pill.''
 &HT;    The patient, Sonesacksith Choummanivong, is a 22-year-old
fine-arts student who is known to his family and his doctors as
Toon. The word means ``groundhog'' in Laotian, his native language,
and it became his nickname because, as an infant, he had chubby
cheeks. The moniker has stuck, a sad counterpoint to all the years
of illness that have left him gaunt and pale.
 &HT;    There is poignancy, too, in the fact that this gentle young man,
with his delicate artist's fingers, represents everything today's
infectious disease doctors fear. To them he is the personification
of contagion, the harbinger of an epidemic, the future of
tuberculosis in the United States.
 &HT;    Complacency, they remind us, led to a sharp spike in cases of TB
during the early 1990s. Vigilance then brought the numbers back
down within the country, but while Americans have been looking
inward, pleased with their progress, a new danger has arisen from
without. Last year, 40 percent of patients with tuberculosis had
come to the United States from other countries, an increase from 16
percent in 1982.
 &HT;    And therein lies the threat. The overall TB rate in New York
City is down to 21.3 per 100,000. Compare that to Bombay, where the
rate is 500 per 100,000. The crisis in Russia's prisons, in turn,
makes the Bombay statistics seem insignificant.
 &HT;    ``If you were a diabolical terrorist and you wanted to
manufacture multidrug-resistant tuberculosis, you would create an
environment and a system of care like the one in the Russian
prisons,'' says Dr. Lee B. Reichman, executive director of the New
Jersey Medical School National Tuberculosis Center.
 &HT;    He recently toured those prisons and saw, among other things,
poorly ventilated rooms where 30 prisoners shared 10 beds, sleeping
in shifts. Last year 20,000 Russian prison inmates fell ill with
strains of TB that resisted known medications. Many of those
infected inmates were then released, and they spread the disease to
15,000 civilians.
 &HT;    Some illnesses are virulent in their contagion. Put a student
with chicken pox at the front of a large lecture hall, and he
could, within minutes, infect a large percentage of the room. AIDS,
by contrast, is remarkably difficult to catch, because its
transmission requires contact with bodily fluids.
 &HT;    Tuberculosis falls somewhere in the middle. In the days before
antibiotics, doctors did experiments that included placing TB
patients in a closed room and directing air from that room into
cages filled with guinea pigs. They learned that a person must, on
average, exchange 11,000 cubic feet of air to have a 50 percent
chance of being infected. That translates into two months of
24-hour-a-day contact or six months of 8-hour-a-day contact.
 &HT;    ``Whenever there's an outbreak, reporters start calling and they
all ask, 'Can you get it on the subway?''' Reichman says. Because
the above figures are an average, he says, ``we tell them,
'Statistically, the answer is yes, you can, but it's more likely
the subway will crash.'''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, researchers estimate that each person with active
TB will go on to infect between 9 and 12 others, meaning a minimum
of 3.5 million new drug-resistant cases in Russia alone in the next
year. Now add modern transportation to this mix. ``It's tempting to
some people to talk about keeping the foreigners out,'' Reichman
says. ``Unfortunately _ or fortunately _ you can't. So we have to
confront the problem, not hide from it.''
 &HT;    Toon Choummanivong escaped from a crowded and chaotic Thai
resettlement camp in 1983, when he was 5. He, his parents and five
siblings legally settled in Holland, Mich., which is 45 minutes
south of Grand Rapids. A few years later, his father developed a
shortness of breath, night sweats and fever _ symptoms similar to
ones he'd had as a refugee in Thailand.
 &HT;    Although the family's medical history is sketchy, Toon's doctors
assume his father had been treated in Thailand with the ``first
line'' tuberculosis drugs that could once automatically cure this
disease. Because he was a penniless man in a poor country where the
health-care system was haphazard at best, he probably took those
medicines only long enough to feel better, which was not long
enough to kill all the TB bacilli in his body.
 &HT;    When he stopped taking his pills, the bugs that remained
continued to grow. Those bacilli were, by definition, the strongest
and most resistant. When he became ill again years later, in
Michigan, his disease had mutated beyond the power of the drugs. He
died in 1989.
 &HT;    Determined to live a healthy life, Toon played tennis and
soccer. He funneled his extra energies into his artwork _ bold
portraits and colorful landscapes. He ate carefully and did not
smoke or drink, even during his first semester at Dordt College in
Sioux Center, Iowa. By Christmas break in December 1995, however,
he was haggard and hacking. The symptoms were alarmingly familiar,
and they led him to Kent Community Hospital in Michigan, the same
hospital where his father died.
 &HT;    The diagnosis for Toon, too, was tuberculosis, and he was placed
in a jury-rigged isolation room for three months. Ventilation is
one low-tech but effective weapon against TB, so an unrelenting
fan, the size of a night table, was placed inches from his bed. It
ran night and day.
 &HT;    Too exhausted to tie on a mask and walk to the lounge down the
hall, he spent weeks alone, drawing with pencils in his
ever-present sketch pad. It was the dawning of the new reality of
his life _ months when no one would talk to him without hiding
behind a mask. He dared not hope for any relationship deeper than
friendship.
 &HT;    ``I've never been with anyone,'' he says. ``How can I be?'' His
life lacked even the intimacy of a smile. His portraits from that
time are striking in that they have no faces.
 &HT;    Every day he took dozens of pills _ multicapsule doses of INH,
rifampin, PZA and ethambutol. Those medications were probably the
same ones his father had taken, the ones that still cure nearly all
non-drug-resistant patients. In retrospect, his doctors now say,
they were not the best choice. Toon, they now know, did not bring
his strain of TB with him from the camps; he caught it from his
father, meaning the bugs were already resistant.
 &HT;    The medications worked well enough that within a few months Toon
felt better. The microscope, however, saw things differently. When
a sputum sample was ``cultured out,'' it grew TB bacilli, evidence
that he still harbored the disease in his lungs. The hospital sent
him home in March 1996 with a month's supply of pills. No matter
how healthy he felt, they said, he had to swallow those pills.
 &HT;    Toon had no objection to taking his medicines, because these
first-line drugs had no side effects. He also willingly observed
the restrictions on enclosed spaces _ no shopping malls or stores
or movies _ because he was reared with a respect for the rules. The
day he left the hospital, he went to the park with his brother and,
fueled by the exhilaration of being outdoors, played soccer for
three hours, until he was exhausted. He was celebrating the end of
an ordeal. He was celebrating too soon.
 &HT;    This young man lost his right lung in November. I was in the
operating room, gowned and wearing the ultraprotective mask that
resembles a duck's bill, as Pomerantz finally freed the diseased
and disfigured tissue from the chest wall and sent it off to the
pathology lab.
 &HT;    This was not my first time in an operating room, and the times I
have been lucky enough to observe surgery, I have found it
mesmerizing and beautiful. Watching a heart transplant I was awed
by the vibrant colors _ a work of art that nature never intended
for us to see _ and the moment when the donor heart was tripped to
life.
 &HT;    Choummanivong's surgery was another defining experience. It was
not beautiful; it was brutal _ hour upon hour of chipping away at
an enemy that would not surrender. The other procedures I had seen
were about giving back, replacing or fixing. This was only about
loss.
 &HT;    For several months after the final pneumonectomy,
Choummanivong's health improved. He was discharged from the
hospital before Christmas, and he weaned himself from the tanks of
oxygen that he considered such a burden. His monthly cultures were
negative for TB.
 &HT;    In late February, Toon got permission to drive with his brother
the 19 hours back to Michigan for a visit. While there, he fell ill
and thought he'd caught the flu from his young nephew. Back in
Denver, he arrived at his next appointment with an oxygen tube in
his nose, dragging the heavy canister behind him. He was shivering
and short of breath and he had dropped more than 10 pounds from his
already frail frame.
 &HT;    The next few months were agony for Choummanivong. Tests showed
he did not have the flu at all. The empty space in his right chest
had filled with TB-infected fluid. Because some surgical staples
had detached, the fluid _ with its traces of TB _ had crossed over
into his remaining lung.
 &HT;    It would take two more surgeries and an experimental new
antibiotic to control the problem. His doctors say it is still too
soon to say whether this fine young man will survive.
 &HT;     c.1999 Lisa Belkin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Lisa Belkin is the author of ``Show Me a Hero: A Tale of
Murder, Suicide, Race and Redemption.'') &LR;
</P>
