<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES &AMP; SHORT STORIES: Feeling dirty in Hollywood
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bob Mrazek has a problem. He has produced a prize
pig, and now it's time to sell it to the slaughterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mrazek thinks so much of his pig that he's trying to make a
special deal, that once it becomes the property of the
slaughterhouse, it'll continue to receive kindly treatment, same as
if it had remained with him.
</P>
<P>
   Never gonna happen.
</P>
<P>
   In way of explanation ...
</P>
<P>
   What Mrazek is selling goes by the name of ``Stonewall's Gold.''
It's not really a pig, it's a novel that he's published. The
slaughterhouse is called Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Mrazek (pronounced ``muh-RAZ-ik'') is a former Congressman from
New York state, now living the life of a successful writer in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stonewall's Gold'' is all about the Civil War, which Mrazek
knows all about. He can even tell you who General Grant was
sleeping with on the night before the Battle of Gettysburg.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year I wrote a complimentary review of
``Stonewall's Gold,'' which, in truth, is about the only kind of
reviews I ever write. If I don't like a book, I won't take up your
time telling you about it.
</P>
<P>
   I liked ``Stonewall's Gold'' ($22.95, St. Martin's Press) as
much as anything I've read lately. Set in the final winter of the
Civil War, the story is told through the voice of a 15-year-old
Southerner, Jamie Lockhart, as he makes his way across the wilds of
Virginia in search of a secret cache of Yankee bullion.
</P>
<P>
   I had talked with Mrazek on the phone but never met him. While I
was in Washington, we made it a point to visit.
</P>
<P>
   What with the success of his first published novel _ picked by
Literary Guild for an alternative selection and included in the May
edition of Reader's Digest condensed books _ I thought he'd be as
happy as ... well, a pig in mud.
</P>
<P>
   Not so. Dealing with Hollywood for the film rights, he is
beginning to feel a bit soiled.
</P>
<P>
   He told several stories of his misadventures. This one was my
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   A producer was going on and on about how wonderful, how
marvelous, how truly touched by greatness his book was. But as a
film, what it really needed was ``contemporizing.''
</P>
<P>
   The author said he wasn't sure what the producer meant by
contemporizing. After all, it's a Civil War story.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw 'Titanic,''' the producer said. ``You know the old
lady, the survivor, who remembers back on the sinking. That's what
we need for your story _ something today's kids can identify
with.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always Katharine Danridge, the beautiful young woman who
joins Jamie in the quest for gold. She was 18 at the time. That
would make her just a little past 150 years old now, Mrazek noted.
</P>
<P>
   A minor detail for Hollywood. Maybe she'd been frozen in time,
kidnapped by space aliens. There are all sorts of ways to get
around it _ as long as it's something today's kids can identify
with.
</P>
<P>
   Mrazek, as of this writing, hasn't made a decision on selling
the film rights. What he'd like is to have script approval, or even
better to write the movie version himself _ whatever is required to
preserve the integrity of the book.
</P>
<P>
   That well could happen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hollywood may come around to his point of view.
</P>
<P>
   When pigs fly.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. His mailing address is P.O.
Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email address,
jmurray(at)lcc.net; website, www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
