<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VUKOVAR-AFTERMATH-BOS     06-08 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VUKOVAR-AFTERMATH-BOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY'S FATE FORETOLD REGION'S MISERY 
</HEADLINE>
   TAKES   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VUKOVAR, Croatia _ In a restaurant on the banks of the Danube,
listening to the roar of bullfrogs from across the mighty river and
watching the fireworks away to the southeast, one might find it
hard to imagine that this is where it all began: The murders, the
ethnic expulsions, the whole prolonged spasm of war crimes that
still consumes the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But that is Serbia across the water, and the frogs are soon
silenced by the roar of NATO jets. The ``fireworks'' are
antiaircraft fire. And, when day breaks, Vukovar is revealed as a
place of catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees are trickling back from the Croatian cities whence they
fled in 1991, when Vukovar was crushed by the Yugoslav Army. If
their houses are not in the great majority that were destroyed,
they often find they must first evict Serbs, who fled their own
homes in more westerly regions of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Much that sickened the world later in Bosnia and Kosovo happened
here first. So as the United States and its allies in Europe settle
into difficult, prolonged peacekeeping roles in those places,
Vukovar is a good place in which to look at whether the evils set
loose in 1991 can ever be extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer probably is yes, but not along the lines being
pursued so far by the nations of the region and the international
community.
</P>
<P>
   Too much disputed history, too many unresolved social tensions,
too many festering personal grievances are being brushed aside,
much as they were after World War II. People cling to the fiction
that, with time, the differences between Serbs and Croats here,
which grew terribly greater during the war, will just fade away.
</P>
<P>
   Some Croats say it is too soon to confront what happened. Some
Serbs say it is too late.
</P>
<P>
   So Croat and Serb children go to school in the same buildings _
but learn separate histories and use different alphabets.
</P>
<P>
   And unmarked graves containing the mangled remains of old people
are uncovered every few days, the awful stench of the bodies
choking neighborhoods where people struggle with how to handle the
reality that many of their loved ones still are ``missing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am for all the mass graves to be dug out,'' said Ankica
Mikic, who works to help former neighbors of different ethnicities
live together again. ``When everyone who has something to say says
it, and everyone can go back to his own house, then we will have
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But few people would agree with her publicly, and none of those
things she seeks is happening. ``The situation is very hard, and
getting harder,'' said Mikic, an ethnic Serb who is a native of
Croatia. ``Both the returnees and people who stayed are full of
emotion. There is a big amount a fear among the people _ of the
government, of their neighbors, of the returnees.''
</P>
<P>
   Mikic directs a nongovernmental organization called the Center
for Peace, Legal Advice, and Psycho-Social Assistance. The name
describes major needs of people in Vukovar, but there are many
others.
</P>
<P>
   Reconstruction aid, police protection, and jobs are all in
critically short supply, and the way those resources are being
allocated suggests that the Croatian regime is discriminating
against ethnic Serbs, some of whom have lived in the region for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   This may be justified by the way Serb administrators and
military men acted when they were in charge, according to local
people who are working, often with only minimal tools and
resources, to resurrect the city, but it is no way to solve the
region's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not every Serb made war crimes, only individuals, a few,''
said Zdravko Funaric, 41, as he doused his sweat-soaked, sun-seared
head and shoulders in cold water after a day's work rebuilding the
106-year-old Tomo Goreta Gymnasium, an imposing school building in
the style of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs also stayed here in Vukovar and helped defend the city
and defend Croatia,'' he said, echoing views, heard often from
individuals here, that it was greedy, power-hungry individuals, not
Serbs as a people, who fanned ethnic tensions for their own gain.
</P>
<P>
   Now everyone suffers except the well-connected, according to
Damir Ivanovic, 29, the child of a Bosnian mother and a Croatian
father. His father was raised in Serbia, Ivanovic in Germany. The
family returned to Yugoslavia in 1984 because of the
then-teenager's passion to ``live in my own country.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his upbringing, Ivanovic does not speak with a
standard Croat accent. As a result, he sometimes is snubbed as a
Serb by other Croats, and is afraid to go into areas where tensions
between the groups are particularly high.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things are now,'' he said dispiritedly, ``I'll
probably go to another foreign country. I'm married, and have a
little kid, and there's no future here for him. Or for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why Vukovar became the flash point for war, and for ethnic
cleansing, is easy to see on a drive through the rich black soil
and Ohio-scale cornfields of Eastern Slavonia, the easternmost
region of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the Middle Ages because of its strategic location for
commerce and defense, Vukovar saw its military value wane after the
city was conquered by Ottoman emperor Suleiman the Magnificent in
1526. But its military significance was tragically restored by the
disintegration of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   To control the Danube and minimize dislocation of ethnic Serbs,
Yugoslav authorities, who were trying to gather as many Serbs as
possible into one state, decided they had to have this city.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in August 1991 and ending that November, the Yugoslav
Army laid siege to the town of 42,000 and cleared the surrounding
suburbs and outlying towns, where another 42,000 lived, of most of
their Croat residents.
</P>
<P>
   The siege of Vukovar was medieval: Snipers shot children and
women going to wells during cease-fires. Yugoslav artillerymen
leveled churches and hospitals, schools, and historic sites,
including those marked in conformance with international
conventions. In the aftermath, the victorious forces executed
civilians and wounded soldiers in the main hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this would happen elsewhere subsequently, in Dubrovnik,
Sarajevo, Mostar, and Kosovo. But the first time, the world barely
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Vukovar achieved Alamo status in Croatia because of the valor of
its defenders, a few thousand poorly armed, undertrained defenders
who held out for 86 days against the tanks, planes, and massed
troops of an encircling modern army.
</P>
<P>
   When the end came, 1,700 were confirmed dead, 5,000 were taken
away to detention camps in Yugoslavia, and there were 500 bodies
that could not be identified, according to Lovre Pejkovic, head of
Croatia's federal Office for Displaced Persons and Refugees. Most
factories were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
