<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7355 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VUKOVAR-LOOKBACK-2ND &LR;      06-08 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VUKOVAR-LOOKBACK-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 VUKOVAR, Croatia: ... were destroyed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Croatians assert to have killed more than 10,000 Serbs, and
to have destroyed 300 tanks and 25 aircraft. They say the
determination of the defenders delayed the attackers enough for the
rest of the new country to prepare defenses against the coming
onslaught. Today, every city and town in Croatia has a street
renamed for Vukovar.
</P>
<P>
   The city was under Serbian control for the next four years. But
as the balance of power in the region began to shift in favor of
Croatia, which conducted two highly successful military campaigns
in 1995 to regain lost territory, Vukovar and its vicinity were
placed in a UN protectorate. By early last year, the ruined and
depopulated town returned to Croatian hands.
</P>
<P>
   How many people live in Vukovar now, and their ethnicity, are
matters of intense political sensitivity. That's in part because
counts of displaced persons influence international aid, in part
because of upcoming elections in which many Croatians say the
ruling party could be ousted. Vukovar town officials release no
demographic information about the municipality.
</P>
<P>
   Pejkovic said the population is now about 3,000 Croats who have
registered, and 2,000 others who have not yet decided to change
their status from displaced person to returnee. He said he cannot
estimate the number of Serbs. Ruza Maric, director of the local
museum, the institution most involved in pulling together the
records of the war era, estimates the number of Croats at 2,000 and
of Serbs at 8,000, based on school enrollment, requests for ID
cards, and applications for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal to have Vukovar the same as it was before,'' said
Pejkovic, noting that a critical shortage of jobs is exacerbating
tensions. Borovo, a diversified conglomerate which before the war
employed about 22,000 people,  &UR; today &LR;  has about 500 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job creation is a huge problem,'' he said. ``If there were
more jobs, maybe there would be a good peaceful situation for both
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tall memorial candles on brass stands, their flames protected
from the breeze by red glass, stand incongruously amid hacked-back
weeds at the opening of a well. The choking odor of rotten human
flesh is in the air, but the workers being lowered into the well
shaft are used to it.
</P>
<P>
   This is Berak, a village in the suburbs of Vukovar which was
overrun and barricaded when the attack on the city began. If Serbs
and Croats are ever to live together again here, both must come to
terms with the experience of the inhabitants of this village, and
places like it.
</P>
<P>
   Knots of housewives approach the well, their arms wrapped
tightly around their chests. Neighborhood children hang on the
fringes, chattering quietly, curious.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of Ljubica Garvanovic have already been brought up,
the 60-year-old grandmother identified by the valuable old gold
coins she always carried in a matchbox in a cloth bag around her
neck. So has her son, Magic, whose remains still has identity
papers on it. They are in body bags nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the skull and long black braid of someone else. A
housewife gasps and walks away. A police officer shoos the children
off. The long, delicate process of extracting a person's bones from
the pit begins.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 117th site unearthed in Croatia containing civilians
who apparently were executed. Some sites have as few as two bodies,
some over 200. Nearly 3,000 bodies have been found like this, and
about 1,700 more who are missing are believed to have been disposed
of similarly.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Drinko Balicevic, who is supervising the excavation for the
Ministry of Health, points out, without evident irony, that from
the fragments of grenades and mortar shells found in many elderly
victims, ``it is evident that they did not die naturally, but were
liquidated.'' The presence of large sums of money on some, he
added, ``leads us to the thought that robbery was not the motive.''
Nearby, last week, he supervised a site where 16 bodies, 13 of them
from Berak, were found.
</P>
<P>
   Mlacika Rusnov, who dresses in black and looks older than her 71
years, knew all three of the people whose bodies were pulled from
the well. They, and she, were among 106 Croats whom the Serbs
released on Dec. 13, 1991, after three months in detention houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that Santa Lucia'' festival ``if I live 100
more years. They did whatever they wanted to us, came into our
house, beat us. I could hear Evica's scream as they took her around
the village, raping her,'' she said, referring to a younger woman
who now has returned to the village.
</P>
<P>
   During the second night of terror, the two older women whose
bodies have been pulled from the well were taken to the command
center, she said, and were never seen alive again. Survivors who
returned knew where to look for the bodies. The next morning,
Rusnov said, the soldiers talked openly of what they had done as
they herded the remaining Croats to town hall to sign documents
``voluntarily'' surrendering their property, then put them on the
road out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandchildren, both teenagers, have listened raptly to what
must be the umpteenth telling of the story. Now they hear their
father say ``there is no problem. Life is going on. I work with
Serbs. My children go to school with Serbs. It's separate classes,
OK. But they spend time together. The neighboring house is a Serb
house . . .''
</P>
<P>
   It is staggering self-deception, a statement that by facial
expressions the children, and perhaps the father, too, indicate
they disbelieve.
</P>
<P>
   What does he tell his children about this history? ``The
truth!'' his wife, Marija, who has been silent through the
conversation, and whose grandmother is among the missing,
interjects forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   The Croatian government insists it is looking into alleged war
crimes dispassionately, without regard to whether the victims are
Serb or Croat. A well-informed diplomatic source in Zagreb, the
capital, said that, too, is nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very real war crimes were committed. The Serb occupation was
brutal,'' the source said. ``When the Croats retook territory'' in
1995 ``_ payback time. There was three months of looting, mayhem,
and murder. There are mass graves on both sides, but the government
makes no effort to exhume the graves of the Serbs.''
</P>
<P>
   Maric, the Vukovar museum director, has spent much of her adult
life working in what was once a magnificent, mid-18th century manor
house of the German nobility. It was one of the first structures
shelled. By the time the Croats regained Vukovar, the house was a
stripped ruin. With help from UNESCO and other international
agencies, the staff has verified that treasures that were not
stolen or destroyed in the war are now in a museum across the
river, in Novi Sad. The Serbs, she said, will not discuss returning
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think in my mind that all people are not the same, but I
was living in exile when my father died, when my friends died,''
she said. ``Many Croats, you cannot find hate for Serbs in their
eyes. They will say at the end of their stories of the deaths and
beatings and imprisonments of their families `I don't hate Serbs. I
just don't want to live with them. I have no interest in those
people.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
