<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEERS, CHEERS FOR 10-YEAR-OLD TRADE PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (i and f designations)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Ten years ago, the signing of the US-Canada Free
Trade Agreement caused a sea change in the way the world's two
largest trading partners do business.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadians are wondering whether the anniversary warrants
cheers, jeers or even tears.
</P>
<P>
   Not in this century has an economic issue split Canadians or
roused more anti-American feeling than the 1989 pact that knocked
down most remaining barriers to the flow of goods and services
between the two countries. The US-Canada deal led directly to the
North American Free Trade Agreement, or NAFTA, which came five
years later when Mexico signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, as Canada and the United States coyly hint at the
possibility of even more intimate forms of economic embrace _ such
as a common currency, North America's answer to the Euro _ the
trade pact remains a prickly issue in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents still insist Canada sold its soul to America Inc.,
losing some of its cultural identity and a great deal of its
autonomy in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to Maude Barlow of the nationalist Council of
Canadians: ``Ten years of free trade has dramatically Americanized
Canadian society and imposed on our country the inequality, culture
and corporate governance of our southern neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   But such discouraging words were seldom heard this past weekend
as some of the best-known champions of free trade _ including
former Prime Minister Brian Mulroney and former President George
Bush _ gathered at Montreal's McGill University for a conference on
free trade that was really more of a 10th anniversary lovefest,
with few naysayers to spoil the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Mulroney, who led Canada from 1984 to 1993, and whose insistence
on closer trade ties with the United States made him one of the
most widely despised prime ministers in the country's history,
credited the pact and other politically unpopular policies of his
government with restoring vigor to Canada's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The US-Canada Free Trade Agreement spawned NAFTA, which is
better known to Americans since deals with Mexico stir more
controversy in the United States than deals with Canada. In Canada,
there is always more trepidation and hostility toward agreements
with the mighty neighbor than with other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian proponents of free trade say their country has reaped
fantastic economic benefits, mainly in the form of dramatically
increased exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past 10 years have seen what can only be described as an
explosion of trade,'' said John McCallum, chief economist for the
Royal Bank of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Goods and services worth more than $1 billion a day now cross
the US-Canada border, by far the largest trading relationship in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, Canadian exports to the US have jumped 169
percent, while US exports to Canada have increased 149 percent. By
the same token, however, Canada has become more dependent on the
United States for its economic well-being: Trade with the southern
neighbor accounts for 28.4 percent of Canada's total economic
output, nearly double what it was a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even McCallum, a booster, conceded that the free trade has been
a bit of a mixed blessing _ or at least not a totally unqualified
success. ``It merits two cheers, not three,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the surge in exports, the Canadian economy is far from
matching the boom across the border. Unemployment rates remain
high, 8.3 percent of the labor force, or double the jobless rate in
the United States. Canadians workers are less productive than
Americans, making the country less competitive. There is a
worrisome loss of the country's brightest doctors, scientists,
entrepreneurs and other talent to the higher pay levels and lower
taxes of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Canada remains one of the planet's most prosperous nations. But
living standards have actually slipped, at least statistically,
since the inception of free trade, with the disposable income of
the average citizen dropping by more than 5 percent, against a 12
percent increase for Americans, according to Royal Bank figures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, although hundreds of thousands of new jobs have been
created in Canada over the past 10 years, hundreds of thousands of
jobs in previously protected industries have been lost.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadian big business is bullish on the benefits of free
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an unambiguous success,'' said Tom D'Aquino,
president of the Business Council on National Issues, which
represents Canada's top 150 companies. ``It has been the catalyst,
which has reshaped the thinking and attitudes of Canadian
governments, workers and enterprises. As a result, we are vastly
more globally oriented and more conscious of who we are in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The major complaint most Canadians seem to have against free
trade is that it has left Canada more vulnerable to the cultural
juggernaut of the United States. Indeed, the McGill conference took
place only a few days after Canada suffered one of its sourest
trade defeats at the hands of the United States, with Ottawa
finally agreeing to remove barriers against American magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Canada had sought to protect its own magazine industry on the
grounds that magazines are an expression of culture, not just a
business. But the United States used the Free Trade Agreement _
coupled with threats of economic reprisal _ to batter that notion
to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's talk of a total integration of the economies of the
United States, Canada, and Mexico, one in which the three countries
might even adopt a common currency. And Canadians have little doubt
which currency would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can bet it won't carry the maple leaf or the Queen,''
commented free-trade opponent Barlow in a recent article.
</P>
</TEXT>
