<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLYMPIC-SIZE ETHICAL DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was loyal to O.J. Simpson after he was charged with double
murder and to broadcaster Marv Albert after he was charged with
sexual assault and sodomy. So it is no shock that network TV
executive Dick Ebersol would stand squarely behind the ethically
challenged International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Ebersol, president of NBC Sports, has no problem deciding which
side to choose in a moral dilemma. He sticks with his friends. And
the IOC has been a very good friend, particularly since 1995, when
the sports division won exclusive rights to carry all five Olympics
from 2000 to 2008.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is costing NBC $3.5 billion. And the hefty pricetag
seems reason enough for Ebersol to attack David D'Alessandro, head
of the John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co., a major Olympic
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro has spoken up about IOC corruption and called for
more reforms. So it makes perfect business sense for the network to
go after him to protect the value of its Olympic investment.
</P>
<P>
   Continuous headlines about alleged IOC misdeeds threaten to
diminish the amount of money corporations will pay NBC for
advertising during the Games. But is something more _ such as its
longterm exclusive television deal _ driving NBC to protect the
status quo?
</P>
<P>
   After the scandal first broke in January, reports focused on the
secretive dealings of the IOC and its president, Juan Antonio
Samaranch. Specifically regarding NBC, The New York Times reported
on what it termed ``a startling pair of deals.'' The first deal
brought NBC the rights to the Games in Sydney and Salt Lake City;
the second, for the three Olympics after that, ``reversed a bidding
practice begun for the 1988 Olympics in which each network
submitted sealed bids,'' the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   In reporting those deals, the Times focused on an Israeli named
Alex Giladi, who, the newspaper reported, was an NBC executive
since 1981, an IOC member since 1994, and a confidant of Samaranch.
The Times found no rules against Giladi's arrangement. It was just
. . . interesting. And it could be interesting as well to a
congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, Ebersol last week accused D'Alessandro of
mounting ``cynical . . . self-serving'' attacks on the IOC. He
called the Hancock executive ``a bully'' who is motivated by ``his
own desire to be on a soapbox'' and charged that his criticisms are
hurting US Olympic athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Those who cover Boston's business community know there is
nothing shy or restrained about D'Alessandro. From his flashy ties
to his flashy quotes, he knows how to make irreverent statements
and seize the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro's criticisms of the IOC are entirely in keeping
with his cocky and calculating image. He knew they would attract
major media attention. After all, he was the only chief executive
of any of the major US companies that spend billions of dollars to
finance the Games to publicly confront the IOC and its scandals.
</P>
<P>
   But here is Ebersol's _ and NBC's _ problem:
</P>
<P>
   The IOC scandals are not hype, spin, or products of David
D'Alessandro's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Ten members of the International Olympic Committee have resigned
or been expelled for conduct related to the awarding of the 2002
Winter Games to Salt Lake City. Some members were accused of
accepting bribes in return for their vote when siting of the Games
was under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday, the Salt Lake Tribune reported that six months
after US Attorney General Janet Reno ordered an investigation of
Salt Lake City's Olympic bid, federal prosecutors are headed toward
more indictments.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the scandal is not over. Congressional investigations
have been launched and laws proposed to force more reforms than the
IOC adopted in Lausanne, Switzerland, in March. Why would anyone
want to stop them?
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be a real weakness at the heart of the Olympic
movement _ an all-too-human drive for money and glory. It is
understandable, perhaps; but if it goes unchecked, it corrupts the
Games, the athletes, and all of us.
</P>
<P>
   Network television created the Olympic spirit. It made us
believers in the grace, power, and perseverance of the athletes and
their commitment to sport. The networks count on us to tune into
the thrill of victory, the agony of defeat, and the billions of
dollars of commercial advertising that go with them.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't we, in turn, be able to count on honest competition,
on and off the Olympic playing fields? That should be more
important than protecting a television network's assets _ or any
part of a network executive's anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
