<SLUG> BC-YUPPIE-HOAX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEKLY ADMITS YUPPIE PROTEST WAS A HOAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An alternative weekly newspaper has gleefully
admitted to fabricating a news event and tricking the news media
into covering it.
</P>
<P>
   John Mecklin, editor of the SF Weekly, said he and his staff
created a fake advertisement for a pro-yuppie rally that was to
take place on Sunday afternoon, hoping that the media would take
the bait and cover the nonexistent rally. The phony ad appeared in
the SF Weekly's pages like any other ad, prompting many to believe
that the rally was legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   The city's daily newspapers _ the San Francisco Examiner and the
San Francisco Chronicle _ and several radio and television stations
did cover the rally, which was supposedly to pit affluent yuppies
against longtime residents of the Mission District who did not want
newcomers living in their neighborhood. About 200 people showed up
to protest the ``Stop the Hate'' rally and its supposed yuppie
sponsors. The police were also on hand to monitor the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   When the sponsors failed to materialize, the Examiner's Monday
editions covered the event under the headline ``No yups, just nopes
at rally in Mission: Was scheduled anti-hate gathering a complete
put-on?''
</P>
<P>
   Mecklin reveled in the prank, saying it proved that the media
were lazy and would respond to any press release or advertisement
without confirming facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made up a political movement out of thin air, called a
rally on its nonexistent behalf, called into being a large
counterdemonstration, and created a minor media uproar,'' Mecklin
said in an editorial that ran on the Weekly's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the journalism industry criticized the prank as
reckless and irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of journalism is not to lie to people,'' said
Austin Long-Scott, the acting chair of the San Francisco State
University journalism department. ``The purpose of journalism is to
get as close to the truth as possible. ... If (gentrification) is a
big issue in San Francisco, and I think it is, you don't trivialize
it by using it as a prank.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Rogers, metro editor of the San Francisco Examiner, said
newspaper saw the advertisement for the rally, tried unsuccessfully
to verify its authenticity and, in the process, reported two
stories on legitimate gentrification struggles within the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one likes to be duped _ it means you're unwittingly leading
readers down the wrong path,'' Rogers said. ``But it's far worse
when a newspaper like the SF Weekly intentionally tries to pull off
a hoax. That's called lying. If a paper admits to lying, why should
you believe anything else it does?''
</P>
<P>
   Mecklin vowed to continue creating pranks that are ``good for
the mental health of the city,'' but said his readers were smart
enough not to be confused by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These (pranks) happen for a reason. They are meant to
illuminate a facet of life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phony rally aside, reporters focused attention on the very real
tension created by gentrification in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The economic boom in the San Francisco Bay area and a shortage
of housing have caused prices for homes and apartments to soar,
pitting working-class people against the more affluent in a
competition for housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mission District is deeply divided between people
struggling to keep a roof over their heads and people desperately
looking for a place to buy a home,'' Rogers said. ``It's too bad
the Weekly trivialized the situation with a cheap publicity
stunt.''
</P>
<P>
   The SF Weekly is owned by New Times Inc., which also has
alternative newsweeklies in Broward-Palm Beach, Cleveland, Dallas,
Denver, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, Phoenix and St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SANJUAN-BOS &LR;      06-08 1641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SANJUAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEART OF PUERTO RICO'S CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ Old San Juan really is. Almost ancient in fact.
</P>
<P>
   The walled town at the heart of Puerto Rico's capital was
founded by the Spaniards in 1521, a century before the Pilgrims
landed on Plymouth Rock. This makes Old San Juan practically
medieval by New World standards. Happily, it carries the nearly
five centuries lightly and is a lively neighborhood, not a museum
village.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan San Juan is a study in contemporary urban sprawl,
like so many American cities, but the original fortified settlement
_ rimmed by 40-foot-high walls and guarded by two great forts _ is
the essence of compactness. Laid out to a precise formal plan
mandated by Spanish colonial authorities in Madrid, Old San Juan
crams a lot of history and considerable charm into a mere seven
square blocks.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 400 restored buildings, including churches,
public buildings, and private mansions: the greatest such
concentration in the Caribbean. There are also monuments, city
gates, sculptured fountains, plazas (frequently used for al fresco
concerts and dances), and hidden gardens. Some of the best
restaurants in the city _ or in all of Puerto Rico, for that matter
_ can be found in the old town, along with some of the liveliest
bars and lounges and most fashionable shops and boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   You can see most of Old San Juan's major sights in a couple of
hours. But it lavishly rewards leisurely strolling and casual
poking around. If a cobblestone street, flower-filled park or shady
courtyard looks interesting, chances are it is.
</P>
<P>
   There are several approaches to Old San Juan, but unquestionably
the most scenic and atmospheric is along Paseo La Princesa. A
harborside promenade, the paseo _ scene of an open-air arts and
crafts market on weekends _ leads from the dock area, where cruise
ships tie up, to the formidable 17th-century San Juan gate. For
centuries this gate was the main entrance to the old town, and it
still retains the original massive iron-studded defensive doors,
now never closed.
</P>
<P>
   Passing through the San Juan gate, the scenic promenade
continues along the walls past La Fortaleza, built in the 16th
century for Spanish officials and still the residence of Puerto
Rico's governor. It continues through Plazuela de la Rogativa, a
small square with an unusual monument depicting a religious
procession that unexpectedly delivered the city from a siege in the
18th century. Thinking the procession along the city walls _
actually, a group of torch-carrying women led by an elderly bishop
_ must be a relief force, the British Navy hastily withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   The harborside fortifications end at San Felipe del Morro, the
great stone fort guarding the entrance to the port. A similar
bastion, San Cristobal, defends the land side. Both have
watchtowers, deep dungeons, and powder magazines as well as
historical exhibits. El Morro, however, definitely offers the best
view of the two, a panorama that takes in the harbor and all of Old
San Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Also a striking example of military architecture is Cuartel
Ballaja, the former Spanish military headquarters. Built around a
central barracks square, the enormous building, largest erected in
the Americas by Spanish army engineers, originally housed soldiers
and their families.  &UR; Today &LR; , it contains the Museum of the
Americas, which displays a superb collection of arts and crafts
from all over the Western Hemisphere. Particulary interesting are
the many colorful ``santos,'' religious figures that are a
distinctively Puerto Rican handicraft.
</P>
<P>
   Another museum, housed in a small 18th-century house on Calle
San Sebastian, is a memorial to the late, great cellist Pablo
Casals. An exile from Franco's Spain, Casals long made his home in
Puerto Rico and founded a prestigious annual music festival. The
great man's beloved cello is here, along with photographs,
manuscripts, and other memorabilia. You can also watch (and hear)
videotapes of some of his finest performances.
</P>
<P>
   Adjacent to the Casals Museum is Casa de Los Contrafuertes
(``House of the Buttresses''), dating from the early 1500s and the
oldest residential building in Old San Juan. It contains both a
small pharmacy museum and a graphics arts museum.
</P>
<P>
   As was usually the case in Spanish colonial towns, an imposing
cathedral is one of the focal points of Old San Juan. A church has
stood on the same spot on Calle del Christo since 1529. The present
church incorporates the remains of earlier ones, destroyed by fires
and hurricanes and plundered by invaders, and is mostly 19th
century. Normally quiet and dignified, the cathedral really jumps
on Sundays at 11 a.m. That's the ``Salsa Mass,'' when the whole
congregation sings, shouts, swings, and sways to a pulsing Latino
beat.
</P>
<P>
   The body of Puerto Rico's first governor Ponce de Leon, killed
by an Indian arrow while looking for the Fountain of Youth in
Florida, now rests in an ornate marble tomb in the transept of the
cathedral. There is a statue of him, made from melted-down cannon
captured from the British, nearby in plaza San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Space is tight within the confining walls of old San Juan but
the town plan designated a number of plazas and squares for public
assembly, from military tattoos to holy day fiestas. These days,
these precious open spaces are often the scene of jazz concerts,
teen dances, and chamber music performances. Largest and most
impressive of Old San Juan's plazas are Plaza de Armas, the
original town square, which has a lovely 19th-century fountain
representing the four seasons; Plaza Colon, dominated by a pillar
topped with a statue of Christopher Columbus (Cristobal Colon in
Spanish); and, Quincentennial Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Located on the highest point of the old town, Quincentennial
Plaza commemorates the discovery of the New World in 1492 and the
500-year-old history of Puerto Rico. The plaza's symbolic
centerpiece is a 40-foot-high totemic sculpture in black granite
and ceramic by local artist Jaime Suarez that symbolizes the
earthen and clay roots of American history. Also decorating the
plaza are fountains, other columns, and sculpted steps.
</P>
<P>
   There are two notable places to stay in the heart of Old San
Juan, both occupying characterful restored buildings.
</P>
<P>
   A deluxe 61-room hotel, El Convento, which stands across from
the cathedral, was built in the mid 17th century as a Carmelite
convent. Eventually abandoned by the nuns, it deteriorated into a
shabby rooming house and was almost demolished. Its restoration in
the 1960s was one of the turning points in the revitalization (and
gentrification) of Old San Juan, which became a colorful near-slum
when the modern city expanded outside the old walls.
</P>
<P>
   El Convento had another multimillion dollar makeover a few years
ago _ rooms now are decorated with hand-made tiles and period
furnishings imported from Spain _ and is one of the island's top
hotels. The hotel's several lounges and restaurants are popular
hangouts for the young professionals who are rapidly transforming
Old San Juan into one of the city's most fashionable residential
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallery Inn on Calle Norzagaray is a cheery survivor from
the days when Old San Juan had more in common with Greenwich
Village than Greenwich, Conn. Jan D'Esopa, a Connecticut born
sculptress and painter, and her husband, Manuco Gandia, opened the
inn _ the only B &AMP; B in the old town _ in the early 1960s. It has
expanded over the years and now occupies four adjacent buildings,
all dating to early colonial days and connected by flowery and
vine-shaded courtyards filled with D'Esopa's idiosyncratic
sculptures and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dining room or swimming pool but the Gallery Inn has
a roof deck with a sweeping view. Other amenities include an art
gallery, a foundry for casting sculptures, and a framing shop.
Guests have the run of the place, as do the three resident parrots.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 rooms range from grandly old fashioned to funky and
distinctly odd. For instance, in one small and windowless guest
room, a former wine cellar, D'Esopa has tried to compensate for the
lack of apertures by covering an entire wall with a mural depicting
the harbor on a sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   Old San Juan has become a real restaurant quarter in recent
years and has something to offer for most taste buds and
pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the restaurants providing a distinctively Puerto Rican
dining experience is the Parrot Club on Calle Fortaleza, which
calls its cuisine ``Nuevo Latino,'' exemplified by such dishes as
pan-seared tuna in rum sauce. Amadeus on Calle Sebastian, open only
for lunch, occcupies an 18th-century former mansion and is known
for giving an international twist to local ingredients, as with
arrowroot fritters and dumplings in guava sauce.
</P>
<P>
   El Patio de Sam on Calle San Sebastian is the restaurant
equivalent of the Gallery Inn, a longtime hangout for expatriates,
Bohemians, and neighborhood folks of all sorts. Burgers are the
specialty, but they're served with typically Caribbean side dishes
such as fried plaintains. The dining room has so many plants it
resembles a rain forest, and there is usually a guitarist playing
evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Uniquely Caribbean is the Butterfly People Cafe on Calle
Fortaleza, which specializes in light fare, particularly dishes
involving tropical fruits. The cafe is connected to the gallery of
the same name, which boasts the world's largest collection of
framed butterflies. Like the gallery, the walls of the cafe are
also covered with brilliantly colored butterflies. And, if you just
want a good cafe con leche and maybe a piece of homemade pastry,
try La Bombonera on Calle San Francisco, a local institution since
1902.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
