<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-VELVET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEXY, SINEWY SOJOURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TIPPING THE VELVET 
By Sarah Waters 
Riverhead, 472 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With her glorious first novel, Sarah Waters achieves the kind of
exceptional debut most novice writers can barely imagine, let alone
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tipping the Velvet'' is a sexy, sinewy sojourn of a young
woman in turn-of-the-century England. This is a shade of those
well-documented times rarely seen, far from those gentle
coming-of-age stories or drawing-room comedies, replete with
stifled, veiled emotions. Waters shakes the dust off Victorian
England, reveling in its bawdiness, and revealing its sassy,
sensuous soul.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the book is Nancy Astley, who narrates the
story. Unfolding as a reminiscence, her tale begins in 1888 when
she worked in her family's oyster parlor. By her own description,
she was ``a slender, white-faced, unremarkable-looking girl, with
the sleeves of her dress rolled up to her elbows, and a lock of
lank and colourless hair forever falling into her eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother would often say Nancy was found as a baby in an
oyster shell, saved from a hungry customer. It was a family joke,
but there was a hint of truth there. All of Nancy's 18 years had
been spent among oysters, working 12-hour days delicately removing
natives from their shells. It was not a life that dissatisfied her.
Her sister Alice was her best friend, and ``for eight-een years,''
Nancy recalls, ``I . . . never looked far beyond my father's
kitchen for occupation, or for love.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, that is, until she meets Miss Kitty Butler, star at
the Canterbury Palace of Varieties.
</P>
<P>
   The Palace, as locals called it, was a 15-minute train ride and
a world away from Nancy's coastal Whitstable home. It was a shabby
music hall, but in Nancy's eyes it was a slice of paradise with its
jaunty rhythms, slyly suggestive songs, and curvaceous painted
ladies. Amid the smoke and scent of wood and greasepaint, Nancy
first spied Miss Kitty, who owned a stage the minute she sauntered
across it.
</P>
<P>
   Waters's writing is plush and inviting _ delicious, even _ when
Nancy first sees Kitty. Clad in a man's suit, Kitty performs as a
West End swell, boyishly beautiful in her 2-inch stand-up collar,
bow tie, and rose in her lapel. But it is Kitty's hair, ``the kind
of brown you might hear sung about,'' which does something
frightening and fabulous to Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had ever seen women with hair as short as hers, it was
because they had spent time in hospital or prison; or because they
were mad. They could never look like Kitty. . . . It curled at her
temple, slightly, and over her ears; when she turned her head a
little to put her hat back on, I saw a strip of pale flesh at the
nape of her neck where the collar ended and the hairline began that
_ for all the fire of that hot, hot hall _ made me shiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy is instantly smitten with Kitty, and is soon making
regular trips to see her perform. Before long she becomes Kitty's
dresser and confidante, and soon Kitty's lover. Eventually, Nancy
succumbs to the lure of the lights and applause, and finds herself
singing and performing _ also in men's clothing _ as Nan King. This
is merely the beginning of Nan's colorful journey.
</P>
<P>
   At 472 pages, could the novel be shorter? Perhaps, but what
would be eliminated? Certainly, not Nan's experiences as a ``rent
boy'' or her ill-advised affair with Diana Lethaby, a wealthy widow
who ``keeps'' Nan for her own sexual high jinks. Given its heft,
the book still manages to be a fairly breezy read.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Tipping the Velvet'' features several love affairs
between women, some will characterize this as a lesbian novel. To
be sure, in this book, the love that dare not speak its name almost
never shuts up. The novel has also drawn some comparisons to
Jeanette Winterson's ``Oranges Are Not the Only Fruit,'' another
novel with an English girl on the cusp of womanhood leaving her
dour surroundings to discover her true sexual self.
</P>
<P>
   But with respect to Winterson's classic, ``Tipping the Velvet''
is a more expansive, adventuresome book. And while describing it as
a lesbian novel may be somewhat accurate, the term is too limited
in portraying the many charms of Waters's layered work. There are
several stories here _ lesbian love, the bumpkin swept into the
hustle-bustle of the big city, a young woman discovering herself as
life takes awkward, unexpected turns _ and Waters juggles each with
panache. Capturing the era in all its naughty, garish glory, Waters
celebrates everything that made the Nineties _ the 1890s _ so
unabashedly gay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
