<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A STROLL IN THE CITY OF TRAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston is a city of trails. There are, of course, the Freedom
Trail and the Black Heritage Trail. But there are others as well,
some for walking and others for driving. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --The GeoTrail. This takes visitors to Boston construction,
including America's biggest road project, the multibillion-dollar
Big Dig, scheduled to be finished in early 2005. Or so they say.
</P>
<P>
   --The Emerald Necklace Trail. Bearing the magic touch of
landscape architect Frederick Law Olmsted, this trail connects the
first park system in America and features gardens, greenhouses, a
zoo, walkways, a bike trail, and a rose garden.
</P>
<P>
   --The Women's Heritage Trail. Said to be the only one of its
kind, this one celebrates four centuries of achievements by women
and includes sites associated with publishers, suffragettes, and
poets.
</P>
<P>
   --The Boston Literary Trail. This lifts some of America's most
beloved authors, including Louisa May Alcott, Henry David Thoreau,
and Edgar Allan Poe, out of the pages of their books and gives
insight into their lives.
</P>
<P>
   These trails begin at, or close to, the revamped Boston Common
Visitor Center, which is open daily and has brochures and trail
maps, as well as guidebooks for purchase. For more information,
call 888-SEE-BOSTON or visit www.bostonusa.com.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: What state capital has three sets of double
letters? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``People in America are always telling me, `I love
your accent.' Ah, but when I go to Boston, I get to tell them, `I
love your accent.' '' _ a visitor from Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Grave moments: ``Tales, Tombs &AMP; Gravestones'' is a new nighttime
trolley excursion that takes guests on a two-hour ``frightseeing''
tour of Boston's scary sights. Conductors and actors sprinkle their
stories with humor and offer rare information, like the weight of a
ghostly spirit and how many whacks Lizzie Borden allegedly gave her
parents with an ax. The jaunt is presented by Historic Tours of
America, via Minuteman Tours, Thursdays, Fridays, and Saturdays at
8 p.m. beginning June 24. Price is $30 for adults and $18 for
children, and tours are by reservation only. Call 617-269-3626.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu: The Parish Cafe and Bar on Boylston Street in
Boston is unique in that its menu pays tribute to some of the
area's most prominent chefs and restaurants. Example: the Lydia, a
lobster salad dish created by Lydia Shire, chef/owner of Biba and
Pignoli in Boston; the Spicy Salamander, an eggplant concoction
created by Stan Frankenthaler, chef/owner of Salamander in
Cambridge; and the Pudding Portobello sandwich, created by Debra
Hughes, chef/owner of Upstairs at the Pudding in Cambridge. And the
Guinness is well-poured!
</P>
<P>
   Come to the cabaret: On the site of Benjamin Franklin's
birthplace, Dr. Franklin, along with Colonial Friends and
Musicians, create the essence of a colonial cabaret ``to lift the
spirits of weary citizens with musicks and merrymaking.'' Franklin
is portrayed lovingly and accurately by two-time Emmy-winner Bill
Meikle, and audience participation is encouraged. From July 2
through Sept. 4, the cabaret takes places Fridays and Saturdays at
8 p.m. in the Great Room of the International Institute of Boston,
1 Milk St. Tickets are $20. Call 781-648-0628 for reservations, and
ask also about colonial Boston walks and lunch with Dr. Franklin or
Abigail Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Planes, trains, etc.: The Boston University Bridge is said to be
the only place in the world where a boat can sail under a train
driving under a car driving under an airplane. (With thanks to
uselessfacts.net via faithful contributor Mike Schuster of
Foxborough, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   Ye olde football: The Oneida Football Club, the first such
organized club in the country, practiced on Boston Common between
1862 and 1865. Many call the games there the beginnings of modern
American football.
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? Tallahassee, Fla. (You thought it was
Bossttonn?) We thank Sal Chancholo of Medford, Mass., for the
question.
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
