<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 IT ALL CAUGHT UP TO CHARISMATIC
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Like a true warrior, Charismatic went out on his shield. In a
game designed for flying aces, he was a foot soldier, and he
accomplished all he could.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of Charismatic becoming the first claimer to win the
Triple Crown ended approaching the eighth-pole of the Belmont Park
stretch Saturday, when Charismatic ran out of gas. The fact that he
fought so hard to resist defeat, fracturing his left leg in the
process, is a tribute to the ``fat'' horse whose heart is as big as
his body.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen Selway, who performed surgery on Charismatic's leg
Sunday, believed the cannon bone fracture happened in the final
furlong, which is where Charismatic was passed, and the sesamoids
fractured as he tried to go on.
</P>
<P>
   Although the term is popular in racing, there is no such thing
as an ``iron horse.'' Thoroughbreds are made of flesh, and blood,
and bones that can break. The Charismatic camp can spin the story
any way they want, but there is no question he was overraced. He
wasn't overraced just recently, he was overraced throughout his
career. Beginning with the Santa Anita Derby April 3, he ran in
five major stakes races in nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Charismatic also ran seven times as a 2-year-old, and the
Belmont was his 17th career start. He lost five straight maiden
special weight races at the beginning of his career, and did not
win until he was put in a $62,500 maiden claimer. He then lost
three more starts until he was placed first via disqualification in
a $62,500 claimer for 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   His connections ran him a lot in an attempt to win purse money
to cut their losses, because he cost $200,000 and they thought he
was a bust. A stakes horse can win $200,000 in one Grade III race.
No one can ever know whether running 17 times from June 20, 1998,
to June 5, 1999, contributed to the breaking of his leg. He might
have taken just one bad step, but the record remains the record.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic retires with a career record of 17-5-2-3. Compare
that with the career record of Affirmed, who won the Triple Crown
in 1978, the last to do so. Affirmed ran 29 times and won 22. He
was second five times, third once, and off the board once. When he
lost, he lost to opponents such as Alydar, Seattle Slew, and
Exceller. Affirmed, both a 2-year-old champion and a handicap
champion, was born to be a great racehorse. Charismatic, whose
owner didn't want him as recently as February, was a classic
overachiever. The horses weren't just on different planes, they
were practically on different planets.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic was not meant to be a Top Gun. He was a ground
trooper who reached for the sky. And that's not a bad way to be
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Overlooked stars
</P>
<P>
   The unfortunate injury to Charismatic stole much of the thunder
from the Belmont victory of 29-1 shot Lemon Drop Kid. Vision and
Verse, who was beaten by just a head at 54-1, also received scant
attention. These are two fresh horses in top hands, and it is
likely they will be heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid, a son of Kingmambo, who is by the late Mr.
Prospector, was considered a top 2-year-old when he won the Belmont
Futurity last September. He ran second in the Champagne, to none
other then Rick Pitino's The Groom Is Red, but disappointed in the
Breeders' Cup, finishing fifth. He bounced back by winning his
sophomore debut in a Gulfstream allowance, but he slipped from view
when he ran poorly in the Blue Grass, in which he was only 4-1, and
the Kentucky Derby. He then improved by running third in the Peter
Pan at Belmont, his Belmont Stakes prep.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that Lemon Drop Kid is a horse for a
course, a lover of Belmont Park, with a 5-2-2-1 record over
America's only 12-furlong oval. But, to his credit, veteran
conditioner Scotty Schulhofer said from the outset that Lemon Drop
Kid was the best horse he had ever trained, and Schulhofer has
trained some good ones, including Cryptoclearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needed a little time to grow up, he's a May 28 foal,''
said Schulhofer. ``He peaked on the right day. We're going to give
him a nice, long rest and probably see about the Jim Dandy (Aug. 8
at Saratoga) and the Travers (Aug. 28), for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Vision and Verse, a son of Storm Cat, is a late developer who
raced only once as a 2-year-old. He came to prominence by wining
the Illinois Derby at Hawthorne May 8 and is trained by Bill Mott,
one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing super coming into the race, and it unfolded
nicely for him,'' said Mott, who is pointing Vision and Verse to
the Jim Dandy and Travers, as well. ``He was dead game in the
stretch, and I thought we were going to get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
