<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURAL BORN SPELLERS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For whiz kid Nupur Lala, spelling homework paid off last
Thursday _ to the tune of $10,000 _ when the 14-year-old from Tampa
won the annual Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee. Her winning
word was logorrhea _ from the Greek for word and flow, though it's
a 20th-century formation, probably modeled on diarrhea, says the
Oxford English Dictionary. As competition words go, it's not
especially challenging; other kids got stung by killer bee words
like pidan, terete, gnathic, and aretalogy. But Nupur and her 248
competitors put on an impressive show, all in all.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, though, think spelling bees are about as
educational as frog races (and a lot more painful for the
contestants; in the Dublin, Ohio, frog jump _ so say the official
rules _ ``tired frogs may be exchanged for rested frogs at no
charge.'' No such luck for the tired young spellers.) The merit of
bees has been debated for years, along predictable lines: Do they
demand meaningless rote learning or provide valuable discipline for
developing minds?
</P>
<P>
   For the semi-pro Scripps Howard bee, in its 72nd year, the
question is especially pointed. As a fellow editor noted, each
year's news story explains that ``many of the words come from the
Paideia,'' a handbook of difficult words passed out to contestants
months in advance. Repeat contenders can study earlier versions of
Paideia, too, since unused words from the past may pop up in the
``surprise'' round. So some kids are putting in serious study time
_ Nupur claimed two hours a day, another contestant five hours _ on
spelling practice.
</P>
<P>
   The words they learn range from the ordinary and useful _
potable, streptomycin, brouhaha _ to those so recondite that even
future William F. Buckley fans may never see them again:
ochlophobia, inconcinnity, traineau. And of course, a word not used
is soon forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   But the manual alone will not a winner make; it's just a
compilation of words, sorted into categories and ranked from easier
to harder. To compete, kids need to know what the words mean and
how they're pronounced, which is where the hours of research and
memorization and parental drill come in.
</P>
<P>
   The question, for skeptics, is whether this is a profitable use
of young scholars' study time. You don't have to be a no-drills
dogmatist to harbor doubts: If they're going to memorize, why not
make it something memorable? When my mother was in school, each
class memorized a poem, together, every six weeks of the school
year. And at her 50th high school reunion, the crowd could still
recite those poems in unison: ``By the rude bridge that arched the
flood'' . . . ``Sail on! sail on! sail on! and on!'' ... ``In
Flanders fields the poppies grow....''
</P>
<P>
   Today's selections would be different, of course, but if you
were memorizing for two hours a day, wouldn't you rather end up
with a head full of Yeats and Dickinson _ or even Ogden Nash and
Dorothy Parker _ than the definitions of oast and affenpinscher?
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, Scripps Howard is trying to make the bee an
educational experience. Several groups of words in Paideia are
drawn from books students enjoy _ ``Emma,'' ``A Wrinkle in Time,''
``O Pioneers!'' On the bee's Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://spellingbee.com, a weekly study guide delves into word
derivations, Latin prefixes, and other aids to understanding how
words work. And for pupils whose parents are all drilled out,
there's an audio version of the 1999 book, with an announcer giving
words and definitions just as in a real bee. (Try it out. If you
start to feel smug, just zoom your RealPlayer toward the end of the
list.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'm grateful that I wasn't drafted for spelling bee duty
till adulthood. Grown-up bees have several advantages: They're
charity events, so you're doing good just by showing up; you get to
work in teams, allowing you to share the blame (or, rarely,
credit); and you're seasoned enough to see how much is just dumb
luck. One year you bomb out on accipiter and moan when the next
team gets byssinosis (``We could have spelled that!''); next year
you get the softball and your opponents draw xiphoid. And whatever
the outcome, grown-up spellers don't cry, throw up backstage, or
ask their parents to file a protest.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the reason could be that they're old enough to go out
for a consoling post-bee drink. Maybe spelling contests, like
Scotch, should be reserved for the over-21 set.
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
