<HEADLINE>
A PLOT THAT DOESN'T TRAVEL WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
HAVANA BAY 
By Martin Cruz Smith 
Random House, 329 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bar is set very high for a new adventure thriller from
Martin Cruz Smith, the author of ``Gorky Park.'' Unfortunately,
``Havana Bay'' falls short of his personal best.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has a great gift for reportage. Better than most
mass-market authors, he travels, learns, absorbs, and then
re-creates foreign milieus. After a brief, two-week stay in
pre-glasnost Moscow, he made the city come alive for Western
readers in his breakthrough thriller, 1981's ``Gorky Park.'' Smith
ably rendered post-Cold War Germany in ``Red Square,'' and he
trolled the little-known world of Russia's blue-ocean fishing fleet
in ``Polar Star.''
</P>
<P>
   His most recent novel, ``Rose,'' was his greatest triumph _ and
his most grating commercial failure. ``Rose'' re-created the world
of Lancashire deep-pit coal mining during England's Industrial
Revolution, and mined intriguing seams of clerical intrigue and
androgyny. But ``Rose'' failed to find its audience _ which, I
think, explains ``Havana Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   In this novel, Smith dances with the one what brung him to
bestseller status: the brooding, phlegmatic Moscow police
investigator Arkady Renko. Renko, memorably played by the brooding,
phlegmatic William Hurt in the Hollywood version of ``Gorky Park,''
was pretty downbeat 18 years ago. Adrift in the chaos of modern
Russia, he's more downbeat than ever. The love of his life has
perished accidentally in a laxly run Moscow hospital. A former
colleague has encountered a spot of trouble in Havana. Author Smith
correctly concludes that Renko is long overdue for some fun in the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   So we depart for Havana. Once again, Smith renders a foreign
landscape almost perfectly. ``Havana Bay'' is by far the most
interesting piece of journalism to emerge from the newly accessible
Cuba of recent years. Castro's grand experiment is nearing its end.
Cuban society is torn between two pasts: the faded glory of the
Revolution, and the idealized memory of capitalist Havana, where
the likes of Ernest Hemingway and Mafia boss Meyer Lansky worked
the gaming tables.
</P>
<P>
   But today, competing mafias _ Russian, American, Caribbean _ are
circling the island like sharks. The once-heroic Soviet comrades,
now too poor to buy Cuban sugar at inflated prices and pump the
island full of cut-rate East-bloc oil, are reviled. The city
suffers frequent power outages. The stores are nearly empty.
Everybody's a pimp, figuratively or literally. In other words, this
provides a perfect setting for a Martin Cruz Smith-Arkady Renko
outing.
</P>
<P>
   The plot starts out promisingly enough. A Russian ``floater''
(waterlogged corpse) surfaces in Havana Bay. Inept Cuban police
investigators, half-trained by the Russians, half-trained by the
FBI, prove that two halves don't make a whole. Corrupt cops;
vestigial Russian diplomats on the take; a chain-smoking,
round-heeled ballerina hoping to emigrate _ among these colorful
types Smith even weaves in a character named George Washington
Walls, identical in almost every way to the real-life Charles Hill,
a black-separatist militant who hijacked a plane in 1971 and still
lives in Havana. But a funny thing happens as we stroll along the
ratty sidewalks of the Malecon oceanfront: We get lost.
</P>
<P>
   The French have a lovely expression for getting bogged down _
``pedaling in sauerkraut'' _ which is how I felt about a third of
the way into the book. Characters appeared and disappeared for no
apparent reason. I felt buried under an avalanche of colorful but
confusing apartment hideaways, place names, and side trips to
nowhere. (The novel does include a map, which helps enormously.)
Left to my own devices, I would not have finished the book.
</P>
<P>
   What's left to say? Havana good. Renko pretty good. Renko-Cubana
romance pretty predictable. Plot not so good. Renko ends up back in
Moscow, available for reassignment. End of one story; beginning of
another?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
