<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS APOLOGIZE FOR REMARK ABOUT COLUMBINE SHOOTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``There's Something About Mary'' filmmakers Bobby
and Peter Farrelly drew confused silence from the star-studded
crowd at the 1999 MTV Movie Awards when they made a Columbine High
School massacre remark.
</P>
<P>
   At the awards show taping Saturday at Santa Monica Airport's
Barker Hanger, the brothers said they hoped the next time some kid
wipes out his class he'll think of a movie by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' won four awards, including best
movie, best actress, best villain and best fight.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the Farrellys apologized, saying they detest violence
and were only trying to state their opinion that ``Hollywood is
getting too much blame for all of our society's senseless violence,
particularly in our nation's schools.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV said it would delete the Columbine remark from the awards
broadcast Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
