<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CITIES WITH MANY TREATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two historic cities, close enough to combine on a visit South,
and offering new reasons to visit, are Washington and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is always a good choice for families. There's
something for every age, and, best of all, most attractions are
free.
</P>
<P>
   The Smithsonian's National Museum of Natural History has opened
a new Discovery Center that features a state-of-the-art IMAX
theater, currently showing ``Africa's Elephant Kingdom.'' The
center also includes a new Atrium Cafe with seating for 600, and
offers added museum shops, which have been lauded as the best shops
of their kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Some Smithsonian museums will be staying open in the evening,
but only to 7:30 p.m. at the latest.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed the Mary Cassatt exhibition in Boston, it is now
on view at the National Gallery of Art through Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   And, at the Washington Monument an interactive center focusing
on Washington _ the man, the city, and the monument _ is open.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore is celebrating its harbor area with the opening of the
National Historic Seaport, which capitalizes on the harbor's
longstanding maritime heritage. Visitors can purchase a Seaport
Passcard to gain access to 15 sites. Attractions can be reached on
foot or by water taxi. Among Baltimore's attractions are Fort
McHenry, the site that inspired ``The Star Spangled Banner,'' the
USS Constellation (the 1854 warship just underwent a 2 1/2-year
renovation and opens on July 2), the Baltimore Museum of Industry,
the US submarine Torsk (it patrolled the Pacific in World War II
and holds the record for the most dives of any sub). And head for
the 27th floor of the world's tallest pentagonal building,
Baltimore's World Trade Center, for great views of the city and
harbor. For more information on the seaport, call 877-NH-CPORT.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ice cream fest
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial start to the ice cream eating season begins June
8 through June 10 when the annual BankBoston Scooper Bowl sets up
shop on City Hall Plaza in Boston. Nine of New England's favorite
ice cream companies are donating 12 tons of ice cream and frozen
desserts for the three-day festival, 11:30 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily.
The all-you-can-eat festival benefits the Jimmy Fund, which raises
funds for cancer treatments and patients at the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute. Entrance to the festival is just $5 for adults, $2 for
children 6-12, free for those under 6. The plaza is just steps from
the Government Center T stop. For more information, call
800-52-JIMMY.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heading for Toronto?
</P>
<P>
   The University of Toronto at Scarborough is offering its
townhouses to visitors at $58 or less a night. Each townhouse
sleeps four to six, and has its own bathroom, bedrooms, living
room, and kitchen. For information, call 416-287-7356, fax
416-287-7323; or e-mail bardgett(at)scar.utoronto.ca.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Paddle Providence
</P>
<P>
   An interesting way to learn about Providence is to join a
kayaking tour hosted by a historian from the Rhode Island
Historical Society. The tours will be held June 24, July 22, Aug.
26, and Sept. 23 from 5 to 7:30 p.m. Cost is $35. On Fridays
through the summer there will be happy hour paddles along the
Woonasquatucket River to Water Place Park. The cost is $24. Fees
include the boat rental and all equipment. For reservations, call
401-453-1633.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sail into Summer
</P>
<P>
   The fifth annual Sail into Summer cruise sponsored by the North
of Boston Convention and Visitors Bureau will be held June 17. The
cruise, which benefits the bureau, will leave from Gloucester. The
$35 cruise includes food from area restaurants, and entertainment.
For information, call 978-977-7760.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Newport walks
</P>
<P>
   The Newport Historical Society is offering walking tours of
three distinct areas of Newport: the Historic Hill, the Point, and
the Cliff Walk. Tours are $7 and tickets may be purchased at the
Museum of Newport History or the Gateway Visitor's Center. For
information, call 401-846-0813,
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Boston happenings
</P>
<P>
   The New England Aquarium will celebrate its 30th birthday with a
free outdoor festival on June 20 from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Enjoy cake,
the harbor seals, and more. Admission to the aquarium is
additional, but because it will be Father's Day, dads, accompanied
by children, will receive free admission.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Science offers ``Masters of the Ocean Realm:
Whales, Dolphins, and Porpoises'' beginning June 12. The exhibit
explores the biology, physiology, and anatomy of these cetaceans,
and even lets you listen to them. Also on the big screen at the
Mugar Omni Theater, ``Everest'' is back. Opening June 24 is the
IMAX film ``Thrill Ride _ the Science of Fun''. Both films will be
shown daily.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Museum Mile
</P>
<P>
   If you're in New York Tuesday, join in the 21st annual Museum
Mile Festival that offers free admission to museums from 82nd
Street to 104th Street. Entertainers will also be performing, and
there will be music at most locations. For more information, call
212-606-2296.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
City Pass
</P>
<P>
   Helping to cut costs to see attractions in Boston, Philadelphia,
New York City, Seattle, and San Francisco is the CityPass. In
Boston, CityPass offers entrance to the John F. Kennedy Library,
New England Aquarium, John Hancock Observatory, Isabella Stewart
Gardner Museum, Museum of Fine Arts, and the Museum of Science at
half price. The pass is $27.50 for adults, $20.50 for seniors, and
$14 for those 12-17. The pass can be picked up at any of the
attractions mentioned. Each pass is good for nine days from its
first use. Another way to save in Boston is to combine the pass
with a Boston T Visitor Passport, which offers unlimited use of all
bus and subway lines. For more information on CityPass in other
cities, call 707-256-0490 or visit www.citypass.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
