<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRY NOT TO CATCH THE INFLATION BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen closely this week and you'll probably hear a lot of
inflation talk. Don't get too caught up in it.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation bug has been buzzing ever since the Federal
Reserve shifted its bias toward raising interest rates last month.
Three government reports will be scrutinized for more clues this
week, the most important being Friday's release of monthly data on
wholesale inflation.
</P>
<P>
   That will set the stage for next week's big event: Fed chairman
Alan Greenspan's testimony before the Joint Economic Committee of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its real-life affects, on everything from the value
of a paycheck to the price of eggs, inflation also whips financial
markets. The bond market is nipping at 6 percent for the first time
in more than a year and analysts wonder if stocks prices,
particularly those of small companies, can hold up if interest
rates continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   But inflation has been so subdued for so long, amid the kind of
economic expansion that historically sparked higher prices, that
markets seem to have a heightened sensitivity to the trend they
have long expected to surface. Inflation may indeed turn out to be
rising, but few analysts or economists believe a serious problem is
before us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who argues that we're looking at a horrible inflation
picture should have their head examined,'' said Nancy Kimelman,
chief economist at Technical Data in Boston. ``It's a little bit of
an uptick from an unsustainably low level.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Fleet Financial Group chief economist Nicholas Perna: ``If
inflation gets bad, it will be 3 percent instead of 2.5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean stock and bond markets will pay little
attention to inflation data or Greenspan's comments. The odds on a
short-term market jolt one way or the other are better than even.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're more sensitive to inflation fears than we should
be,'' said Barry Evans, fixed income strategist at John Hancock
Funds in Boston. ``The market will probably react a little more
than it should to a slightly higher inflationary bias. I personally
feel it's done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts usually recited to explain sustained low inflation,
from a globalized workforce, vast gains in productivity and the
abundance of capacity they both created, have not changed.
</P>
<P>
   But for investors who need something to worry about, consider a
kind of back-door inflation scenerio that could pose a more
realistic threat in the future. The culprit: America's gaping trade
deficit and its eventual impact on the value of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The US trade deficit in goods and services reached a record
$19.7 billion in March, running at about two to three times the
typical monthly rate recorded over five years before 1998. Measured
as a percentage of gross domestic product, the deficit is near
record territory, but not quite there yet.
</P>
<P>
   That means foreigners are collecting more and more dollars over
time. We might have paid for Saudi oil or German cars or French
wine, but every trade deficit dollar is like money borrowered from
a foreign lender.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually foreigners will have too many dollars for their own
liking, sooner rather than later at the current pace of the trade
deficit. If they sell dollars on a large scale, the value of a buck
will head lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have now become not only the largest debtor, but the
largest by any stretch of the imagination,'' said Perna. ``At some
point, the risk is that investors could get concerned because they
are increasingly less diversified.''
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston chief economist Wayne Ayers doesn't think that will
happen soon, but still expects it. ``As the rest of the world
starts to recover, investors logically are going to want to not
abandon the dollar, but diversify,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The declining value of dollars creates inflation and boosts
interest rates as a lock-step reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Its effect on rates was shown in the middle 1980s, when a
declining dollar helped boost long-term interest rates from about
7.5 percent to nearly 10 percent. That period followed a steep
decline in long-term interest rates from a peak of nearly 14
percent two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As investors diversify out of dollars, as Perna and Ayers
suggest, money will flow anywhere in search of the best value.
Evans thinks it's an easy call to predict where that will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you would see is dollars chasing the competitive
advantage created in these Asian and Latin nations,'' he said. ``Go
to where the pain was, because that will be the source of
competitive advantage in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not going to happen next week, or anytime very soon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
