<HEADLINE>
DREAM FOR A DOLLAR? LOTTERY PLAYERS GIVE IT A SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Forget it. Stop dreaming. Save your buck. You're
not going win that $65 million SuperLotto jackpot on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because Jeff Davis will. Why? Because that's the way life is. Of
course, this being California's biggest SuperLotto jackpot in about
a year _ it hit $70 million in July, and $104 million in April 1998
_ people have been lining up at Lotto machines, forking over $1 per
dream, no matter how ridiculous the odds or how lousy their luck
has always been.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has won the last six drawings. Davis, 28, is confident he
will change that.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had he never succumbed to Lotto Fever, but he works at
Healthy Spirits, a gourmet market that sells lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   This irony was too much Monday night for one customer, Anthony
Palombit, a personnel consultant who for the past 20 years has been
playing the same ``lucky'' numbers, game after game.
</P>
<P>
   His picks _ based on his family's birthdays _ have reaped just a
few $5 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Palombit, 41, heard Davis go on and on about how he'd give the
money away to friends and AIDS charities because money can't buy
happiness. He then took out his wallet, slapped a dollar on the
counter, and said he wanted to cash in on Davis' luck.
</P>
<P>
   Davis picked out the numbers. Four of the winning numbers will
be based on Davis' family birthdays. The fifth is 9, his lucky
astrological number. The sixth number is 35, what he considers the
ideal age. When Davis wins, the men pledged to split the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, not everyone would agree that Davis is the sure
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' boss, Rami Barqawi, is one skeptic. He plans to buy his
own Lotto ticket anyway _ though maybe, just maybe, he'll let Davis
push the buttons for the Quick Pick, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   And if Barqawi wins? He's old enough to know that money can buy
some happiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be in Costa Rica, sitting on some beach butt-naked,
smoking fat ones, listening to Bob Marley,'' Barqawi, 32, said with
that wistful, faraway look of Lotto players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
