<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FULL MOON &QL; 
 &UR; Michael Light (Knopf, $50)
</P>
<P>
   We doubt there is a more seductive image anywhere than that
taken of the Earth by astronaut Michael Collins on July 24, 1969, a
few hours before the crew of Apollo 11 splashed down after making
the first landing on the moon. Only a fraction of the planet is
visible against the unforgiving blackness of space _ a teasing,
blue curve that is so lovely, so familiar in its embodiment of all
that is (begin itals) home, (end itals) that it is poignant even
for those of us who never have been so far removed. It's not often
that New &AMP; Notable tells you a book is worth $50, but here we are.
You can see from the cover and the title that the Earth itself is a
supporting player. The conquered moon is the real focus, and it is
breathtaking. Light has chosen 129 images from more than 32,000
made by Apollo astronauts from 1968 to 1972. Only a few have been
published previously, but the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration allowed its master negatives to be taken off site
and digitally scanned for this volume. The resulting reproduction
is as haunting as it is near-perfect. There is, for example, a
photograph of a snapshot left on the surface of the moon by Apollo
16 astronaut Charles Duke _ a picture of his family, incongruous
not just because of its muted colors but its Beaver Cleaver
sweetness in the most stark and forbidding of places. In another
photo, Apollo 17 commander Eugene Cernan looks as if he has worked
a long day in a coal mine, but the smudges on his face are really
lunar soil from three days of exploring the moon's Taurus-Littrow
valley. With essays by Light and Andrew Chaikin (author of ``A Man
on the Moo''n). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE HOME DEPOT: BUILT FROM SCRATCH &QL; 
 &UR; Bernie Marcus and Arthur Blank (Times, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Bernie Marcus made a speech to a Rotary Club and asked
how many of the 400 people in his audience were
``do-it-yourselfers,'' how many owned tools, how many could repair
a toilet without calling a plumber. About 20 people raised their
hands. Fifteen years later, he appeared before the same group and
asked the same questions, and only 15 out of 450 (begin itals)
didn't (end itals) raise their hands. The difference? Home Depot,
which in 20 years had revolutionized the way people look at home
repair. It all began on April 14, 1978, when Marcus and Arthur
Blank were fired from their jobs at Daylin Corp. by an arrogant
chief executive who called himself ``Ming the Merciless'' after the
villain in the old Flash Gordon movies. Marcus and Blank were
dejected, but spurred on by friends (including Sol Price, founder
of Price Club), they met over coffee and sketched plans for their
dream, the home-improvement store of the future. They had no money,
but plenty of nerve _ Marcus walked away from $2 million in
start-up money from Ross Perot because he thought Perot was too
controlling (if Perot had behaved better, his original share of
Home Depot stock would be worth $58 billion today). They found the
cash elsewhere, picked a name for their company (an early rejectee:
``Bad Bernie's Buildall'') and began with four stores in Atlanta.
Today, they have 775 stores and $30 billion in sales. This is the
appealing story of a business coup accomplished by the seats of its
founders' pants, with energy, conviction and more than a little
luck. Marcus and Blank surprised even themselves, but they say
every word here is true _ ``Cross our hearts and swear to bleed
orange.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; I AIN'T GOT TIME TO BLEED &QL; 
 &UR; Jesse Ventura (Villard, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, the professional wrestler who was elected governor of
Minnesota, spends the first chapter of this book explaining that he
is not a politician, and the next chapter (in which he tells us
where he stands on the issues) sounding just like one. He then
proceeds, with profound bad judgment, to discuss the time he
visited a Nevada bordello just before he went overseas with the
Navy SEALs, trading a belt he'd made out of bullet-shell casings
for time with a less-than-opportunistic prostitute. You alone can
decide how much you want to know about Ventura, but Garrison
Keillor has written a fictionalized account of the governor's
escapades (``Me, by Jimmy (Big Boy) Valent''e) that is mildly funny
and better than this. In that spirit, we'll seize the chance to
mention Donny Osmond's new book, ``Life Is Just'' ``What You Make
It'' (Hyperion, $22.95). Donny does not visit any bordellos, but he
spends lots of time lamenting the trials and tribulations of being
himself, which might wear thin on readers who make do without their
own talk shows. Oddly enough, these very different men make the
same mistake in ignoring the rules of a good autobiography. First
hurdle: You have to be a pretty interesting guy to carry one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ADVICE TO WRITERS &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Jon Winokur (Pantheon, $22)
</P>
<P>
   Books like this are a dime a dozen, and we can't put them down.
``Appealing workplaces are to be avoided,'' Annie Dillard says.
``One wants a room with no view, so imagination can meet memory in
the dark.'' Here's F. Scott Fitzgerald on punctuation: ``Cut out
all the exclamation marks. An exclamation mark is like laughing at
your own joke.'' D.H. Lawrence on style: ``Be still when you have
nothing to say; when genuine passion moves you, say what you've got
to say, and say it hot.'' Jules Renard on words: ``(They are) the
pieces of change in the currency of a sentence. They must not get
in the way. There is always too much small change.'' As proof that
New &AMP; Notable can take a hit, we mention what we consider to be one
of E.B. White's lesser thoughts: ``It is almost impossible to write
anything decent using the editorial `we,' unless you are the Dionne
family.'' &QL; 
(Reach correspondent Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson &LR; worldnet.att.net via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
