<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-Y2K-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPORT'S 2000 BACKUP PLAN: CALL IN THE KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL DeMARE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ The Albany International Airport has a year 2000
contingency plan that includes hiring high school and college
students to carry baggage to arriving passengers if the luggage
carousel fails on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who will be on call, may also be used to operate
doors and direct passengers, John A. O'Donnell, the airport's chief
operating officer, said Monday in presenting the Y2K plan to
airport authority members.
</P>
<P>
   Baggage from incoming flights would be loaded on vehicles, as
usual, which would take the luggage to the carousel. If the
carousel isn't operating, the students would grab the suitcases and
run in with them, O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are great; they can go forever,'' he said after the
session.
</P>
<P>
   Students would also be used to hand out tickets at the parking
areas if the automatic ticket dispensers fail, he said. Airport
workers would be in charge of the students, guiding them in the
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Egan, chief executive officer of the airport, indicated
that all airport personnel could be working on Jan. 1 to help with
potential emergencies. But the days following New Year's also could
produce problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airport has an emergency generator that would kick in if
there are power failures, O'Donnell said. If the emergency
generator strikes out, then the airport's truck-mounted generator,
known to workers as ``Big Boy,'' would serve as the backup, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan said he has assurances that the power is not going to fail
on Jan. 1. But the airport has made preparations, as have other
businesses and some residents, in the event that power, telephones
and water supplies are cut off or curtailed by computer failures
liked to the Year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Computer experts fear that many computers originally programmed
to recognize only the last two digits of a year will fail or
malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume it is
1900.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, the airport staff worked to identify systems and all
key elements at the airport that could be affected by the Y2K
glitch, said J. Dwight Hadley, the airport's chief financial
officer. Now the proposal will be fine-tuned.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has three priorities _ mandatory, important and
nonessential.
</P>
<P>
   Power, the airport's main computer system and water supplies are
listed as mandatory. Loss of elevators, escalators, fire alarms and
computerized flight information (chalkboards and felt-tip markers
would substitute) are secondary. Considered nonessential are
parking lot gates and ticket dispensers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
