<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARE-TIPS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW TO SELECT HIGH-QUALITY DAY CARE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    With CHILD-CARE.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   To choose a high-quality day care center for pre-schoolers,
parents should look for:
</P>
<P>
   _ A low ratio of children to adults. The best centers have no
more than eight to 10 children per adult.
</P>
<P>
   _ Educated teachers. In general, teachers with a bachelors
degree in any major do better than those with an associates degree
in child development, who do better than those without a degree.
</P>
<P>
   _ Higher teacher pay and benefits. Staff turnover, which
disrupts relations between a child and teacher, is lower at centers
where compensation is near or at the level for beginning teachers
in the local public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Carollee Howes of UCLA, a principal investigator for the
Cost, Quality &AMP; Outcomes Study.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
