<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-08 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-BEAN SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
(This is the third of eight columns by Thomas Keller, the chef and
owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, Calif. His collaborator
is Michael Ruhlman.) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've named this salad after those crocks of marinated green
beans, garbanzo and kidney beans in every American salad bar. But
my three-bean salad is really something entirely different, a
simple composition of dried beans and fresh beans: a base of pureed
white beans is infused with truffle oil, topped with a mixture of
fresh beans in a vinaigrette and finished with field greens or
fresh herbs.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success is your bean technique. Dried beans must be
properly rehydrated and then gently simmered, never boiled. If you
boil the heck out of beans, they tend to explode. Soaking them in
warm water and then gradually bringing the cooking liquid up to a
gentle heat insures even cooking and intact beans. Add salt toward
the end of cooking rather than at the beginning, or it will inhibit
rehydration.
</P>
<P>
   The salad works well with any fresh beans _ Blue Lake, haricots
verts, yellow wax, fava, lima or cranberry beans, to name some
possibilities _ cooked until they are firm but give no resistance
to the teeth. To cook fresh beans _ or any green vegetable, for
that matter _ I use a technique I call big-pot blanching: cook your
vegetable in so much water that the water does not lose its boil
when you add the vegetables. Your water should be heavily salted,
about a half cup for each gallon. The result is a vegetable of the
brightest possible color.
</P>
<P>
   If you've cooked your beans properly, you almost can't go wrong
with this salad. Feel free to experiment with the vinaigrette: wine
vinegars (sherry, red or Champagne) or balsamic are good choices. I
love to serve it throughout the summer when we have abundant
varieties of ``fresh from the garden'' beans. It's seasonal,
elegant and fun _ an interpretation of a salad bar standard that's
worthy, I think, of haute cuisine. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THREE-BEAN SALAD  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours, plus overnight soaking of beans  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dried marrow beans or other white beans, soaked in 4 cups
water at room temperature overnight
</P>
<P>
   5 cups plus 2 tablespoons vegetable stock or canned vegetable
broth
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, peeled and halved, plus 1 teaspoon minced
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Bouquet garni: 3 sprigs parsley, 1 sprig thyme and 1 bay leaf,
wrapped in two 5-inch sections of leek greens and tied with string
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 tablespoons white truffle oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sherry wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup trimmed haricots verts in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 cup trimmed yellow wax beans in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   { cup shelled, peeled fava beans
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups frisee or baby greens, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon peeled, seeded, diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare the bean puree: Drain the white beans. In a large
saucepan or casserole, combine the beans with 4 cups of water.
Place over low heat, and bring to a simmer. Remove from the heat,
and allow the beans to rest for 5 minutes. Remove any beans that
float to the surface. Drain, and chill under cold running water.
Return the beans to the saucepan, and add 5 cups of the vegetable
stock, shallot halves, carrot and bouquet garni. Place over low
heat, and simmer for 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add \ teaspoon salt, and continue to cook until the beans are
completely tender, 25 to 30 minutes. There should still be some
liquid remaining in the pan. Place a strainer over a bowl, and
drain the beans, reserving the liquid. Remove and discard the
carrot and bouquet garni. Using a food processor, begin to puree
the beans. With the machine running, slowly add the reserved liquid
through the feed tube, adding just enough to make a smooth puree.
Next, pass the puree through a tamis or drum sieve. Measure 1 cup
of puree into a mixing bowl, and set aside the remainder for
another use. Whisk in the remaining 2 tablespoons vegetable stock,
2 tablespoons of the truffle oil and 1 teaspoon of the vinegar. The
puree should have a creamy consistency; add 1 more tablespoon of
truffle oil if desired. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare the bean salad: Make an ice-water bath by filling a
large bowl with ice and water. Bring a large pot of water to a
boil, adding { cup of salt for each gallon. Add the haricots verts,
and blanch until they are cooked but still firm to the bite, 2 to 3
minutes. Using a slotted spoon, immediately transfer the beans to
the ice-water bath. Bring the water to a boil again, and repeat
with the yellow wax beans and finally the fava beans. Drain the
chilled beans, and pat dry with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a small bowl, whisk together 2 tablespoons of the truffle
oil, the olive oil, lemon juice and remaining vinegar. Season to
taste with salt and pepper. Toss 1 tablespoon of vinaigrette with
the salad greens, and season to taste with salt and pepper. In a
mixing bowl, combine the remaining vinaigrette with the blanched
beans, diced tomatoes, and minced shallots. Season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, use a spoon to smooth an even layer of puree in the
center of each serving plate. Arrange about 1/3 cup of the bean
salad over the puree. Gently stack a mound of greens over the
salad, and sprinkle the top with a little additional salt.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASQUE-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     06-08 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASQUE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BASQUE KITCHEN' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Piperade is a quintessential Basque dish that combines the
signature ingredients: tomatoes, onion, garlic, chilies, and
controversy,'' reads the headnote to a recipe in Gerald Hirigoyen's
book, ``The Basque Kitchen'' (HarperCollins, $35).
</P>
<P>
   It is just that kind of light, clever touch that distinguishes
the book. Hirigoyen, the chef at Fringale and Pastis in San
Francisco, is a native of the Basque country, a land steeped for
centuries in conflict. As he returns to it in this book, you can
feel the love and respect he has for his homeland and for its
cuisine, how it fits into the larger world of French and Spanish
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   In the introduction, Hirigoyen places himself in Basque culture:
``I cannot paint like Ramiro Arrue. Nor can I compose like Maurice
Ravel, born in Ciboure; nor write like Pierre Loti ... who gave the
Basque heart a voice. I can, however, cook.''
</P>
<P>
   The book contains a mixture of old Basque dishes like gateau
Basque, a layered creamed-filled pastry, and garbure, a country
vegetable soup, and what Hirigoyen calls ``New Basque Cuisine,''
dishes like a quince and goat cheese layer cake and a salmon fillet
with red pepper sabayon. Surprisingly, the two styles of recipes
work together, an unusual success that can be attributed to the
author, who makes clear the distinctions between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a lengthy introduction reviewing Basque cultural
history, the book is primarily a collection of recipes, with very
little commentary on technique. Hirigoyen speaks to the competent
cook.
</P>
<P>
   Hake San Sebastian style is one of his more challenging
restaurant-style recipes. The hake is floured and fried, then
quickly braised with clams, asparagus, peas, wine and, strangely
enough, chopped hard-boiled egg. The recipe turned out fine, but it
was the kind of dish that will be better the next time I try it,
now that I understand the components and how they must fit
together.
</P>
<P>
   Other recipes are much simpler. A gratin of walnuts and sheep's
milk cheese for dessert took about five minutes to assemble and
looked beautiful, puffed like a souffle and browned like a loaf of
bread. Best of all, though, was the flavor, rich with cheese and
walnuts and drifting pleasantly between sweet and savory.
</P>
<P>
   Cherries in red wine soup had a similar sort of instant
gratification. Red wine, port, sugar, vanilla bean, star anise and
citrus zests are simmered for a few minutes, then the pitted
cherries are added just long enough to wilt lightly.
</P>
<P>
   The dish to make you return to this book again and again,
though, is the humble baked garbanzo beans. The beans are simply
braised with garlic, bay leaves, coriander, chili and saffron.
absorbing the flavors of the aromatics. With a loaf of bread to sop
up the cooking liquid, I would have been happy to make a meal of
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BAKED GARBANZO BEANS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Basque Kitchen'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour and 10 minutes plus 24 hours soaking  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 garlic cloves, finely sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 dried chili, mild or spicy
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coriander seeds
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   3 cups garbanzo beans (chickpeas), soaked 24 hours at room
temperature
</P>
<P>
   5 to 6 cups vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   10 saffron threads
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground white pepper or more to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. In a large casserole, warm
the olive oil over medium-high heat. Add the onions, garlic, chili,
coriander and bay leaves; saute for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drain the garbanzo beans, and add them, along with the broth,
saffron, salt and pepper. Cover and bring to a boil. Transfer to
the oven.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake until the beans are soft and cooked through, 45 to 50
minutes. Season to taste with salt and pepper, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
