<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      06-08 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFECT CUT FOR THE GRILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMANN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may be no meat better for grilling than boneless leg of
lamb. This is a cut that cooks reasonably quickly, usually in less
than half an hour, but still develops an irresistibly crunchy
crust. Even better, that crust can be flavored in minutes before it
is cooked with any of a dozen combinations of seasonings.
Marinating is unnecessary, as the meat itself has exquisite flavor
and really needs no more than salt.
</P>
<P>
   There are other advantages to boneless leg of lamb, also called
butterflied leg for the two-lobed shape formed when the bone is
removed. There is no need to do the boning yourself, as there once
was; nearly every supermarket carries boned leg. Most pieces are
big enough to serve six, and often 10, making the cut ideal for a
get-together. Best of all, the leg's irregular shape virtually
guarantees that every eater will be happy _ lamb is the only meat
good at every stage of doneness. When the thickest parts have
cooked to rare, the ends will be well done, the parts in between
medium.
</P>
<P>
   The boneless legs sold in supermarkets are sometimes wrapped in
an elastic net to form them into a round roast. For grilling,
remove this so the meat lies flat.
</P>
<P>
   If the larger end of the meat is three or more inches thick, you
might cut a flap to make that lobe thinner and flatter so that it
cooks more evenly. Using a sharp, thin-bladed knife and working
from the side of the lobe that faces the rest of the meat, make a
horizontal cut about halfway down from top to bottom, most of the
way through, and fold the meat out; in essence, you are
butterflying the butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   The thickness of the meat makes grilling easier than it is with
thinner cuts, because you can keep the lamb over the heat long
enough to insure a well-browned and crisp crust without overcooking
the interior. If you use a fairly hot, but not blazing hot,
charcoal or gas fire, you can sear the meat for five minutes on
each side. Then, either cover the grill or move the meat to a
cooler part and cook until done. The ideal moment is when an
instant-read thermometer inserted into the thickest part of the
meat reads 125 degrees. That means you will have rare meat in the
thick part, well-done meat at the ends. As always with grilled
food, the broiler _ essentially an upside-down grill _ is an
excellent alternative. Keep the rack four or six inches from the
heat source.
</P>
<P>
   Flavoring options are many. My favorite combinations include
coriander or fennel seeds for added crunch.  &QL; 
GRILLED BONELESS LEG OF LAMB  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 3- to 4-pound butterflied leg of lamb
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh rosemary or 2 teaspoons dried rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped or crushed fennel seeds
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Start a charcoal or wood fire or preheat gas grill or
broiler; the fire should be quite hot, and the rack 4 inches from
heat source.
</P>
<P>
   2. Trim the lamb of excess fat. Mix together the olive oil,
garlic, rosemary, fennel seeds, salt and pepper; rub this mixture
well into the lamb, making sure to get some into all the crevices.
(If time allows, it does no harm to let the prepared lamb sit in
the refrigerator for up to 24 hours; just return the meat to room
temperature before grilling.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Sear the meat over the hottest part of the grill until nicely
browned on both sides, 10 to 15 minutes. Continue to cook with the
grill covered or uncovered for 5 to 15 minutes longer, until the
internal temperature at the thickest part is about 125 degrees. Let
rest for 5 minutes before slicing and serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: at least 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Substitute 2 teaspoons fresh thyme (or 1 teaspoon
dried thyme) for fennel seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Use 1 tablespoon soy sauce or 1 tablespoon minced anchovies
instead of the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Use a combination of 1 tablespoon coriander seeds, 1 teaspoon
black peppercorns, 1 tablespoon garlic and 1 tablespoon fresh
ginger, all minced or coarsely ground together; moisten with a
little soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the lamb all over with 2 tablespoons curry powder mixed with
{ cup yogurt.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
