<HEADLINE>
AN INN'S OWN BREWS (JUST REMEMBER WHICH DOOR YOU CAME IN)
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, Vt. _ To cosset their guests, some innkeepers bake
their own bread, make their own jams or grow their own mesclun. Tim
Wilson, an owner of the Jasper Murdock Alehouse at the Norwich Inn
here, brews tasty, full-bodied beers _ from hoppy pale ales to
thick, creamy stouts.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sally, bought the 1797 inn in 1991, and around the
same time, he went to England and discovered the local aromatic
ales. ``It was an epiphany,'' he said. ``Before, I had only had
American lagers.''
</P>
<P>
   So he started brewing Irish and English-style ales at the inn,
using English malts, hops and yeast. In 1993 he quit his job as a
senior loan officer at a bank in White River Junction and became a
brewmaster-innkeeper. Each year he makes 10 different beers, with
three available at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   The beers are on tap at the pub or in 22-ounce bottles for
takeout. ``Our customers pay at the front desk, go outside to a
little alley, and we hand it out to them through a side door, much
like Prohibition days, when this was a speak-easy,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the delayed gratification and extra footwork is
Vermont's liquor laws: The inn has two licenses, one to sell the
beer for consumption on premises, another for off-premises
consumption _ and each requires its own entryway-exit.
</P>
<P>
   The three brews now being sold are Whistling Pig Ale, Second
Wind Oatmeal Stout and Old Slipperyskin India Pale Ale.
</P>
<P>
   Whistling Pig Ale is smooth with a garnet color, a faint aroma
and a rounded, malty flavor with a lingering hoppy aftertaste.
Second Wind Oatmeal Stout pours black and has a thick,
coffee-colored head, a flavor that suggests espresso and a hoppy
bite.
</P>
<P>
   Old Slipperyskin is a medium amber color, with a hoppy aroma and
an equally hoppy, full-bodied flavor and a pleasantly bitter
aftertaste. It is named for a bear that, in 17th-century legend,
was so strong it could squeeze sap from the biggest maple trees.
The bear is said to have been first seen by Indians in the 1600s
and by colonists in the 1740s.
</P>
<P>
   Same bear?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Wilson said, ``that's why it's a legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Murdock beers are sold only at the Norwich Inn. A
22-ounce bottle is $4. No mail orders. Information: (802) 649-1143.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
