<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MELISSA CLARK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comparing Flours &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the difference in flour made from spring wheat and
winter wheat?
</P>
<P>
   A. Spring wheat is sowed in the Northern United States and
Canada in spring and harvested in late summer, said Joe Caron, a
spokesman for King Arthur Flour. It is generally the faster-growing
``hard'' variety. When ground, hard spring wheat yields a
high-protein, high-gluten flour well suited for baking bread,
bagels and some pastas.
</P>
<P>
   Winter wheat is a slow-growing type that is sowed in the fall,
goes dormant over the winter and is harvested in mid- to late
spring. In the United States, winter wheat is grown from Texas to
Kansas and may be either ``hard'' or ``soft.'' In general, winter
wheat flour has less protein than spring wheat flour. It is best
for pastries, cakes and cookies. Many bakers say that it is more
flavorful than spring wheat because of its longer growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Although most brands of flour do not indicate the type of wheat,
bread flours are almost always made from hard spring wheat and
pastry flours from soft winter wheat. All-purpose flour is usually
a mix of several types.
</P>
<P>
   Butter Goes Gently Into a Good Batter  &QL; 
Q. I have been having a lot of trouble making a genoise sponge. It
somehow splits into two layers and comes out with a rubbery
texture. I take care to fold in the flour and butter carefully,
even lightening the melted butter with some of the beaten egg
first. What's going wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. Making a perfect genoise cake takes practice, especially if
the recipe calls for butter: it adds richness and tenderness but
requires a delicate balance between beating the batter enough to
incorporate it but not so much that the eggs deflate.
</P>
<P>
   Your batter may not have been beaten enough. While you don't
want to overdo it, it's essential to fold the butter into the
batter very, very thoroughly, until no streaks of melted butter are
visible.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick, from Rose Levy Beranbaum's ``Cake Bible''
(William Morrow, 1988), is to add the melted butter when it's still
warm but not hot. Once the butter begins to solidify, it becomes
harder to incorporate and can weigh down the cake.
</P>
<P>
   No Fear of a Clove Shortage &QL; 
Q. Is there a worldwide shortage of ground cloves? I finally found
a tiny jar with } ounce (21 grams) in a supermarket for $7.19!
</P>
<P>
   A. Fear not: there are plenty of cloves to go around. That jar
was probably just a high-end brand using the best of the harvest.
The cloves were probably also packaged soon after grinding to
maintain freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Good cloves can be found for much less. One option is to buy
spices in bulk from a store with high turnover. They should smell
pleasantly pungent, with no traces of an off odor.
</P>
<P>
   You can also buy by mail. Penzey's Spices, (414) 679-7207, sells
\ cup (1.2 ounces) of ground cloves for $2.29.
</P>
<P>
   If Worms Show Up in the Fish Fillet &QL; 
Q. Recently I purchased lemon sole at a reputable fish market. I
put it in the pan to saute and was horrified to see two very thin
worms, about two inches long, crawling out of the flesh. The vendor
refunded my money and explained that this condition is endemic to
certain fish. What kinds of fish are these? Do the worms pose any
danger if ingested?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fish that feed on the bottom of the ocean, like haddock,
flounder and sole, are especially susceptible to parasites, said
Dr. Mike Timmons, professor of agriculture and biological
engineering and director of the Cornell Aquaculture Program at
Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't impractical, the fish fillets could be put on a
light table and screened for worms before being sold. But most fish
are worm-free. And if you should eat a parasite, rest assured that
it is not harmful.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
