<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DISCOVER TWO HEAVY ELEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Berkeley scientists have discovered two new
elements, the heaviest ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Unromantically dubbed 116 and 118, they were created inside a
cyclotron, or atom smasher, at the Lawrence Berkeley National
Laboratory. They're as fleeting as a discovery can be, though: Each
lives only a moment. Then, within a tiny fraction of a second, they
decay into subatomic fragments and pure energy.
</P>
<P>
   At the lab, people are very excited by the discovery that
involves a team led by physicist Ken Gregorich.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge amount of effort has gone into it,'' said Claude
Lyneis, an accelerator physicist who runs the 88-inch cyclotron
where the discovery was made.
</P>
<P>
   Lyneis said the lab decided to announce the discovery Monday
morning after rumors of the achievement began to appear on academic
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery marks a major step toward one of nuclear
physicists' Shangri-Las: a hypothetical ``island of stability'' of
super-heavy elements that might last for many years, rather than
instantly decaying. The heaviest element found in sizable amounts
in nature is uranium, with the atomic number 92. (The number refers
to the number of protons, the positively charged occupants of the
atomic nucleus, in an element.)
</P>
<P>
   Physicists who study the nuclear structure of atoms have been
seeking super-heavy elements for decades. They dreamed of finding
super-heavy elements in the ``island of stability'' that might
endure for billions of years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Berkeley scientists entered a Bay Area Rapid
Transit tunnel to look for radiation from hypothesized super-heavy
elements in the geological layers. They looked there because the
purported elements' radioactive signals would be easier to detect
than on the surface, where background radiation from cosmic rays
and other sources constantly confuses instruments.
</P>
<P>
   But they found nothing, said physicist Darleane Hoffman of
Lawrence Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   So they tried to create the elements by bashing together
high-speed particles inside accelerators. So did physicists working
in Russia, who previously said they had created _ in collaboration
with scientists from Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory east of
San Francisco _ element 114. However, the Russian-Livermore claim
is based on a single observation and is not yet proven, Lawrence
Berkeley scientists maintain.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the discovery of 116 and 118 is based on the
Lawrence Berkeley scientists' observations of three separate decays
of the elements in the cyclotron, Lyneis said. Element 118 decays
into 116, then into smaller products.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, he said, ``it looks like we've landed on the edge of the
island of stability, or on the shore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said old hopes of finding super-heavy elements that last
a billion years or so have faded. Nowadays, optimists hope to find
super-heavy elements that last about a century.
</P>
<P>
   Does the discovery have practical applications? Hoffman recalled
the words of the late Lawrence Berkeley Nobel laureate Glenn
Seaborg, who died early this year after a career that included the
synthesis of the element plutonium, used in nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot very often predict the practical applications of
basic science,'' Seaborg said, ``but we can predict that those
practical applications will occur to the enduring benefit of man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1607EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-08 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOUVRAYS: BEYOND TRADITION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOUVRAY, France _ The last time I was here, 14 years ago, the
railroad was planning to run its new high-speed train through the
town's vineyards. The winemakers were up in arms, and one of them,
Gaston Huet, explained it all to me over a bottle of his 1947
Vouvray, an unforgettable wine the color of burnished gold.
</P>
<P>
   The trains went elsewhere and the vines were saved, but I never
forgot that 1947 wine. Deciding to go back to Vouvray to meet some
of the new winemakers, I called Jacqueline Friedrich, who wrote ``A
Wine &AMP; Food Guide to the Loire'' (Henry Holt, 1996). She told me
about Catherine and Didier Champalou, a young couple with 50 acres
of vineyards who are making a name for themselves. In her book, she
described them as having created ``one of the most exciting
wineries in Vouvray.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go see them,'' she advised, and I did. And never got any
farther.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Champalous' cellar was carved out of the chalky soil
some 400 years ago, the couple are relative newcomers. ``We only
started in 1984,'' Mrs. Champalou, 38, said. ``At first, we had one
hectare of vines. Now, we have 20, which is just about what one
needs to succeed independently in Vouvray.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about 50 acres. And from that plot comes both sparkling
and still wines that are creating a stir for their intense taste.
In this tradition-bound region, their freshness makes them
standouts.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Champalou is a Vouvray native whose grandfather once worked
some of the land she and her husband now call their own. Champalou,
40, is also from a Loire winemaking family, and grew up about 30
miles from Vouvray. They met at viticultural school in nearby
Saumur.
</P>
<P>
   The Champalou wines range from dry to intensely sweet, or what
the French call moelleux. With the couple's guidance, I tasted many
of them. They may differ in sweetness, but they share the same
flavor intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, finding them in the United States is difficult
outside the major markets. Most of the Champalous' annual
production, 5,000 cases, is sold in France, where good Vouvray has
a solid following.
</P>
<P>
   Vouvray is one of the best-known appellations in the Loire
Valley, along with Muscadet, Sancerre, Chinon, Bourgueil, Saumur
and Anjou. Eight communes are entitled to the Vouvray appellation,
but the best wines come from the vines closest to the river in four
towns; Vouvray itself, Rochecorbon, Noizay and Vernou.
</P>
<P>
   In an average year, about a million cases of Vouvray are made,
half of it sparkling wine. All Vouvray is made from the chenin
blanc grape, which the French call simply chenin because, as its
name implies, it is a white grape; there is no red chenin.
</P>
<P>
   In much of the world, chenin has an indifferent reputation. In
South Africa, where it is called Steen, many growers are beginning
to replace it with chardonnay. In California's hot Central Valley,
it produces a soft, flabby wine fit mostly for jugs, but a few
North Coast producers, including Dry Creek and Chappellet
Vineyards, make surprisingly good table wines from it.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Vouvray is known as a mostly indifferent
sparkling wine. In fact, most producers in Vouvray make more
sparking wine than anything else, counting on it to pay their
bills. There are some excellent sparkling wines, but few are
exported.
</P>
<P>
   The best Vouvrays are still wines. They range from dry to sweet
and are often wines of immense breed and complexity, capable of
improving over astonishing stretches of time. A 50-year-old Vouvray
can be as fruity and rich as a five-year-old chardonnay, and some
cellars here still hold a few bottles near or at the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   Chenin is a big producer, but the Champalous have a knack for
keeping the yields low. Indeed, it takes character to keep trimming
it back. In some instances, as in 1996, a particularly sunny
growing season helps out; water in the fruit evaporates, leaving
only concentrated juice. Some Vouvrays are helped along by
botrytis, the famous noble rot of Sauternes, but the fogs that
carry it are less common here in the Touraine wine region than they
are south of Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The Champalous have produced some extraordinary botrytized
wines, but do not count on it for producing good wines. In the
cellar, Champalou works slowly. Grapes are pressed for up to five
hours, and fermentation can last three months or more. Dry wines
are aged in stainless steel, sweet wines in oak barrels, never much
longer than nine months. Among Champalou's finest Vouvrays are his
Cuvee des Fondraux and Cuvee CC.
</P>
<P>
   Both are sweet wines, the Fondraux less so than the CC, and both
are made from grapes picked by the trie system used in Sauternes.
Pickers go through the vineyards as many as six times over a 10-day
period, selecting only the perfectly ripe grapes each time. The
Cuvee CC, which is sold only in half-liter bottles, is a wine for
the ages, and probably shouldn't even be sampled until it's 10
years old.
</P>
<P>
   The Champalous, like most Vouvrillons, make sparkling Vouvray,
but theirs is not a commercial, cash-flow wine. Made in the classic
methode champenoise, it is a rich, elegant wine that easily
outclasses many supermarket Champagnes.
</P>
<P>
   So seek out the Champalou wines, but keep some other fine
Vouvray producers on your shopping list, too, among them Huet,
Domaine des Aubuisieres, Marc Bredif, Francois Pinon and Clos
Baudoin.
</P>
<P>
   As for me, I won't wait 14 more years to go back to Vouvray, and
next time, I will definitely see Huet. Thank goodness he didn't
stop the high-speed trains completely. The local train station, in
Tours, is only an hour from Paris now _ even with that detour
around the Vouvray vines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
