<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-TOMATOES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUMPING THE GUN FOR TOMATOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867. ) 
 (HLW)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anyone who is panting for the local tomato season to
begin has already missed its opening. For true tomato fans, the
season begins when the first green tomatoes arrive at the markets.
And they have.
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. Green tomatoes are not eaten in the spring but
in the fall, when the ripe ones are waning. But when Joel Patraker,
the assistant director of the Greenmarket program in New York City,
waxes poetic about green tomatoes, you will rush out and buy them
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a balance of citrus and sweetness,'' he said. ``There
is a lot of juiciness and a fragrance, and they do get the
characteristic hints of pineapple and chardonnay. People are
missing the boat because they don't know what to do with them.''
</P>
<P>
   They could do what Patraker does: saute cornmeal-coated slices
of the tomatoes and layer them in a sandwich with slices of dry
goat cheese. While frying is the traditional way of preparing them,
especially in the South, they can also be baked, which gives them
the texture of eggplant, or used in a sauce.
</P>
<P>
   At Savoy, in Manhattan, the chef, Peter Hoffman, likes green
tomatoes because ``they speak to both ends of the season, '' he
said. Hoffman, who makes a point of cooking with local ingredients,
recently offered veal scaloppine with green tomatoes, which, he
said, ``bring a bright acid flavor to a dish.'' Sometimes he chars
them as he would tomatillos, the small green fruits that lie hidden
beneath papery skins and are so popular in Mexican cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Romano, the chef at Union Square Cafe, serves a green
tomato sauce with salmon that has been marinated in a chili rub.
``One of the things I love most about Indian food is the exquisite
balance between sweetness and acidity which I find in a green
tomato,'' he said. ``And it cuts through the richness of the
salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   You will not find green tomatoes on the menu at Gotham Bar and
Grill, but its chef and owner, Alfred Portale, frequently grills
them at home because he has so many tomato plants.
</P>
<P>
   He cuts them in half and marinates them for a couple of hours in
a mixture of extra virgin olive oil, garlic, shallots, thyme, salt
and pepper and then grills them, cut side down, just until they
brown. Then he turns them, moves them to the side of the grill,
away from the direct heat, and lets them continue to cook until
they are very soft and pulpy. He advises handling them carefully
when transferring them to slices of grilled bread.
</P>
<P>
   If you have green tomatoes in your garden, do not pick them
until they are heavy and have a little bit of give; picked too
soon, the tomatoes will be like cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   Green tomatoes have a place of honor on the menu at the City
Bakery, where Ilene Rosen, the savory chef, coats them with crumbs
from the cafe's own corn bread, bakes them and then serves them
with a tomato-yogurt sauce and slices of Cheddar cheese.
</P>
<P>
   They will soon appear in sandwich form on an onion Parker House
roll. With or without the bread, the combination is utterly simple,
utterly summer, utterly American.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
