<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DODGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO PLAYS HERO'S ROLE AGAIN IN RANGERS VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Texas Rangers departed for their six scheduled
interleague games at Arizona's Bank One Ballpark and Los Angeles'
Dodger Stadium with this question:
</P>
<P>
   Could Rafael Palmeiro emerge as a factor?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: yes.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who Saturday made his season debut at first base and
drove in six runs on the strength of two homers during the Rangers'
9-8 victory against the Diamondbacks, delivered again.
</P>
<P>
   Eighth-inning singles by Palmeiro and catcher Ivan Rodriguez off
right-hander Ismael Valdes propelled the Rangers to a 3-2 victory
Monday night against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I can help this team. I know what I can do,''
Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Those two clutch, one-out base hits scored second baseman Mark
McLemore and right fielder Juan Gonzalez, and right-hander Aaron
Sele (6-4) pitched seven strong innings before the Rangers' 1-2
bullpen punch of Jeff Zimmerman and closer John Wetteland preserved
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro started 51 of the Rangers' first 53 games as the
designated hitter while allowing his right knee heal sufficiently
for his return to the field. Palmeiro underwent arthroscopic
surgery Feb. 10 and March 7 to remove torn meniscus from the knee,
and those surgeries restricted the lateral movement required to
play defensively.
</P>
<P>
   However, interleague games played in National League ballparks
prohibit the designated hitter. Palmeiro, though, made his third
consecutive start as the Rangers' first baseman and again made a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   So did Sele, who surrendered only two runs on five hits and did
not issue a walk during an economic, seven-inning appearance that
required only 80 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had good command of . He could throw it anytime he
wanted,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said of Sele. ``Not too many
guys throw 80-pitch ballgames, other than Maddux, and it could've
been.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that I feel like I'm throwing the ball
better than I did earlier in the year,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile, who Saturday committed a fifth-inning
error that led to three unearned runs during the Rangers' 4-2 loss
to the Arizona Diamondbacks, delivered the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile's two-out, second-inning double snapped his 0-for-18 slump
and scored Juan Gonzalez, who led off the inning with a line-drive
single to right field off Valdes (5-4).
</P>
<P>
   Sele entered the seventh inning with a three-hit shutout intact,
but center fielder Trenidad Hubbard _ who replaced the injured
Devon White in the fourth inning _ led off the inning with a
well-hit ball to center field.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin, perhaps the American
League's fastest player, chased the ball into deep left-center
field. The ball, though, deflected off Goodwin's outstretched
glove, and Hubbard coasted into second base with the leadoff
double.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard advanced to third when Rodriguez's pickoff attempt
eluded shortstop Royce Clayton and bounced into center field. Sele,
though, induced the first of two consecutive ground balls with the
infield in from third baseman Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard could not score on Beltre's ground ball, but the one off
the bat of catcher Angel Pena was not hit hard enough for Clayton
to make a play at the plate. Clayton fielded the ball on the
infield grass and retired Pena while Hubbard scored the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman replaced Sele after Eric Young's leadoff single in the
eighth inning, and the right-handed reliever worked out of a
one-out, bases-loaded jam to preserve the Rangers' one-run lead
after Eric Karros' sacrifice fly. Wetteland pitched a scoreless
ninth for his major-league-best 20th save. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
