<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZUBOV BREAKS SILENCE, BUT ONLY ON ORDERS OF NHL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA, JENNIFER FLOYD, JIM REEVES, DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ AND
MEDE NIX 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sergei Zubov broke his media ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL made me,'' the Dallas Stars defenseman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He has made a policy of not talking to the media during the
playoffs. He talked during the Stars' second-round series against
St. Louis, and not long thereafter made a turnover that led to the
Blues' game-winning goal in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk, bad things happen,'' Zubov said. ONE HOT POWER
PLAY
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres have 15 power-play goals in 16 games. They score on
almost one of every four attempts. So what are the Stars to do if
they find themselves shorthanded?
</P>
<P>
   ``We should do what we've been doing,'' winger Jere Lehtinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lead the NHL in penalty-kill percentage, negating 91.3
percent of the power plays they have faced. The secret, Lehtinen
said, is being aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like St. Louis: They shoot a lot from the point,''
Lehtinen said. ``We have to get pressure.'' FAVORED AND PROUD OF IT
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock said the Stars deserve to be favored in the
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in first place since day one,'' he said. ``We
deserve the accolades and the pressure that goes along with being
favored.'' MARSHALL, HOGUE LIKELY OUT
</P>
<P>
   Winger Grant Marshall could be out for an extended period with
an injured left groin muscle, joining winger Benoit Hogue as
unlikely to play in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said that he considers himself ``day-to-day'' and that
he's not sure whether he can return for the Finals. Marshall, a
native of Mississauga, Ontario, said he's working to get tickets
for his parents to Game 3 and 4 in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock reiterated that Hogue is not expected to play, but
Hogue said he is postponing surgery until after the Finals on the
rare chance that he might return.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said team doctors have advised Hogue, who tore the
anterior cruciate and medial collateral ligaments in his left knee
May 24, not to play, and he does not expect to put Hogue in the
lineup under any circumstance. HULL AMBIGUOUS
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull isn't changing his tune for the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   He knows the checking-oriented scheme of Ken Hitchcock works;
he's just not thrilled playing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's like every sport,'' Hull said, pointing to the
NBA. ``All they talk about is defense wins. I think that is what
will always be the case. I am openly against it, but it is a
situation where you go out and you play. It is not up to us as
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said that, in emphasizing his defensive style, Hitchcock
``is hard on you. He drives you. He's relentless. He'll ride you
until you play his way.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he doesn't expect changes in that style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to live and die with it,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hull said he is having ``a lot of fun this year,'' and is
firmly convinced that the system works, especially after the Stars'
sloppy defense in Game 5 of the Western Conference finals caused
them to give up seven goals to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing that ever happened to us was losing Game 5,''
Hull said. NO WAGERING, PLEASE
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk said he doesn't know whether he'll place a
bet with the mayor of Buffalo on the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that Buffalo's got anything else to offer after
two Super Bowl losses to the Cowboys,'' Kirk said, noting the
Dallas Cowboys' two blowout Super Bowl wins against the Buffalo
Bills in 1992 and 1993. ``We've got just about all the Buffalo
wings we need.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a bet, Kirk said, it might be for something simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll have a bet to fly the other's flag over City Hall
for a day,'' he said. RIBS VS. CHICKEN WINGS
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush wagered barbecue ribs and brisket
against New York Gov. George Pataki's 100 Buffalo chicken wings and
a dozen roast beef, gravy and horseradish ``Beef on Weck''
sandwiches that the Stars will beat the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Bush expressed confidence in the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas Stars will prevail and bring the Stanley Cup to
Texas where it rightfully belongs,'' Bush said. WORK ETHIC
</P>
<P>
   The key to beating the Sabres is simple, Ken Hitchcock said _
outwork goalie Dominic Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to win bad enough, you have to outwork the best
player, and the best player is the goalie,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
learned our lesson two years ago (against Edmonton) with (Curtis)
Joseph. We didn't outwork him, we didn't out-battle him in front of
the net, and we didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're prepared to outwork this guy, we'll get our offensive
opportunities, and we'll get our goals. If not, if we just get
discouraged and walk away after one shot, we're not going to be
very good.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
