<SLUG> BC-HKN-MODANO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR OF WORDS STEMS FROM MODANO'S `LETDOWN' TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Inside the Stars Club on Monday, the atmosphere was
festive, downright party-like as media members from across the
nation feasted on food and the quotes of the Dallas Stars and
Buffalo Sabres players.
</P>
<P>
   But while the press went home happy, it appeared the
participants had a little heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals at 7 p.m. Tuesday
at Reunion Arena, players and coaches from both sides tossed barbs
across the media throng. The acrimony began Saturday with ``The
Buffalo News'' printing comments from Stars center Mike Modano
saying he thought fans were anticipating a bit of a letdown going
into the finals from the Colorado Avalanche to the seventh-seeded
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Modano said Monday he was simply answering a question and didn't
mean to disparage the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing to light a fire under them,'' Modano said. ``I
don't want to get into a war of words. Grade me the way I play, not
the way I talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres have decided to do exactly that. And right now,
Sabres coach Lindy Ruff isn't handing out high grades to Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play anybody against Modano. He hasn't given anyone any
problems lately,'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano had just one goal in the seven-game Western Conference
finals series with the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   But Stars coach Ken Hitchcock fired back his own volley. When
asked if the Stars would struggle with Sabres center Michael Peca,
a Selke Trophy finalist who likely will check Modano, Hitchcock
responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano is about to become a 30-minute player. He's not going
to play 20 minutes, not with four games left in the season,''
Hitchcock said. ``He's going to be a 30-minute player. So if Peca
can play 30 minutes, bring it on. Let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   In between, Sabres players criticized the bad ice at Reunion
Arena and said the Stars were ``cheaters'' in the faceoff circle.
Ruff talked about getting into the head of Stars goalie Ed Belfour,
and Stars center Brian Skrudland pondered possible psychological
tactics against Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both claimed that what is supposed to be a
``boring'' finals series between two defensive hockey teams will at
least have intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an instant rivalry as soon as the puck is
dropped,'' Ruff said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
