<SLUG> BC-HKN-FRIENDLY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDOR, ZHITNIK WERE FIRST FRIENDS, NOW ON-ICE FOES
</HEADLINE>
 FOES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Fresh off the plane from Ukraine and in Los Angeles as
a Kings rookie in 1992, Alexei Zhitnik described himself as ``a guy
from another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he crossed paths with Darryl Sydor, who became Zhitnik's
roommate, defensive mate with the Kings and interplanetary tour
guide. Sydor taught Zhitnik, both 20 at the time, the ways of the
NHL world, and together they figured they would become the core of
a Stanley Cup defense.
</P>
<P>
   Why not when the Kings made the Finals that season before losing
to the Montreal Canadiens?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I was really understanding what kind of level we
were playing at,'' Zhitnik said. ``I had a lot of guys around me
with four and five Stanley Cup rings. Maybe I thought it was easy
to get to the finals. I thought maybe it's not going to happen
every year, but every second year I can play for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time showed me I was wrong, and it took me another seven
years, same as Darryl Sydor, to get that opportunity again.''
</P>
<P>
   Former LA Kings coach Barry Melrose remembers Zhitnik and Sydor
as ``best friends,'' along with defenseman Rob Blake. Melrose
remembers the time Zhitnik purchased a Lexus with cash and
proceeded to drive it around Los Angeles with no American driver's
license.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of stuff like that right off the bat,'' Melrose
said. ``He didn't know. He never had money like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor said he enjoyed the process of assimilating Zhitnik to
life in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I taught him a few things about what was going on,''
Sydor said. ``He liked the busy life. LA was a good fit for him. He
had fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zhitnik: ``I really wasn't speaking English first of all,''
Zhitnik said. ``It was probably a lot of hell for him. I can say he
probably babysit me once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhitnik, who is from the Ukraine, reminisced about eating
Ukrainian meals in Edmonton at Sydor's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``His grandparents speak Ukrainian pretty good,'' Zhitnik said.
</P>
<P>
   The friends were not defensive partners with the Kings, but
shared plenty of ice-time in Melrose's four-man defensive rotation
that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were unbelievable,'' Melrose said. ``We would have never
gotten to the finals without Zhitnik and Sydor.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor and Zhitnik differ in their defensive styles, however.
Sydor, who has two goals and nine assists in the playoffs, is a
battler, Melrose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loves to play in pressure situations,'' Melrose said. ``He
wants to be the guy with the puck, that's what leaders do. He's
somebody you're proud of every night; he never lets you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhitnik, who has three goals and nine assists, bears more
resemblance to a Sergei Zubov-type defenseman with more grit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the best skaters in the world,'' Melrose said.
``He could put up huge offensive numbers on the right team. I'm
talking 20 goals and 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he is very, very brave. Right from the start, he was going
head-to-head against these big Canadian forwards and not giving an
inch.''
</P>
<P>
   While the two spent a little time together at the All-Star game
this year, Zhitnik said he hoped there would be time to reunite
with his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``East and West is kind of far away to keep in touch,'' Zhitnik
said.
</P>
<P>
   At least the two are now on the same planet. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
