<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GAINEY-TEX     06-08 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GAINEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM GAINEY HAS BUILT THE STARS IN HIS IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Bob Gainey's finger twitched for a moment. He
wanted to react to what he thought was a bad call, he wanted to
find justice, the same way he did in his playing days with the
Montreal Canadiens _ with a covert elbow or a deftly turned stick
to the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't. The Stars general manager sat still after his
team had a crucial Pat Verbeek goal disallowed in Game 2 of the
Western Conference finals. Gainey didn't rush to the replay booth
to voice his opinion. He didn't demand to get NHL commissioner Gary
Bettman on the telephone to ``save the integrity of the game,'' as
Colorado Avalanche general manager Pierre LaCroix had done when his
team was stung by a disallowed goal in Game 1 of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Gainey sat. And waited. And won.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk scored in the third period. So did Mike Modano.
The Stars took a hard-fought 4-2 victory in a game in which Gainey
believes his team deserved one more goal. So why didn't he rush to
the rescue of his players?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to score,'' he said with a wink.
</P>
<P>
   And with that, the general manager turned and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   In a few words, Gainey said it all. In a few words, he summed up
his control, his confidence, his belief in what he is doing. In a
few words, Gainey summed up the Stars organization. And he walked
away _ knowing that the real message was delivered in his stride,
not in his words.
</P>
<P>
   Crack the Stars open and they bleed Gainey's blood. Look for a
reason to explain why a team that three years ago missed the
playoffs is in the 1999 Stanley Cup Finals, and the fingers all
seem to point to Gainey. Yes, the money of owner Tom Hicks is
crucial. Yes, Ken Hitchcock's coaching style has been
indispensable. Yes, the talents of Mike Modano, Joe Nieuwendyk and
others win games on the ice. But the core of that success has been
in the organization since 1990, when a five-time Stanley Cup
champion and first-ballot Hall of Famer was plucked from a French
semipro league and named coach of the Minnesota North Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fabric of this organization, there are hundreds of
threads that weave back and forth,'' assistant coach Rick Wilson
said. ``But most of those threads have been touched by Bob
Gainey.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals is scheduled to begin at 7 p.m.
Tuesday at Reunion Arena. The Western Conference champion Stars
will play the Buffalo Sabres before 17,001 boisterous fans looking
for any extra advantage. They might want to turn an eye to the
press box, where Gainey will be quietly sitting, jotting down
notes, seemingly doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances couldn't be more wrong. Behind the scenes, Stars
center Guy Carbonneau praised Gainey's ability to adapt the lessons
of the Canadiens to a different kind of NHL. Stars defenseman Craig
Ludwig talks about Gainey's integrity as a general manager and his
ability to make the Stars a franchise ``where players really want
to play.'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher looks at the Stars'
victories in Games 6 and 7 against the Avalanche and cites his
team's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we could have come back in Game 6 or won Game 7
without character, and I think a lot of that has had to do with
Bob,'' Hatcher said. ``When he's signed guys or drafted guys or
traded for guys, he's looked for character players, and I think you
see that in this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey chuckles when people talk about his stoic appearance, his
calm hand. Hitchcock has calmed under Gainey's guidance, he's told.
Ed Belfour has found peace because of the Stars' no-panic
environment. They are calm, the theory goes, because Gainey is
calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I may show you that calm side,'' Gainey said. ``But
there are times I have to close the door and sit down and say to
myself, `What the heck am I doing here?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gainey did that at the trade deadline when he refused to panic
and sign a high-dollar rent-a-player while the Avalanche and
Detroit Red Wings went on spending sprees. Gainey said he wasn't
sure he was making the right decision. But he said his heart told
him to ``trust the players, trust what we had built.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the decision looks good. But as he always does, Gainey
paints his team in shades of gray and not black and white. In
truth, crediting Gainey with the transitions of Hitchcock and
Belfour is simple-minded. It takes away from the immense individual
accomplishments of the coach and goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Gainey is so important to the Stars. He doesn't
seem to get wrapped up in his own worth. He doesn't overemphasize
victories or losses. He looks at the good and the bad of each
situation and appreciates both.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bob is more than anything for the coaches and the players
and the whole organization, is he's big-picture,'' Hitchcock said.
``We might get caught up in the minutiae of the day, but Bob has a
way of looking through all of that. Bob has a great way of stepping
back from any situation and studying it from every angle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bob does for us is he has a way of never losing sight of
the goal.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
