<HEADER>
A7497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-LOUNGE-DINING-ART     06-08 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-LOUNGE-DINING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING REACHES FOR THE COMFORT ZONE: THE LOUNGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I was sitting on a plush velvet sofa, a low oval
coffee table before me, in a room with a low ceiling and dim random
lighting. It was no different from a living room, a very nice
living room, where I would have been happy just to sit and relax.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a restaurant, Soma Park on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   The server handed me a linen napkin and flatware, and I was
about to experience a whole new way of dining. Sitting on that
sofa, plate on my knees, just as I might eat at home, I lingered
over seared hamachi with braised artichokes and a melon
vinaigrette, and then roasted loin of veal with fava beans,
cosseted all the while by an attentive staff.
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange experience _ and a strangely addictive one.
Living room and kitchen had fused. I had a sophisticated meal and
impeccable service without any formality.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of casual dining that you might expect to find
in the East Village, not in the East 50s. But Soma Park is just one
of many restaurants, from downtown lounges to restaurants with
caviar service, packing in the sofas and cushy chairs for dining in
living room style. In a city where few apartments even have dining
rooms, finding ways to recreate the warmth of home has led even
luxurious dining spots like Daniel to start serving food in the
lounge area in the last month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Eating in these appealing spaces can sometimes be awkward and
tricky, but the food is often good, sometimes surprisingly so, with
smaller portions and lower prices than in the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific,'' said Susy Davidson, co-publisher of
the Briefing, a restaurant industry newsletter. ``I see it as being
American and wanting it all in blue jeans but I think it's also, `I
want it great and I want it on my terms.'''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, restaurant dining has lost much of its rigid
structure, becoming a malleable concept that can be sculptured into
any form the restaurateur wants. As diners yearned for better food
with less formality, restaurant designers began creating more
casual, often whimsical, dining spaces. Soon afterward, they began
serving small appetizers and eventually full meals at the bar.
Recreating home-like environments, then, is just a natural
evolution from eating at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the fast-paced times and people not sitting down for long
dinners, it allows for flexibility,'' said John Elliott Sime, the
owner of Sime &AMP; Mandel, a design firm in East Atlantic Beach that
designed Alaia, a new restaurant in Greenwich Village. Small groups
can have a more intimate setting, he said; people can come and go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real operative here is living room,'' Ms. Davidson said.
``A great number of younger Americans have grown up with
restaurants as their living room.''
</P>
<P>
   People use restaurants in many different ways. Some like to sit
alone and read while having a few small dishes. Others like to
bring in friends and entertain instead of doing it at home. Cushy
lounges simply welcome these alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   In the lounge at Daniel, for instance, people often reserve
small enclaves of gray sofas and rust-colored chairs at lunch for
birthday and anniversary parties. Why have a party at home when you
can indulge in a place that feels as relaxed as home but looks part
palazzo, part Park Avenue apartment?
</P>
<P>
   Many of these lounges make you feel like you're in a fantasy
living room that has the energy and fizz of a cocktail party. And
because you needn't _ and most times can't _ reserve in advance or
dress up, there is something deliciously indulgent about dining in
them.
</P>
<P>
   Show up at Firebird on Restaurant Row, for instance, and you are
immediately transported to the parlor of a wealthy family home in
Russia. There are gilt framed sofas, velvet divans, urns, busts and
yards of brocade. You can order off the regular menu, but it is the
perfect setting for zakuska, or small dishes, like beet and apple
salad and herring in sour cream with buckwheat blini. Waiters cover
the antique tables, which are held up by reed thin legs, with
linens and serve the blini in a covered silver dish. Vodka is
poured in chilled, elegant fluted glasses. You can sip and recline
and there is no expectation to order more or to turn the table.
</P>
<P>
   Le Colonial in midtown is more a place in which to hide.
Upstairs, the lounge is dim, lighted by a few lamps that shed a
soft yellow light and narrow shafts of sunlight that squeeze
through the front windows. Large palm-like plants enclose the small
plots of emerald green cushioned wicker sofas and chairs. It is a
place to sink in, smoke and graze on vibrant, bluntly flavored
dishes like grilled eggplant with basil or artichoke and crab salad
with rice crackers.
</P>
<P>
   The French-Vietnamese fare at Le Colonial, as with many ethnic
foods, lends itself to light eating and sharing at small tables. In
fact, restaurants like the pan-Asian Rain and the Turkish Pasha
have long maintained casual, lounge-like settings.
</P>
<P>
   Some lounges have less of a point of view. In the East Village,
the upstairs lounge at Velvet feels part coffeehouse, part
Victorian home, part bar. Heavy antique furniture is arranged in
what seems like three separate living rooms. There are magazine
racks, a long bar and a menu with no particular bent. There is
salmon tartare _ a two-level disk with salmon and shredded cucumber
_ and steak au poivre, as well as simple country dishes like a pure
pea soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to so many different places, so many different lounges
and the furniture is really, really ugly and uncomfortable,'' Louis
Donato, an owner of Velvet, said. ``I wanted more of a parlor
setting. People can come here for many different things.'' Eating,
drinking, even a game of chess, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although styles vary, the lounge concept is spreading like a
rumor. Several restaurants with comfortable lounge areas are
scheduled to open in the next few months. Coup, in the East
Village, is converting its basement room into a lounge with a
separate menu. The Landmark Club, a new restaurant on the Upper
East Side, has just opened up. And Southwest NY in the World
Financial Center is opening with a lounge outdoors. Yes, sofas on
the sidewalk, like in college.
</P>
<P>
   Lounge areas may appear to have less structure than a
restaurant, but most of these scattered sofas and tight groupings
of stools and benches are carefully set down. ``We were really more
concerned with conversations,'' Sime, who designed Alaia, said.
``We wanted almost a living room atmosphere where one group could
meld into another and it wouldn't be so rigid.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice of sofa is also important. ``You have to sink,'' John
Scotto, the owner of Soma Park, said. ``It can't be something
that's hard. When you sit in a couch it's a little sexy, it's a
little romantic.'' A comfortable sofa, he said, allows people to
let down their guard and relax. He chose small love seats for a
Venetian-style room in the front of the restaurant, and oversize
swivel chairs for the spacious French-style back room.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Donato, who furnished the lounge at Velvet with some of his own
living room furniture, said: ``Tables can sometimes be more a
barrier than anything else.'' The tables there, and in many
lounges, are often low, small or practically nonexistent. In the
tiny space upstairs at Savoy in SoHo, where there is no table,
servers prop the food directly on the sofa. In the salon at the
SoHo Grand Hotel, they've placed the dishes on any available
surface, including cushioned stools.
</P>
<P>
   Which presents a special challenge when you try to disassemble a
leg of roasted chicken. Though it may feel all right to hover over
your coffee table at home while you watch the evening news, trying
to do that and look good in a restaurant is another story. You need
either to learn to balance a plate in one hand and eat with the
other or to keep the plate level on your knees. If you're really
coordinated, you can also wield a glass of wine. You just might not
want to wear your best pair of pants.
</P>
<P>
   It is a skill worth acquiring, though, considering what great
food can be had in restaurant lounges. At Daniel, the lounge menu
offers a ``plateaux'' for two. The charcuterie arrives on one level
of a three-tiered plate stand with three tiny bowls of soup on top
_ pea, a capon curry gelee and asparagus _ and salads on the second
tier. A handful of charcuterie dishes like oxtail and foie gras
terrine and chicken ballottine are on the bottom plate.
</P>
<P>
   You can also order ``tastes,'' or half orders of appetizers,
full appetizers and main courses, all derived from the regular
restaurant menu. They are not cafe versions of the menu, but Daniel
in jeans, you could say.
</P>
<P>
   You can just drop in and have a sommelier on your left offering
suggestions, a waiter on your right setting down a plate of
fabulous little flavors, and under you a beautifully designed sofa.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't even have to sit up straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
