<HEADLINE>
RANGERS MANAGER SHUFFLES ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Right-hander Rick Helling, the only member of the
Texas Rangers' rotation with an earned-run average better than
5.00, could gain an additional start before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates made that a possibility Monday by
scheduling Helling (5-6, 4.81) to start Friday's game against the
Colorado Rockies at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will skip right-hander Ryan Glynn (0-0, 8.66)
through the rotation this time in order for Helling to start
Friday, when the Rangers begin a stretch of 20 games scheduled for
20 days. Helling will be required to pitch once with three days
rest this month to gain a seventh start before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to give a guy an extra start,'' Oates said,
``he should be the one to get it.'' MORGAN SET TO RETURN
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan to reinstate right-hander Mike Morgan
(inflammation, right leg) from the 15-day disabled list for his
scheduled start tonight against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan experienced no significant difficulties during his
20-minute bullpen session Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good again,'' Morgan said. ``I don't have the pain. I'm
not 100 percent, but I'll be fine as long as I can push off the
rubber, cover first base and back up home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Danny Kolb, whom the Rangers recalled Wednesday
from Triple-A Oklahoma, likely will be optioned to Oklahoma to make
room for Morgan on the 25-man roster. UN-CLEMENS-LIKE
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Roger Clemens lost for the first time since May 19,
1998, with the Yankees' 7-2 loss Sunday to the Mets. Sixteen
pitchers have lost at least once while pitching for the Rangers
during Clemens' 20-game winning streak. The list includes: Pitcher
Losses Aaron Sele 13 John Burkett 12 Rick Helling 12 Xavier
Hernandez 6 Esteban Loaiza 6 Mark Clark 4 Mike Morgan 4 Danny
Patterson 4 Todd Stottlemyre 4 Eric Gunderson 3 Darren Oliver 3
Matt Perisho 2 Todd Van Poppel 2 John Wetteland 2 Bobby Witt 2 Tim
Crabtree 1 while pitching for the Rangers
MORE DRAFTEES SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers on Monday agreed to terms with three players
selected during last week's 1999 First-Year Player Draft and one
undrafted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Among those included their third-round selection, infielder Hank
Blalock of Rancho Bernardo (Calif.) High School. The Rangers also
agreed to terms with Shippensburg State University right-hander
Victor Hillaert and Kennesaw State University outfielder Jason
Jones, their fifth- and 13th-round selections, respectively. The
Rangers also signed University of Alabama-Huntsville left-hander
Jamie Hill, an undrafted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers assigned Blalock, Hillaert and Hill to their
rookie-league affiliate in the Gulf Coast League. Jones will report
to Pulaski, the Rangers' rookie-league affiliate in the Appalachian
League. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan for left-hander Eric Gunderson to begin his
medical rehabilitation assignment Wednesday with Triple-A Oklahoma.
The Rangers placed Gunderson (0-0, 7.20) on the 15-day disabled
list May 9 with partial tears of the rotator cuff and labrum in his
left shoulder. Gunderson's rehabilitation assignment can be no
longer than 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   A limited number of seats remain for the Conversation with Hank
Aaron, scheduled for 1 p.m. Saturday at the Legends of the Game
Baseball Museum at The Ballpark in Arlington. Admission is free,
but interested parties should call (817) 273-5600 for seating
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers announced that their Aug. 12 game against the
Detroit Tigers at The Ballpark in Arlington has been rescheduled
for 6:05 p.m. instead of 7:35 p.m. The change was made to
accommodate a FOX Sports Net national broadcast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers placed right-hander Derrick Cook of Double-A Tulsa
on the disabled list with inflammation in his right shoulder. The
Rangers promoted right-hander Matt Miller from Class-A Charlotte to
replace Cook on the Drillers' roster.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
