<HEADER>
A7501 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SATAN-TEX     06-08 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SATAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISTAKEN IDENTITY: SABRES' SATAN WICKED IN HOCKEY DEEDS ONLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dixon Ward remembers looking into a crowd Marine
Midland Arena in Buffalo and seeing a sign that said: ``Thank God
for Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not that Satan.
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Satan, Buffalo's leading scorer thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ``SHUH-tan'','' he corrected, emphasizing the ``sh''
sound that folks back in Topolcany, Slovakia, use when saying his
name.
</P>
<P>
   Satan used to be known as the guy with the name. Now, he has
become a guy that managed to score 40 regular-season goals for a
Sabres bunch not usually known for scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Satan brings his show to the Bible Belt when Stanley Cup Finals
play begins with Game 1 at 7 p.m. Tuesday at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel bad if this is the first time you've heard of the
stick-wielding, not pitchfork-wielding, Satan. Unlike the horned
fellow from down below with whom he shares a name, Miroslav Satan
has had a little trouble developing a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was traded here, I was surprised with his stats,'' said
Sabres forward Joe Juneau, a March addition for Buffalo. ``You
don't hear about the guy all year, and then you are on his team and
you realize he's scoring like 40 goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Satan had personal bests in goals (40) and assists (26) this
season, and his totals were far and away better than any of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   He looked to be ready to continue his work in the playoffs until
a bruised ankle sidelined him in Game 3 of Buffalo's opening-round
series against Ottawa. He had a pair of goals and an assist despite
only playing in two and a half games that series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that if he had been healthy from Day 1,
he'd be leading our team in scoring,'' Sabres defenseman Jason
Woolley said.
</P>
<P>
   Woolley instead has taken on that role, although, Satan's
gaining on him fast. In his first game back, Game 3 against Toronto
in the Eastern Conference finals, Satan had a goal. He has since
added three assists.
</P>
<P>
   And now the sign reads, Satan's back.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Satan has seen them all, heard all of the jokes, the Prince
of Darkness references, the suggestions that he'd be a perfect fit
with the New Jersey Devils, the long pauses when he orders a plane
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   He laughs, saying he finds most of it amusing.
</P>
<P>
   Satan admits he had little idea of what awaited him when he came
from Slovakia. He says ``cert'' not Satan is the word for the devil
back home. So what's the big deal, he thought?
</P>
<P>
   Then, he attempted to order a pizza.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me: `Is this really your name?''' Satan said. ``All I
can say is that's the way it is. ... Now, I don't give last name
when I order pizza, just first name.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first signed with Edmonton, Oilers officials politely
suggested a spelling change. Maybe add an H, they suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a different name for me,'' Satan said. ``In my
language, I would read it with an `H' and it would be a different
word. I didn't want to change.''
</P>
<P>
   What's in a name anyway?
</P>
<P>
   The Satan the Sabres know and love is described as ``quiet,''
``unassuming'' even ``goofy.'' Buffalo winger Dixon Ward said they
don't even make jokes any more in the locker room. There is no
``Saturday Night Live'' _ like wonderings of: Could it be Satan?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too obvious,'' Ward said. ``We don't tease him
because he never says anything. We barely even know he's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be Satan is just quietly going about his business?
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what he does on the ice,'' Ward said. ``The rest of
the league may not. He's not in the press a lot. He's a very quiet
guy. He's very unassuming. ... That's his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I guess, we're all Satan worshipers.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
