<HEADLINE>
RAY ADJUSTS GOALS AFTER WEAK FINISHES
</HEADLINE>
 RAY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Texan Greg Ray began the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League season with a realistic set of goals: four victories
and the driver's championship.
</P>
<P>
   But a string of three consecutive 21st-place finishes _
punctuated by the pit mishap that ended his day while leading the
Indianapolis 500 _ have prompted Ray to redefine his outlook for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what drives me is the highest of highs,'' said Ray,
the Plano, Texas, resident who is in his first full IRL season and
first with Team Menard. ``I'm not going to climb Mount Everest
every morning. We have realistic goals. But we're certainly running
out of ways that you can't win. We have to win and win in a hurry.
We're in a desperation mode as far as the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray heads into Thursday night's qualifying session for the
Longhorn 500 at Texas Motor Speedway tied with Stephan Gregoire for
20th in driver points at 34. That is 81 behind leader Jeff Ward
with seven races remaining. Ray admittedly began the season in a
conservative mode _ partly in deference to car owner John Menard
and the organization that won the 1997 IRL championship with Tony
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose that if you finish five or six races in a row and
win 'em all, there's potential there to catapult yourself into the
lead,'' said Ray, who is winless in 17 career IRL starts. ``But I
can forget about this conservative stuff. That probably fits my
personality better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said the 1.5-mile TMS quad-oval, with its 24-degree banked
turns, also is better suited to his all-out driving style.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of tracks fit me like a glove. These tracks are
made for gladiators,'' said Ray, 32, whose day at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway ended when he inadvertently drove into the side of
Mark Dismore's car while exiting pit road on Lap 120. ``It was
nobody's fault but my own. It was just heartbreaking to have
something so silly like that happen. That incident took me from
achieving a childhood dream. But I'm still young enough and hungry
enough to know I can use that for experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving his own car and working with team manager Thomas Knapp
at TMS last June 6, Ray battled pole-winner Billy Boat nose-to-tail
and side-by-side in the closing laps en route to a career-best
second-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole race was fast and furious,'' said Ray, who finished
0.928 seconds behind Boat after 208 laps. ``I had a lot of friends
and family in the stands and there was a lot of commotion on Lap
200 because people thought the race was 200 laps. And I was leading
at 200 laps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he dutifully has readjusted his goals after each
nonvictory this season. Winning at TMS on Saturday night would make
his wait much easier to justify.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track has been kind to me,'' said Ray, who is $47,000
short of reaching $1 million in earnings for his IRL career. ``When
I drive into the racetrack, people wave at me and honk at me. I'm
not the Dallas Cowboys, but I'm the local racer. We've had a lot of
well-wishers from the Internet to telephone calls and notes with my
kids from school and at church. It's exciting. It feels like a
community event.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
