</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BE TELLING STARS THEIR WAY ISN'T RIGHT ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ We come to you today, O' Great and Magnificent
Guardians of the mighty National Hockey League, with 10-gallon
Stetsons in hand. Forgive us, we beseech you, for having the brass
to crash saintly Lord Stanley's party.
</P>
<P>
   We promise not to spike the punch or puke in your shiny silver
chalice. Well, at least not before the Dallas Stars win it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   After that, we'll do what we damn well please.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, we've come to the dance in our faded Wranglers and
scuffed-up Justins but don't go sticking your noses in the air and
acting like you're not counting on Fort Worth-Dallas to carry your
royal Canadian behinds in the TV ratings. We know better.
</P>
<P>
   And that baloney about the Stars giving the NHL a black eye
because they take the air out of the puck? You can take that and
stick it ... well, I suppose Brett Hull has already mapped that
geographic route out for you eloquently enough.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL came to Texas sporting that same shiner six years ago.
You want more offense in your league? Lower the pitching mound and
juice the puck. It's worked wonders for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, shut up and let Bob Gainey and Ken Hitchcock take
care of the hockey bidness around here. They seem to know a little
bit about it, having disposed of the league's pet team, the
Colorado Avalanche, which in turn had done a number on the two-time
defending champion Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have done what any team and any coach should do:
Figured out how to win with their personnel. Sure, maybe Mike
Modano could be the next Wayne Gretzky in another system. Why don't
you ask him, right now, if he'd trade his chance at that big shiny
cup for that ``maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many inches to fill in their columns,'' Gainey grumbled
Monday about the so-called experts who have tried to make the Stars
the villains of these playoffs. ``This happens every year with
every team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the first pick in the draft. When he's marked, 18
months before as the No. 1 guy, by the time he gets to draft day
he's got a lot of problems because you've had 18 months to pick him
apart and find out what his problems are. We all have them and our
team has them but we play with what we've got and we do it pretty
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock, in fact, came to the Stars with an
offensive resume. His last junior team averaged ``seven'' goals per
game. His K-Wings would run-and-gun with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really arrogant and made a big mistake when I first came
here,'' Hitchcock said. ``I put my system in for this team and we
couldn't play it. We were smaller and quicker at Kalamazoo and we
could afford to gamble a little more and I put that system in place
when I got here and we got burned a lot in the first half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I changed to a system closer to what Bob had and somewhere
between the two systems we've reached a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The change, Hitch said, was dictated by the personnel he had at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to play a more aggressive system but you need
footspeed to play more aggressive, so based on our personnel,
that's the way we play,'' he said. ``The philosophy is more
five-pack, almost like wolves, mentality. We're either all up
together or all back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to play, in a zone, very tight together, and we don't
have any space between the forwards and the defensemen. We want to
take the middle of the ice away, make them play east-west and don't
allow them to come north-south. We want to take away half the ice.
They want to play on 80 feet; we give them 40.''
</P>
<P>
   And please, before you accuse of the Stars of playing a boring,
``trap'' defense, you should have some clue what you're talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there are 10 hockey writers who really know what
the trap is,'' Hitchcock said, ``but we don't play it. We play a
1-2-2 forecheck. There's only one team left in the league who plays
a 2-1-2 forecheck and that's Edmonton. Some teams play a `high'
1-2-2, which is the trap, and some people play the `low' and we
play the `low,' just like Buffalo does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get offended when people say that because we protect the
lead well, because we play well without the puck, that somehow
we're a disappointment to the league. As a coach, I don't tell my
players how to play with the puck. They know how to play with the
puck. I tell them how to play without the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's'' what sets the Stars apart from most teams in this
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's Brett Hull or Mike Modano, there are
certain rules to playing without the puck,'' Hitchcock said. ``When
you don't have discipline without the puck, it's like telling your
defensive team in the NFL that the other team has the ball so go
wherever you want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or (in baseball) it's like telling your three outfielders to
stand where they want. To me, that's what makes a coach in the
National Hockey League _ how you get your team to play without the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   That's our coach. He's not a sleek former NHL star, like some
others are and he has a little weight problem. It's part of his
charm. Any day now Ty will issue the official Ken Hitchcock Beanie
Baby.
</P>
<P>
   He took the family dog for a walk the other day and it, well, to
put it bluntly, peed on his foot.
</P>
<P>
   He gets no respect, but he has promised to change his socks
before taking his spot behind the Stars bench Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   We like him _ and his system _ because he wins and, as has been
well documented, this is a winner's town.
</P>
<P>
   Relax. Have a chicken-fried steak or some barbecue while you're
here. Or some real bacon _ we know the difference between bacon and
ham _ with your eggs.
</P>
<P>
   We're still a little rough around the edges on this hockey thing
but you might has well learn to live with us, guys.
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, we're here to stay. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
