<HEADLINE>
TATTOOS, NOSE STUDS A LITTLE TOO EDGY FOR BARBIE AND GANG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CINNAMON BAIR   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ She meant to appear avant garde.
</P>
<P>
   The giant butterfly tattoo on her tiny midriff represented the
height of fashion for today's teens and young adults. All her
friends had butterfly tattoos, even her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Butterfly Art Barbie'' just didn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   So the first Barbie doll to sport a permanent tattoo has been
taken out of production by Mattel due to parental outcry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just had some consumers who didn't like it,'' said Lisa
McKendall, director of communications for Mattel. ``We always want
to try and be responsive to our dolls' audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, many of whom bristle at the thought of their teen-agers
getting tattoos and piercings, didn't appreciate it when their
little girls' best-loved doll, and her doll friends like Ken,
decided to sport body art.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbie dolls _ maligned for years for their outrageous body
proportions _ were again sending the wrong message about the human
body to children, said parents and critics alike. She seemed to be
saying girls couldn't be pretty, cool or accepted unless they
decorated their bodies in some way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pierced ears and tattoos and so forth: They are not part of
what children understand. They shouldn't be a part of childhood,''
said Dr. Albert Eskenazi, a psychologist in Lakeland. ``To me,
there's a message there that says, `Kid, as soon as you can, be
like that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Butterfly Art Barbies,'' released earlier this year, were
meant to be the start of a trend for the 11 1/2-inch doll. At the
1998 Toy Fair in New York City, Mattel debuted prototypes for a new
Barbie doll and friends that featured tattoos, triple-pierced ears
and nose studs.
</P>
<P>
   The new line, titled ``Generation Girl Barbie'' and released
this spring, was eventually toned down to include a tiny red and
blue tattoo on Barbie's ankle and a nose stud on her British buddy,
Chelsie.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the parental criticism, however, Mattel has
performed plastic surgery on the dolls to remove the tattoos and
piercings, Kendall said. No future ``Tattoo Barbies'' are planned,
Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel initially wanted to include tattoos and temporary tattoos
in its Barbie line ``because kids love them,'' Kendall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just meant to be fun and something little girls like,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And tattoos as toys are nothing new. Cracker Jack boxes have
included temporary tattoos as prizes for years. Hasbro debuted
``Action Man Tiger Stripe,'' a GI Joe doll with a large tiger
tattoo covering his chest, in 1995. The problem isn't with the toys
themselves, but with the culture that promotes them, Eskenazi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any particular type of game or toy that
in and of itself influences a child,'' he said. ``If you get a
perfectly healthy child in a perfectly healthy environment, there's
probably not much influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not everyone sees tattooed Barbies as a bad thing.
Just as a traditional Barbie might send a message of unearthly
proportional perfection and conformity, a Barbie with a tattoo lets
kids know it's OK to be different, said Lee Brook, a tattoo artist
at Lou's National Tattoos in Lakeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's about time Barbie got a little risky,'' he said.
``She was too pretty. They needed to bring her down to earth a
little.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the tattooed dolls also acknowledge that different
families have different ideas of what is ``normal,'' Brook said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
