<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTS WHO DIDN'T CARRY THE POPULAR VOTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Which presidents, if any, were elected by the Electoral
College but failed to carry the plurality of the popular vote?
</P>
<P>
   _J.R.B., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Three presidents were elected despite trailing another
candidate in the popular vote: John Quincy Adams in 1824,
Rutherford B. Hayes in 1876 and Benjamin Harrison in 1888.
</P>
<P>
   Adams received 50,000 fewer votes than Andrew Jackson in an
election in which each of four candidates won the popular vote of
one state. Because no candidate received a majority of electoral
votes, the House of Representatives chose the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes received 4,033,950 votes, 250,000 fewer than Samuel
Tilden, and Harrison received 5,444,337 votes, trailing Grover
Cleveland by 95,000.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents are elected by the Electoral College, not the popular
vote. A narrow win in a large state usually gives a candidate all
of its electors, and this can overcome larger losses in several
smaller states with fewer electors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathematicians calculate that there is a one-in-two chance
that a very close election (like 1960) will elect a president that
has lost in the popular vote,'' Michael Young of the Center for
Survey Research wrote last year in USA Today Magazine. ``It is a
ticking time bomb that sooner or later will go off.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm a longtime listener of Paul Harvey. Where can I write to
him?
</P>
<P>
   _J.T.L., Azle, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to him in care of Paul Harvey News, 333 N. Michigan
Ave., Chicago 60601.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, who has an audience of 19 million listeners on 1,600
radio stations, has been broadcasting his daily news program for
ABC Radio Networks since 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-old broadcaster has been working in radio since
1933, when KVOO of Tulsa hired him at age 14.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What happened to ``Legacy''?
</P>
<P>
   _C.G., Stephenville, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: UPN canceled the series in May along with ``America's
Greatest Pets,'' ``Clueless,'' ``DiResta'' and ``Love Boat: The
Next Wave.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``Keep `Legacy''' fan effort is encouraging fans to tell
producers they will follow the show to another network. The
suggested address for these letters is Peter Sussman, Alliance
Atlantis Communications, 808 Wilshire Blvd., Third Floor, Santa
Monica, CA 90401.
</P>
<P>
   The group has a Web site at
www.geocities.com/~loganslegacy/keep.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
