<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-FULLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASSICAL CAREER WASN'T IN THE CARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It was supposed to be a summer job: Move to
Tahoe, deal cards and take some time off before pursuing a Ph.D. in
piano.
</P>
<P>
   Then Allan Fuller's life took an unexpected turn. He loved the
casino: the intrigue, the characters, the structure and security of
working for a big company.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades have passed since Fuller graduated from Central
Washington University with a master's degree in piano performance
and went to work for Harrah's, first in Lake Tahoe, then in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   He's a manager now, director of table games, to be exact. But
his acceptance to the Cliburn Competition for Outstanding Amateurs
proves that he's kept his fingers limber.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the dichotomy is striking. Classical pianist. Casino
manager. It makes you wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller's professor at CWU says he was the most talented, focused
student she has seen at the school in 26 years of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Allan) announced that he and his wife were going to be
card dealers in Tahoe, I nearly fainted,'' says Professor Bonalyn
Bricker-Smith. ``I thought, `What is he doing? He should be getting
a doctorate and teaching at the college level.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once at Harrah's, Fuller learned to deal cards correctly so he
wouldn't ruin his hands. That obstacle aside, he's managed to
balance both a fulfilling career and a consuming passion for music.
</P>
<P>
   He started playing piano at 6. His mother, a full-time piano
teacher, had bought a recording of Bach's Two-Part Inventions.
Allan seemed drawn to it, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put it on every chance he got,'' Georgette Fuller recalls.
Out of the blue, Allan started picking out the right-hand part of
Invention No. 8, sounding it out like the music was written down in
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Georgette Fuller quickly added her son to her roster of
students, which included her older child, Richard. Eight years
Allan's senior, Richard Fuller is a successful fortepianist in
Vienna and is considered a Mozart expert.
</P>
<P>
   When the boys were young, the Fuller home, near Wenatchee,
Wash., was filled with music: ``It was a wonderful environment to
grow up in,'' Fuller notes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Fuller says his interest in classical piano waned
during his teen-age years. He wanted to play rock 'n' roll. His
teacher during those formative years, Stella Knoebel, was very
traditional. She had studied with Russian pianist Josef Lhevinne,
whose wife, Rosina, taught Van Cliburn at the Juilliard School of
Music.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 18, something clicked. To his mother's surprise,
pursuing classical piano became his goal. He entered Whitworth
College in Spokane, Wash., and received a full scholarship to the
University of Oregon for a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon didn't feel right, though, so Fuller returned to
Washington to finish his master's at CWU.
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way from the early days when his mom says she
could hardly stand to listen. The piano ``was this great big wild
animal that he was going to tame,'' Georgette says, ``and he had a
terrible touch.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 20 years, Fuller has continued to study and perform
recitals. He taught for a year at the University of Nevada-Reno, in
between training new blackjack dealers. He practices two to three
hours a day, even when there isn't a competition looming.
</P>
<P>
   In his younger years, Fuller, 43, favored the forceful,
virtuosic compositions of Beethoven and Liszt. There came a point,
though, where he started to feel like a musical assembly line:
learn a program, play it in recital, put it away, start all over
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to initiate my own self-improvement program and not
to play in public for a while,'' he explains. He listened to and
read every piece of music he could get his hands on. He studied the
repertoire and zeroed in on his musical goals. Now he thrills at
the challenge of putting together a recital that creates ``a
flow,'' that meets the audience's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really intrigued by the notion of programming and how
pieces fit together,'' he says. ``It's just constantly fascinating
to me how much beautiful music there is.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Fuller returned to his hometown to perform a recital, an
event that made him more nervous than even the Fort Worth
competition does. After all, people he knew were in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Allan ``has realized, as he's gone farther into his career, that
(piano) is not only a joy, but a release,'' says Georgette. ``It
has a steadying impact on his life.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
