<SLUG> BC-TAXIS-CAMERAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY PANEL RECOMMENDS CAMERAS IN TAXIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Taxis here may soon be equipped with small
infrared digital cameras that photograph drivers and their
passengers under a safety plan to be considered by the San
Francisco Taxicab Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``A security camera in a tamper-proof box gives a measure of
protection to both driver and passenger,'' said Jane Bolig, a
member of the task force advising the Taxicab Commission on safety.
``I think that just the presence of the cameras will discourage
violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The police also see some benefits. ``It could discourage people
from doing things illegal or harmful if they knew there was a
camera there,'' said Dewayne Tully, a spokesman for the Police
Department, which neither endorsed nor opposed the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers who were told of the idea on Monday said they
worried about a loss of privacy, for themselves and their
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras are one of many ideas being considered to make
drivers and passengers feel safer about riding a cab in San
Francisco. Both taxi drivers and many prospective passengers have
been unnerved by recent high-profile homicides in which cabbies
have either been victims or, in one case last month, a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Other safety suggestions include an emergency 911 switch in each
cab that can be activated by either the driver or the passenger,
and increased safety training and background screening for drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department is studying how many times cab drivers are
either victims or suspects in crimes. The police said the
preliminary data back up the widespread belief in the industry that
driving a taxi is a dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a lot more likely to be victims,'' said Sgt. Vincent
Simpson, who is overseeing the study. ``It's one of the most
dangerous jobs that you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, taxi drivers are more likely to become victims of
workplace homicides than other workers, ranking well ahead of
retail store clerks and police officers, according to studies by
the National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   Three San Francisco taxi drivers have been killed on duty in the
past 18 months. None of the cases has been solved. The police
believe robbery was the motive in each case.
</P>
<P>
   But when a taxi driver allegedly raped and killed a 24-year-old
woman after picking her up outside a trendy Financial District
champagne bar on May 14, the focus shifted to include passenger
safety as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bolig, a taxi driver for the past 25 years who also sits on the
seven-member Taxicab Commission, said that digital cameras the size
of cigarette packs may be the most promising options. She said
that, if bought in bulk, cameras would cost only about $500 each
and could easily be installed in the cabs and mounted on the
rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be the fastest thing and probably the most cost
effective too,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
