<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HORSE FOUNTAIN IN DOWNTOWN FORT WORTH CALLS TO MIND TALES OF
THE OLD ONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fort Worth is in the middle of a birthday
party.
</P>
<P>
   There have been sesquicentennial fireworks and music _ ranging
from Motown to cattle calls. Remembering Fort Worth's past has been
the focus; rediscovering the people and places that made the city a
success has been the goal.
</P>
<P>
   That goal has been accomplished mostly in the smaller events.
Events like the dedication of a new flagpole or the unveiling of
the new horse fountain at the Tarrant County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Under the spreading mesquite tree at the corner of Commerce and
Weatherford streets, hundreds of visitors endured a stinging
noonday sun to see a new fountain emerge where the old one once
stood. The city doesn't need a new fountain to water its horses. It
just wanted one. There were some good tales told about the old
fountain, and Fort Worth loves old tales.
</P>
<P>
   The original fountain was put there in 1892 by The Woman's
Humane Association. It was one of six such fountains spread around
town. The only other places where horses could be watered at the
time were the livery stables, and they charged for their water. A
lot of horses went without refreshment before the fountains were
installed.
</P>
<P>
   The fountain was a noble cause, but not so noble that a few
drunken cowboys didn't try to climb up on it and ride the horse on
top. There are no records as to how many cowboys came crashing down
in the wet troughs below, but we do know that one finally managed
to break the horse's tail off and it had to be re-attached.
</P>
<P>
   No telling what the cowboy broke.
</P>
<P>
   Drunken cowboys were a part of Fort Worth history. So were bad
drivers, and one crashed into the base of the fountain in the
1940s, and the whole thing had to be dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   That could have been the end of the fountain. Certainly by the
1940s there weren't many horses wandering around downtown. But
people in Fort Worth embrace their past, and because the watering
hole was a popular place in the city's history, they wanted it
back.
</P>
<P>
   Kids sent their pennies, fees were levied and a benefactor _
Melissa Gordon _ gave thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Coburn made sure the horse that endured so many
light-headed cowboys was saved.
</P>
<P>
   The horse, rumors said, had been sighted at a Colleyville
racetrack, then a funeral home, then a downtown western wear store.
The rumors weren't far off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around the late 1950s or early '60s, Mother went into Otha
Tiner's harness shop and Otha asked her if she wanted to see a
little pony,'' Jerrell Coburn remembered. ``It was the pony from
the original fountain. Mr. Lucas, from Lucas Funeral Home, had
taken it and put it on his barn. It was blown down in a storm.''
</P>
<P>
   The pony was in pieces, but Coburn and Tiner put it back
together and took it to a foundry, where a cast was made and four
more ponies were manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   The Coburns gave one to Tarrant County so that one day it could
rest atop the fountain again.
</P>
<P>
   ``About every 10 years, somebody would say they discovered the
little horse,'' Coburn said. At the dedication of the new fountain,
several people talked about rediscovering the little horse in the
dark basement of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always around,'' Coburn said. ``It never was
undiscovered.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: Artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1632EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-CARE09-COX     06-08 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-CARE09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH QUALITY DAY CARE HELPS STUDENTS FOR YEARS, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    540&AMP;add. With CHILD-CARE-TIPS. Moving in (w) Washington and (l)
lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A child's benefits from care at a high-quality
pre-school center last at least three to four years, according to a
federally funded study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings added weight to reformers' arguments for higher
government spending on day care, more training for providers and
stricter monitoring of the quality of day care.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many previous reports on day care, the study covered
children from many backgrounds, ranging from very rich to very
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from four major universities evaluated a random
sample of classrooms in 401 private and public day care centers in
four states in 1993 and 1994. The study compared how children from
top-rated centers compared with those from lowest-rated centers in
1997, at the end of second grade.
</P>
<P>
   Those who had attended the best-rated centers were doing
measurably better than those from the worst-rated centers in math,
understanding spoken language, paying attention and getting along
with other children. But there was no significant difference in
reading skills, which seemed to depend more on the quality of their
education in first and second grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most areas of development that we examined, there was
evidence of a modest continued influence of child care quality on
children's abilities and skills through second grade,'' concluded
the researchers from the University of North Carolina, the
University of Colorado, Yale University and the University of
California Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we can say about 60 percent of children (from) very
high-quality child care were achieving well as second graders and
only 40 percent of children (from) low-quality centers were
achieving well,'' said UCLA Professor Carrollee (cq) Howes, one of
the principal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The boost from high quality care was even stronger among those
who needed early help the most _ boys and girls whose mothers had
little or no education.
</P>
<P>
   ``While heightened public awareness (from such studies) is a
plus, our progress has been far too limited,'' said Education
Secretary Richard Reilly. ``The number of quality child care
facilities that meet high standards and offer employees a livable
wage remains woefully inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for more federal funding for day care and asked states
to imitate ``the progressive efforts'' in Georgia and North
Carolina, which he said ``capitalize on some of the latest
information available'' on how to educate children in their
earliest years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Former Georgia Gov. Zell(cq) Miller launched an effort that
will make his state the first in the nation to offer universal
pre-K classes for 4-year-olds,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Jim Hunt's Smart Start initiative in North Carolina
covers a range of early childhood services, but focuses primarily
on the quality of child care, making it more affordable and making
it more available,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was particularly impressed by North Carolina's plans
to start a rating system this summer. To help parents find high
quality centers, state licenses for child care centers will include
one to five stars, with five stars awarded to centers with the
highest quality ratings.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding quality child care is one of the most difficult and
emotional tasks facing working parents across America,'' he said.
Too often, working parents, whether long employed or recently off
the welfare rolls, ``cannot find child care that is both affordable
and high quality,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Howes offered three rules of thumb for parents: The best centers
almost always have no more than 10 children per adult, teachers
with college degrees and teachers with salaries near to those for
beginning teachers in nearby public schools.
</P>
<P>
   About 6.8 million pre-schoolers, including three-quarters of
those aged three to five, are receiving some sort of day care,
according to Richard Clifford, a co-director of the study from the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
