<HEADER>
A7532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0609-COX     06-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVAR REBELS PLEDGE NOT TO SHOOT AS YUGOSLAV FORCES WITHDRAW
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0609.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Rebels fighting for the independence of Kosovo
pledged Tuesday to hold their fire on Serb-led Yugoslav forces if
they begin to withdraw as part of a NATO-approved peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo Liberation Army will neither raise obstacles nor
attack Serb military units if and when they withdraw,'' Bajram
Kosumi, the minister of information for the Provisional Government
of Kosovo, said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA also said it would lay down its weapons once it judges
that the threat posed by the Yugoslav military and Serb police is
gone. ``The KLA will be disarmed when there is no longer the need
to keep the guns,'' Kosumi said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders have been seeking assurances from the rebel army,
which claims to have more than 15,000 soldiers inside Kosovo
province, that it will cease its campaign once a peace deal is
concluded. The Provisional Government of Kosovo is headed by Hashim
Thaci, the leader of the KLA's political wing.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci and Ibrahim Rugova, Thaci's rival for the Kosovan
leadership, and Rexhep Qosja, an influential Kosovar Albanian
nationalist, also met with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright Tuesday as she sought assurances that they would not try
to disrupt a swift Yugoslav military withdrawal. Serb officials in
Belgrade stressed there could be no ``security vacuum'' opening up
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pledges of cooperation, the Americans are keen to
promote consensus among the various Albanian factions, which are
bitterly divided. A vicious power struggle, mainly between Rugova
and Thaci, is expected to erupt in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   While the separatist leaders said they would accept NATO's
leadership, they expressed deep reservations about the use of
Russian troops as peacekeepers. ``Russian diplomacy has not shown
itself to be unbiased,'' Kosumi said. ``It's also a well-known fact
that many Russian officials have joined the Serb army.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, KLA units have been engaged in intense fighting
against Serb forces near the Yugoslavia border with Albania.
Casualties on both sides have been said to be heavy, but neither
has been willing to provide casualty figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a great number of KLA soldiers killed,'' Kosumi said.
``But the number of Serbs killed is many times more.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Serb artillery has pounded villages in northern
Albania, forcing thousands of residents to flee their homes. A
World Food Program official here said the agency was feeding 8,000
Albanian villagers and Kosovar refugees displaced by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   NATO warplanes have bombed Serb positions destroying several
pieces of artillery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to the acceptance of the peace plan by the
(Serb-dominated Yugoslav) Parliament, contrary to the first signals
of the war ending in Kosovo, the Belgrade regime has intensified
its military activities on all fronts inside Kosovo,'' Kosumi said.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused Serb forces of using chemical weapons in two
recent attacks within Kosovo, a province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA said chemical weapons were used on June 4, 5 and 6 in
the village of Dushka and in the Berisha mountains by Yugoslav
forces. If so, it would be a violation of international law.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has sent investigators to gather more information about
the incidents. An army spokesman said it had encountered victims
with medical symptoms of the chemicals as well as witnesses who had
seen the shells explode and emit clouds of vapor.
</P>
<P>
   International groups such as Amnesty International have reported
that the Yugoslav military has stockpiled chemical weapons
containing sarim, sulfur mustard and the agent, BZ.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The KLA also said they believe the Serbs may be stalling the
peace talks to buy time to hide evidence of atrocities by
transporting the bodies of slain ethnic Albanians to be buried
elsewhere or cremated. The KLA, which said it has videotapes and
photographs to support its
</P>
<P>
   allegations, also accused Serbs of using bulldozers to dig up
mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen trucks pulling trailers full of bodies away to be
individually buried or cremated,'' said Isa Blumi, the director of
the Kosova Press agency, which is affiliated with the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   There was no way to independently confirm these allegations.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the Pentagon have received such reports but have not
verified them, the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA said it has turned over its evidence to the
international war crimes tribunal at the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
