<HEADLINE>
SHEEP ACCOMPANY TEXAS FAMILY ON MORNING JOGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT FRAZIER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEYVILLE, Texas _ This is not your ordinary barnyard yarn.
</P>
<P>
   This is the ram-bunctious tale of the Smullin family, postmodern
shepherds who prefer city streets to hilly green pastures and
running shoes to the traditional 6-foot wood staff.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every morning for three years, they have enjoyed a jog
through their upscale neighborhood _ followed by sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's hysterical,'' neighbor Teresa McGaha said.
``We've gotten used to it. But it's funny when we have company
over. They look out the window and say, `Hey, there are sheep out
there!'''
</P>
<P>
   This woolly display began three years ago when the Smullins'
daughter, Christine, brought home rams _ Elmo and Grover _ as part
of a project at school. Students at Grapevine High School would
take home their animals, raise them and feed them, then sell them
at the end of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the students let their sheep exercise in pastures, on
a treadmill or lamb racetracks,'' said Christine Smullin, 18. ``We
took ours jogging. And they are a lot more energetic than my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sheep followed the family through the neighborhood, the
school projects became family pets. It made it difficult to give
them up at the end of the year when they, like most other rams,
were sold for slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Smullins couldn't bear the thought of their family pets
ending up as sliced mutton served next to piles of peas, carrots
and mint jelly, so last year they started taking home female sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sell them _ that was pretty tough,'' Christine Smullin
said. ``When you raise an animal for a year, you get attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we will breed sheep and sell them to the school.''
</P>
<P>
   The family now has two ewes, 2-year-old Peppermint and
1-year-old Snuffleupagus, who have been jogging since they were
tiny lambs. The sheep, who are kept in the back yard, learned the
proper exercise etiquette early and graduated from the leash.
</P>
<P>
   But they do sometimes lag behind the Smullins, sprint ahead,
stop to smell the shrubbery or stick their heads in the open car
windows of amazed passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they have muzzles on? Do they bite?'' the passers-by
sometime ask while petting the tops of the woolly heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never bite,'' the Smullins say. ``We have the muzzle so
they don't eat everyone's grass.''
</P>
<P>
   The cars pull away, and Peppermint and Snuffleupagus happily
continue their workout over curbless streets and past widely spaced
houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we are the silliest sight,'' said Lyn Smullin,
Christine's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Because Christine Smullin is heading to Baylor University this
fall with dreams of becoming an orthopedic surgeon, such sightings
might soon end. The family is planning to breed the sheep and sell
them to the school.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as planned, the bleat of newborn lambs should sound
in this Colleyville neighborhood in less than a year. When the
lambs are weaned, they, Peppermint and Snuffleupagus may disappear
forever from the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Lyn Smullin said.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the newly shorn Peppermint and Snuffleupagus will be
out jogging beneath the early morning sun every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we skip one day, the next morning they are frolicking and
hopping and jumping,'' Christine Smullin said. ``They miss it, and
they let you know it.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
