<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-VALDEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAIRDRESSER'S BRUSH WITH MUSICAL FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Juilliard's loss was hairstyling's gain.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Valdez, an outstanding senior-level piano student at the
University of Northern Colorado, knew exactly what he wanted to do
when he was turned down for graduate-level admission to the
prestigious Juilliard School in New York. Instead of selecting a
different conservatory, or trying Juilliard again, Valdez dropped
out of college and went to beauty school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 13 years ago,'' says Valdez, a hairdresser. ``I
haven't looked back.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdez, who turned 35 last week, loved the piano from an early
age while growing up in Boone, Colo. When he was 7, he begged his
older sister, who was already studying at college level, for
lessons. He immediately became one of those kids who takes it
seriously and is taken seriously by teachers and other adults. Like
any kid who plays the piano well in a small town, he played solo
recitals and frequently accompanied choirs and singers. After
graduating from high school, he entered the University of Northern
Colorado as a piano major.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught piano, and that was the turning point in his
career. A moment of truth came about midway through his college
years, while he was getting his hair cut at a salon owned by the
father of two of his young students. There, he noticed the
sociability and constant person-to-person contact of the
hair-styling profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pianist spends at least four hours a day alone with a
piano,'' he says. ``I wanted to be around people.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Valdez does now, usually working four 11-hour days
weekly at a locally owned chain of salons in the Denver suburbs.
It's on the other three days of the week that he puts in the heavy
practice, at home, at his 7-foot Steinway grand piano. He says his
practice time ranges from one to four hours daily, depending on his
anxiety level.
</P>
<P>
   He'll make his bid for recognition in round one in Fort Worth
with Chopin's Ballade in G minor, and hopes to advance through
round two with music of Mendelssohn, Prokofiev and J.S. Bach. Round
three allows for repetition from the earlier two rounds, and
Valdez's strategy, if he makes the finals, is to simply combine and
repeat the well-polished repertoire from the previous two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   After hair school, Valdez says he continued to play the piano,
though without the demands of a teacher, not quite as well. To meet
his continued desire for competition, he took up tennis, playing in
adult-league matchups.
</P>
<P>
   The chance to play piano in the amateur competition in Fort
Worth has encouraged Valdez to renew his practice habits, but not
obsessively. Indeed, in his determination to keep the rest of his
life going smoothly, he has decreased his practice time, making
sure to take time for friends and tennis. He also continues to keep
up his schedule as a volunteer, accompanying area school choirs and
performing at charity events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be balance in life,'' Valdez says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
