<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUN-BELTS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HUMAN RIGHTS GROUP CALLS FOR BAN ON 'STUN BELTS'
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amnesty International called Tuesday for a ban on
high-voltage ``stun belts'' in the criminal justice system, saying
their use on prisoners recalls the conduct exposed in the New York
police brutality trial.
</P>
<P>
   The battery-powered belts deliver 50,000 volts of electricity
for eight seconds at the touch of a remote-control button. They
cause temporary muscle paralysis, loss of control of bodily
functions and intense pain.
</P>
<P>
   More than 130 U.S. jurisdictions, have used the belt since its
introduction in the past few years, said William F. Schulz,
executive director of Amnesty International. This includes state
prisons in Florida, Georgia and Colorado, and some local systems in
Ohio and Texas, the group said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for a ban on the belt and suspension of other stun
technology pending a strict medical review, Schulz drew parallels
between the Abner Louima police brutality case in New York and
situations in which stun belts have been used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zapping a prisoner is no less cruel, inhuman or degrading than
sodomizing a suspect with a stick in a police station,'' he said.
``Even if it is state-of-the-art, it is torture nonetheless.''
</P>
<P>
   While beatings with nightsticks and other weapons can leave
noticeable marks, stun belt abuse amounts to ``torture without a
trace,'' Schulz said.
</P>
<P>
   Groups representing prisons and corrections officers had no
immediate response to the call for a ban.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International plans to ask Congress for a federal review
of the devices and has filed briefs in lawsuits been filed by
inmates against corrections systems where stun belts were used, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulz commended the U.S. Bureau of Prisons' policy prohibiting
the use of stun belts on pregnant women and inmates suffering from
epilepsy or heart conditions, but said a ban is still warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International has been joined by former heavyweight
boxing champion Muhammad Ali in an effort to raise public awareness
of the use and potential dangers of stun belts. His youngest
daughter, Laila Ali, spoke on his behalf on Wednesday and said she
supports the international campaign as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often the message gets across when someone we are familiar
with speaks out,'' said Laila Ali, who is training to be a boxer.
``That is sad, but whatever way we can get this message across is
good.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
