<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-HIBBARD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LITTLE PIANIST THAT COULD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ David Hibbard was 5 years old when he heard
Beethoven's ``Moonlight'' Sonata on the radio. He immediately loved
it, as have people of many generations before him.
</P>
<P>
   He begged his parents for piano lessons. By age 7, he was
studying with a teacher in his hometown of Peoria, Ill. Right away
he informed her that he wanted to play the ``Moonlight'' Sonata.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher found a simplified version for him fairly quickly.
He managed to get a copy of the more difficult original version on
his own, however, and taught it to himself on the sly _ struggling
with some of the stretches.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I learned the `Moonlight' Sonata, I quit,'' Hibbard, now
52, said recently, sitting in the handsomely restored bungalow just
southeast of the Texas Christian University campus where he and his
wife, Anna, live.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't quit piano forever, though, and he is among the
competitors in the Van Cliburn International Piano Competition for
Outstanding Amateurs. It begins this week in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Hibbard's love of piano blossomed again when he was a teen-ager
in Canton, Ill., and he earned first prize with flourish-laden
Rachmaninoff in a statewide music contest for high-schoolers. After
graduating, he entered the University of Illinois at
Urbana-Champaign as a piano major, and spent two semesters there
before the need to earn money sent him to work for a railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Hibbard had railroad work in his blood as much as piano music:
His Irish-born mother came from generations of railroad workers.
When he returned to college 10 years later at the University of
Illinois at Chicago, he majored in Slavic languages and Eastern
European history.
</P>
<P>
   But he never gave up his love of piano. While working in Kansas
City in 1989-92, he took lessons from a Russian immigrant,
Svyatoslav Levin, continuing until 1993 when he was assigned to
Fort Worth. He is manager of locomotive utilization for Burlington
Northern and Santa Fe Railway, dealing with reciprocal use among
different railroad companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard about the amateur competition on Channel 8,'' he says.
``I pulled up the Cliburn Web site, and, more or less on a lark,
threw my name in the hat. You could have knocked me over with a
feather when I was accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   He generally puts in 10- to 12-hour days at his job at the
railway. But since being accepted to the competition, he has made
time for regular practice on the 1925 Steinway that dominates his
house. His program of Chopin and Scriabin reflects his interest in
Slavic history and culture.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
