<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JET-SKI-RULES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE COULD MAKE WAVES FOR PERSONAL WATERCRAFT USERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Wash., Fla., La., N.J.)  (bl)  
 By CATHERINE HOLLINGSWORTH  
 
 NYT Regional Newspapers  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A beachgoer out for a sunset stroll is startled by
the sudden roar of Jet Skis in the surf. Paddling through a quiet
cove, canoeists encounter a gang of zipping water bikers. As he
casts for an evening catch, a fisherman finds it is prime time for
personal watercraft and all the fish have been chased away.
</P>
<P>
   While some head to the beach and tranquil inland coastlines in
search of solitude and a quiet moment with nature, water beckons
lovers of Jet Skis and similar high-tech recreational vessels as a
source of high-speed thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Now that conflict could be resolved on the high ground of
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with complaints of loud, aggressive personal watercraft
users disturbing serene settings, uprooting wildlife and
endangering other boaters, Congress is prepared to make some waves
of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The House Subcommittee on Fisheries Conservation, Wildlife and
Oceans is considering whether to restrict personal watercraft from
certain areas under the Coastal Zone Management Act. But before it
moves forward, the subcommittee wants to study the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to make sure that the problem is understood
before making a blanket federal law,'' said Jeff Sagnip
Hollendonner, spokesman for subcommittee chairman Rep. Jim Saxton,
R-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton originally proposed broad federal restrictions in
``sensitive areas'' along the East and West coasts and the Great
Lakes. Now he is floating a plan to have states determine whether
such areas exist and to document any safety problems with personal
watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the studies are completed, we will have beneficial
information to look at,'' said Sagnip Hollendonner. Proponents of
the measure say the study could be the basis for federal
restrictions in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials hope to block the effort. They argue that
their particular kind of boat has been unfairly singled out for
stricter regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government should be regulating boats across the
board in determining sensitive areas,'' said Larry Lambrose,
executive director of the Personal Watercraft Industry Association
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But David Jenkins, director of conservation and public policy at
the American Canoe Association, said personal watercraft pose
different problems from other boats because of their ability to
navigate shallower water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little bays, inlets, coves, estuaries, those have been
kind of the realm of paddlers,'' he said. ``With Jet Skis it is
totally different. They like to be anywhere. They just stay in that
area for the whole day.''
</P>
<P>
   Communities in states like Florida, California and Washington
already are moving to restrict personal watercraft in certain areas
and many others are requiring a minimum age and user education.
</P>
<P>
   But conservationists say state laws are not enough. ``They're
always being challenged by the industry,'' said Laurie Martin,
conservation associate at the Izaak Walton League, which supports
federal restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was passed, it would protect them from those kinds of
challenges. It would be one of the strongest protections they can
enact to address the problems of personal watercraft,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While some say federal regulations could bolster states' efforts
to regulate personal watercraft, others say states could be
hindered by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue that a lot of states are grappling with. But
it's a controversial issue at the state level,'' said Chris
Darnell, policy analyst at the Coastal States Organization. He said
a federal regulation may limit state flexibility in addressing the
personal watercraft issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., a member of the House panel exploring
the issue, agreed that a restricted use measure ``might not make a
whole lot of sense'' for some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of personal watercraft such as the Jet Ski and WaveRunner
say current models deal with many concerns about these one to
four-person watercraft.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers point to quieter engines that whir rather than buzz like
a giant mosquito. And they claim that new models have cut harmful
emissions by 70 percent, making them kinder to the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need to look at the mixed use of the waterways,''
said Lambrose. ``There is room for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   (Catherine Hollingsworth is a correspondent in the Washington
Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
