<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT ME WITH YOUR PET SHARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attention, class! Today we will test your knowledge of popular
music.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more specifically, test your knowledge of popular music
``lyrics.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what you want about today's music, the words are every bit
as indecipherable as the stuff we listened to 10, 20 or even 30
years ago. There are many ways to mishear song lyrics (stoned being
foremost among them) but the odd thing is that the misunderstood
words often make as much, or more, sense than the originals.
</P>
<P>
   Author David Trevas collected 600 of the most bizarre in his
book, ``The Compendium of Misunderstood Lyrics'' ($10, Viselley
Press). I discovered another good source at Kissthisguy.com _ The
Archive of Misheard Lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: Only one lyric in the following songs is correct.
That is unfortunate, because some of the alternatives are a lot
better. Although the correct lyric will be identified at the bottom
of the column, feel free to continue singing the song incorrectly
if you think it makes more sense or you just enjoy annoying people.
It won't hurt my feelings in the slightest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I now know that the correct lyric in the song ``The
Ballad of Davey Crockett'' is ``killed him a bar when he was only
three.'' That is too bad because I intend to go on singing ``killed
in a bar when he was only three'' because that's how I heard the
lyric when I was 8 and I see no reason to change now. (I figured it
was the Disney way of discouraging toddler alcoholism.)
</P>
<P>
   Scoring: Score five points if you thought the line to Johnny
Rivers' ``Secret Agent Man'' was ``Oswald, he won't live to see
tomorrow'' rather than ``Odds are he won't live to see tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Score four points if you thought the line to the Beatles' ``Lucy
in the Sky With Diamonds'' was ``The girl with colitis goes by''
rather than ``The girl with kaleidoscope eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Score three points if you thought the line in David Bowie's
``Space Oddity'' was ``Ground control to Mao Tse-Tung'' rather than
``Ground control to Major Tom.''
</P>
<P>
   Score zero points if you seriously expected to see the name
``Barry Manilow'' in this column.
</P>
<P>
   1. From Black Crows' song ``Hard to Handle:''
</P>
<P>
   a) Pretty little thing, lemon-lime chicana 'cause mama, I'm sure
hard to henna now, yes I am
</P>
<P>
   b) Hey little thing, let me light your chemicals, 'cause mama
I'm sure hard to henna now, mess around
</P>
<P>
   c) 'Cause mama, I sure am a handy man, yes I am
</P>
<P>
   d) Pretty little thing let me light your candle, 'cause mama,
I'm sure hard to handle now, yes I am
</P>
<P>
   2. The Rolling Stones' ``Beast of Burden''
</P>
<P>
   a) I'll never be your beef of bourbon
</P>
<P>
   b) I'll never be your beast of burden
</P>
<P>
   c) I'll never leave your pizza burnin'
</P>
<P>
   d) I'll never be your pizza burger
</P>
<P>
   3. Nirvana's ``Heart-Shaped Box''
</P>
<P>
   a) Hey, wait, I got a new complaint
</P>
<P>
   b) Hey, way, I got a bill to pay
</P>
<P>
   c) Hey, wait, I got a menstrual pain
</P>
<P>
   4. Billy Joel's ``Piano Man''
</P>
<P>
   a) Making love to his Tommy cat Jim
</P>
<P>
   b) Making love to his tonic and gin
</P>
<P>
   c) Making love to his Hanukkah chi
</P>
<P>
   5. Elton John's ``Benny and the Jets''
</P>
<P>
   a) She's got electric boots, a mohair suit, you know I read it
in a magazine
</P>
<P>
   b) She's got electric boots, a motor scoot, y'know I heard it
from a hag in Zaire
</P>
<P>
   c) She's got electric boobs, a mower suit
</P>
<P>
   6. Elton John's ``Tiny Dancer''
</P>
<P>
   a) Hold me closer, tiny dancer
</P>
<P>
   b) Hold me closer, tie me down, sir
</P>
<P>
   c) Hold me closer, Tony Danza
</P>
<P>
   Answers: 1) d; 2) b; 3) a; 4) b; 5) a; 6)a.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
