<SLUG> BC-DIET-CHEFS-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATING WELL: CHEFS JOIN A DRUG COMPANY PROMOTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a new twist in celebrity endorsements, some
well-known New York chefs have teamed up with a pharmaceutical
company to promote a low-fat diet that is part of the company's
campaign for a new anti-obesity drug.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the chefs _ who include Larry Forgione of An American
Place, Jonathan Waxman of Colina and David Burke of Park Avenue
Cafe _ have agreed to promote the diet, but not the drug itself.
They are being paid by the drug company, Hoffmann-La Roche, to help
promote ``The Taste for Healthy Living,'' its diet and educational
program that calls for eating meals in which no more than 30
percent of the calories come from fat. Earlier this year, the
company introduced Xenical, a weight-loss drug that the company
says should be accompanied by such a diet.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York in May at which the program was
introduced, Dr. Russell Ellison, the company's vice president for
medical affairs, said: ``We are here to help people make life-style
changes. Xenical is not a magic pill _ it acts by helping you do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Suga, a spokeswoman for Hoffmann-La Roche, said later
that the use of chefs in the campaign was ``a crucial component
because they are influential.''
</P>
<P>
   But the new alliance is an odd one: the concept of food as
medicine is not one that chefs usually want to present, and until
now, few chefs have been in the vanguard of the battle against fat.
</P>
<P>
   At least two restaurateurs who had agreed to participate have
had second thoughts. Drew Nieporent, whose restaurant Heartbeat is
known for its low-fat, high-flavor food, said he backed out because
``there was a fine line between endorsing the drug and just the
diet.'' Michael Lomonaco of Windows on the World and Wild Blue also
changed his mind. ``I didn't feel comfortable with creating a menu
program that was commercially linked,'' he said. He had offered a
low-fat, low-calorie menu when he was the chef at the ``21'' Club
and, he said, ``it wasn't all that successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Forgione, who owns several restaurants in addition to An
American Place, said he was not worried about the link between the
diet and the drug. ``Whether there seems to be a cross-reference
with Xenical, those crossovers are fine with me,'' he said. The
company has hired him to form a coalition of chefs, restaurateurs
and health professionals in 19 cities to try to persuade Americans
to adopt the company's suggestions on fat.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to get Americans to reduce their fat intake are not new.
The last big push, in the early 1990s, led many people to replace
the calories from fat with calories from carbohydrates. Today,
Americans are fatter than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The chefs who are being paid for the use of their names said
that even before Hoffmann-La Roche's campaign began, they already
had low-fat dishes on their menus and supported the program's
goals.
</P>
<P>
   The amount a chef receives for his participation depends on what
he is willing to do. An honorarium of $3,000 will be given to those
who put a few dishes on their menus that contain 30 percent fat or
less and label them as such. (Forgione said he was receiving
``considerably more'' than that for his role.) More money will go
to chefs who agree to make public appearances on behalf of the
program. Even more is available if a chef is willing to promote
Xenical, but so far there have been no takers.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palomino, who is chef and owner of Sonora, a Latin
American restaurant in Manhattan, said he was offered $5,000 extra
if he would ``promote the drug by telling people it doesn't have
any side effects and helps lose a lot of weight.'' But he added,
``No one is going to do that because of the liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Xenical works by blocking the body's absorption of dietary fat.
Patients who have used it have lost modest amounts _ 5 to 10
percent of their body weight _ but some have also suffered side
effects like abdominal pain and fecal incontinence. And as the
insert in the drug's package notes, ``If Xenical is taken with any
one meal very high in fat, the possibility of gastrointestinal
effects increases.'' Ellison said doctors could explain the program
to patients ``in a 10-minute consultation.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without a pill, losing weight _ and keeping it off _
requires more than a 10-minute consultation. It takes a lifetime
commitment to healthy eating, with or without the help of your
favorite chef.
</P>
</TEXT>
