<HEADER>
A7591 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOBY-POPLIFE-NYT &LR;      06-08 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOBY-POPLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: AFTER `GO,' MOBY WENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Mich., Ill.)  (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The year was 1991, and American youth had just
begun to wake up to the electronic dance music-techno that the
British had appropriated from the Chicago and Detroit club scenes.
Though the New York disk jockey Moby was far from the nation's
first techno musician, he was its first great hope.
</P>
<P>
   His single ``Go'' was a club classic, with three samples _ an
orchestral sweep, a voice yelling, ``Go!'' and a snippet of a diva
_ sparring over a fast, piano-enhanced dance beat. His self-titled
album the next year was one of the first high-quality American
techno albums produced in a form that traffics in singles.
</P>
<P>
   To the rock establishment at least, Moby seemed like the man who
would bring mainstream credibility to techno: he could release full
albums, perform energetic concerts and as a skinny shaven-headed
self-declared vegan environmentalist Christian, he had a marketable
personality. In what was then called a ``faceless'' kind of music,
he was to be its first face.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997 techno had its first face _ or haircut, actually _ in
the dyed, spiked fringes of surviving hair on the head of Keith
Flynt, the singer and dancer in Prodigy, from England, which that
year gave techno music its first No. 1 album on Billboard's pop
charts. And where was Moby? The techno crowd had long since
declared him a traitor _ a populist who was too popular _ and Moby
had done his best to alienate that audience, interspersing albums
and concerts with hardcore punk songs.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the double bind of being too mainstream for the rave
underground and too marginal for the mainstream, his major-label
album from that year, ``Animal Rights'' (Elektra) _ a hodge-podge
of punk, new wave, mock classical, heavy metal, and electronic
dance _ was more or less ignored.
</P>
<P>
   This month, with a new album (``Play'') recorded for a new label
(V2), Moby, now 33, has returned with a surprise, the best album of
his career. It is an electronic dance album, but not techno.
Compositionally it's similar to his earliest work, but it's also
completely new.
</P>
<P>
   The best music on ``Play'' takes a chugging midtempo dance beat,
adds soulful keyboards and tops it with a sample from old blues and
gospel recordings. But even the album's more traditional
verse-chorus-verse pop songs that Moby sings himself, in particular
``South Side,'' are his most accessible and fully realized.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of sampled forms of music, from electronica to hip-hop,
has given rise to a new way of listening, in which albums are
consumed in search of just a bar or two in which an instrument, be
it drums or voice, can be heard without accompaniment, so it can be
cleanly sampled and used as the foundation of a new song. For Moby
on ``Play'' that music was the field recordings made by folk music
archivists John and Alan Lomax and others from the first half of
this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered the Alan Lomax stuff, and I didn't get excited
about them because of the cultural context,'' Moby said last week,
sitting down for an interview at the Bar Marmont in Los Angeles.
``I got excited about them because I liked the performances, and
they were well recorded a cappella, which, as an electronic
musician, meant that I could sample them and write songs around
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Honey,'' Moby grabs phrases and hand claps from the
Lomax-aided Sea Island singer Bessie Jones, adding slide guitar and
a piano-driven beat not unlike the one Dr. Dre reinterprets in the
hit ``California Love.'' And he emotionally charges ``Why Does My
Heart Feel So Bad?'' by adding string and keyboard melodies in
pitch with pleas from the Shining Light Gospel Choir.
</P>
<P>
   When he played early versions of these songs for people, Moby
said, one friend warned that he might be lambasted for using some
of these recordings. ``The fact that I was a white kid from the
20th century sampling African-American vocals from the early 20th
century had never even crossed my mind,'' he said. ``In the long,
nonillustrious history of white people pilfering African American
culture, have I just perpetrated that? I'm motivated by a love for
the music and by a love of the performances, and I really hope I
haven't done anything bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Seen in another light, Moby is an update of Alan Lomax, helping
to spread and continue the legacy of traditional American ballads
and folk songs. The way Moby uses these recordings to construct
fully realized songs that are more than just beats with sampled
phrases is likely to inspire other musicians to do the same. And
whether that is an honor to or a disrespecting of the original
recordings is up to the musical morality of the listener.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best hip-hop beats incorporate the surface noise of
a vinyl record playing an old funk beat into the music. In the same
way Moby didn't try to eliminate the hiss and noise from the old
recordings he used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like noise,'' he said. ``It's always puzzled me why one of
the goals of contemporary recording is to get rid of noise and to
eliminate any element of a performance. In some of the greatest
recordings ever made, the performance is a part of the recording.
Dylan's ``Rainy Day Women No. 12 and 35'' is all about the esthetic
of that performance. You can hear the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times good, pristine recordings prevent the listener
from getting emotionally involved in the music.''
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with other albums by Moby, a musician more likely to
be found reading The Economist than a music magazine, ``Play''
includes extensive liner notes musing on religion, politics and the
environment. In this case the essays concern prisoner rights,
fundamentalism, veganism, genocide and a message insisting that the
essays and the music are unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hate the essays, you might still like the music,'' he
writes, hoping that his ideology won't scare off potential fans.
Then in a note of characteristic humility he adds, ``And if you
like the essays, you might hate the music.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the old burden of having to be a face for techno, Moby,
with even more humility, says that was never a goal. ``I didn't
think of myself in those terms because I always thought other
people made better records than I did,'' he said. ``Even when
people were saying I was the king of techno or whatever, I never
for a second thought of myself like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
