   COKE-AUSTRALIA _ Australian regulators have rejected for the
second time Coca-Cola Co.'s plan to buy soft drink brands in
Australia from Cadbury Schweppes PLC because it would reduce
competition. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EQUIFAX-PRESIDENT _ Equifax to announce a new president and COO
Wednesday. (Saporta, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 10.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZONCOM-DISTRIBUTION _ Amazon.com will build a
800,000-square-foot, $51 million distribution center in McDonough
that will open in late summer with 500 employees, and expand to
1,000 employees early next year. The company will hold a job fair
Friday, Saturday and Sunday, and that's our lead. (Cowles, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-BUSINESS _ The Hispanic Business 500, the equivalent of
the BE 100 is out today, with lists of the nation's top Hispanic
businesses. About a dozen Georgia companies made the cut. We take a
look. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft attorneys cross-examine Garry
Norris, an IBM executive who offered damaging testimony in the
federal antitrust trial. (Glass, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   DRKOOP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Drkoop.com is scheduled to make an
initial public offering today. The offering could raise $83.7
million. Analysts say that despite nervousness about Internet
stocks, koop could be a standout because its site, which offers
health care information, is appealing to investors. (Hawkins,
Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TOYSRUS-FORMAT _ Toys R Us CEO Robert Nakasone tours the
Alpharetta store today to show off the retailer's new store format,
which allegedly makes the stores easier to shop. Toys R Us tested
the new layout in the Atlanta market and is holding its annual
meeting here Wednesday to show the stores to shareholders and
executives. Following the tour, Nakasone will give a presentation
about internet strategy and other initiatives. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   KOOP _ Drkoop.com is scheduled to make an initial public
offering today. The offering could raise $83.7 million. Analysts
say that despite nervousness about Internet stocks, koop could be a
standout because its site, which offers health care information, is
appealing to investors. (Hawkins, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   IBM-NCR _ IBM has sold part of its financial self-service
business to NCR Corp. for an undisclosed amount. (Bischoff, Dayton
Daily News).
</P>
