   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-RAYS _ ATLANTA _ Braves vs. Tampa Bay. (Rogers,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: First pitch is at 7:40 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-NOTES _ ATLANTA _ Braves notebook. (Rogers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-MCGRIFF _ The first year with Tampa Bay was disastrous for
former Braves first baseman Fred McGriff. Critics said Tampa Bay
had been taken in a trade with the Braves. Now those critics are
rethinking, because McGriff is on a tear in his second season.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-REEVES _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons head coach Dan Reeves
announces plans to become a ``heart missionary.'' (Winkeljohn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   WNBA _The third WNBA season begins Thursday as the only
(women's) game in town, now that the ABL has folded. A labor spat
resulted in improved benefits and slightly better salaries for
players, and the league welcomes the acclaimed Chamique Holdsclaw.
But publicity has been reduced as owners look at the bottom line.
Four new franchises for next season are expected and Atlanta could
fall in two years from now. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LENNYWILKENS _ ATLANTA _ Coach Lenny Wilkens acknowledged in an
interview that his long-time affection for Mookie Blaylock at point
guard may be wearing off. Wilkens said he could see Blaylock as a
backup or part-timer next season. Another need, he said, is a
scorer to complement Steve Smith, who was injured down the stretch.
He likes the overall mix of the team. And, he says, his passion is
equal to any other coach's; he just doesn't throw chairs. (Denberg,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING
</P>
<P>
   RUN-RECORD _ This past weekend at the Emory University track a
group of 100 masters (40 and over) men topped the world record in
the 100X 1 Mile Relay by over 6 1/2 minutes _ the team averaged
5:23 per mile and finished in 8 hours, 57 minutes 31 seconds to
topple the record set by a group from Houston of 9:04:02. Dick
Buerkle, 51, and the former world record holder of the indoor mile,
ran the final leg for the team in 4:39. (Hiskey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12-14.
</P>
