u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-08 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: A BROADWAY RESCUE; HOSPITAL UNDER FIRE CLOSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Broadway Hero? It's Letterman
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman's ``Late Show'' on CBS rode to the rescue of the
Broadway show ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues'' Tuesday, offering
a home for the production number from that musical that was bumped
from the network's Sunday night broadcast of the Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Burnett, the executive producer of the ``Late Show,'' said
Tuesday that he has booked the number for the Letterman show
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' who were
upset enough Sunday night to say that the bumping might lead to the
show's closing, had hired a lawyer in the hope of some kind of
compensation from the groups that put on the Tonys, the League of
American Theaters and the American Theater Wing.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of that performance, which was squeezed out when the
broadcast started to run late, was one of many problems with the
show. A recap of the awards given out earlier in the evening _ and
shown on PBS _ was also cut. A segment of dramatic readings from
nominated plays, inserted late into the broadcast, added to the
controversy when the musical number was cut.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, including a precipitous drop in ratings, left some
executives at CBS feeling more than a little frustrated about the
way the Tony broadcast was being run.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was already extremely unhappy that the two groups that put
on the show had failed to secure the services of Rosie O'Donnell as
the host once again this year. In the two previous years, with Ms.
O'Donnell as host, the show's ratings, in decline for years, had
soared.
</P>
<P>
   This year they plummeted again. The national rating came in at a
7, down from an 8.4 last year and a 9.6 the year before. (Each
rating point represents 980,000 homes.)
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which has a contract to broadcast the Tonys through 2004,
has a yearly option that would allow the network to drop out of the
show if it chose to do so. But the network quietly let it be known
that it is not thinking of exercising the option.
</P>
<P>
   The only CBS executive willing to comment on the record about
this year's show was Chris Ender, the vice president for media
relations. ``Obviously nobody wanted it to turn out like this,'' he
said. ``You always want higher ratings and less controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Letterman show stepped quickly into the breach, with Burnett
contacting the producers from ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues''
Tuesday afternoon after he had cleared an opening for a musical
guest Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he had done it, Burnett said, ``David Michael
Letterman has always been a champion of the American theater.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what he had said to convince the producers of the show,
Burnett had another joke: ``We had to guarantee them they wouldn't
get bumped.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Eric Krebs, one of the producers of the musical,
is thrilled. ``It's absolutely stupendous that the Letterman show
called,'' he said. ``And it's really important to us.'' Krebs said
the show was barely breaking even and needed the exposure from the
Tony awards show to help bring in tourists this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tony show speaks to 5 million or so fans of musicals,'' he
said. ``So this doesn't make up for that. But we are totally elated
to have this opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   Faulted Hospital Closes
</P>
<P>
   On April 21, a few hours before Ed Bradley's hourlong special
report on abuses of children in the nation's largest chain of
psychiatric hospitals was to be broadcast on CBS News' ``60 Minutes
II,'' the chain sought a restraining order to block CBS from
showing the report. A judge denied the request on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Now the chain, Charter Behavioral Health Systems, is shutting
down the hospital that was the focus of the ``60 Minutes II''
report, Charter Pines in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's pretty extraordinary,'' Bradley said Tuesday.
``I've never been involved in a story with that kind of a direct
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the 89-hospital chain, Karen Jenkins, refused
to say whether the CBS News report played a role in the decision to
close Charter Pines, saying that the move was based only on the
company's own internal review.
</P>
<P>
   The report relied heavily on film obtained with a hidden camera,
something news organizations now tend to avoid because several have
lost lawsuits as a result of such methods. In this case, the camera
was in the eyeglasses of a licensed social worker who was hired by
the hospital as an aide after agreeing to work undercover for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   He recorded a nurse's entering fabricated information on
patients' records (saying it had to be done to get insurance
payments); doctors who arrived late and made cursory updates of
patient charts without examining the patients, and admittedly
ill-trained workers handling troublesome patients without trained
supervision. In one instance, burly aides could be seen forcing a
teen-age patient into wrist and ankle restraints even though he had
a wrist injury they were obviously re-injuring.
</P>
<P>
   David Gelber, the segment's producer, said Tuesday that great
care had been taken in the use of the hidden camera. ``We got
someone who was qualified for the job, and we didn't lie about who
he was,'' he said. He said the report could not have been done
without the hidden camera, because hospital officials would not
explain their procedures for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very careful,'' Bradley said, ``And the bottom line
is, Charter didn't sue us _ they closed the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly for Bradley and the producers, who had worked for a year
on the program, it was broadcast the night after the Littleton,
Colo., school shootings, and a ``Dateline'' special on NBC trounced
``60 Minutes II'' in the Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   To help make up for that, next Wednesday night at 10, after a
regular edition of ``60 Minutes II,'' CBS will run the report
again, with updates.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
</TEXT>
