<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LAST CIGARETTE': SMOKING, FROM DIVINE TO DISGUSTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Coughs due to smoking disappear! Parched throat clears up!
That stale, smoked-out feeling vanishes!'' Those claims for a
miracle cure can be found in ``The Last Cigarette,'' a witty but
deliberately choke-inducing documentary by Kevin Rafferty and Frank
Keraudren about the mystique of smoking in America. The real
miracle turns out to be somewhat different: that those claims were
once used to promote even more smoking, with the promise that
``when you change to Philip Morris you'll feel better.'' And that
the glamour of the cigarette habit has been so successfully
manufactured for so long.
</P>
<P>
   A horde of film clips illustrate the movie shorthand of a
meaningful gesture and a lighted cigarette. It was an especially
valuable prop in the days when films required visual metaphors for
what they could not otherwise say, as in a romantic scene that ends
with Jennifer Jones and a bare-chested William Holden locking eyes
while touching their cigarettes together. And by angrily throwing a
cigarette away, John Wayne could make himself look even tougher.
There are even glimpses of latter-day smoke-porn videos in which a
fully clothed woman, perhaps one with two-inch talons and a tattoo,
does nothing but smoke her cigarette and talk about it. And it goes
without saying that an actor who pauses before exhaling looks
thoughtful, even if he's not.
</P>
<P>
   As in Rafferty's earlier ``Atomic Cafe,'' anything goes. This is
a film for anyone who'd like to see a frog smoke, or two human
lovebirds puff from a single heart-shaped holder. There are also
amusing clips from ultra-square educational films with the look of
the early 1950s. An instructor demonstrates what one drop of pure
nicotine can do to a laboratory rodent, then helpfully points out,
``Now fortunately, man is many times larger than a mouse.'' Having
seen this (and it's not a pretty sight), one of his listeners
shakes his head and says: ``No kidding, doc, you really have
convinced me.'' And the doctor's final warning to the audience is
as real as it is quaint: ``Don't forget, tobacco is a loaded
pistol. And time pulls the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   While films like ``Atomic Cafe'' and ``Reefer Madness''
addressed exaggerated perils (the atomic bomb and marijuana,
respectively), this one is essentially more sober and stays closer
to reality. Much of ``The Last Cigarette,'' which opens today at
the Film Forum, is essentially a fancifully illustrated look at
C-SPAN, with much time devoted to 1994 congressional hearings that
summoned the chief executives of major tobacco companies. Quietly
outrageous excerpts from these hearings find them claiming not to
care whether their children or grandchildren smoke, touting the
grownup appeal of Joe Camel and excelling in carefully bland
double-talk. Asked whether smoking is addictive, the research
director of Philip Morris replies, ``It is a very complicated
question, which requires an extremely complicated answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Less complicated are the film's howlers. They reveal the absurd
extremes of pitchmanship that have shaped smoking's public image,
like when Julie London sings ``You get a lot to like from a
Marlboro'' as if it were the sexiest song ever written and as if
cigarettes were definitely beside the point. Behind the funny
naivete seen in some of the film clips, there is an awareness of
nicotine's real hold in the smoker. In a scene from ``Black Robe,''
missionaries tell Indians that they won't need tobacco (or women)
in paradise, only to have the Indians laugh pityingly.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain repetitiveness to the sight of famous people
smoking, as in the film's many glimpses of Albert Einstein puffing
on his pipe. And ``The Last Cigarette'' would have benefited from
incorporating more up-to-date views of smoking and its well-managed
image.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the filmmakers have enterprisingly looked for the truth
about smoking and found it in the strangest places, like Michael
Curtiz's 1950 film, ``Bright Leaf,'' in which Gary Cooper plays a
19th-century North Carolina businessman who is approached with a
proposition to manufacture cigarettes in large numbers. He thinks
about it, then exclaims: ``Anything like that'd make an awful lot
of money!'' In the same film, as the first cigarettes roll off the
assembly line, Lauren Bacall is on hand to enjoy Hollywood's
second-favorite fantasy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
