<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOVIES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THEATER OWNERS' GROUP TO CHECK ID'S AT R-RATED FILMS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's campaign against excessive
violence in children's entertainment yielded its first major
results Tuesday when hundreds of theater owners agreed to require
photo identification of young people seeking admission to R-rated
movies.
</P>
<P>
   William Kartozian, president of the National Association of
Theater Owners, unveiled the new ID policy at the White House with
Clinton at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us, I believe, have had our sensibilities heightened
since the recent tragedies at Columbine and in Georgia, and we as
theater owners feel our responsibilities as keenly as does
anybody,'' Kartozian said.
</P>
<P>
   The theater owners association has 700 members, described by
Kartozian as ``mom and pop'' operators, who control nearly 20,000
movie screens in the United States, about 65 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in the communities that we serve, and we want to be a
part of those communities and be a part of the solution to whatever
problems may be going on in your communities,'' Kartozian added.
</P>
<P>
   Kartozian said association members will display posters at their
box offices informing customers that ``every young person who comes
to the box office to see an R-rated movie (will be) asked to show a
photo ID.'' He said the association will also work with parent and
community organizations to promote the new policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this will go a long way in carrying out our
responsibilities to the parents of America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who want their children under 17 to see an R-rated movie
will still be able to buy tickets and escort them into theaters,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The president praised the theater owners for ``clearly drawing
the line'' in helping parents keep their children out of movies
that are not intended for viewers under the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about the multiplex is that there's a movie
for every member of the family, but not every movie is for every
member of the family,'' Clinton said. ``When you drop them off, you
shouldn't have to worry about your G-rated kids getting into
violent or suggestive R-rated movies. Too often children do get
past the ticket counter, unescorted and under age.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated his challenge to the movie industry to re-evaluate
its 30-year-old voluntary rating system, which categorizes movies
according to content and appropriate age levels of viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For rating systems to work, they must also be enforced, not
simply by watchful parents, but by retailers at the point of sales,
and theater owners at the multiplex,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, head of the Motion Picture Association of America,
applauded the ID requirement. ``It's a big step forward,'' he said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   However, other segments of the entertainment industry have not
been as responsive to the president's challenge as the theater
owners.
</P>
<P>
   At another White House event, an Oval Office meeting with
President Arpad Goncz of Hungary, Clinton acknowledged the ``public
ambivalence'' of entertainment executives about his anti-violence
campaign, but insisted their uncertainty is more about concern over
censorship than disagreement with his policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all work at it ... so that nobody's pointing a finger at
anybody else, I think we'll have good participation from the
entertainment community,'' the president said. ``I'll be surprised
if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been pressuring the entertainment and gun industries
ever since the fatal student shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., two months ago and the wounding of students at
Heritage High School in Conyers, Ga., on the one-month anniversary
of the Columbine killings.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he asked the Justice Department and the Federal Trade
Commission to study the extent to which the video game, movie and
music industries market violence to children.
</P>
<P>
   Kartozian said his organization endorsed the idea of national
studies of the causes of teen violence. ``We believe it to be a
good idea to examine all factors which go into this very critical
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
