<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7634 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIDOW-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-08 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIDOW-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ARTIST'S WIDOW': PLUCKY IN A BATTLE AGAINST FRAILTY AND
TORMENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are images of bereavement, after a long and devoted
marriage that has a painter's widow attending a retrospective show
of her late husband's work and reflecting, as if he were there too:
``It was the sort of party John and Lyris Crane hated.'' Then, in
the swirling currents of snobbery, canape jostling, bluff
congratulations and deep indifference, Lyris' mind heels before a
different, valedictory gust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyris felt a pang of envy for John, among the flowers and
berries of the crematorium gardens. But the trees would be
gathering darkness now, the reeds and bulrushes whispering, a
chilly dew rising to meet the rain. Time to come indoors.'' Later,
after a cheap dinner given by the gallery owner, ostensibly in her
honor but full of people she doesn't know, she goes home to
exchange the torture of tight blue shoes for a pair of John's
slippers. ``Kind boats,'' she thinks: two words that tell the
lifelong history of a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Shena Mackay is wise about shoes and old age. If fish rot from
the mouth down, we grow old from the feet up. The abiding theme in
``The Artist's Widow,'' the filament that lights it, is the
portrait of Lyris, herself a painter, rallying against sorrow,
solitude, frailty, the drifts of confusion that intermittently
cloud a sharp vision and the fear that goes with the shift of
relative power between one's 80-year-old self and a surrounding
world that seems to threaten and sometimes really does.
</P>
<P>
   It is a filament only, though, and in a flawed, cloudy bulb. Ms.
Mackay, a Scottish novelist, knows some particular truths better
than just about anyone else, and in her best books _ ``The Orchard
on Fire'' and last year's ``An Advent Calendar'' _ she locates
truths that even she does not know. She is fierce and on the left;
her villains, mostly the various categories of Britain's
politically, economically or culturally privileged, are atrocious.
Her heroes, misused but sparky, are angelic: the downtrodden who
take wing. This is hard to get away with, but Ms. McKay uses
elusiveness, sudden shifts and reversals to manage it much of the
time, along with writing that can be sheer magic in short bursts
and comically unexpected in longer ones. The rule for a sad clown
is to be very lovely and very funny.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Artist's Widow'' the managing largely fails and the
clown's sadness is reduced to grimaces. It is a novel with a
winning center _ Lyris _ and a messed-up series of things that
happen to her, mainly other people. These divide into the author's
customary baddies and goodies, but the former are crudely and
exaggeratedly drawn and the latter turn out pat or pallid.
Comeuppances like so many gong strokes are in store for the former,
and happy endings for the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among Lyris' tormentors is Nathan, her great-nephew by
marriage: a loathsome and ultimately futile specimen of a young
artist on the make. He works in a grubby collective, each of whose
members tries to make sure that none of the others gets ahead. He
crashes the desirable parties, shamelessly flatters guests he
thinks useful and cultivates a repulsiveness that he understands to
be cutting-edge. Missing his 20 minutes of fame by a year or two,
he creates an installation with a bucket of entrails but has to
throw them out because of the stink.
</P>
<P>
   ``His eyelids, with a bristle of pale lashes, were tender and
his eyes dull green and hard,'' Ms. Mackay writes, employing a
fairly sharp scalpel. She switches to a bludgeon and Nathan becomes
``a pond with green scum on its surface.'' Language overkill is
spread around. An only moderately unpleasant woman is nicknamed
``The Wounded Squid'' because ``she was so clinging and so easily
hurt into squirting her purple sentimental ink over everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Lyris' dead husband gets splashed. ``The last canvases
burned with the brilliant chemical derangement of autumn when the
slow fuses smoldering up the stalks of senescent leaves burst into
mineral fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, backed by a Neanderthal father connected with the East
End mob, has designs on Lyris' house and art collection. He sneaks
into her house, scaring her almost literally to death. Possibly
mistaking it for water, he offers her a drink of denatured alcohol
and proceeds to flatter her about the inspiration she and her
husband have been. She briefly melts _ Ms. Mackay gives a plausible
explanation but it is pretty awkward _ and then he steals her
purse.
</P>
<P>
   With all his awfulness, Nathan has no more reality than a
cutout. (At the end, when he is destroyed several different ways,
his seeming repentance is simply the cutout reversed.) Neither does
Zoe, his partner, who blasts in on Lyris to make a television
feature about neglected painter-wives of famous painters. This
happens near the beginning, and for a while it seems that Zoe's
brashness conceals something redemptive and that a promising theme
will take shape. Like a number of other false starts, this one
peters out.
</P>
<P>
   As for the good guys, there is Jackie, brutally ditched by
Nathan and doubly brutalized at work when her black supervisor
accuses her of racism for growing dreadlocks and pretending to be
half black. Far-fetched, I know; equally so is Jackie's asking
Lyris for sanctuary, settling in and eventually restoring the old
woman's life and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Other good guys include a sensible plumber and his wife, and
Candy, mistress of a married Conservative member of Parliament who
for 20 years used her like ``a weevil feeding on bread buttered on
both sides.'' Principally nice, apart from Lyris, is Clovis, a
gentle, mixed-up bookseller. He is plunged into near lethal despair
when he fails to come to the aid of a man caught in a subway
up-escalator as he rode down. ``I am doomed,'' he tells himself.
Doom and kindness wrap him in a formless cloud right to the end,
when Candy's efforts to rescue him may perhaps succeed.
</P>
<P>
   There are several other dispensations of justice, but they come
pell-mell as if a doll's tea party had been issued a sudden closing
time. With plotlets and most of the characters shaped and exercised
so disjointedly, Ms. Mackay _ never tidy but able to draw charming
provocation out of anarchy _ has managed only sporadically
promising confusion.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ARTIST'S WIDOW'
</P>
<P>
   By Shena Mackay
</P>
<P>
   151 pages. Moyer Bell. $21.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
