<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7640 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-LOLA-RUN-FILM-$AD     06-08 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-LOLA-RUN-FILM-$ADV13-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REBEL WITH RED HAIR RUMPLES STUFFED SHIRTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(jt) 
 By LAURA WINTERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not many films have inspired both a hair color  &UR; and &LR; 
a conservative politician's campaign poster. But the German
director Tom Tykwer's ``Run Lola Run'' certainly did.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which has sold more than 2 million tickets in Germany
and which opens here on June 17, is the anarchically charged story
of a flame-haired punk, Lola (Franka Potente), who races through
the streets of Berlin in a desperate attempt to save her
boyfriend's life. After ``Run Lola Run'' was released in Germany
last year, girls started dyeing their hair a shade that quickly
became known as ``Lola red.'' And displayed throughout the city was
an image of the mayor of Berlin, Eberhard Diepgen, running above
the caption ``Diepgen Rennt'' (``Run Diepgen'').
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer took legal steps to halt the posters, but the Diepgen
episode nonetheless confirmed the widespread appeal of the film's
speeding kaleidoscope of color, music and narrative techniques _
techniques that go beyond spoken language. ``Run Lola Run'' was one
of the two most popular German films of 1998 and had success
internationally as well: it shared the World Cinema Audience Award
at the Sundance Film Festival in January and was chosen to open the
recent New Directors/New Films series at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its daring, kinetic style, the film is succeeding in
Germany and elsewhere because it so effectively evokes a prevailing
cultural mood. ```Run Lola Run' symbolizes very much where we are
now, and especially where the young people in Germany are,'' said
Dieter Kosslick, executive director of the Filmstiftung
Nordrhein-Westfalen, a public agency in Duesseldorf that helped to
finance the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lola'' is the third feature directed by the 33-year-old
Tykwer, who conceived of it as a rebellious cry against what he
sees as the sclerotic society of today's Germany. ``I wanted to do
a film about the energy of my generation,'' he said recently in a
cafe near Lincoln Center, ``an energy which all too often is kept
bottled up inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very strong feeling among young people today that no
matter what we do, we can't change things anymore. After all,
Helmut Kohl was in power for 16 whole years in Germany. But with
`Lola,' I wanted to do a story of this energy breaking the chains
of our existence.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the movie is simple: by telephone, Lola learns
that her boyfriend, Manni (Moritz Bleibtreu), has lost a bag
containing 100,000 marks that he was supposed to give to his
sinister thug of a boss. Lola promises the desperate Manni that in
20 minutes she will come up with the money to save his life, and
she sets off, hurtling through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Tykwer creates three different versions of this
20-minute trajectory, with each version set at the same time but
unfolding differently and concluding with a different ending. ``I
wanted to make it feel like a completely classical drama,'' he
said. ``With three acts, and this big task where she has to get the
Holy Grail.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not three acts in a conventional sense, however, but
three versions of reality that blur the strictures of time and
space.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film was shot for only $2 million, Tykwer employed an
arsenal of techniques, from animation and split screen to the
alternation of film, video and still photography. ``I think Tykwer
is the first person since Fassbinder to do something radically
different in German cinema,'' said Laurence Kardish, curator of
film and video at the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer acknowledges that he was influenced by music videos and
video games, but he insists that his creative mix goes much
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``In asking the question `What can happen in your life, what
chances do you have?' I wanted also to ask the question `What
possibilities can there be in filmmaking?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In person, the director is both playful and serious, like his
movie. Tall and rangy, sporting a windbreaker, he has an
unpretentious sense of humor but also an unvarnished intensity. A
self-taught filmmaker who was a projectionist for 15 years, he has
always been drawn by what he calls ``elements of fate and
coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer's first feature, ``Deadly Maria'' (1993), is the caustic
depiction of a woman's attempt to free herself from an abusive
husband and an invalid father. ``Wintersleepers'' (1997) is a moody
study of four friends' interlocked relationships, set against the
wintry Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer also was a co-writer for the film ``Life Is All You Get''
(1997), a seriocomic portrait of Berliners directed by Wolfgang
Becker.
</P>
<P>
   All these films are different in style. ``Rather than just
trying a formula, Tom is someone who's inventing his own,'' said
Richard Pena, program director of the Film Society of Lincoln
Center, which presents the New Directors/New Films series with the
Modern.
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer's innovative career is a sign of a larger spirit of
expansion in the German film industry right now. He has made all of
his movies with the production company X-Filme Creative Pool, which
he and several other filmmakers formed in Berlin in 1994. Their
aim, as Stefan Arndt, Tykwer's producer, says, was ``to build a new
force for German films to be successful both in Germany and in
other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, there was barely any market for German films
within Germany itself. The box office was dominated by American
movies, as it is today. But with the blossoming of a new sort of
German relationship comedy _ films like Soenke Wortmann's ``Maybe
... Maybe Not'' (1994) and Rainer Kaufmann's ``Talk of the Town''
(1995) _ Germans started to return to German films. And with these
films came a new generation of directors and stars: directors like
Wortmann and Detlev Buck, actors like Til Schweiger and then Ms.
Potente and Bleibtreu.
</P>
<P>
   Although the comedies have continued in recent years, other
sorts of films are also gaining attention. Caroline Link's ``Beyond
Silence,'' a 1998 drama about a young musician with
hearing-impaired parents, was nominated for an Oscar. And, along
with ``Lola,'' Joseph Vilsmaier's ``Comedian Harmonists'' (released
in the United States as ``The Harmonists''), based on the true
story of a German singing group in Nazi Germany, was the most
successful German film of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The comedies brought us back our audience, and now we're going
in a more serious vein,'' said Kosslick.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately enough, given the themes in ``Lola,'' Tykwer made
the movie rather quickly, writing the script at the end of 1996 and
filming in the streets of Berlin in the summer of 1997. During the
shoot, the details in all three versions of Lola's 20-minute sprint
had to be consistent. ``We were terrified that the weather would
change,'' recalled Maria Kopf, the head of production.
</P>
<P>
   For the 24-year-old Ms. Potente, the film was a physical
workout. ``I'm a smoker,'' she confided at breakfast in New York
recently. With two-toned nail polish and her naturally dark hair
now blond for another role, Ms. Potente, in person, has a lot of
Lola's dynamism.
</P>
<P>
   To incarnate Lola, she dyed her hair and sported the vivid
hairdo for six weeks straight. ``Little babies loved it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer and Ms. Potente are now a couple, but they weren't at the
time the movie was made. Asked why he chose Ms. Potente for the
role, Tykwer said: ``I wanted this person to be believable.
Franka's not a trained runner; she's just normal. Both she and
Moritz are the biggest stars in Germany, but they both have this
incredible capacity to attract empathy.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Bleibtreu, who has a bright-eyed, hip assurance
quite unlike Manni's bumbling panic, recalled Tykwer's
thoroughness. ``Tom gave us maps of our characters detailing who is
Manni, where does he come from, what is his astrological sign,'' he
said over coffee at a Manhattan hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Both actors believe that the characters they play are typical of
Germany today. ``In Berlin, a lot of people look like Lola,'' said
Ms. Potente.
</P>
<P>
   Bleibtreu put it this way: ``There's this whole generation of
kids living for the day, not really knowing what they want to do
with their lives, getting money here and there. The only thing
Manni has is Lola.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, which Lola crisscrosses repeatedly, becomes a kind of
character in the film. ``This could take place in any major city of
the world,'' said Tykwer. ``But Berlin is the perfect match,
because Lola is someone who is running between times and Berlin
itself is a city between eras. The whole center of town is a
construction site.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tykwer now lives in Berlin, he grew up in Wuppertal,
near Duesseldorf, the son of a clothing salesman and a secretary.
Even as a child, he knew that he wanted to make films. At the age
of 10, he was creating Super-8 remakes of ``Godzilla,'' exploding
miniature houses in his backyard with firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 16, he was the projectionist at the movie
theater in Wuppertal. He would stay up every night watching movies
until dawn, then go to school. ``I can't tell you how many times I
fell asleep in my chair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tykwer did not get into film school, but he continued his film
education on his own. When he was 20, he moved to Berlin, where he
studied philosophy and became the programmer of an art house, the
Moviemento. It was there that he met Arndt, the programmer for a
rival movie house, the Sputnik. Eager to start making films, they
and the filmmakers Dani Levy and Wolfgang Becker founded X-Filme.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the success of ``Lola,'' Tykwer has been
receiving job offers from Hollywood. He has chosen not to go that
route, but he and his partners at X-Filme, interested in seeking
overseas financing, have made a development and coproduction
agreement with Miramax Films. Miramax will have a first look at all
X-Filme properties and will submit possible projects to X-Filme
members as well.
</P>
<P>
   Both Arndt and Tykwer, however, stress the importance of their
remaining German filmmakers who tell German stories. ``My next film
is a love story set in my hometown, Wuppertal,'' said Tykwer. ``I
really know my way around there, and I have some stories to tell
which I hope will be much more individual and special than if I
take a script and translate it and shoot it in Houston, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Production of the new film, ``The Princess and the Warrior,''
will start this summer, and if the title is any indication, it
should be quite different from ``Run Lola Run.'' The director will
say only that it's a contemporary love story, and that it will star
Ms. Potente.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a fair guess, however, that the film will touch on
the questions of fate and personal choice that interest Tykwer. He
gets reflective when asked to speculate further about the appeal of
``Lola.'' ``It's a film about passion, and the energy that comes
from passion,'' he said. ``I think a lot of people want to see a
film that believes in utopian elements. Utopian not in the
old-fashioned socialist sense, but in the sense of believing in the
power of inventiveness. The film invents its own system: it says,
`I don't care if the time is only 20 minutes, I'm going to make it
become 60 minutes.' Just as Lola says: `I don't care if I can't get
there. I'm just going to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
