<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ELECTION-475&AMP;ADDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA ELECTION RETURNS USHER IN A FUNDAMENTAL SHIFT IN POWER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Slow election returns left Indonesia in
suspense on Tuesday about the shape of its political future. But
whatever the outcome of Monday's vote, a fundamental shift in power
already seemed to be taking place: people were choosing their
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It was Indonesia's first free election in four decades, and in
thousands of towns and villages around the country, voters defied
the wishes of the officials who had ordered their lives for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny number of election returns on Tuesday showed the ruling
party, Golkar, trailing, and the opposition party of Megawati
Sukarnoputri in the lead. While anecdotal evidence and assessments
of some party leaders indicated that Golkar might be heading for
defeat, election analysts said that the numbers were still too
small to be significant.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports from Indonesian poll-watching groups indicated
that the voting had generally been free of manipulation and
intimidation, although the possibility of fraud in the tabulation
of votes remained.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the poll watchers said, Indonesians appeared
to be voting as they wished for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   What seemed to be changing _ hesitantly, tentatively _ was a
culture of subservience during President Suharto's 32 years in
power that had come to be known as ``A.B.S.,'' the Indonesian
initials for a phrase that translates roughly as, ``If it makes you
happy, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Suharto said, `You do it like that,' OK, OK, I'll do
anything for you,'' said Yeni Gayatri, a personnel manager. ``For
32 years it worked. And now _ we open our eyes now. Oh, it was so
silly.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a realization that seemed to take hold across the country
on election day.
</P>
<P>
   People in the town of Buaran Indah, a bedroom community for
civil servants 20 miles west of Jakarta, had never seen anything
like it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote began at polling place No. 1, Pana Supena, the
local Golkar chief, ordered and pointed, and local residents
listened deferentially. Then they voted against him, 396 to 55.
</P>
<P>
   Supena seemed to shrink in his seat as the ballots were opened
and announced, one by one, to the whoops and cheers of his
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onward!'' shouted a young man in an Einstein T-shirt each time
a vote was read for Mrs. Megawati's party, the Indonesian
Democratic Party of Struggle, which won the most votes here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Before the votes were cast, a 70-year-old retired engineer named
Mulana refused even to hint at his preference. After Golkar's
defeat, he could not seem to stop talking. ``I was full of hope
that this would happen,'' he said. ``This day was for my children
and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Parno, 49, a clerk in the Justice Ministry, said he had cast a
vote against the ruling party simply to assert his independence.
``The way they used to pressure people has turned everybody off of
Golkar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were similar moments at polling places in downtown Jakarta
and in the rice-farming villages that surround it.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Pakuhaji Kelapa, 25 miles west of Jakarta,
where the tart smoke of burning rice husks sweetened the air, the
Golkar poll watcher, Sainan, seemed at first to have more authority
than the election officials.
</P>
<P>
   But as the count was read, he hunched lower and lower over his
tally sheet and his right hand slid slowly across the page to hide
the shamefully small total.
</P>
<P>
   In the well-to-do Menteng district of Jakarta, where Suharto
himself voted on Monday, high-ranking officials and wealthy traders
turned against him en masse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is very special for us,'' said Lastry, 44, the
wife of a Foreign Ministry official, stepping carefully around
puddles from an early morning rain. ``Last time, we had to vote a
certain way because of my husband's government work. Now we can
choose any party we want.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But in a complicated process, Monday's vote will produce just
462 members of a 700-seat assembly that will choose the next
president later this year. The remainder of the seats will be
appointed rather than elected, and a long, unpredictable period of
coalition building, arm twisting and vote buying is expected.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight parties were on Monday's ballot, and both the
candidates and the voters had a jumble of agendas in this moment of
sudden political freedom. The votes against Golkar had similarly
varied roots, from economic hardship to democratic hopes to Islamic
idealism.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the voting seemed to express a shared desire for a
fresh start after a lifetime of repression under Suharto.
Anti-Golkar voters shared a common hope that is described here,
without further definition, as ``reform.''
</P>
<P>
   This was reason enough to vote against Golkar, said Johanes
Subandi, 51, a driver for the Justice Ministry who lives in Buaran
Indah. ``If we all voted the same way we did before,'' he said,
``it wouldn't be reform yet, would it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
