<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-CREDITCARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS URGE CONGRESS TO LIMIT STUDENT CREDIT CARD ISSUANCE. 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trisha Johnson said Tuesday that her daughter,
Mitzi Pool, might be alive today if she hadn't been bombarded with
credit card solicitations when she began her freshman year at the
University of Central Oklahoma in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pool was able to obtain three credit cards without her mother's
permission and racked up $2,500 in debt during her first semester.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, 1997, Pool called her mother to explain that she was
deep in credit card debt and didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $2,500 credit card debt does not sound like that much to
you or I, but for an 18-year-old trying to be an adult too fast,
$2,500 is devastating,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said she tried to assure her daughter that they would
figure out a way to pay the debt when she returned home to Enid,
Okla., for a weekend visit.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later Johnson received a call from police telling
her that Pool had committed suicide. Police found credit cards,
bills and a checkbook spread out over Pool's dorm-room bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credit card companies target these young adults just like
the tobacco industries,'' Johnson said. ``They lure them in and
then they have them hooked.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and consumer groups want Congress to require credit card
companies to obtain a parent's permission before issuing credit
cards to students under 21, most of whom have little or no outside
income. Parental permission would not be required if the students
can show the credit card issuers that they are financially
independent of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Such legislation may be considered when the Senate takes up a
bankruptcy reform bill later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The credit industry has worked to defeat similar legislation
last year. Visa U.S.A., a major credit card issuer, didn't take a
position on the proposal Tuesday but issued a statement that it is
working to educate young adults about responsible credit card use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visa feels it is important that consumers learn to properly
manage their finances at an early age,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brobeck, director of the Consumer Federation of America,
said many students are ill-equipped to handle credit card debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never been financially independent, they have modest
incomes and they have not received adequate financial
information,'' he said. ``Yet as early as freshman orientation they
are bombarded with credit offers from issuers who frequently extend
thousands of dollars of unaffordable credit lines.''
</P>
<P>
   One such advertisement offered a Visa credit card to students
with this pitch: ``Free from parental rule at last. Now all you
need is money. Cha-Ching.''
</P>
<P>
   Brobeck said the credit lines all seem ``so affordable'' to
students who are told they only have to pay a minimum monthly
payment that is often as little as $10. The problem is with
interest rates that can be as high as 20 percent the amount of the
debt can quickly grow if only the minimum monthly payment is made.
</P>
<P>
   Janne O'Donnell, of Norman, Okla., also lost a child to what she
said is the ``aggressive marketing tactics used by credit card
companies that prey on kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Sean Moyer, had more than $10,000 in debt on 12 credit
cards before he committed suicide on Feb. 7, 1998, at age 22.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer earned a full academic scholarship to the University of
Texas at Dallas and worked at a part-time job earning $5.15 an hour
to pay for non-academic expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so bright about so many things but so stupid when it
came to managing his money,'' O'Donnell said of her son, who later
transferred to the University of Oklahoma. ``How those companies
can justify giving credit cards to a person making $5.15 an hour is
beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell also faults universities and colleges for allowing the
credit card companies to aggressively market credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't attend a college event without seeing credit card
booths giving students gifts for signing up,'' she said. ``The
University of Oklahoma's (Internet) web page allows a student to
sign up without asking how much money they make...(but) they ask
how many of the student's other credit cards they want to transfer
to the new card.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Manning, a sociology professor at Georgetown University
who has studied student credit-card use, said credit card firms
like Visa U.S.A. Inc., often sponsor various school activities. In
some cases a school receives a small percentage of students'
purchases when the school has a deal with a credit card issuer to
market a card with the school's name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Manning estimates that about 70 percent of college-age students
have credit cards. He explained that many students quickly run up
hundreds of dollars in debt on one card, then realize how easy it
is get other credit cards while making minimum payments on each
card, which only increases their indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
   According to Manning, if a person has $1,500 debt and pays $25 a
month at 19.8 percent interest, it would take 282 months.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
