are bombarded with credit offers from issuers who frequently extend
thousands of dollars of unaffordable credit lines.''
</P>
<P>
   One such advertisement offered a Visa credit card to students
with this pitch: ``Free from parental rule at last. Now all you
need is money. Cha-Ching.''
</P>
<P>
   Brobeck said the credit lines all seem ``so affordable'' to
students who are told they only have to pay a minimum monthly
payment that is often as little as $10. The problem is with
interest rates that can be as high as 20 percent the amount of the
debt can quickly grow if only the minimum monthly payment is made.
</P>
<P>
   Janne O'Donnell, of Norman, Okla., also lost a child to what she
said is the ``aggressive marketing tactics used by credit card
companies that prey on kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Sean Moyer, had more than $10,000 in debt on 12 credit
cards before he committed suicide on Feb. 7, 1998, at age 22.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer earned a full academic scholarship to the University of
Texas at Dallas and worked at a part-time job earning $5.15 an hour
to pay for non-academic expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so bright about so many things but so stupid when it
came to managing his money,'' O'Donnell said of her son, who later
transferred to the University of Oklahoma. ``How those companies
can justify giving credit cards to a person making $5.15 an hour is
beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell also faults universities and colleges for allowing the
credit card companies to aggressively market credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't attend a college event without seeing credit card
booths giving students gifts for signing up,'' she said. ``The
University of Oklahoma's (Internet) web page allows a student to
sign up without asking how much money they make...(but) they ask
how many of the student's other credit cards they want to transfer
to the new card.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Manning, a sociology professor at Georgetown University
