<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7650 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SCENE-1STLD-WR     06-08 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SCENE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SERBIAN HOLY LAND, FEARS OF AN AVENGING KLA 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: FIXES dateline to Yugoslavia sted Serbia.) 
 (rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVO POLJE, Serbia _ This is the place where the Serbian
national consciousness was born in a noble slaughter, and the Serbs
of Kosovo Polje are both anxious and defiant. They are less
concerned about the imminent influx of NATO soldiers than about the
Kosovo Liberation Army and the Albanian capacity for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Serbs who may live in more isolated villages here in
Kosovo, these Serbs, only a few miles from the capital, Pristina,
are not ready to leave their homes and businesses and begin new
lives as refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is holy Serbian land,'' said Ljubisa Lazic, 53, a jovial
telephone inspector who suddenly turned serious. ``Our churches and
our graves are like a stop sign to us _ they don't let us leave
here. If we did, we would be damned anywhere in the world we go,
both us and our children.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Petar Rapajic, scoffs at such fervor, blaming the
disaster of Kosovo on bad leadership in Belgrade, Washington and
London that allowed the rise of the KLA. But he also acknowledges
that many Serbs have behaved criminally here in this war against
the Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Rapajic has no intention of leaving Kosovo, he said, but in the
last few days other Serbs have begun to depart. On Tuesday, driving
south from Belgrade, numerous Serbian cars, with belongings packed
on their roofs, were passed heading north toward central Serbia.
There were also at least 10 large trucks and buses filled with
soldiers and military equipment also leaving Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbs are afraid, and for good reason,'' Rapajic said. ``There
are a lot of burned houses and destroyed lives, and they fear
revenge. They did a lot of bad things to the Albanians that
shouldn't have been done _ killings and burnings _ and they're
afraid that the KLA will appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about the Serbian army and police withdrawing
from Kosovo, he said: ``The problem isn't that they are leaving.
The problem is if the KLA comes in. People aren't afraid of NATO or
the United Nations, but of the KLA. And they're not sure that the
foreigners will protect them or fight the KLA. After all, NATO
fought for the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The defining myth of Serbian statehood is here in this region,
on Kosovo Polje, the field of blackbirds, where the Serbs lost
nobly to the Turks 610 years ago this month. The Serbian commander,
Prince Lazar, is revered as a saint, but few here are willing to
give the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, that much
reverence.
</P>
<P>
   A young woman, a Serb who would not give her name, said she
would leave Kosovo. She was very anxious about the future, and
furious about this defeat. ``I will kill him,'' she said softly and
slowly, referring to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that his policies had produced Serbian refugees before,
from Bosnia and Croatia, she said: ``It doesn't matter. I will kill
him for all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapajic, 47, owns four auto service stores and rents another
here. He lives in Devet-Jugovica, a mixed Serbian-Albanian village
8 miles north of Pristina, and he described matter-of-factly how
Serbian paramilitary police burned Albanian houses, sometimes
helped by Serbian neighbors, and how the KLA had killed a man and
his two sons in front of their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have traumas,'' he said. ``It can't be that the KLA comes to
a house and murders a family, and Serbs can't burn and steal and
loot. God gave no one the right to do these things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapajic said that the Albanians of his village had fled out of
fear, but that when he attempted to stop the burning of their empty
homes, he was nearly shot by the police. ``They said I was a
traitor to my people and they pointed their guns at me,'' he said.
``So I stepped back.'' It may have been brave, he acknowledged.
``But I don't know how clever it was. But I built my house myself,
and I felt on my skin what it is to build a house.''
</P>
<P>
   When he kept a car for an Albanian friend who fled, Rapajic was
interrogated by 20 military policemen who searched his house.
``They wanted to know how many Albanians I know, how I know them,
why I drove them around,'' he said. ``They asked me for a satellite
telephone and almost said I was working against the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped, laughing. ``I don't even know what a satellite
telephone looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   The police took the car, which they insisted was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   But Rapajic also believes that NATO's decision to bomb set off
the worst of the catastrophe, enraging Serbs against the Albanians
and giving them the pretext for terrible crimes. And this solution,
he says, ``won't solve the problem of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   That is rooted in competing claims to the land, he said, ``and
there is a lot of hatred now.'' Like many Serbs, he would prefer to
divide Kosovo and give the Albanians their own territory, but he
acknowledges that it may be too late for that.
</P>
<P>
   Dragisa Nikolic is prepared to keep fighting. Now 43, he was
mobilized into the army and was wounded May 19 by a KLA sniper near
Grabovac, in the Cicavica mountains only 15 miles northwest of
Pristina. Three more members of his 11-man patrol were wounded in
the same KLA ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Only Monday, he said, a friend of his from here, Marko Vujacic,
37, with three children, was killed, shot in the head by a sniper
100 yards from where Nikolic was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, driving toward the Macedonian border town of Djeneral
Jankovic, an Israeli journalist, Ron Ben-Yishai of Yediot Aharonot,
and a Serbian driver, Ivan Cvejic, were wounded near Kacanik when
their car was fired upon by snipers.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA is still a big problem,'' Nikolic said, his arm in a
sling and his dogtag poking out over his black polo shirt. ``I'll
fight them again, and I won't leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he believe that NATO forces will demilitarize the KLA?
``NATO will demilitarize us, not the KLA,'' he said. ``NATO works
for them.'' But he said he would not try to fight the peacekeeping
forces. ``Our struggle is not with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His friend, Boza Tadic, says he will also stay and take his
chance. He is one of the hundreds of thousands of Serbs ethnically
purged from Croatia in 1995 and resettled in Kosovo. ``So where do
I go now?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Two young men, Aleksandar Zivic, 18, and Milan Stanovic, 17,
said they were very nervous, and so were their parents, who talk a
lot about leaving. Zivic's father and Stanovic's father and brother
have been mobilized and are ``in the field'' with the army, and the
young men are very worried about them, too, as the bombing campaign
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life might become impossible here,'' Zivic said. Why?
``Because the Albanians will be on top.'' And what might they do?
Stanovic said: ``Maybe worse things than what we did to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
