<P>
   JOGGING SHEEP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLLEYVILLE, Texas _ This is the ram-bunctious tale of the
Smullin family, postmodern shepherds who prefer city streets to
hilly green pastures and running shoes to the traditional 6-foot
wood staff. Almost every morning for three years, they have enjoyed
a jog through their upscale neighborhood _ followed by sheep. By
MATT FRAZIER. Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T E X A S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHAPMAN-TEXAS AT LARGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Fort Worth is in the middle of a birthday
party. There have been sesquicentennial fireworks and music _
ranging from Motown to cattle calls. Remembering Fort Worth's past
has been the focus; rediscovering the people and places that made
the city a success has been the goal. That goal has been
accomplished mostly in the smaller events. Events like the
dedication of a new flagpole or the unveiling of the new horse
fountain at the Tarrant County Courthouse. By ART CHAPMAN. Story
has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   L I F E S T Y L E &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-INTERNET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Someday soon, you will be able to dial
``star'' DR (''star'' 37) on your push-button phone, ask your
medical questions, and get within hours personalized answers from a
doctor who specializes in your medical problems. The telephone,
that most basic of communication tools, is being integrated with
computer software, radio and television to get consumers the
medical information they want when they want it. ``Information
exchange is going to be `the issue' in medicine for at least the
next 20 years,'' says Dr. Bob Lanier, physician-broadcaster and
president-elect of the Tarrant County Medical Society, who is
already aggressively using the Internet to provide information for
a growing number of people with health-care concerns. By CAROLYN
POIROT. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
