<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERTRUDE-STEIN-ART-2T     06-08 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERTRUDE-STEIN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLAY DEPICTS THE LIFE AND LOVE OF GERTRUDE STEIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a blinding hot day in 1908, Gertrude Stein and
Alice B. Toklas climbed a hill above the Italian town of Fiesole,
where both were spending the summer. There was tension in the air,
a powerful attraction; there were unanswered questions. Stopping in
the heat, the two had a conversation. In the onrush of feelings, in
the way of people newly in love who want to make a clean break from
the past, they told each other about the people they had loved
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't Nelly and Lilly love you?'' Stein asked, referring to
two of Toklas' intimate friends. Toklas' answer is unknown, but
evidently it was satisfactory because Stein asked Toklas to marry
her. Thus began a relationship that was to endure for 38 years,
with Stein referring to herself as ``husband'' and to Toklas as
``wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't Nelly and Lilly Love you?'' The question Stein asked
that day runs like a refrain _ allusive, insistent _ through
``Gertrude and Alice: A Likeness to Loving,'' a new play about the
women that opens Wednesday night at the Signature Theater here.
</P>
<P>
   The play, directed by Anne Bogart, is a production of the
Foundry Theater, and it gives perhaps the most intimate look yet at
a friendship that was sensual, tempestuous and supremely enabling,
with Toklas as Stein's lover, editor, secretary, housekeeper and
cook. It stars Lola Pashalinski as Stein and Linda Chapman as
Toklas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pashalinski and Ms. Chapman also created the play, from the
stream of references to the relationship in Stein's published and
unpublished writings. They were assisted by a prominent Stein
scholar, Ulla Dydo, with credit also going to Bill Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Likeness to Loving'' is but one sign of Stein's enduring
influence as a writer who broke apart the language _ out of a
passion, she wrote in ``The Autobiography of Alice B. Toklas,''
``for exactitude in the description of inner and outer reality.''
Stein, who was born 125 years ago, saw herself as nothing less than
one of the creators of 20th-century art and literature. And Paris
was at the center of that genesis. At her home at 27 Rue de
Fleurus, Stein nourished Picasso, Juan Gris, Matisse, Hemingway,
Sherwood Anderson, F. Scott Fitzgerald and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us balk at her soporific rigmaroles, her echolaliac
incantations, her half-witted sounding catalogs of numbers,''
Edmund Wilson wrote in ``Axel's Castle'' in 1931. Yet ``we are
always aware of her presence in the background of contemporary
literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Stein is seen as a precursor of postmodernism and as a
feminist icon. Last year two large volumes of Stein's writings,
edited by Catharine Stimpson, were published by the Library of
America. And in February a scholarly conference at Washington
University in St. Louis assessed her influence on avant-garde
fiction, poetry and film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serious criticism about Stein is expanding at a great rate,''
Ms. Stimpson said. ``She is a pop icon, a reference when people
want to talk about repetition, Paris and the bohemian life, and
increasingly, when you want to talk about alternate ways of
loving.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein's legacy can be felt in the work of Language poets like
Lyn Hejinian, Bernadette Mayer, Leslie Scalapino and Clark
Coolidge, poets as interested in language itself as in the content
of poetry. Stein has had a powerful effect, too, on writers like
Donald Barthelme and William Gass who have questioned the
fundamental forms of fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``She taught me more than any other writer,'' Gass said. He
offered a Stein sentence as an example: ``It looked like a garden,
but he had hurt himself by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's skewing syntax to open up what's going on in the
sentence,'' Gass said. ``She arranged language spatially rather
than temporally.'' She played with the book form. For instance, she
would write two sentences and call that a volume, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had this sense of the phenomenon of reading, that reading
is interrupted, recursive, looping all the time,'' Gass said. He
added that Stein had influenced his novel ``The Tunnel,'' with its
streams of similar scenes, each one slightly rewritten and
different from the last.
</P>
<P>
   The new play takes on the nonlinear form of Stein's own writing.
Like Stein and Toklas, the stars, Ms. Pashalinski, 63, and Ms.
Chapman, 48, are ``partners in life,'' Ms. Chapman said. They have
been together 19 years and are fixtures of downtown theater. Ms.
Pashalinski was a founding member with Charles Ludlam of the
Ridiculous Theatrical Company. Ms. Chapman was an associate of the
Wooster Group and is associate artistic director of the New York
Theater Workshop.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the lives of Ms. Pashalinski and Ms. Chapman
mirror those of Stein and Toklas. They met when each was breaking
away from an old existence. Ms. Pashalinski had just left the
Ridiculous Theatrical Company. ``I had a need to strike out on my
own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chapman had come to New York from Spokane, Wash., to be an
actor, but hated the life of the commercial theater. ``I was a
little lost,'' she said. She became general manager of the Theater
for a New City. ``I was starting to reinvent myself,'' Ms. Chapman
said. She was also married to a man. ``Lola was very suspicious of
me. It took a while to win her trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship grew gradually, ``while we were having a lot of
laughs,'' Ms. Pashalinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``our relationship is much more free-form than theirs,''
Ms. Chapman said, referring to Stein and Toklas. ``They played
fairly rigid roles'' _ and not without irony, she said. In the
play, ``I reflect that you reflect about me,'' Stein says to
Toklas, and Toklas responds: ``I reflect what you reflect about
me.''
</P>
<P>
   The play begins with their meeting in Paris, where Stein was
living with her overbearing brother Leo, who disdained her writing.
In an interview that has been incorporated into the play, Toklas
remembered: ``Gertrude had a certain physical beauty and enormous
power. Definitely. She sat there and said nothing _as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Stein's initial impression of Toklas was less
complimentary. ``The whole of her is made up of every conceivable
kind of weakness, crookedness,'' she says in the play, based on a
passage in an unpublished notebook. ``Every thing induces
crookedness, the practical sense, the melodramatic imagination, the
passion for vulgar beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Toklas moved in, and eventually Stein's brother moved out.
Toklas' belief in Stein's talent was uncompromising. She rose early
to type Stein's writing while Stein slept late. ``Sweet pinky,''
Toklas says, in words from the margin of one of Stein's
manuscripts, ``you made lots of literature last night, didn't
you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of time to be a genius; you have to sit around
so much doing nothing,'' Stein said. When famous men visited,
Toklas entertained their wives so Stein could talk to the other
geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   Stein's first published book, ``Three Lives,'' came out in 1909.
But her writing was nearly impossible to publish. It took 17 years
to publish ``The Making of Americans: Being a History of a Family's
Progress'' (1925), her attempt to tell the story of the human race.
And in 1914 she herself paid for the publication of ``Tender
Buttons: Objects, Food, Rooms,'' essentially ``cubist'' writing
about familiar objects.
</P>
<P>
   At the outbreak of World War I, Stein and Toklas went to
Majorca, where they were truly alone for the first time. ``My wife
is my life is my life is my wife,'' Stein says in the play. In her
writing, Stein used the image of a cow to talk about their
relationship. ``Have a cow, now, not now but later,'' Stein says in
``A Likeness to Loving.'' ``Later means sooner and sooner means
better and better means fuller.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the writers whom Stein and Toklas had nurtured
began to achieve success. But they were not helping Stein. ``The
need for recognition for both had gotten to a critical mass,'' Ms.
Pashalinski said. Stein and Toklas turned them away. Virgil
Thomson, who wrote the music for the Stein operas ``Four Saints in
Three Acts'' and ``The Mother of Us All,'' was dismissed with a
note: ``Miss Stein declines further acquaintance with Thomson,''
Stein declares in the play.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932 came a crisis. Toklas discovered an unpublished
manuscript of Stein's first novel, ``QED,'' which told of an affair
with a woman named May Bookstaver before Stein met Toklas. Toklas
confronted Stein in a frenzy of jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   As presented in the play, Stein, in a gesture of reconciliation,
wrote ``The Autobiography of Alice B. Toklas.'' In the book,
published in 1933, Stein assumes Toklas' voice to tell her own
story. The autobiography ``enables Ms. Stein to write about herself
while pretending she is someone clearly devoted to herself,'' the
critic Robert Cantwell wrote. It was the easiest of Stein's books
to comprehend, her only best seller.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, after the success of ``Four Saints in Three
Acts,'' Stein and Toklas toured the United States and were received
as the celebrities they had always wanted to be _ or wanted Stein
to be. ``Gertrude was one of the early inventors of self-promotion
as we know it today,'' Ms. Chapman said. ``She knew how to use the
media before it was commonly done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Likeness to Loving'' draws to a close with words from a
Stein book, ``Everybody's Autobiography'': ``And then gradually it
was ending and we went out and on to the stage, and there where I
never had been with everything in front all dark and we bowing and
all of them coming and going and bowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the victory was Pyrrhic. ``She became famous, but not for
her real writing,'' Ms. Pashalinski said. ``And she never went back
to that kind of experimental writing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein died in 1946. Toklas lived until 1967, vigilantly guarding
Stein's legacy, and is buried beside Stein in Pere Lachaise
Cemetery in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was everything, it was all over and we went back to sit
down,'' Stein says at the end of the play. ``I guess it was a great
success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
