</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LET US NOW PRAISE THIS FAMOUS CITY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the opening of the New Yorker's Talk of the Town piece about
San Francisco's new Metreon complex,  &UR; Lillian Ross  &LR; gives the city
a high five:
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, she writes, ``seems to have the U.S.A.'s tidiest
homes and garages, the fewest potholes, the freshest salads and the
most communal enthusiasm for projects.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted, for the record, that the author of this
enthusiastic endorsement spent a few weeks here recently but lives
in New York, where most potholes are craters that seem to have been
created by meteorites the size of Yankee Stadium. While Ross is
probably qualified to judge the comparative merits of salads, her
pothole credentials may be spurious. She admits that she tries to
avoid driving in San Francisco because of the hills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARE YOU HIP? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post got hold of a test given to prospective
employees of Interview magazine to see how hip they are.
</P>
<P>
   Among the figures candidates are asked to identify in the pop
culture quiz:  &UR; Tina Brown &LR; ,  &UR; Bridget Hall &LR; ,  &UR; Barry Diller &LR; ,  &UR; Faith &LR; 
 &UR; Popcorn &LR; ,  &UR; Francesco Clemente &LR; ,  &UR; Ellen von Unwerth &LR; ,  &UR; Donna Tartt &LR; ,
 &UR; Peter Lynch &LR;  and  &UR; Michael Richards &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   (FYI: Talk magazine editor, model, USA Networks chief, futurist,
painter, photographer, novelist, former Fidelity Magellan fund
manager and Kramer on ``Seinfeld.'')
</P>
<P>
   And if you thought you were smart when you read that, who was
 &UR; Teri Toye &LR; ? (See Flash.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Shooting is about to begin on ``Battleship Earth,'' a movie
based on a science fiction novel by Scientology founder  &UR; L. Ron &LR; 
 &UR; Hubbard &LR; .  &UR; John Travolta &LR; , who is a Scientologist, told the New
York Daily News that the movie is being made because he pushed for
it. ``It's the pinnacle of using my power for something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   - The Wolfsonian Museum in Miami explains that the Farouk
matchbook collection _ long owned by the museum _ was shown to
teenagers as part of an Artful Truth program ``to teach kids about
messages in visual culture.'' Money for that program came from a
settlement with tobacco companies, but Farouk's collection was used
to inspire teens to make their own anti-smoking matchboxes.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sammy Sosa &LR;  has signed with  &UR; Joe &LR;  and  &UR; Gene Silverberg &LR; , who
run a restaurant bearing the name of  &UR; Michael Jordan &LR; , to open a
Sammy Sosa restaurant in Chicago, says the Chicago Sun-Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Stan Floride &LR;  will be there when RWS (Release When Sober), a
rock 'n' roll and country band whose members are cops at the Park
Station in San Francisco, plays at 1 p.m. Sunday at Belvedere and
Haight at the Haight Street Fair. A colleague told Personals they
never play in uniform, but their attire will be a special surprise
``to add to their mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Vanessa Brown  &LR; was listening to the KALW quiz show ``Minds
Over Matter'' when she and her boyfriend were picked up at her
house by a cab, so she asked the driver to tune into the show
during the ride. She was frustrated when the cab arrived at her
destination before one of the questions was answered. A few days
later, she got a postcard addressed to ``Trivia Fans'' from driver
 &UR; Jim Battles &LR; , giving her the answer (and much happiness and
delight).
</P>
<P>
   - That Subaru ad that featured the Colorado plates with a
rainbow logo presented a few other gay icons, too, notes  &UR; Cass &LR; 
 &UR; Brayton &LR; : Another plate said XENA LVR, and a third, from Colorado,
said PTOWNIE (for Provincetown, a Cape Cod town popular with gays).
Meanwhile,  &UR; J.D. Ecklebarger &LR;  spotted a Subaru in the Castro with
the license plate CMON OUT.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Teri Toye  &LR; was a transsexual runway model in the '80s, who
got married and moved to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Size doesn't matter. It's technique. One trick is to expand
your stomach by drinking a lot of water for two or three days
before. Also, you have to crunch the bun, make it as small as you
can, and take a lot of small bites.''
</P>
<P>
   - George Shea &LR; , maestro of the annual Fourth of July &LR; 
 &LR; hot-dog-eating contest in Coney Island, N.Y., quoted in &LR; 
 &LR; Smithsonian magazine. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
