<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELGIUM-FOODSCANDAL-N     06-08 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGIUM-FOODSCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIUM'S FOOD SCANDAL IS LATEST IN A LITANY OF WOES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The chicken definitely came first in
Belgium, then the egg _ followed by pork, veal, beef, and now even
milk, cheese and butter.
</P>
<P>
   Belgians are having trouble finding any of these things on the
market unless they are imported. Millions of dollars' worth of
Belgian-produced meat and dairy products are being sent to
incinerators in a widening crisis caused by the unexplained
contamination of animal feed by poisonous dioxin chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   In a country with more Michelin-starred restaurants per capita
than France, it is hard to imagine a calamity that would strike
harder at the national solar plexus, except possibly a revelation
that Belgium's famous beer was being watered down.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene's coalition
government in a national election on Sunday is now uncertain, with
a fifth of voters indicating in surveys that the scandal will
affect their decisions at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Politics aside, supermarket meat and poultry shelves are empty,
fish prices are soaring, restaurant menus are as misleading as they
used to be in the Soviet Union, where ``there isn't any'' seemed to
be the national dish. Pity the poor gourmand, who can't even fall
back on mussels, because they're out of season now.
</P>
<P>
   In Luc Selicq's butcher shop, the Boucherie-Charcuterie Paul off
the famous Grand' Place in Brussels, it was slim pickings on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got good American horse meat, a lot better than the
Argentine stuff I used to sell,'' Selicq said on Tuesday morning,
his display cases half empty for lack of anything edible to put in
them. ``We can still sell lamb, and beef when we can get it from
other countries, but all I know is what I hear on the radio _ we
have no official information from the government at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Bennie, a regular customer at Paul's, took a couple of
beefsteaks from Ireland, and hazarded a veal cutlet that Selicq
said he could still sell because it had been certified free of
dioxin. ``Stay away from the fat,'' he cautioned anyway, ``because
that's where any dioxin would be concentrated.''
</P>
<P>
   How the dioxin got into chicken and animal feed is under police
investigation. The suspicion is that this is one more in a
never-ending series of malfeasances, part of the cronyism,
corruption and Civil Service incompetence that have been almost a
way of life in Belgium for most of the last 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The father and son owners of the company to whose products the
problem was first traced, Jean and Lucien Verkest of the
agricultural center of Deinze, have been in preventive detention
since last week. They are suspected of having knowingly fabricated
or bought from Dutch suppliers feed grain mixed with cheap,
second-hand oil or fat that turned out to be contaminated with
dioxin. The tainted feed was sold to 1,400 producers in this
country and others in France and the Netherlands, authorities
believe.
</P>
<P>
   The Verkests' lawyers deny the accusations, but Belgian
agricultural inspectors are also being faulted for not checking
feed more closely. And authorities of the 15-nation European Union,
which is based in Brussels, wonder why it took two months for the
Belgian authorities to inform them about the problem once they
finally did discover it, in March.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union countries have now banned the export of most
major food products from Belgium, including things like mayonnaise,
offering to lift the ban if the Belgians can provide them with a
list of producers they can certify as being free of dioxin
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the government led by Dehaene, a Christian Democrat from
the Flemish-speaking northern part of the country, has been unable
to provide one. But the government said on Tuesday that it would do
so in a couple of days, and, in the meantime, let cleared items go
back on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion has caused hundreds of millions of dollars in
agricultural losses that will probably have to be footed by Belgian
and European taxpayers. The United States and some Asian countries
have banned agricultural products from all over Europe as a
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   European officials are furious with the Belgians, accusing the
government of informing the rest of the Continent about the problem
only two months after it was first discovered by a Health Ministry
veterinarian in March. The ministers of health and agriculture
resigned early this month. This week, Dehaene, 59 and prime
minister for seven years, described the crisis as the most serious
of his long political career.
</P>
<P>
   But Belgium, a creation of 19th-century European
balance-of-power politics that the French historian Jules Michelet
said never was a true nation and never would be, has also been in
crisis in recent years, demoralized by demonstrations of
incompetence by other national institutions like the police.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred thousand people demonstrated in the streets of
Brussels in late 1996 demanding change after disclosures that
police incompetence and, many people suspected, corruption had
allowed a pedophile serial killer, Marc Dutroux, to escape arrest
until after he had killed five little girls.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last year, three former government ministers,
including Willy Claes, who had been secretary-general of NATO, were
convicted of having taken bribes from an Italian helicopter
company, Agosta, and the French aviation giant, Dassault, in
Belgian military contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium seems less one nation today than ever. The 5.9 million
people of Flanders, the increasingly prosperous and self-assertive
northern part of the country where the language is close to Dutch,
feel they have little in common with the 3.3 million people of
Wallonia, the French-speaking southern half of the country that was
an industrial dynamo a century ago but is now a rust belt. Nearly a
million more people live in Brussels, historically Flemish
territory but now populated mostly by French-speakers.
</P>
<P>
   If Flemings and Walloons ever took to using guns against each
other, in fact, Belgium could fall into the kind of violence that
has torn apart Bosnia or Kosovo, a sobering realization that has
dampened separatist passions in the election campaign. They do
share an aversion to violence, however, along with a love of good
food, but that looks unlikely to be satisfied for a while yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
