<HEADER>
A7679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABBEY-FRIEL-NYT &LR;      06-08 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABBEY-FRIEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIME FOR CALM IN IRELAND AND A NEW VIEW OF FRIEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ After 26 years of neglect, the Abbey Theater
is enthusiastically reviving Brian Friel's most political play,
``The Freedom of the City,'' set in the sectarian warfare of
contemporary Northern Ireland. The play has been well received by
audiences and critics in a Friel festival at the Abbey and will
move to the Lincoln Center Festival in New York on July 7 for a
brief run.
</P>
<P>
   Its long absence has been attributed to its bluntness at a time
when violence was raging between majority Protestants and minority
Roman Catholics in the British province and the Irish and British
governments were trying, and failing, to make peace. The play had
brief runs in Dublin and London in 1973 and on Broadway in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The Abbey, Ireland's heavily subsidized national theater, was
reluctant to put on ``Freedom'' because it was perceived by some
critics as an exercise in Britain-bashing and because Dublin
audiences preferred not to dwell on the killing in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Friel, 70, a Roman Catholic born in Northern Ireland, now lives
in County Donegal near the border with Northern Ireland. He wrote
``Freedom'' in 1973, a year after the British army shot and killed
14 Roman Catholics at a civil rights demonstration in Londonderry
in what became known as Bloody Sunday. A British inquiry exonerated
the soldiers and suggested that the demonstrators were terrorists
linked to the Irish Republican Army. Decades later the British
government conceded that the demonstrators were innocent and had
not attacked the army, but no action was taken against the
soldiers. A new investigation is under way, partly as a result of
the peace effort that is moving forward in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Mason, 48, the Abbey's artistic director, and Conall
Morrison, the director of ``Freedom,'' say that the play also
reveals a neglected aspect of Friel, who is widely considered
Ireland's best living playwright. For decades, they said in
interviews, Friel has been favorably compared to Chekhov and
Pirandello. ``But there's also a political Friel who knows how to
use the theater as politically as Bertolt Brecht,'' said Mason, who
is leaving his job at the Abbey at the end of the year. ``He has a
range beyond his Chekhovian aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison, 33, who grew up in a Roman Catholic family in Northern
Ireland and is a candidate to succeed Mason, said that ``Freedom''
was ``not remotely'' an anti-British diatribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It blows a hole the size of Manhattan in the perceived image
of Brian Friel'' as a writer whose work must be filtered through
that of Chekhov, Pirandello or even Brecht,'' Morrison said,
adding: ``He's Brian Friel. He's his own genre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is political with a small p, Morrison said of ``Freedom.''
In the play, three innocent demonstrators are shot by British
soldiers who are absolved through an inquiry in which participants
refer to the dead as terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wonder of the play is that while it feels like a broad
Brechtian flag-waving piece, it is actually a very astute,
insightful, very detailed examination of the nature of
individuality,'' Morrison said. Individuals get ignored or abused
or destroyed by the state, by the so-called collective will, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a superb examination of the concept of truth,'' he
continued. ``How so many people will have so many versions of the
same story, which they believe to be wholly objective, wholly
moral, wholly truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, events are manipulated by Roman Catholic
nationalists, a British judge, an Irish reporter and a priest, each
with his own ideological ax to grind.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper photographs of the real Bloody Sunday are blown up on
a screen behind the stage, and there are convincingly violent
skirmishes between the army and the demonstrators. There is dark
humor in the chat of the demonstrators as they sit in the mayor's
ornate office and drink his liquor, trying to avoid the line of
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Their heavy Ulster accents will be tempered for the American
audience. Morrison, who has also written plays set amid the
violence of Northern Ireland, recalled watching the IRA recruit his
school friends, with some of them ending up in jail or in coffins.
He was never tempted to join, he said, and once considered the IRA
``a bunch of madmen.'' Later he concluded that the violence had
roots in Irish history and English colonialism. He is a strong
supporter of John Hume, the mainstream Roman Catholic head of the
Social Democratic and Labor Party in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison has been commissioned to make a play out of Joseph
Conrad's novel ``Under Western Eyes,'' in which he will introduce a
Unabomber character to the plot. The possibility of becoming
artistic director of the Abbey was attractive, partly because ``it
would be an excellent excuse not to write,'' he said. ``Writing is
hard. Directing is an easier task. I read so many scripts by people
who have nothing to say. I do not want to add to the slush pile.''
</P>
<P>
   The best advice he has received on writing, he said, came 16
years ago after he sent a script to Friel, who is married to
Morrison's father's sister, Anne. ``He didn't encourage me, but he
was very polite,'' Morrison said. ``He wrote a list of principles
of writing. Now I can't find the letter, but I remember one phrase:
Don't tell me, show me.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RETURN-0609-CO     06-08 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RETURN-0609-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IMMINENT RETURN OF KOSOVARS PUTS RELIEF AGENCIES IN HOT PLANNING
MODE
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0609.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ As thousands of tons of food sit waiting to
be loaded onto trucks bound for Kosovo, the aid workers who will
take it are laying plans first for how to find and feed the
half-million Kosovar Albanians believed to be still hiding in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Then they will have to care for the more than 800,000 refugees
who want to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're assuming the worst,'' said Abby Spring of the U.N. World
Food Programme (WFP), speaking of internally displaced families.
``People have been foraging around for food for weeks. As each day
goes by, their condition is worsening.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Sunday's collapse of negotiations that would mandate
immediate Yugoslav troop withdrawal from Kosovo and finally the
return of the refugees was such a setback to humanitarian agencies
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to go in,'' said Nancy Shalala, who works with
Catholic Relief Services. ``It was demoralizing.''
</P>
<P>
   A morale-booster for humanitarian workers as well as refugees
may be a visit later this week by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, especially if a deal finally has been struck between NATO
and Yugoslavia. While her visit drops a heavy logistical burden on
groups already deep in work, it also may energize them for the hard
task ahead.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting the emergency needs of outgoing Kosovar refugees
who surged across the borders here and in Albania, now the world's
relief organizations are trying to plan strategies to help those
who never made it out, as well as get the refugees back home
without starving.
</P>
<P>
   That may not be so easy in a territory the size of Connecticut
where unknown numbers of homes have been burned, means of
livelihood trashed, and two-thirds of the fields never planted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no pesticides or fertilizers, no harvest this
year,'' Spring said. ``There's no farm equipment. The livestock has
been killed or stolen or eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   There also are fears about landmines left by retreating Serb-led
Yugoslav troops and potential booby traps for returning Kosovars,
such as explosives left in homes or poison in wells.
</P>
<P>
   At least, aid workers have some time to get ready for a change.
</P>
<P>
   So groups like Catholic Relief Services are amassing food and
trucks and drivers, and their leaders are picking the areas where
they believe the most vulnerable people will be found.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said the Catholic agency is ready to supply preliminary
aid even before a master plan by the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees kicks into gear.
</P>
<P>
   That plan divides Kosovo into regions and assigns a
non-governmental organization to run each sector, much as refugee
camps have been run here and in Albania. It also parallels the
tentative military scheme dividing Kosovo into five areas, putting
each area under peacekeeping troops of a different nation.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Relief has 40 trucks ready to roll, and the WFP has
about as many. The latter also plans helicopter and truck rescue
units to search for displaced people who fled their homes under
attack or fear of it, and have been living in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Both agencies expect to be among the vanguard, once NATO troops
say the roads are safe to travel. They anticipate that could be as
soon as a day or two after peacekeeping troops arrive, and they
hope well before the refugees head back.
</P>
<P>
   The food agency expects to send in mobile warehouses and even
mobile bakeries that have their own source of power and can start
putting out fresh bread within 72 hours of arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The WFP hopes that before each refugee family crosses back over
the border into Kosovo it will be handed enough food to live on
until the family makes it home. That means enough food for one to
three days, Spring said.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the agency has enough food stocked in the region
to feed both the total number of refugees and internally displaced
persons for two weeks. Spring said WFP's target is having 1,000
metric tons of food each day available inside Kosovo to feed 1.5
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
