<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-SENATORS09-COX     06-08 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SENATORS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    19 FORMER SENATORS ENDORSE GORE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign
collected endorsements Tuesday from an array of retired Democratic
senators.
</P>
<P>
   In a basement ballroom at the posh Mayflower Renaissance Hotel,
the group of 10 former senators jovially confronted perceptions of
Gore as stiff and bland in an endorsement rally that focused on
reversing the negative implications of that image rather than
disputing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things that happen in public life that are dramatic are
not good governance,'' said former Sen. Mike Gravel of Alaska. ``Al
Gore is very competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell Heflin of Alabama, who supported Gore's 1988 presidential
bid, said that while the ``elitist media'' has branded Gore as
wooden, that characterization isn't entirely bad since it conveys
stability and strength. And he said Gore will be plenty colorful
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out he is a terrific campaigner,'' boomed Heflin,
``and don't sell him short on hitting the campaign trail and
getting people to vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen former senators endorsed the Gore campaign Tuesday,
though only half made it to the Washington event. Those who did
stressed Gore's experience as a former member of the House and
Senate, arguing, as Ohio's Howard Metzenbaum did, that ``there is
no person better trained to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a primary challenge by another former senator, Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, but the Mayflower gathering seemed targeted
at Gore's standing in the general election, where polls say he
would be an underdog to the Republican's front-running candidate,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the debates come, you'll see the difference'' between
Gore and his opponents, said Wendell Ford of Kentucky. ``When the
debates come, that'll separate them pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
