throwing up another obstacle in military talks on Kosovo, are
trying to exercise control over which Kosovo Albanian refugees
would be allowed to return. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ White House reaction to U.N.
resolution on peacekeeping force. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Kumanovo, Macedonia) _ NATO and Yugoslav
generals resumed their talks on the details of a Yugoslav
withdrawal from Kosovo Tuesday, hours after the world's major
industrialized nations agreed on a draft security council
resolution designed to end the conflict over Kosovo. By David
Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (United Nations) _ Asserting that the United Nations
Security Council is not a ``rubber stamp,'' China's representative
here made clear Tuesday that Beijing has serious reservations about
the peace plan for ending the Kosovo conflict. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO military and civilian
officials braced themselves Tuesday night to send peacekeepers into
Kosovo after a bombing pause, as Serb generals agreed to resume
talks on arrangements for their military pullout from the province.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ After a six-hour visit to Beijing to
explain the Kosovo peace plan, a European envoy said Tuesday that
he was confident that China would cooperate. But China continued to
call for an immediate end to NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and left
unclear whether it would permit speedy passage of a U.N. resolution
to provide a mandate for a Kosovo peacekeeping force. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (Washington) _ Talking to the Chinese government is a
little difficult these days, but trying to figure out the best ways
to apologize over the Chinese Embassy bombing have tied the varying
teams of the administration into knots. A mission of some officials
may go to Beijing by the end of the week, with hopes of settling
the World Trade Organization matter. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
