<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-HN     06-08 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TAKING BACK SEAT TO EUROPEANS IN POST-WAR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States led the crusade against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and provided the vanguard for the
crushing air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But now that peace and reconstruction are in the wind, the
United States is taking a back seat to European nations in the
ground force destined for Kosovo and down the road in the quest for
long-term economic and political stability across the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the shrinking U.S. role lies domestic U.S. politics,
preservation of the U.S.-Russian relationship and the Clinton
administration's bid for the 15-nation European Union to embrace
the former communist nations in the Balkans and Eastern Europe that
have been the front lines of World War I, World War II and the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, an official with the White House National Security
Council, said the Clinton administration is deliberately adopting a
subordinate role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flew the vast majority of attack sorties during Operation
Allied Force,'' Leavy said Tuesday. ``But as we move forward to
implement a peace agreement, rebuild Kosovo and reintegrate the
Balkans into Europe, we think it's appropriate for the Europeans to
take a more prominent role.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Haass, a former Bush administration aide who served on
the National Security Council during the Persian Gulf War, says a
diminished U.S. role makes military and political sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peacekeeping is a less demanding mission _ a mission the
Europeans can fulfill,'' Haass said. ``American forces have more
global responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   European leaders have wider leeway than President Clinton to
commit ground forces to an open-ended peacekeeping mission that is
being designed to encourage uprooted ethnic Albanians to return to
Kosovo from refugee camps and safe havens across Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post-war mission in Kosovo is an easier sell for European
leaders,'' Haass said. ``There is precious little support for it
here in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emphasized in a report to Congress Monday, for example,
that U.S. forces will begin to withdraw from Kosovo soon after ``an
initial stabilization period'' as newly trained police forces take
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is playing a dramatically different role in
the Kosovo crisis than it did four years ago in Bosnia, a former
Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the Clinton administration brokered the peace agreement
that ended four years of communal warfare in Bosnia that claimed
200,000 lives. Nearly 30,000 American troops were the vanguard of
the 60,000-strong ground force that swept into Bosnia to enforce a
agreement hammered out at a military base in Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The United States later retained a prominent role in a smaller
``stabilization'' force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   But the quest for peace in Kosovo and the implementation of the
agreement is decidedly a European affair.
</P>
<P>
   The peace agreement with Milosevic was brokered by the envoy of
the 15-nation European Union, Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari,
and the Kremlin's envoy, former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of Russia, Britain, France, Germany and
Italy, joined Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the foreign
ministers of Canada and Japan, drafted a U.N. Security Council
resolution at a meeting in Cologne, Germany, Tuesday designed to
govern the international force that moves into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Britain _ not the United States _ will lead the 50,000-member
force on the ground with 12,000 troops patrolling roughly 50
percent of Kosovo's territory.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining half of Kosovo will be divided into four roughly
equal sectors patrolled by troops from the United States, Italy,
France and Germany. The United States is contributing about 7,000
troops, or about 15 percent of the total force.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official said Russia may contribute as many as
10,000 troops to the operation, once Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott works out details with Russian officials on a trip
to Moscow on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials readily concede that domestic
politics plays a part in the decision to trim the U.S. role. The
Republican-led Congress, deeply divided on the combat operation in
Kosovo, remains concerned on the scope and duration of U.S.
participation in a follow-on peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   By downplaying the U.S. role in post-war Kosovo, the Clinton
administration also helps allay Moscow. The bombing of Yugoslavia,
which has close ties to Russia, stirred anti-American sentiments in
the communist-dominated Russian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Clinton administration's decision to adopt a
supporting rather than leading role helps thrust the Europeans and
Russia into the forefront of efforts to fashion stability in the
Balkans. The 15-nation European Union has been leery about
extending membership in its integrated economic market to the
struggling nations of Eastern Europe and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to all of this at the end of the day is the
integration of the Balkans into the economic and political
institutions of Europe,'' said a White House official who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Europe after all is their continent. It's
their back yard, not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
