<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7706 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETERPAN-TOUR09-COX     06-08 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETERPAN-TOUR09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta Ballet takes `Peter Pan' to London for the holidays
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Ballet will take a new production of its
full-length ballet ``Peter Pan'' to London over the Christmas
holidays, performing a 20-day engagement at Royal Festival Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The project, including airfare and housing for the dancers,
orchestra fees and transportation for sets and costumes, will cost
about $2.5 million, said Robert Chumbley, executive and music
director of the ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these expenses are guaranteed by Royal Festival Hall,
which is presenting the company as the centerpiece of its holiday
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The newly designed production, which will be seen in Atlanta in
the 2000-2001 season, is underwritten by an $85,000 grant from the
Katherine John Murphy Foundation of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At its Atlanta performances in 1997, the ballet used sets and
costumes from Cincinnati Ballet and Ballet West of Salt Lake City,
its co-producers. Atlanta Ballet artistic director John McFall
redid the choreography, replacing the original, which was by Peter
Anastos of Cincinnati Ballet. The score is by Carmon DeLeone,
Cincinnati Ballet's music director.
</P>
<P>
   For the London trip, McFall wanted a new, all-Atlanta Ballet
production, so the ballet commissioned new sets and costumes from
Peter Cazalet of Cape Town, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most spectacular set designs I've ever seen,''
said Chumbley.
</P>
<P>
   Backdrops are being constructed and painted in South Africa.
Costumes and carpentry will be provided by the ballet's scene and
costume shops in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be easier to tour,'' McFall said of the new design.
The ballet plans a North American tour of ``Peter Pan'' after it is
seen in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The production will involve all 23 company dancers, as well as
two children from the ballet's school who will alternate as the
youngest Darling child. The Lost Boys will come from the Central
Ballet School in Leeds, England, training academy of Northern
Ballet Theater, which has collaborated with Atlanta Ballet on
``Dracula'' and the forthcoming ``Hunchback of Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the ``Peter Pan'' engagement runs Dec. 21 to Jan. 9,
which dovetails with the company's ``Nutcracker'' (Dec. 3-24 at the
Fox Theatre), extra dancers may have to be hired in England until
the full complement arrives, Chumbley said.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Festival Hall, located in an arts complex on the south
bank of the Thames, is one of London's best-known concert halls.
The London Philharmonic is its resident orchestra, and the BBC
Philharmonic, now based in Manchester, gives its London
performances there.
</P>
<P>
   For the ballet's 28 performances of ``Peter Pan,'' the BBC
Philharmonic will be its pit orchestra, with Chumbley conducting.
</P>
<P>
   With the Royal Opera House at Covent Garden closed for repairs
for at least a year, Royal Festival Hall has been playing host to
the Royal Ballet, English National Ballet and other dance companies
left homeless for the season. Importing an American company is part
of the hall's plans to keep dance on its agenda, according to
Chumbley, and the idea of the ``Peter Pan'' venture came from its
programming director, Elspeth McBain.
</P>
<P>
   The hall has installed a rigging system for lights and scenery,
but ``Peter Pan'' will present a greater challenge: airborne
dancers, which require an extra set of rigging tracks and
reinforced harnesses and ropes.
</P>
<P>
   For the aerial effects, Atlanta Ballet will test the rigging and
practice flying in October at the Gwinnett Cultural Arts Center.
The flying harnesses and equipment are under the supervision of
Flying by Foy, which specializes in theatrical flying and has made
``Peter Pan'' its signature.
</P>
<P>
   However, Scottish novelist-playwright James M. Barrie made sure
that ``Peter Pan'' would benefit more than its audiences or its
stage workers. A provision in his will requires that whenever the
story of the boy who wouldn't grow up is produced, royalties go to
London's Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Ballet's previous experience with international touring
did not go happily. It had planned and announced a trip to China
for June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of cutbacks and restrictions by the Chinese
government, the ballet canceled the project.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
