u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEACEKEEPING-KOSOVO-H     06-08 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEACEKEEPING-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINES, ARMY CONTINGENT WILL LEAD THE WAY INTO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A force of 1,900 Marines and 1,700 Army troops will
provide the ``point of the spear'' for U.S. military units that
will move into Kosovo after Yugoslavia signs a peace agreement and
NATO stops bombing, possibly within days, Pentagon officials said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Troops from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit aboard a
three-ship amphibious group on the Aegean Sea and Army soldiers
based in Albania will be ``the enabling force,'' or the lead
element of the U.S. contribution to the 50,000-member Kosovo
peacekeeping mission, dubbed Operation Joint Guardian.
</P>
<P>
   In a potential logistics logjam, much of the NATO military
equipment and personnel that will flow into Kosovo will travel over
one highway that runs north from Skopje, Macedonia, to Pristina,
the capital of Kosovo. Macedonia borders Kosovo to the south.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. troops will conduct security and reconnaissance
missions and establish base camps in a U.S.-controlled sector of
Kosovo until the arrival of 7,000 heavily armed Army troops, mostly
based in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. forces could be inside Kosovo within days after a peace
agreement is signed and NATO verifies that Yugoslavian forces are
being withdrawn from Kosovo and the bombing is halted, said
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,700 Army troops will come from Task Force Hawk, the U.S.
protection force sent to Albania shortly after the NATO conflict
with Yugoslavia began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines and Army troops will be well-protected as they take
up positions inside Kosovo, a province of Serbia, which is the
dominant republic in Yugoslavia. NATO bombing over the last 11
weeks was intended to halt ethnic killings and removals by Serb
troops against the ethnic Albanian population of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines will unload at the Greek port of Thessaloniki and
move by bus and helicopter to a staging area in Skopje. They then
will move by road in armored personnel carriers and humvees and by
helicopter to a sector in Kosovo that would be controlled by U.S.
forces. Along the way, they will begin mine clearing operations for
forces that follow, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marines will bring with them light-armored vehicles, which
carry 25mm rapid-fire cannons, anti-tank missiles and mortars, and
amphibious assault vehicles, which carry machine guns and grenade
launchers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Marines will bring more than a dozen support
helicopters, four ``Cobra'' attack choppers and six AV-8B Harrier
jump jets that can fly low and slow to protect ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The initial Army contingent will include eight Apache anti-tank
helicopters, two light infantry companies, an anti-tank company, a
company of Bradley fighting vehicles and artillery, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army troops will be shifted to the staging area in Skopje,
about 100 miles to the east from their current position in Albania.
``From Macedonia, they'll move in with the Marines to Kosovo and
assume the first positions in the American sector,'' Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   Current plans call for the Marines to eventually withdraw to
their ships and for the Army to dispatch three armored battalions
from the 1st Infantry Division, nicknamed the ``Big Red One,''
based in Germany, with M1A1 main battle tanks, engineers to build
roads and bridges, attack helicopters, artillery and military
police.
</P>
<P>
   Under the NATO plan, Kosovo would be carved up into five
sectors. The United Kingdom will be responsible for the largest
sector, about 50 percent of Kosovo, including the capital of
Pristina, while the United States, France, Italy and Germany will
control equal segments of the remaining half.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. sector will be along the Macedonian and Serbian
borders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
