<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 9, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much cooler air will affect New England on Wednesday behind a
cold front sliding southward through the region. Indeed, afternoon
readings will be about 30 degrees colder than Tuesday, particularly
near the Northeast seaboard, where onshore breezes will import
chilly, ocean air inland. Isolated showers may accompany the return
to cooler conditions as a jet stream disturbance passes overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The weather will remain rather hot and humid across the Great
Lakes and Middle Atlantic states, excepting the Atlantic coast,
where developing sea breezes temper the heat. Beneath partly to
mostly sunny skies, afternoon readings will reach well into the 80s
over the region, exceeding 90 degrees in several locations.
</P>
<P>
   Bands of showers circulating around low pressure in the eastern
Gulf of Mexico will affect portions of the Florida peninsula on
Wednesday. More than an inch of rain will douse a few locations
with local flooding possible. Thunderstorms will also erupt in
southeastern Texas and southern Louisiana as humid air is lifted
along a sea breeze front, which is a boundary separating hot and
humid air over interior sections from cooler air originating over
the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms, capable of producing damaging winds and
large hail, will occur in the northern Plains and upper Mississippi
Valley ahead of a potent cold front. Unusually cool air will arrive
behind the front across the northern Rockies. Clouds will linger in
the Northwest, to the west of the Cascades, while the Southwest
stays mainly sunny and seasonably hot.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Ozone Pollution &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ozone in the stratosphere is a gas that is essential in
protecting humans from carcinogenic ultraviolet radiation from the
sun. However, an increase in ozone near the surface of the Earth
can be the harmful by-product of heat wave conditions. Ozone is the
primary ingredient of photochemical smog that plagues urban areas
in summer. Sunlight reacts with clouds of hydrocarbons and carbon
monoxide emitted by automobiles and industries to produce ozone.
When winds are light, ozone concentrations can increase to levels
that irritate the eyes and throat and damage vegetation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
