<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARABIA-IRAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDIS AND EMIRATES AT ODDS OVER IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ After years united by worries about Iran,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates have become embroiled in
a bitter dispute over the idea of reconciliation with the Tehran
government.
</P>
<P>
   Harsh exchanges between Arab allies in the Persian Gulf are rare
and seem to reflect broader differences about how the Arabs should
respond to overtures from Iranian President Mohammed Khatami, who
in May became the first Iranian leader since 1979 to visit the Arab
world.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Syria and Qatar, Saudi Arabia was host to Khatami on
that tour, showing a willingness to warm a relationship riven for
more than two decades by hostility and suspicion. That was seen as
a betrayal by the United Arab Emirates, which still regards Iran as
a foe.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Emirates Foreign Affairs Minister Rashid
Abdullah al-Nuaymi complained that any reconciliation with Iran
would come at his country's expense. The Saudi defense minister,
Prince Sultan, quickly shot back, saying that view was mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case, the ignorant is his own enemy,'' Prince Sultan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates are the two most
powerful members of the six-member Gulf Cooperation Council, an
alliance established in large part to create a common military
front against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats interviewed by telephone said they did not believe
that the dispute would lead to any serious rupture. But they did
say that it seemed to reflect the combination of hope and
uncertainty with which many Arabs regard Iran. Under Khatami, a
relative moderate, Iran has worked to court its Arab neighbors. But
it remains a formidable military force, and in the past it has
called for the toppling of gulf monarchies and for the
establishment of more Islamic states.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Bahrain and Kuwait, Saudi Arabia has a substantial
minority population of Shiite Muslims, who are seen as potentially
receptive to any criticism of the Sunni-led gulf states. The
populations of Qatar, Oman and the United Arab Emirates include far
fewer Shiites, but the Emirates has long felt threatened by Iran's
occupation of three gulf islands not far from its shore.
</P>
<P>
   The islands of Abu Musa and the Greater and Lesser Tumbs were
occupied by Iran in 1971, when Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi was still
in power. Iran says the islands are part of its territory, which
the Emirates vigorously disputes. In the past, the Gulf Cooperation
Council has taken strong stands against Iran's occupation of the
islands. But officials in the Emirates are making clear their
concern that the allure of warmer ties with Iran might cause the
solidarity to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Reuters quoted a senior official of the Emirates as
saying that his country was ``very much displeased'' with other
gulf countries for their failure to press Tehran on the islands
issue during Khatami's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Among other Arab countries debating whether to move toward
closer relations with Iran is Egypt, which has still not restored
the air links and full diplomatic relations with Tehran that it
severed after the 1979 revolution.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides, there are major irritants. As Egyptian officials
note whenever the issue comes up, a street in downtown Tehran is
still named for one of the Egyptian militants, Khaled
al-Eslambouli, who assassinated President Anwar Sadat in 1981, a
leftover from the days when Iran openly championed revolution.
</P>
<P>
   On Iran's side is the fact that the shah is buried in Egypt _ a
reminder of the sanctuary that the Cairo government gave to him
after he was forced to flee Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
