<HEADER>
A7731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TONY-CLOSINGS-NYT     06-08 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-CLOSINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TONY AFTERMATH: 4 SHOWS TO CLOSE ON SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Faced with wilting box office numbers and scant
success at the Tony Awards, four Broadway productions announced
Tuesday that they would close on Sunday. Among them is the musical
``The Civil War,'' which producers say will have lost an estimated
$8 million in its two-month run at the St. James Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for two other productions, the long-running revival of
``The Sound of Music'' and the play ``Night Must Fall,'' said their
performances would end later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The announcements were part of an annual rite, as Tony losers
realized they would have little fodder for marketing or advertising
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   This year proved no exception as producers of ``The Lonesome
West'' and ``Not About Nightingales,'' both of which were nominated
and lost in the category of best play, said they would shutter at
week's end. Also closing on Sunday is the musical revival of
``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown,'' which won Tonys in two acting
categories but failed to win for best revival.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest money loser by far is ``The Civil War,'' with a
score by Frank Wildhorn, which opened to poor reviews in late
April. Scott Zeiger, one of the producers, said it had been losing
more than $100,000 a week. ``The level of the enthusiasm in the
theater has not translated to the box office,'' Zeiger said. ``The
word of mouth has just not been happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial picture for ``Charlie Brown'' was also sobering.
It cost $4.2 million to produce and had been losing money every
week. Producers of the show had a glimmer of hope when Kristin
Chenoweth and Roger Bart won Tonys on Sunday for best featured
actress and actor in a musical. But the show lost as best musical
revival to ``Annie Get Your Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lonesome West,'' Martin McDonagh's black comedy, was a
disappointment for producers, who brought the show in on the heels
of McDonagh's highly successful 1998 entry, ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane.'' Randall Wreghitt, a producer for the play, said the
show's loss would be $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Misery loves company,'' Wreghitt said of the closing shows,
``but this is a company I'd rather not be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Not About Nightingales'' closing was less of a surprise.
The play, written by Tennessee Williams in 1938 but only recently
produced, had been expected to close by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a rough week on Broadway, with the Tony Awards
broadcast receiving lackluster ratings and an outcry arising when a
production number from ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues'' was cut
from the ceremonies. (David Letterman's ``Late Show'' agreed
Tuesday to present the number on Wednesday on CBS.) Several of the
closing shows will tour, producers said, including ``The Sound of
Music,'' which will end its 16-month run at the Martin Beck Theater
on June 27 and begin a national tour in August.
</P>
<P>
   Jed Bernstein, the president of the League of American Theaters
and Producers, said the closings were an unfortunate reality.
``Every year at this time shows must face the decision about
whether or not to make a stretch run through the summer,''
Bernstein said. ``Unfortunately, some decide that the demand is
just not strong enough to carry them forward.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
