A7738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CABLE-ISP-COX     06-08 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-ISP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court says AT&AMP;T cable must be public
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A ruling Friday by a U.S. district judge that AT&AMP;T
must give competing Internet service providers access to its cable
television networks in Portland, Ore., is being hailed as a victory
by MindSpring and other members of the OpenNet Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is fighting for access to the high-speed cable
modem lines that are still fundamentally closed to competition from
other Internet service providers. They also think the ruling sets a
precedent that could lead to similar decisions elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers who use AT&AMP;T's Internet service _ which can be 100
times faster than dial-up modems _ must subscribe to AT&AMP;T and TCI's
Excite At Home service provider to receive cable modem service. The
members of the OpenNet coalition, which also includes America
Online, U S West, Sprint and Verio say that without access to
AT&AMP;T's network, they could be left behind once broadband becomes
widely available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiring open access is the first step,'' says Dave Baker,
MindSpring vice president of legal and regulatory affairs. He says
the Portland decision alone won't give competing ISPs access to the
now-closed cable wires. ``We'd still have to negotiate an agreement
with AT&AMP;T,'' he says. ``Hopefully, this will give them some
incentive to negotiate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring says it has made numerous requests to AT&AMP;T to
negotiate for access to its cable lines everywhere AT&AMP;T offers
high-speed cable modem service. ``They've either ignored or refused
these requests,'' Baker says. ``Or at best they've been
noncommittal.''
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring and most industry watchers say AT&AMP;T will appeal the
decision. ``I expect AT&AMP;T will appeal this and do everything they
can do to avoid complying, but this is the law. Hopefully, they
will talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be some incentive for competition,'' agrees
Jupiter Communications telecommunications director Abhi Chaki.
``Nobody is going to invest in broadband if a company is going to
upgrade their infrastructure and hand it over on a silver
platter.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaki says the Portland decision doesn't bring any competing ISP
closer to cable wire access. ``It's just not economical to fight
these little battles as they erupt across the country.'' He says
neither the OpenNet Coalition nor the Oregon ruling is going to
derail AT&AMP;T's cable and broadband strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T is not stupid,'' he says. ``They have armed themselves
with platoons of lawyers taking care of regulatory concerns in
Washington. If the climate wasn't favorable to AT&AMP;T they wouldn't
have wasted their shareholders' money.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard has said
he's reluctant to place too many limits on new technologies such as
cable Internet services, which could mean an uphill battle for the
OpenNet Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an insider's game on Capitol Hill,'' Chaki says. ``I
don't think the OpenNet Coalition should be celebrating at all.
It's going to be squashed. AT&AMP;T is going to fight this. It could go
on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
