</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-BUSINESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic-owned businesses thriving in Atlanta area
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Norberto Sanchez opened one small Mexican
restaurant in Norcross, Ga. in 1987, he barely dreamed of the day
his company would own nine restaurants _ two in Kentucky and the
rest in metro Atlanta _ along with four Mexican fast-food
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard work and more work were the main ingredients of
success,'' said Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Norsan Foods also is a grocery and food distributor, and
a subsidiary distributes meat products to the hospitality industry.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 months ago, Sanchez said, the company opened its first
supermarket, called La Mexicana, in Norcross. Another is in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   As testament to the growth of Hispanic-owned business activity
in the metro area, a new bank _ The United Americas Bank _ will
open its doors in 60 days, with Sanchez as a member of the board of
directors and Sal Diaz-Verson serving as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Norsan Group is among 10 Georgia-based, Hispanic-owned companies
to make the top 500 list in Hispanic Business magazine's annual
roundup. Companies were ranked by 1998 revenue. To participate,
companies must be 51 percent owned by U.S. citizens of Hispanic
descent and must have headquarters in the 50 states or Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the list reflects considerable growth by
Hispanic-owned companies. This year's list includes 81 companies
with revenue of $50 million or more. In 1994, only 53 companies
made that top bracket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five-year data indicate that the Hispanic economy has
established a viable pipeline for producing large corporations in
the future,'' the magazine observed. The Georgia firms run the
gamut from food service and restaurants to engineering and natural
gas distribution. What they all share, though, is a determination
to grow.
</P>
<P>
   At Cape Environmental Management, President Fernando Rios wants
to quadruple his employee base and annual sales in the next four
years. Currently, the environmental engineering company has 90
employees and $9.90 million in revenues. Lou Sobh, whose auto
dealership is the top-ranked Georgia company on the list at No. 43,
told the magazine he has rejected several buy-out offers. ``I've
been in this business a long time, and I want my kids to be
involved,'' he said. ``I have a daughter who is general manager of
one store, a son that's with me in another, and I'm looking at
opening more because another son wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1842EDT &QL; 
