A7740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERCOMM09-COX     06-08 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMM09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Microsoft's Ballmer to communications industry: Join us
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs w/BALLMER-BOX.)
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Atlanta Tuesday to address a major communications
hardware industry convention, Microsoft president Steve Ballmer
stressed the increasing convergence of his company's software
products and communications products. Ballmer told
telecommunication companies to ``partner with Microsoft as quickly
as possible'' to effectively and profitably deploy new
telecommunications strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can fill an auditorium like a Microsoft executive. Even
those who regard Ballmer and his boss Bill Gates, as beings only
slightly this side of Darth Maul turned out for his 8 a.m. keynote
at Supercomm, the annual telecommunications exhibition and trade
show being held in Atlanta at the Georgia World Congress Center
through Thursday. Over 60,000 are expected to attend the show
featuring more than 700 exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Ballmer harkened back to that fateful day when
Gates and Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen went to IBM with a vision
of a personal computer on every desktop. At that historic meeting,
one of the turning points in the evolution of the home PC,
Microsoft promised IBM an operating system that would make its PCs
operate easily and efficiently. IBM said okay, and the rest as they
say is history.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years later, Ballmer stood before telecommunications
executives, a crowd just as old school, bureaucratic and skeptical
as IBM was back in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   However, this time, Microsoft has the products to sell, the
money to invest and wisdom to approach the communications industry
with just the right mixture of conviction and humility. ``Now we're
talking about access from anywhere to the Internet,'' he said
describing Microsoft's plans for the company's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of interest in the telecommunications
world about what the heck we are up to,'' he told the crowd. He
proceeded to tick of the various software products and services
Microsoft had to offer not only for the PC, but for cellular
phones, Palm Pilots and other communication devices. ``We are
convinced the nature of what we do is most influenced by broadband
than anything else going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also said Microsoft was investing in high speed
technology for both the cable modem technologies and high speed
Internet telephone access, stressing the company had no bias for
either. ``We just want to see these services deployed. ``I'm very
focused and serious about the need for speed,'' he said.
``Broadband is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Ballmer talked about where Microsoft wanted to
go today and in the future. He is keenly aware of his company's
infamous reputation heightened by the on-going federal anti-trust
trial, for co-opting the ideas of competitors. He knows Microsoft's
image needs some polishing and refining before the
telecommunication industry will consider joining forces with it.
``Mostly I'm hoping people will come away thinking that we are
friend, not foe,'' he said. However, he maintains that Microsoft's
current woes with the Justice Department will have no impact on the
business he hopes to garner from the Supercomm crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't care about the suit,'' he said. ``Our
customers don't care. The guys in this audience want to know how to
make telecommunications products. They have their own issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Information about Supercomm: www.supercomm99.com
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
