<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECHJOBS-COX     06-08 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHJOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia employment in tech arena growing
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No matter how you calculate it, Georgia is on the
move, in the midst of a technology boom that is having big a impact
on employment.
</P>
<P>
   In figures published last week by the American Electronics
Association, Georgia emerged as 10th in the country in technology
employment, up from 16th in 1990. State officials believe Georgia
may stand even higher now, since the comparative figures used by
the association date to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more novel ways to view Georgia progress is to
examine the concentration of technology employees, using as a base
the total state employment without farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   That perspective shows that Georgia ranks fourth among the 10
biggest technology employment states in terms of the concentration
of technology-related jobs. More than a quarter, or exactly 27.8
were in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to use gross figures rather than the concentration
because that catches the eye, and the attention of the business
world,'' said Jeff Humphreys, economist and economic development
specialist at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concentration factor does give an interesting perspective,
however.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the gross number of jobs, totaling some 133,000 in
Georgia, by one count, that determines level of investment banking
services and the development of a technology community. These
factors can be the basis for accelerating technology growth.
</P>
<P>
   Activity is so hot that small factors in the analysis of
technology growth make a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, specialists at the American Electronics
Association conceded Tuesday that they did not include employment
in the area of fiber optic cable production in their statistics on
technology jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We excluded that area mostly because the federal government
statistics did not separate fiber optic cable from wire and other
cable that would not be a part of the technology component,'' said
Chris Novak, an analyst for the association.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Lucent facility in Norcross, Ga. is one of the world
largest producers of fiber optic cable and would not have been
counted toward the technology jobs base, Novak said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that for technical reasons the survey had not
include workers in the area of biotechnology, an area that has been
the source of collaboration between Georgia Tech and Emory
University to build a biotech base for Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The association study included three major categories of
activity, including high-tech manufacturing, communications
services, and software and computer-related services.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Conrad, an epidemiologist at Emory, who specializes in
statistical studies, suggested the use of a population denominator
in the examination of technology jobs as a way to compare the
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be interesting to see new perspectives, such
as using population factors,'' he said, ``which would say more than
that California dominates technology.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, many states, including Georgia, are on the move.
While California may have an insurmountable edge, with some 784,000
technology jobs, the gap separating the rest of the top 10 seems to
be closing in.
</P>
<P>
   California added some 66,000 jobs on a net basis since 1990, but
officials at the American Electronics Association said the growth
rate of the California powerhouse lagged behind several states on a
percentage basis, including Texas, Georgia, Washington, Colorado
and other smaller states. State officials here already estimate
that Georgia may have more than 165,000 technology jobs,
representing considerable growth in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
