<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7744 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-PORTLAND-JOBS-A     06-08 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-PORTLAND-JOBS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A TAX BREAK, INTEL WILL CURB JOB GROWTH IN SPRAWL-CONSCIOUS
PORTLAND AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rm) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBORO, Ore. _ When county officials sat down with the Intel
Corp. to develop a package of tax incentives that would keep the
Portland area's largest employer here, the two sides struck a deal
that had some fairly standard provisions. Intel would invest up to
$12.5 billion in new equipment and plant upgrades over the next 15
years, and the county would grant $200 million in property tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   And just one more thing, the county asked: please don't create
too many new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual arrangement that reflects both the flush national
economy and Oregon's particular obsession with controlling sprawl,
the computer-chip maker has agreed to pay a ``growth impact fee''
if it exceeds a ceiling of 1,000 new manufacturing jobs on top of
the 4,000 it already provides here in Washington County, part of
the growing Portland metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Under the package, which county commissioners are expected to
approve next week, Intel will pay the county $1,000 per excess
worker per year if it surpasses the job limit. County officials say
they are thrilled to keep the jobs here but really are not
interested in a major expansion, which would put new strains on
schools, roads, utilities and many other services in an area that
is trying to hold on to the patchwork of farms, forests, orchards
and other undeveloped space that make it a particularly attractive
place to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole process was geared toward consolidating our
victories,'' Charles D. Cameron, the Washington County
administrator, said of the negotiations with Intel. ``We're more
concerned about retaining the economic strength we have rather than
creating more.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Walter C. Peck, a county spokesman, put it, if Intel had
been ``talking about 5,000 new jobs here, the sense is they
wouldn't have gotten to first base'' with any demand for tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of providing incentives for a company not to create
many more jobs has a certain man-bites-dog quality to it, county
and state officials concede. Indeed, Bill Scott, the state's
director of economic development, says that the arrangement is the
first such deal in Oregon and that he does not know of any like it
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   But, the officials say with some pride, if communities really
want to battle sprawl, the innovation here could well prove to be a
national model for how to achieve sensible, precisely defined
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is maybe a tenor-of-the-times thing,'' Scott said. ``A
few years ago, Oregon was really interested in all the jobs we
could get. But the political environment has changed. People know
there's more than one side to growth. We aren't just interested in
jobs, jobs, jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some local opposition to the growth impact fee, but not
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hair on the back of my neck stood up on that one,'' said
state Rep. Jim Hill, a Republican who is from the area and
otherwise supports the tax-break package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could send the message to businesses, `Yeah, you
can show up here, but you're going to pay a premium for it,''' Hill
said. ``I don't think we can afford to do that. I don't think any
community anywhere can sit there and say we're going to pick and
choose who we want to arrive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said the package was a creative one that was not in
any way a slap at businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the message is more complicated, but it's a healthy
message,'' he said. ``The idea is we want you to have incentives
for investment that also give us ways to deal with livability
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Livability is an especially potent issue to many Oregonians,
whose passion for protecting the state's natural splendor has been
interpreted by some critics as a reflection of a moat mentality and
hostility to outsiders. The state's legendary governor, Tom McCall,
a staunch environmentalist, famously said in his tourism-promotion
pitch three decades ago that visitors were welcome, ``but for
heaven's sake don't come to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the Portland area, planners have brought an almost
religious zeal toward regulating a roughly 400-square-mile ``urban
growth boundary'' area into which almost all development is
channeled, while a broad necklace of green space and farmland
maintains the region's stunning beauty. It is an anti-sprawl model
that other planners from around the country routinely come to
research.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   So, in Washington County, where more than 90 percent of its
population of around 400,000 people live within the 15 percent of
the county's land that is inside the growth boundary, the desire to
limit Intel's job growth has some obvious roots.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Intel, who have worked intensively with county
planners over the years on growth issues, even donating land in
order to place a light-rail station near their offices and chip
plants, said they were as concerned as anyone else in the Portland
area with livability. They said they were happy to agree to the
impact fees, though the idea was unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something that's come up in other communities, so
far, anyway,'' said Bill MacKenzie, an Intel spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the annual impact fee would actually be enough to deter
Intel from creating new jobs here is an open question, though, as
another Intel spokesman, Mike Salsgiver, said, ``It certainly could
be a factor. This is a cost-conscious company.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, though, the fees have a powerful symbolic value,
and represent a clear attempt on the county's part to set a target
for new jobs, one that the company says is a reasonable one.
Moreover, the impact fees are also a selling point in information
the county administrators have posted on their World Wide Web site
for local residents who have questions about the tax package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Intel is combining a $12.5 billion investment
and a focus on job retention, not new employment growth, means new
impacts should be minimal to schools and public infrastructure
(roads, sewers, water systems, etc.),'' according to the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, when the state's timber industry had
collapsed and Oregon's unemployment rate soared into the double
digits, the idea of levying ``growth impact fees'' would have been
almost unimaginable. In fact, six years ago, the state kicked off
its Strategic Investment Program, under which Intel has negotiated
this and previous tax breaks, in a determined bid to attract
high-technology companies.
</P>
<P>
   The state has done spectacularly well with its transition from
wood chips to computer chips, and the state's ``Silicon Valley'' is
a large part of the reason that Oregon's unemployment rate is
routinely below the national level, which is itself at historic
lows.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Intel, with 11,000 employees here over all, is the largest
private employer in the state.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new tax package is intended, state officials say, to help
mitigate a provision in the state tax code that assesses property
taxes on a company's machinery and other equipment as well as its
buildings and land, and thus imposes particular burdens on the
high-technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Intel's investments here will be in
equipment, which sometimes needs to be upgraded in a matter of
months to accommodate manufacturing changes in the fast-changing
industry. And as that equipment is increasingly automated, Intel is
unlikely to be creating large numbers of jobs here despite the
billions of dollars it is investing, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With no sales tax, Oregon has a particular reliance on property
taxes, with what critics call a hodge-podge of breaks to go along
with it: until just a few years ago, for instance, the state gave a
tax break for the construction of nuclear fallout shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The critics also question whether the breaks for the technology
industry amount to ``corporate welfare,'' but in many ways, the
deal Washington County worked out looks to be a good one for
taxpayers. It almost certainly averts a possible large-scale
relocation by Intel to Arizona and New Mexico, which have both
beseeched the company to expand operations there, and among other
things, it guarantees the county nearly $30 million in fees
regardless of whether the company makes any new investments here at
all.
</P>
<P>
   And overall, the company's payments to the county will increase
from $12 million last year to an annual average of nearly $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also has provisions, the county says, to strip away the
growth-impact fees if the economic situation here reverses itself
and the area wants more jobs. For now, though, even many workers
who hold good jobs at Intel said they are just as happy that the
company has disincentives to create too many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The housing prices, the traffic, it's all going off the
charts,'' said 37-year-old Mark Kent, a technician, as he donned
the protective clothing for his shift at the company's Ronler Acres
chip plant that is designed to keep all impurities away from the
chips and looks a lot like a NASA-style space suit, though it is
more commonly called a ``bunny suit'' at Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll never be able to stop the growth but if this puts it
at a slower pace, that's good,'' Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   And Dave Stegemann, a litho technician who moved here from
Albuquerque a year and a half ago, said he found the idea of
discouraging growth a bit jarring, but only at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unusual, I'd never really heard of that idea before,''
Stegemann said. ``But then I read about it, I thought about it, I
talked to my wife about it, and it seemed like it's a really
innovative approach. I think it's a fair idea. Growth does have
costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
