r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-KILLING-HNS &LR;      06-08 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KILLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNERS OF SLAIN PERSONALITY CALL FOR END TO VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSANA HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Stunned by the slaying in broad daylight of
popular television personality, thousands of mourners on Tuesday
demanded an end to the violence that has become commonplace in one
of the world's largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   In a year laden with do-or-die politics as candidates position
themselves for a national election in 2000, the slaying Monday of a
man who for decades was a fixture in living rooms could also weaken
the presidential hopes of Mexico City Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
criticized as inept in the face of growing violence in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the attack on Francisco ``Paco'' Stanley, in
which another person was killed and three others wounded in a
barrage of bullets, opposition politicians and critics of Cardenas'
leftist administration called for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Although authorities said they suspected the execution-style hit
to be the work of organized crime, Stanley's death played on the
fears of a population fed up with carjackings, muggings and
kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of weeping mourners attended Stanley's funeral
Tuesday. The soft chants of ``Justice! Justice!'' could be heard
from the throng.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made us laugh. He said laughter was the best medicine,''
said one mourner who didn't want her name used. ``Unfortunately, we
live in hard world. What happened to Paco can happen to me or my
family _ to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Her thoughts were shared by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impunity is killing us. Where are the authorities?''
Ricardo Salinas Pliego, the president of TV Azteca where Stanley
worked as a host, asked in a national television address. ``Why do
we pay taxes? Why do we have elections?''
</P>
<P>
   The director of TV Azteca, Jorge Garralda, meanwhile, blamed
Cardenas, whose failed presidential bids as a candidate of the
Democratic Revolutionary Party date to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibility falls on Cuauhtemc Cardenas, a man who
promised us security,'' Garralda said.
</P>
<P>
   The influential Televisa network anchor Jacobo Zabludovsky, who
is closely associated with the ruling Institutional Revolutionary
Party, said ``someone must resign and allow competent people to
protect us.''
</P>
<P>
   He called Mexico City's violent climate ``worse than Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   But at first glance, the killing of Stanley, 56, did not appear
to have anything to do with everyday street crime common in this
capital of 22 million people. The police have ruled out theft or
kidnapping as motives.
</P>
<P>
   At a Monday night news conference, Cardenas blamed opponents for
trying to politicize the crime in time for the presidential
elections and speculated the television host was the victim of
people who wanted ``to even a score.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City Attorney General Samuel del Villar said early
indications ``point to a specific attempt to take his life.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack was reminiscent of other recent slayings of noted
Mexican figures, including presidential candidate Luis Donaldo
Colosio, ruling party official Francisco Ruiz Massieu and
Guadalajara's Cardinal Jesus Posadas Ocampo.
</P>
<P>
   Their deaths have not been solved but have been linked to
organized crime or political plots.
</P>
<P>
   Regarded by many as Mexico's Johnny Carson, Stanley was shot at
close range four times in the face and head while inside his luxury
minivan as he was leaving a restaurant near a busy highway. His
bodyguards were reportedly unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   In the fusillade _ the police said at least 26 shots were fired
_ a passerby also was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Gil, an entertainment Televisa reporter who was a
passenger in the car, was wounded. He was listed in stable
condition Tuesday. So were a valet parking attendant and his wife
who also were shot in the assault.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four assailants escaped into the heavy traffic, and the
police were still looking for them Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
