<HEADER>
A7759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIA-ECON-ART-65     06-08 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-ECON-ART-650&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN MARKETS DANCE, AT LEAST BRIEFLY, TO A DEMOCRATIC BEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A day after Indonesia held its first
democratic elections in four decades, the joyful clamor of voters
gave way to a resounding rumble of approval from the financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks in Jakarta surged 12.2 percent on Tuesday, closing at
their highest level since Indonesia went into an economic tailspin
in August 1997. Indonesia's currency, the rupiah, strengthened to a
rate of 7,650 to the dollar, extending a rally that began last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The good feelings were infectious, as stock markets in
neighboring Malaysia and Singapore also recorded powerful gains.
Everywhere in the region, investors seemed to view Indonesia's
harmonious exercise in democracy as a milestone in Asia's recovery
from economic calamity.
</P>
<P>
   Given the dire predictions of election-related riots and
bloodshed, such euphoria is understandable. But many analysts here
said that it would be transitory. Indonesia faces prolonged
political maneuvering that may leave people as baffled as ever
about this sprawling country.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does an election _ however peaceful _ heal Indonesia's ills,
which range from shuttered banks and debt-plagued companies to
jaded foreign investors who still view the country as an economic
leper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elections are one milestone,'' said Mari Pangestu, an
economist at the Center for Strategic and International Studies in
Jakarta. ``But there are two or three other milestones to come. Who
will lead the coalition? Who will be the next president? Who will
get the economics portfolio?''
</P>
<P>
   Based on early returns, the Indonesian Democratic Party for
Struggle seemed likely to win the largest number of votes. But even
if it wins this parliamentary election, analysts said it would have
to assemble a coalition to wrest control of the government from the
ruling Golkar party and its leader, President B.J. Habibie, the
protege of his predecessor, Indonesia's longtime leader, Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as investors and economists weighed the implications of
Monday's vote, their attention swung to the leader of the
Democratic Party for Struggle, Megawati Sukarnoputri, and her
economic advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Megawati, 52, said little about the economy during the
campaign. The soft-spoken daughter of Indonesia's founding
president, Sukarno, Mrs. Megawati ran a heavily symbolic campaign,
drawing on an emotional public yearning for a return to the
Indonesia of her father.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that under Sukarno, Indonesia fell into its deepest
economic crisis until the current one _ with crushing government
debt, soaring inflation, eroding exports and rampant smuggling. In
a speech in 1964, Sukarno told the United States to ``go to hell
with your aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her credentials as a nationalist, Mrs. Megawati is not
about to follow her father's lead in spurning foreign money. Her
party has embraced Indonesia's agreement with the International
Monetary Fund, which lays out changes required for it to keep
receiving the fund's money.
</P>
<P>
   John Bresnan, an expert on Indonesia at the East Asian Institute
at Columbia University, said he was surprised that Mrs. Megawati
and other opposition figures had not tried to turn the IMF's role
into a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have some sense of the severity of the
situation,'' Bresnan said. ``Some of the opposition notables are
now close to being in a position of responsibility, and that is a
sobering prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the polls closed on Monday, the IMF approved a $450
million loan to Indonesia, the latest installment in its
$43-billion rescue package. Anoop Singh, the deputy director of the
IMF's Asia and Pacific division, said Tuesday that he viewed the
election as an ``opportunity to intensify reform efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to heeding the IMF, advisers to Mrs. Megawati say
they are committed to a free-market strategy that welcomes foreign
investment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   But that does not mean Mrs. Megawati's aides do not harbor
provocative ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Kwik Kian Gie, an economist who is perhaps Mrs. Megawati's most
influential adviser, recently proposed fixing Indonesia's currency
at an exchange rate of 5,000 rupiah to the U.S. dollar. Without a
stable rupiah at that level, he says, Indonesia's economy will
continue to stagnate because the rupiah's weakness and
unpredictability have hurt the purchasing power of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This proposal is certainly not for the current government,
which evidently cannot create stability, but for the government
resulting from the coming general election,'' Kwik wrote in The
Jakarta Post.
</P>
<P>
   Because Kwik is mentioned as a future finance minister, his
ruminations about the rupiah have alarmed some business leaders
here. Indonesia struggled to maintain a fixed exchange rate early
in the Asian crisis _ abandoning the effort after it squandered
foreign reserves by spending enormous sums of dollars to buy
rupiah. Beyond the currency issue, some executives here said the
Democratic Party for Struggle has a more active bent than the other
major parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some concern that there is a central-planning bias and
an unwillingness to let the market take over,'' said James W.
Castle, a consultant and member of the American Chamber of Commerce
here. ``We've tried to tell them that the regulations of the
Suharto government were fairly good. The problem was corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the next government adopts any innovative policies,
investors said it must tackle Indonesia's pervasive cronyism and a
legal system that leaves foreign banks and other creditors queasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see how any bank in Frankfurt or New York would
get approval to make new loans to Indonesia,'' said Bill Kaye,
senior managing director of the Pacific Group, an asset management
firm in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye said investors would hesitate to pour money back into the
country until they saw evidence that bankruptcy courts here were
treating creditors consistently. But doing that will involve
challenging some of the most politically connected business tycoons
in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that a resurgent stock market and
strengthening currency will help Indonesia solve its problems. As
asset values rise, it is easier to overhaul debt-laden
conglomerates. And that, in turn, eases the cost of bailing out
Indonesia's banking system, now estimated at more than $40 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems facing Indonesia, some experts said they
did not want to diminish the psychological lift that the economy
would enjoy simply because the elections were so remarkably
peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make people feel safe, a lot of Indonesian money
that went abroad will come back,'' said Rizal Ramli, a prominent
economist. ``People want to be given a reason to come back to this
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
