<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SIGNS EDUCATION BILLS INTO LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Just three days before he heads out on the
presidential campaign trail, Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday signed
into law an education bill that pumps a record amount of new money
into public education and proves, he said, that education is Texas'
top priority.
</P>
<P>
   But during a bill-signing ceremony at an elementary school in
this Austin suburb, Bush also urged school districts not to play
games with the $3,000 pay raise the law guarantees every teacher,
nurse, counselor and school librarian.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging he is aware that many teachers are concerned
districts will decrease other benefits to compensate for the pay
raise, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly urge school boards not to do that. That's not the
intent of this legislation. ... We don't want there to be a zero
sum politics when it comes to teachers. That's not right. School
board members have got to understand our intent in this bill
provides no unfunded mandate when it comes to teacher pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 4 will pump $3.8 billion of new money into public
school funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading is the new civil right,'' Bush said, quoting a Houston
school official. ``You cannot realize the American dream if you
cannot read. And so I think one of the really long-lasting effects
(of Senate Bill 4) is to make sure that every child is given the
basic skills to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the shrieks of summer school students who welcomed the
governor to Jollyville Elementary School was one youngster who may
be able to read minds. Responding to Bush's question if they knew
what he thinks is most important, one child piped up: ``You are
going to be president?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer Bush was seeking, though, was getting an education,
and he chatted briefly with students about the importance of
reading and stopped in a first-grade classroom to read to them
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also signed into law two other school-related bills: Senate
Bill 103, which makes the high school exit level exam more
difficult and adds new tests to the Texas Assessment of Academic
Skills, and House Bill 2075, a truth-in-taxation measure designed
to make school budgets and property taxes clearer to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to guaranteeing the largest pay hike the state has
ever given teachers, SB 4 also focuses on three other areas:
</P>
<P>
   _ An end to social promotion, a cornerstone of Bush's
re-election campaign last fall. This would be achieved through
requirements that students who cannot pass certain state-mandated
tests be given intensive instruction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Property tax reductions, achieved through new state funding
that will help school districts pay off debt they have incurred for
building and renovating facilities and lessen their need for taxes.
The average tax rate reduction will be 6 cents, although some
districts would get no reduction in taxes while others are
projected to be reduced as much as 44 cents per $100 valuation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Changes in school finance formulas that will aid fast-growth
districts and mitigate the impact of ``Robin Hood'' requirements on
districts now forced to share their wealth with poorer districts.
</P>
<P>
   He said the $250 million lawmakers put into new programs for
kindergarten and pre-kindergarten will help ensure that schools
meet the goal of having every child reading at grade level by Grade
3 and remain at grade level for the rest of their academic careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be relentless in making sure every child learns
to read,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an initiative I believe is going to change Texas,'' he
added. ``When we teach every child to read, we are going to change
every child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensive instruction programs for students who face being
held back in school if they cannot pass certain state tests will
further enhance students' academic careers, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of giving up, instead of this great state just
quitting and saying, `We're just going to move you through,' we're
going to make sure that child gets additional help,'' Bush said.
``We're not going to quit on any child in Texas. ... We're going to
end the failed practice of quitting on children.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the lawmakers attending the ceremony was State Rep. Scott
Hochberg, D-Houston, who was a member of the House Public Education
Committee that helped fashion SB 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember coming away from a session feeling as good
about what we did as I do this time,'' Hochberg said. ``we have
provided the means like we never have before for public education
to succeed in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   Hochberg added that any teacher who does not get the $3,000 pay
hike plus whatever step increase they are due to get next school
year should contact Education Commissioner Mike Moses.
</P>
<P>
   Moses said school districts will ``have an accreditation visit''
from TEA if the pay raises are not funded in the manner the
Legislature intended.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
