<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT &LR;      06-08 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. DELEGATE EXPRESSES CHINA'S CONCERNS ON KOVOSO PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Asserting that the U.N. Security Council is not
a ``rubber stamp,'' China's representative here made clear on
Tuesday that Beijing has serious reservations about the peace plan
for ending the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Shen Guofang, China's deputy representative to the United
Nations, said the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia must stop before the
Security Council could vote one way or another on the peace plan.
Russia's representative here, Sergey Lavrov, also insisted on
Tuesday that the bombing the stopped before council action is
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Shen also warned on Tuesday that his government, which as a
permanent member of the council has a veto over its decisions, was
particularly unhappy about two specific provisions of the draft
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   First is a provision demanding ``full cooperation by all
concerned, including the international security presence with the
International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia,'' which
in May indicted President Slobodan Milosevic for war crimes. Shen
called the indictment ``politically motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, he said that China was unhappy that the Security Council
is taking this action under Chapter 7 of the U.N. Charter, which
allows it to authorize the use of armed force against an aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats here spent much of the day privately debating how
China would manifest its unhappiness with these provisions. All
Shen said on Tuesday was that he had referred the text of the
resolution to Beijing for instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats did not foresee difficulties over China's
insistence that the bombing be halted before the new resolution is
put to a vote. They expect Serbian and Western military officials
to agree soon on a detailed withdrawal plan for the Serbian
military at the same time as Security Council members are putting
finishing touches on the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Once the withdrawal starts and the more than one million
refugees and displaced people begin returning to their homes, the
bombing will be halted and the Security Council will be invited to
approve the new peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock, Britain's U.N. ambassador, predicted on
Tuesday that such a vote could come within 24-48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   China's other objections, however, fueled more spirited
speculation. Some Western diplomats, including the Americans, were
said to be optimistic that Beijing would not veto the resolution
because of the two provisions. First they argued, while China
complained about Chapter 7 resolutions, it did not use its veto to
block the use of force either in the 1991 Gulf war or in the
Bosnian conflict. Second, a U.S. official said, China did not wish
to be seen as an isolated spoiler _ the country that had thwarted
an agreement that all major countries, including Russia, supported.
</P>
<P>
   A positive sign, one Western diplomat said, was China's decision
on Tuesday to allow speedy consideration of and vote on the
resolution by waiving a regulation that requires a 24-hour delay
before the formal printing of a resolution and a council vote.
</P>
<P>
   Another cause for optimism, said Sir Jeremy, was that despite
Russia's and China's expressed misgivings about the resolution,
neither had yet formally introduced suggested changes in the text.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, drafted by the G-8 ministers, gives the United Nations
sweeping responsibility in Kosovo. Policing the province,
establishing a new judicial system, tackling human rights abuses,
organizing new elections, and enabling the return of more than a
million refugees and internally displaced people are just some of
the challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a much bigger role for the United Nations than what we
were given in Bosnia,'' said a senior U.N. official.
</P>
<P>
   Under the peace plan, Secretary-General Kofi Annan must appoint
``in consultation with the Security Council'' a ``special
representative'' to oversee the civilian structure and insure close
cooperation by the NATO-led military force.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who until now has been kept largely on the political
periphery of efforts to solve the crisis, said on Tuesday he hoped
that ``whatever hurdles there may be will not be insurmountable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
