<SLUG> BC-LAWYERS-PARTNERSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABA PROPOSAL WOULD LET LAWYERS FORM PARTNERSHIPS WITH NONLAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A special panel at the American Bar Association rocked the legal
profession Tuesday by recommending that lawyers toss out
decades-old rules that have prevented them from setting up
partnerships with accountants, consultants and other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that would transform the way legal services are
provided in the United States, the committee recommended that
lawyers and nonlawyers be allowed to share fees and profits. If the
plan gains final approval, it would allow law firms to get into
lucrative new businesses like consulting. And, it would allow
accounting and consulting firms to begin practicing law.
</P>
<P>
   But winning final approval from a majority of American Bar
Association's policy-makers, the House of Delegates, and then from
the separate bar associations and top courts in each state, will
not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers are sharply divided over the issue, with supporters
saying that their clients want the ease of having one firm provide
all of their legal, accounting and other professional service
needs, while opponents respond that such a ``one-stop shop'' is
dangerous and not in their clients' best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The avoidance of any conflict of interest is a fundamental
hallmark of the attorney's obligation,'' said Thomas Rice, chairman
of the New York State Bar Association. ``One of the great risks is
that the profit motive could begin to skew the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Rice said, the new rules could allow lawyers
specializing in estate planning and writing wills to form a
partnership with financial consultants selling life insurance
policies. A conflict would result, he contended, if greater profits
could be made selling life insurance than from legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the panel said that they were not lowering
ethical standards that lawyers must follow. They said that all
lawyers, whether they work in a law firm or an accounting firm,
must still avoid any possible conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwin Simmons, chairman of the panel that proposed the new
rules, said, ``These changes would allow clients more options in
where they obtain legal services, and lawyers more choices in how
they serve clients, but maintain the core values of the legal
profession and the protections those values guarantee the public
and clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules would allow lawyers to practice in what the panel
called ``multidisciplinary firms,'' which would provide both legal
and other professional services.
</P>
<P>
   Already the Big Five accounting firms have added legal work to
the myriad of services they provide for their corporate clients
outside of the United States. The giant accounting firms have long
hired lawyers to prepare tax returns for clients, but they have
hired so many non-tax lawyers in other countries that they are now
among the biggest law firms in the world.
</P>
<P>
   According to a November survey by the American Lawyer magazine
the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers had 1,663 non-tax
lawyers outside the United States, enough to make it the third
largest law firm in the world. Just behind was Arthur Andersen,
with 1,500 non-tax lawyers, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Big Five firms welcomed the panel's proposal
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission's recommendations are a step in the right
direction,'' said Richard Spivak, managing partner of Arthur
Andersen's tax practice in North America.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan would put up some high hurdles for giant accounting
firms. The panel recommended that any firm providing legal services
would have to abide by the same conflict rules that law firms must
now meet. Those rules say that a firm must check its entire list of
clients for possible conflicts before accepting a new client.
</P>
<P>
   For the Big Five, which have thousands of clients, the
requirement could be difficult to meet.
</P>
<P>
   And, many lawyers believe that accountants and lawyers have such
different responsibilities that they should never be allowed to
share fees. They point out how accountants, as auditors of public
companies, have a duty to tell shareholders and the public about
problems they find during their audit. That responsibility
conflicts with the duties of lawyers, the critics say, who must
keep their work for the company confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard to reconcile those two roles,'' said Richard
Ziegler, the former chairman of the New York State Bar
Association's ethics committee and a partner at Cleary, Gottlieb,
Steen &AMP; Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firms would also have to find a way to please
federal securities regulators, who have said that they would not
allow an accounting firm that audits the financial books of a
public company to also provide legal services to that client.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some serious implications here,'' Lynn Turner, the
chief accountant at the Securities and Exchange Commission, said
Tuesday. Turner has referred the matter to the Independence
Standards Board, a group that sets many of the ethical rules for
auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The American Bar Association has scheduled a public hearing on
the proposal for Aug. 8 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
