<HEADER>
A7778 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COYLE-LISTEN-THEATER-     06-08 1450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COYLE-LISTEN-THEATER-ART-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY ALSO ACT WHO ONLY SIT AND LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 13) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MATT WOLF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brendon Coyle has spent almost 400 performances, his elbows
propped on a bar, a lager or a whisky at the ready, listening to
his fellow players in ``The Weir'' turn a litany of ghostly tales
into a haunting study of collective self-revelation. But playing a
bartender also named Brendan, Coyle never gets a story of his own,
unless you believe _ as some do _ that Brendan's tale begins once
Conor McPherson's play ends.
</P>
<P>
   Coyle's isn't the only performance now on Broadway that puts the
auditor tantalizingly center stage. Over at ``The Iceman Cometh,''
Jeff Weiss and Katie Finneran are portraying just two of the
booze-soaked habitues of Harry Hope's saloon, most of whom are
spoken to far more often than they speak.
</P>
<P>
   At ``Art,'' meanwhile, a Broadway newcomer named Buck Henry is
experiencing his own moments of silence onstage. Although Henry's
fiercely anti-modernist character, Marc, embodies the energy that
drives Yasmina Reza's play, he is eventually forced to look on and
listen as a friend's aria of prenuptial nerves nightly stops the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Can listening be its own reward?
</P>
<P>
   As Coyle's acclaimed performance shows _ in February, he won an
Olivier Award in London for best supporting player _ listening has
the capacity to be as potent as speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought, this part is about being present, about being
there,'' the actor was saying in his quiet, husky voice one recent
afternoon, explaining his connection to a play that he has been
with since its first incarnation. That would have been in July
1997, in a 60-seat studio theater in London that more or less
placed the audience right inside the rural Irish bar that the
character Brendan tends.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Coyle was offered a different role, that of Finbar
(subsequently inherited by Dermot Crowley). Finbar is the lone
frequenter of the desolate County Leitrim pub to make a commercial
success in town, thereby forsaking the rural life spent, as he puts
it, ``on the bog.'' It is Finbar who brings the new arrival to the
community, Valerie (Michelle Fairley), a Dubliner who serves to
transform, at least for an afternoon, the bluff-and-bluster men's
world inside the bar. The others who tell their tales at the Walter
Kerr Theater are Jim Norton and Kieran Ahern, who have also been
with the play since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still locked in stage time and line counts,'' said Coyle
about the role of Finbar, referring to the customary ways by which
a part is judged. But at the urging of his girlfriend, Emer
Reynolds, a film editor working on a new movie, ``Saltwater,'' that
McPherson is writing and directing, Coyle decided less might be
more. ``She said, `This is the heart of the play,''' remembered
Coyle, who decided that Brendan truly was. He compared the
character to Prospero in ``The Tempest.'' ``Brendan is the
facilitator,'' Coyle said. ``The play couldn't happen without
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was an ideal fit, said Ian Rickson, the director.
``Brendan has all sorts of affinities with Brendan in the play,''
Rickson said by telephone from the Royal Court Theater in London,
where he is the artistic director. He said that he and the cast had
discussed the fact that ``The Weir'' is about testimony and
listening. ``We presume listening is a passive activity,'' Rickson
said. ``It's actually extremely active.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyle said the part of the bartender ``is like one long reaction
shot sometimes; I spend a lot of time physicalizing listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't his mind ever wander during a performance, particularly
as the same tales are told over and over? Coyle said ``applied
listening, almost like meditation,'' was what gets him through the
occasional rough night. ``Sometimes you do think, `Oh, I forgot to
set the video,' but you have to fight that; you have to get rid of
all that rubbish,'' he said. ``Brendan is the character who's
really going to have an impact on the play, so it's all about
transitive concentration and listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention, he said, laughing, that by now ``I could recite
the whole play, I'm sure of it. I can prompt any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   At ``Art,'' the Tony Award-winning comedy now on its fourth cast
at the Royale, Henry must leave off the philistine outbursts of his
character some two-thirds of the way through while Wayne Knight's
Yvan delivers a monologue that runs nearly three pages in the
published text.
</P>
<P>
   It's very long,'' Henry said of the soliloquy on which he and
George Segal's Serge must focus during every performance. ``It
gives you a long rest, and it's fun to listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the speech hard to sustain interest in as an active
listener? ``It solves its own problems,'' said Henry, who is also a
writer. ``It's such a complicated story, you have to listen to it
in order to stay afloat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We could almost not be there, except that part of the dynamic
is that Yvan is boring and irritating, too. We're hungry, twitchy
guys who have been waiting for him for 45 minutes so we can go out
and eat. And then we have to listen to this long nightmare of
woe.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Henry added, his own character ``has got a great big
agenda in his head because he knows somewhere down the line _
probably at dinner, he thinks _ he's going to rip this guy apart
for his cowardice.''
</P>
<P>
   How, then, does Henry communicate that during Knight's spiel?
``I'm looking at him with amiable contempt _ I think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the revival of ``The Iceman Cometh,'' at the Brooks Atkinson,
most of the actors in the 19-member company spend much of the play
listening as one abject barfly after another gets his or her moment
of stage glory before slumping back into the stupor and haze
accompanying Eugene O'Neill's glimpse into the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   The real test comes in the play's fourth and final act, as the
characters hear a marathon confessional from their no longer
beloved Hickey (played by Kevin Spacey) that goes on for more than
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to listen to the words,'' said Weiss, who plays the
former carnival man Ed Mosher and who is himself a longtime fixture
of the downtown performance scene in New York. ``I can't anticipate
any of it. I have to know how it builds. It's not an intellectual
process but an emotional one. I never take my eyes off Kevin; I
listen to everything he's saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that a long time to remain actively silent? Weiss shrugs
off such considerations. ``Twenty-two minutes may be long in
theater time, but it's a short space of time in any given day, and
anyway, life ultimately is much harder than theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss is onstage from the outset, slumped in varying degrees of
consciousness for as long as 50 minutes before he utters his first
line. B Y contrast, Ms. Finneran's prostitute, Cora, enters the
saloon 45 minutes into the play, though she, too, spends far less
of her time onstage speaking than she does drinking the dyed sugar
water that passes for liquor. (The same substitute can be found at
``The Weir,'' alongside the odd splash of Coors Light.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If your brain goes to the grocery store and you start doing
your list,'' said Ms. Finneran, ``at least then you have a little
time to get yourself back on track.'' By contrast, she added, a
previous New York stage run in John Guare's ``Bosoms and Neglect''
Off Broadway late last year was ``constant banter back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   In both assignments, Ms. Finneran said, ``you must listen, or
you fall into that black hole where you forget who you are or where
you were born or what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Uta Hagen, she said, ``who is my teacher, talks about animated
listening: whenever someone's talking, it's about anticipating what
they're going to say next.'' Ms. Finneran pointed out proudly that
Cora has four interjections during the climactic fourth act of
``Iceman'' _ ``more than any other character.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss and Ms. Finneran said Howard Davies, the British director
of the production, had not instructed them on how to listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howard put together an extraordinary group of people who he
instinctively felt would be able to sustain that alertness through
the play,'' Weiss said. ``The barflies are thinking about many
things, principally getting a drink. They're alert from the outset
to the prospect of a high.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are really an actor, said Ms. Finneran, ``listening is
the easiest thing there is.'' Even if ``some of the boys do
sometimes fall asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
