<SLUG> BC-PILOTS-CATHAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHAY PACIFIC CANCELS FLIGHTS AMID DISPUTE WITH PILOTS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ Cathay Pacific Airways Ltd. grounded more than half
its flights on Tuesday in an increasingly bitter dispute with
pilots who have been calling in sick over a looming deadline to
accept pay cuts at the big Asian airline.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay has given its pilots until the end of the week to choose
between taking stock options in return for an average 7 percent
reduction in salary or quitting the airline with six months' pay.
The airline said on May 28 that it would dismiss pilots who failed
to accept any option, a threat that pilots say has made them too
sick with anxiety to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, many have been passing along letters signed by
physicians to excuse them from work, the airline said, so many that
Cathay was forced to cancel 67 of its 113 scheduled flights on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope they get well soon,'' an airline spokeswoman said,
adding that the airline was not bothering to question the veracity
of the letters. Pilots have denied they are conducting an organized
sickout.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots of the Hong Kong-based airline, most of whom are
British, have said they will strike if any are dismissed. Cathay
managers were planning to meet on Wednesday with the pilots union,
though there have been no signs of progress since talks on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay says the pay cuts are needed to stay competitive in a
toughening market for international air travel. It says its pilots
are among the most highly paid in the world and as a group
represent 40 percent of its labor costs _ a disproportionately
large amount. The airline last year posted its first loss as a
public company and blamed Asia's economic crisis and high labor
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay's pilots, however, say the airline has acted in bad faith
by trying to force them to accept terms. Pay talks earlier this
year broke down over the pilots' insistence that an independent
auditor be allowed to examine Cathay's books.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay reported an operating profit and posted a net loss
because of one-time write-downs and aircraft deliveries. Cathay
said these adjustments were unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The flight cancellations are costing the airline $30 million
(Hong Kong), or $3.9 million (U.S.), a day in lost revenue,
according to one estimate, not including the cost of chartering
flights on other airlines for its passengers. Cathay has chartered
aircraft from 10 airlines, some of them direct competitors like
Singapore Airlines, Thai Airways and Malaysia Airlines. Analysts
warn that even if Cathay and the pilots reach a deal, it may be
losing market share that will be hard to win back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
