<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAMPING GREED OUT OF COLLECTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sounds swirl at baseball-card shows and Beanie Baby
conventions _ the hustle and bustle of deals made, prices haggled
over, values questioned.
</P>
<P>
   They blend together into a deafening roar best described with
one word:
</P>
<P>
   Greed.
</P>
<P>
   When's the last time a kid wanted an Albert Belle card because
he liked Albert Belle and not because he thought it would be worth
$25 a year from now? When's the last time a parent bought a
mint-condition Beanie Babie because she thought her daughter might
like to play with it and not because she considered it a blue-chip
investment?
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Stamp Show is different. The silence isn't
deafening, but it's a nice change of pace. Held the first Sunday of
every month at the Ramada Plaza Hotel Metrocenter, the show is
devoid of flash, glitz and glamour. And all the more enjoyable for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Glenda Lovera pored through a box stuffed with postcards at Mark
Schulzinger's table, searching for just the right stamp. All around
the room other stamp collectors, hunched over what looked like
miniature drawers from old-timey library card catalogs, did the
same thing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Possession-minded &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is very intent,'' Schulzinger said as he bit into a
bagel. ``This is more of an anal-retentive hobby than baseball
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovera shook her head and chuckled _ without once lifting her
gaze from the postcards. Well?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am anal-retentive,'' she said. At least she's honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the anal-retentive, the collecting, the acquiring is the
important thing,'' Schulzinger continued.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently. Noel Kasper certainly gave that impression. The
acquiring impression, that is, if not the anal-retentive one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's greed in stamps, too,'' Kas per, a 66-year-old Sun
City resident, said. ``Not money greed. Possession. Not that they
want the stamp to resell it. They want to have it because Joe Blow,
who they talk to regularly about stamps, doesn't have it. And
that's kind of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasper's interest began early.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people start when they're kids,'' he said. ``When girls
and sports take over, you quit. Then when you can't do girls and
sports anymore, you start back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My latest venture started in 1972. That happens to coincide
with my divorce.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
An older attraction &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kasper, who keeps his most valuable stamps in a safe-deposit
box, once shelled out $3,000 for one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard to pull the trigger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I would think so. Doesn't he ever look at that stamp and see
part of the payment on the Cadillac he's not driving?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm driving a Cadillac,'' Kasper said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Still, doesn't he have any regrets?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a cabin in Minnesota,'' he said, laughing,
``but I've got all these damn stamps instead.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes patience, stamp collecting. Perhaps that's why the room
was filled with mostly older people. It's not a young man's game
anymore. John Kraft is only 32 _ a relative toddler _ but he
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stamp collecting is coming down,'' Kraft said as he searched a
box for Belgian stamps (he's from Belgium). ``There's a lot of
other interests for people other than stamps.''
</P>
<P>
   But stamps interested him from the age of 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take the time and effort to learn why the stamps were
released, there's always something behind it,'' Kraft said. ``It
can be history, it can be geography. It's a form of curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he has the patience part down pat. He found a few stamps
he was looking for, tracking them down in the hardback Belgian
stamp catalog (written in French) he carries with him to shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me an hour, though,'' he said, using tweezers to pull
one of his finds from a waxed envelope. ``But still, that's the
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun. Now there's a word not tossed about enough at a
baseball-card show or a Barbie convention. In its own quiet way,
the stamp show offered plenty. Signed, sealed and delivered. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
