<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNDEAL-COX     06-08 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNDEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crime weapons traced back to states, dealers
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A tiny fraction of the nation's 100,000 gun dealers
sold nearly half of all guns traced to crimes, a new study has
found.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia gun dealers ranked third behind Illinois and Indiana for
the number of guns linked to gun crimes in 1996, 1997 and 1998, the
study found.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, Georgia was the leading source of guns used by
criminals in other states, according to Sen. Charles Schumer
(D-N.Y.), whose staff compiled the study based on data from the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said the findings highlight the impact of weak gun laws
in states such as Georgia and demonstrate that a few ``bad apple''
gun dealers account for most of the guns that wind up in the hands
of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are some dealers out there who cater to people
who use guns to commit crimes,'' said Schumer, a fierce advocate of
gun control. ``Being the source of a lot of crime guns does not
necessarily mean that these dealers are breaking the law, but it
cries out for an explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   J.R. McCollum, the ATF's spokesman in Atlanta, disputed
Schumer's conclusions. McCollum said the guns traced to gun crimes
most often came from the gun dealers who sold the most guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just logical that you would have high numbers there,''
McCollum said. ``I don't think it's startling.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Schumer's analysis of ATF data, 15 gun dealers in
Georgia were the source of 3,726 crime guns between 1996 and 1998.
Twelve of the 15 dealers were located around metro Atlanta, spread
out among Doraville, Decatur, Jonesboro, East Point, Smyrna,
Mableton and Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Three others were in Chickamauga, Macon and Bogart. The state
has 2,877 licenced gun dealers as of April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The gun dealer with the highest number of crime guns sold was
located near Decatur. The dealers were not identified by name in
the study.
</P>
<P>
   ATF officials in Washington said they could not comment directly
on Schumer's findings because they did not review his methodology.
But ATF spokesman Jeff Roehm said the bureau routinely traces guns
to identify potential gun traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he said, the bureau traced a number of guns used in
gang crimes in Boston to a gun dealer in Mississippi. It turned out
that a Boston man attending school in Mississippi was using his
relatives in the state to purchase guns, which he in turn
transported to Boston to sell to gang members.
</P>
<P>
   But a high number of crime guns traced to a single dealer isn't
always an indication of a problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of all of the (dealers) listed,'' Roehm said.
``Some are out of business, some are in prison, some are under
investigation. Some of them also have been inspected many times and
are operating completely within the laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he will introduce legislation this week that will
make it easier for ATF agents to target potentially bad gun
dealers. The legislation would allow the ATF to target dealers for
sting operations and suspend their licences for infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, ATF is forbidden from inspecting any gun dealer more
than once a year without a warrant and can only revoke, not
suspend, dealer licences.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Rand, federal policy director at the Violence Policy
Center, said the threshold for revoking a licence is much higher
than suspending it, making it more difficult for ATF to act against
dealers who sell guns that they suspect might end up in the hands
of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``ATF is not being aggressive in revoking licences,'' she said.
``They need some suspension authority.''
</P>
<P>
   The last gun dealer licence revocation in Georgia was in 1996,
according to Schumer's analysis, but that does not include dealers
whose licences came up for renewal and were denied.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Schumer's study found that 1,160 gun dealers _ 1.1
percent of the nation's total _ were the source of 34,626 crime
guns in 1998, or 45 percent of all the guns successfully traced by
the ATF. One-hundred thirty-seven gun dealers sold more than 50
guns that were involved in gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   On average, the ATF can successfully trace 50 to 60 percent of
all the guns that local and state jurisdictions ask them to trace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the same stores show up year after year as the
source of crime guns proves that there is a funnel from certain gun
stores to criminals and to the black market,'' Schumer said.
``Criminals and straw buyers seem to know the gun sellers who will
look the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
