<HEADER>
A7793 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-VIOLENCE-COX     06-08 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-VIOLENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans take about-face on legislation timetable
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After insisting on a deliberative schedule to
consider gun control legislation in the House Judiciary Committee,
Republican leaders abruptly reversed course Tuesday and announced a
new timetable that by-passes the committee and moves the
legislation to a House vote next week.
</P>
<P>
   The change in tactic is due in part to the discomfort many
Republicans feel about swallowing new gun control restrictions,
Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are uncomfortable with gun issues would rather vote
once, rather than twice,'' Hyde said. ``A lot of people don't want
to vote repeatedly on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats reacted angrily to the change in schedule, which
effectively denied them another opportunity to capitalize on the
gun debate in the ideologically polarized Judiciary committee. The
committee had been scheduled to consider the gun control
legislation as part of a juvenile justice crime bill this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told they had to go through the committee,'' said
House minority leader Richard Gephardt (D-Mo.), who made himself
available to reporters to voice his displeasure. ``It's now obvious
to me that this was all a show to allow the NRA and other groups
time to regroup.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's office distributed copies of a National Rifle
Association fund-raising letter that urges its members to fight the
new gun restrictions and warns that the new laws are an attempt
``by gun haters and the enemies of your Second Amendment freedoms
to dismantle the Second Amendment one step at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, adopted by the Senate three weeks ago, would
require all guns to be sold with trigger locks or safety storage
boxes, ban violent juveniles from ever owning a gun, outlaw
high-volume ammunition clips and require criminal background checks
for guns purchased at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA informed its members that it is buying newspaper ads
across the country, manning phone banks ``coast to coast'' and
waging a full-court press to lobby against the proposed
restrictions. The cost of the letter alone, the NRA letter said,
was almost $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders also signaled that they were softening
the most controversial component of the Senate legislation, the one
dealing with background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Senate bill, non-licensed gun dealers at gun shows
would have to sell guns through licensed dealers, who would then
perform the background check. The Senate bill allows law
enforcement officials 72 hours to complete the checks, so as to
take into account that gun shows frequently occur on weekends when
access to criminal records is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said the House bill would reduce the 72 hour time-period,
perhaps to 24 hours. The NRA is opposed to any background check
that is not able to be completed ``instantly.'' The gun lobby also
vigorously opposes the record keeping requirements proposed under
the new bill, claiming they would amount to a national gun
registry.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde and House Republicans are also championing new legislation
geared toward outlawing the sale of explicitly violent or sexual
material to juveniles. It would also require music stores to make
available to parents for on-site review any lyrics packaged with a
compact disc or tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more to this problem of juvenile violence than just
gun laws,'' Hyde said. ``We're trying to address the problem of
juvenile violence in a comprehensive way.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hyde said he also plans to offer an amendment to the bill
that would prohibit anyone under 21 from possessing a handgun, a
proposal also endorsed by President Clinton. Aides to Hyde later
said that the chairman's bill would ban those under 21 from
purchasing a handgun, not possessing one.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
