<HEADLINE>
TOWN CHAFES UNDER REBEL PRESENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRUMA, Albania _ It was a sleepy mountain border town, then a
massive refugee camp. And now, this town has morphed into a de
facto base for the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened residents and refugees here are not happy about their
new neighbors, especially after getting shelled by the Serbs in the
past week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my country, but I don't think they should have a
military base in the city,'' said Uke Sheta, Kruma's deputy mayor.
``It's a big risk. I'm the deputy mayor, and no one listens to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not your ordinary ``not in my backyard'' syndrome. Some
say the new locals in Kruma have taken over. And the presence of
the KLA may well be what has been attracting so much artillery
recently. Several days ago, a woman was killed and six people were
injured after eight shells landed in Kruma.
</P>
<P>
   Technically Albania is not part of the KLA effort, though it is
widely known that the rebel army trains and operates bases on the
Albanian side of the border. The presence of the KLA in Kruma could
draw Albania closer into the war, residents and refugees worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are shelling the city because there are UCK here,'' said
Lulzim Gashi, 21, a refugee from Djakovica, referring to the
Albanian name for the KLA. ``Everybody's leaving _ not just
refugees, but also the townspeople,'' said Gashi. He himself is
waiting for family members to get him the cash to go eight hours
south to Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of the refugee crisis, the town of Kruma and the
surrounding villages was populated by around 25,000 permanent
residents and 30,000 refugees, Sheta said. The combined number for
the northern region is now down to about 17,000 residents and very
few refugees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the refugees left because of the shelling. Many were
moved south as part of a general practice by aid organizations to
spread the refugee burden around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
estimates that about 4,000 people have left Kruma in recent days,
when fighting escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are afraid. We would like to go, but we have nowhere to
go,'' said Zenon Gashi, 47, who has been staying for two months on
the floor of a central mosque with her 11 children.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has practically usurped authority from the local police,
Sheta said, adding that there has been ``a bad relationship''
between the KLA and the local government. But the local authorities
can do nothing, Sheta said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers seem to be everywhere in Kruma, strutting in
camouflage uniforms and yellow, red, and black UCK badges. A KLA
hospital dominates the center of town, and uniformed soldiers take
up most of the tables at the outdoor cafes. UCK military vehicles
cruise down the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a few children playing in the streets and old men
sitting in the sun, Kruma looks more like an official army base
than a mountain town.
</P>
<P>
   Sheta estimated that there are 5,000 KLA soldiers in Kruma and
the surrounding mountains. The men come down to Kruma to rest and
get medical care, he said. KLA soldiers refused to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say the KLA makes Kruma better protected. ``When
they are near us, we are feeling safe,'' said Nehbi Leshi, 73. The
KLA has responded to Serbs shelling, while ``the Albanian army does
nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of them I am wounded,'' scoffed an 18-year-old
Albanian Army soldier, who would not give his name. ``When will
they go?''
</P>
</TEXT>
