A7795 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TEENS-IDS-2TAK     06-08 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TEENS-IDS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER OWNERS SAY THEY WILL ASK FOR PHOTO I.D.'S FROM YOUNG
MOVIEGOERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Egged on by President Clinton, representatives of
movie theater owners across the country announced on Tuesday that
they would require teen-agers to present a photo identification
card when they showed up without an adult to see an R-rated film.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was the latest effort by politicians and
officials from the entertainment industry to respond to public
concern that pervasive violence in movies and on television was
partly responsible for the shootings this spring in high schools in
Littleton, Colo., and Conyers, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   William Kartozian, president of the National Association of
Theater Owners, said he expected most theaters to begin enforcing
the policy within the next 30 to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this will go a long way in carrying out our
responsibilities to the parents of America,'' said Kartozian as he
stood next to the president at the White House. The association
represents the owners of theaters that have about two-thirds of the
country's movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton agreed with Kartozian's assessment. ``When you drop them
off,'' the president said, ``you shouldn't have to worry about your
G-rated kids getting into violent or suggestive R-rated movies.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie-rating system was adopted in 1968 by the Motion
Picture Association of America and relies on voluntary enforcement
by the theaters. An ``R'' rating means ``restricted: under 17
requires accompanying parent or guardian.'' The rating is usually
based on sex, violence and language.
</P>
<P>
   But many authorities on adolescent psychology said that
requiring proof of age could backfire, making violent movies even
more enticing to young teen-agers because of the challenge of
getting in, and creating a new market for fake identification
cards.
</P>
<P>
   And the teen-agers themselves who are used to going to movies
supposedly forbidden to them were blase, saying they were confident
that in the age of multiplex cinemas they would still have no
problem seeing any movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have to do is say I am going to see `Star Wars' and then
sneak into the movie I really want to see,'' said Paul McSweeney,
14, who attends West High School in Madison, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth I. Howard, a psychology professor at Northwestern
University who specializes in adolescence and who has six children
of his own, the youngest of whom is 11, said of the new policy: ``I
suspect it'll promote kids sneaking into movies, though now they
may have to be a little more clever.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Howard said, the traffic in phony identification cards
is generally confined to young people who are 19 or so and want to
buy beer or get into bars where the legal age is 21. The new movie
policy, he said, could not be enforced and would drive the market
for fake i.d.'s down to 14- and 15-year-olds
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to do,'' Howard asked, ``throw all the
15-year-olds in jail?''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Cohen, director of the Child Studies Center at Yale
University, said that the intention of the policy was right but
that the result might be to make young people even more cynical
about the rules set by adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents should be helping their children decide what movies to
go to,'' Cohen said. ``Neighborhoods should be deciding what movies
should be shown.''
</P>
<P>
   The word in the industry is that enforcement of the
age-restriction policy has been more rigid in small towns and
suburbs in the South and Midwest and less so in big cities and on
the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love,'' which won the Academy Award for the
best movie of 1998, was rated R. So were three of the other four
films nominated for the award, all but ``Life is Beautiful,'' which
was set in a Nazi concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a certain way, kids want to see an R-rated movie because
it's illegal,'' said Jeff Vierstra, another 14-year-old from
Madison, ``but I go to see them because they're good.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the announcement on Tuesday, Kartozian of
the theater owners association said he knows that underage
youngsters sneak into movies with abandon and that they might even
be more attracted by the prohibition. ``But we're going to try to
be vigilant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the high school shootings, lawmakers, especially those
opposed to gun control, have been scrambling to offer legislation
meant to reduce teen-agers' exposure to violence in entertainment.
Among the bills in the drafting stage is one that would impose
stiff fines on theater owners who violate the age requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Kartozian acknowledged that one reason for the new policy was to
try to head off onerous legislation, but he said the main motive
was that theater owners wanted to live up to their responsibilities
to the community.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The source of the politicians' interest in the matter is not
difficult to find. A Gallup Poll last month found that 62 percent
of adults said violence in popular entertainment was ``one of the
major causes of violence among young people.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll in April by CNN and USA Today the day after the shootings
in Littleton found that 81 percent of adults thought stricter
regulation of violence on television and in movies would reduce
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Since the high school shootings, Clinton has pressed Congress to
enact gun-control laws. And he has had one event after another to
express his interest in limiting violence on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, he convened a White House meeting on youth and
violence that some in the entertainment business refused to attend
because they thought it was an effort to demonize Hollywood for the
prevalence of violence in society.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the president raised $2 million for the
Democratic Party at a dinner in Hollywood given by top movie
executives. At the dinner, he gently chided his hosts for including
too much violence in their products.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has generally pulled his punches when dealing with his
reliable donor base in the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   The president has also directed the surgeon general to study the
possible link between stylized violence in popular culture and real
violence by young people. And he has asked the Justice Department
and the Federal Trade Commission to study whether the entertainment
industry was violating its own voluntary codes by enticing children
to watch violent films, listen to explicit music and play murderous
video games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
