<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RUBES HAIL FROM OUTER BOROUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mark Jackson thought he was a gym rat until he met up
with Chris Mullin. Then he discovered how far he was down the
rodent chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was phenomenal,'' Jackson recalls. ``I was doing my
fancy stuff, and he was just scratching away.''
</P>
<P>
   They were together for two years at St. John's University in
Queens, and now they are together with the Pacers in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   The tabloid cliche is that the Pacers are ``hicks'' _
conveniently rhymes with ``Knicks'' _ but the reality is that these
two hail from the land of ``Me and Julio Down by the Schoolyard,''
and play with the savvy of people who can safely jaywalk across
Union Turnpike with their eyes closed and their headset on full
blast.
</P>
<P>
   These two alleged rustics played the more sophisticated game in
Monday's 90-78 victory that tied this playoff series at two games
each. Jackson distributed the ball, and the Knicks never seemed to
figure out that Mullin and Jalen Rose shoot left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night in Indiana, Mullin and Jackson will try to beat
the team of their childhood, the team that let Jackson go, the team
that has never managed to bring Mullin home, and probably just as
well for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson played five years for the Knicks before being run out by
the kind of corporate dysfunction that never seems to go out of
style at the Garden. Mullin is better off under the stability of
Donnie Walsh and Larry Bird, to say nothing of supportive fans who
do not scream for blood when the home team falls behind early, as
they do at the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Now thriving in the hinterlands, Jackson and Mullin first met in
their home borough of Brooklyn. Looie Carnesecca of St. John's was
in the stands, scouting Mullin with Xaverian, when he spotted
Jackson, a sophomore with Loughlin. Two years later he brought
Jackson out to the campus in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Carnesecca told me to work with Mark,'' Mullin recalled
in his still-blessedly lush Bruklun accent. ``I'd be pushing off on
him, he'd be pushing off on me.''
</P>
<P>
   They got to the Final Four together in 1985, and soon went their
separate ways. Mullin played in Golden State, confronted his
alcoholism, has played sober and steady for a decade. Jackson came
to the Knicks, young and headstrong, which led to his exile. If the
Knicks' management had been able to see past the occasional
showboating, to the intelligent and caring person within, Mark
Jackson could still be playing point guard for the Knicks. Instead,
he has been reunited with his old gym-rat mentor. ``He's one of my
favorite people,'' Mullin said Monday. ``I never knew how much I
missed him until I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just special to me, the relationship we had,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is a minister now, married with three children, still
intense about controlling the game, but a calm man away from the
court. He has seen his close friend, Patrick Ewing, hear the
catcalls in Jackson's hometown _ but all the same, Jackson loves
coming back. He was walking in midtown Monday, trying to rid
himself of the demons of Saturday's last-moment loss to the Knicks,
when he opted for that most cathartic of remedies, a good
old-fashioned head-shaving. The Pacers used to shave their heads
for the playoffs, but this year they got away from it. Jackson went
into the first barbershop he saw and asked for the Full Jordan, but
that wasn't the end of it. The barber then held an electronic
vibrator in the palm of his hand and applied it to Jackson's smooth
dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great, man,'' Jackson reported after beating the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   How much did the haircut cost? Last week Bob Baffert, the
white-maned trainer of Silverbulletday, reported a $78 trim at the
salon in his upscale Manhattan hotel. Jackson's tab, down a side
street, was exactly one-sixth of Baffert's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirteen dollars,'' Jackson said. ``But I gave him $30.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson got on the team bus a few hours later, Reggie
Miller spotted His Baldness and shouted, ``It's on,'' an old war
cry that still worked. ``Just getting back to the old days,''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``old days'' were reinforced before the game when an Italian
leprechaun named Carnesecca popped his head into the locker room
and hoarsely wished Mullin and Jackson good luck.
</P>
<P>
   Bald and brash, Jackson seemed to finally set a pattern for this
round, now that the Knicks are facing the reality of life without
Ewing. The big man from Georgetown kept them out of the college
finals in 1985. This time Mullin and Jackson could return the favor
_ the revenge of the gym rats. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
