<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELEMENTS-DISCOVERED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS REPORT CREATION OF 2 NEW ELEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a discovery that came as a complete surprise to most nuclear
chemists, an international team of scientists at Lawrence Berkeley
National Laboratory in California has added two new elements to the
periodic table.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory announced on Monday that the two elements, with
atomic numbers 118 and 116 on the periodic table, were created in
late April using a cyclotron accelerator to bombard a lead target
with projectiles of krypton atoms. In three of the collisions
observed by the Berkeley team, target and projectile atoms fused to
form gigantic atoms with nuclei containing 118 protons and 175
neutrons.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the atoms of Element 118 survived for less than 1/10,000
of a second before decaying radioactively into an atom of a second
new element, Element 116, with 116 protons and 173 neutrons in its
nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   Until this experiment, the fusion route by which Element 118 was
created was considered impossible by most of the scientists
involved in heavy-element research, including those at Germany's
Society for Heavy Ion Research in Darmstadt (GSI) and Russia's
Joint Institute for Nuclear Research at Dubna.
</P>
<P>
   However, a young Polish theorist, Dr. Robert Smolanczuk, made a
series of calculations from which he concluded that a
lead-and-krypton collision technique could produce the desired
element.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one, including the people at GSI where Robert was
working, believed it,'' said Al Ghiorso of the Berkeley laboratory,
who is himself one of the world's leading discoverers of new
elements.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Darleane Hoffman, a professor at the Berkeley laboratory and
one of the 15 scientists listed as codiscoverers of Element 118,
said in an interview that Dr. Smolanczuk had approached her asking
to join the Berkeley team. ``I didn't have any money to employ him,
but he had been awarded a Fulbright scholarship to pay his way,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smolanczuk's calculations were at odds with prevailing
theories of possible routes to heavy artificial elements, the
Berkeley laboratory resolved to try them out, using krypton atoms
containing 86 protons to bombard lead atoms with 208 protons. A
special detector, the design for which was proposed by Ghiorso,
measured the debris produced when a single ephemeral atom of
Element 118 decayed in a characteristic way.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley experimental team, headed by Dr. Kenneth Gregorich,
measured the atom's decay into Element 116, then 114, then 112 and
on down to 106 _ an artificial element that was recently named
seaborgium in honor of the late Dr. Glenn Seaborg, the chemist who
discovered plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a surprise that we couldn't believe it at first,''
Ghiorso said. ``Robert Smolanczuk's calculations were verified
almost perfectly. The results are out today and seem to be causing
a lot of excitement. Already the GSI laboratory in Germany has
started an experiment to confirm our result.''
</P>
<P>
   All elements containing more than the 92 protons in the nucleus
of a uranium atom are called ``transuranic'' elements, and none
exists in nature in appreciable quantities. Most are so radioactive
that they decay swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Some have practical uses. Plutonium fuels nuclear weapons.
Americium is used in smoke detectors, and several transuranic
elements are used in nuclear medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But the main interest of nuclear chemists is in discovering just
how far the limits of matter can be pushed. In particular, they
search for ``super-heavy'' elements, including some that may lie in
an ``Island of Stability,'' capable of surviving for relatively
long periods.
</P>
<P>
   Theories of nuclear structure suggest that protons and neutrons
are arrayed in distinct shells within a nucleus. A shell fully
occupied by neutrons or protons is regarded as more stable than an
unfilled shell, and less likely to decay radioactively.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, theorists have predicted that if an atom with
114 protons and about 184 neutrons could be packed together without
shaking itself to pieces, it might prove to be fairly stable. Last
January, Russian scientists and the Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory in California said that they had created this element,
which reportedly survived for about 30 seconds _ a very long time,
by transuranic standards. Efforts are being made to confirm the
scientists claims.
</P>
<P>
   Although Elements 118 and 116 survive only very briefly, their
lifetimes are still longer than would be the case outside the
Island of Stability. One theoretical prediction is that Element
126, if it could be created, might be especially stable. Dr.
Hoffman and Ghiorso said they intended to try for 126 soon, drawing
from Smolanczuk's calculations and bombarding a lead target with
ruthenium atoms. They will also attempt to fill in some blanks in
the sequence of elements in the periodic table, using a bismuth
target to create Element 119. This would presumably decay by
emitting a helium nucleus containing two protons. That would yield
Element 117, which in turn would decay to Elements 115 and 113.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our unexpected success in producing these superheavy elements
opens up a whole new world of possibilities using similar
reactions,'' Gregorich said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new elements, those higher than 109 have yet to be
formally named. Dr. Hoffman said on Tuesday that she intended to
propose Ghiorso's name for one of them _ ``ghiorsium.'' Ghiorso was
the designer of many of the machines that created new elements and
was a codiscoverer of a dozen artificial elements.
</P>
</TEXT>
