A7814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-GAREAX-COX     06-08 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-GAREAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia theater owners vow to police underaged moviegoers
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Young teens aching to see the new R-rated ``South
Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' debuting later this month will
likely find it harder to get a seat following Tuesday's pledge by
most of the nation's theaters to require photo IDs for admission to
restricted movies.
</P>
<P>
   Several metro Atlanta theater chains said they would step up
policing of admissions to current R-rated films like ``The
Matrix,'' ``Election'' and ``Trippin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often children do get past the ticket counter unescorted
and underage,'' President Clinton said in Washington as the
National Association of Theater Owners announced its photo
identification pledge. ``The theater owners are clearly drawing the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see a much more concerted effort to do
a better job (at policing),'' said Phil Zacheretti, vice president
of marketing and advertising for Regal Cinemas. ``We're going to do
more staff training, more emphasis on what we've already been
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had earlier challenged the movie industry to enforce its
rating system more strictly in the wake of the high school
shootings in Littleton, Colo., and Conyers. The president denied
the move was precipitated by hesitancy among Hollywood executives
to embrace his call to reduce violent content in films, and
predicted they eventually will join his crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all work at it . . . so that nobody's pointing a finger
at anybody else, I think we'll have good participation from the
entertainment community,'' Clinton said. ``I'll be surprised if we
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater owners group, which represents about 65 percent of
the movie screens in the United States, said theaters would display
posters at their box offices informing customers that every young
person who comes to see an R-rated movie will be asked to show a
photo ID.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who want their children under 17 to see an R-rated movie
will still be able to buy tickets and escort them into theaters,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of surprised that I have 65 to 70 calls from the
media about this,'' said Brian Callaghan, manager of communications
for General Cinemas. ``It's pretty much the policy we have enforced
for years.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that General Cinemas would ``redouble our efforts
by checking auditoriums, by checking IDs.'' And his chain is well
aware of a common youth practice _ buying a ticket to a lower-rated
movie and then heading to an R-rated screening.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a group of 15-year-olds buying tickets to a
G-movie late on a Friday night, it raises eyebrows,'' Callaghan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chain representatives were quick to admit that sometimes younger
patrons do buy tickets to R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to say that never happens,'' Zacheretti said.
Decisions on who gets carded are often made at the box office and
are subjective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may let a 15-year-old go by who looks 19, but you do the
very best you can,'' Zacheretti said.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly all chains have an age checkpoint at the box
office, additional policing varies widely.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Theatre Company rechecks ages in the lobby ticket-taking
area and has staffers patrol theaters and look at the audience,
according to chain president Bill Stembler. He is also considering
instituting a parental consent form for those parents who would
allow their underage kids to see R-rated movies unaccompanied.
</P>
<P>
   AMC Theatres' Brenda Nolte says her chain has two secret
checkpoints beyond the box office. She also maintains AMC has been
in compliance with the policy since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   At Regal, ushers are not posted routinely at theater doors to
recheck ages, but staffers do patrol screening rooms and will
question patrons who look under age.
</P>
<P>
   Other chains weren't as quick to jump on board Tuesday's
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a problem currently,'' said Phil Smitely,
director of marketing for Columbus, Ga.-based Carmike Cinemas,
which is not a member of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always had a policy adhering to film ratings and we
try to police it as best we can,'' Smitely said. ``It is the
discretion of the theater manager (whether to ask for a photo ID).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at what NATO is proposing and if it's something we
want to adopt, we will address it at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO said theater owners also pledged to undertake a national
community education effort to develop additional programs to
enhance the ability of parents to make decisions on what movies
their kids can see. And NATO endorsed the idea of a national study
of youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has directed the surgeon general to compile a report on
youth violence by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Contributing: The Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
