u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTRICITY-NEWENGLAN     06-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTRICITY-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT CAUSES PRICES ON SPOT MARKET TO SOAR 
</HEADLINE>
 ENGLAND-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prices on New England's new spot market for electricity soared
to 30 times the normal levels for a second day in a row Tuesday as
sweltering heat drove huge demand for air conditioning and
refrigeration and raised the risk of rolling blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   But while the offering price for one megawatt-hour of power hit
$1,003 Tuesday morning _ compared to $20 to $30 on a normal day _
industry officials stressed that typical consumers will see
virtually no impact on their June electric bills.
</P>
<P>
   The people getting killed _ and making a killing _ on the
month-old New England spot market for electricity were huge
generating companies, electricity brokers, and speculators. And
some of the prices may be ordered reduced by ISO New England, the
Holyoke nonprofit company that runs the power auction for the
six-state region and can act to prevent gouging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Murphy at 222 Elm Street or even a large industrial
customer isn't affected by this at all,'' said Neal B. Costello,
general counsel to the Competitive Power Coalition, a Boston group
that represents plant owners selling to the grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emphatic answer to the question is: The retail customer
does not pay,'' Costello said. ``It's the wholesale middlemen who
are at risk. They fully know what the risks are, and it really is
capitalism at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Edison, for example, buys all power for its 550,000
customers under a long-term, fixed-price contract with Select
Energy, a subisidary of Northeast Utilities, said Edison spokesman
Michael Monahan.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, ComEnergy, serving 360,000 homes and businesses in a
region that includes Cambridge, New Bedford, and Cape Cod, gets
``100 percent under contracts. We don't buy power on the spot
market,'' said spokesman Peter A. Dimond.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, on a typical day, about 88 percent of power moving
through the New England grid has been paid for on a fixed-price
contract, and 12 percent is being purchased on the spot market,
said Jim Sinclair, a spokesman for the ISO group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new wholesale auction market that began May 1 in New
England, who is buying and selling power at what price is now a
closely guarded trade secret, and efforts to learn who was paying
and getting the huge prices were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the big players in the trading market are known to
include Enron, Select Energy, and Southern Energy, as well as a
host of energy brokerages. They guarantee to provide certain levels
of power to utilities or big producers and then play the market to
get the best price, bearing risk when the supply-demand curve
drives prices through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two days, an unexpected heat wave combined with
reduced generating capacity pushed demand for electricity almost
past what the New England grid can supply. A half-dozen of the
largest of the region's 330 plants are off line for scheduled
service, but additional power is also available from connections to
the New York and Canadian grids.
</P>
<P>
   ISO New England officials threatened to impose two-hour rolling
blackouts Tuesday morning, but backed off after voluntary
conservation efforts _ including a state government shutdown in
Massachusetts _ eased demand to safe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new system, ISO New England each day takes
hour-by-hour bids to supply the next day's spot-market power needs
and takes bidders from cheapest to most expensive, paying all spot
bidders the highest bid price each hour. Fixed-contract prices,
however, do not fluctuate with the market.
</P>
<P>
   As demand rises to levels nearly exceeding supply, the ISO has
to start accepting bids from, for example, plant owners who have
offered to turn on an ancient generator only for a huge price or
from speculators who offer to sell their last few megawatts at a
gigantic premium.
</P>
<P>
   Costello said that despite what may look like ``profiteering''
by companies taking advantage of a regional energy crisis, ``from a
consumer standpoint, it's more important to ask what is an average
yearly price'' for electricity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
