<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: FORBES PUSHES ITS WEB SITE, WITH ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ga., Mass., Mich., Calif., N.Y., Wash.)  (jw) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To put its two-year-old World Wide Web site on the map, Forbes
Inc. is waging its biggest ad campaign ever.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held publishing company plans to spend $10 million
on the campaign for forbes.com, the most it has ever spent on any
campaign, through the end of the year. The campaign, created by
Merkley Newman Harty, a unit of Omnicom Group, is intended
primarily to increase traffic on the site and, ultimately,
advertising sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel this is a real opportunity for us to grow the site and
revenues,'' said Gregory Zorthian, vice president for business
development at Forbes and the acting chief executive of forbes.com.
``If we wait six months, others might do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to grow the brand fast,'' added Bruce Rogers, vice
president for marketing communications at Forbes. ``The time span
to build a brand on the Web is different. The life span of a Web
entity is shortened because there's so much competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Its promoters say Forbes.com, which includes original editorial
material as well as electronic versions of articles appearing in
Forbes' flagship business magazine and other supplements, is
building a robust audience. According to Zorthian, the site logged
2.5 million visits in May, compared with 1.6 million visits in the
month a year earlier. The site's year-to-date advertising revenue _
for advertising that has either appeared or been ordered _ is 2{
times that generated in all of 1998, he said. Sponsors include Sun
Microsystems, Gateway, MCI Worldcom and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   Zorthian also said the site had been profitable for several
months last year and several months so far this year, but that it
was not turning a profit now.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the record budget, Merkley Newman Harty's campaign for
the site differs from its traditional advertising for Forbes in
several ways. It is the first Forbes campaign geared to consumers _
all previous campaigns have been directed at potential advertisers
and their agencies. The campaign is also using radio for the first
time, devoting about a third of its budget to it.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign's target audience also differs from that for
Forbes magazine because an estimated 80 percent to 90 percent of
visitors to forbes.com do not subscribe to Forbes and its two
supplements, the lifestyle-oriented Forbes FYI, and the
technology-oriented Forbes ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a younger, knowing kind of audience that's
technologically savvy, entrepreneurial, investment-minded and
comfortable with the Web,'' said Susan Popper, a group account
director at Merkley Newman Harty.
</P>
<P>
   To reach this audience, a series of three 60-second radio spots
are running, mostly during drive time, in seven large markets where
the site already has a strong following: Atlanta, Boston, Detroit,
Los Angeles, New York, San Francisco and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Intended to sound like public service announcements, the ads
feature folksy guitar music and an unctuous male announcer who
describes people who have become wealthy through the Web. One,
Jimmy, is a high school student who used a computer he received for
Christmas to create a Web site ``some big company bought,'' making
him ``disgustingly wealthy.'' Another is Sandy, a young mother
raising three children who designed ``an amazingly successful Web
site and got ridiculously wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   All the ads end by saying that forbes.com provides
``uncompromising views and opinions,'' and telling listeners:
``We're here to help. Forbes.com. It's a new game.''
</P>
<P>
   The print part of the campaign is made up of three ads whose
graphics and copy maintain the cheeky, cynical tone of the radio
spots, as well as the tagline.
</P>
<P>
   One features a fashionably punk young woman, described as a
``college-quitting, credit card-maxing, $23 million stock
option-owning retiree.'' Another shows a scruffy-looking young man,
who it says is a ``no-salary-earning, old underpants-wearing,
billionaire on paper CEO.''
</P>
<P>
   The third features a smirking youth wearing his baseball cap
backward: a ``21-year-old, pizza-eating, parent-mocking, software
company-owning capitalist pig.''
</P>
<P>
   The print ads are running on buses in the seven radio markets;
on billboards in San Francisco; on taxi tops, newsstands and
construction site posters in New York; in magazines like Fast
Company, Red Herring, Wired and Business 2.0; and in advertising
trade publications.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nail, a senior analyst for Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass., praised Forbes' efforts to ``give the site a completely
different personality than the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional Forbes audience is older, higher up, of
limited size,'' he said. ``They're trying to break out of the
mold.''
</P>
<P>
   Nail also commended Forbes for using drive-time radio, which he
called a potentially ``very effective medium,'' but warned that the
site faced steep competitive challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dowjones.com just launched, and Wall Street Journal
Interactive is very successful,'' he said. ``Their other big
competitors are portals like Yahoo, MSN and Excite. People at work
use portals to get their basic business information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes definitely will drive traffic to the site and raise its
profile, but $10 million is a lot of dough,'' he said. ``I doubt
they're going to generate enough more advertising revenue to pay
this back any time soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
