A7820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES09-COX     06-08 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons coach reflects on new life after heart surgeryBy Matt
Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Reeves still gets emotional thinking about the
open-heart surgery that saved his life last December, but it was
hard to tell that Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Reeves made his way through the areas of Piedmont Hospital
where he underwent surgery and began his recovery, he smiled a lot.
Several patients were clearly happy to see him. Reeves seemed
pleased as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can beat a heart attack, you can win the Super Bowl,''
said Lilburn's Charles Doss, who had open-heart surgery a couple of
days earlier. ``I may not win a Super Bowl, but I'm glad you beat
the heart attack,'' Reeves said, chuckling. ``That's much more
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Given what he went through last winter _ in the middle of the
Falcons' drive to Super Bowl XXXIII _ Reeves said Tuesday that his
idea of what is important has changed. After visiting about a dozen
patients and some of the nurses who cared for him last winter,
Reeves, his cardiologist, Dr. Charlie Brown, and his internist, Dr.
Charles Harrison, spoke to an auditorium of about 150 people about
coronary heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always have this disease,'' said Reeves, who will visit
eight hospitals around the country to talk about his experiences,
advise how to heed warning signals, and tell how to recover from
heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want (heart patients) to know they can lead a normal
life. You've got to have goals.''
</P>
<P>
   By reducing his fat intake and exercising, Reeves said, his life
has returned nearly to normal.
</P>
<P>
   He's lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Coronary heart disease is the largest killer of American men and
women, and Brown said about one-third of the 1.1 million Americans
who will have heart attacks this year will die from them.
</P>
<P>
   Other times, people have symptoms like those Reeves ignored for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He had tightness in his chest, and a burning sensation in his
throat for several weeks. Only after it worsened after a Dec. 13
victory at New Orleans did he say anything. He was in surgery the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Brown noted that people are more likely to have heart trouble if
they have bad cholesterol levels, weight problems, family history
of heart disease and diabetes. It also is more likely for men over
45 and women over 55.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the December news conference, in which Reeves had to
pause several times to gather himself, it happened only once
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He recovered quickly and said he also is trying to reduce the
stress in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Wife) Pam made me promise to take four (long weekends), and
we've taken two. And she's learning to golf with me,'' he said.
``I've also tried to narrow my vision just to tomorrow rather than
the big picture, which can be overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also delegating more. Obviously, my coaching staff is very
capable; look what the team did when I was out (winning the final
two games of the regular season). This is the beginning of your
life, not the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
