A7824 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-ASSE     06-08 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: VAGUENESS OF COUNCIL RESOLUTION MAY GIVE MILOSEVIC
ROOM TO MANEUVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOVOSO-ROUNDUP, KOSOVO-SCENE) 
(rm) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The European foreign ministers and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright pronounced themselves well satisfied
here Tuesday after haggling for 12 hours over the final draft of a
U.N. Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But their handiwork, which is supposed to provide the basis for
an end to the Kosovo war, leaves plenty of unanswered questions, as
well as some possible loopholes for Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to exploit.
</P>
<P>
   In a war increasingly defined as fought to return the more than
one million refugees driven out of Kosovo, the draft resolution is
vague about how that goal will be accomplished. Other unresolved
issues include the composition of the international security force
that is supposed to enter Kosovo in the wake of retreating Yugoslav
troops; the role of Russian soldiers in that force, and the
disarming of an increasingly cocky Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   A conflict over the return of the refugees broke into the open
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav foreign ministry spokesman, Nebojsa Vujovic, wasted
no time saying that Yugsolav and Serb guards and customs officials
would be at the borders to monitor the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In the peace terms that Milosevic agreed to, which became Annex
2 of the Security Council resolution, an agreed number of Yugoslav
and Serbian personnel are allowed to ``maintain a presence at key
border crossings.''
</P>
<P>
   Such monitoring could scare away many refugees, many of whom
watched Serb forces and paramilitaries kill, beat or harass family
members. Many of the refugees had their documents, birth and
marriage certificates destroyed by the Serbs before they were
forced to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that refugees in Macedonia and Albania had been
issued new identity papers by the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees. A ``few symbolic'' border guards would have no right to
inhibit their safe passage back to Kosovo, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said Tuesday that the refugees' return was
not primarily a NATO problem, but would instead be handled by
civilian authorities the Commissioner for Refugees is the agency
mentioned in the annex to the resolution. But the agency may well
need military backup to ensure the refugees' safety.
</P>
<P>
   For a leader whose country has been on the receiving end of more
than 10 weeks of air bombardment and who apparently acquiesced to a
peace plan last week, Milosevic is still able to wield influence.
</P>
<P>
   By having his generals insist this past weekend that they would
not negotiate with NATO on withdrawal arrangements until the
Security Council draft resolution was drawn up, Milosevic was using
the presence of the Russians in the drafting of the resolution to
filter out as much as he could of what he found distasteful. In
some respects, he succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the rush to closure, the Russians were able to keep
any mention of NATO out of the body of the resolution. NATO is
mentioned only in one of two annexes.
</P>
<P>
   In Annex 2, which is an almost total reprint of the accord
Milosevic agreed to last week, paragraph 4 says ``the international
security presence with substantial NATO participation must be
deployed under unified command and control.''
</P>
<P>
   But missing from this annex is a footnote to last week's accord
that further spells out how the security force has ``NATO at the
core.'' The next key sentence from the footnote, ``This in turn
means a unified NATO chain of command under the political control
of the North Atlantic Council in consultation with non-NATO force
contributors,'' is also missing from the annex.
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official traveling with Albright said
that the missing footnote represented NATO's ``internal business.''
The Yugoslavs, the official said, could not dictate how NATO would
form the security force or what command arrangements it would have.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior NATO official involved in the military talks with
the Yugoslavs that stalled last weekend said that Milosevic could
well exploit the absence of detail, balking at any measures that
were not spelled out in the Security Council resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little likelihood that the Serbs are going to sign a
military agreement that goes further than the Security Council
resolution,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution states that Kosovo remains a sovereign part of
Yugoslavia, a factor that still allows Milosevic to decide who
enters Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this rests on a strategic assessment that he is
prepared to withdraw and give up Kosovo. If you have doubts about
that, you will be worried,'' the NATO official added. The doubts
were easy to come by because in the first round of military talks,
the Yugoslavs said they would only draw down to ``peace time''
levels of 15,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-ASSE     06-08 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-ASSESS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 COLOGNE, Germany: 15,000 troops. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The role of the Russians in the security force, which is still
to be negotiated, apparently with the return to Moscow this week of
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, was also left unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian defense minister, Igor Sergeyev, said Tuesday that
Russia was ready to send up to 10,000 troops to Kosovo, 3,000 more
than Washington has promised for the 50,000 strong peacekeeping
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO officials believe this may be a bluff _ Moscow does
not have the money or the means to send these soldiers to Kosovo _
there are concerns about Russia deciding to transfer some of its
troops already serving in Bosnia. The Russians have stipulated one
thing: As in Bosnia, their troops in Kosovo will not be under NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton said he did not expect Russian troops to be
under NATO control but expected a similar arrangement to the one in
Bosnia, where Russian peacekeepers work in the American sector and
report to a U.S. general in his capacity as head of American forces
in Europe, rather than his role as NATO's military commander.
</P>
<P>
   The early presence of Russian troops in Kosovo, as virtual
free-lancers outside the control of NATO, could also threaten the
return of ethnic Albanian refugees. The Russians are viewed by the
refugees as Slavic brethren of the Serbs who expelled them.
</P>
<P>
   Further, through the Russians, Milosevic would be in a perfect
position to keep a hold on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He had already started to play that game through the Russian
military attache who was dispatched from Belgrade to attend the
NATO-Yugoslav weekend military talks. Though he was supposed to be
only an observer, the Russian attache sided with Yugoslavs on every
issue, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO tries to persuade Milosevic's generals to organize an
orderly withdrawal from Kosovo _ or, more accurately, as the
generals await the signal from their ultimate superior, Milosevic,
to leave _ NATO must also consider what to do about the Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla force has swelled with new recruits in northern
Albania and there are deepening concerns about how to prevent these
men, as well as those left inside Kosovo, from taking revenge on
retreating Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Albright met Tuesday with the political director of the
guerrillas, Hashim Thaci _ with whom she had had less than smooth
relations at the ill-fated Rambouillet talks in February _ and
asked him to control his forces. They must refrain, she said, from
seeking revenge and must disarm..
</P>
<P>
   Thaci, 31, who is now being eyed as the new power in Kosovo,
said his general staff would issue a statement in the coming days,
pledging not to take revenge on the Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   But in the rambunctious world of a guerrilla group that has been
battered by more than two months of fighting the better armed
Serbs, it was not clear that Thaci had the authority or the means
to quell what the Clinton administration fears: the outbreak across
Kosovo of civil wars between elements of an emboldened Kosovo
Liberation Army and Serb forces making their last stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
