<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-ART-NYT &LR;      06-08 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING LONG-TERM INTEREST RATES DAMPEN SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term interest rates hit 6 percent for the first
time in more than a year Tuesday after two Federal Reserve
officials made comments that suggested the central bank will raise
interest rates at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates and concern about the outlook for computer
companies helped send stocks lower in what promises to be continued
volatility ahead of the Fed policy meeting. After rising 109.54
points Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 143.74
points, or 1.32 percent, on Tuesday to 10,765.64.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest rate bell rings louder and stock knees get
weaker,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. He thinks interest rates can move
higher and stocks lower between now and the Fed meeting. But he
thinks that good second-quarter earnings reports and getting by the
Fed rate increase will help stocks rally in July.
</P>
<P>
   Before then, investors will have to contend with a Commerce
Department retail sales report Friday that is expected to be strong
and heighten expectations of a Fed rate increase. Then next week
comes the Consumer Price Index for May. If it is even moderately
strong, a rate increase will seem guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   In trading Tuesday, the yield on the 30-year bond slipped back
just under 6 percent at the end of the day, finishing at 5.99
percent, up from 5.96 percent Monday. Six percent is an important
psychological barrier and going through it ought to make investors
worry more in the near term about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Computer stocks, including IBM, Hewlett-Packard, Intel Corp.,
Cisco Systems and Dell Computer, lead the market lower. A report
from Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette said that sales and profits of PC
makers and software companies would be hurt at the end of the year,
as spending on information technology was reduced as the year 2000
_ and the possible computer problems associated with it _
approached. Many companies appear ready to delay spending not
associated with solving year 2000 problems because they do not want
to implement new programs that might complicate the transition to
the new year.
</P>
<P>
   The technology heavy NASDAQ index dropped 49.65 points or 2
percent, to 2,474.56, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500
stocks fell 17.19 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,317.33.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been expecting a rate increase since last month,
when it was reported that the April Consumer Price Index jumped
seven tenths of one percent and the Fed then announced that it was
leaning toward raising interest rates to slow growth and curb any
inflationary spurt.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of such a rate increase was not clear. But since then
a series of economic reports, including the May employment report
that was released Friday, have shown that the economy is still
strong and that wage pressures may be growing. And that has pushed
investors to betting that the Fed will act when its meets on June
29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   And the comments from William Poole, the president of the
Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis, and Alfred Broaddus, the
president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., were seen
as further confirmation of this view.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference at the Federal Reserve Bank in Boston, Poole
said that he ``would share the view'' that the odds now favor
higher inflation, according to Bloomberg News. According to
Reuters, Poole also said that it is best that Fed policy changes
``do not take the market by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
said, ``There seems to be more hawkish talk coming out of Fed
officials and the market is becoming more convinced that the Fed
will raise interest rates when it meets at the end of June.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are now predicting a quarter-of-a-percentage point
increase in the Fed's interest rate target, which is the interest
charged on overnight loans between banks. The target, known as the
Federal Funds rate, is now 4.75 percent. But based on one barometer
of market sentiment _ the difference between the Fed Funds target
and the yield on the two-year Treasury note _ some investors are
expecting that the Fed will push its target up another quarter of a
percentage point later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Some money managers think that if interest rates push a little
higher it will be time to buy bonds again because they expect the
Fed to succeed in slowing economic growth and curbing inflation, a
fact that would push interest rates lower.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Holzman, the managing partner of Cypress Funds LLC, a
hedge fund in Los Angeles, is being more cautious. He said that he
wants to see data that confirms the slowdown of the economy before
jumping back in. ``I would rather be in at 5.65 percent,'' he said,
referring to the yield on the 30-year bond, ``based on the fact
that you saw some slowdown than at 5.95'' without that
confirmation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
