<SLUG> BC-RUN-RECORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Master runners race for record book
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
   ATLANTA _ Note to the Guinness Book of World Records: Make room
for Atlanta's baby-boomer runners.
<P>
   One hundred men, all at least 40 years old, took turns Sunday
running a mile each at Emory University and easily broke the world
record in the 1x100 mile relay for male masters runners. They
finished in 8 hours, 57 minutes and 31 seconds, breaking the old
record by more than 6 1/2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The runners, almost all of whom live in the metro area, averaged
5:23 per mile _ 3.4 seconds faster than the mark set by a team from
Houston. ``There are guys in other cities just as fast or faster,''
one of the relay's organizers, Kirk Rosenbach, 47 of Atlanta, said
Tuesday. ``But the depth here is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m., Rosenbach set the pace by running the first mile in
5:18, followed by relay captain Joe Schroeder, 44, of
Lawrenceville, with 5:21. The pair stayed at the track to organize
the field they had recruited for the past 10 months. They had
advertised for runners who could break 5:45, but received such a
response that the qualifying time dropped to 5:31. About 15 runners
were in their 50s, and many hadn't run on an oval track since
high-school days.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbach coordinates the Atlanta Track Club's competitive
masters team and stacked some of his best runners early in the
relay. Six of the first 12 runners ran under 5 minutes, building a
cushion that grew to as much as 7 minutes faster than the old
record pace.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't the stars. As the temperature rose into the
80s, the less stellar runners in the middle of the relay never
slacked off: 55 of the runners were 5:26 or better. The slowest
mile was 5:56; only eight runners were above 5:39. ``They could
have melted in the afternoon sun,'' Rosenbach said. ``But guy after
guy kept hammering these great miles.''
</P>
<P>
   They had company on the track: One team of women and another of
men of all ages attempted unsuccessfully to break their own 1x100
records.
</P>
<P>
   For the masters men, last year's winner in the Peachtree Road
Race, Dick Buerkle, averaged 5:29 minutes per mile. Buerkle, 51 and
the former holder of the world indoor mile mark, capped off the
relay with a blistering 4:39 mile.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 of the runners stayed and cheered as he blazed around
the track and broke through the ribbon. Then they all took a
victory lap together.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbach still felt a lump in his throat days later. ``This
isn't something someone attempts every day,'' he said. ``It's an
unbelievable amount of work getting that many people together, and
that many fast people together.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hiskey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
