<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MCGRIFF-COX     06-08 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MCGRIFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crime Dog back in Atlanta, back on track
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As homecomings go, Fred McGriff's return to Turner
Field was warm _ game time temperature Monday evening: 85 degrees _
and, if not fuzzy, then certainly appreciative. When the Crime Dog
was introduced for his first at-bat, the applause was generous and
peppered with a once-familiar back-beat: the sound of a few fans
barking.
</P>
<P>
   Woof, woof. Welcome back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' said McGriff, after his first game here in a
Tampa Bay Devil Rays uniform. McGriff was the Braves' first baseman
and cleanup hitter from mid-1993 through '97. ``At least until
Smoltz hit the home run. Then, it wasn't too good after that.''
</P>
<P>
   When John Smoltz smacked that three-run homer, it started Tampa
Bay spiraling to yet another loss. The Rays' fourth defeat in a row
was their 13th in the last 15 games. After an 11-7 start, the
second-year expansion team has played .333 (13-26) ball since.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder then that, when asked what he misses about
Atlanta, McGriff grinned and replied, ``I miss winning all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the guys,'' he added. ``I had good times here. There's
a lot of memories. The World Series. Great years. Great fans.''
</P>
<P>
   So not even another night of devilishly bad Rays baseball could
ruin McGriff's homecoming. McGriff, who will turn 36 on Oct. 31,
was back in the city that spawned some of his fondest memories,
particularly the 1995 World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, unlike three interleague games against Atlanta
last year in Florida, McGriff is far more reminiscent of the power
hitter the Braves acquired in '93, not the 22-homer, supposed
bat-in-decline they sold to Tampa Bay in '97 for a mere $25,000.
They had sent him to his hometown but also to a new team that would
lose 99 games.
</P>
<P>
   Never the most effusive guy, McGriff's bite is once again worse
than his bark. ``I just think Fred McGriff is back to being Fred
McGriff,'' said his manager, Larry Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ McGriff already has 15 homers, four shy of his total last
year, when his 19 homers led the Rays but were McGriff's fewest in
12 full big-league seasons. His 15th homer came Sunday and gives
him 373 for his career, 43rd all-time and one behind Rocky
Colavito. Last season, McGriff didn't hit No. 14 until Aug. 22 and
broke his string of 11 consecutive 20-homer seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ McGriff homered in a club-record four straight games May 4-7,
matching the longest such streak of his career, from 1992 with San
Diego. He homered twice against Kansas City on May 5, the 31st
two-homer game of his career. McGriff became the first player to
hit a ball off the roof of the Batter's Eye restaurant beyond
center field in Tropicana Field; that 451-foot blast was outdone by
his 468-footer off the catwalk in center.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven of McGriff's 15 homers have come on the road, where last
season he hit only five. He's part of the top home-run duo in the
majors with new teammate Jose Canseco, who hit his 22nd on Monday.
One should become the first player to hit 30 homers with four
different teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ McGriff already has 39 runs batted in, after totaling 81 last
season, his fewest since 1987. He has hit safely in 32 of his last
39 games, batting .357 (51 for 143) in that stretch with 12 homers
and 32 RBIs. He's batting .320 overall and is fifth in the AL in
slugging percentage (.637).
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I was human. I wasn't Superman,'' McGriff said.
``This year, I'm fine. I'm getting hits. That's the name of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   To explain McGriff's resurgence, some people point to off-season
weight work or the running program McGriff began in spring training
and still maintains. Others cite the presence of Canseco, batting
in front of McGriff. The Crime Dog thinks that all of them are,
well, barking up the wrong tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same ol' same ol','' McGriff said. ``When you're not hitting,
everybody comes up with reasons. When you're hitting, everything is
fine. It's like if (Greg) Maddux is struggling, people gotta have
reasons.'' As for Canseco: ``Jose hits third. I'm protecting him. I
make sure he gets pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Rothschild agrees that there is a marked difference in
McGriff this season. ``He's back on his legs more. He's getting
more drive,'' the manager said. ``Last year, his legs were sore his
calf, nagging injuries. He couldn't get the strength out of them
like he is now. He's balanced, crouched more, knees bent. Before,
he was upright, stiffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he feels better. I think he came into spring training
and right away did a lot of running and got in shape. Looks like
it's paid off for him.''
</P>
<P>
   And could again during the off-season _ McGriff is in the last
year of his contract. ``All I want to do is go out and play,'' he
said. At his pace, who wouldn't?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
