<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7838 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GOP-HNS &LR;      06-08 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT URGES GOP COLLEAGUES TO COME TOGETHER ON SPENDING BILLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Speaker Dennis Hastert warned his Republican
colleagues Tuesday that the party could lose its majority hold on
Congress in the next election unless they settle differences and
pass major spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary closed-door meeting with his conference, the
Illinois Republican pleaded for the bickering to end between GOP
moderates and conservatives on a wide range of issues from gun
control and campaign finance reform to pet spending projects that
many members are trying to keep away from the budget ax this year.
</P>
<P>
   The internal bickering over matters large and petty, Hastert was
quoted at telling his colleagues, has kept Congress from moving all
but one of the 13 major spending bills that have to be passed by
Oct. 1 to keep the government operating. Failure to move quickly,
Hastert reportedly said, will allow Democrats to label the GOP as
the ``do-nothing'' majority just at the 2000 campaigns are
beginning to gear up this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert later told reporters that his message to the GOP
conference was ``we ... either hang together or hang separately.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker said he was encouraged by the response to his
rallying call. ``I can report that as a conference, we're
together,'' he said. ``We're united. We're standing to balance the
budget. We are a part of fiscal restraint.''
</P>
<P>
   That may have been the case in 1994 when they first took control
of Congress. But Republicans of all political ranks and persuasions
have done as much as Democrats over the past year to pad out
certain spending bills to satisfy their own constituencies. They
have also split their conference apart over a number of issues,
including the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the war, Hastert failed to rally support among
Republicans for a crucial vote last month backing the allied
bombing campaign and stood by as House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, lobbied members on the floor, who had already voted in
favor of it, to change their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Republican members later complained that the two GOP leaders
looked like they were were working against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hastert didn't say so in the meeting this morning, but I think
he's a little disappointed in the way Tom has handled some
things,'' said one Republican member close to both men. ``But the
speaker knows, too, that he's got to step out there and lead before
we'll pick up and follow. And I don't think he's done that
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering a plan aimed at bringing Republicans
together on spending bills, Hastert is trying to rally Republicans
behind a series of modest gun-control measures that the House may
vote on next week. After watching Senate Republicans get criticized
by the public last month for trying to head off a series of
amendments designed to strengthen gun-control laws in the wake of
the Colorado high school tragedy, Hastert said the House leadership
would not make the same mistake again.
</P>
<P>
   But House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, announced Tuesday
that neither Democrats nor Republicans would be allowed to amend
the gun-control measures in House Judiciary Committee hearings
dealing with a juvenile crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement surprised Republicans and Democrats. Committee
Chairman Henry Hyde had scheduled hearings for that purpose, and
committee Democrats called a news conference to denounce Republican
leaders as little more than ``marionettes'' of the National Rifle
Association. The NRA, which opposes the Senate-passed measures
requiring background checks on gun buyers at gun shows and pawn
shops, has been lobbying Republican members hard over the Memorial
Day recess in hopes of derailing the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Armey suggested that members will get a chance to amend the
gun-control measures when they are brought directly to the floor
next week. But he said it is still unclear just how flexible the
rules for considering the legislation will be or what kind of
changes members will be allowed to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Armey said Republicans would make every effort to
honor ``the speaker's commitment'' to have a full debate on
gun-control issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the Republicans want to skip the microscope of the
committee process is because they cannot stand the scrutiny while
they are gutting the Senate-passed gun violence amendments,'' said
Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Hastert, Hyde also favors tougher gun-control
measures. But he worries that the Senate bills may be doomed in the
House, where conservative Republicans and three dozen Democrats
from mostly southern and rural areas are opposed to any any
legislation that might restrict individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want a bill that has a future,'' Hyde said, adding that he
might try to change the Senate measures to be more acceptable to
Republican and Democratic members.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's speech to the Republican conference lasted 15 minutes
by most accounts and centered on the urgency of passing all
spending measures before the start of the new fiscal year on Oct.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a compelling argument that if we want to stay the
majority (party), we've got to act like the governing party,'' said
Rep. Ray LaHood of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Hastert proposed shifting some funding from
defense and other big appropriations measures to help pay for some
educational, health and other programs that have been earmarked for
cuts by Republicans. He also suggested that the government could
sell off part of the broadcast spectrum to raise billions more to
help Congress stay within its self-imposed budget caps next year.
</P>
<P>
   The caps, if honored, would force Congress to slash government
spending from current levels by some $20 billion. But Republicans
and Democrats are having a hard time keeping the caps agreement
that was reached with the White House in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, DeLay told reporters Tuesday that Republicans are
committed to doing their part to stay within budget limits, despite
the calls by many GOP members for more spending on defense and
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay acknowledged, however, that the leadership's problems in
dealing with the budget are far from over. ``It's going to be a
long, hot summer,'' DeLay told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
