<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7839 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LENNYWILKENS-COX     06-08 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LENNYWILKENS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wilkens `wide open' to changes for Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lenny Wilkens has come to the conclusion that the
Hawks must upgrade their talent level, even to the point of
considering a shake-up in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Tanned and upbeat after a short vacation in Seattle, the Hawks
coach touched on the declining play of point guard Mookie Blaylock,
the injuries that disrupted a promising season and his own reaction
to criticism, particularly that dealing with a perceived absence of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Wilkens also expressed unbounded optimism for next
season, ``because we finally have a home (in the new Philips Arena)
and because we have the tools to improve our team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wide open next year. Nobody's guaranteed
anything,'' Wilkens said of the roster, which could have a
significantly new look. The Hawks have four draft picks and can
bring in a veteran under the $4.4 million salary cap exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need good veteran players. We're all on the same page about
that. If you look at the teams that are still playing, you see it's
the veteran players that help you win. We've got young guys, and I
always want to have young guys, but we can't be so young that
everybody's a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of the 32-year-old Blaylock, his starting point
for six years, Wilkens expressed reservations for the first time.
The coach acknowledged the problems presented by a player who
doesn't shoot well (.413 career, .379 this season) but insists on
shooting often and ranked only 20th in assists (5.8 this season).
``That's the area that we have to evaluate very strongly,'' Wilkens
said. ``Whether it's having someone come in who has to play ahead
of him or getting him to the point where he understands he's got to
run the show, find people and think pass first. Not worry about his
scoring. There are enough guys who can score if you just get them
the ball. He should be comfortable enough with his teammates to
understand that.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens is not going to abandon Blaylock, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got off to a slow start _ a lot of guys did _ so he
resorted to the one crutch: `I've got to score some points.' Now,
he's got to run the show, really run the show. If he can do that,
we'll be all right. What's happened is he wants to do it, but when
things go wrong, that (thought) is over.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter who the point guard might be, the Hawks can help him
by adding offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get another guy who can get us points,'' Wilkens
said. ``We can't have Mookie feeling he's the only guy who can
score points.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens said Blaylock felt like he had to score more because of
injuries to Steve Smith, who missed a third of the season with a
sprained knee; LaPhonso Ellis, out the last 60 percent with a torn
stomach muscle, and Alan Henderson, who sat during the playoffs
with a scratched eye that caused double vision. ``I empathize with
him, understanding he knows we need to score,'' Wilkens said.
``But, at the same time, he has to trust the other guys on the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks started out running but evolved into a dull,
half-court team. Wilkens points to the injuries as a culprit but
concedes it's more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best features of my teams in Seattle and Cleveland
is that we passed the ball ahead, and that's how we should play
here. We're yelling, `Push it up. Throw it up.' It's not happening.
Toward the end of the year, Dikembe (Mutombo) started to throw the
ball up the floor. With Mookie, once he started shooting poorly, it
reflected on the rest of his game. He wasn't throwing it up. He
didn't trust guys.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the fans, Wilkens said he can understand their
disappointment and that he shares it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to a lot of people and they seemed to know and
understand. You always hear the ones who are unhappy. But I don't
have a problem with that. I'm unhappy. They can't possibly be as
disappointed as I am. I'm the one in the trenches. I wanted to win
so badly because I thought we were capable. The fans are angry. I'm
angry. But you've got to be realistic, too. Our team wasn't 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries haven't lessened the heat on the coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking heat goes with the territory. I've gotten used to it a
little. The only time it bothers me is when people don't have the
facts. I know what happened. Pete (Babcock, general manager) knows.
Stan (Kasten, club president) knows. The players know. Radio talk
shows know nothing. We all get a little down. We have our moments.
But I'm an optimist. I bounce back. I'm a tough loser. I don't like
to lose, especially when I think we have an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens is not openly emotional, leading some to believe that he
is a man devoid of passion. He disputes that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players know how upset I get,'' he said. ``I get tired of
explaining myself because I don't yell and I don't kick things
around. That doesn't mean anything. Maybe I should cry. That's
popular. But, hey, a lot of coaches won't show all their emotion.
It doesn't mean we don't get upset, we don't want to win. I'll tell
you something: You can't coach this game and not have it working on
you.''
</P>
<P>
   How does that emotion translate to the players who appear
remarkably detached at times?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not entirely true. I think Smitty is always ready, but
what happens is he gets caught up emotionally. That hurts him. Now,
if I see Dikembe standing around and chatting, I'll say something
to him. I told him, `I love my mother, but if she's on the court
trying to stop me, I'm going to run over her.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens laughs. ``But that's where Grant (Long) is great for us.
Grant is tough, hard-nosed. Every time he steps on the floor, he's
trying to get it done. He was terrific. We need another guy who can
come in and push that attitude among his peers. I don't care what
position it is. But we're going to find that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Wilkens says he feels good about next season. For
starters, he noted Henderson and Ellis will probably be fully
healed. ``We're going to get better at point guard, whether it's
A.J. (Anthony Johnson) or somebody to help Mookie. We're going to
get another scorer and an inside guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're going to have a home where we practice, take rehab,
play games, have meetings. Our own place. Don't undersell that.
We'll have a building our guys will be proud of, and that's going
to set a tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
