<HEADER>
A7841 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EQUIFAX-PRESIDENT-COX     06-08 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EQUIFAX-PRESIDENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Powerful partners to guide Equifax
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Equifax, the financial information services company,
will announce today that Lee Kennedy will be its new president and
chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Chapman, 55, who has held the title of CEO and
president since January 1998, succeeded C.B. ``Jack'' Rogers as
chairman at the Atlanta-based company's annual meeting in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it should not fall on deaf ears that as chairman, my
first act was to give up a title within the first month and bring a
partner in to run the day-to-day operations,'' Chapman said.
</P>
<P>
   The two intend to serve as a management team that will allow
Chapman to focus more on strategy and emerging business
opportunities. Kennedy, who has been executive vice president and
group vice president of Equifax Payment Services in St. Petersburg,
Fla., will become a hands-on manager of the company's existing
businesses in North America, Europe and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Equifax also is operating in a more ``complex environment,''
Chapman said. The 100-year-old company had nearly $1.7 billion in
revenue in 1998. It has 13,000 employees, operations in 18
countries and sales in another 32 international markets.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment also suggests a potential succession plan for
the company. Last October, the Equifax directors met at their first
strategic retreat in 99 years to hear from Chapman about succession
options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that if I got hit by a truck or if they canned me,
that Lee was their guy,'' Chapman said. ``I'm not going anywhere,
anytime soon,'' he added quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Does Kennedy have his sights on the top job?
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I haven't thought about it for one second,'' said
Kennedy, 48. ``I'm taking it step by step. I don't know whether I
would want Tom's job in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after joining Equifax in 1990, Chapman said he was
impressed with Kennedy, who was one of the top two executives of
Telecredit, a company Equifax acquired that year.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was running the credit card processing operations for
Telecredit, then considered the ``throw-away'' part of the
acquisition. Chapman, who had been in charge of credit card
processing at First Atlanta in the 1970s, quickly grasped the
potential of the Telecredit acquisition. As soon as he got to know
Kennedy, Chapman recognized that the two had compatible
personalities and business philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee had a toughness to him, and he was customer driven,''
Chapman said. ``When he said he was going to make his numbers, he
made his numbers.'' After being acquired by Equifax, the card
business at Telecredit jumped from $50 million to nearly $500
million.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman and Kennedy also have become comfortable with each other
in hard times. When Equifax's European business sank in December,
Kennedy was one of the few company executives to call Chapman to
see how he was doing and to help provide support.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who will move to Atlanta from Tampa-St. Pete with his
family later this month, said they share business values, but have
different communication styles _ complementing Chapman's ability to
``paint a whole picture.''
</P>
<P>
   In describing the new team, Chapman explains that he will still
stay close to the business operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to go to 50,000 feet.'' Chapman said. But
he also added that ``Lee will do what he wants. I have not been his
daddy up to this point, and I won't be his daddy now.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Saporta writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: msaporta(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
