<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOBBS-CNN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP CNN FIGURE IS QUITTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lou Dobbs, one of the most important executives and
on-camera personalities for Cable News Network, is leaving CNN to
start his own Web site, CNN announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Dobbs, an executive vice president of CNN and
anchor of the financial news show ``Moneyline,'' ends what had
become a somewhat rocky relationship. Staff members at CNN and
CNNfn said that Dobbs had had a number of problems, which one
executive labeled ``creative differences with management,'' and had
clashed recently with Rick Kaplan, the president of CNN, over
pre-emptions of his program for live news coverage and the
allocation of resources.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Dobbs could have serious financial repercussions for CNN.
``Moneyline'' is the most lucrative show on the network in terms of
advertising revenue. It reaches such a concentrated audience of
wealthy investors that it has been able to charge a higher price
for commercials than any other program on CNN, two CNN executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dobbs' influence went beyond ``Moneyline.'' He also was in
charge of all the financial news coverage for the network. He
managed a staff of more than 300 people around the world,
supervised all financial news for CNN's Web site and headed all
financial coverage for CNN's international channels. In addition,
Dobbs was the president of CNN's spinoff cable channel for
financial news, CNNfn.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs is leaving to start a Web site called Space.com, which
will offer news and educational and fictional entertainment content
about space, including science and business content. Dobbs will be
the venture's chairman and have a substantial equity stake, said a
person close to him who spoke on condition of anonymity. The same
person said the venture's primary investor would be Venrock
Associates, the venture capital firm based in New York and
associated with the Rockefeller family.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, CNN's chairman and chief executive, Tom Johnson,
and Dobbs both expressed gratitude and respect for each other. The
parting is effective Friday, and was described in their statement
as ``amicable.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN named two executives to replace Dobbs on an interim basis.
Jeff Gralnick, a longtime news executive at both ABC News and NBC
News who joined CNN in February as the executive producer of CNN
financial news, will continue in that role. David Bohrman, the
executive vice president of CNNfn, will continue to oversee the
cable network. Both will report to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Senior executives at rival financial news programs called the
blow to CNN a serious one, saying that Dobbs had been the main
reason for the loyal following built up by ``Moneyline.''
</P>
<P>
   But his management role has been equally important, several CNN
executives said. He was considered one of the architects of the
overall Internet strategy for CNN's parent company, Time Warner.
The company had put him in charge of all the financial aspects of
the Internet portal it was designing to cover all its financial
news operations, which included not only CNN but also the magazines
Fortune and Money.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problems between Dobbs and the management of CNN go
back several years. In 1997, for example, Dobbs threatened to quit
CNN unless CNNfn was expanded to 18 hours a day from 12. CNN
complied.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, in the most public example of differences, Dobbs
feuded on the air with Kaplan after Kaplan made a decision to
pre-empt a portion of ``Moneyline'' last month for a speech by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came when the president was visiting Littleton,
Colo., after the shootings at Columbine High School. Dobbs made his
displeasure with the decision known when he told viewers that ``CNN
President Rick Kaplan wants us to return to Littleton.''
</P>
<P>
   In subsequent days two memos appeared, the second of which
appeared to be a retraction of the first. The first said that the
CNN management in Atlanta had ``full authority'' to pre-empt
``Moneyline'' for breaking news and that ``violations could result
in demotions or terminations.''
</P>
<P>
   The second memo, three days later, said that Dobbs had the right
to determine when ``Moneyline'' would be interrupted ``whenever
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN staff members said that Dobbs had also protested the
allocation of resources to the news magazine program ``Newsstand,''
which Kaplan created. ``Newsstand'' got off to the rockiest of
possible starts when its first broadcast, about the alleged use of
nerve gas by U.S. forces in Vietnam, was retracted.
</P>
<P>
   But one of Dobbs' associates at CNN said Tuesday that the
conflict with Kaplan was ``a symptom, not the cause, of his
decision to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The real enticement was the potential for an enormous financial
windfall in the Internet business, this associate said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
