<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-2000-2TAKES     06-08 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-2000-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER HOPES CHARACTER ISSUE WILL BUY HIM ATTENTION IN
PRESIDENTIAL BID 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYVILLE, Tenn. _ The last time he ran for president, Lamar
Alexander saw no need to parade before voters his membership in the
elite fellowship of Eagle Scouts. To any son of this modest,
contented hill town, it would have been a vainglorious declaration,
made creaky by the rustle of ancient merit badges.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, the self-effacement is over, jettisoned
with the flannel shirts and statewide hikes. Suddenly, Alexander
has decided he has every reason to inform voters of his Eagle Scout
award, his impeccable family life, his respectable record as a
two-term governor of Tennessee. Convinced by a year of Washington
scandal that his moment has finally arrived, he does so with little
prompting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1974, Ray Blanton beat me by calling me Richard
Nixon's choirboy,'' Alexander said in an interview, referring to
the disgraced former governor of Tennessee. ``But four years later,
after people found out he was selling pardons for cash, they
decided electing a choirboy wouldn't be so bad. And this year,
people are looking for character again. They come up and tell me
they want someone who will restore decency to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal failings of President Bill Clinton have created a
new theme for Alexander's second presidential campaign, which until
recently had threatened to sound very much like his earnest but
lackluster attempt in 1996. His proposals to decentralize education
and lower taxes, impassioned as they sound, have yet to arouse many
voters, and his fund-raising has fallen so far below expectations
that it is threatening the viability of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He has plowed and seeded Iowa and New Hampshire for seven years,
but much of his organizing work has been washed away by the leading
Republican candidate, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has
considerably less governmental experience than Alexander but a much
better-known name and his father's prodigious list of contributors.
Many party leaders on whom Alexander had counted have embraced
Bush, who is attracting so many Republican dollars that Alexander's
campaign has been forced to lay off senior staff members just to
stay alive.
</P>
<P>
   And so Alexander is going beyond most of this year's mainstream
challengers in using the Lewinsky scandal and its moral
repercussions as a broad cudgel to batter the Clinton
administration _ and by extension, Vice President Al Gore _ in
diverse areas like Kosovo and Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, he says, has ``destroyed the nation's confidence in its
government'' and squandered the moral authority he needs to wage
war and heal the wounds of the school shooting. Gore, as the
president's ``head cheerleader,'' is no less guilty because of his
supporting and continued praise for Clinton, Alexander said, adding
a compact aphorism: ``He can't take all the credit for Mr.
Clinton's economy and none of the blame for his misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Alexander's straightbacked persona also presents a
contrast with the dimly lit background of Bush, that won't bother
him a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect all of us in the field will get asked lots of
questions about our background,'' he said, driving a visitor around
the placid neighborhood where he grew up and took piano lessons.
``And I for one intend to answer those questions. I don't expect
I'll have very many to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   He wants desperately to be asked, though, and quickly. As cheery
and confident as Alexander sounds, his campaign is in some danger
of starvation. Though he has stump appeal and one of the best
fund-raisers in the Republican Party, he has not been able to draw
nourishment from the party's donors. The reason might be summed up
in one of the maxims that punctuate his life and fill the
self-deprecating and amusing ``Little Plaid Book'' he published
last year: ``If you want to be noticed, don't ride in a convertible
with Dolly Parton.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it is Bush who fills the role of the alluring
country siren, and it frustrates Alexander to no end that so many
Republicans are betting on a well-known name. He had hoped to raise
about $7 million by now, but was expected to report less than $2.5
million in his second-quarter filing later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, he has been forced to lay off four of his
most senior staff members, including the directors of research,
communications and legal affairs, along with several other workers.
It was a painful admission for a candidate desperate to radiate
confidence and momentum, particularly when he was still trying to
convince his supporters that his single-digit poll ratings meant
nothing at this early stage. Now, he must bet his entire treasury
on the two states with the first voices of 2000, Iowa and New
Hampshire, all the while praying for Bush to bungle his lead.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy remains plausible, however, particularly given
Bush's reticence so far to outline his positions, and in the
absence of any other nationally known, tested Republican in the
race. By most reckonings, the Alexander campaign is the best
organized in Iowa, with most of the county leaders as well as the
popular former governor, Terry Branstad, supporting him. He
announced on Tuesday that he has volunteer organizations set up in
each of the state's 99 counties, more than any of the other
contenders. That actually counts for something in Iowa, where
voters have to be persuaded to come out on a frozen winter night,
but it is hardly a guarantee of eventual success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been visiting here regularly for the last seven years,
and historically that has made a difference for some candidates who
are not that well known,'' said Hugh Winebrenner, a professor of
public administration at Drake University in Des Moines and author
of a book on the Iowa caucuses. ``The flip side is that he's got to
have some good news at some point, because in the end it's
enthusiasm that puts you over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander prefers, of course, to take the long view, and
counsels skeptics to ``remember the fable of the tortoise and the
hare.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
