<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7854 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALEXANDER-2000-2NDTAK     06-08 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALEXANDER-2000-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MARYVILLE, Tenn.: the hare.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alexander's third-place showing in Iowa in 1996 brought him
considerable money and attention, at least until he was shot down
in the New Hampshire primary by Bob Dole, and Alexander dropped out
a few weeks later. Now, he is staking seven years of work on the
hope that something like his third-place showing will happen again,
that his unassuming personality will play well in Iowa and attract
a quick pivot of the national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who grew up in Maryville, plays the piano, was an
Eagle Scout and goes to church, is going to do well in Iowa, and
not badly in New Hampshire,'' Alexander said. ``Iowa and New
Hampshire suit me fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The real question, of course, is how he will fare in those parts
of the nation that do not share the open countryside, the
comfortable porch swings, the uncynical outlook of his hometown or
the rural precincts of Iowa. Though he is not as conservative as
Ronald Reagan, he frequently invokes Reagan's optimism and thematic
use of the presidency as his models, soothing his listeners with
slightly dreamy descriptions of how the country could return to
small-town values. But without Reagan's magnetism, his words may
play differently in large cities and their suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, parents and teachers were deeply
involved in the lives of children,'' Alexander said in a speech a
few weeks ago at an outdoor festival in Elizabethton, Tenn.,
population 13,289, explaining why so many of today's children seem
to be lost. ``There were nosy neighbors who watched us as we went
to school, teachers who knew they had authority from the community
to teach us right from wrong as well as math and English. There
were choirmasters and scoutmasters and churches open so many days a
week that it seemed like Sunday came every other day. That is not
nostalgia, it is a tried and true recipe for helping our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not a wooden speaker; his delivery is crisp and effective,
particularly with like-minded crowds, but he rarely sets his
listeners vibrating with an emotional connection. As frustrated as
he is with Bush's outsized silhouette, the worst thing he can say
about him is that the Texas governor is untested.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican Party official who has worked with Alexander said
he could probably outspeak Gore or Bill Bradley, the former New
Jersey senator who is challenging the vice president for the
Democratic nomination, but would have trouble against a more
charismatic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a dear and wonderful man, but he can be in a room two
hours before you know he's there,'' the official said. ``It's hard
to define, but he needs more of that star quality people have come
to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who is 58, seems aware that he is no firebrand, but
he argues that people have grown weary of charisma. This is not an
unfamiliar argument; it has been made many times over the years by
similar candidates, and is also being used this year by the Gore
and Bradley campaigns. But it is central to Alexander's conception
of himself, and this year he has decided to forgo the gimmickry of
the plaid shirts, which were originally designed to help him stand
out, and concentrate on the things he does well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't intend to try to manufacture an issue just to capture
the headlines,'' he said, referring to the recent publicity
surrounding Elizabeth Dole's embrace of gun control. ``That
wouldn't work; people would see through it. The best course for me
is to remember the fable of the tortoise and the hare, and organize
the counties and raise enough money, and practice my speeches and
have a good time. And hopefully the day after the Iowa caucuses,
everyone in the country will know who I am. So I'm going to have to
be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who listen will hear a firmly etched manifesto of moderate
grass-roots conservatism, presented in an easygoing Presbyterian
style, all common sense and good will. He is convinced that with
less interference from Washington, the parents, school boards and
local elected officials around the country can find their own
solutions to educational problems.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer advocates the dismantling of the Department of
Education, aware that such a proposal sounds a bit strange coming
from a man who was President George Bush's education secretary. But
he still wants to help families by giving children $1,500
scholarships and letting them choose their own school, public,
private or charter. He favors breaking the power of teachers'
unions and federal bureaucrats, believing that schools can in
essence fix themselves if parents and principals are given more
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore thinks he knows what's best for this country,''
Alexander says in every stump speech. ``What I want to do is bring
out the best in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes him about 20 seconds to go from denouncing the
Littleton shootings to demanding an end to the marriage tax and a
tripling of the child deductions, certain that a restructuring of
federal tax policy will strengthen families as much as the economy.
He does not favor an amendment outlawing abortion and says he could
support some federal gun-control legislation, but also supports a
missile defense system and wants no limits on campaign fund-raising
from individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a clerk for the late Federal Judge John Minor
Wisdom, one of the authors of modern affirmative action, he opposes
any form of racial preferences and says the Clinton administration
has talked too much about race and too little about unity.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander is annoyed by the suggestion that he is unusually
persevering, suspecting the implication is that his cause is
hopeless, and he correctly points out that Reagan and many other
politicians tried more than once for the presidency. He is clearly
propelled by a sense that he has trained for the presidency, and
seems mystified that the country might not want to make use of the
skills he developed in the Tennessee state house, at the helm of
the University of Tennessee, and in the leadership of a successful
day- care business that made him a wealthy man after drawing on his
contacts as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By this age, I pretty much know what my skills are, and I felt
like when I was governor, I was really at the peak of my
performance in making the most contributions I could make,'' he
said. ``I just feel that this is what I should be doing. My
character and demeanor, which wouldn't be suited to every set of
times, might be, as it turns out, very well-suited to these
times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
