<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-08 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES, RUSSIA AGREE ON KOSOVO PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ NATO and Yugoslav Army generals Tuesday night resumed
their discussions to organize the withdrawal of Serb forces from
Kosovo, after the world's seven industrialized nations and Russia
agreed on the wording of a United Nations resolution that calls for
an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   The UN Security Council could vote on the resolution Wednesday,
but in a concession to the Serb side NATO will suspend its air
strikes before that vote is taken. Once NATO verifies that Serb
forces are withdrawing from Kosovo, the air campaign will be
formally called off.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, NATO had said the Serbs would have seven days to
leave Kosovo, but US Defense Secretary William S. Cohen has said
that could be extended a few days if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events was crucial to winning agreement between
the Western allies, who are NATO members, and Russia, which is an
ally of Yugoslavia and has been trying to broker a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO officials got a key point they wanted. The resolution
calls on parties to the agreement to cooperate with the war crimes
tribunal at The Hague, which indicted Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and four other top Serb officials two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Air-raid sirens sounded Tuesday night in Belgrade, but there
were no explosions.
</P>
<P>
   However, NATO sources said a B-52 bomber caught two Yugoslav
army battalions of possibly more than 1,000 men in the open Tuesday
near the Kosovo-Albania border after Serbia stalled on withdrawals,
and that many hundreds of troops might have been killed. Serb
sources denied that major casualties resulted.
</P>
<P>
   US intelligence has detected signs that Serb forces are making
preparations to withdraw from Kosovo, although no troops are moving
or assembling for a pullout, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters at the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon
said the signs include the mobilization of Serb transport vehicles
in Kosovo that would be used to move soldiers out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just beginning to see signs of preparations for
withdrawal. We have not yet seen any withdrawal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the Western allies, meanwhile, the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army said it would not attack withdrawing Serb
forces. Yugoslav generals had expressed concerns about leaving
their troops open to ambush by rebel forces as they left Kosovo.
The American government, in particular, has been pressuring Kosovo
Liberation Army leader Hashim Thaci not to exploit the pullout for
tactical gain.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic efforts to end the war got back on track Tuesday
after several days of delay, which had more to do with domestic
Serbian politics than anything else. Milosevic is trying to
convince the public here that by holding out for more than 70 days
of NATO bombing, he has forced NATO to relinquish to the UN the
responsibility of administering postwar Kosovo, safeguarding
Yugoslav sovereignty over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Yugoslav generals balked at signing the
agreement that stipulates the routes and timetables of their
pullout. Serb officials delayed its initiation so they could
characterize it as the UN assuming control rather than NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who helped persuade
Milosevic to accept the Group of Eight withdrawal principles last
week, flew to Beijing to ask the Chinese government not to use its
veto on the Security Council to block the resolution. The Chinese
are still angry over the bombing of its Embassy here last month,
which NATO says was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   China, which did not help draft the resolution with foreign
ministers from the Group of Eight countries, took issue with two
points in the text that will create the peace force.
</P>
<P>
   China's deputy permanent UN representative, Shen Guofang, said
Beijing objected to a passage that will allow the peacekeepers to
use force. Beijing was also upset by mention of the war crimes
tribunal in the Hague, which has indicted Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. Sheng said the indictment was ``politically
motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   But the main sticking point to adoption remains Beijing's and
Moscow's insistence that NATO stop bombing. Both Russia and China
hold veto power on the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``By adopting the resolution we cannot give justification to
NATO for the further bombing of Yugoslavia,'' Sheng said. ``Only
after the Security Council receives confirmation that NATO stops
bombing can we take action. The Security Council is not a rubber
stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Western allies and Russia were able to bridge their
differences, mainly by moving any reference to NATO to the
resolution's annex, there was still a divide over who would control
the estimated 50,000 troops that will form the international
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, where the Group of Eight representatives drafted the
UN resolution, US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Russian
foreign minister Igor Ivanov contradicted each other as they
discussed what they had signed. She said the resolution stipulates
that ``NATO will be the military leader'' of the peacekeeping
force. But Ivanov said Russian troops, which may make up 10,000 of
the force, would not be under NATO command, and insisted all
matters for the peacekeeping force are ``a subject of
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer tried to smooth over the
differences, saying, ``precise details of the peacekeeping group
need to be worked out. This will certainly have a NATO element to
it, but all these questions have to be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Russians said they had prevailed in getting the West
to make concessions, British Foreign Minister Robin Cook insisted
that the agreement that Milosevic had accepted last week had not
been renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Yugoslav capital, deputy Foreign Minister Nebojsa
Vujovic said his government would adhere to the resolution, but he
insisted that the agreement that calls for a withdrawal of Serb
soldiers and police in Kosovo does not cover customs officials. He
said the Yugoslav government wants to leave those customs officials
at border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should see who is crossing the border,'' said Vujovic. He
said only refugees who left Kosovo would be allowed back in, and
that Yugoslav officials were needed to deter Albanian citizens or
``terrorists who will start chasing Serbs'' from entering the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But speaking in Germany, where the Group of Eight foreign
ministers gathered to hash out the UN resolution, Albright
dismissed that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a few (Serb officials) at the border, but as
observers,'' she said. ``They will not be able to control access to
or from Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo said that Serb officials took
their identification papers as they left, saying they would never
come back. But Albright said the UN High Commissioner for Refugees
has provided refugees with new identification papers.
</P>
<P>
   Vujovic, who returned to Macedonia to attend the discussions
with NATO officials, would not even refer to NATO by its name. He
called it ``the delegation under UN auspices.''
</P>
<P>
   Such semantics explain the sensitivities and much of the
stalling by Yugoslav officials since they began discussions with
Lieutenant General Mike Jackson, the commander of 16,000 NATO
forces in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea welcomed the agreement
reached in Germany, saying, ``We now have a clear road map to bring
this conflict to an end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
