u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-DRUG-600&AMP;ADD     06-08 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUG-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG MAKERS SKEPTICAL OVER DRUG PLAN FOR ELDERLY
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Wash., Ore., N.Y., Calif., Texas, Fla.)  (jw) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drug industry and insurance executives reacted with skepticism
on Tuesday to reports that the White House was planning a new
prescription-drug benefit for all elderly Americans. Under the
proposal, Medicare recipients would pay $10 to $25 a month in
addition to the current Medicare premium of $45.50, which does not
cover drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Drug manufacturers said they did not believe administration
officials' assurances that the proposal would not lead to price
controls on drugs. Alan Holmer, president of Pharma, a trade
association, said the manufacturers favored government support for
drugs for the elderly but opposed a program that would be run by
Medicare officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we don't need is more restrictions, more bureaucracy and
government red tape, which we believe would inevitably flow from a
giant new program run by HCFA,'' he said, referring to the Federal
Health Care Financing Administration, which administers Medicare.
``In our view the proposals will inevitably lead to price
controls,'' Holmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lamberton, a drug industry analyst at HSBC Securities, said
the Clinton administration was likely to demand price rebates from
the drug companies, like those already in force for state Medicaid
for low-income people. Controls or rebates could reduce profits.
</P>
<P>
   Managed-care executives said government spending curbs were
threatening existing drug coverage under Medicare managed-care
plans. ``You cannot give with one hand and take away with other,''
said Phil Nudelman, chairman of Kaiser Group Health, which provides
Medicare managed-care coverage for 100,000 people in Washington and
Oregon. Kaiser Group Health is a joint venture of the Kaiser
Permanente unit in the Northwest and the Group Health Cooperative
of Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, a managed care trade group, said Medicare health plans in
many big cities _ including New York, Los Angeles, Houston, Dallas
and Miami _ were considering cuts in drug benefits because of the
cost squeeze in the 1997 Balanced Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers outside the government said it would be difficult
for a drug benefit to generate overall savings. ``Drugs save money
in treatment for certain conditions,'' said Michael Gluck, director
of health policy studies at the National Academy of Social
Insurance. But he expressed ``healthy skepticism'' about ``systemic
savings.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy, a nonpartisan research center supported by
foundations, has predicted that adding a general drug benefit will
increase Medicare costs by 7 percent to 13 percent over the next
decade, or $17.5 billion to $24 billion the first year. The higher
cost would come if the government picked up 100 percent of the
costs, above a certain threshold, for expensive illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always concerned about who is going to pay for this in
the budget, whether the savings that the administration projects
are indeed achievable,'' said Joyce Oberdorf, a spokeswoman for
Aetna Inc., the big health insurer.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Kalen, executive director of the Managed Health Care
Association, an employers group, said her members would welcome a
pharmacy benefit that would help retirees and save money for the
companies. But she added that savings from covering drugs had yet
to be proven. ``We are seeing health premiums generally rising and
seeing drug costs rising'' even faster, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of the president's proposal, which he mentioned in
the State of the Union message last winter, were reported Tuesday,
but industry spokesmen cautioned that they had not yet seen a
detailed version.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the 39 million Americans eligible for Medicare
already have drug benefits, but the coverage is often incomplete.
Most are covered by former employers, but many companies are
cutting back as prescription drug costs rise.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 5 million have drug plans in Medicare health maintenance
organizations, which vary widely across the country. Drug coverage
is low in the Northwest, for example, because Medicare payments are
lower than in other regions, Nudelman of Kaiser Group Health said.
</P>
<P>
   John Rother, policy director of the American Association of
Retired Persons, said the proposals under discussion in the
administration would probably be ``much more expensive'' than
Medicare HMO coverage in many cities. To keep down overall costs in
the federal budget, the elderly would have to pay a stiff share of
the cost of a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the proposals would not make much difference to
the standard supplementary policies offered through AARP and by a
number of commercial insurance companies. Only three of the 10
types of supplementary policies cover drugs, and only 10 percent to
15 percent of the customers buy this expensive coverage, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
