<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON WARNS OF PERILS IN KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID BEARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Instrumental in a prisoner release in Yugoslavia and
trying for another, the Rev. Jesse Jackson predicted Tuesday that a
US-led peacekeeping mission in Kosovo may last for decades and
culminate in US soldiers battling ethnic Albanian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic agrees ... to pull out, and we move in ground
troops, there is no cause for celebration,'' Jackson told reporters
and editors at the Globe. ``It is premature.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, in town for commencement exercises at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government, characterized
the NATO-led air campaign on Yugoslavia as well-intentioned but
riven with unintended consequences: ecological damage, stirrings
with Russia, costly dustups with China, and commitments to spend
billions of dollars that could have improved education and job
opportunities at home or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Russia saw us as the big superpower'' before Kosovo,
Jackson said, ``11 weeks later, they have to be a little less
afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   China, too, could exact a high price from the United States for
its cooperation with a United Nations resolution that could halt
hostilities, he said. Jackson ticked off a checklist of potential
US paybacks to Beijing, such as less pressure by Washington on
issues including human rights violations, repression in Tibet,
creeping hegemony over Taiwan, espionage disclosures, and US
campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the interview, Jackson referred to his triumph
working with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to free three US
servicemen on May 2. He said he had spoken three times with
Yugoslavia's foreign minister and hopes to return to Belgrade soon
to arrange the release of three workers for the humanitarian group
CARE who were convicted of spying and sentenced to prison on May
29.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson dismissed any suggestion that the CARE workers, two
Australians and a Yugoslav, were spies. ``To arrest them,'' he
said, ``is to chill the work of humanitarian aid agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a multibillion-dollar flow of aid to the Balkans,
Jackson envisoned an effort without end. ``We will be in Bosnia and
Kosovo as long as we are in Korea,'' said Jackson, reflecting on
nearly a half-century of US involvement on the Asian peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paradox,'' he said, ``is that we'll end up fighting the
(Kosovo Liberation Army) to protect the Serbs.'' Jackson
characterized the ethnic Albanian guerrilla force as funded by drug
money.
</P>
<P>
   This US time and attention, he said, comes at the expense of
Africa, with 800 million potential consumers and a rising source of
US oil imports. Jackson said US media outlets and Washington, which
closely tracked his prisoner release in Belgrade, generally ignored
his trip a week later when he helped negotiate an end to a far
bloodier conflict in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said 10,000 people died in January alone in Sierra
Leone's civil war, more casualties than throughout the Kosovo
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The US civil rights leader said he has not wearied of striving
for change. He reflected on the cascade of opportunities that have
revolutionized American race relations in the past four decades as
well as the job to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later at the Kennedy School, he was pushing again,
combining commencement comments on Yugoslavia with a challenge to
the roughly 500 graduates and family to change the school itself.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 106 professors at the Kennedy School, only six are black,
Jackson said, citing figures that a school spokesman confirmed. Of
those, only one is tenured and two are on tenure tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions like the Kennedy School of Government have the
ability to move with alacrity if they so desire,'' he said. ``I
challenge the administration of the school to double the number of
tenure-track minority faculty members in a year, two years if
absolutely necessary. ... If this institution desires to instill in
its students the ability to make just choices, let it lead by
example.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
