<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM REPORTS PROGRESS ON LUXURY-SEAT SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New England Patriots have sold 43 of the 80 luxury suites in
a proposed stadium in Foxborough, with about $80 million already
committed to the premium seats over the first decade the facility
is open.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than half of the seats are already sold, and that's the
fastest, that we are aware of, for any new stadium,'' said Paul
Tagliabue, commissioner of the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue and local business officials leading the push to help
the Patriots sell the luxury suites announced the status of the
sales Tuesday, after unveiling a preliminary artist's sketch of the
proposed 68,000-seat stadium.
</P>
<P>
   While the rendering revealed little about the construction
plans, the brick-and-steel design appears to have a retro flavor.
The architect, HOK Sport in Kansas City, Mo., is in the early
stages of the design.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the stadium would be built to optimize prime
</P>
<P>
   views, with a comparatively high proportion of seats, about 80
percent, along the sidelines, as opposed to the end zones.
</P>
<P>
   The 80 luxury suites would seat about 2,000 people and provide
amenities like bars, restrooms, private food services, and
televisions. All of the suites would be larger than the 42 suites
at Foxboro Stadium, and the eight largest, at about 1,800 square
feet, would be among the most spacious in the NFL. Suite owners,
who will pay $85,000 to $325,000 per season, would have designated
parking with entrances and exits designed to substantially shorten
the ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots games would be the only admissions included in the
luxury suite deals. Owners would have to pay for admission to New
England Revolution games, concerts, and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury suite owners are required to buy the suites for 10 years,
and are being asked to pay deposits as high as $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The new stadium also would have 6,000 club seats. The current
Foxboro Stadium has none. Officials said those customers would be
served by a lounge running the length of the stadium, with
televisions and large windows facing the field to allow fans to
watch the game when they leave their seats.
</P>
<P>
   No prices for the club seats or the 60,000 regular admission
seats have been determined, Patriots and NFL officials said. ``The
Patriots tickets have always been in about the middle of the ticket
prices around the NFL, and we expect that will continue,'' said
Patriots spokesman Stacey James.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Robert Kraft, vice president Jonathan Kraft,
quarterback Drew Bledsoe, commissioner Tagliabue, BankBoston CEO
Charles ``Chad'' Gifford, and John J. Connors, chairman of Hill
Holliday Connors Cosmopulos, all spoke to representatives of 50
businesses at a breakfast meeting at BankBoston headquarters
Tuesday, hoping to spur suite sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who reportedly will earn $7 million next season and $8
million in 2000, later vowed to buy a luxury suite, joking that he
had a compelling, personal reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife won't have to listen to the comments when I throw an
interception,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The early luxury suite sales will provide a key source of
revenue for Kraft, who walked away from a deal to publicly finance
a stadium in Hartford earlier this year. Kraft is paying the $285
million construction cost, while the state pays for $70 million in
infrastructure improvements around the stadium. The NFL will loan
him $141 million for the construction, and allow him to repay that
amount from the share of the club seats that is normally given to
the visiting teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly looks like businesses are stepping up to the
plate, and we hope more businesses will buy into the luxury
seats,'' said Governor Paul Cellucci, who attended the meeting. The
level of business support, along with approval from municipal
officials in Foxborough, are the only remaining issues, Cellucci
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
