</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET'S LENDING TO THE POOR, MINORITIES LAGS AFTER MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp. have trumpeted
their planned $16 billion merger as one in which the combined
company will do more than each institution alone to provide housing
loans to the poor and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``One plus one is greater than two,'' the banks' chief
executives have intoned, trying to assuage fears among community
groups that the new firm could slash lending and impoverish
recovering neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But a study released Tuesday on post-merger lending practices
suggests while BankBoston historically has adhered to that
arithmetic, Fleet has fallen strikingly short.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by University of Massachusetts at Boston economics
professor James Campen, suggests black, Latino, and low- to
middle-income borrowers are less likely to receive mortgage loans
from Fleet after it makes acquisitions. Fleet is buying its rival.
</P>
<P>
   The study is likely to serve as a rallying point for activists
who hope to force the banks to make commitments to poorer borrowers
before they merge later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is viewed as more hard-nosed in its practices, while its
rival is seen as having a strong community image. Because the two
firms, to become the nation's eighth-largest bank, will have such a
big share of the New England market, the area is open to a net loss
in lower-income housing loans, Campen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are excellent reasons for communities to insist and
regulators to require that the new institution be committed to
achieving its stated standard of `one plus one is greater than two'
for mortgage lending to traditionally underserved borrowers,''
Campen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Campen, a specialist on the Community Reinvestment Act, the 1997
federal law that requires banks to lend to poorer areas, examined
data for Fleet after it acquired Shawmut National Bank in 1995 and
NatWest Bank NA a year later.
</P>
<P>
   He found that in 1998, Fleet made 334 mortgage loans to black
borrowers in Massachusetts _ 52.4 percent fewer than Fleet and
Shawmut made separately in 1995. Fleet made 335 mortgage loans to
lower-income borrowers in Boston last year _ 50.3 percent fewer
than Fleet and Shawmut made in 1995. Overall, Fleet's mortgage
lending to black, Latino, and lower-income borrowers in Boston
dropped by 40 percent from 1995 to 1998, Campen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The decline was accompanied by a comparable fall in Fleet
mortgage loans to all borrowers, including affluent ones.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, by contrast, continued to lend to poor and minority
borrowers at a strong rate after it acquired BayBanks Inc. in 1996.
The bank made as many loans to disadvantaged borrowers as the two
banks made before they merged _ even though BankBoston's lending to
affluent borrowers also declined.
</P>
<P>
   Campen said black borrowers in Boston received 143 home loans
from BankBoston in 1998 _ 16.3 percent more than in 1995 from
BankBoston and BayBanks. Boston Latinos took as many home loans
from BankBoston in 1998 as they did in 1995 from both banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-SPYING-HNS &LR;      06-08 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-SPYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AIDE SAYS INTERNATIONAL TEAMWORK MUST CONTINUE DESPITE
SPYING SCANDAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal lawmakers must resist the temptation to
restrict visits by foreign scientists to the United States
following alleged Chinese spying at a U.S. laboratory, because such
a halt would harm national security, President Clinton's chief
science adviser said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Lane, assailing congressional efforts to limit the visits
as ``xenophobic (and) misguided,'' called global scientific
cooperation important in preserving peace and essential in
combatting natural and man-made threats. International teamwork has
improved global understanding of climate change and other worldwide
environmental concerns, said Lane, assistant to the president for
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science must be a global undertaking,'' he said. ``We simply
cannot afford to isolate our national laboratories.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane, a former Rice University provost and physics professor in
Houston, cited as instrumental in the drive for peace the efforts
of U.S. scientists to give weapons specialists in the former Soviet
Union humanitarian outlets for their expertise. For example,
nuclear-arms experts have turned their attention to disposing of
weapons-grade plutonium, and scientists who had mixed biological
weapons have begun working on vaccines and cures for infectious
diseases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lane's comments at an international science symposium followed
the introduction of legislation by Rep. Todd Tiahrt, R-Kan., that
would eliminate the Energy Department and transfer control of the
agency's national laboratories to Defense Department control.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., and Rep. Jim Ryun, R-Kan., have
introduced measures to prohibit scientists from countries that pose
a danger to the United States from visiting U.S. national
laboratories without special federal approval.
</P>
<P>
   The measures, which have yet to be considered by the full Senate
and House, were introduced after Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwanese-born
scientist, was fired in March from Los Alamos, N.M., National
Laboratory amid suspicion he was spying for China.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ryun, in defense of his proposal: ``Legislation is needed
to close the pipeline of vital national security secrets to China,
Iraq and other rogue nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Without specifically mentioning the congressional measures or
lawmakers, Lane assailed ``some of the things that are being said
that I don't think are careful and constructive.'' He noted that
Lee, who has not been arrested, was an employee of the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no allegations that any foreign visitor has
been engaged in espionage,'' Lane said at the symposium on
scientific cooperation between the United States and the former
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lane conceded that U.S. enemies interested in American
technology might attempt to infiltrate the laboratories. Lane,
echoing comments from Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, said the
United States will increase efforts to bar foreign access to
sensitive and classified material at the laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we know where our visitors come from and
what they intend to do here,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2035EDT &QL; 
