<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMAZONCOM-DISTRIBUTIO     06-08 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZONCOM-DISTRIBUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Amazon.com hiring for Georgia facility
 &HT;    By Anne Cowles
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amazon.com Inc., the country's largest Web-based
bookseller, isn't wasting any time finding about 1,000 employees
for a new $51 million, 800,000-square-foot regional distribution
center in Henry County.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after it was announced Tuesday that Amazon.com selected
a site at Greenwood Industrial Park in McDonough, Ga., the online
retailer scheduled a three-day open house beginning Friday at the
city's Windy Hill Recreation Center for prospective employees.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com will open the facility later this summer and hire 500
employees by the end of the year. It plans to have a work force of
about 1,000 by the end of March 2000. It could become the largest
industrial employer in Henry County. Home-grown Snapper Power
Equipment in McDonough currently is the largest business, with
close to 900 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This facility will be the largest Amazon.com center to date in
the United States,'' said Jim Wright, the company's chief logistics
officer. ``It will be a highly mechanized facility ... within
excess of 12 miles of conveyor system.''
</P>
<P>
   The distribution center will serve the southeastern United
States, as well as South America and Mexico. The full line of
Amazon.com merchandise, including books, CDs and DVDs, will be
housed at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Henry County Commission Chairman Jim Joyner said his county is
now firmly planted as a player in technology business. ``Amazon.com
just adds to the fact that Henry County is moving into the era of
technology business,'' Joyner said. ``And now I believe we can be
known in the business world as Henry County.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, first in a long line of speakers at Tuesday's
announcement, said Amazon.com's selection of McDonough confirms
metro Atlanta's position as a center of e-commerce. ``The point is
this: Whatever you can find on the Internet, you can find in
Georgia,'' Barnes said. ``Whatever you can find in Silicon Valley,
in the Research Triangle, on Boston's Route 128, you can
increasingly find here in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com founder Jeff Bezos opened the Seattle-based company
in 1995 when he began shipping books out of his garage. Today the
company has six distribution centers around the country, including
McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   Initial site analysis indicated that north metro Atlanta would
be a prime spot for the distribution center. But traffic congestion
led Amazon.com to look south of I-20.
</P>
<P>
   Henry County had a 400,000-square-foot speculative industrial
building that could easily be expanded to fit Amazon.com's needs.
``Without a speculative building they would not have been looking
down here,'' said Jeff Lucas, economic development specialist for
the Henry County Development Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, which gives stock options to all employees, needs
workers skilled in distribution center work, including unloading
trucks, picking orders and driving forklifts. Between 40 and 60
management positions are available, with two-thirds likely to be
filled locally.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com has set up a toll-free job line at 877-975-4273. The
company is accepting applications by e-mail at gajobs(AT)amazon.com
and will answer questions by e-mail at gaquestions(AT)amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Cowles writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0336 </DOCNO>
