<HEADLINE>
SECOND N.Y. OFFICER FOUND GUILTY IN LOUIMA CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A second police officer was put behind bars Tuesday
for the torture and sodomy of Haitian immigrant Abner Louima, while
three others who had been accused of involvement in the crime were
set free.
</P>
<P>
   However, the case that shocked the nation and threw the city
into its worst fit of racial tensions in over a decade was far from
closed.
</P>
<P>
   A Brooklyn jury Tuesday found Officer Charles Schwarz guilty of
holding down Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn stationhouse
while his fellow officer, Justin Volpe, sodomized Louima with a
stick.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe pleaded guilty to the crime two weeks ago, after four
other officers testified that he had told them what he did. Volpe
and Schwarz are in federal custody and could receive life
sentences. Schwarz's lawyer said he would appeal the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   However, shortly after Tuesday's verdict, Marvyn Kornberg,
Volpe's lawyer, said that the jury convicted the wrong man _ that
Schwarz was not in the bathroom at the time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   And in another development, US Attorney Zachary Carter said a
second criminal trial will soon take place, charging three
officers, Schwarz and two of the officers acquitted Tuesday, with
conspiring to cover up the assault.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict came after a six-week trial that recalled the events
of Aug. 9, 1997, when Volpe arrested Louima, a Haitian immigrant,
outside a Brooklyn nightclub, then took him to the bathroom of the
70th precinct stationhouse, assaulted him with the stick, smashed
it against his teeth, and threatened to kill him if he ever told
anybody what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Two other officers _ Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder _ were found
not guilty of charges that they beat Louima in a patrol car.
Sergeant Michael Bellomo was acquitted of making false statements
about Volpe's assault.
</P>
<P>
   When Volpe pleaded guilty three weeks into the trial, he
confessed to committing the crime ``in the presence of another
police officer,'' but did not name the officer. The jurors were not
in the courtroom during the plea.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg said in a phone interview Tuesday that before Volpe
took the plea, he privately told the prosecutors and Schwarz's
lawyer who the other police officer was _ and said he would repeat
the name if called to testify in court.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg would not say, in the interview, whom Volpe had named,
but he did say, ``It was not Officer Schwarz.'' Asked if this meant
the jury convicted the wrong man Tuesday, Kornberg replied,
``That's absolutely right.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters outside the courthouse if it was true that
Volpe named an officer other than Schwarz, Carter replied, ``As a
participant in the bathroom assault, no.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Volpe had said another officer saw what he was
doing and did nothing to stop him, even if he did not participate
directly, Carter replied, ``I'm not going to respond to that
because that's going to be the subject matter of the next trial.''
</P>
<P>
   One criminal charge was set aside during the trial that ended
Tuesday _ accusing Schwarz, Wiese and Bruder of conspiring to make
false statements about what happened to Louima in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said this charge will be refiled in a second criminal
trial, to take place in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie Cochran, the lawyer who is representing Louima in a
civil lawsuit against the city, said of Tuesday's verdict, ``We
think some measure of justice was obtained,'' and added that he
hoped other officers would be convicted in the trial to come.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese and Bruder were acquitted Tuesday of charges that they
beat Louima in a patrol car. Carter said it is very difficult to
make such charges stick when the only witness is the victim.
Cochran agreed, and praised the prosecutors' performance, calling
Volpe's guilty plea and Schwarz's conviction ``clearly a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has often appeared at Louima's side,
did so again Tuesday, telling a crowd at his Harlem headquarters,
``We're going to fight for you until all the guilty see justice.''
Louima's cousin, Sam Nicolas, told the gathering, ``We want to act
for peace, for calm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
