<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSRUS-FORMAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toys `R' Us unveils redesign with test store
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toys ``R'' Us isn't playing games with its new store
format.
</P>
<P>
   As other retailers introduce online toy stores to battle Toys
``R'' Us in cyberspace, the Paramus, N.J., chain has been busy
polishing its bricks and mortar. In a massive remodeling project
that began in October, Toys ``R'' Us is taking down the towering
racks and replacing the familiar warehouse look with a softer
discount department store feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old stores are claustrophobic,'' said Chief Executive
Robert Nakasone on a tour Wednesday at a Toys ``R'' Us near North
Point Mall in Alpharetta, Ga. ``Now we've got a layout that's much
easier to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta store is one of nine in the Southeast with the
new look. Toys ``R'' Us chose the Southeast as a test market
because of its major distribution center in McDonough, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta tour, which was followed by a meeting with 300
vendors, marked one of Nakasone's first public statements since he
became CEO last year. The tour coincides with the company's annual
shareholder meeting today at the Westin Atlanta North near
Perimeter Mall. The company held its annual meeting here to
showcase the Alpharetta store.
</P>
<P>
   The new store format features fewer toys but a better
presentation, Nakasone said. The retailer cut back-room space by a
third to make room for wider aisles and new departments. Each
department targets a different age group. For example, ``juvenile
world'' aims to lure mothers and babies with its pastel green
colors and new line of toddler clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research shows that apparel drives 30 percent of a
mother's shopping trips, so we're trying to capitalize on that,''
Nakasone said. It's also a way to generate more year-round sales
for a retailer that depends on seasonal traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude switches in the sports department, where Toys ``R''
Us is trying to grab the attention of teenagers with wild graphics
and lots of skateboards.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges of a more cheeky generation is evident in the
department that targets girls. Barbie, it seems, has given up shelf
space to more mature fancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole toy industry is facing the fact that kids are
growing up faster than they used to,'' Nakasone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to be able to give a Barbie to a girl anywhere from
age 2 to 10. Now they're outgrowing Barbie at 5 or 6 years old, and
that's compressing our business,'' Nakasone said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other retailers, Toys ``R'' Us is pushing Barbie fashion
instead. Cosmetics, jewelry and miniskirt outfits for girls who
want to look like Barbie make up the bulk of the department.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us is combining the new prototypes with a big push on
the Internet as it faces increasing competition. Amazon.com is
introducing an online toy store this month. EToys, based in Santa
Monica, Calif., is off to a heady stock market start after going
public last month.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is crucial for both the Internet and store
initiatives. Toys ``R'' Us, which had flat sales of $11.2 billion
in 1998, lost sales to Wal-Mart and other discounters that sell
toys at bargain prices. Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer,
surpassed Toys ``R'' Us last year as the biggest U.S. toy retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Amid restructuring charges that contributed to a $132 million
loss in 1998, Nakasone has been shutting stores, firing workers and
reducing inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Those cost-cutting efforts have been coupled with a plan for the
revamped store layout.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us spent roughly $6 million to re-do the nine stores
with the new layout, Nakasone said. It will spend up to $700,000
per store to revamp another 185 to 200 stores this year and another
325 next year.
</P>
<P>
   The compnay has 700 stores in the United States. In metro
Atlanta, Toys ``R'' Us will remodel three more of its nine stores
this year but hasn't identified which ones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
