<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-SPENDING-NYT &LR;      06-08 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTERT PEP TALK CAN'T UNITE REPUBLICANS ON SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas., Mo., Fla., Okla.)  (mk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Dennis Hastert, pleading for unity, told
fellow Republicans Tuesday that they must stick together and pass
the party's major bills or risk losing their majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   But despite a public display of mutual respect among the
Republicans after Hastert's pep talk, they are still deeply divided
over how to pass $538 billion in spending bills to finance the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a long, hot summer,'' said the majority whip,
Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas. ``We all know that. It's going to be very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 20-minute closed-door speech to the House Republican
conference, Hastert cracked no whips, twisted no arms and laid down
no laws. Paraphrasing Benjamin Franklin, the speaker said the
Republicans had to hang together or they would assuredly hang
separately.
</P>
<P>
   He asked them to ``give your leadership the benefit of the doubt
and just follow,'' according to members who were there. He urged
them to ``search your heart _ search your conscience,'' to put
aside the politics that have torn conservatives and moderates
asunder, ``and then decide to join us.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he warned that the stakes were high. ``Whether you
call it political, whether you call it the fiscal future of this
country or whether you call it the moral future of this country,
we're at the crossroads and that's what we're talking about in this
thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert reminded the Republicans of their precarious 223-211
majority, and warned that they could lose the House next year if
they did not govern the Legislature, govern themselves and pass the
spending bills _ the only thing Congress is legally required to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This notion that we're a do-nothing Congress sinks in after a
while,'' said Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill. He said Hastert made ``a
compelling argument that if we want to stay the majority, we've got
to act like the governing party.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, all the spending bills have been stalled. The main
stumbling block has been conservative Republicans who want all
domestic spending frozen or cut, and all Social Security surpluses
saved.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert offered no financial details of his plans to win passage
for the year's major spending bills. Republican aides say he will
shift more than $5 billion from bills financing the Defense,
Treasury and Agriculture Departments, Congress and military
construction, and move the money into bills for the Labor,
Education, Health and Human Services Departments and other domestic
programs, which took deep cuts in the Republican budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to mollify moderate Republicans who say those cuts
are too deep, while assuring conservatives that the strict budget
caps approved by Congress and the White House in 1997 will remain
in place.
</P>
<P>
   But the strategy may be doomed. Many Republicans say there is
simply too little money to pass the bills under the caps. Shuffling
a few billion dollars, says the staff director of the House
Appropriations Committee, James Dyer, is like rearranging the deck
chairs on the Titanic.
</P>
<P>
   So Hastert and DeLay have a fallback plan, key aides said
Tuesday: Let the appropriations process fail.
</P>
<P>
   Then they would try to force Democrats to create a spending plan
that breaks the budget caps, soaks up Social Security surpluses and
gives the Republicans a campaign issue for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans will demagogue on Social Security and we're
prepared to fight that battle,'' a senior Republican aide warned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument against the Democrats would be: `` `You're the
party of school lunches, we're the party of Social Security,' '' he
said. ``We will tag them as big spenders. We'll be able to define
ourself on two potent political issues: Save Social Security,
balance the budget. If we don't, we'll be the ones who didn't
balance it, and who raided Social Security, in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats may not fall for this strategy. ``It's their budget,''
said the minority leader, Dick Gephardt, D-Mo. ``They're going to
have to pass it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans said they were baffled by the lack of details
in Hastert's new spending plan, which appears to be a work in
progress. The plan was not cleared in advance with Rep. C.W. Bill
Young of Florida, the chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, which controls the 13 spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't understand how this new strategy works,'' said
Elizabeth Morra, a spokeswoman for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Edward Porter, R-Ill., chairman of the appropriations
subcommittee for the Labor, Health and Human Services, and
Education departments, said an extra 2 or 3 billion dollars would
not help his bill that much. His appropriation was cut by nearly
$11 billion by House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan, or its goals, won over a key conservative, Rep.
Tom Coburn, R-Okla. ``The proof,'' he said, ``will be in the
details and how we stay together.''
</P>
<P>
   And by winning over Coburn, Hastert unlocked the first major
spending bill to reach the House floor, a $60.8 billion measure for
agriculture programs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Coburn, a family physician, singlehandedly
stalled the agriculture bill in the name of the Social Security
surplus. It increased spending for the coming year, and that was
intolerable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Young cut $102.5 million from the bill on the House
floor, and Coburn withdrew the legislative roadblocks he had
erected.
</P>
<P>
   But then the doctor, showing the power of conservatives to shape
the spending bills, won an amendment barring the Food and Drug
Administration from testing, developing or approving the use of the
abortion drug RU-486. The amendment passed by a 217-214 vote after
three Republicans, at the behest of DeLay, switched their votes
from nay to yea at the last minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
