<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES DEFENSE APPROPRIATIONS PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Iowa, Calif.)   (bl)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate passed a $265 billion appropriations
bill for the Pentagon by a 93-4 vote on Tuesday night. The measure
includes a pay increase for military personnel and the authority to
lease luxurious executive jets for generals.
</P>
<P>
   By voice vote, the Senate added an amendment that would bar the
United States from spending any money to help reconstruct Serbia so
long as Slobodan Milosevic remains president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A second amendment, also approved by a voice vote, would bar the
use of emergency funds approved in May for military operations
against Yugoslavia for any reconstruction projects, whether in
Serbia or Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriations bill finances new weapons, military
operations and Pentagon personnel costs for the coming year. It
does not include money for military construction or the Energy
Department's nuclear weapons programs, which together will boost
the costs of military spending for the coming year to close to $290
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed on Tuesday night includes an across-the-board
4.8 percent pay increase for military personnel. It now goes to the
House, which has not brought military spending bills to the floor
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also resurrected a bid by the Air Force to win the
authority to lease six top-of-the-line Gulfstream executive jets
for military brass, at a cost that could run to nearly $500 million
over 10 years. The measure had been included in, and then withdrawn
from, the nearly $15 billion emergency supplemental bill passed by
Congress in May that financed NATO's air war in Yugoslavia and
added unrequested billions to the Pentagon's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The jets would be used by the Pentagon's nine unified and
regional commanders-in-chief, six of whom have headquarters in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate
Appropriations Committee, said the jets were needed to keep the
commanders from flying ``old Dumbos,'' aging 707 aircraft that he
said were antiquated and expensive to maintain. ``It would save
money in the long run,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, called the measure ``government
waste at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The American taxpayer should not be forced to pick up the tab
for this silver-starred perk,'' Harkin said. His amendment to block
the leasing authority, co-sponsored by Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., was defeated, 66-31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
