<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Automakers and Union Eager for Long-Term Deal
</P>
<P>
   With General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler scheduled to begin
talks next week with the United Automobile Workers union, it
appears increasingly likely that negotiators will seek a national
labor contract lasting four or more years, the longest such deal
since the 1950's, auto executives and union officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chastened by a strike last summer against GM and enjoying the
soaring profits and bountiful overtime pay produced by record auto
sales, management and workers appear eager to avoid another
showdown this year. The UAW would also be able to avoid having the
next round of auto labor talks in the summer of 2002, when the
union could be locked in a power struggle after the retirement of
its president, Stephen Yokich.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Intel Agrees to Limit Jobs
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual arrangement that reflects both the flush national
economy and Oregon's particular obsession with controlling sprawl,
Intel has agreed to pay a fee if it exceeds a ceiling of 1,000 new
manufacturing jobs on top of the 4,000 it already has in Washington
County, part of the Portland metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   More IBM Testimony on Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft executive told IBM privately in 1997 that the
computer maker would pay a lower price for Microsoft's Windows
operating system if it did not ship a competing Internet browser,
an IBM executive, Garry Norris, testified in the Microsoft
antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Replay Networks in Panasonic Deal
</P>
<P>
   Replay Networks has signed an agreement with Panasonic Consumer
Electronics to make its new digital video recorders systems and
have them in stores for the Christmas shopping season. The set-top
boxes blend the power of computers with television.
</P>
<P>
   Prescription Plan Draws Skepticism
</P>
<P>
   Drug industry and insurance executives reacted with skepticism
to White House plans for a new prescription drug benefit for all
elderly Americans. Drug manufacturers said they did not believe the
assurances of administration officials that the proposal would not
lead to price controls on drugs.
</P>
<P>
   GM to Buy Bank of New York Unit
</P>
<P>
   General Motors agreed to buy Bank of New York's commercial
lending unit for $1.8 billion as the auto maker diversifies its
holdings and the bank continues to specialize its operations. For
Bank of New York, the deal fits a pattern of concentrating on
fee-based operations. Its shares rose $2.375, to $37.0625, while GM
fell $1.375, to $67.75.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Panel Backs New Alliances
</P>
<P>
   In a move that would transform how legal services are provided,
a special panel of the American Bar Association recommended
abandoning decades-old rules that have prevented lawyers from
setting up partnerships with accountants, consultants and other
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Air Passengers Told to Be Punctual
</P>
<P>
   With the airline industry's on-time performance lagging, US
Airways is the latest carrier to require passengers to board planes
at least 10 minutes before scheduled departure _ or risk being left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific Grounds Flights
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific Airways grounded more than half its flights in a
bitter dispute with pilots who have been calling in sick over a
demand by the carrier to accept pay cuts averaging 7 percent or
quit with six months' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity Figures Revised
</P>
<P>
   Revised figures showed that worker productivity rose 3.5 percent
in the first quarter, less than the 4 percent previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Change-Over at Economic Council
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said that they would most likely nominate
Martin Baily, a partner at McKinsey &AMP; Co., to succeed Janet L.
Yellen later this year as head of the Council of Economic Advisers.
Ms. Yellen plans to leave this summer to return to teaching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
