<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7897 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARK-PLANE-CRASH-780&AMP;A     06-08 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARK-PLANE-CRASH-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SAFETY MEASURES ABSENT FROM ARKANSAS RUNWAY WHERE PLANE CRASHED
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ark. N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of the problems for the airliner that skidded
off the runway and crashed last week at the airport in Little Rock,
Ark., appears to be a string of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   The government provides money for three safety measures designed
to eliminate or reduce the risk of such accidents. But none of
those steps had been taken in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,000-foot buffer zone now required at the end of runways is
not in place in Little Rock because construction of the runway
began before the rule took effect. The airport does not have
breakaway light poles, common at the edges of airports, because the
flood-prone ground is too soft. And it does not yet have a safety
trap, called an arrestor bed, although one was approved before the
June 1 accident.
</P>
<P>
   Nine people, including the captain, were killed in the crash,
and 80 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The runway that was used by the plane, American Airlines Flight
1420, lacked the 1,000-foot buffer zone required on new runways
since Jan. 1, 1988, even though it opened in 1991. But because work
on the runway began in the early 1980s, the airport did not have to
comply with that rule, Federal Aviation Administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The overrun area for the runway, 4 Right, was 450 feet. The jet
went through that area, smashed into stanchions holding lights that
direct planes approaching from the opposite direction, and broke up
and caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   The parallel runway has such a 1,000-foot area, recently
expanded from 766 feet, when it was rehabilitated. But 4 Right, old
enough to be grandfathered, is too young to be rehabilitated and
thus still is not subject to the rule, which requires 1,000 feet
wherever practical. Exactly how far the zone could have been
extended on 4 Right is uncertain, because the Arkansas River's
flood plain is off the northeast end.
</P>
<P>
   But for the very spot where the crash occurred, the airport has
already been promised money from the FAA for an arrestor bed,
designed to catch and safely stop airplanes doing just what
American's MD-80 did, overrun the end of the runway. The project is
supposed to be built next year, at a cost of $1 million to $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Transportation Safety Board, which is in charge
of the investigation, officials are still trying to determine why
devices on the wings that help cut lift after landing, called
spoilers, did not deploy. On the MD-80, standard procedure is to
``arm'' the spoilers by setting a control in the cockpit before
landing, allowing the spoilers to pop up when the plane's wheels
start spinning. Reducing lift gives the wheels more traction as the
plane's weight settles on them.
</P>
<P>
   The first officer, who survived the crash, told investigators
that he saw the captain arm the spoilers, but the flight data
recorder indicates they were never deployed. Experts say that
investigators may be able to hear the sound of the spoilers being
armed on the cockpit voice recorder.
</P>
<P>
   George Black Jr., the member of the board in charge at the
scene, said there was no mention of the spoilers on the tape. But
investigators say that this does not establish that they were not
armed.
</P>
<P>
   The runway that the plane used is 7,200 feet long, on the short
side for an MD-80, which is known to pilots as a heavy plane with
relatively low aerodynamic drag, and thus harder to stop. Airport
engineers had to fit it into a space 8,650 feet long, because the
flood plain of the Arkansas River is at the northeast end. They did
take 1,000 feet for a buffer zone, but they put it at the other end
of the runway, so it is a buffer for planes coming in the other
direction, in which case the runway is called 22 Left. (Runways are
named by compass heading.)
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear why the plane used the runway, 4
Right, instead of 4 Left, which is 1,000 feet longer. Both were
available that night, according to an airport spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lighting stanchions like the ones that Flight 1420
hit are supposed to be designed to break away on impact, so they do
not break up the airplane, as happened in this case. But the
stanchions that this plane hit sit in the flood plain of the
Arkansas River, and their bases had to be made sturdier to avoid
having them tilt or fall, according to FAA officials.
</P>
<P>
   Arrestor systems, first put in use at Kennedy and La Guardia
airports in New York, are rare. One at Kennedy got its first
operational use last month, saving a commuter plane from taxiing
into the water at the end of a runway. Asked if they were often
considered by airport managers, David Bennett, the director of the
FAA's office of airport safety and standards, said, ``If it wasn't
before, it probably is now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials in Little Rock reopened the runway Tuesday, although
for planes landing in the opposite direction, it is available for
visual approaches only, since the MD-80 destroyed some navigation
equipment at the far end.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, meanwhile, continued to examine the wreckage of
the plane, some of which was inaccessible until it was moved off
the field. Matthew Furhman, a spokesman for the National
Transportation Safety Board, said that part of the landing gear,
for example, was only now available for study.
</P>
</TEXT>
