<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERB-REFUGEES-COX     06-08 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERB-REFUGEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugees wary about peace prospect
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO _ The accord reached Tuesday in Europe on a framework
for peace in Yugoslavia was greeted with skepticism by
ethnic-Albanian refugees who fled to Bosnia-Herzegovina from the
troubles in their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800,000 refugees have left the Yugoslavian provinces
of Sandzak and Kosovo, with more than 100,000 seeking refuge in
Bosnia, Yugoslavia's neighbor to the east.
</P>
<P>
   A delegation from Dayton arrives in today in the Bosnian capitol
of Sarajevo on a three-day goodwill mission to meet with Bosnian
officials and sign a Sister Cities agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Both in downtown Sarajevo and in a refugee camp about 20 miles
outside of the city, ethnic-Albanians said Tuesday they long to
return to their homes and villages, even if burned-out and
destroyed, if peace could be assured by international forces.
</P>
<P>
   After a flurry of optimism last weekend that the fighting would
soon end, ethnic-Albanians said they could not trust the promises
of Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic that he would keep his
side of a peace bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I would return) only under guards,'' said Aziz Osmanaj, who
left the Kosovo village of Runik with his wife and three children.
``I know my house has been burned down. I know 80 percent of the
towns have been destroyed. I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmanaj, an economist, said he first left his home a year ago as
intimidation increased from the Serbian-dominated Yugoslavian
government against non-Serbs in his territory. Road block
checkpoints sprang up throughout the region and police harassment
became common.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us came back into the village, but it was
impossible,'' he said. ``Most of us had to flee again.''
</P>
<P>
   Osmanaj left for good last winter, the week international
negotiators failed to convince the Yugoslavian government to allow
international peacekeepers into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if the bombing started, we knew the killing would
start and we knew we would be the first to be hit,'' he said
through a United Nations interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Osmanaj is one of 250 refugees who arrived Saturday at a new
camp in the Bosnian village of Visoko run by the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugee. He spent a couple of months at
another camp that was set up when the refugees began arriving and
eventually became overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   Here, they sleep 70 to a room crammed with bunk beds in
temperatures that climb near 90 degrees during the day. There is
one spigot for fresh water, which residents use to drink, bathe and
wash clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Children pass the day kicking balls around an unkempt field near
their building, and adults listen to radios, talk and wait.
</P>
<P>
   Mehmet Gorcaj, 31, and his wife and three children stayed in
their Kosovo village of Istok through the winter even as the
political climate worsened. After the NATO offensive began in
March, however, Serb forces shelled his village and Gorcaj said he
was one of thousands from his region to flee along snow-packed
roads through the mountains to neighboring Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   They moved on to the Bosnian refugee camps when the Serbian
government in Montenegro began looking for young men to draft into
the Yugoslavian army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since no one knew what would happen next, no one could stay,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorcaj said he would be starting from ``under zero'' when his
family returns to their village.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. refugee officials have been caught off guard by the sudden
prospect for peace. In Sarajevo they have just opened another small
tent-city, even though the flow of refugees has slowed. Their
efforts are split between planning for having to house refugees
during the harsh Balkan winter six months off and planning to deal
with a feared rush of refugees flooding back into Kosovo once peace
is declared.
</P>
<P>
   Sarajevo has also become home to an estimated 22,500 refugees
from the Yugoslavian province of Sandzak. Many of them arrived on
buses and in rented cars over the past several months to stay with
family or rent apartments.
</P>
<P>
   One, a 68-year-old man who gave only his first name as Omar,
wandered slowly around the Sarajevo train depot and bus station
Monday with a grandson in tow. He left his home in March even
though he and Serbian neighbors were on good terms, he said. NATO
bombing was coming and he feared the bombing would create a
backlash against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feared that after bombing paramilitary units would come
into our village and our town and start killing and burn out,'' he
said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   His said his family pays the equivalent of $700 a month for a
two-bedroom apartment and will stay for as long as their money will
last. The rate is high _ three times what a Bosnian family would be
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic-Albanians in Sarajevo slept for weeks on the floor of the
train station's main hall when the NATO campaign first began and a
flood of people hit the city. Now the station remains a gathering
place for them, and they cluster around buses which still arrive
every day from Zenica, a city in Sandjak.
</P>
<P>
   One bus driver said Tuesday conditions in Sandjak are calm and
that his bus has not been stopped by troops. He said Sandjaks not
wanted for evading the draft could return today unmolested.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
