<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, THEATER GROUP ANNOUNCE ADMITTANCE CRACKDOWN TO R-RATED
MOVIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most movie theater owners agreed Tuesday to require
an ID check of youths seeking admission into R-rated movies to halt
underage youngsters from sneaking into restricted films.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the National Association of Theater Owners appeared
with President Clinton in the White House's Roosevelt Room to
announce the new crackdown as the president's campaign against
youth violence gained support from one segment of the entertainment
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about the multiplex is that there's a movie
for every member of the family, but not every movie is for every
member of the family,'' Clinton said. ``When you drop them off, you
shouldn't have to worry about your G-rated kids getting into
violent or suggestive R-rated movies. Too often, children do get
past the ticket counter unescorted and underage.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie rating system was developed in 1968 by the Motion
Picture Association of America. The ratings have been refined over
the years to G for general admission, PG for parental guidance
suggested, PG-13 for parents cautioned material may be
inappropriate for children under age 13, R for restricted to age 17
and over unless accompanied by a parent or guardian and NC-17 for
no one under 17 admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed commitment to enforce the R-rating came in wake of
the series of school shootings, including the murder of 12 students
and a teacher by two Columbine High School teens in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us, I believe, have had our sensibilities heightened
since the recent tragedies at Columbine and in Georgia, and we as
theater owners feel our responsibilities as keenly as does
anybody,'' said William Kartozian, president of the National
Association of Theater Owners.
</P>
<P>
   Kartozian said the association will ask its 700 members, who
control 65 percent of the screens nationwide, to post notices of
the crackdown, educating parents about the ratings and the new
policy, and support for a national study on the causes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in the community that we serve, and we want to be a
part of those communities and be a part of the solution to whatever
problems may be going on in your communities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hailed the action by the theater owners to adopt a new
policy requiring a photo identification of unaccompanied youths
seeking admission into R-rated films. Every state but Massachusetts
allows either a driver's license or a photo identification for 17
year olds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased to announce today the theater owners are clearly
drawing the line,'' Clinton said. ``From now on, parents will know
that the R rating means what it is supposed to mean _ restricted _
no one under 17 without a parent or guardian, and no exceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the theater owners is the latest in a series
of White House efforts launched since the Columbine shootings. The
president previously hosted a conference at the White House on ways
to reduce youth violence, ordered a study to determine if the
entertainment industry is marketing violence to youngsters and
embraced gun-control efforts pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also pressed the House to follow the Senate's lead to
increase the age restriction for purchasing guns, require
background checks at gun shows, require safety locks to be sold
with every handgun and ban importation of large ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our growing national campaign to prevent youth violence,
none can stand aside, none should stand in the way,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But that campaign has been greeted cautiously by the movie and
music industry, where fears of censorship are paramount. Clinton,
who has drawn policy support from Hollywood, predicted more
industry officials will join the effort to tame the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a significant number of people in the
entertainment industry who will participate in it, because a lot of
them said something to me about it,'' Clinton told reporters as he
met with Hungarian President Arpad Goncz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all work at it ... so that nobody's pointing a finger at
anybody else, I think we'll have a good participation from the
entertainment community. I'd be surprised if we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his call for a crackdown on R-rating age
restrictions during a May 15 radio address in which he also noted
the typical teen-ager will see 40,000 simulated murders by age 18.
During the radio address, he also called for a halt to showing guns
in previews watched by children and for a re-evaluation of the
entire ratings system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
