<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVLIN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: END OF AN ILLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as the markets have soared in the last few
years, most sophisticated investors have enough wits to beware of
anyone who promises to double their money within two weeks in
risk-free investments in a secretive global trading market backed
by the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   But the illusion of such returns can become alluring when the
person making the claims has pictures on his office wall of himself
with presidents and other luminaries, and a pedigree to match.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the illusion came crashing down on Lewis Rivlin, a
prominent Washington lawyer, when the Securities and Exchange
Commission accused him in a lawsuit of defrauding investors of $6.2
million.
</P>
<P>
   According to government lawyers and court papers, Rivlin traded
on his prominence by promising investors that they would lose
nothing if they invested in a high-yield trading program that he
said would be conducted under the auspices of Chrysanthos
Chrysostomou, who had been the metropolitan of Limassol, a bishop
in the Greek Orthodox Church in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin now says that all of the money has been stolen by
foreigners, and the investors, which include an Ecuadorean charity
for underprivileged girls, have been left with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Richard Walker, head of the SEC's enforcement
division, it turns out that the market _ as well as the securities
that Rivlin promoted with a former law partner and former aide _
was entirely fictitious.
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin said in an interview Tuesday night that he did nothing
improper and that he would prevail. ``I can take the government's
pants down, there's no question about that,'' he said. ``I didn't
waste years of training at the Justice Department and then in
private practice and go lightly into something that the government
said is all fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, at least, Rivlin's career would seem to be incongruous
with Tuesday's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Swarthmore College and Harvard Law School, Rivlin
began his legal career in the civil division of the Justice
Department and rose to become a senior trial lawyer in the
antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, he co-founded a law firm whose other members included
former Sen. Albert Gore Sr. of Tennessee, the father of Vice
President Al Gore; former Gov. Endicott Peabody of Massachusetts,
and Charles Duncan, the former dean of Howard Law School. Rivlin
was also a campaign coordinator for Hubert Humphrey's unsuccessful
presidential campaign in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Rivlin's marriage to Alice Rivlin, the vice chairwoman of the
Federal Reserve, ended in divorce more than 20 years ago. The
couple have three children, and she recently said she would retire
from the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's complaint is the latest in a string of setbacks for
Rivlin, who is 69. Two months ago, a federal judge awarded $16
million to the Ecuadorean charity, which sued Rivlin after it
invested more than $1.7 million with him. Representing himself in
that case, Rivlin said he could not produce many details about the
investments because they were secret, according to another lawyer
involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sharp, a lawyer representing the charity, said that Rivlin
contended in his deposition in the civil case that the investment
was legitimate and that because it was secret, he could not talk
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Lamberth, the judge hearing that case, has been assigned
to preside over the SEC's action and has ordered that Rivlin's
passport be seized.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate proceeding, an ethics panel is weighing sanctions
against Rivlin for allegations that he committed fraud and
commingled $48,000 of a client's money with his own. Rivlin
supposedly asked the client to invest in the purchase and resale of
diamonds and gold from the Central African Republic.
</P>
<P>
   In that proceeding, Rivlin has denied any wrongdoing, though the
Office of Bar Counsel in Washington has accused him of using a
client's money to pay himself; his wife; a local supermarket; Radio
Shack; Sears, Roebuck, and Publishers Clearing House.
</P>
<P>
   According to the complaint filed Tuesday by the SEC, the
investment agreements Rivlin promoted said that all money invested
would be ``secured'' either by a bank guarantee or some other
security. Some investors were also told by Rivlin that he would
personally guarantee them against any loss.
</P>
<P>
   Each agreement said that either Rivlin or Chrysostomou had a
relationship with at least one person who would conduct or control
trading in the secret program, specifically the purchase and resale
of deeply discounted bank instruments, the SEC said. The agreements
also said trading would begin soon after the transfer of the
investor's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading, in fact, never began,'' the agency said in its court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also named as defendants Alfred Velarde, Rivlin's
former law partner, and Edwin Huling III, a former employee of the
firm. Velarde has settled with the government and agreed to pay a
$20,000 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop, who resigned in November, was suspended from
religious duties for two years after the church accused him of
profiteering. The SEC named him as a recipient of ill-gotten gains.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the SEC said the case was not a novel one but
provided an important lesson for investors. ``People need to focus
on the quality of the investments they make, not the connections of
the broker they deal with,'' said Elizabeth Gray, an assistant
director of enforcement. ``In this case, it turns out that they
were both corrupt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
