<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DOKIC-FATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE AGAIN, A FATHER IS EJECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By SAMANTHA STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ The father of Jelena Dokic, a promising
16-year-old Australian, was ejected during her tennis match at a
tournament here Tuesday and later picked up by the police after
lying in the middle of a road.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, the father, Damir Dokic, was cautioned
for drunken and disorderly behavior and was released without being
charged.
</P>
<P>
   During his daughter's match at the DFS Classic, Dokic began
shouting at spectators and officials during a first-round match
against Rita Grande of Italy. Brenda Perry, a WTA Tour director,
asked Dokic to leave the area, having already cautioned him during
Dokic's qualifying match earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards said Damir Dokic pushed Perry and refused to
leave. Six guards then lifted Dokic, struggling, past spectators to
the exit at the rear of the grounds, at the Edgbaston Priory Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began running down the street and shouting,'' said Marcus
Allchurch, a tournament security guard. Dokic then jumped on the
hood of a car and rolled off, the guard said, zigzagged down the
street and threw himself in the middle of the road in front of
another car.
</P>
<P>
   Allchurch said the automobile, driven by a woman with a child in
a car seat, stopped, avoiding running him over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He flipped his lid,'' said Lester Smedley, a security guard
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Dokic was held by security guards for more than an hour until
the police arrived and arrested him. Several times he fell on his
knees in prayer and at one point tried to cut his arm with his
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not seen anything like this before,'' said Roy Dixon, a
club member. ``I know of the Mary Pierce incident and others that
have happened in tennis. I've played 45 years of tennis and nine
years at Wimbledon, and no, I have not seen anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's tour has been concerned with the parents of the
young players, worried about not only their behavior in the stands
but toward their children. Pierce's father, Jim, was banned from
the women's tour from 1993 to 1998 after two incidents at the
French Open, one in which he punched a fan. His daughter, then 18,
later accused him of abusive behavior. Last year, Mirjana Lucic,
then 16, left her father, Marinko, saying that he had physically
abused her. In both cases, the fathers denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Bart McGuire, the chief executive officer of the WTA Tour, said
that Damir Dokic would be barred for the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The match between Dokic and Grande was suspended by wet grass in
the third set. She asked to be to be driven to the police station
to see her father.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Handford, the custody sergeant of the Harborne Police
Station, said: `` Dokic was cautioned for drunk and disorderly
conduct. He was more sober than he had been and so he was released.
We've seen worse offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelena Dokic was born in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and took up
tennis at the age of 6 before her family moved to Australia when
she was 10. Known for her mental tenacity, Dokic has been compared
to a youthful Monica Seles. WTA Tour officials said her father had
been cited previously for yelling at a security guard in an
incident in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Dokic and Mark Philippoussis led Australia to its
first Hopman Cup title. She won the U.S. Open junior title last
year and at the 1998 French Open she was a finalist in the junior
singles and won the junior doubles. She finished the year as the
world's top-ranked junior and is ranked 133rd on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
