<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUNS-JUVENILES-800&AMP;AD     06-08 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-JUVENILES-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS ROUTE GUN MEASURES STRAIGHT TO THE FLOOR
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill., Mo., Fla., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders said Tuesday that they
would bring gun-control legislation to the House floor next week
without holding a previously scheduled meeting in the House
Judiciary Committee, a change in strategy that demonstrated their
acute sensitivity to the potency of gun control as a political
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The move would deny Democrats an additional showcase, in advance
of the debate on the House floor, to paint Republicans as outright
foes of real change or reluctant, half-hearted converts to the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republican aides said party leaders did not want the
passage of gun-control measures, which they now see as a political
necessity, to get tripped up by the opposition of Republicans on
the Judiciary Committee, who tend to be more conservative as a
group than other House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, House Republicans' gun-control proposals, which were
unveiled Tuesday, bear the imprimatur not of the entire Judiciary
Committee, but of its chairman, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., or of Hyde
and the chairman of the committee's crime subcommittee, Rep. Bill
McCollum, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, those measures largely mirror the gun-control
provisions passed by the Senate, but there were some changes in
language and one particularly significant divergence that is sure
to provoke intense dispute between Republicans and Democrats in the
days to come.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Hyde and McCollum for mandatory background
checks on all buyers at gun shows contains a more liberal
definition of those shows, and less stringent requirements on
record-keeping, than the Senate measure did.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Hyde and McCollum proposed that any gathering of
fewer than 10 vendors, no matter how many guns they exhibit, was
not a gun show. Under the Senate measure, it could be regulated as
a gun show, if there were 50 or more guns for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats instantly cried foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're clearly watering down the Senate provisions, and it's
an outrage,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., an ardent advocate of
gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But in a number of other ways, Hyde's proposals dovetailed with
the desires of Democrats or fell short of their worst fears.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-show measure did not put a 24-hour limit on the time
that vendors would have to conduct background checks, as many
Republicans and officials with the National Rifle Association had
advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it set a cap of three calendar days, a time frame only
slightly more liberal than the three business days allowed by the
Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the collection of measures proposed by Hyde and
McCollum proposed raising the minimum legal age for all handgun
purchases from 18 to 21, something that the Senate did not tackle.
The measures also went beyond the Senate's by calling for parents
to be held legally culpable when their guns end up in the hands of
children and do harm.
</P>
<P>
   Because the House Judiciary Committee meeting was canceled, the
gun-control proposals will not actually be rolled into the juvenile
crime that will serve as the vehicle for the measures on the House
floor. Rather, the measures _ some of them lumped together, some of
them standing alone _ will be offered as amendments, and will
likely be supplemented by a few additional or rival Democratic
amendments that Republican leaders allow to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of the committee meeting opened the door to
complaints by Democrats that Republicans were trying to give the
gun-control debate a lower profile and evade accountability with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., said it was the latest
sign of Republicans' coziness with the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me suspicious that they're in control and they're
driving the ship so they can get the results they want,'' Gephardt
said of the gun lobbying organization.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde called the Democrats' criticisms a ``knee-jerk, mindless
reaction. I, the chairman, do not want to kill the gun bill. I am
not part of any strategy to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, by eliminating the scheduled meeting of Hyde's panel,
Republican leaders may have removed a few potential obstacles to
the passage of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   One is a proposal by Hyde that would prohibit the distribution
to children and teen-agers of any violent books, videogames and
other materials. That measure, rife with potential violations of
the First Amendment and odious to many Democrats and Republicans,
might have been added into a Republican gun-control package during
the Judiciary Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it will apparently come to the House floor as its own
amendment, which Republican aides said was likely to be defeated.
``It's legally ridiculous,'' said one Republican aide.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But it was an example of the many possible pitfalls for the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the Hyde-McCollum gun-control measures are combined
with some strict new requirements on punishing juvenile offenders
that many Democrats will not want to vote for. Additionally, some
Democrats who do not usually vote for gun control do not want to
brave those waters now unless the juvenile crime bill is amended to
include more money and programs for the prevention of violence
among children.
</P>
<P>
   The two gun-control measures that McCollum did not choose to
sponsor with Hyde concerned the minimum age for handgun purchases
and a ban on the import of high-capacity ammunition clips, the
latter of which the Senate approved.
</P>
<P>
   That Hyde put these proposals forward by himself was an
indication that they enjoyed more narrow support among Republicans
and were less likely to pass than other measures, like a
requirement that child safety devices accompany all handguns sold
by federally licensed dealers.
</P>
</TEXT>
