<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7915 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-BOS &LR;      06-08 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKER TRIES TO UNIFY REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He was supposed to be the un-Newt.
</P>
<P>
   Installed as House speaker last fall during one of the most
chaotic chapters in Republican Party history, Representative Dennis
Hastert of Illinois was hailed as everything his predecessor was
not: quiet, collaborative, unifying, firm.
</P>
<P>
   During the past six months, Hastert has proven to be all of
those things, colleagues say. And yet the Republican-controlled
Congress is still plagued by the same legislative logjams that
helped destroy Newt Gingrich as speaker _ so much so that many
members have begun questioning Hastert's leadership style, too.
</P>
<P>
   The appropriations process has stalled. Gun-control legislation
is up in the air. A key vote on Kosovo in April ended in a baffling
tie vote, drawing accusations that Hastert had no political muscle
and that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas is really running
the place.
</P>
<P>
   As if to respond to those charges, Hastert on Tuesday summoned
his party together to deliver one of the most forceful speeches of
his term, quoting Benjamin Franklin as he pleaded with House
Republicans to get a budget passed, many of those present said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do either hang together or hang separately,'' Hastert told
members, who burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   But whether that message will become reality remained a question
in the minds of many Democrats as well as, privately, some
Republicans. The problem, they said, may have less to do with
Hastert than the fractured party he is forced to lead with a narrow
six-vote margin in the House.
</P>
<P>
   His usually tempered tone has brought him respect from most
factions of the Republican Party, even from Representative
Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican who is at odds with the
speaker over when to bring the campaign-finance overhaul bill to
the House floor. Unlike during the Gingrich days, Shays said, ``I
don't wake up every morning wondering what my speaker said that I'm
going to have to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sleep better at night,'' Shays said. ``I may disagree with
Denny, but that's different from saying I don't think he's an
effective leader.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gingrich, who was forced by his own party to step down,
thinks Hastert is ``proving to be an effective legislative
leader,'' according to Michael Shields, communications director for
the Friends of Newt Gingrich Political Action Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Such praise, however, depends on which measuring stick for
effectiveness is used _ whether it is gauged by popularity ratings
or election results or pieces of legislation passed. Democrats
argue that the budget resolution passed earlier this year cannot be
counted as a Hastert success if it collapses during the
appropriations process. Three spending measures were expected to
pass before the Memorial Day holiday, but have become bottlenecked
primarily because of resistance from conservatives who say the
bills cost too much.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, Hastert has voiced support for measures similar
to the ones recently passed by the Senate. But House leaders pushed
back consideration of the legislation until next week as
Republicans wrangle over various amendments that gun control
supporters say would water down the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Hastert presented a plan designed to rescue the
appropriations process, starting with adhering to budget caps and
shaving money off a $60.8 billion agriculture bill that
conservatives had promised to kill. Conservatives indicated Tuesday
they would go along with the plan, which would shift some spendin
to bolster domestic programs that would be cut under the current
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the unusually stern tone of Tuesday's speech that
indicated a shift for Hastert. He made it clear that any six
Republicans could defeat a bill, and that any major political
embarrassments for the party could make it easy for Democrats to
win control of the House next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, you cannot be happy all the time,'' Hastert said.
``Some days you have to give your leadership the benefit of the
doubt and just follow. That is the difference between a majority
mentality and a minority mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I need you to stand together,'' he continued. ``To move
forward together. To not just cry out for leadership, but be
willing to follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, Democrats questioned whether Hastert
could provide such leadership. Representative Steny H. Hoyer, a
Democrat from Maryland, said Congress ``will have to see if there's
really a shift'' within the Republican leadership team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew they needed a kinder, gentler face on the caucus,
but what we've seen in the last month is that they still have a
hard heart,'' he said. ``I don't think the problem has been so much
with the speaker. It's been the Republicans. The enemy is within.''
</P>
</TEXT>
