<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW ENVOY'S PEACE EFFORTS, PRAISED IN WEST, ARE PANNED AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-RDP, KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-ASSESS) 
 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ When Russia's special envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, went
to Belgrade last week with the president of Finland to help resolve
the Kosovo conflict, he was seen in the West as a heroic statesman.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner did Chernomyrdin return to Moscow than he ran into
a buzz saw of criticism. Communist lawmakers demanded that he be
censured for working too closely with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military also did its best to undermine his
diplomacy. Lt. Gen. Yevgeny Barmyantsev, the Russian military
attache in Belgrade who was sent to military talks in Macedonia as
an observer, went so far as to encourage the Serbs to rebuff NATO's
demands, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Even President Boris Yeltsin's dutiful foreign minister, Igor
Ivanov, mounted a quiet effort in Cologne over the past two days to
dilute the agreement that Chernomyrdin and the Finnish president,
Martti Ahtisaari, brought back from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Ivanov urged that a one-year limit be set on
NATO's peacekeeping presence in Kosovo. He finally agreed to an
open-ended deployment.
</P>
<P>
   In the end it was Yeltsin's desire to see the war brought to an
end that seems to have prevailed. Following days of confusion and
considerable intrigue, the Kremlin belatedly endorsed the
negotiating efforts of Chernomyrdin by embracing a draft U.N.
Security Council resolution on ending the Yugoslav conflict.
</P>
<P>
   His commitment was reinforced by two telephone calls in the past
two days from President Clinton, as Washington strove to keep the
Russians on board.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Russian politics has left its imprint on the peacemaking
process in these and other ways that are still not entirely clear.
</P>
<P>
   The draft U.N. resolution, hammered out by Western and Russian
foreign ministers in Cologne on Tuesday, seeks to allay Russian
anxieties by avoiding any direct reference to NATO's plan to
command 50,000 peacekeepers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials described the omission as
little more than a sop to Moscow and insist that the Kremlin is
under no illusion about the allies' plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the Russians every step of the way that the only
force that will work and that we will support is one that has NATO
at its core,'' a senior Clinton administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Western officials worry that the studied vagueness in
the text will be exploited by the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the intent was to come up with a fuzzy document that the
Russians could agree to, the foreign ministers achieved their
purpose,'' one diplomat said. ``If the intent was to clarify the
nature of the international security presence that would be
deployed in Kosovo, that presence was left undefined.''
</P>
<P>
   The West's decision to include the Russians in a Kosovo
settlement was one of the most fateful moves in the complex Balkan
diplomacy. The aim was to increase the diplomatic pressure on the
Milosevic regime. NATO also hoped to avoid a complete rupture with
Moscow, which has objected bitterly to the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiating with Moscow has not been easy. Yeltsin has an
enormous political stake in seeing the war brought to a close and
ending the criticism that Russia's power had dwindled so much on
his watch that the Kremlin was powerless to stop NATO's air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Having railed against NATO expansion, Moscow finds it
excruciatingly difficult to endorse a settlement brought about by
allied bombing and which places NATO troops firmly in charge of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is motivated less by a desire to help Belgrade than by
its worries about NATO's willingness to flex muscles in a region
that Moscow long considered to be within its sphere of influence.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7920 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2NDTAKE     06-08 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: of influence. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Russian policy has oscillated between bitter
criticism and cooperation. Russia started off assailing NATO policy
from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Then Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov went to Belgrade with two
top intelligence officials. It was not clear whether Primakov was
there to help bring about a settlement or encourage Milosevic to
resist.
</P>
<P>
   Russia began to cooperate more with NATO after Chernomyrdin
became the envoy. A former prime minister and former head of
Russia's gas industry, Chernomyrdin is a pragmatist who has long
favored strong ties with West.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of Western officials, Chernomyrdin succeeded, not by
presenting his own plan, but by endorsing the NATO demands carried
to Belgrade by Ahtisaari. That made Chernomyrdin an easy target for
critics at home. So bitter is the criticism that Chernomyrdin's
dreams of reviving his political career seem to be all but dead.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to the nationalist sentiment, Yeltsin did not leap to
Chernomyrdin's defense. The Kremlin's silence emboldened the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Col. Gen. Leonid Ivashov, the head of the Defense
Ministry's department for international military cooperation, was
publicly challenging the agreement. At the Macedonia talks,
Barmyantsev urged the Serbs not to agree to a NATO-led force.
</P>
<P>
   As the divisions widened, Yeltsin aides did their best to paper
over the obvious divisions in the ranks. Dmitri Yakushkin,
Yeltsin's spokesman, insisted in an interview that there were
differences of opinion but ``no contradictions'' within the Russian
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cologne meeting approached, however, Yeltsin was faced
with a difficult choice: work closely with NATO or watch the war
drag on. President Clinton tried to drive home the message by
telling Yeltsin in a phone call that a settlement would be imminent
if the Kremlin would put its full weight behind the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement on a U.N. resolution still leaves one thorny
issue: the role of Russian troops in Kosovo. The Russians have
offered to contribute up to 10,000 troops. The Kosovo Liberation
Army says that ethnic Albanians may be afraid to return to an area
controlled by such a large Russian force, given Moscow's sympathies
for Belgrade and its insistence that its troops not be under NATO
command.
</P>
<P>
   Washington hopes to work out an arrangement modeled on the
peacekeeping force in Bosnia in which the Russian troops indirectly
report to a NATO general. So far, however, a solution has proved
elusive. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is coming to
Moscow to try to resolve the details.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of mixed signals, even Chernomyrdin's rivals sought
to put the best face on the diplomacy Tuesday. Ivanov defended the
draft resolution as the quickest way to bring an end to NATO
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any agreement is a compromise,'' Ivanov said. ``We had one
principal compromise, which is to end the war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
