<HEADER>
A7923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SCANDAL-NYT &LR;      06-08 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE MEXICAN TELLS OF HUGE PAYMENT TO RULING PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For years, the governing party in Mexico has
sought to keep its finances cloaked in secrecy. Industrialists who
have profited from government contracts and other insider dealings
have donated vast sums to underwrite the party's 70-year domination
of Mexican politics, with little or no public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But a political storm erupted here in the last week after Carlos
Cabal Peniche, a banker who fled Mexico five years ago, began
relating for the first time his own huge donations to the party,
the Institutional Revolutionary Party, before the last presidential
election, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   From a prison in Australia, where he is fighting extradition
proceedings, Cabal has described how he collected $25 million from
associates and channeled the money to the party, known as the PRI.
That included about $5 million that was donated during the 1994
campaign of President Ernesto Zedillo, Cabal said recently in
written statements.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Zedillo on Saturday said he had no personal
knowledge of Cabal's contributions to his campaign or the party.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, in a written response to questions that were
transmitted to Cabal through his Australian spokesman, Cabal said
he had discussed the donations personally in a face-to-face
encounter with Zedillo. He said he met Zedillo at the PRI's Mexico
City headquarters on Jan. 12, 1994, when Zedillo was still the
campaign coordinator for the PRI's presidential candidate, Luis
Donaldo Colosio. Colosio was assassinated a few months later and
Zedillo went on to become the PRI's candidate and to win the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the meeting well,'' Cabal said.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's spokesman, Fernando Lerdo de Tejada, said Tuesday that
Zedillo ``never discussed campaign donations, not with Carlos Cabal
Peniche nor with any person. That was not his role as campaign
coordinator.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabal has been charged in Mexico with financial fraud amounting
to $700 million, and was an international fugitive before his
arrest in Australia last November. His decision to provide details
about what he says are some of the PRI's back-room secrets appears
to be part of his legal campaign to avoid extradition to Mexico,
where he has been accused of fraud in connection with the collapse
of his banks. Mexican officials have portrayed him as an inveterate
liar, but so far, nothing they have said about his disclosures have
shown him to be telling tales.
</P>
<P>
   The political donations Cabal has described appear to have been
legal under the free-for-all election rules that prevailed in
Mexico in 1993 and 1994, officials of the Federal Electoral
Institute said. The rules were tightened somewhat in a 1996
campaign finance reform law backed by Zedillo. The Institute voted
last month that it lacked the power to investigate further into the
PRI's 1994 campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   The transactions may, however, have constituted fraud or other
financial crimes, according to a criminal complaint filed last
September by the opposition Party of the Democratic Revolution.
Leaders of the party, known as the PRD, based the complaint on
documents they obtained that detail many of the financial
transactions Cabal is now acknowledging.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint, which Attorney General Jorge Madrazo said he is
investigating, argues that Cabal used Banco Union, a bank he bought
from the government during a privatization drive, to extend some
$15 million in unsecured loans to associates, who in turn donated
the money the PRI. These transactions helped drive Banco Union into
insolvency in 1994, forcing the government to bail out the bank,
the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians who view Madrazo's handling of the
investigation as sluggish are now demanding a special prosecutor to
investigate the financing of the 1994 campaign that brought most of
the current leaders of Mexico's executive branch to power.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the result of the investigation, Cabal's claims have
altered the country's political landscape before the 2000
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Money!'' was the front-page headline of the newsmagazine
Proceso, in an article about Cabal's assertions. The article quoted
several opposition congressmen saying that Cabal's money was dirty
because his banks had been used in what appeared to be a
money-laundering scheme with suspicious origins.
</P>
<P>
   Both opposition parties, the PRD and National Action, are using
the scandal to portray the PRI as a clique of reckless millionaires
whose financial abuses during the 1994 campaign caused the economic
meltdown that began in the first weeks of Zedillo's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexicans can no longer tolerate the complicities that keep a
small group in control of all political and economic power at the
cost of the impoverishment of the citizenry,'' National Action said
in a communique.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1993, at the time Cabal says he began organizing
donations to the PRI, there were virtually no limits on how much
money corporations or individuals could give to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal says, and PRI leaders have acknowledged, that he collected
some 47 million pesos from his associates, then the equivalent of
about $15 million, and turned the money over to a PRI trust fund in
July 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1993, the PRI agreed to establish the first limits
on donations and spending. That step came after a damaging scandal
growing out of a private banquet organized by party leaders in
which 25 of Mexico's richest men were each asked to donate $25
million to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Under the limits, corporations were prohibited from making
political donations, and individuals were limited to about two
million pesos a year, then the equivalent of some $597,000.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the rules in effect when Cabal says he met with
Zedillo in January 1994 to discuss a new package of donations. As a
result of his conversations with Zedillo, Cabal says, he gave one
million pesos, then the equivalent of about $330,000, well below
the individual cap, to the PRI in May 1994. That donation is not
disputed by the party or the President.
</P>
<P>
   Cabal also ``promoted and facilitated'' donations by his
associates to the PRI at about the same time in an amount
approaching $5 million, he said in Tuesday's statement.
</P>
<P>
   Lerdo de Tejada, the presidential spokesman, has confirmed
Cabal's one million peso donation, but has denied that Cabal made
any other donation to either the Colosio or Zedillo presidential
campaigns. Other PRI leaders, however, have acknowledged that Cabal
assembled a $15 million donation for the party in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Lerdo de Tejada denied categorically that Zedillo was aware
of any of Cabal's donations in 1993 or 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither as campaign coordinator for Luis Donaldo Colosio, nor
later, as candidate for the presidency, did President Ernesto
Zedillo have knowledge of any contribution whatsoever made by Mr.
Carlos Cabal Peniche to either of these campaigns,'' Lerdo said in
a statement issued Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Zedillo supported a campaign finance reform law that
established generous public financing for Mexican campaigns and
imposed reporting requirements on individual donations. But the
regulations apply only to the official party nominees, not
individual politicians seeking the nomination. Next year's
presidential campaign does not officially begin until January. As a
result, half a dozen informal candidates from all three major
parties are now collecting donations with no legal restrictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
