<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WNBA-COX     06-08 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WNBA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WNBA expanding teams, talent base
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The slogans have been catchy, even if the quality of
basketball has been lacking. But with the demise of a rival league
and the arrival of the most acclaimed female collegian ever, the
WNBA can boast a theme this summer that actually might live up to
the hype cranked out by the league's relentless publicity machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Got 'Mique.''
</P>
<P>
   The league hasn't unveiled any such catch phrase, and Chamique
Holdsclaw isn't all that's new as the WNBA tips off its third
season on Thursday. But the four-time Tennessee All-America player
is the pivotal figure in what should be a vastly improved league
that has expanded by two teams to 12 and will add four more next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics bemoan the league as nothing more than the NBA's
summer ladies auxiliary, on the same plane with indoor soccer and
arena football. But the WNBA also includes 36 former American
Basketball League players and a growing contingent of international
stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no more talk about which league is best,'' said
former Georgia Tech star Kisha Ford, who will be in uniform for the
expansion Orlando Miracle on Thursday against the two-time
defending champion Houston Comets (8 p.m., Lifetime). ``We just
have to go out and play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 24 players drafted in the first two rounds, 18 came from
the ABL, which filed for bankruptcy and folded in December.
Holdsclaw, the first pick of the woeful Washington Mystics (3-27)
who signed a seven-figure endorsement deal with Nike, has been an
instant attraction. In an exhibition game against the Comets last
week, Holdsclaw had 20 points, 10 rebounds and six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all this will help us at a time when we recognize that
the novelty of the league has worn off,'' WNBA commissioner Val
Ackerman said. ``Our league is going to stand or fall on the basis
of how good a game we have and how much fans want to come and
support us.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston coach Van Chancellor, whose team faces Holdsclaw again
Saturday, said, ``Everybody in this league is so much better.
There's a great talent improvement. It's going to be a severe
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the league announced it would expand into Miami,
Indiana, Portland and Seattle for the 2000 season. The Atlanta
Hawks want a franchise, but they passed on next season because of
their impending move to the new Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been on our radar screen from Day 1,'' Hawks executive
vice president Lee Douglas said. ``We want to maintain a basketball
presence 12 months out of the year. There is a completely different
audience than what comes to NBA games. It's an enterprise we feel
is worth doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks would be ready to go in 2001, but Ackerman said the
WNBA hasn't begun to consider future expansion. ``We didn't plan to
expand this quickly,'' she said. ``We need to see how we do in
these new cities, but I believe we will be in Atlanta someday.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional 44 playing slots next year were the result of an
agreement with the NBA Players Association, which represented WNBA
veterans. After a brief standoff, the two sides settled on raising
the minimum salary to $25,000 for rookies and capping the number of
ABL veterans at three per team. Players also get year-round health,
maternity and dental benefits and a share of WNBA merchandise
royalties.
</P>
<P>
   For ABL refugees like Kedra Holland-Corn, whose original league
had an average salary of $80,000, the cut in pay has prompted major
changes. The former University of Georgia guard is seeking playing
opportunities in Brazil or Europe in the winter. It's a route taken
by her Sacramento Monarchs teammate, ex-Georgia star Lady Hardmon,
who has played four seasons in Italy, Turkey and Hungary, and Ford,
who played in Sweden last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay for your housing, your utility bills and your
benefits,'' Holland-Corn, a second-round draft pick, said. ``It's a
$50,000 job when you add it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABL, which played in the fall and winter, went under after 2
1/2 seasons. Crowds were small, but the ABL claimed in its suit
that the WNBA used its muscle to prevent them from making
television and corporate sponsorship deals. The WNBA isn't
commenting on the allegations, which are being investigated by
attorneys general in five states.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
