<HEADLINE>
GENERALS MEET AGAIN ON WITHDRAWAL OF KOSOVO FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ Two days after a first round of talks
ended in deadlock, NATO and Yugoslav generals met here again
Tuesday night to discuss the withdrawal of Yugoslav and Serbian
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav delegation _ mostly the same officers who took part
in the earlier meetings _ arrived just after 9 p.m. local time in a
column of vehicles escorted by NATO liaison officers and Macedonian
police officials. The talks are being held in a hangar in the
center of a muddy French helicopter base in northeastern Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, a Briton who is to lead the NATO
security force in Kosovo, arrived minutes later by helicopter. But
the Yugoslavs spent the next several hours in a small trailer
reviewing changes proposed to them in the six-page military
agreement they rejected only a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Three senior members of the Yugoslav delegation, including its
leader, Col. Gen. Svetozar Marjanovic, deputy chief of the army's
general staff, left the talks at 1 a.m. to cross into Yugoslavia
and consult with officials in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, over
secure telephone lines. They returned an hour later and the talks
continued.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials, who say they are not negotiating with the
Yugoslavs, said there had been only ``small technical changes'' in
the agreement they proposed after the talks failed on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one American military officer has been meeting with
the Yugoslavs since the talks collapsed: Lt. Gen. Robert Foglesong,
a military adviser to Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott,
held meetings with the Yugoslavs Monday and Tuesday, NATO officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   An allied official who took part in the weekend talks said the
completion of a draft resolution for the U.N. Security Council by
the major industrial nations and Russia increased the allies'
leverage here. But he said it would not resolve NATO's specific
role in a security force, the issue the Yugoslav officers cited
when they rejected the allies' terms over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The official warned that the Yugoslav officers could again
refuse to agree to the details of the withdrawal in the hope of
forcing the issue on the Security Council, where Russia and China
could insist on terms more favorable to Yugoslavia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
