<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OFFICER CONVICTED, 3 ACQUITTED OF TORTURING HAITIAN IMMIGRANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: A full version of this story will move by 10 p.m. ET)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One police officer was convicted on Tuesday of
joining in the torture of Abner Louima in a Brooklyn station house,
but three others were acquitted in the case, which transformed an
unknown Haitian immigrant into a national symbol of police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   The convicted officer, Charles Schwarz, was found guilty of
violating Louima's civil rights by holding him down while another
officer, Justin Volpe, rammed a stick into his rectum in the
station house bathroom. Volpe pleaded guilty to the charges against
him two weeks ago and is awaiting final sentencing while in
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Two officers, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese, were acquitted of
charges that they helped beat up Louima in a patrol car while
transporting him from a street brawl to the 70th precinct station
house. Sgt. Michael Bellomo, was acquitted of trying to cover up
the beating of Louima in the car and a separate assault by Volpe on
a second Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine. When the verdict
against him was announced in a packed federal courtroom in
Brooklyn, after an anonymous jury of seven men and five women had
deliberated for 18 hours, Schwarz, 33, initially stared straight
ahead and showed no reaction at all. But before being taken into
custody, Schwarz appeared to be glaring at the federal prosecutors
in the case, and his reaction to the verdict was one of
``disbelief, shock, rage,'' said his attorney, Stephen C. Worth.
Schwarz could be sentenced to as much as life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Worth, who said his client would appeal the verdict, said part
of the grounds for the appeal would be that the case was tainted by
the dramatic confession of Volpe who admitted two weeks ago that he
rammed the stick into Louima in order to humiliate him. In that
confession, which occurred outside the presence of the jury, Volpe
did not implicate any other officer by name.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's plea on May 25, after three weeks of testimony,
dramatically changed the landscape of the trial, removing the
principal defendant and changing the focus of a prosecution that
had massed its artillery on him. The case against the four other
defendants was far less substantial. It took only two days after
Volpe's plea for the prosecution to conclude its case.
</P>
<P>
   The cases against Schwarz, Bruder and Wiese, who had been free
on $100,000 bail each since their indictments last year, were
largely circumstantial and less solid than the case against Volpe,
though the evidence against Schwarz appeared stronger than against
Wiese and Bruder.
</P>
<P>
   In a pointed attack on the ethics of the prosecution, the
attorney for Volpe criticized the way in which the verdict against
Schwarz was obtained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really disappointed in the fact that Officer Schwarz
was convicted,'' said Marvyn Kornberg, noting that his client
``advised the prosecutors that the other officer in the bathroom
was not Schwarz, but in fact, another officer whose name was given
to them at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters who that officer was, Kornberg refused to
divulge a name. Federal prosecutors angrily dismissed Kornberg's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dare say that neither Volpe nor his attorney have any
credibility with respect to any factual issue touching on this
case, including the identity of the other officer or officers with
him,'' said Alan Vinegrad, one of the prosecutors, referring to
Kornberg's opening argument in the trial. Kornberg had suggested
that Louima might have suffered his internal injuries _ a torn
rectum and bladder - in a a consensual sexual encounter with
another man.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Louima could not identify the officer who he
said held him down during Volpe's attack in the bathroom, but he
said it was done by the same officer who had driven him to the
station house. Police records indicate that Schwarz was the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Two policemen gave major testimony against Schwarz. Detective
Eric Turetzky and Officer Mark Schofield said they saw him walk
Louima, handcuffed and with his pants down, from station house desk
where he was booked on assault charges _ later dropped _ directly
to the bathroom area.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Schwarz, Worth, who vigorously cross-examined
these witnesses, insisted that his client was never in the bathroom
with Louima and that Louima was mistaken in asserting that it was
the driver of the car who held him down. He emphasized that
Turetzky and Schofield had said they saw Schwarz taking Louima
toward the bathroom, but not into it.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese Schwarz and Bruder still face charges of conspiring to
obstruct justice by misleading investigators as to Schwarz's role
in the bathroom torture. Prosecutors point to Wiese's claim that he
saw Volpe alone in the bathroom with Louima.
</P>
</TEXT>
