</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SUPREMECOURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN PICKS WOMAN AS HER FOURTH APPOINTEE TO HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Saying that she intended to create a more
diverse Supreme Court, Gov. Christie Whitman on Tuesday made her
second nomination in four months to the state's highest court,
picking Virginia Long, the presiding judge in the Appellate
Division of Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Long, 57, would become the third woman on the seven-member
court, joining Chief Justice Deborah Poritz, whom Whitman appointed
three years ago, and Justice Marie Garibaldi.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I appointed Judge Poritz it was with an understanding on
my part that I wanted to see more women, qualified women, elevated
and given the opportunity to see what they can do,'' Whitman said.
``I don't have a quota system that there should be three or four,
whatever. But I do seek diversity _ youth, age, all sorts of
diversity on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has used her three previous nominations to appoint the
first woman to be chief justice, Mrs. Poritz; the high court's
first black member, Justice James Coleman, and its youngest member,
Peter Verniero, who turned 40 in April.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman will have the chance to place at least one more person
on the Supreme Court next year because Justice Daniel O'Hern will
reach the mandatory retirement age of 70 on May 30.
</P>
<P>
   With the prospect of appointing at least five justices on the
state's highest court before she leaves office, Whitman has the
opportunity to change not only the demographics of one of the
nation's most respected benches, but also its views on issues from
the fate of death row inmates to the way New Jersey funds its
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the state Senate, Long would replace Justice
Alan Handler, who in his 22 years has established himself as one of
the most liberal voices on the New Jersey Supreme Court. He is the
court's most outspoken opponent of capital punishment and, in
recent years, has taken the lead in rulings involving the long
fight over how rich and poor school districts in the state should
be financed.
</P>
<P>
   No new member of the court would be expected to have the kind of
influence that Justice Handler established. And it is not clear how
Long would vote on an issue like capital punishment; appeals of
death sentences in New Jersey are handled only by the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Long is considered moderate to liberal, court officials who have
worked with her said. But meeting with reporters Tuesday, Long
declined to assign herself a political label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decide the cases based on merits,'' she said. ``I treat
everybody the way I would like to be treated, and I write opinions
that leave no doubt as to what it is that I'm saying and where
exactly I stand. Whether that's liberal or conservative in each
individual case depends on whose ox is being gored.''
</P>
<P>
   Long is a Democrat, as is Handler. By tradition, New Jersey
governors have maintained a balance of Democrats and Republicans
among the six associate justices on the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said Tuesday that she had never queried her choices
about how they would rule on individual issue. ``I don't know, I
don't want to know,'' Whitman told reporters. ``I try to be as
un-litmus-test-oriented as I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Long's nomination comes only a month after the Senate narrowly
confirmed Verniero at the end of a bruising political fight between
Democrats and Whitman that was shaped in some part by the
governor's anticipated run next year for the Republican nomination
for U.S. senator and by the controversy over racial profiling by
the state police.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats, who had criticized Verniero as unqualified to
sit on the Supreme Court, were guarded Tuesday in their comments
about Long. But they seized the opportunity to revive their attacks
on the governor over the earlier nomination and over her decision
not to submit future court nominees to a review panel of the New
Jersey State Bar Association after the group soundly rejected
Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, a unanimous approval for Judge Long would have
highlighted the panel's overwhelming rejection of Peter Verniero
based on his lack of qualifications,'' said state Sen. John Lynch,
the senior Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee, which
reviews nominations to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said again Tuesday that the governor
would not send Long before the Bar Association's review panel, a
practice that New Jersey governors have observed for 30 years, and
one that Whitman followed in her first three nominations. But Long
held out the prospect that she could go before the panel on her
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the governor's decision,'' Long said, ``but she's made
it clear to me that if the Bar Association wants me to appear, it's
fine with her if I do. And if they do ask me to appear, I will be
there on their doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Long was named to the Superior Court in 1978 by Gov. Brendan
Byrne, a Democrat. Six years later, she was named to the Appellate
Division, the level just below the Supreme Court, and in 1995
became a presiding judge.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1978, she was the commissioner of the Department of
Banking in the Byrne administration.
</P>
<P>
   Long served as the director of the state's Division of Consumer
Affairs in 1975 and worked in the state attorney general's office
for three years.
</P>
<P>
   She is a 1966 graduate of Rutgers University Law School and is
married to a lawyer, Jonathan Weiner, and has three children. They
live in Hopewell Township.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said Long had published more than 200 opinions
and has handled about 1,500 cases, many of them involving
matrimonial, divorce and child-care issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a superb choice,'' said Ronald Riccio, dean of
the Seton Hall University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is highly experienced, highly intelligent and has the
respect and admiration of her colleagues on the bench and at the
bar. She is going to approach every case with an open mind, and she
is going to be very well prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
