<SLUG> BC-GORE-SENATORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senators throw support behind Gore
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories.)
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Retired Ohio senator Howard Metzenbaum led a cadre
of former senators Tuesday in endorsing Vice President Al Gore for
president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a basement ballroom at the posh Mayflower Renaissance Hotel,
the group of 10 former senators jovially confronted perceptions of
Gore as stiff and bland in an endorsement rally focused on
reversing the negative implications of that image rather than
disputing it
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things that happen in public life that are dramatic are
not good governance,'' said former senator Mike Gravel of Alaska.
``Al Gore is very competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Howell Heflin of Alabama, who supported Gore before he teamed
with President Clinton in 1988, said that while the ``elitist
media'' has branded Gore wooden, that characterization isn't
entirely bad since it conveys stability and strength. And he said
Gore will be plenty colorful when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out he is a terrific campaigner,'' Heflin boomed,
``and don't sell him short on hitting the campaign trail and
getting people to vote for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen former senators endorsed the Gore campaign Tuesday,
though only half made it to the hotel event. Those who did stressed
Gore's experience as a former member of the House and Senate,
arguing as Metzenbaum did that ``there is no person better trained
to be President.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore faces a primary challenge by another former senator, Bill
Bradley of New Jersey. But the Mayflower gathering seemed targeted
at Gore's standing in the general election where polls say he would
be an underdog to the Republican's front-running candidate, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the debates come, you'll see the difference,'' between
Gore and his opponents, said Wendell Ford of Kentucky. ``When the
debates come that'll separate them pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Montgomery writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
