<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-550&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROOMING A SERIOUS CHALLENGER TO LOCAL LATE-NIGHT NEWS  
 BY JOHN CARMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When they think about local TV news at PBS, they
wince and picture a live remote shot of a bubbleheaded reporter
standing in a pool of blood.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, a grossly unfair depiction. Many local TV
reporters are not bubbleheaded.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea is that PBS' commercial cousins are steeped in gore
rather than ``serious'' news, and the people who bring you
``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer'' want to do something about it.
MacNeil-Lehrer Productions is reviving plans to assemble a national
newscast at 11 p.m. weekdays, without the low comedy of local news.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no one at that hour of the day who's providing
responsible national and international coverage,'' says
``NewsHour'' executive producer Les Crystal, in San Francisco for
this week's annual PBS meeting. ``It gets extremely short shrift on
local news. It's been a vacuum for ages.''
</P>
<P>
   A vacuum that MacNeil-Lehrer Productions hopes to fill with a
nightly 30-minute newscast in partnership with the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The program would tap into the Times for the expertise of its
correspondents in a hard-news broadcast summarizing the day's news
and peeking at what the next day's news is likely to be.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Werner, president of MacNeil-Lehrer Productions, says the
news program would be a tidy lead-in to the nightly Charlie Rose
talk show on many PBS stations.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds sensible. Admirable, even. But this is PBS, and
nothing at PBS is built in a day. In fact, some things never get
built at all.
</P>
<P>
   There's the usual problem of underwriting. Werner concedes that
not a dime is committed to the program yet, and it would take six
to eight months to get on the air even after the project is fully
funded.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the vagaries of PBS' byzantine system of
scheduling, and station clearances, and differing notions about
priorities, and petty jealousies, and public TV pooh-bahs guarding
their fiefdoms like medieval lords.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it's not outside the emotional repertoire of
someone else providing news and public affairs programming at PBS
to question why MacNeil-Lehrer should be awarded more airtime than
it already has.
</P>
<P>
   And I get the feeling that there is, inside PBS, some polite ire
over a perception that MacNeil-Lehrer is pushing a little too hard,
a little too early and possibly a little too publicly.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little like a professor buying billboard space and
commercial airtime to campaign for tenure.
</P>
<P>
   (For the record, Crystal was in town for an unrelated panel
discussion at the PBS meeting. He and Werner didn't seek out
publicity.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's a bit premature to have this out of the box,''
said John Wilson, who's been on the job only a few weeks as PBS'
acting head of programming.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said there is, so far, no more than ``anecdotal''
evidence that an audience exists for an 11 p.m. PBS newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Also, where would the newscast be based? New York, home of the
Times? Or Washington, home of ``NewsHour''? And, sure, there are
possible problems with stations clearing the time.
</P>
<P>
   It's advisable, Wilson said, to regard the proposed newscast as
``a work in progress'' and not a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But even as he was flinging pails of water onto the plan, Wilson
allowed himself a little wistfulness over the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are, after all, MacNeil-Lehrer Productions,'' he said of
the company that generates TV's straightest, most informative
newscast.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Wilson added, ``a few people might have heard of this
thing called the New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Other news from the PBS annual meeting:
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Megan Follows will return to star in a third ``Anne of Green
Gables'' miniseries, this one called ``The Continuing Story.'' Odd
that the announcement would be made in San Francisco. PBS said, in
rejecting ``More Tales of the City'' a few years ago, that it
doesn't do sequels.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Crystal said PBS would forge ahead with its own political
convention coverage next year without NBC News, its partner in 1992
and 1996. NBC broke off with PBS because it now has the MSNBC cable
news channel.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Crystal also said ``NewsHour'' anchor Jim Lehrer hoped to
entice the major presidential candidates next year into a series of
joint conversations about the issues. This would be separate from
the formal presidential debates, Crystal said, and presumably less
adversarial.
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Mike Sullivan, executive producer of ``Frontline,'' said
that program was preparing a four-part series examining the federal
government's war on drugs. Sullivan said ``Frontline'' also was
considering ``a big takeout on the Clinton administration at its
end, trying to figure out what (set ital)was(end ital) that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; PBS is planning to use high-profile voice talent for its
documentary series ``The American President,'' scheduled to
premiere in April. Providing George Washington's voice: Walter
Cronkite. And giving voice to Herbert Hoover will be former  &LR; Sen.
 &LR; Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
