<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-BNY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM TO BUY BANK OF NEW YORK COMMERCIAL LENDING UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. agreed Tuesday to buy the Bank of
New York's commercial lending unit for $1.8 billion as the
automaker diversified its holdings and the bank continued to
specialize its operations.
</P>
<P>
   GM's lending unit, General Motors Acceptance Corp., said it
would add BNY Financial Corp. and its affiliates as a new unit by
the end of the month. ``We're buying this for growth,'' said
William Muir, GMAC's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``While auto finance remains our core and our largest business,
it is a mature business, just like the automobile business is a
mature business,'' Muir said. ``We've had to look at nonautomotive
opportunities for growth.'' The new subsidiary will be called GMAC
Commercial Credit Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Tuesday risked the ire of the United
Automobile Workers union, which has opposed automakers' past
attempts to diversify.
</P>
<P>
   For the bank, the deal fit a pattern of concentrating on
fee-based operations while selling off other businesses. It sold
the last of its credit card operations to Chase Manhattan Bank in
October 1997 and it announced in March that it would buy a
pension-fund services company, RBS Trust Bank, from the Royal Bank
of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction further advances our overall strategy, which
is to focus on our higher-growth fee-based activities, including
securities servicing, cash processing and fiduciary services,''
said Thomas Renyi, the chairman and chief executive of the Bank of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the unit's sale would dilute earnings by 2 percent
to 3 percent this year but would pay off later.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of New York said that it would have a pretax gain of
$1.1 billion on the deal and that it planned to buy back 30 million
of its shares with the proceeds. Since December 1998, the bank has
bought back about 18 million shares. Its shares rose $2.375
Tuesday, to $37.0625, while GM fell $1.375, to $67.75.
</P>
<P>
   For GM, the deal has the opposite effect. Buying the customers
and staff of the nation's largest asset-based lending and factoring
business has nothing to do with cars or car loans. Both asset-based
lending and factoring are specialized forms of business lending.
</P>
<P>
   Asset-based lenders make secured loans to companies that cannot
otherwise readily borrow from commercial banks or the debt market.
Such loans are often used for inventory financing or equipment
financing, with the inventory or equipment serving as collateral
for the loans. Lenders typically charge 2 percent to 4 percent
above prime lending rates for the credit.
</P>
<P>
   In factoring, which is common in the textile industry, a
financial institution buys a company's accounts receivable,
immediately paying the company what a third party owes it. In
exchange for the payment, the company effectively pays the factor a
high interest rate on the money. The financial institution then
assumes the risk while collecting what is owed to the first
company.
</P>
<P>
   Muir said the strategy was to make commercial lending GMAC's
fourth major business. The auto finance unit generated $984 million
of the $1.33 billion GMAC earned last year, with its insurance
business accounting for $226 million of the profits and its
mortgage business generating $115 million. Since the early 1990s,
GMAC had concentrated on expanding its mortgage and insurance
business, and it planned to do the same for the commercial finance
business. GMAC accounted for nearly a third of GM's net income of
$2.96 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Muir declined to disclose details, he said the new
business would start out smaller than GMAC's $115-million-a-year
mortgage business. But he said GMAC would try to expand the
business internationally by expanding its British unit to the
European market.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which is expected to be approved by antitrust
regulators, will not lead to layoffs at the Bank of New York unit,
which has 900 employees, or at GMAC, which already has a small
factoring and asset-backed lending arm, Muir said. He expected the
new unit to post a return on earnings this year of 14 percent to 15
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
