<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BEN HOGAN ROOM SPEAKS WELL FOR A QUIET MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAR HILLS, N.J. _ As she walked around the Ben Hogan Room from
one exhibit to another, Valerie Hogan seemed to be reliving their
62 years together. Here were her husband's trophies, his awards,
his 1953 irons in a leather golf bag, his books, even the sports
jackets and shirts that were in his locker at the Shady Oaks
Country Club near their Fort Worth, Texas, home when he died in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In her soft blue suit, the white-haired Valerie Hogan suddenly
stopped to gather herself emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized what I was seeing and I realized he was not here,''
she would say later. ``I would give anything if he could be here
even if I were not here. Just for him to see this beautiful room
and to know that people appreciate his contribution to golf.''
</P>
<P>
   In other years, the United States Golf Association created
separate rooms for two other golfers, Bobby Jones and Francis
Ouimet, at its museum here at Golf House, but they were amateurs.
Ben Hogan is the first professional golfer so honored.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Hogan's trophies and memorabilia were on display at
the Colonial Country Club in Fort Worth, but after two burglaries
there, he changed his will, granting them to Golf House where,
beginning Wednesday, they will be on display, free of charge. ``The
burglaries made us realize we needed to put them in a safer
place,'' Valerie Hogan said. ``When we made our last will, it
wasn't that Ben was ill. We wanted to get that changed.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who remembers when Ben Hogan was the world's best
golfer, the exhibit is a treasure. Here is the 1-iron he hit to the
18th green at the 1950 U.S. Open at Merion, Pa., to force an
18-hole playoff with Lloyd Mangrum and George Fazio that he won the
next day, 18 months after his legs were shattered in his Cadillac's
head-on collision with a bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The night before that last round,'' Valerie Hogan said, ``he
was so tired, I didn't think he would be able to play the next
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the the gold Hickok Belt he was awarded as the
Associated Press male athlete of the year in 1953, when he won the
Masters, the U.S. Open and the British Open _ the only golfer to
win those three major titles in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want to go to the British Open,'' Valerie Hogan
said. ``He kept saying, `I just think you want me to go over there
to see me get beat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Here are his four USGA gold medals for winning the United States
Open in 1948, 1950, 1951 and 1953. Nearby is a similar gold USGA
medal for winning the 1942 Hale America National Open, a World War
II substitute for that year's canceled United States Open. With
6,519 entries as well as local and sectional qualifying, it had the
atmosphere of a United States Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medal for the Hale America Open is the exact same medal
with the USGA seal that Ben received when he won the U.S. Open the
other four years,'' Valerie Hogan said. ``He always thought it was
unfair for the PGA to count Byron Nelson's PGA Championship in 1942
with a smaller field, and for the USGA not to count the 1942 Hale
America Open that he won.''
</P>
<P>
   In that Hale America Open at Ridgemoor outside Chicago, Hogan,
with a second-round 62 in a 17-under-par 271, won by three strokes
over Jimmy Demaret and Mike Turnesa. Nelson finished fourth. If the
USGA counted that wartime Open as a United States Open, Hogan would
hold the record with five instead of sharing the record with Jack
Nicklaus and Bobby Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you look on the back of that medal,'' said David Fay,
the USGA executive director, ``it says, `Hale America Open,' not
`United States Open.'''
</P>
<P>
   And over here in the exhibit is the sound of Ben Hogan's voice,
firm and precise, for about 10 minutes, as recorded in a 1951
interview by Si Burick of The Dayton (Ohio) News:
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, concentration is the business side of golf. Swinging
the golf club is incidental. I won more tournaments playing badly
than I ever did playing good. I try to outwork 'em and I try to
outmanage 'em. The shots I miss, they don't bother me because I
anticipate those. You're lucky if you hit three shots that you
actually like in 18 holes.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear that voice is a bonus because when Ben Hogan was
playing, he was more of a listener than a talker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben liked to say that people who talk all the time don't learn
anything,'' Valerie Hogan said. ``You have to listen; that's when
you learn. Believe me, he listened.''
</P>
<P>
   And he learned so much, Golf House created a room for him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
