u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-CANTY-BOS &LR;      06-08 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-CANTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CUT CANTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ After two seasons of trying to make something of
their former No. 1 draft choice, the Patriots decided to cut their
losses by cutting Chris Canty.
</P>
<P>
   Canty made his mark not for his play at cornerback, where he was
an occasional nickel back and briefly a starter of minimal impact,
but rather for his impromptu dancing after what he perceived to be
big plays. More than a few times they were in response to a tackle
after a pass completion, a show of bad judgment that fans,
teammates, and coaches wondered about from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree it was that judgment, or lack of it, that led to
his dismissal three days before the opening of the final offseason
minicamp. Canty, who had been only an occasional participant in the
team's offseason conditioning program, failed to hold a starting
position last season after one was opened up for him with the trade
of Jimmy Hitchcock to the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Canty started the first nine games but was replaced by Steve
Israel as soon as Israel was healthy enough to return to the field;
he missed the first half of the season with a recurring knee
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Canty compounded the mounting case against him when he was
arrested last season after police found him asleep in his Mercedes
at a gas station at 2 a.m., some six hours before he was to have
been at practice, with a container of an alcoholic beverage in the
car. Like most things that were near Canty during his two years in
New England, the container was open.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made Canty their No. 1 pick in 1997, the 29th
overall selection. It was the first pick made solely by vice
president of personnel Bobby Grier, and it was not a good one. To
take him, New England passed up a cornerback with better size,
speed, and skill: Louisville's Sam Madison, who went on to become a
starter last year in his second season with the Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Canty, meanwhile, continued to be plagued by a lack of
explosiveness. Lacking size (5 feet 9 inches on tiptoes, 185
pounds) and the speed undersized corners need to survive in the
NFL, Canty simply could not stay with the game's great receivers
and was further hampered by the fact that guys such as Keyshawn
Johnson towered over him.
</P>
<P>
   But the final straw for the Patriots was his lack of commitment
to the offseason fitness program and a laissez-faire attitude in
general toward his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy was given a tremendous opportunity last year,'' said
Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``We made a commitment to Chris last
year and he didn't take advantage of the opportunity. When you add
everything up, it was time to let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Symptomatic of Canty's attitude was the fact that when Carroll
went to cut him, the coach had to find him by phone because he was
not at the team's complex Tuesday, as many other players were. This
had been the case for much of the offseason after Canty claimed to
have suffered a rash caused by a reaction to the team's laundry.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same laundry worn by every other player in attendance,
none of whom seemed to break out in hives at the thought of
strength and conditioning coach Johnny Parker's regimented
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Rash actions and, finally, a rash itself spelled the end for
Canty after just two seasons in New England. It was a short run for
a short man at a position not long on patience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have begun to search the league discount table.
Tuesday they brought in former Giants No. 1 draft choice Derek
Brown, a tight end who had seven receptions for 89 yards last
season in Oakland after spending the previous two seasons as an
occasional starter in Jacksonville. On Thursday, they will take a
look at running back Harold Green, who rushed for 37 yards on 20
carries for the Falcons last year. Green is a nine-year veteran who
began his career in Cincinnati, where he played six seasons and was
a 1992 Pro Bowl selection after rushing for 1,170 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
