<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-REACT-NYT &LR;      06-08 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBORHOOD RESIDENTS CALL LOUIMA VERDICT NEITHER OUTRAGE NOR
TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
  (With LOUIMA-TRIAL, LOUIMA-ASSESS)  
 (bl)  
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Oprah Winfrey show was interrupted by a news
bulletin announcing the verdict in the Abner Louima trial,
Charmaine Dreckette took a quick break from washing a customer's
hair in the back of St. Cecile's Unisex Salon on Church Avenue in
Brooklyn and turned up the volume.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four police officers charged with violating the civil
rights of Louima, a Haitian immigrant, was convicted, she learned.
And her own verdict was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``All four of them, I feel, are guilty,'' declared Ms.
Dreckette, 29, an immigrant from Jamaica. ``All of them should go
to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on a barber's chair up front, Eddie Joseph, 35, said he
was neither surprised nor entirely unhappy to learn that the jury
had convicted only Charles Schwarz, the officer charged with
holding Louima down while another officer, Justin Volpe, sodomized
him with a stick. Volpe pleaded guilty May 25, midway through the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph, a Haitian immigrant who drops in to chat with
friends at St. Cecile's on his way home from his job as a cook in
Manhattan, said that what really angered him was the suggestion by
Volpe's lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, that the injuries suffered by
Louima were not the result of the attack, but of a consensual sex
act.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair enough,'' Joseph, 35, said, speaking of the verdict.
``But my only question is about this lawyer _ coming out and saying
this was a gay nightclub, saying this was a consensual thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The voices in this barbershop were much like the voices
throughout Flatbush, the heart of Caribbean Brooklyn, as news of
the verdict trickled in Tuesday. There were many who regarded a
partial conviction as patently unfair, but their emotions were
nowhere as hot as the late afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Life seemed to go on as usual in this dense strip of roti
take-outs and money transfer shops. People sat in their doorways,
trying to catch an afternoon breeze, and mothers braided their
children's hair under the shade of sidewalk trees. Women sold
plastic bags of cloves and cinnamon on the street, and police cars
circled the streets.
</P>
<P>
   At the studios of Radio Soleil, a Haitian radio station housed
inside a Nostrand Avenue storefront, Ricot Dupuy, the manager, said
the verdict carried a certain sense of vindication. ``It's clear
that Abner Louima has been vindicated in the sense that nobody can
say the man fabricated the story,'' he said. ``I take comfort in
the fact that you can't call this a brutal miscarriage of justice:
two of five people were found guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mood among Haitians, Dupuy said the handful of people
who had been calling into the station Tuesday afternoon did not
believe that only two policemen could have been responsible for a
crime so brutal. Still, they seemed to share his own lukewarm sense
of satisfaction. ``They were hoping all four of them would be
convicted,'' he said, ``but they never expected it to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, up and down the commercial corridors of Flatbush, many
people said that while Volpe and Schwarz might have been the chief
malefactors, the other officers must have known, and perhaps aided,
in the torture of Louima in a bathroom at the 70th Precinct station
house, just blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you abuse somebody, you need punishment for that,'' a
neighborhood resident, France Frank, said as she stopped off to
talk with a friend selling bags of cinnamon and cloves on the
sidewalk. ``I'm not  &UR; angry &LR;  angry. I'm interested in justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Deslande Rincher, the owner of a Creole-language bookshop on
Church Avenue, reserved his dismay for the acquittal of Sgt.
Michael Bellomo, who was accused of covering up the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a supervisor, he is aware of what's going on,'' said
Rincher, 52, of Rosedale, Queens. ''You can call it partial
justice. Since the guy pleaded guilty _ Volpe _ we were under the
impression they were going to use his guilty plea to prove the
other guys did it, especially the sergeant and Schwarz.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a coin laundry down the street, where televisions blasted
cartoons rather than the news, Enlil El, 26, likened Bellomo's
plight to that of a parent held responsible for a child's
wrongdoing. It was the two other officers on trial, Thomas Bruder
and Thomas Wiese, who were accused of beating Louima in a police
car, who should have been convicted, he said. To him, the verdict
was unfair, but understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's head had to roll,'' he said, referring to the two
officers, against whom he believed prosecutors had mounted the
strongest evidence. ``They could not let an acquittal go for the
whole party. You'd have a whole riot going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
