<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-ADVISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDES SAY CHOICE IS NEAR FOR WHITE HOUSE ECONOMIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House officials said Tuesday that President
Clinton would most likely nominate Martin Baily, a partner at
McKinsey &AMP; Co., to succeed Janet Yellen later this year as head of
the Council of Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they hoped to move swiftly to fill
the job, which is effectively that of the president's chief
economist. Ms. Yellen plans to leave this summer to return to
teaching at the University of California at Berkeley after having
served two years in the White House and three years before that as
a Federal Reserve governor.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they had asked Ms. Yellen to consider returning
to the Fed to replace Alice Rivlin, the central bank's vice
chairwoman, who said last week that she would resign, effective
next month. But they said Ms. Yellen was intent on joining her
husband, George Akerlof, who is also a prominent economist, in
returning to their home and teaching jobs in California.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had said on Monday that Ms. Yellen
intended to resign. In formally announcing her decision Tuesday
night, Clinton said in a statement that her ``extraordinary
intellect and keen grasp of domestic and international economics''
had contributed to a wide range of administration initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Economic Advisers has had widely varying degrees
of influence in different administrations, and under Clinton has
taken a backseat to the National Economic Council, which
coordinates policy-making across Cabinet departments and agencies.
Ms. Yellen was the third person to hold the post under Clinton,
following Laura D'Andrea Tyson and Joseph Stiglitz.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said there had not been a final
decision on nominating Baily, who served as one of the three
members of the Council of Economic Advisers in 1995 and 1996. But
they said he was very likely to get the post. Baily did not return
a phone call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
