Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PLYMOUTH, Montserrat -- June 8, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JUNE 13 --MONTSERRAT-VOLCANO-COX-1, 6-8 -- Once the island's main
center, Plymouth is now a ghost town where up to 10 feet of ash and
rock from the Soufriere Hills volcano have buried or destroyed all
of the town's buildings as seen in this photo taken earlier this
month. For decades Montserrat was dubbed the Emerald Isle. The
reference was, in part, a nod to the tropical lushness that for
years attracted upscale tourists. But all that changed in July 1995
when Montserrat's long-smoldering volcano blew its stack. (Rick
McKay/Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
