<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      06-08 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: JURORS ACCEPT ONLY SOME OF OF LOUIMA ALLEGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (with LOUIMA-TRIAL, LOUIMA-REACT)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two weeks ago, when Officer Justin Volpe pleaded
guilty to putting a stick into Abner Louima's rectum, prosecutors
believed they had been given what they needed to convict other
police officers accused of violating Louima's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's plea dramatically bolstered Louima's credibility as a
victim of police brutality, and so prosecutors devoted much of
their closing arguments to a detailed retelling of Volpe's assault
in the bathroom of a Brooklyn station house. ``It shows that Abner
Louima was telling the truth,'' Alan Vinegrad, an assistant U.S.
attorney, told jurors last week.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors thought Louima's credibility would extend beyond the
bathroom, that jurors would accept his account of how Volpe and
three other officers beat him before he arrived at the station
house.
</P>
<P>
   They thought wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By their verdict Tuesday, jurors demonstrated their
unwillingness to take Louima at his word _ even knowing that his
most chilling tale of police brutality was no longer in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   While convicting Officer Charles Schwarz of restraining Louima
during the bathroom assault, jurors exonerated Schwarz and two
other officers _ Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder _ of assaulting
Louima in a police car on the way to the 70th Precinct station
house.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Zachary Carter said the verdict underscored what
prosecutors have long feared about police misconduct cases: that it
is ``historically difficult'' to win convictions ``where the only
witnesses to the assault are the victims themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   It was significant, he said, that jurors returned guilty
verdicts only where Louima's testimony was supported by the
testimony of other police officers from the 70th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Four officers gave damaging testimony against Volpe, describing
how he boasted of ``breaking'' a man and how he brandished the
feces-covered stick throughout the precinct house. Two of those
same four officers also testified that they saw Schwarz lead Louima
toward the bathroom just before the assault.
</P>
<P>
   But not a single officer backed Louima's account of being beaten
in a squad car, and Carter suggested that more must be done to
change ``the belief system'' of officers who, he said, think that
testifying against another officer _ violating the blue wall of
silence _ is the ultimate act of disloyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for Wiese and Bruder drew entirely different
lessons from the verdict. They said it showed that jurors saw what
they had argued for weeks: that Louima, the victim of a singular
act of depravity, then inflated his allegations to implicate as
many officers as possible, thereby drawing attention and support
from those who believe the Police Department fosters a culture of
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, though, Tuesday's verdict failed to vindicate either
of the two great themes that clashed throughout the four-week
trial: was Abner Louima the victim of a sick police culture, or
merely of one sick police officer?
</P>
<P>
   For years, these questions have been central to the debate about
the New York Police Department, and they surfaced again from the
moment Louima first recounted the attack he endured on Aug. 9,
1997, after a night of dancing in a Brooklyn nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people marched on City Hall, claiming Louima as the
latest victim of an out-of-control Police Department. At the same
time, Police Commissioner Howard Safir called the assault an
aberration, and he said it was a ``myth'' that abusive officers
were protected by a wall of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, these same two arguments were repeated by
prosecutors and defense lawyers, so much so that at times the
arguments seemed like echoes of past public forums on the Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if one were to flip through the 1994 Mollen Commission
report on corruption in the New York Police Department, one would
find each of the major points stressed by the prosecutors in the
Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   The Mollen Commission found that officers frequently used
unnecessary force ``to administer what they believed was street
justice'' and then covered up their brutality by falsely charging
victims with resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad told jurors that Louima was the victim of ``street
justice,'' and he said the officers ``trumped up'' phony charges of
resisting arrest against Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, defense lawyers called Louima the victim of a single
officer acting out his ``sick rage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This case has been tried to be made into this culture of
police brutality, and it never was,'' Stephen Worth, a lawyer for
Schwarz, told jurors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
