<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT &LR;      06-08 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA PLAYERS LEARN THAT LABOR STRESS IS GENDER BLIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LENA WILLIAMS and JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The players union of the Women's National Basketball Association
overwhelmingly ratified a labor contract last month, the first in
women's professional team sports in the United States. The players
won increased salaries, year-round health coverage, including
maternity leave, a matching 401(k) program and limited job security
for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the WNBA players agree that the process of insuring
labor peace and jobs for the next four years was a lot rougher than
they expected.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three months of bargaining revealed an inexperienced
union at odds with itself, its leadership and management, insecure
in the knowledge that it stood to lose as much as it might gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As women basketball players, we weren't really experienced in
dealing with things like the union, the league and collective
bargaining,'' said the Houston Comets' Cynthia Cooper, the league's
two-time most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   But the union also faced an issue it could not control: 90
fellow pros were out of work because the rival American Basketball
League had folded in late December. As the WNBA prepared for its
third season, the pros no longer had the option of playing in
another American league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no bargaining power,'' said Rebecca Lobo, the Liberty
forward and a member of the negotiating committee. ``As soon as the
ABL folded, we had no leverage. ``We went in there and just tried
to get the best thing we could get. And I think we did a good
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The union wanted to limit the number of ABL players allowed into
the WNBA, while the league wanted no restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely difficult because we had to continually
justify, not only to ourselves, but to our friends in the ABL and
the public, the general position that we took,'' said Coquese
Washington, the Liberty forward who emerged as one of the most
vocal player representatives. ``As a union that organized before
the ABL folded, we had a constituency that had issues to be met,
and job security was an issue before the ABL went under.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the WNBA expansion teams in Orlando and Minnesota
were allowed to have five ABL players each. The other 10 WNBA teams
were limited to three each, either as draftees or free agents.
After this season, there will be no limit on signing ABL players
and in 2000 four more teams will join the league, creating an
additional 44 jobs for players.
</P>
<P>
   Other bumps in the negotiations were predictable once the women
voted last November to align themselves with the National
Basketball Players Association. By the time the women started
negotiating their contract with the league, the NBPA had just ended
its contentious labor dispute with the National Basketball
Association, which owns and operates the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feared being shut down all together and alienating fans of
the league,'' said Lisa Leslie, the star center for the Los Angeles
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Given the tangential concerns _ plus the players' labor
inexperience _ their mistakes were inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who are new at collective bargaining always make
mistakes,'' said Richard Hurd, professor of labor studies at
Cornell University. ``If you're negotiating an established
contract, then you go over every word and see if you can improve
it. With a first agreement, things slip by.''
</P>
<P>
   The union, for example, did not raise the issue of how players
from the ABL would be classified upon joining the league. Union
leaders assumed the players would be considered veterans, which
would entitle them to be paid at a higher scale. The league viewed
them as rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute was one of a handful of issues that on April 22 led
to the collapse of an agreement in principle reached between the
league and the union eight days earlier. What happened next caught
the union off guard: the league issued a news release accusing the
union of reneging on key terms of the agreement and making new
economic demands. It also postponed the April 27 draft.
</P>
<P>
   When the WNBA made those announcements, the union's top three
officials were out of town. Some of the players learned of the
developments in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   A small but vocal group of players made it clear to the
negotiating committee that they weren't prepared to walk out over a
few lingering contract demands. Among the issues was a league
stipulation that players would not be allowed to play for the
season if they had not signed a contract by May 14, the start of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the draft was canceled, that really caught my eye,'' said
Nikki McCray, a guard for the Washington Mystics. ``That's when
everybody just got together and said, `Look, what's at the table
right now is not worth us losing our season.' We didn't want to
start the season with negative energy from our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The players said they were hearing one thing from the union, and
reading another from management.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew which side to listen to,'' said Rhonda Blades,
who plays for the Mystics. ``I would listen to the conference
calls, but it was hard to know who to trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players also had a hard time trusting the union leader they
inherited: Billy Hunter, the head of the NBPA, who played an
integral role in organizing the women but was better known for his
role in the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seen, or at least, I was characterized as being somewhat
of an impediment to the negotiations,'' said Hunter, who
participated in only a half-dozen negotiating sessions. ``I felt it
was incumbent on my part, and probably in the best interest of the
women, to remove myself from the scene. So while I was involved, I
just wasn't out front.''
</P>
<P>
   But his conspicuous absence led to accusations, from some
players and advocates of women's pro sports, that he was neglecting
the women.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said he was briefed on everything that took place. By the
time he appointed Pamela M. Wheeler as director of operations for
the WNBA players association on March 30, most of the groundwork
for the contract was already in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to the women to have a woman there,'' Hunter
said about Wheeler during the final stages of negotiations, which
also involved Valerie B. Ackerman, the WNBA's commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't operating in a vacuum,'' Wheeler said. ``I was armed,
not only with the necessary tools from Billy, but his confidence in
my ability to help arrive at a bargaining agreement. We also had
extremely competent attorneys from the NBPA''
</P>
<P>
   Yet others were disappointed in the players' decision to accept
the men's union. The Women's Coaches Association, which has 4,500
members in the collegiate and professional ranks, felt it could do
more to champion the needs and concerns of the women of the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not up on the personalities of women's basketball,
the coaches, the players, not just the athletes but the movers and
shakers of the game,'' Beth Bass, executive director of the Women's
Basketball Coaches Association, said about the men's union. ``This
is the very thing our association was worried about. You get people
involved that don't understand the history of game, and especially
the women's game. The men's game is different from the women,
especially in development.''
</P>
<P>
   And as a new union, the women were completely dependent upon the
men of the NBA for funding and staff. The women didn't have the
luxury of holding out with the men footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the logistics of briefing 132 athletes, some playing
overseas, and facing a deadline imposed by a season timed to the
NBA's off season, the union said it was proud reaching an agreement
in less than four months and walking away with something to please
most, if not all.
</P>
<P>
   Next time around, however, the players hope to do things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Lobo would like to get rid of some of the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have six or seven lawyers on each side involved,''
Lobo said, ``you're in for a lot of, `What does this word mean?'
The negotiations would have been good, if you had a player, who
really had a good handle on things, a bright attorney with Val and
a bright attorney with the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, Lobo suggested, would be a change in scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three years, when we have to renegotiate, we should all go
out on a golf course and get the deal done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
