<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE: OTHER STATES CHALLENGE FOR POSITION 
LOUISIANA: BOTH SIDES ENDORSE BUSH 
MINNESOTA: JESSE TO GO THE DISTANCE, AS GOVERNOR
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.H., Del., Mich., S.C. La., Texas., Kan., Ariz., Idaho,
Mont., Nev., N.M., Minn.)  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new War Between the States _ the competition to schedule the
first Election 2000 primary or caucus _ is escalating.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire House will take up a bill today that, if it
becomes law, will allow the Granite State to hold its primary as
early as December of this year.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has held the first primary for decades, of course,
by tradition and, for that matter, by law. A state statute requires
that New Hampshirites must vote first, by at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   And for years New Hampshirites did vote first, usually around
Feb. 1, give or take a week or two.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Delaware, wanting some of the political glory
for itself. It adopted a rule that says its primary must fall four
days after the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   The war was on, and continues with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by national party officials to stop it, either through
mediation or threats of sanctions, have gone nowhere. In fact, the
war is spreading as more and more states advance their primary and
caucus dates in an effort to grab political attention and
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, Michigan moved its Republican primary date up to
Feb. 22, from March 21, a shift meant to put the state among the
first half a dozen or so to vote. Not to be outdone, South Carolina
Republicans then decided over the weekend to advance their primary
date by a week, to Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolinians figure that unless things change _ and
they very well may _ the new date will make their primary the third
``meaningful'' contest in Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will open it up and we'll be the focus of attention
again,'' Henry McMaster, the chairman of the South Carolina
Republican Party, said after the weekend vote. ``This ensures that
South Carolina will remain the make-or-break state in our
presidential nominating process.''
</P>
<P>
   The first ``meaningful'' contest, if tradition holds, will be
the Iowa caucuses, now scheduled for Feb. 7. For decades they have
been the first of the first, taking place a week before even the
New Hampshire primary, the second ``meaningful'' contest.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Delaware threatens New Hampshire claim to the first
primary, so Louisiana is challenging Iowa's right to hold the first
caucuses. Louisiana Republicans recently passed a resolution that
says their party will caucus first, no matter what Iowa's caucus
date.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Secretary of State Bill Gardner says he favors a
Feb. 14 primary for his state, one that would follow Iowa's
caucuses by the traditional week. He insists he does not want to
call a December primary in order to maintain New Hampshire's
decades-old position in the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   But if Delaware election officials persist with their
four-days-later plan, he warns, he will, with legislative approval,
try to thwart them by scheduling New Hampshire's primary on Dec.
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think they would like to have their primary on Christmas
Day?'' he mused the other day, not entirely in jest.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he continues to pressure White House hopefuls to
forgo any campaigning in Delaware, lest New Hampshire voters punish
them for breaking with tradition. And he just might be making a bit
of headway, but don't bet on it yet.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the leading Republican hopefuls, Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas and Elizabeth Dole, the former Red Cross president, called
upon other states not to encroach on the New Hampshire primary,
while the author of Delaware's primary law, state Sen. Robert
Marshall, D-Wilmington, said on Monday that perhaps the four-day
period should be extended to the week of separation called for by
New Hampshire law.
</P>
<P>
   If we don't change the law, he said, ``then all the major party
candidates' stops won't include Delaware.''
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: When the rush to front-load the primary and caucus
calendar first began, some Western leaders dreamed of putting
together an eight-state regional primary that would give the
sparsely populated Rocky Mountain area more nominating clout than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   It's not going to happen. Five states have now rejected the
proposal: Arizona, Idaho, Montana, Nevada and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Only three states have agreed to the proposal: Colorado, Utah
and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   BOTH SIDES ENDORSE BUSH IN LOUISIANA
</P>
<P>
   Whatever date Louisiana Republicans finally choose for their
presidential caucuses next spring, maybe they should let Democrats
join once the caucusing starts. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Before last year's elections, the top Democratic and Republican
officeholders in the state who were up for re-election concocted a
pact. It stated, bluntly: No Democratic signatory would take part
in any effort to unseat a Republican signatory, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Given the flux in party politics in the South, Democrats often
act more like Republicans than Republicans themselves. But the
brassiness of that pact struck many members of both parties as a
bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes more ideological muddling. The other day, 21 Democrats
in the Louisiana House of Representatives, including Speaker Hunt
Downer, joined 23 Republican legislators in endorsing Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas for president. In fact, they not only endorsed the
front-running Republican hopeful but also praised his ``high ideals
of integrity and ethics'' and offered ``enthusiastic support'' for
his election effort.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for state Rep. Travis Holley, D-Bastrop. When
the Democratic State Central Committee met over the weekend, he
proposed that it adopt a resolution ending the party's
long-standing policy of routinely endorsing Democrats seeking
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be allowed to consider and act upon the request of
challengers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There was no vote. Holley could not find a quorum.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA'S GOVERNOR TO SERVE A FULL TERM  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Jesse Ventura, running as the Reform Party candidate, was
elected governor of Minnesota last year, he gave the party a needed
lift. Not since its founder, Ross Perot, finished a surprising
strong third in the 1992 presidential race had any of its
candidates enjoyed such success.
</P>
<P>
   Now, says the governor, it is time to build on that success.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean he intends to run for president?
</P>
<P>
   No, he replied the other day, while on another cross-country
swing to promote his new book, ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed''
(Villard). Rather, he said, he planned to serve his full four-year
term and, at the same time, work to strengthen his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to step forward as a leader,'' he said. ``You don't
have to be a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he have a candidate in mind, say, Perot?
</P>
<P>
   Perot, he answered pointedly, should ``step aside'' and the
party should search for a fresh leader.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura, he insisted, was not looking to be that leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
