<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR TELLS OF CONCEALING BASKETBALL STAR'S AILMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., the doctor who announced to the
world in May 1993 that Reggie Lewis had a benign fainting disorder
that would not end his basketball career, testified Tuesday that he
had met with Lewis, Lewis's wife, hospital officials, and Boston
Celtics representatives and had agreed not to reveal that Lewis
might have a serious heart condition as well.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's assertion that Lewis and those close to him had
concealed the full prognosis was made as the Brigham and Women's
Hospital cardiologist, who was in charge of Lewis's care, returned
to the witness stand to defend himself in the malpractice case
sparked by Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very calculated plan . . . that we would present only
one diagnosis,'' Mudge said of the May 1993 press conference. ``I
remember being quite adamant about this . . . I did not want to
have to discuss or debate Mr. Lewis's medical care in a public
forum.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven weeks after Mudge confidently proclaimed that Lewis
didn't have a life-threatening heart condition, the 27-year-old
Celtics star died of heart failure while casually shooting baskets
at Brandeis University.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Mudge for the first time told jurors about the
conversation he had with Lewis two weeks before he died in which
Lewis reportedly admitted that he had used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge said the confession took place in Lewis's car at a Celtics
rookie training camp in July 1993. Although he had asked Lewis on
three prior occasions if he had used cocaine, Mudge said he raised
the issue again because cocaine use was the only explanation for
the abnormalities he'd detected in Lewis's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge said Lewis dodged the question twice that day, once by
making an unrelated comment and once by signing an autograph for a
child who had approached his car.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mudge recalled, ``I said, `You still haven't answered
my question.' '' Then, Mudge said, ``He nodded his head and said
`yes' . . . I was actually not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also recounted a phone conversation with Lewis's widow,
Donna Harris-Lewis, two months after Lewis died in which she said
that Reggie's mother had used cocaine and that he had been killed
by the same ``poison.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis has denied that her husband used drugs and has said
that Mudge's allegation that he had admitted using cocaine prompted
her to bring the malpractice suit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite misleading the public and the press about his full
diagnosis of Lewis's condition, Mudge on Tuesday insisted he had
not lied.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, doctor,'' asked Robert G. Harley, the attorney for
Harris-Lewis, ``you can be pretty convincing when you want to tell
a story, even though it's not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing untrue I said in that press conference,''
answered Mudge, speaking more deliberately, and humbly, than he had
during his testimony last month.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also testified that Lewis's belated confession to drug use
impeded his ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had had a clear indication of his use of cocaine . . . it
certainly would have changed our analyses of the tests,'' Mudge
said. ``By not knowing he was on cocaine, we deprived many
consultants who saw Mr. Lewis of, really, a better opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   And had he known about Lewis's drug use earlier, ``We certainly
would never have had a press conference,'' Mudge said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his daylong testimony, Mudge spoke kindly of the
Lewises, noting that he sympathized with the ``intense and
unrelenting interest by the press in (Lewis's) medical care.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Lewis's ``gentle demeanor'' and ``quiet nature,''
he called the player ``an individual who I can relate to.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by his attorney to describe his impression of
Harris-Lewis, Mudge said he found her to be ``very caring, very
intelligent . . . she had a very impressive command of the medical
issues we were confronting.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also spoke of the complexity of Lewis's case, noting that
the player often experienced physical symptoms that were not
accompanied by abnormal heart readings, and abnormal heart readings
not accompanied by symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was puzzled . . . I didn't fully understand what was
happening,'' Mudge said.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also said he and the Lewises had an understanding that
Reggie was not to exercise unless he was monitored. He said that
when Harris-Lewis told him that her husband wanted to begin
shooting baskets after his discharge, ``I said that was
unacceptable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge also testified that in the September following Lewis's
death, Harris-Lewis telephoned him to discuss her dismay with
continuing press coverage of the case. During that phone call,
Mudge said, Harris-Lewis ``indicated to me that Mr. Lewis's mother
had a problem with cocaine and that in fact Mr. Lewis had died from
the poisons his mother had given to him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
