<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-POLICE-NYT &LR;      06-08 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE HOPE LOUIMA VERDICT WILL LIFT CLOUD OVER DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (with LOUIMA-TRIAL, LOUIMA-ASSESS, LOUIMA-REACT)  
 (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the police officers who walk beats and patrol in
radio cars here, there was some hope Tuesday that the verdicts in
the Abner Louima brutality trial would mark the beginning of the
end of what many described as one of the ugliest episodes in the
Police Department's history.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since allegations first surfaced that an officer had used a
stick to sexually assault Louima in a station house bathroom, the
department has been under a cloud. Not only were there angry
rallies denouncing the department as brutal, but also, officers on
the beat were taunted day in and day out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would get comments when you went out on jobs,'' recalled
Sgt. Noel Leader, a member of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, a police group. ``People would say, `Don't sodomize me' or,
`What are you going to do, sodomize me like Louima?' It only made
our job that much more difficult, and it dented the reputation of
the NYPD both nationally and internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult police assignments since the attack on
Louima was given to Inspector Raymond Diaz, who became the new
commander of the 70th Precinct in Flatbush, Brooklyn, where the
attack occurred. He was given a mandate to improve relations
between the police and the public and to improve morale in the
station house.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, at the conclusion of a federal civil rights trial that
resulted in the convictions of two police officers in the August
1997 attack and the acquittals of three others, Diaz said he hoped
that the verdicts would help people in the neighborhood put the
incident behind them. ``It's good that we get to see some
closure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a community of immigrants, and many people who come
here start out feeling fearful of the police, and now we have
something like this happen and it sets us back,'' he said. ``It's
going to take a lot of work to show these people that this is not
what the NYPD is all about, that it was a terrible aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is to show people that we're here for them for
reducing crime, improving their quality of life, solving their
problems, and that we're not the enemy and we don't see them as the
enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Pamela Rinando, a 17-year department veteran who works
in the 48th Precinct in the Fordham section of the Bronx, said she
hoped that the incident would lead officials to try to change how
the department deals with the public and how it handles its own
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start healing at this point,'' she said. ``We have
to start building a bridge between us and the community. We have to
start evaluating what's going on. We have to start looking at the
human factors. And instead of looking to hang police officers all
the time, we should start looking at why these horrible things are
happening. If a cop has a problem, he should be able to go for
psychological help without a stigma.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Donald Jirak, president of the Gay Officers Action League,
said he hoped that the verdicts would encourage the department to
take further steps to protect police officers who come forward to
report misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   At the 70th Precinct station house Tuesday, Diaz said that while
there was a sense of relief that the main federal trial had ended,
officers were aware that there could still be another trial on
lesser charges and a civil trial. But he said he hoped that the
officers under his command would continue to win back the trust of
the people they are sworn to protect and serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship has really been strengthened,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2215EDT &QL; 
