<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-CHARGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUIMA LEGAL PROCEEDINGS ARE FAR FROM OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (with LOUIMA-TRIAL, LOUIMA-ASSESS, LOUIMA-POLICE, LOUIMA-REACT)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The verdicts issued Tuesday involving four police
officers in the Abner Louima brutality case did not end the legal
proceedings against those acquitted in the trial or against the
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the acquitted officers, Thomas Bruder and Thomas Wiese,
still face a charge that they conspired with Officer Charles
Schwarz to keep investigators from concluding that Schwarz had
participated in the torture of Louima. Schwarz was the only officer
convicted Tuesday, as a U.S. District Court jury in Brooklyn found
that he helped Officer Justin Volpe torture Louima by holding him
down during an attack in a restroom of the 70th Precinct station
house.
</P>
<P>
   After the verdicts were announced, Zachary Carter, the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, said his office would now try Schwarz, Bruder
and Wiese on a charge of conspiring to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder and Wiese were acquitted of charges that they beat Louima
in a police car before he arrived at the station house. The lawyers
for those two officers said they hoped now that Carter would not
pursue the obstruction charge against their clients, but said they
if the prosecutor did, ``We'll fight that one, too,'' in the words
of Joseph Tacopina, Wiese's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Police Department itself is undergoing scrutiny
from prosecutors. Carter's office has been conducting an inquiry
into whether the Police Department's conduct in the Louima case and
in related matters reflects a broader, institutional pattern of
police brutality. If he finds that to be the case, he may seek an
agreement under which the department would make changes, or, if
unable to reach an agreement, he could sue the department.
</P>
<P>
   The department plans administrative trials that could result in
the dismissal of Bruder, Wiese and the third defendant acquitted
Tuesday, Sgt. Michael Bellomo.
</P>
<P>
   The jury's finding that their actions did not violate the
criminal laws does not mean that they did not violate department
policies and regulations in dealing with Louima or Patrick Antoine,
a second man assaulted by Volpe.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe was dismissed from the force when he pleaded guilty, and
Schwarz was dismissed upon conviction Tuesday, said lawyers in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Police Department trials are also to be held for about a
half-dozen more police officers whom police officials have accused
of lying to investigators about what they saw or knew about the
treatment of Louima and Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   They include Officer Michael Schoer, who testified as a key
prosecution witness against Volpe at the trial. He said Volpe had
shown him the stick with which he later admitted attacking Louima,
but Schoer admitted on the stand that at first he had not told
investigators about the stick. The inconsistency has led to the
departmental charges of lying against him.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Louima has filed a civil suit in which all the officers
who had been charged in the criminal case are among the defendants,
along with the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
