<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDBIZ-KIDBIZ </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Enterprising Kids Go Beyond Lemonade Stand  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Summer vacation is at hand for the K-12 crowd, or will be soon.
That means more time to snooze, socialize and _ for an increasing
number of kids _ start a business.
<P>
   With more online connections and experience than many of their
parents, students increasingly are doing more than selling
lemonade, washing cars and weeding neighbors' gardens. Some, for
example, are setting up computer training and consulting practices.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Success for these budding entrepreneurs often hinges more on
passion and investment of time than money. Creating a business also
requires a streak of creativity and independence. And age certainly
isn't a consideration since some local preteenagers have created
successful enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   However, kids are not simply born inventors or entrepreneurs. It
helps to get the support, both personal and financial, of parents
or a mentoring organization.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  With increasing publicity about high-tech success stories and
the proliferation of entrepreneurship training programs, (See &LR; 
story page tk),  &LR; more kids are getting bitten by the business bug.
David Schincariol, author of ``Start and Run a Profitable
Student-Run Business'' (Self-Counsel Press, $12.95), estimates that
one in four students becomes an entrepreneur while in school.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In fact, many decide to continue their summer business
endeavors into the school year and after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, take Tom Whitnah, who graduates next week from
Menlo-Atherton High School. He started playing with his dad's Radio
Shack computer when he was 2 years old. In elementary school, he
offered free advice to other kids. Then he graduated to
volunteering his computer-training services at the San Carlos
Senior Center &UR;  &LR; and his high school, where he helped create a
2,000-page Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Through referrals, Tom &UR;  &LR; landed his first paying customers and
set up his own consulting business two years ago. First, he tutored
senior citizens and others on how to use PCs and online services
and charged $15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Whitnah then reinvested some of the revenues to pick up 3-D
graphic design and other skills as he shifted the focus of his
Vision Net Consulting business ( &LR; www.thevisionnet.com &LR; ) to Web site
and other services for businesses. Whitnah found that shift not
only more interesting but it also allowed him to easily raise his
hourly fee to $20.
</P>
<P>
   His main client is now an Atherton startup called SurfWax, where
Whitnah works about 12 hours a week, helping to create a new type
of Internet search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when he starts studying computer science at Stanford
University and will be one of about 200 freshman to receive a
$3,000 intellectual exploration grant, Whitnah plans to cut back
his consulting business but raise his hourly rates to $25 or $30.
</P>
<P>
   His advice to would-be entrepreneurs is to ``first get into
something you love, even if you do it for free.'' Next, ``get to
know your market and the type of services they are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, computer expertise is easier to sell these days than,
say, soccers skills, Whitnah acknowledges. But students who excel
in sports or music can also join programs or camps to help train
younger kids. Whitnah adds that the best marketing is word of
mouth. He has relied entirely on positive client referrals to build
his business and now has more work than he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps to have good connections and positive role
models at home. Whitnah's dad is a computer aficionado and heads
the math department at Menlo-Atherton; his mother is a career
guidance assistant at Redwood High School.
</P>
<P>
   Whitnah also took advantage of training programs. Last summer,
he signed up for a free two-week BizCamp at Stanford University
sponsored by the National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship
and this year won a $1,000 entrepreneurship award from the New York
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the kids who take NFTE's programs in school or summer
camp are less privileged than Whitnah. One of its graduates and
another award winner this year is Ricardo Garcia, who dropped out
of George Washington High School in San Francisco four years ago
after skipping most of his junior year classes.
</P>
<P>
   But he took NFTE's business lessons to heart and later attended
Heald Business College and Renaissance Entrepreneurship Center and
established a Latino rap and hip-hop magazine. Now 20 and executive
editor of Info-magazine, Garcia echoes Whitnah's advice to pursue
one's interests. Last December, he also became an instructor for
NFTE.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferycq &LR;  Toney, 18, who graduates next Wednesday from
Castlemont High School in Oakland, also is tuning in to a music
career. Last year, he made about $10,000 giving rap concerts and
selling his ``Skyballin''' CD, which he cut with his friend Cameron
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Toney has plowed much of the money back into music equipment and
in September will study music and the music business at Columbia
College in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can teach you how to be an artist,'' said Toney, who
hopes one day to create his recording label. ``But it's not just
about music. You have to keep your head in the books and know the
business part.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Mehrad Noori, 15, who will be a junior at California High
School in San Ramon next year, stumbled on a business idea while
playing on his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Using Adobe Illustrator software, he designed logos that look
like traffic signs but with different wording. For instance, he has
come up with a stop sign that says ``Think,'' a yield sign that
says ``Chill,'' and a one-way sign that says ``My way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehrad's older brother showed the designs to a friend who runs a
snowboard and skate shop and who was enthusiastic about potential
consumer response to caps or T-shirts bearing the logos.
</P>
<P>
   Mehrad's father, who is in the construction business and once
taught economics at the University of California at Santa Barbara,
put up about $7,000 to have the first 1,200 caps manufactured at a
San Diego plant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Mehrad is talking with a lawyer about trademark protection. He
also is registering the name Civilian Ltd. and setting up a Web
site along with the business.
</P>
<P>
   The local kid entrepreneur who has gained perhaps the most fame
and fortune recently is toy designer Rich Stachowski of Contra
Costa County. He came up with an idea for an underwater talking
device when snorkeling with his dad on Maui nearly three years ago
at the age of 11.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, about 200,000 Water Talkies have been sold. Scuba
Scope and Pool Pogo Stick also are on the market and Stachowski,
who will be 14 next month, has several other products under
development.
</P>
<P>
   It helps to have entrepreneurial role models. Stachowski's
mother has 86 inventions to her credit, the latest of which is a
newfangled hair clip that sells on the QVC cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Stachowski has learned some important lessons about
the business world, like being discriminating about disclosing
information. Asked about reports that he sold his business Short
Stack to San Francisco's Wild Planet in February for $1 million or
more, he said, ``I don't talk about finances.''
</P>
<P>
   To be a successful entrepreneur, he recommends using your
imagination, brainstorming, making lots of prototypes and
surrounding ``yourself with people who can do things you can't and
learn from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stachowski has won several young entrepreneur and inventor of
the year awards and also serves on the board of directors of
BizWorld in Redwood City. Venture capitalist Tim Draper, of the
firm Draper Fisher Jurvetson, got the inspiration to set up
BizWorld as a nonprofit organization to teach kids about
entrepreneurship when his daughter was in the third grade and asked
him, ``What do you do when you're away?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For kids who prefer to work for someone else before they start
their own enterprises, there are various programs. For instance,
Enterprise for High School Students places more than 2,000
teenagers in San Francisco jobs each year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There's also the San Francisco School-to-Career Partnership, a
joint venture of the San Francisco Chamber of Commerce, the mayor's
office, school district and city college, which hopes to place 500
students in paid internships this summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
