<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIVO-TIVO_SFCHRON &LR;      06-08 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIVO-TIVO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Post-VCR Companies Get Backing 
 &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Two Silicon Valley startups that have just launched competing VCR
replacements have won votes of confidence from major players in
broadcasting and consumer electronics.
<P>
   Replay Networks of Mountain View announced yesterday that
Matsushita, the Japanese giant behind the Panasonic brand name,
will begin manufacturing digital recording devices based on
Replay's technology later this year, in time for the holiday
shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, TiVo, Replay's archrival, and NBC are slated to
announce a strategic partnership today. The broadcast giant will
make a ``significant'' investment in the Sunnyvale company, and Tom
Rogers, executive vice president of NBC and president of its cable
subsidiary, will join TiVo's board.
</P>
<P>
   Both TiVo and Replay have developed set-top boxes that convert
TV programming into digital format and record it on computer-style
hard drives. Users who are watching a program and get interrupted
by a phone call can hit the pause button and start recording. When
they come back, they can pick up watching where they left off while
continuing to record the rest of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Both Replay and TiVo launched their products this spring, but so
far, they've been available only from the companies' Web sites, and
only in limited quantity.
</P>
<P>
   Replay currently makes and markets its set-top box under its own
name, but the deal with Panasonic will give it much wider
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TiVo's are built by Philips Electronics, which is scheduled to
begin offering it in retail stores next month.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for both products start at about $700, including lifetime
access to program listings, which the devices download by modem
every night. As users are surfing through the TV listings and see a
program they like, all they have to do is click on it and it will
be recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Replay said pricing for the Panasonic versions haven't been set.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo and NBC officials refused to disclose details of the
network's investment. DirecTV, the Hughes Electronics subsidiary
that delivers digital TV programming through satellite receivers,
is TiVo's largest corporate investor, after taking a stake of more
than 10 percent in April. Other investors include Philips, Showtime
Networks and several venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   For NBC, the TiVo investment is the latest in a flurry of recent
moves to reach beyond traditional broadcasting. In addition to
MSNBC, the TV and Internet news service it co-owns with Microsoft,
the company has invested in Cnet, Talk City, iVillage and several
other Internet properties. Together with Snap.com and Xoom.com,
it's in the process of forming a new company called NBC Internet
(NBCi), which plans to integrate broadcast, Web-portal and
e-commerce services.
</P>
<P>
   Peg Murphy, vice president of business development for NBC
Interactive, called today's deal ``not just a good financial
investment, but an incredible strategic partnership for NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   The partnership, she said, will ``allow us to package and
promote our properties in whole new ways.'' NBC will, for example,
produce special previews and promotional materials about its
miniseries and other programs to supplement the bare-bones listings
that TiVo currently delivers to subscribers' screens.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Murphy said, ``someone might be watching a `Law
and Order' episode they've recorded on the hard drive, and we'll be
able to pop a promo for `Law and Order _ Special Victims Unit' (a
spin-off series the network will launch next fall) right on their
screen.'' Or fans of ``Saturday Night Live'' could be invited to
tune into an archive of old episodes already waiting on their hard
drives, complete with new ads.
</P>
<P>
   The deal won't prohibit TiVo from making similar arrangements
with other TV networks, nor will it keep NBC from marketing its
programming through Replay's service, according to officials from
the two companies. They also denied that NBC shows would get
favored treatment on the TiVo system, which provides subscribers
extensive materials and suggestions about upcoming programming.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo and NBC also plan to work with advertisers to develop
``targeted advertising'' based on users' viewing habits and
preferences. TiVo devices store such information and currently use
it to come up with entertainment suggestions, but company officials
say the data stays in the user's own machine and is not collected
in a central database, out of respect for customers' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
