<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGENCY-AGENCY_SFCHRON     06-08 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGENCY-AGENCY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Ad Agencies McCann-Erickson, Anderson &AMP; Lembke to
Join  Forces 
 &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
McCann-Erickson San Francisco, known for the ``It's the Cheese''
commercials, is merging with tech specialist Anderson &AMP; Lembke to
form the city's fifth-largest advertising agency.
<P>
   Both companies, the seventh- and ninth-largest in the city,
respectively, are owned by McCann-Erickson North America, part of
the Interpublic Group of Cos., so no money or stock will change
hands.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency, with combined billings of $333.7 million, will
be called McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L and headed by Nick Bishop, A&AMP;L's
president. He will become chief executive when the deal closes
August 1.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was precipitated by the companies' joint win last
month of Microsoft's Windows 2000 account, formerly held by Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy of Portland, Ore. Microsoft wanted A&AMP;L for the
business-to-business portion of the account; A&AMP;L's sister agency,
McCann, was brought in to pitch the consumer end.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the combination, we have everything all in one place,''
said Microsoft spokesman Rob Schoeben.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, to be announced today, is the latest example of a
consumer-product agency partnering with a tech specialist. Earlier
this year, the city's largest independent ad shop, Citron Haligman
Bedecarre, which creates ads for companies like Power Bar, was
acquired by New York tech agency Euro RSCG Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Many tech businesses are trying to boost their name recognition
beyond geek audiences, even as consumer-product companies begin to
market themselves online.
</P>
<P>
   By merging, ``we believe we will have the profile to ... move to
the very top of the agency business in San Francisco,'' said Don
Dillon, president of McCann-Erickson North America.
</P>
<P>
   Both McCann and A&AMP;L have experienced bumpy times in recent
years. McCann's billings dropped 25 percent, to $205 million, last
year after losing accounts including AT&AMP;T's wireless business.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;L, whose billings totaled $129 million in 1998, was in danger
of closing five years ago after an unsuccessful attempt to broaden
its tech focus. The company is healthy now but is dominated by a
single client, Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by combining, they are hoping for the critical mass
they've never been able to achieve separately,'' said one agency
source on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Benza, the outgoing general manager of McCann, opted to quit
the company rather than transfer outside the Bay Area. Benza has
spent his entire 23-year career with McCann.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a 14-year McCann veteran who has run A&AMP;L only since
January, said layoffs are not expected and that in fact the agency
is recruiting new employees to staff the Microsoft account and a
new McCann account, Siebel Systems, with billings of $20 million to
$30 million.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, A&AMP;L employs about 200 people and McCann has 140.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and its agencies refuse to disclose account sizes, but
trade magazines estimate Microsoft's total ad spending at $220
million domestically and $180 million internationally.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;L's Amsterdam and Hong Kong offices will not be affected by
the merger with McCann.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
