<HEADLINE>
USC EYES WOMEN`S NATIONAL COACH HALEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's search for a women's volleyball coach has
turned to U.S. women's national team coach Mick Haley, after UC
Irvine men's coach Charlie Brande turned down the job.
</P>
<P>
   Brande mulled an offer for several days before deciding over the
weekend that he would remain at Irvine, where he was named Mountain
Pacific Sports Federation Coach of the Year last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tremendous offer, but my family's here in Orange
County and I decided to stay home,'' Brande said. ``It was the
toughest decision I've made in my life. I thought it would be a
tremendous place to coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Brande, 51, received a raise from Irvine to remain as men's
coach. Another factor in his decision is the successful girls' club
program he runs in Newport Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My love of coaching is for the club,'' Brande said.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Haley as USC's next choice. He has already visited
USC and formally interviewed for the job. Haley previously coached
at Texas, where he won national championships in 1981 and 1988.
Haley compiled a 522-137-1 record in 17 seasons at Texas and won 13
Southwest Conference titles.
</P>
<P>
   He will coach the U.S. women's national team through the 2000
Olympics, meaning USC would have an interim coach, expected to be
current assistant Jerritt Elliott, for the 1999 season if Haley
accepts the job.
</P>
<P>
   Also interviewed for the position were Stanford assistant Denise
Corlett, who played at UCLA, and Florida coach Mary Wise.
</P>
<P>
   USC has been searching for a coach since Lisa Love resigned in
April to concentrate on being an associate athletic director at the
university.
</P>
</TEXT>
