<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALZA-ALZA_SFCHRON &LR;      06-08 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALZA-ALZA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Alza Gets Strong Backing for New Uses of 2 Drugs  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Food and Drug Administration advisory panel said yesterday
that Alza Corp. should be allowed to promote new uses for two of
its existing drugs, one to fight the side effects of radiation
therapy and the other to battle advanced ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Saks, chief medical officer of the Palo Alto firm, said the
strong show of support from the advisory panel makes it ``highly
likely'' the FDA will soon give its final blessing to the new uses
of Ethyol and Doxil.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to create additional revenues, drug companies
routinely try to win FDA approval for secondary uses of drugs that
are already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Ethyol was first approved for use in 1995 as an intravenous
treatment for patients undergoing chemotherapy. Ethyol enters
healthy kidney cells and protects them from the toxic effects of
cancer-fighting drugs, Saks said.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA advisory panel said in an 11-to-1 vote that Ethyol seems
to offer similar protection for the salivary glands of patients
undergoing radiation therapy for head and neck cancer. Saks said
radiation often destroys these glands, making it tough for patients
to swallow or speak.
</P>
<P>
   If the FDA gives final approval, which could be in a matter of
weeks, Alza could advertise the benefits of the $9,000 Ethyol
treatment, Saks said.
</P>
<P>
   Alza's second drug, Doxil, also won FDA approval in 1995 as a
remedy for Kaposi's sarcoma. In this cancerlike condition,
associated with AIDS, patients develop internal or external
lesions. Doxil is a chemotherapy drug wrapped inside a fatty layer
that helps the drug find and kill cancer cells over time while
minimizing damage to healthy tissue.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since it became available for Kaposi's sarcoma, some
doctors have prescribed it to fight ovarian and breast cancer, Saks
said. Doctors often experiment with prescribed drugs to treat
life-threatening situations before the FDA has officially approved
such procedures. But companies cannot promote these so-called
``off-label'' uses until and unless the FDA approves the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Alza wants to advertise Doxil as a secondary remedy for ovarian
cancer patients who have tried current drugs like Taxol but have
not been cured. Saks said Alza is also studying Doxil's effect on
breast cancer in hopes of winning FDA approval for that use in the
``near future,'' Saks said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Sales of Doxil totaled $48 million last year. Sales of
Ethyol, which was developed by Pennsylvania's U.S. Bioscience and
marketed by Alza, hit $32.6 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Securing FDA approval to advertise new uses for the drugs would
``boost growth,'' said analyst David Maris with Bear Stearns in New
York, who thinks Doxil could be a $77 million product in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Alza, one of the few profitable biotech firms, earned $112
million last year on revenues of $584 million. Its shares, which
hit a 52-week high of $55.75 on February 16, slipped 56 cents
yesterday to close at $38.31
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
