<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-US-HNS &LR;      06-08 1441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-US-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA JOINS NATO IN URGING YUGOSLAV FORCES TO LEAVE KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Russia joined NATO on Tuesday in demanding
Yugoslav forces leave Kosovo, intensifying pressure on President
Slobodan Milosevic to take his troops out of the war-torn province
and allow an international military force to oversee return of
hundreds of thousands of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless he is totally tone deaf, he should be getting the
message it is time to withdraw,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said in Cologne, Germany, where foreign ministers of eight
major powers hammered out final wording of a U.N. resolution on the
Yugoslav pullout and Kosovo's future.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon later reported ``a number of
indications that the Serbs plan to withdraw,'' including massing of
military transport, but ``we have not yet seen any withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic sent his generals back Tuesday night to restart talks
with the local NATO commander on the alliance-dictated plan for
taking Belgrade's 40,000 troops out of Kosovo and back into Serbia,
the Yugoslav heartland. British Lt. Gen. Michael Jackson, who will
command the multinational occupation force, returned with the
Yugoslav delegation to the camouflaged tent at Kumanovo air base in
Macedonia where talks collapsed early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations were high at the camp near the Yugoslav border.
NATO spokesman Trey Cate, said: ``We fully expect them to sign
tonight.'' Failure of the earlier discussions prompted the two-day
diplomatic dance that culminated in the proposed U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said it would continue air strikes, at an unspecified
level, until the Yugoslav withdrawal begins. Allied spokesman Jamie
Shea said NATO bombing would stop only ``when we see that dust on
the tracks'' as the tanks of Milosevic's force start to depart from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said NATO needs to see ``a certain amount of movement''
from ``certain zones,'' but he refused to give the exact
formulation, saying that was for Jackson to explain to the Yugoslav
generals.
</P>
<P>
   As outlined by Albright and her colleagues, the latest plan is
for a tightly choreographed script that opens with the Yugoslav
generals agreeing on the NATO withdrawal plan and actually
beginning the retreat from Kosovo. Then would come a suspension of
the NATO bombing, which is apparently a condition for China, one of
five Security Council members with veto power, acquiescing in the
U.N. resolution. That would be followed by the international force
advancing into Kosovo and the first return of refugees, primarily
ethnic Albanians who fled or were exiled by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key now, as it has been from the beginning of this
process, is implementation,'' President Clinton said in Washington.
``A verifiable withdrawal of Serb forces will allow us to suspend
the bombing and go forward with the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Exact timings seemed impossible to lay down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot give a categorical guarantee when the process will
be completed,'' said German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer. But
Shea said in Brussels, ``If Milosevic wants, things can go
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook contended the
basic tenets of the peace plan had ``not been renegotiated in any
shape or form'' since they were agreed to by Milosevic last week,
there was some diplomatic finessing in drafting the resolution. The
central role that NATO is to play in KFOR (for ``Kosovo force``) is
spelled out only in an appendix, a bow to Russian and Chinese
sensitivities.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said an annex carries the same force as the body of the
resolution and declared: ``We got what we came for.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that a few Serb officials will be allowed to
remain at border crossings ``as observers'' while refugees return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs in no way will be able to control who goes back into
Kosovo,'' Albright said. Serb military and police stripped many
Albanian Kosovars of identity papers as they herded them out of
Kosovo earlier in the conflict, perhaps thinking it would
complicate their return. U.N. refugee workers have been issuing
them new identity papers.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that the Serbs, as one of their ``last-minute
tricks,'' had forced recent refugees to sign documents renouncing
their Yugoslav citizenship. He said the ploy would not prejudice
the refugees' right to return to the province.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said that Milosevic, by insisting on the U.N. resolution,
had apparently hoped to ``ratchet down the (peace) agreement'' of
last week. ``He didn't get away with it,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is expected to send up to 10,000 troops to Kosovo, but
their role in the force remains to be worked out. Igor Ivanov, the
Kremlin foreign minister, left the issue vague, apparently for
domestic consumption in Russia, where there is strong opposition to
Russian troops being commanded by the old Soviet nemesis NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops, in fact, function under NATO direction in the
multinational force in Bosnia, but little is said about the
arrangement. Clinton said he was certain ``acceptable levels of
coordination'' between NATO and Russia could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Russia also lost out on bids to water down the resolution's
references that make it clear the international force can take
strong military measures to enforce the peace in Kosovo. A second
disputed reference demands the troops help apprehend Serbs indicted
as war criminals by the international tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to bring an end to the war,'' Ivanov said. ``If we
can achieve that as quickly as possible, we can be satisfied with
this resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland, who represented the
European Union when the peace plan was taken to Belgrade last week,
flew to Beijing to sell Chinese President Jiang Zemin on the
proposal. Although China has been a vocal critic of the NATO
bombing, it rarely invokes its Security Council veto unless a clear
national interest is involved. China could abstain in a vote on the
Kosovo resolution.
</P>
<P>
   All the other nations with a Security Council veto _ the United
States, Russian, Britain and France _ were party to drafting of the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Various groups of geopolitical players stood by to perform their
roles. The North Atlantic Council, NATO's policy-making arm made up
of ambassadors from each of the allied nations, was to meet Tuesday
night in Brussels. The foreign ministers sent the proposed
resolution to U.N. headquarters in New York, where ambassadors from
nations on the Security Council were on alert.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Kosovo is in ruins, and many paths of return studded
with land mines, so the prospects for the multinational force as
well as the refugees may be harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said that in addition to the peace plan, the foreign
ministers discussed getting the World Bank and European Union to
quickly work on economic aid needed to help rebuild Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Many political leaders in the United States and Europe have said
that no international aid should go to Serbia as long as Milosevic
remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer led the talks because his nation currently chairs the
G-8 _ the United States, Russia, Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy and Japan. The group's annual summit is to be held in Cologne
in 10 days, and financing reconstruction of the Balkans is likely
to emerge as a major topic.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who met with Albanian Kosovar chiefs in Germany, won a
promise from a top ethnic leader, Hasim Thaci, to refrain from
attacking Serb troops as they withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Albright flew to Brussels for dinner Tuesday with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana, who will move to his new job as
chief defense representative for the European Union as soon as the
Yugoslav air campaign is completed.
</P>
<P>
   As the diplomats huddled in Germany trying to get the peace
process back on track, NATO lived up to its promise to step up the
bombing campaign. Allied sorties were up 36 per cent Monday from
the day before, and actual strikes were up 56 percent, NATO said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday, U.S. B-52s pounded concentrated Serb
positions near the Albanian border. Bacon said he could not confirm
reports that the bombardment had resulted in heavy Serb casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commission for Refugees estimated Tuesday that
more than 985,000 refugees, almost all of them ethnic Albanians had
left Kosovo in the last 15 month, 782,300 since the U.N. bombing
campaign began March 24, which sparked an intensified wave of Serb
aggression and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
