<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRAVES NOTEBOOK: Weiss to have test on aching quad
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A repeat of history is the last thing Braves shortstop
Walt Weiss wants, but his sore quadriceps is feeling dangerously
familiar.
</P>
<P>
   After spending almost all of last season warding off quadriceps
and hamstring problems that limited him to 96 games, Weiss is
fighting it again. He missed his second consecutive game Tuesday,
and ninth in the past 12 games, after aggravating his strained
quadriceps running to first on a single to lead off the 10th inning
Sunday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss is scheduled to have an MRI today to gauge the damage. The
disabled list is an option, though he managed to avoid it all last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait a day or two, and if there's not much improvement,
we'll make a decision,'' Weiss said. ``My hope is that it doesn't
last four months like it did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen struggles
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' replacement at shortstop, Ozzie Guillen, has held his own
in the field but continues to struggle at the plate. He was hitting
.141 entering Tuesday night's game, the lowest among Braves
position players, and .111 (4-for-36) as Weiss' replacement in the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two weeks I've had real bad at-bats, and I'm not
happy about it,'' Guillen said. ``I'm trying to get five hits in
one at-bat and that doesn't work. . . . I'm not panicking. I've
been there before in my career. . . . They need me now. I've got to
do good until (Weiss) comes back.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen said he takes comfort from knowing that manager Bobby
Cox is behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a slump, some managers don't want to talk to
you, they hide from you,'' Guillen said. ``Not Bobby. Hopefully I
won't let him down. With him, you get motivation to do good every
day, go hard and do better.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Jones heats up
</P>
<P>
   It's been an on-and-off season offensively for Andruw Jones, who
improved his April average from .204 last year to .272 this year,
but slumped to .252 in May. Entering Tuesday's game, Jones was 13
for his last 60 (.217).
</P>
<P>
   But in his previous two games, Jones reached base in seven of
his last eight trips to the plate and scored four runs. He homered
Monday for the first time since May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep telling yourself to be patient,'' Jones
said. ``Sometimes you try to do too much and chase bad pitches.
When you're patient, that's when you'll be successful. (Monday)
night and the last game in Boston, I've been really relaxed and
looking for the pitch I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Through May last year, Jones was hitting .264 with eight homers
and 30 RBIs. Through Monday night, he was hitting .268 with nine
homers and 32 RBIs.Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko was unavailable for the second consecutive game
because of flu symptoms. Klesko came by the clubhouse to see a team
doctor but didn't stay for the game. . . . New fashion around the
clubhouse? Some navy-colored T-shirts ordered by Justin Speier in
honor of hard-throwing closer John Rocker that say: ``I know the
guy who throws 100 mph.'' And on the back, in a reference to the
relievers: ``I wanna rock. 1999 Braves Grunts.'' . . . All-Star
ballot update: Chipper Jones has pulled to a close second (108,259
votes) behind Matt Williams (109,216) in the most recent release of
fans' voting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
