<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF SHURMUR'S LIVER CANCER STUNS SEAHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Something was definitely missing when the
Seattle Seahawks returned to the practice field Monday to begin
their final minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   You could sense it from the lack of enthusiasm and execution in
most drills. You could see it on the faces of the players and
coaches after the 90-minute practice. You could hear it in their
voices as they tried to explain how the team must forge ahead
without defensive coordinator Fritz Shurmur.
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur, 66, has begun receiving treatment in Green Bay for
liver cancer, which he was diagnosed with last month and sources
say has spread to other parts of his body.
</P>
<P>
   When, and whether, he returns will be determined by how he
responds to the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   No one will say Shurmur won't return, and although it really is
too early to say it, the possibility is evident because of the
somber undercurrent surrounding his situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The football side of it, you really realize how unimportant it
is when you're talking about someone's life _ especially a man like
Fritz, who basically gives his heart and soul to everything he
does,'' linebacker Darrin Smith said. ``We miss him tremendously,
and we know he misses us.''
</P>
<P>
   The players gathered as a team Monday for the first time since
Shurmur was diagnosed two weeks ago. Before practice, coach Mike
Holmgren explained the seriousness of Shurmur's condition to most
of them for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I thought today's practice was a little lackluster
for the first time,'' Holmgren said, adding that he felt it was a
reaction to what was discussed before the workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about some serious things in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren also was forced to make some necessary moves.
Linebackers coach Jim Lind will assume the additional duties of
defensive coordinator. In part, because he has been involved with
both the run and pass defense while working with the linebackers
for the past five seasons under Shurmur in Green Bay. But also
because he received Shurmur's endorsement for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz is a good friend, and for me he's been a mentor,'' Lind
said. ``He taught me an awful lot. We fished together. So when
something like this happens, it's a major jolt. You make an
adjustment, and you keep going . . . but I think the players
certainly are disappointed because Fritz brought an excellent
reputation with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The defensive playbook already has been completed, so it is
Shurmur's defense that Lind is coaching and coordinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found myself thinking, `What would Fritz do?' And that's not
all bad,'' Lind said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, former Buffalo Bills secondary coach Dick
Roach will join the staff as a defensive assistant. Roach, 61, was
out of the league last year after stints with the Bills (1987-97),
Tampa Bay Buccaneers (1985-86), New England Patriots (1981) and
Kansas City Chiefs (1978-80).
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren hopes that Roach's experience will ease the loss of
Shurmur's wisdom and also provide Lind with a sounding board. Roach
will begin by helping Ken Flajole coach the defensive backs. But,
Holmgren said, ``The job will kind of develop as our minicamps and
training camps go along.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither move was easy for Holmgren because of what they could
ultimately mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``The harsh reality is, I had to do something as far as the
staff is concerned,'' said Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it will be to replace Shurmur the coach, it will
be even harder to replace the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss him as a football coach certainly, but he was really
a good friend,'' Holmgren said. ``He was a little bit of a mentor
to me. He'll be a part of this thing as long as he can and as long
as he wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur followed Holmgren to Seattle after he was hired in
January. The players have not known Shurmur that long, but they
quickly developed a bond with him and were looking forward to
playing for a coach who is considered one of the most innovative
defensive minds in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz always started off the meetings with a joke,'' Smith
said. ``It wasn't always funny, but at least he tried. Those are
the little things we have to do as a team to keep it going and keep
the focus on doing well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
