<HEADLINE>
N.J. UNIONIZED STATE WORKERS VOTE TO AUTHORIZE STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey's 27,000 unionized state employees
have voted to authorize a strike if Gov. Christie Whitman does not
meet their demands to increase wages, freeze workers' health care
costs and preserve the civil service seniority system, union
officials announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the current four-year contract expiring June 30, the strike
authorization won overwhelming support from state workers, who say
they sacrificed during the state's lean fiscal years and are now
entitled to share in New Jersey's billion-dollar budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The strike threat also underlines the bitter opposition to
Whitman's plan to replace the state's byzantine civil service job
classification system with a merit system that would weaken the
role that seniority plays in promotions and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and union leaders declined to reveal the
specifics of the state's contract proposals. But Larry Mancino,
vice president of District One of the Communication Workers of
America, pointed out that the union had accepted two years of wage
freezes during its last negotiation, followed by only small annual
raises, and that workers had been forced to pay for 20 percent of
their health insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Mancino said the governor's plan to alter the seniority system
had complicated the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to try to force through some merit system
that we can't live with or force through an increase in employees'
health care costs, we're going to end up with a strike,'' Mancino
said at a news conference in the State House. ``But I think there's
a lot of room to work things out short of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mancino's announcement of the strike authorization, which was
approved by 91 percent of the members, included some conciliatory
notes. For one thing, Mancino's news conference was devoid of the
angry rhetoric that has marked many past negotiations between the
state and its employees.
</P>
<P>
   Mancino also said that the Whitman administration's first
contract proposal, which was offered to the union after the strike
vote was scheduled, was ``a good starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no law that specifically prohibits New Jersey public
employees from striking, but the courts have repeatedly ruled that
such strikes are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman did not comment on the strike vote, but her press
secretary, Jayne O'Connor, said the state would take action to stop
a walkout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a responsibility to provide services to the people in
this state,'' Ms. O'Connor said, ``and if state workers are going
to disrupt that, we won't hesitate to go to court and stop it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
