<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-INTERVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-08 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-INTERVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE SAYS HUSBAND HAS KEY FUND-RAISING ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole, continuing to run a distant second
in the polls to Republican presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, said Tuesday that she has turned the corner in fund-raising
with help from the most reluctant source she knows: her husband,
Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who Wednesday travels to Boston and New
Hampshire, said in an interview that her husband ``never raised
money for himself. He hates to ask people for money. And he didn't
do it in his own campaign. But you know what he's doing? He's on
the phone raising money for me. He's going to do four fund-raisers
in June.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of Bob Dole as a financial focal point in
Elizabeth Dole's campaign, while long anticipated by some,
underscores the urgency felt by many candidates to have strong
financial reports to be filed at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   With a number of campaigns suffering from a monetary drought,
Dole could strengthen her position significantly if she proves she
has the financial muscle to fight Bush through the fall and winter.
She told reporters and editors in the Boston Globe Washington
Bureau that she has raised $500,000 in the past week. Now her
campaign hopes that Bob Dole, who last month said it would be
difficult for her to be a candidate if she couldn't raise enough
money, will help erase any lingering doubt about his wife's staying
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind asking for money,'' she said. But, she added,
``It sure is easier when you can ask someone for $1 million than
$1,000,'' contrasting her experience as president of the American
Red Cross and asking for donations with being a presidential
candidate subject to federal contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Dole hired a new chief strategist, Tony Fabrizio, who was the
pollster in her husband's 1996 campaign. Asked Tuesday if she is
positioning herself as the moderate in the GOP field, she
responded, ``I'm not the strategist.'' Instead, she called herself
a ``mainstream conservative'' and a ``change agent'' who prides
herself on taking ``cutting edge'' stances and looks for ``the
tough issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who started collecting money later than most candidates,
raised $685,253 in the first quarter of this year. Bush, by
contrast, collected $7.6 million in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm suspending judgment until I see the figures for this
quarter,'' political analyst Stuart Rothenberg said. ``She better
have raised $3 (million) to $4 million.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Bush's fund-raising success is draining much of
the financial oxygen out of the Republican race, making it
difficult for most other GOP candidates to raise money. For
example, Lamar Alexander recently laid off some aides because of
financial problems, and two top fund-raisers for former vice
president Dan Quayle recently left his staff. An exception to the
trend is publisher Steve Forbes, who is using his personal fortune
and already is running television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Tuesday's interview, Dole stressed that she believes
she is gaining support from people outside the political
establishment, especially from younger people. Enthusiastically
recalling the crowds attending her events in college towns, she
said: ``It's not a strategy. It's what's coming to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, she has been on something of a political
roller-coaster ride, bouncing from 24 percent in the polls in April
to 14 percent in a Gallup survey conducted last weekend, far behind
Bush's 46 percent support in the the same poll.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, known for years as a strong antiabortion advocate,
surprised some of her longtime associates by declaring that
abortion should be a non-issue in the campaign. Then Dole told a
New Hampshire audience she favors some gun-control measures,
including safety locks on handguns, an announcement that garnered
much publicity and seemed prescient in light of the Senate's
subsequent approval of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Dole signaled that one of the next issues she will tackle will
be the environment. She said the most important legacy to be left
to Wednesday's children is clean air and clean water. ``Those who
cause the pollution should pay for the pollution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole heads Wednesday to Massachusetts, where she once taught
high school and was a student at Harvard Law School. ``Boston was a
second home to me,'' she said. ``I left part of my heart there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole recalled that when she was one of about two dozen women at
Harvard in 1962, she encountered a male student who questioned why
she was there. ``What are you doing?'' Dole recalled his saying.
``Don't you realize that there are men who could use a legal
education?'' Dole said this man is now a Washington lawyer who is
petrified she will reveal his name.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the only woman in the presidential race, Dole said she
doesn't feel at any disadvantage. To the contrary, she said, the
country is ready for a woman president. ``We are behind'' other
nations, she said, citing Britain's Margaret Thatcher and Israel's
Golda Meir as women who have led a country's government.
</P>
<P>
   After Dole speaks Wednesday at the Harvard Business School, a
speech that is closed to the press, she plans to go to Portsmouth,
N.H. In an ironic twist, Dole now points to her husband's defeat in
the state's primary in 1996 as evidence that she can beat Bush. At
this time four years ago, the Dole campaign notes, Bob Dole was
beating Buchanan by 51 percent to 10 percent but still lost the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush really hasn't gotten out of Texas,'' Dole said,
suggesting that the front-runner will lose momentum as he heads to
the campaign trail for the first time this weekend in Iowa and next
week in New Hampshire. Asked when she will start heading up in the
polls, she said: ``Wait until next week!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKULA-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      06-08 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKULA-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANNAH PAKULA: PROFESSIONAL SUCCESS THAT DIDN'T BEGIN UNTIL
MIDLIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hannah Pakula set her condition for this interview:
attention must be paid to Human Rights Watch. Its 10th annual film
festival begins Wednesday night with a benefit screening of ``The
Parallax View,'' the 1974 political thriller directed by Alan J.
Pakula, Ms. Pakula's husband, who died in a car crash on the Long
Island Expressway in November.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiation ensued. Ms. Pakula is a journalist and biographer
who understands how these things can play out. She is also known in
New York social circles as a woman of stunning, even formidable
presence, accomplished in the art of the gracious dinner party, one
to whom public face and personal dignity mean much. ``All right,
dear,'' she said, adding firmly, ``but don't make me out to be the
brave widow.''
</P>
<P>
   To many who know Ms. Pakula, 65, her own biography is a story of
how expectations of upper-middle-class women changed from the 1950s
to the 1990s. (It is also a life scored, several times over, by
tragedy and luxury.) Raised to be the perfect wife/hostess/mother,
or, in a friend's words, ``a Jewish geisha,'' she did not fully
realize her intellectual gifts until she was about 50, when she
threw herself into human rights advocacy and published her first
book, about Queen Marie of Romania, which upon its reissue the
novelist Graham Greene called the best biography of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Her second biography, ``An Uncommon Woman,'' a highly praised
study of Empress Frederick of Germany, appeared in 1995. She is now
researching the life of Madame Chiang Kai-shek. ``Alan said all
three women were smarter than their husbands, but had to work
through them,'' she said slyly, ``and he wondered what that was
about.''
</P>
<P>
   She sat the other morning in the library of her Upper East Side
home, furnished with the elegance of two people who read, traveled
and shopped together with hunger and seriousness. They chose New
York, because of its multitude of professionals, rather than Los
Angeles, where Pakula, who directed ``Klute'' and ``Sophie's
Choice,'' worked extensively. A sought-after couple, they
entertained frequently, drawing marquee names from the Manhattan
and Hamptons worlds of high society, journalism, finance and film.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pakula grew up in Los Angeles, her father a representative
of auto-parts manufacturers, her mother bent on seeing her
beautiful daughter well married. ``I was Miss Perfect,'' she said.
``Quite a burden.'' Although she wanted to attend Radcliffe, her
parents feared she would become a bluestocking, and so sent her to
Wellesley. In her junior year, she married Robert Boorstin, a
financier whose family owned a Texas oil business. For the next 15
years, she lived well, playing tennis, raising a daughter and twin
sons.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while the couple were vacationing in Greece, Boorstin
collapsed and died of a heart attack in front of his wife. She was
35.
</P>
<P>
   Falling apart was not an option. ``I realized I was the only
person in the world who cares more about those children than
anything else,'' she said. ``They're needier than you. So you go
on. I became like a mama lion.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, she married Pakula. Shortly thereafter, he
made ``The Parallax View,'' with Warren Beatty, about political
assassination conspiracies. It includes a montage of religious and
family-values images whose meanings turn distorted and violent.
``That has great resonance today,'' Ms. Pakula said.
</P>
<P>
   Although imbued with social confidence, Ms. Pakula felt shaky as
a writer. Pakula, an actor's director, similarly bolstered his
wife. ``He gave me the space to experiment,'' she said. ``I
couldn't fail. Alan said, `It's OK. Fall flat on your face.' That
was an enormous gift. He gave me his protection. He honored work,
successful or not.''
</P>
<P>
   At Pakula's memorial service in February, Ms. Pakula's son
Robert said: ``He learned from her not to be scared of loving to
the fullest, and in return he taught her not to be scared of living
to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pakula was filming ``All the President's Men,'' Ms. Pakula
found her metier: biography. Although she had no research training,
she is disciplined, exacting and curious (she calls her
intellectual ambition ``arrogant'' and ``hubristic''). She spent
seven years immersed in Balkan history to write ``The Last
Romantic'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), her exploration of the glittering
Queen Marie. She spent six weeks in Romania at the height of the
repressive Ceausescu regime. In those years she joined the PEN
American Center, eventually becoming a co-chairwoman of the Freedom
to Write Committee, writing letters for imprisoned writers.
</P>
<P>
   With an investigator for Human Rights Watch, she traveled to
Indonesia and Turkey. Along with Pakula and others, she helped form
Human Rights Watch/Film Watch, which enlists American filmmakers to
write on behalf of foreign directors under political attack.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, her son, Robert, now an official with the
U.S. Treasury Department, suffered two breakdowns. Manic depression
was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   How did she manage?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' she said coolly, ``what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now just over six months since Pakula died. For Ms.
Pakula, there is a new dog from a pound (``we were both lonely''),
talk of her late husband that shifts unsteadily between present
tense and past, the next biography.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't write about myself,'' she said. ``That's why I write
about other people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
