<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPREWELL-COMPANY-     06-08 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPREWELL-COMPANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL FITS COMPANY'S IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa., Minn., Calif., Ga., Ill.)  (jw) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSEMONT, Pa. _ Inside the company that markets Latrell Sprewell
as ``The American Dream,'' sneakers are strewn on stained
carpeting, jammed against walls and hung from cork boards. The top
executives wear baggy shorts, T-shirts and sneakers, speak in
street lingo and try to get in a daily run of hoops.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Game and Your Momma ... They're Both Phat'' is among the
raft of trash-talk slogans emblazoned on the company's posters and
billboards. Photographs and newspaper clippings, mostly about
Sprewell, are taped to doors. In this cramped suburban office suite
that is more locker room than workplace, Spree is a deity.
</P>
<P>
   There is attitude aplenty at And 1, where the founders were so
consumed with basketball that they started a company in 1993 that
manufactures only footwear and apparel for hoops-obsessed
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   But if you lack serious game _ if you're unwilling to ``break
ankles and rain jumpers with no conscience,'' as one of the
promotional pieces suggests _ And 1 would prefer that you wear
sneakers by Nike, Adidas or Fila.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their single-mindedness made And 1 what it is,'' said Keith
Daly, a senior vice president of Footaction USA, the retail chain,
which is And 1's top customer. ``They're totally focused on a niche
that they live and breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   It offers no running, tennis, soccer or cross-training sneakers.
It has no yen to expand beyond basketball because that's what the
founders care about and what pushed sales from zero in 1993 to an
estimated $120 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   And 1 has impressed retailers and analysts because it has
quadrupled its share of the basketball shoe market from 1997 to
1998, said the NPD Group, an athletic footwear tracking service.
The market has been hurt because of an oversaturation of expensive
shoes endorsed by athletes, many of whom have been cut from
corporate rosters, and a shift to brown shoes like Doc Martens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tapped into a vein of kids playing basketball better than
anyone while everyone was marketing athlete athletes,'' said John
Horan, editor of Sporting Goods Intelligence, an industry
newsletter. ``You could argue that they've focused too much on
basketball and that it's a great strategy to go to $100 million,
but not so great to go to $500 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Having bonded with consumers through T-shirts, sneakers and a
Web site, And 1 embraced the talented, erratic and chaotic
Sprewell. His infamy was secured when he was suspended from the
Golden State Warriors for most of the 1997-98 season for choking
Coach P.J. Carlesimo in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel he deserved a second chance,'' Seth Berger, And 1's
president, said Monday in his cluttered office in a Philadelphia
suburb. ``You can't undo what he did. But he apologized. It was
time to move on. But there will always be people who won't forgive
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And 1 adored Sprewell from the day he joined the Warriors in
1992, envied Converse for signing him to endorse its sneakers and
faxed his agent last year when his ties to Converse ended, offering
to pay him even if he did not play this season. And 1 signed him on
April 19, when the Knicks were 21-20 and not yet in the playoffs.
Four days later, it paid his $25,000 fine when his agent criticized
Knicks' management.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprewell commercial broke last month. Until then, And 1 was
known to basketball aficionados and readers of magazines like
``Inside Stuff.'' But as a company in Nike's muscular shadow, And 1
existed on the public periphery.
</P>
<P>
   The spot shows Sprewell having his hair corn-rowed while he
speaks: ``People say I'm what's wrong with sports. I say I'm a
three-time NBA All-Star. People say I'm America's worst nightmare.
I say I'm the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   In the background, an electric guitar plays ``The Star-Spangled
Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot encapsulates what appears to be a risky strategy. To
the over-30s, Sprewell is easy to reject as a viable commercial
spokesman. But he appeals to the company's 12-to-18-year-old
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our marketing has to make sense to the kids,'' said Jay Coen
Gilbert, vice president and co-founder. ``Every kid with game is
fiercely competitive and talks trash and smack, at least inside his
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger added, ``He acknowledged his mistake but also said,
`Don't forget, I'm a three-time NBA All-Star,' which for every
16-year-old is the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a week of the spot's first national exposure, the Knicks
had beaten Miami in their first-round playoff series and Sprewell
had scored 31 points in consecutive games in the next series
against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The spot provoked instant debate on talk radio and in other
segments of the news media. Was Sprewell worthy of starring in a
commercial campaign for an estimated $500,000 annually? Should he
be treated differently from other commercialized ``bad boys'' like
Allen Iverson or Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, Berger and Tommy Austin launched And 1 in 1993 by
selling T-shirts with trash-talk slogans that were devised during
lively in-house meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert and Berger have known each other since seventh grade at
the Horace Mann School in Manhattan. The threesome had scant
knowledge of manufacturing, finance or administration and no
experience whatever in sporting goods other than being frequent
purchasers of sneakers, T-shirts and shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The T-shirts began selling in 1993 and quickly exploded.
Retailers like Footaction and Foot Locker liked the goods and
encouraged And 1 to accelerate its expansion into footwear by three
years. But their first shoe, one endorsed by Stephon Marbury of the
Minnesota Timberwolves, turned into a minidisaster.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was a ``bad-looking shoe with poor value,'' Gilbert
said. Then, Marbury sprained his ankle badly wearing the And 1
sneaker for the first time early in the first game of his 1996
rookie season. Even worse, And 1 introduced the shoe with what it
called the ``Breaking Ankles'' print campaign, which featured an
X-ray of a broken ankle in the advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury left And 1 last year in a contractual dispute. The
company has since added a dozen other endorsers, including
Philadelphia's Larry Hughes, Sacramento's Chris Webber and
Orlando's Darrell Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Sprewell, whose impact on And 1 sales has not been
felt. ``You could get an immediate impact if you have Michael
Jordan or spend millions of dollars in marketing money,'' Gilbert
said. ``This is a long-term thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said rapid success would neither nudge the company to
expand beyond basketball nor induce it to sell stock through a
public offering. He said, ``Just think of what a shareholder would
think if we signed Sprewell.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
