<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8001 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SLUG-TEX     06-08 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH GROUP OF DRIVERS CLOSING IN ON NASCAR TRUCK STARS SPRAGUE,
HORNADAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Sprague is in his accustomed place: atop the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck series standings.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hornaday isn't too far off his usual pace. He's in third
place, within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like the same old, same old as the series comes to town
for the running of the Pronto Auto Parts 400K on Friday night at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague and Hornaday. Sprague, who won the points title in 1997.
Hornaday who won last year and in '96, with Sprague finishing
second each year.
</P>
<P>
   Hornaday and Sprague, who have combined to win four _ two each _
of the nine races this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both want to win, and that's all there is to it,'' Sprague
said. ``I think we give the fans what they pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is more to the series this year than the two
familiar warriors. The top end of the standings is populated by new
faces, relative newcomers to the series who are determined to knock
off the Big Two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's changing,'' Hornaday said. ``You've got different
drivers winning races, guys in the top five that weren't there
before. The competition level has grown by leaps and bounds. In
this truck series, everybody's trying to make a name for
themselves. These kids want to beat Jack Sprague and Ron Hornaday,
because if they can do that it will put them on the map. So when
that green flag drops, it's tough racing. They come from different
divisions, they're all winners, they've won championships, and when
they strap in there, they want to see the checkered flag, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Compton is one of the guys putting pressure on Sprague and
Hornaday, along with Andy Houston, Dennis Setzer, Kevin Harvick,
Greg Biffle and Kevin Cywinski.
</P>
<P>
   All are in the top 10 in points as the series comes to TMS. Only
Compton and Biffle were there at the end of last season, and none
was in '97.
</P>
<P>
   All are in their second or third full season racing trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have been doing it from the start of the thing, for
the last five years,'' Compton said of Sprague and Hornaday. ``This
is our third year. Everybody is closer to catching up with those
guys and those teams than we ever have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough series, and it's a competitive series. Each week
we see qualifying getting closer and closer, and more trucks on the
lead laps at the end of races.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton is the most consistent driver, not only among the new
faces but in the entire series. He has finished in the top five
eight times in the nine races and is second in points.
</P>
<P>
   He's doing it even though a switch to Dodge from Ford could have
meant a slow start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like starting over,'' Compton said. ``We had a lot to
learn, and a lot of trucks to build.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the switch to the unfamiliar truck, Compton is
continuing a steady rise to the top. In 1997, he finished 13th in
the points and third in the rookie standings. Last year he improved
to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pattern seen in the other newcomers to the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle was eighth as a rookie last year, when he had four poles,
led five of seven races and twice finished second.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up his first career victory this year in the Memphis
200 on May 8 and is seventh in the points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a few things that are major factors,'' Biffle said.
``One is going back to the racetracks now that I've seen them once,
knowing the racetrack and what it looks like. And eliminating the
rookie mistakes I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston could say the same thing. Last year he was second to
Biffle in the rookie standings and 12th overall.
</P>
<P>
   This season the 29-year-old son of former Busch Grand National
standout Tommy Houston is fourth in the points.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is followed by Setzer and Harvick.
</P>
<P>
   Setzer is in his first full-time season in the trucks. He subbed
for an ailing Bob Keselowski last year and finished in the top 10
three times in the final six races, including a victory at the
Dodge California Truck Stop 300 on Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Harvick is the series' ``kid,'' a talented 23-year-old driver.
He had three top-five finishes last year, including a career-best
fourth at the TMS race, and was 17th in the points while also
competing full time in _ and winning _ the Winston West series.
</P>
<P>
   Cywenski, the 1997 American Speed Association champion, was 28th
last year. This year he's up to eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the season is still early. The Pronto Auto Parts 400
is the 10th of 25 races. The challenge for the newcomers is to stay
competitive all season.
</P>
<P>
   But Hornaday, for one, expects the series to remain close.
</P>
<P>
   ``As close as the points are, I think you're going to see five
or six teams coming down to the last couple of races,'' Hornaday
said.
</P>
<P>
   The truck series no longer is just Sprague and Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Sprague, Hornaday and Co. \Ntagtop:Simon Gonzalez,
(817) 390-7760 \Ntagbottom:gonzalez\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2242EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
