<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPERHOLD-DEATH-COX     06-08 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPERHOLD-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 sentenced in 'sleeper-hold' killing of Fort Pierce man
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Troy Orr and Patrick Jameson each began
serving two decades of prison time Tuesday for killing 55-year-old
John Coble with a wrestling ``sleeper-hold'' on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the last things they heard before leaving the
courtroom after sentencing was the agonized voice of Coble's
mother, Dorothy, who stood amid a line of family members a few feet
away from the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was very loving, considerate, and a very giving person,''
she said, trying to stifle sobs. ``You took him away from us and
now we have a very large emptiness that cannot be filled. What kind
of people are you? You killed our son.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr, 39, of West Palm Beach, and Jameson, 31, a transient
originally from Michigan, were charged with first-degree murder and
other crimes after confessing in July to killing Coble. The pair
picked Coble up at a truck stop and they went to his home in Fort
Pierce, police said.
</P>
<P>
   After they got there, Jameson put Coble in a ``sleeper-hold'' he
learned in high school and Orr took his money, car and television.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Marc Cianca sentenced Jameson to 26 years in
prison after Jameson pleaded no contest to second-degree murder and
robbery. Orr, who pleaded no contest to manslaughter and robbery,
got 20 years. Neither is eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Jameson, wearing an orange jail uniform, said he didn't mean to
kill Coble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't an intentional death, your honor,'' he said. ``It
was a wrestling move, a sleeper hold. I did not strangle him. . . .
I just want to apologize to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you heard the mother of the victim,'' Cianca told him.
``I suppose that will soak down deep . . . I just want you to do
time, and an abundance of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Coble said she agreed with the judge's sentence, but
told Orr and Jameson that she and her family members ``do not want
either of you back on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Orr, clad in a sea-blue jail suit, simply told the Coble family,
``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy that they faced,'' Cianca told the defendants,
``will hopefully be brought to some kind of closure today.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
