<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-WATERCHIEF-COX     06-08 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WATERCHIEF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's staff questions salary of interim water chief
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The nearly $20,000-a-month salary of
South Florida's top water manager is drawing questions from Gov.
Jeb Bush's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harvey is drawing $109.92 an hour as interim executive
director of the South Florida Water Management District, which
hired him in March as a temporary consultant.
</P>
<P>
   That's 57 percent more than the $70-an-hour salary of former
Executive Director Sam Poole, who was fired in March by six
Bush-appointed board members.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, district spokesman Bruce Adams said Tuesday,
comes from the dollar value of Poole's other benefits _ including
health insurance, retirement benefits and five hours per week of
accumulated sick and vacation time. As a consultant, Harvey
receives no such benefits, so he's getting them in cash instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is he isn't being paid more than we paid Sam
for the same job,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some board members said this week that they had no idea
they're paying Harvey that much. The board voted March 11 to pay
Harvey ``an amount not to exceed . . . (Poole's) total monthly
compensation'' _ a sum that some interpreted to mean only salary.
</P>
<P>
   The board never voted on the details of the contract. It's being
overseen by Chairman Mike Collins, a friend and business partner of
Harvey's.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers questioned the salary difference last week,
prompting the district to fax a written explanation Friday to
gubernatorial Chief of Staff Sally Bradshaw.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's staff is still studying whether Harvey is getting
a better deal than Poole, Bush spokesman Cory Tilley said Tuesday.
He couldn't explain what drew the staff's attention to Harvey's
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the case is that it's not comparable and Mr. Harvey is
being paid a much larger sum than Mr. Poole was paid, we think the
board should take corrective action and change it,'' Tilley said.
``Obviously it's a little complicated with benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Some board members defended Harvey's contract and said its terms
match what they had approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I understood I was voting for was someone who could keep
the ship on course, and Mr. Harvey has done an extraordinary job of
doing that,'' said Jerry Fernandez, a Miami environmental
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compensation is broader than just salary,'' said Nicolas
Gutierrez, a corporate lawyer in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But two dissenting board members called Harvey's contract a
disturbing surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what I was asked to vote on,'' said Mitchell
Berger, a Broward County lawyer. ``What we voted on was not a gross
monthly stipend for James Harvey. . . . If that's what their intent
was, it should have been spelled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Vera Carter, a former Orange County commissioner, added: ``I'm
extremely surprised. . . . It never crossed my mind that an interim
director would be entitled to anything but salary.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Carter and Michael Minton of Fort Pierce _ all
appointees of former Gov. Lawton Chiles _ voted against firing
Poole and hiring Harvey. The six board members appointed by Bush
supported the actions.
</P>
<P>
   The actions occurred in a single vote March 11, based on wording
that board member Patrick Gleason of Lake Worth has said he
received from Bush Everglades adviser Allison DeFoor.
</P>
<P>
   DeFoor, a former business partner of Harvey and Collins, could
not be reached for comment this week.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's contract caps his total pay at $89,570 for his tenure,
which is set to end one week after a permanent executive director
begins work. It's unclear when that will happen, although the board
is expected to pick a director Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Poole's salary was $145,600 a year, and he left with a combined
$74,410 in severance pay, unused sick leave and vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said Harvey made financial sacrifices to take the district
job, including the interruption of his West Palm Beach lobbying
business during its busiest time, the spring legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey also is losing the $966-a-week salary of his wife,
Suzanne, who works in the district's communications office. She is
on unpaid leave but receiving benefits while Harvey serves as
director.
</P>
<P>
   And Adams said other consultants would charge as much as $265 an
hour for work similar to what Harvey is doing.
</P>
<P>
   But Berger said the district didn't have to hire a consultant to
fill in for Poole. He said the agency could have tapped one of its
two deputy executive directors, or accepted Poole's offer to resign
with six months' notice.
</P>
<P>
   Under his original contract, Harvey was supposed to receive
$39,570 for two months, including 45 working days, which was set to
end May 14.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted May 13 to extend the deal for what some board
members thought was a firm period of five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The final paperwork, signed by Harvey and Collins two weeks
later, contains no set deadline, however. It also entitles Harvey
to as much as $50,000 in additional payments, the equivalent of 11
weeks' pay.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said it's unclear when the new director, whoever that is,
will be able to start work. The finalists are three district
employees and two former U.S. Army Corps of Engineers commanders
living in Virginia and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
