A8006 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-08 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN CHEVEDDEN STRIVES TO HAVE SHAREHOLDERS HEARD THROUGH VOTESD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 26, shareholders of Airborne Freight Corp. voted that
directors be elected every year instead of every three years. The
board recommended a ``no'' vote, but 66 percent of the shareholders
voting were voted ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Airborne hasn't responded, and no board meeting is scheduled
until August. It was not a binding resolution, anyway. But it was a
clear statement by Airborne's owners.
</P>
<P>
   David Anderson, the Seattle company's counsel and secretary,
said those owners are mostly institutions. ``I heard from a few of
them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a reflection on Airborne or Airborne's management. It
tends to be their overall view: They don't want anything to impede
a potential takeover.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure was the work of John Chevedden, a former production
scheduler for Hughes Aircraft who was laid off in 1992. Since then
Chevedden has become a corporate gadfly in the tradition of John
Gilbert and Evelyn Davis, who have been questioning poison pills,
CEO perks, the independence of directors and other such matters for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Chevedden, 53, of Redondo Beach, Calif., has sponsored votes at
Boeing, Paccar, AlliedSignal, General Motors and others.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his measures come up every year. At Boeing, 48 percent
voted for annual election of directors in 1996, 48 percent in 1997,
42 percent in 1998 and 49.8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In Boeing's proxy this year, Chevedden argued that staggered
terms give directors ``three years of isolation from the
consequences of poor decisions.'' Boeing responded that they reduce
``the chance that a third party will effect a sudden, unsolicited
change in the company's direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevedden has other resolutions. At General Motors, 16 percent
of shareholders supported his 1996 proposal that the chairman be
from management. At Northrup Grumman, 12 percent supported his 1998
proposal to limit ``golden parachutes'' for management in case the
company were sold.
</P>
<P>
   This year 64 percent at Northrup Grumman voted for his proposal
that shareholders ballot on the adoption by the company of any
poison pill.
</P>
<P>
   The poison pill is a company by-law in which inexpensive shares
are sold to old stockholders to water down the value of the shares
of an unwelcome buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Such resolutions have to follow the rules of the Securities and
Exchange Commission. ``You have to own stock for a year prior to
the day you submit it,'' Chevedden says. ``If you miss it by one
day, they can disqualify you. I missed on Alaska Air.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of these measures don't get on corporate ballots. The
Investor Responsibility Research Center, a group created by
institutional investors, has been tracking 85 measures that would
repeal the staggered board of directors; about half are expected to
come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   What are the effects of such votes? Jonathan Karpoff, professor
of finance at the University of Washington, says his studies of the
issue have made him skeptical. He says, ``A lot of people, myself
included, went into this research thinking, `This was a good thing.
We're going to find ways to improve company performance.' But the
numbers are different. You find that, on average, shareholder
proposals don't have much impact.'' More important, he says, is
that management not be insulated from a takeover attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Some shareholder votes speak to just that issue. In 1994, 1995
and 1996, Weyerhaeuser shareholders voted on outside proposals to
dismantle the poison pill. In 1996 the resolution passed with 52
percent. That December, the board let the 1980s-vintage poison pill
quietly expire.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Ailman, chief investment officer of the Washington
State Investment Board, says, ``We're not very thrilled with poison
pills or things that may entrench management.''
</P>
<P>
   The board, which manages $52 billion of pension money for public
employees, keeps its stock holdings mostly in index funds. Though
it doesn't vote those shares, it likes the idea of making managers
accountable, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors, he says, are more likely to bring up
issues like the poison pill in private meetings with management.
Chevedden's way is not their way. But some managements are
receptive and some are not. There is more than one way to skin a
cat _ or a CEO.
</P>
<P>
   As for the gadflies like John Chevedden, Ailman says, ``We think
they're helpful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
