<SLUG> BC-GEN-CSUNPRO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIAS SUPPORTERS WANT REVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Protesting the choice of Dick Dull as Cal State
Northridge's athletic director, supporters of Robert Arias'
candidacy for the job are seeking a review of the selection
process.
</P>
<P>
   William ``Blinky'' Rodriguez and members of the CSUN Advisory
Board who supported Arias are planning to ask Assembly Speaker
Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, and CSU Chancellor Charles
Reed to look into Dull's hiring on May 26. Dull resigned from his
post as the athletic director at Moravian College, a Division III
school in Bethlehem, Pa., to take the CSUN job.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Dull was the athletic director at Maryland when the
program came under fire after basketball star Len Bias'
cocaine-induced death. Dull resigned five months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just feel like we can't allow it to be `business as usual,'
'' said Rodriguez, a community leader who was an outspoken advocate
of Arias. ``(Dull) doesn't know the community. He is not making
fund-raising a No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Swisher, the media-relations spokesperson for the CSU
office, said Reed is on the East Coast and unavailable for comment.
Swisher said he didn't anticipate Reed taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   ``That search was complete and it was a campus-based decision,''
Swisher said.
</P>
<P>
   John Chandler, who works in CSUN's public-information office,
said the university stands by the choice of Dull, calling him
``eminently qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias, a San Fernando Valley resident, was one of four finalists
for the job that went to Dull, who starts July 1. Rodriguez said
supporters of the inquiry include CSUN Advisory Board members Lee
Alpert, Leroy Chase, Edward Moreno and David Honda.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our understanding, the support (for Arias) was staunch,''
Rodriguez said. ``Many letters were sent to Blenda before she left.
She never answered one of them. We want to know what happened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8008 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-TEXAS-     06-08 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-SUSPECT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$50,000 REWARD OFFERED FOR SUSPECT LINKED TO DEATHS IN TEXAS,
KENTUCKY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ky.) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
and STEPHEN JOHNSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Law officers from Beaumont to San Antonio have formed
a task force to help capture a drifter suspected in six murders in
Texas and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   And authorities are offering a $50,000 reward for information
leading to the arrest and conviction of Rafael Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is brutal,'' said Houston homicide Lt. Ronald Walker, a
task force spokesman. ``In all instances, there are massive head
injuries. It's a blitz-type attack. This is a purely mean man, and
everyone needs to be looking for this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although motor vehicles and other items have been stolen in the
killings, Walker said police do not believe money or property are
motivating the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more of a power-type play, sexual
gratification,'' he said Tuesday after a meeting here of state,
local and federal officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get him soon, I'm afraid we are going to find
another innocent victim. He's just not going to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez, 39, is suspected in killings in the Houston
area and in a corridor along the railroad line that runs along
Interstate 10.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a suspect in an Aug. 29, 1997, slaying near a
railroad track in Lexington, Ky., and an investigator said DNA
evidence gathered from the crime scene there is being compared with
that from area homicides. A woman was raped during the Lexington
slaying but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has also been linked to slayings in Weimar,
Schulenburg and West University Place. All information pertaining
to the case will be channeled through the Houston FBI Command
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Houston FBI Special Agent in Charge Don K. Clark said that based
on a Harris County burglary indictment of Resendez-Ramirez, the
federal government has charged him with unlawful flight to avoid
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has a criminal record in California, Florida
and New Mexico on charges ranging from carrying an illegal weapon
to residential burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez is also considered a suspect in a killing in
southwest Houston, where the body of Noemi Dominguez, 26, was found
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   She died from a blow to the head, and her white 1993 Honda Civic
with license number JJH 57N was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Police have found no concrete evidence linking Resendez-Ramirez
to the killing, but investigators said similarities between it and
the other cases indicate a strong possibility he was involved.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said evidence at Dominguez's house, near a rail line, is
still being processed.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity to rail lines was a key link that investigators
noted when the probe into the multiple area slayings began.
</P>
<P>
   The first case occurred Dec. 17, when the body of Dr. Claudia
Benton, 39, was found in her West University Place home just a few
blocks from railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   She had been beaten and stabbed to death and sexually assaulted.
Her stolen Jeep Cherokee was found abandoned in San Antonio with
Resendez-Ramirez's fingerprint in the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   In March, he was indicted on a charge of burglary in the case.
This charge led to the federal count against Resendez-Ramirez,
allowing the FBI to search for him anywhere in the country, Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have linked Resendez-Ramirez to the deaths of the
Rev. Norman ``Skip'' Sirnic, 46, and his wife, Karen, 47. They were
found beaten to death with a sledgehammer in the parsonage behind
the Weimar United Church of Christ in Colorado County when they did
not show up for services May 2.
</P>
<P>
   About three weeks later, investigators said evidence found in
the Sirnics' home linked Resendez-Ramirez to the Benton case.
Authorities have declined to release specific details.
</P>
<P>
   The Sirnics' stolen pickup was found May 28 by police in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   One week later, a relative found the body of Josephine Konvicka,
73, in her house in Fayette County, just 3 1/2 miles from the
Sirnics' home.
</P>
<P>
   Konvicka had been beaten to death and the killer tried to steal
her car but could not locate the keys. Resendez-Ramirez's
fingerprints were found in her home, also near railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington victim was University of Kentucky student
Christopher Maier, 21. He was beaten to death and his girlfriend
assaulted as they walked along railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said investigators have been flooded with tips and leads.
Those seeking to provide information on Resendez-Ramirez's
whereabouts can call the FBI Command Center at 713-479-6325 or
713-693-5000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are checking any locations where he may be, soup kitchens,
homeless shelters, places where he can get a shower, food,'' Walker
said. ``Wherever these types of individuals congregate, we're
talking to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said Resendez-Ramirez could be watching his potential
victims or he may simply hop off a train and strike.
</P>
<P>
   He described Resendez-Ramirez as being very elusive, common and
someone who uses anonymity to move about freely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is how we view the homeless,'' Walker said. ``We walk by
and don't see them. This is the type we are dealing with here, a
transient, the type we have a tendency to overlook.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers from more than 20 police agencies met at DPS
headquarters here to pool their resources and coordinate efforts in
capturing Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado County Sheriff R.H. Wied said they hope to find the
suspect by sharing knowledge about the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   An in Hispanic man found dead Friday in Stephen F. Austin State
Park from a head blow was not specifically listed as a suspected
victim of Resendez-Ramirez, and Clark said he did not want to
comment on that case.
</P>
<P>
   The park lies along I-10, which runs through the communities
where the Sirnics and Konvicka were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Wied said officers in his county will be monitoring all freight
trains going through the county and stop them if unauthorized
passengers are spotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make sure that this is not the suspect we are looking
for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weimar Police Chief Bill Livingston said his department has
doubled its patrol activity since the Sirnics' slayings and that
Colorado County officers and DPS troopers are checking the city and
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is around there, we're going to find him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
