<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY READING AND MATH SCORES FALL SHARPLY
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew released citywide
reading and math test scores Tuesday that showed a sharp decline
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   He attributed the plunge to new, more challenging tests and a
higher standard of performance. But he made no effort to play down
the grimness of the new statistics _ the results of citywide
reading and math tests given in third, fifth, sixth and seventh
grades this spring.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was determined ``not to make excuses'' for the
scores, and he pledged to move aggressively in the next weeks to
hold administrators, teachers and students accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Crew said that he would require 70,000 third-, sixth- and
eighth-graders to go to summer school as he phased in tougher
promotional standards that would be expanded to other grades. As a
result of the fourth-grade reading test introduced by the state
this year, which 67 percent of city students failed, 16,000
fourth-graders will be strongly urged to go to summer school, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would set performance targets for next year _
requiring the city's 32 school districts and individual schools to
meet either a test-score target or a target for improvement. Saying
he was distressed by the wide achievement gap between black and
Hispanic children and white and Asian ones, he said he would also
set targets by race, in a program similar to one that has been
adopted in Texas but which generated immediate opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the targets for blacks and Hispanics going to be higher or
lower than for whites and Asians?'' asked Michael Meyers, executive
director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition, who said he would
watch the policy closely with an eye to a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Crew also promised to use the test scores to sanction and
replace district superintendents, principals and teachers who were
not performing well. ``You are looking at this system going through
a watershed moment in reform,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The city scores have traditionally been among the most closely
watched measures of student performance. Scores have risen steadily
over the last few years, and last year Crew boasted that students
were performing just shy of the national average in reading and
well above it in math, a remarkable achievement given the large
concentration of immigrants and children in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The new scores show students performing significantly below the
national average in reading and about average in math. The scores
of third-graders _ the centerpiece of a focus on literacy by Crew
and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ dropped most of all, in both reading
and math.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was ``very alarmed and concerned,'' Giuliani renewed
his call for radical reform of the system, including abolishing the
semi-independent Board of Education and placing the schools
directly under the mayor's control.
</P>
<P>
   But he stopped short of blaming Crew, saying the chancellor had
``done a very good job within a system that is totally
nonfunctional.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WR     06-08 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the court.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he was taken into custody, Schwarz appeared to be glaring
at the federal prosecutors in the case and his reaction to the
verdict was one of ``disbelief, shock, rage,'' according to his
lawyer, Stephen Worth, who promised to appeal. Schwarz was taken to
the Metropolitan Correctional Center in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the grounds for the appeal, Worth said, would be that
the case was tainted by the dramatic confession of Volpe. In that
confession, which occurred outside the presence of the jury, Volpe
did not implicate any other officer by name.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe confessed to torturing Louima only after a parade of other
police officers testified that they saw him in the 70th Precinct
station house brandishing a feces-stained stick that he used to
brutalize Louima and bragging about how he had humiliated him.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's plea on May 25, after three weeks of testimony,
fundamentally changed the landscape of the trial, removing the
principal defendant and changing the focus of a prosecution that
had massed its artillery on him. The case against the four other
defendants was less substantial. It took only two days after
Volpe's plea for the prosecution to conclude its case.
</P>
<P>
   None of the officers testified in his own defense, and neither
the prosecution nor the defense lawyers called Volpe to testify
after his guilty plea, saying his testimony was not believable.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz, along with Bruder and Wiese, was also accused of
beating Louima in a patrol car while transporting him from a street
brawl to Brooklyn's 70th Precinct station house. All three were
acquitted of those charges. Volpe earlier admitted that he
assaulted Louima in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese, Schwarz and Bruder still face charges of conspiring to
obstruct justice by misleading investigators as to Schwarz's role
in the bathroom torture.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo was also acquitted of trying to cover up the beating of
Louima in the car and of a separate assault by Volpe on a second
Haitian immigrant, Patrick Antoine, 38.
</P>
<P>
   The cases against Schwarz, Bruder and Wiese, who had been free
on $100,000 bail each since their indictments last year, were
largely circumstantial and less solid than the case against Volpe,
though the evidence against Schwarz appeared stronger than that
against Wiese and Bruder.
</P>
<P>
   Marvyn Kornberg, Volpe's lawyer, said that the jury wrongly
convicted Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really disappointed in the fact that Officer Schwarz
was convicted,'' said Kornberg, adding that, on Volpe's behalf, he
had ``advised the prosecutors that the other officer in the
bathroom was not Officer Schwarz but, in fact, another officer
whose name was given to them at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter who that officer was, Kornberg refused to
divulge a name. Federal prosecutors angrily dismissed Kornberg's
credibility.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I dare say that neither Volpe nor his attorney have any
credibility with respect to any factual issue touching on this
case, including the identity of the other officer or officers with
him,'' said Vinegrad, referring to Kornberg's opening argument in
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   In that argument, Kornberg suggested that Louima had suffered
his internal injuries _ a torn rectum and bladder _ in a consensual
sexual encounter with another man. Because of Volpe's guilty plea,
Kornberg did not have the opportunity to present any evidence or
witnesses to bolster such a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe's crime and Kornberg's behavior in the trial also drew
criticism from a lawyer representing Wiese. Joseph Tacopina said
that the ``stench'' of Volpe's crime and the ``outlandish,
outrageous theories'' of Kornberg, damaged all the defendants in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Several days before Volpe pleaded guilty and threw himself on
the mercy of the court, he tried to make a plea deal with the
prosecutors. He reportedly told prosecutors what Kornberg announced
Tuesday _ that Schwarz was not the other officer in the bathroom.
But prosecutors refused to make a plea deal.
</P>
<P>
   When Volpe pleaded guilty, he said ``there was another police
officer in the bathroom with me'' but ``that police officer saw
what was going on did nothing to stop it.'' He did not identify the
officer.
</P>
<P>
   While Volpe and Kornberg have not said publicly who the second
officer was, it appeared from court documents that he was referring
to Wiese, who told investigators that he walked into the bathroom
after the assault.
</P>
<P>
   In the first days after the 1997 attack on Louima, Wiese, in an
unsuccessful effort to make his own deal, said he walked into the
bathroom after Volpe had attacked Louima with the stick, according
to the documents. He said there was no other officer there.
Investigators said he failed a lie detector test, and as a result
no deal was made with him. His lawyer said he passed a later test.
</P>
<P>
   In the case against Schwarz, Louima could not identify the
officer who he said held him down during Volpe's attack in the
bathroom, but he said it was done by the same officer who had
driven him to the station. Police records indicate that Schwarz was
the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Two policemen gave major testimony against Schwarz. Detective
Eric Turetzky and Officer Mark Schofield said they saw him walk
Louima, handcuffed and with his pants down, from station house desk
where he was booked on assault charges _later dropped _ directly to
the bathroom area.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Schwarz, Worth, who vigorously cross-examined
these witnesses, insisted that his client was never in the bathroom
with Louima and that Louima was mistaken in asserting that it was
the driver of the car who held him down. He emphasized that
Turetzky and Schofield had said they saw Schwarz taking Louima
toward the bathroom, but not into it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
