<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAGIC OF FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How high do the various flying creatures (birds, bats, bugs)
fly?
</P>
<P>
   J.R., Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin ital) The jet above the Ivory Coast
</P>
<P>
   Was seven miles high
</P>
<P>
   As the Rupell's Griffon Vulture rode
</P>
<P>
   the thermals in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The plane collided with the bird
</P>
<P>
   The vulture was no more
</P>
<P>
   But now we know how high they go
</P>
<P>
   The heights to which birds soar. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   A. And then there was mountain climber L.W. Swan, who heard the
barheaded goose at 28,000 feet on the Himalayan peak Mt. Makalu. Or
the alpine chough (as in that was one tough bird) that followed a
1924 Mt. Everest expedition up to 26,000 feet scavenging food from
their camp.
</P>
<P>
   But those are the oddities in the avian record books. Common
birds like warblers, thrushes, and shore birds commonly fly at 10
to 20,000 feet, according to Simon Perkins, field ornithologist for
the Massachusetts Audubon Society. But they're not up there just
for the view. They go to those heights to migrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes too much energy to get up to greater altitudes if
they're only going to come right back down,'' Perkins says. ``At
higher altitudes the air is more stable, which makes for easier
flying. It's worth it for them to do the work to get up into that
stable air for their long migratory flights. It is a trade off
though, because the air is thinner, which requires them to work
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   But birds are such efficient fliers, he says, that they use very
little oxygen, so even the oxygen-poor air at higher altitudes has
enough to keep them going. Many birds migrate at night, Perkins
adds, because night air is more stable than daytime air being
warmed and stirred up by the heat of the sun.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) The free-tailed bat of Mexico
</P>
<P>
   spends summer nights quite high.
</P>
<P>
   In search of buggy dinners
</P>
<P>
   10,000 feet up in the sky. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kunz of Boston University, a Professor of Biology and
world-renowned expert on the 1,000 species of Chiroptera, (bats
make up one quarter of all mammals) is about to head to the 15
caves in southern Texas that each house between seven and 20
million Mexican free-tailed bats. He says radar has seen these
flying mammals at 10,000 feet feeding on insects carried that high
by thermal air currents.
</P>
<P>
   Kunz says stray bats have been at higher altitudes including
some specimens found 16,000 feet up in the Andes mountains.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) Cold-blooded bugs that flap their wings
</P>
<P>
   Need warmish air to fly
</P>
<P>
   Without it they will crash right down
</P>
<P>
   and some will even die.
</P>
<P>
   The chill above 6000 feet
</P>
<P>
   Is just too cold to take
</P>
<P>
   To try and fly much higher
</P>
<P>
   Is a flying bug's mistake. (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elson Shields, Entomologist at Cornell University, uses
radio controlled planes towing nets to collect bugs at various
altitudes. He says they need air that's at least 50 degrees
Fahrenheit to warm them enough so they can use the muscles that
keep their wings extended. Cooler than that and bugs can't even
float along like a glider. The wings retract and down they come.
Shields says 6,000 feet is the highest anyone has ever found bugs
buzzing around.
</P>
<P>
   Of course insects reach much greater heights. Non-flying species
like spiders and caterpillar larvae fly by spinning long silk
strands that are picked up in the wind and carry the little
creatures like parasails. Strong updrafts can carry them miles
high. In some cases, they freeze to death. Sometimes they come back
down and thaw out just in time. Shields says their light weight and
strong exoskeleton that forms the outer shell of their bodies
protect them from death after falling from such altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Shields says that many winged insects are experts at using the
wind to help them fly. One fascinating example is the potato leaf
hopper, a bug just one sixteenth of an inch long, that migrates
between Georgia and New York. It apparently can sense changes in
barometric pressure that occur at the beginning of stormy weather.
The tiny leaf hoppers launch themselves into the storm front and
can make their thousand-mile journey flapping along with the help
of hundred mile an hour winds in just 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
