<SLUG> BC-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: into it.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Moreover, Worth pointed out that the first police investigator
who spoke to Louima, at Coney Island Hospital a day and a half
after he was attacked, testified that Louima told him he had been
placed in a cell for 10 minutes between the time he was booked at
the station desk and when he was taken into the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Worth called this a crucial contradiction of Louima's later
accounts, and his trial testimony, that he had been taken directly
from the desk to the bathroom. The lawyer also said it called into
question the testimony of the officers who said Louima was taken
straight to the bathroom area.
</P>
<P>
   He also accused the prosecution of improperly hiding the account
by the investigator, Sgt. William Hargrove, until nearly the end of
the trial. Prosecutors denied this, and dismissed the account of
the 10-minute interval in the cell, saying that Louima had been
``under heavy medication'' during the hospital interview. They
insisted that the rest of his account was consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked repeatedly after the verdict if a third officer might have
been in the bathroom with Volpe and Schwarz when Louima was
brutalized, Carter said he would not respond because ``that is
going to be the subject matter of the next trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney said that Schwarz, Bruder and Wiese will be
tried for obstruction of justice in connection with charges that
they invented a phony story about what occurred in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   As for the acquittal of the three officers of beating Louima,
Carter said he was disappointed but not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has historically been difficult to obtain convictions in
assault cases where there are allegations of assaults by police
officers, where the only witnesses to the assaults are the victims
themselves and the police officers,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   The abhorrent details of the case made it politicall
