A8145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-NYT &LR;      06-08 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LOUIMA VERDICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Zachary Carter said it best Tuesday as he stood
outside the Brooklyn federal courthouse and assessed the latest
verdicts in the Abner Louima case. The most important lesson that
New York City police should learn from the Louima trial, he said,
is that their ``worst betrayal'' is not testifying against a fellow
officer. It is betraying their oath of office out of ``a false
loyalty'' to colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's case was bolstered dramatically in May by a series of
police officers who broke the old code of silence and testified
against officer Justin Volpe. After having protested his innocence
for months, Volpe then confessed to sodomizing Louima with a stick
in a police precinct house bathroom. A federal jury in Brooklyn on
Tuesday convicted Charles Schwarz as the officer who held Louima
down in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   While the same jury acquitted three other officers on charges of
beating Louima in a squad car and lying to the FBI, the verdicts do
not end the court action in the Louima case. Nor should these
acquittals close this matter within the Police Department, where
internal investigators are expected to judge the conduct of these
officers and others as well.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz and two other defendants, Officers Thomas Wiese and
Thomas Bruder, still face court charges of obstructing justice,
allegations that they deny. Carter said the three were accused of
``offering an alternative and false scenario about what went on in
that bathroom.'' Thus this next trial will focus even more clearly
on the issue of whether the officers tried to cover up the Louima
attack during the investigation that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, it could help destroy the code of secrecy
to the benefit not only of the Police Department brass but also of
those honorable officers who have long chafed at the unwritten
rules that require silence. The Louima case brings home the old
warning that silence about a bad police officer can make trouble
for the entire department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
