<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL: THE ABSENCE SPEAKS LOUDER THAN LOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As strategies go, Jeff Van Gundy has come up with
better ones than starting Latrell Sprewell. The New York Knicks'
coach was predictably weathering the usual criticism and
second-guessing Tuesday for not staying with his bigger lineup in
Game 4, as if a dynasty featuring Kurt Thomas at power forward was
suddenly in danger of crumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell failed to energize the offense and the Knicks gave up
home-court advantage in the Eastern Conference finals Monday night.
But Van Gundy's decision on Sprewell had little do with why the
Indiana Pacers will most likely wake the No. 8-seeded Knicks from
their sweet NBA finals dream.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' problem is not that Sprewell's name was announced
during player introductions Monday night. The problem is that
Patrick Ewing's name was not.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing has been out only two games, and the Knicks already miss
his defensive rebounding and his go-to savvy in the fourth quarter.
Everyone has an occasional rotten night in this league. Yet if you
watched closely enough on Monday, you would swear that Sprewell,
Allan Houston and Larry Johnson took turns not wanting the ball at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the National Basketball Association playoffs
are about matchups. Who can guard whom and who cannot. Who is
quicker and who is bigger. By not allowing them to run the break on
offense, the Pacers have neutralized Sprewell and Houston, the two
best offensive weapons the Knicks have now.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby's elongated, 7-foot frame aside, the Knicks have
not nullified Indiana's size advantage. The Knicks were
outrebounded, 41-30, in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   There is a reason Dale Davis and Antonio Davis were able to
defend and help out on Johnson on Monday; they don't have to help
double-team a 7-foot scoring threat in the post. There is a reason
Camby's face and corn-silk-thin body contort when he is called for
a questionable foul; as a young, still unproven player, he gets
little respect from the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Cold-but-true NBA playoff fact: if Ewing gets plowed into by
Antonio Davis at the end of Game 2, an offensive foul is probably
called instead of the block on Camby. At any rate, as this
entertaining series heads for perhaps a seventh game in
Indianapolis on Sunday, so, too, does the Patrick Redemption Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ewing, his supporters are stubborn. They sometimes utter
their drivel about why the Knicks can't win without him based only
on their resentment toward the Patrick-Must-Go faction. John
Thompson, a devout member of that fraternity, said last week how
much Ewing will be missed when he is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Bias and all, Thompson was right. There will be something sad
about the Knicks' finally going down and not being able to have a
shot at winning that elusive championship ring for their franchise
center.
</P>
<P>
   It says something about Ewing's career in New York that he may
eventually be accorded more respect with his injured left foot in a
walking boot on the sideline than when he played gallantly on the
floor to help get this team this far.
</P>
<P>
   During the fourth quarter of Game 4, the overhead scoreboard
honed in on a fan holding up a sign that read ``Do It for Ewing.''
There was a smattering of applause, but after the initial rush no
one bothered to put their hands together.
</P>
<P>
   Few times in American sports history has there been a prominent
superstar so disconnected from the people and the city he plays in.
That lack of public affection is mostly Ewing's fault. Private and
reclusive, he rarely avails himself to the people who paid and
clapped 14 seasons for him. Nor did he accommodate in any
substantive way a news media contingent that could have been his
conduit to the public.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous appearances in the name of charity and
many genuine moments with sickly, wide-eyed children in the locker
room after games. But there was no real mutual love, the comforting
feeling that he and New York were hitched _ for better or worse
until retirement did them part.
</P>
<P>
   Only now, in repose, do you get snippets of Ewing's personal
feelings on matters of importance. He jokes so often about being
traded in the off season, you almost wonder if he is fed up with
the franchise to a point that he might try to force the Knicks to
explore deals for him.
</P>
<P>
   His figurehead role in the lockout engendered more vitriol
against him than almost any of his last-second missed shots. His
major crime, at age 36, was reporting to training camp too heavy
and out of condition. He can be stubborn, fussy and as selfish as
any career-driven person making a lot of money in this city. Ewing
indeed gives you a litany of reasons it is hard to identify with
him on a regular-guy level.
</P>
<P>
   But not once he takes the court. This season he did that as a
shell of the player who once dominated in the middle. Battered body
and all, you saw the best of Ewing these last two months. Not just
the skill to break down a younger, stronger player inside, but the
grit to keep playing on through the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were underdogs to begin with, and they don't go on to
lose the series because Sprewell starts or comes off the bench.
They may have lost to the Pacers when the results of that magnetic
resonance imaging test showed a partial tear in the left Achilles'
tendon of Patrick Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Cold-but-true fact: the Knicks can't win it without him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
