<SLUG> BC-SUDAN-BROWNBACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNBACK, SENATE COLLEAGUES SAY SUDANESE ATROCITIES MUST BE
STOPPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just back from a trip to famine-ridden Sudan, Sen.
Sam Brownback of Kansas said Tuesday that the United States needs
to press the Khartoum government to end the genocide and slavery of
its own people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have arguably the worst human-rights situation in the
world in Sudan: 1.9 million killed over the last 10 years, 4
million internally displaced, with some of the most horrifying
suffering you can imagine,'' Brownback said. ``It needs to be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback, a Republican member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, said that during his brief trip to the east African
nation, he saw bombed-out hospitals and evidence that the
government was contributing to a famine by denying food aid to
needy parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan, which the State Department considers a terrorist nation,
has been embroiled in a civil war for 15 years. Rebels in the
south, who are largely black Christians and members of tribes, are
fighting the primarily Arab Muslim government.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International has branded the government's war on the
south as ``ethnic cleansing.'' The United Nations, relief agencies
and other groups have reported religious persecution, the
government bombing of civilians and an extensive slave trade.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Committee on Refugees reports that 10,000 southern
Sudanese are forced into slavery each month.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Donald Payne, a New Jersey Democrat, and Rep. Thomas
Tancredo, a Colorado Republican, accompanied Brownback to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Payne called Sudan the ``unknown disaster.'' Trancredo said
Sudan ``makes Kosovo look like a Sunday school picnic.'' He said
U.S. national security is at risk because Sudan exports terrorism
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is considering legislation to formally condemn the
slave trade, impose an arms embargo on the Khartoum government and
increase American support for the relief efforts and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said members of Congress hope to meet soon with
President Clinton. Standing at the senator's side, exiled Sudanese
Catholic Bishop Macram Gassis said the situation has been allowed
to go on for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of slavery, the issue of rape, the issue of the
destruction of the traditions and customs of an African ethnic
group is a reality,'' he said. ``Time has gone by while people are
discussing. Committees, subcommittees. Commissions, subcommissions.
And in the meantime, the people are dying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
