<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT     06-08 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION DEPARTMENT OFFICIAL HEADS LIST FOR SCHOOL
SUPERINTENDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A top-ranking official in the U.S. Department
of Education is a leading candidate to become Kansas City school
superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Pascal D. Forgione Jr., 54, commissioner of education
statistics, will leave the $120,000-a-year federal post this month
because the Clinton administration will not renominate him for a
four-year term. Forgione confirmed his interest in the Kansas City
job this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the community has a lot of reflecting to do on what
they need,'' Forgione said. ``I think there will be a lot of
conversations ahead of us, but I am very interested in looking for
an urban superintendency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Board of Education has discussed raising the
salary for the next superintendent. The last person to hold the
job, Henry Williams, made about $200,000 a year in pay and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Desegregation Monitoring Committee, which is
screening candidates, briefly discussed submitting only Forgione's
name to the school board, possibly as early as this week. The
school board will make the selection.
</P>
<P>
   But committee Chairman John Murphy said Tuesday the three-member
panel now hopes to submit at least three names, possibly next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the initial selection,'' Murphy said. ``Our
internal struggle now is to find three strongly qualified
candidates. Maybe we're being overly selective in our criteria, but
our desire is to get the very best candidates we can find so they
end up with an outstanding superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring committee says it continues to seek applicants
but has not ruled out reconsidering previously rejected candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is scheduled to meet privately today with the
school board to discuss the search. Some board members are angered
by its involvement and said they have not been kept informed.
</P>
<P>
   Some board members also want to find out why previous
candidates, including Phyllis Chase, interim chief administrator
for curriculum and instruction, were rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just a lot of confusion over this whole process,''
school board President John Rios said. ``We know nothing about the
person the DMC has selected at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Confirmed as an education commissioner in 1996, Forgione
oversees a federal agency with a $68 million budget and 116
employees. The National Center for Education Statistics collects,
analyzes and disseminates education data, including the National
Assessment of Educational Progress. The center also conducts
international comparisons of statistics, such as the Third
International Mathematics and Science Study.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley, in a news release, credited
Forgione with making the agency's complex data widely
understandable and more publicly accessible. He also credited
Forgione with making the collected information more relevant and
timely.
</P>
<P>
   Forgione called his work as commissioner a ``terrific journey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to communicate a vision and a commitment that
data are a federal role that can be an asset to states and
districts and this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgione last week announced his resignation. Administration
officials told him they feared a confirmation fight because of his
failure to file his income tax returns in a timely way for eight
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   Forgione acknowledged he missed the filing deadline but said he
was always due a refund and violated no federal tax laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a technical mistake in not completing and getting my
refund back, but I had no idea that there would be this severe
consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that he twice has passed FBI background checks and that
his tax situation did not arise during his Senate confirmation
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in my background professionally that would
cause me any difficulty,'' he said. ``This is a private issue and
one I will certainly never let happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Other educators and former department officials contend the
administration is punishing Forgione for criticizing Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made a campaign-style appearance at a news conference in
February to announce that national reading scores had improved.
Some House members called the appearance inappropriate and said the
results should have been released independently, and Forgione
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are supposed to be an independent statistical agency, and I
have called things the way I felt they needed to be called,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The advisory board that oversees Forgione's agency panned the
administration's move and called Forgione's departure a
``tremendous loss.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(The board) is deeply grateful for what Pat has accomplished
in his all-too-short tenure,'' Andrew C. Porter, chairman of the
Advisory Council on Education Statistics, said in a letter to
Riley. ``We advised you that he be retained, and we are
disappointed that he has not been.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgione said a move from the federal level to a school district
would take him back to his roots.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut native began his career as a U.S. history
teacher in a 3,000-student high school in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to school, earned two master's degrees and a
doctorate and took a series of jobs before returning home in the
late 1970s to Connecticut. He eventually rose to director of
research, evaluation and assessment for the state Education
Department.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1991, Forgione took over as Delaware's state
superintendent of public instruction, where he was credited with
starting large-scale reform of the state's 19 school districts. He
served until June 1996 when he was nominated for the federal post.
</P>
<P>
   In Delaware, Forgione oversaw an $18 million project to toughen
academic standards in hopes of improving student performance. It
included development of a new curriculum and new instructional
methods.
</P>
<P>
   Forgione has three grown sons and recently remarried.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, lawyer for the plaintiff children in the
school desegregation case, spent an afternoon last week
interviewing Forgione in Washington and came away impressed. He
called Forgione the most capable superintendent candidate the
district has had in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very articulate, passionate person,'' Benson said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Forgione sees a district that is more
financially stable than most urban school systems. He also
considers the district small enough to enact reform that will bring
widespread improvement during his tenure. He considers the public
hungry for reform of its school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity to give leadership in a caring and committed
community is something I would value,'' Forgione said. ``The key
for me is to find the right community that would have the
opportunities where I could exercise leadership and be a resource
to the board, the community and educators. At this moment I'm very
much open to that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
