<HEADLINE>
FAIR PROMOTES ALTERNATIVE TRANSPORTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA THESING  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Air pollution does a lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   It contributes to asthma. It converts some die-hard drivers into
walkers and carpoolers. And, perhaps strangest of all, it makes
allies out of environmental activists, corn farmers and carmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The varying agendas of those groups converged Tuesday at Way to
Go, an annual fair promoting alternative transportation that would
lower pollution and improve health.
</P>
<P>
   The fair offered employees from nearby corporations a chance to
view transportation options. Displays offered information from
transit agencies, ride-share groups, bicycle and pedestrian
associations, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bearly, a senior production planner for Hallmark Cards Inc.,
wandered through the fair with some co-workers to inspect the
ethanol-, propane- and electric-powered vehicles on display.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ethanol is definitely a good idea,'' Bearly said. ``I love
the idea, because (American farmers) produce the product. It also
gives the farmers something to do with their crops.''
</P>
<P>
   The alternative fuels benefit the region with an ethanol plant
under construction in St. Joseph, Mo., said Kevin Lickteig,
research and programs assistant for the Kansas Corn Growers
Association. Alternative fuels also reduce American dependence on
foreign oil, Lickteig said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the federal government already had 300
ethanol-powered fleet vehicles on Kansas City roads and that more
private fleets would use alternative fuels to meet federal
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Lickteig's organization showcased vehicles that could run on
either an ethanol fuel or regular gasoline. Dodge, Plymouth and
Chrysler minivans, as well as the Ford Taurus and the Ford Ranger,
can come from the manufacturer with this dual capacity at no extra
cost, Lickteig said. Honda also has a model with the ethanol
option.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two Goodyear representatives were on hand to answer
questions from motorists who wanted to retrofit their vehicles to
run on propane as well as gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Oades, owner of Goodyear service centers in Overland Park
and Kansas City, Kan., said alternative fuels would help improve
air quality and health _ an issue in which Oades has a special
interest. Oades said that two of his children had asthma and that
he believed their breathing ailment came from pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Guebara, who represented the American Lung Association,
said eight persons in the Kansas City region died of asthma in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asthma is on the rise regionally as well as nationally,'' she
said. ``We've got to do something about the quality of air control,
or we're not going to attack the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's fair was coordinated by the Metropolitan Energy
Center, the Clean Cities Coalition, the Mid-America Regional
Council and Bridging the Gap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
