<HEADLINE>
JAIL STAFF HAD BEEN WARNED ABOUT INMATE BEFORE ESCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEYTESVILLE, Mo. _ The Chariton County Jail staff had been
warned about Donnie Lee Fisher before his escape Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reinforced that he might be a danger,'' Sheriff Chris
Hughes said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher broke out of jail but was captured the next day nearby.
He was being held after escaping from a Georgia jail and getting
into a shootout with police in February in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Chariton County's jail in Keytesville is 5 years old and before
Sunday never had an escape. The prison holds 32 inmates and is
nearly full.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said his jail would add guards and install aluminum
safety wires in the exercise yard.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher had been transferred to the jail in a program in which
the county is paid to hold out-of-county inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Many counties take in inmates as a source of revenue. Their
counterparts often need relief because their jails are outdated,
crowded or closed. Chariton County receives $30 per day per inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was transferred from Randolph County.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, who was transferred Tuesday afternoon to the city jail
in Moberly, had become proficient at prison escapes.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 15 he and two other men hid in the back of a food
service van as it left the Georgia State Prison in Reidsville. They
then attacked the driver after the van was clear of the prison
fences.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and Roy Kenneth Sanford, 30, fled to central Missouri.
Police tracked them to a trailer in Huntsville, where both were
arrested after the shootout. Five officers were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was convicted in 1991 of kidnapping and robbery in
Pulaski County, Mo. In 1994, he began serving an eight-year
sentence in Georgia on kidnapping charges there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
