<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL AND HOUSTON: DYSFUNCTION LOVES COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once their insecurities with one another dissolved
near season's end, Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston of the New
York Knicks formed a happy couple on the court. It did not matter
if they liked the same music or shared the same barber, because
they had success in common.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the thread that tied them together through the
first round of the playoffs, and then the second. They were
communicating on the court, running side by side on the fast break
and finding the other when their own path was cut off.
</P>
<P>
   They made quite a pair until the Indiana Pacers began to come
between them in the Eastern Conference finals. For four games of
this four-of-seven-game series that stands even at two games apiece
heading into Game 5 on Wednesday night in Indiana, the Pacers have
used Reggie Miller like a stick for Houston to chase and have cut
off the lifeline to Sprewell's offense by nearly eliminating
fast-break opportunities. One has been run ragged, the other has
been foiled by Indiana's size in the halfcourt. Houston has been
listless on offense, while Sprewell has been lethargic on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Houston and Sprewell do not look so great together.
Their combined shooting percentage is hovering at a miserable 35.7
percent, their turnovers are up, and Sprewell, for one, has had
only five assists the entire series. He had none during his first
start of the playoffs in Monday's deflating 90-78 loss at Madison
Square Garden. So it seems the lack of cooperation and trust that
nearly caused the collapse of the Knicks at midseason has sprung up
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to playing together, using each other, driving and
kicking, but we kind of left each other out to dry,'' Houston said
after the dispiriting Game 4. ``We forced each other to play some
one on one.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Sprewell lost the battle almost every time he
tried to post-up Chris Mullin or tried to score off the dribble. A
wagon wheel compared to the racing Sprewell, Mullin was thought to
be vulnerable. That was part of the reason coach Jeff Van Gundy
started Sprewell, wanting someone to go at Mullin. The problem was,
Mullin planted his body on Sprewell and shut him down in the
halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, Sprewell seemed so flustered on offense,
it carried over to his defense. Mullin, who was cutting to the
basket and moving well without the ball, slipped right under
Sprewell's nose for layups. In transition, Sprewell got caught once
allowing Mullin _ a longtime 3-point threat _ to pull up and nail
one while he watched from six feet away. When Mullin was not
reminding Sprewell of the crafty nature he had as his teammate at
Golden State, the gangly Jalen Rose was taking a turn driving on
Sprewell and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get Allan and Latrell going,'' Van Gundy said. ``We
have to get Latrell going defensively as well.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not a one-time lapse for Sprewell. He has struggled
throughout the series at small forward, unable to combat the
Pacers' size. He needs the fast break as a stage for his speed. Of
his 24 field goals in this series, at least 10 of them have been on
the rare occasion that he has been able to run out on the break.
</P>
<P>
   But everything is tied together. If the Knicks cannot rebound
without Patrick Ewing, there is no outlet pass. If the Knicks do
not defend with aggression, they end up taking the ball out of the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, Sprewell is left standing still, which is the
best way to dilute his impact. The Pacers saw how Miami and Atlanta
buckled under his speed. And they had a firsthand look in Game 1,
when the Knicks scored 22 points on the break. Since then, the
Pacers have resisted the urge to toss up 3-pointers _ which equal
long rebounds, and instant fast breaks _ and are sprinting back in
transition defense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Van Gundy indicated that he intended to keep Sprewell in
the starting lineup for Game 5 with the hope that he will awaken
along with his team. ``I know this is the way we have to go to have
a chance to win the series,'' Van Gundy said. ``We're going to
stick with that. No matter who we start, we have to guard and
rebound. We didn't get it done in the staring lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Sprewell were the main culprits. In Game 1, it was
Ewing who delivered the game-deciding free throws. In Game 3, it
was a gallant performance by the miracle worker, Larry Johnson, who
delivered a 4-point play to save the Knicks despite the absence of
the injured Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the series tied, who will come through? Houston has
done it before _ it was he who sent up a last-second runner that
licked the rim, kissed the backboard and fell into the net to give
the Knicks their memorable Game 5 victory against Miami. But there
have been too many games in this series when Houston has been a
wallflower on offense.
</P>
<P>
   While he deserves credit for tracing the whip-like moves of
Miller _ with some help from the Knicks' big men stepping out to
greet the Pacers' dangerous star _ Houston has had little left on
offense. His jumpers look as flat as sneaker soles, and his moves
to the basket have been languid at times. Not that he agrees with
this pattern of play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in slumps,'' said Houston, who has shot 20 for
60 in the series. ``I don't ever believe in missing a shot. It's
not frustrating at all. I'm out there having fun. You miss shots,
you miss shots.''
</P>
<P>
   He seems earnest when he says fatigue is not a factor. But it
takes energy to chase Miller, and then more muscle to hold off Rose
when he comes into the game. Houston allowed Rose to put his head
down and go right at him in Game 4. If Rose was not driving on
Houston, he was posting him up or darting outside for open jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Houston and Sprewell realize this is no time to revert back
to the dysfunction of the past. One or the other _ but preferably
both as far as the Knicks are concerned _ needs to rebound when
they can, get the stops that lead to the fast-break style they
thrive in and score in the face of fatigue and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't win another game if we can't find a way for Latrell
and Allan to be more efficient,'' Van Gundy said. ``That's how it
is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
