<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS OVERCOME THE WORRY HABIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Mark Jackson was perched on the scorer's table,
throwing his head back and laughing. Chris Mullin lounged a few
feet away, his arms draped over the back of a chair.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after their momentum-swinging victory in Game 4
against the New York Knicks, the Indiana Pacers had the body
language of people who had just spent the weekend at a spa: all
loose limbs and inner glow.
</P>
<P>
   Gone were the bleary eyes from the sleepless night that followed
the loss in Game 3. Missing were the incessant questions about when
Reggie Miller might show up.
</P>
<P>
   Miller still hasn't, although Indiana beat New York, 90-78, to
tie the series at 2-2. Miller scored 12 points Monday night _ he
was 0 for 3 and in foul trouble in the first half _ but even that
did not matter Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Any concerns about Miller _ and just about anything else _ were
sloughed off by coach Larry Bird and his players in the wake of
their best performance of the series.
</P>
<P>
   With Game 5 at Market Square Arena on Wednesday night and some
of the magic dust brushed off the Knicks, it is clear the Pacers
think they escaped disaster in the first three games and finally,
by playing the way they are capable of, seized control of this
series again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood shift is unbelievable,'' Rik Smits said. ``It worries
me. Before Game 4 you saw a lot of concentration. It was almost a
must-win situation. The attitude was different. Now the guys are a
little more relaxed. I think we're feeling confidence. We finally
had a better game than the first three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits didn't. He picked up two fouls in the first 30 seconds of
the game and played only 13 minutes. But his high spirits Tuesday
were indicative of the change in tone among the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Where there was dissonance Sunday _ with Bird challenging Miller
to grab the ball and the leadership role and Antonio Davis ruefully
ruminating on his foul that sprang Larry Johnson's 4-point miracle
to win Game 3 _ there was only sweet music Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers could afford to be magnanimous when asked whether
they thought putting Latrell Sprewell in the starting lineup was a
mistake. (If he had done well, Jackson said, Jeff Van Gundy would
have looked like a genius.)
</P>
<P>
   They were gracious when questioned about whether the
ineffectiveness of Sprewell and Allan Houston is because of bad
shooting or good defense. (It depends on whether you think Miller
is shooting poorly and being guarded well.)
</P>
<P>
   So swift was the transformation in the tone of this series that
the Pacers found themselves addressing how they would avoid
overconfidence now that they own the home-court advantage again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't relax at all,'' Miller said. ``If I'm New York, I'm
feeling pretty good about myself. Games 1 and 2, they played
particularly well here in our building and we didn't play too
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Bird, not one for mindless cheerleading, had trouble
with anything but plaudits, calling the Game 4 performance ``four
great quarters.'' Still worried about Miller, he was asked? ``He'll
break loose sooner or later,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   With their angst shed, the Pacers were renewed and refreshed.
The stress that preceded Game 4 has been replaced by a sense that
the Pacers' course to the finals has been righted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel danger,'' said Jalen Rose, who had 19 points and
6 rebounds in Game 4. ``I feel we've got control of the series.
It's for us to go out there and take. I want them to be confident,
to understand we've got a chance to play for the world
championship. We're right at the door with the foot there. All
we've got to do is kick it in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
