<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW SHOWDOWN ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of reason to be skeptical about House Speaker
Dennis Hastert pledge in May to support ``common-sense'' gun
control legislation in the House. After all, the Republican
leadership has tried every technique to gut or block gun control in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in a highly unusual parliamentary move, Hastert said he
would bypass the Judiciary Committee, where most Republicans are
hostile to gun control, and bring the legislation directly to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   If the speaker really means to carry out his pledge, he needs to
allow open debate and constructive amendments from both sides of
the aisle. Given a chance, the House could improve on the Senate
bill approved in May.
</P>
<P>
   To keep his pledge to instill a new bipartisan spirit, however,
Hastert has to break with the radical right, beholden to the
National Rifle Association, and permit moderate Republicans to join
the emerging congressional majority favoring gun control. He should
make each vote a matter of conscience and not have Tom DeLay or
other leadership henchmen threatening lawmakers if they vote
against the wishes of the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also have obligations. Their leader, Richard Gephardt,
has not always been enthusiastic about this issue. He is determined
to win back the House in the next election and fears that passing
stiff gun control laws might make it harder to win seats in the
South or rural areas. But he should realize that the Littleton
school massacre has changed the political climate and that there
are votes to be gained from leadership on gun control. This is no
time for Democrats to slacken their efforts to get the best
possible measure through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved by the Senate in May was already too modest,
but now the NRA wants to water down several provisions,
particularly the one requiring a three-day background check for
purchasers at gun shows. The bill to be introduced next week in the
House reflects their demand to reduce the check to 24 hours, too
little time to thoroughly peruse criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   The House should support the three-day check period, and reject
other efforts to weaken the bill. Lawmakers should also go beyond
the Senate and subject Internet gun sales to background checks, and
raise the age for the purchase of assault weapons and handguns from
18 to 21 years. The House must also be sure not to load the
legislation down with ``poison pill'' provisions designed to repel
Democratic votes, such as mandatory incarceration with adults for
some juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Hastert has let the right wing of his party call the
shots on campaign finance reform, the budget and Kosovo. But a
``new center'' for gun control has clearly emerged in Congress, and
it should be given a chance to pass legislation favored by the
overwhelming majority of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a margin of only 11 votes in the House. As many
as 30 Democrats are said to be nervous about being targeted by the
gun lobby and may not vote for tough legislation. But as many as 50
to 60 Republicans are probably ready to vote with the majority of
the Democrats. If Hastert lets this group have its say, the whole
country can benefit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
