<HEADER>
A8186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEW-DIGS-     06-08 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NEW-DIGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Corporate sponsors would fund most of new Falcons facility
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Corporate sponsors, with their names prominently
interwoven onto the Atlanta Falcons ``experience'' at Stone
Mountain Park, would build most of the new $10 million-plus
football training facility being proposed there, those involved
with the negotiations said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly the trend to make these training facilities
destination stops,'' said Archie Ellis, vice president of
Knoxville, Tenn.-based Partners and Associates, which two years ago
put together a $13.5 million training facility for the Cincinnati
Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons met Tuesday to iron out details with representatives
from Partners and Silver Dollar City, the Branson, Mo., firm that
manages Stone Mountain Park's attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who now train at a 20,000-square-foot facility in
Suwanee, Ga. in Gwinnett County, have signed a non-binding letter
of intent to build a 70,000-square-foot office complex and training
facility on 30 acres of an old airfield east of the mountain. But
team spokesman Aaron Salkin cautioned ``that this doesn't mean
everything is automatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials said Stone Mountain, with its 4 million annual
visitors, is heads above the six other sites where the Falcons have
looked. And if everything goes smoothly, park visitors could by
next summer take in Robert E. Lee as well as Falcon linebackers
hitting tackling dummies with the same $6 Stone Mountain parking
fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stone Mountain is Georgia's No. 1 attraction and is always
getting proposals _ golf courses, soccer villages, reproductions of
Stonehenge,'' laughed Curtis Branscome, chief executive of the
Stone Mountain Park Memorial Association, the governor-appointed
authority that oversees the park. ``This is a benefit to the park
because it's something additional for people to do there.''
</P>
<P>
   Branscome said the corporate sponsorships and naming rights
would enable Silver Dollar City to get loans to build the facility.
The Falcons would then lease the facility from the park.
</P>
<P>
   The extra patrons coming to Stone Mountain would increase
revenue for the park association, said Ned Stancliff, senior vice
president for Silver Dollar City. The contract between Silver
Dollar City and the park association specifies that 3 percent of
revenue raised beyond $9.6 million goes back to the park
association. Stancliff said the extra revenue would raise
additional sales tax for DeKalb County and the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, football training camps were built on
out-of-the-way pastures where players could shed off-season pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, instead of isolating themselves, you'll see more pro
teams building (facilities) onto other amenities,'' said Stancliff,
who used the terms ``unlimited potential'' and ``natural synergy''
while talking about the potential arrangement. He said the
arrangement would be not unlike the new Atlanta Braves spring
training facility at Disney World near Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Stancliff said the new facility probably would have bleachers
for fans to watch workouts, and he did not foresee ``any extra
charge'' other than the standard parking fee.
</P>
<P>
   There would be three training fields and an indoor training
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Other Falcons attractions, such as a hall of fame and a gift
shop, would be included.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Torpy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
