<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-OHIO-REAX-COX     06-08 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OHIO-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Theaters to card youths
 &HT;    (ATTENTION: OHIO EDITORS)
 &HT;    By Meggen Lindsay
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Theater owners Tuesday agreed to demand
identification from young people entering R-rated movies _ a move
that some Dayton-area teens called silly, while parents said the
action was worth trying.
</P>
<P>
   The move drew the applause of President Clinton, who has been
pressing the theater owners on the issue of violence in movies.
</P>
<P>
   Some local theater owners said they think the burden for keeping
kids out of movies they shouldn't see ought to be up to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my personal opinion that it is the parents'
responsibility, not my responsibility, as far as what their child
is or is not watching,'' said Phillip Chakeres, owner of Chakeres
Theatres in Kettering and Fairborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of stupid,'' said Dan Shisler, 18, of Huber
Heights. ``If you want to see a movie, you should be allowed to.
Teen-agers can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton argued that children see too much violence in popular
entertainment, and that the typical American will see 40,000
dramatized murders by the age of 18. ``They're subject to too much
violence through media and cultural contacts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about the multiplex is that there's a movie
for every member of the family,'' Clinton said. ``But not every
movie is for every member of the family. When you drop them off,
you shouldn't have to worry about your G-rated kids getting into
violent or suggestive R-rated movies.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``too often children do get past the ticket counter
unescorted and underage.'' He said that with Tuesday's
announcement, ``The theater owners are clearly drawing the line.''
</P>
<P>
   The president launched the plan with the leaders of the National
Association of Theatre Owners, whom he had challenged May 15 to
strengthen its movie-rating enforcement. The association, which
represents about 20,000 screens _ 65 percent of the motion picture
screens in the United States _ said it will begin requiring photo
IDs for teen-agers at R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's three-part plan also includes an educator outreach
program for parents about the rating system and support by theater
owners for a national study on the causes of violence.
</P>
<P>
   The president also challenged the movie industry to reevaluate
its PG-13 rating to determine if it allowed too much violence in
movies that young children may see without a parent. The
association also asked theater owners to post notices reflecting
the R-rated admissions policy.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with movie enforcement, the president repeated
his call on Congress to pass common-sense gun legislation, and
urged the video-game, recording, and movie industries not to market
violence to children.
</P>
<P>
   However, many Miami Valley teen-agers interviewed at the Dayton
Mall on Tuesday said the new rule is unnecessary, and would do
little to deter violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous that people think violence in movies causes
violence in teen-agers,'' said 17-year-old Susanna Letham of
Centerville. ``Life is not written in script.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dumb,'' said Jeff Nartker, 16, of West Carrollton. He
said teens ``will get in anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Letham said she thinks ratings are almost beside the point,
given the general scope of sex and violence in pop entertainment.
``If they cut it out (movies) would still still have the same
quality, and more people would come to see them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents, perhaps not surprisingly, had more mixed views.
</P>
<P>
   While John Stevens of Cincinnati said he believes Clinton has a
good idea, he was not optimistic about it decreasing teen-age
violence. ``I'm not a believer that (the entertainment industry)
causes violence. How parents bring their kids up determines how
they behave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with this enforcement totally,'' Carlisle resident
Betty Landsaw said. ``If our kids would not see so much stuff, they
wouldn't do so much stuff. It's a little late in the game to be
effective, but it's a start.''
</P>
<P>
   A Dayton mother of two teen-age girls agreed. ``It's worth a
try. Kids see too many things they don't need to see, as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people wondered how effectively theaters would be able to
enforce the new rule. Several teen-agers said they didn't expect to
have much trouble getting in to see movies they want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't work _ people at the places won't follow the rule
because they don't now,'' said Demetria Chambliss, 15, of Huber
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now more fake IDs will get made,'' said Adam Taylor, 25, of
Eaton.
</P>
<P>
   Barb Gells of Englewood was more optimistic. ``It is a good
idea, if the people at the movie theaters enforce it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most local theater managers declined comment. But Bill
Alexander, assistant manager of downtown Dayton's New Neon Movies,
said enforcement may be difficult, and will depend primarily on
who's working the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't think it will work. It's at the cashier's
discretion. If they look underage, we would card, just like for
alcohol and tobacco,'' he said. ``But there's no real way one could
enforce it unless ushers went through and checked every person.''
</P>
<P>
   Meggen Lindsay writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
