<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: US AIR MAKES PASSENGERS BOARD EARLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last-minute passengers on US Airways risk being left at the gate
as the carrier has begun to follow the industry standard of
requiring that they board planes at least 10 minutes before
scheduled departures. The reason, the airline said, is that
customers expect and deserve dependability, and on-time departures
are necessary for achieving that result.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry's on-time performance, meaning flights that
arrive within 15 minutes of schedule, has dropped from a high of
82.5 percent in 1991 to 77.2 percent last year, a drop that would
probably not surprise many passengers. The major reasons for the
fall, airlines say, are record numbers of passengers in recent
years, fuller planes and time-consuming security procedures at
check-in.
</P>
<P>
   Because delays typically ripple throughout the system, angering
passengers on late-arriving planes as well as passengers waiting to
connect to them, airlines _ which have been profitable the past few
years, after losing billions earlier in the decade _ have not
hesitated to play hardball with laggard passengers. Michael Boyd,
president of the Boyd Group, an aviation consulting company, said
that when he was in Chicago's O'Hare International Airport
recently, a gate agent announced: ``Ladies and gentlemen, we have
four people who have not gotten on the airplane. If you're not on
in one minute, you lose your seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Airline News
</P>
<P>
   Other major airlines followed the lead of United Airlines on
Tuesday after United, the nation's biggest carrier, reduced
off-peak fares as much as 25 percent for travel from June 22
through Sept. 30, and capped advance round-trip fares for peak
travel days at $498. Among the restrictions are that tickets must
be bought no later than June 18. Examples include a New
York-to-Chicago round trip for $238 with up to two companions
traveling for $138 each, and New York to London for $398. The sale
followed United's warning Friday that its second-quarter earnings
would fall short of forecasts because of higher costs and lighter-
than-expected traffic in May.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways is offering $338 round-trip fares bought on the
Internet for travel between Los Angeles and six Eastern cities _
Baltimore, Boston, New York (La Guardia Airport), Newark,
Philadelphia and Washington (Ronald Reagan National Airport and
Dulles International Airport). Tickets must be purchased by June 13
for travel from June 24 through Sept. 30. In both cases,
restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are all United States domestic flights smoke-free, so
are 97 percent of all flights between the United States and foreign
destinations, according to Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
Two days ago Slater said that All Nippon Airways, Japan Airlines,
Transero Airlines, Turkish Airlines and Varig Airlines had recently
eliminated smoking on all their flights, while Air India eliminated
smoking on all flights serving the United States and Alitalia
prohibited smoking on 80 percent of its trans-Atlantic flights.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the first nonstop flights between Miami and
Istanbul, Turkish Airlines is offering round-trip flights between
both cities for $599 through the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Update
</P>
<P>
   The latest hotel planning to rent all or part of its rooms over
this New Year's Eve is the adobe-style Hotel Loretto in downtown
Santa Fe, N.M. For $49,000, the Loretto is offering its
presidential suite plus four oversize rooms for three nights,
suitable for a party of 10.
</P>
<P>
   Guests can save 15 percent off Howard Johnson's regular rates
this entire year by paying for their stay with an American Express
credit card. The lodging chain is owed by Cendant.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms at all La Quinta Inns are on sale for $49 a night through
Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   After Motel 6's long-running ``We'll leave the light on for
you'' advertising campaign was recently chosen as one of the 100
best ad campaigns of the last century by Advertising Age magazine _
making it the only hotel company to make the list _ the hotel
chain's new television ads are using actors for the first time. Tom
Bodett, who has been the Motel 6 spokesman since 1986, will be
off-camera when he interviews the ``guests'' about when they first
``saw the light'' and began staying at Motel 6, owned by Accor.
</P>
<P>
   A Matter of Duty
</P>
<P>
   After duty-free shopping is abolished by the European Union on
July 1, Amsterdam's Schipol Airport and the shopkeepers of the
airport's duty-free shopping center will pay the value-added tax on
all items except alcohol and tobacco bought by passengers traveling
within the European Union. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
