<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HAPLESS AT PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's time for a change, Mo Vaughn says.
</P>
<P>
   What the Anaheim Angels hitters are doing these days isn't
working, so they need to make adjustments. Which sounds logical,
considering their only runs in a 6-2 loss to the San Francisco
Giants on Tuesday at 3Com Park were driven in by pitcher Steve
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks' two-out double in the fifth inning was his first
major-league hit.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks also pitched well, giving up three runs and eight hits in
61/3 innings, but the club's lack of offense made his effort almost
meaningless and put the pressure on the defense to be perfect.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 2-2, shortstop Andy Sheets couldn't come
up with a hard grounder by Armando Rios with two out in the seventh
inning. Though it was ruled a single, it was a play Sheets said he
should have made and led to three Giants runs and a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With the way they're hitting, a three-run deficit late in the
game is curtains for the Angels, who didn't have a hit after Todd
Greene's one-out single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The last-place Angels are 27-31 despite having the No. 2
pitching staff and No. 1 defense in the American League. The
offense, though, ranks 12th in batting average and runs scored. On
the current road trip (three games in L.A. and two in San
Francisco), the Angels are hitting .235.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like this,'' said Vaughn, who went 2 for 2 with a walk
before leaving the game in the sixth inning when his ankle
stiffened up. ``I'm not used to this. One of the things that this
team needs is it's got to find itself and iron things out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to shake things up with our mental approach in terms
of what we're trying to do, because that's what this game is all
about. It's mental. . . . It's not always about talent. It's how
you are mentally. If I'm making outs, I'm going to do something
different. I'm going to break my bat to stay inside the ball and
hit the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   What made the Angels' performance so bad Tuesday was it made
Giants pitcher Shawn Estes (3-4) look so good. Estes had been in
danger of losing his spot in the starting rotation until facing the
Angels. But he allowed only the two runs and five hits in seven
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Angels right fielder Tim Salmon has four or five weeks of rehab
on his sprained left wrist, but he had as many hits Tuesday as
Angels starters Randy Velarde, Reggie Williams, Garret Anderson,
Troy Glaus and Tim Unroe combined _ zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's having fun,'' Salmon said. ``I can guarantee that.
Everyone's trying hard, maybe too hard to get that hit. And that's
disabling in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins promised more changes in the lineup
for today's game, but unless the club is planning to trade for Ken
Griffey Jr., the lineup figures to have the same punchless players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to work with what he's got,'' Vaughn said of Collins.
``What are you going to do? There's nothing he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants jumped out to a 2-0 lead in the first inning off
Sparks, the inning keyed by Bill Mueller's double and a solo homer
by Jeff Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks tied the game with his two-run double in the fifth, but
the Angels fell behind in the seventh after Sparks was lifted with
one on and one out. Consecutive two-out singles by Rios and Stan
Javier (off Scott Schoeneweis) and Rich Aurilia (off Mark
Petkovsek) turned a 2-2 game into 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, every team I've been on, the offense gets in a
little funk sometimes,'' Sparks said. ``The pitching has the job to
pick up the slack, because there are going to be times later in the
season when they pick us up. As soon as we get on the same page,
we'll get on a roll.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
