<SLUG> BC-NYS-BUDGET-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY BUDGET RIFT WIDENS AS LEGISLATORS TRADE INSULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On a day when New York state's budget became the
third latest in history, the Capitol's power players reinforced
Tuesday how far they are from an accord, digging in their
positions, heading off in divergent directions and insulting one
another.
</P>
<P>
   With legislators despairing of a deal any time soon, the
Republican-controlled Senate passed its own, detailed version of
the budget Tuesday, a largely symbolic step usually taken in March,
not June.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-controlled Assembly has not gone even that far.
Tuesday, the Assembly began passing the pieces of the budget that
are relatively free of controversy, excluding disputed areas like
health care and education that account for more than half the
state's spending.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver reiterated his claim that Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno was trying to lure the Assembly into
passing the Senate's budget, only to have Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican, veto the Democrats' projects. ``All of this is just an
exercise in futility,'' Silver said. ``It's just a sham. It is the
Republican Party putting Senator Bruno and other Republicans in
line in order to stake out a political position.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno retorted: ``The speaker has a way of sort of getting
exasperated and frustrated and calling names. Shelly's got to go
back to kindergarten.'' As for the Assembly's passage of parts of a
budget, he said, ``He's playing a shell game with the budget, a
Shelly game, where you pass the easy parts and don't deal with the
hard parts.''
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point remains Silver's insistence that the governor
get involved in budget talks and promise not to engage in the kind
of wide-ranging line-item vetoes he made last year, when he
eliminated 1,300 items worth more than $1 billion, mostly inserted
by the Democrats, from the Legislature's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has refused to be drawn into the process, a position
unlike that of previous governors. But Tuesday, he appeared to give
a little. ``I'm willing to talk, and if the speaker needs certain
assurances on certain things, I'm willing to do that,'' he said.
But he refused to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, both houses are set to finish their business for the
year, and it would be all but impossible for them to agree on a
budget by then. It is unclear how they will proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the April 1 start of the fiscal year, the state has kept
running with a series of two-week emergency bills. Silver said his
budget, if adopted by the Senate, too, would eliminate the need to
return repeatedly over the summer to pass emergency bills.
Republicans, including the governor, have talked of a longer-term
emergency bill, perhaps of two to three months, an overt admission
that attempts to form a budget have utterly failed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest state budget was in 1997, 126 days overdue, when the
Assembly Democrats refused to negotiate until the state's rent
regulation laws had been renewed. The second tardiest was in 1996,
at 104 days late, when Pataki refused to enact a budget until the
Legislature agreed to changes in the state's workers' compensation
law to save employers money. On Wednesday, this year's budget will
be 70 days overdue, one day past the 1994 mark for futility.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has proposed a $72.7 billion budget. The Senate's plan
adds $1.1 billion in spending, though it says the net increase is
smaller, because the governor overestimated some expenses, and $1.2
billion a year in tax cuts. The Assembly's plan adds an estimated
$2 billion to $4 billion in spending over the governor's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
