u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-TRANSIT-NYT &LR;      06-08 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RICHARD SHELBY IS NO ROBIN HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the Memorial Day recess, Sen. Richard Shelby
started to pick the pockets of both California and New York state.
The Senate Appropriations Committee voted overwhelmingly to impose
the Alabama Republican senator's 12.5 percent ceiling on what any
one state can receive of the annual total of federal rapid-transit
aid. That would siphon off some $200 million to $300 million that
would ordinarily go to New York or California in fiscal 2000 and
redistribute it in equal shares to the other 48 states for mass
transit.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby seems eager to reopen a fight Congress settled last year.
After considerable haggling among rural states, populous ones and
regional blocs, Congress reached consensus on the formulas for
apportioning more than $200 billion in highway and transit aid over
the next several years. The formula for highway aid, which is where
most of the federal gas tax revenue goes, tilts toward awarding
many states as much in aid as they contribute in gas taxes. That
helps auto-dependent states.
</P>
<P>
   Standard aid formulas for mass transit, by contrast, rely on
ridership, passenger miles and rail service, much of which happens
to be concentrated in New York and California. New York State
carries a third of the nation's rail and bus riders. California
transports nearly 15 percent. Without these subways, commuter rail
lines, light rail systems and buses, major metropolitan areas in
both states would choke on highway congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby's Transit Equity Provision pretends to champion fairness
even as it steals money from overburdened transit systems and
distributes it to states that may not have matching funds or
projects ready to carry out. But ``fairness'' cuts many ways.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 1997, by one analysis, New York delivered $14.2
billion more in taxes to Washington than it received in aid, and
California delivered $11.8 billion more. Shelby's Alabama, on the
other hand, was the beneficiary of $6.9 billion more in aid than it
gave Washington in taxes. Is it ``fair'' to make these imbalances
even greater?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
