<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-RAYS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves outslug Rays 11-2
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget about the Tampa Bay Devil Rays and any cliches
that might apply to their five-game losing streak. The Braves are
finding new ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   And new people to do it.
</P>
<P>
   With Ryan Klesko at home with flu symptoms the past two days,
Gerald Williams has used Tampa Bay pitchers for his own personal
rampage. Ozzie Guillen got in on the act Tuesday as well. They had
four hits apiece to fuel Atlanta's offense in an 11-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   In two games, Williams is 6-for-8 with five RBIs and three runs,
Monday in the eighth spot and Tuesday at leadoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a leadoff hitter, what I was trying to do was have patience
and be more relaxed at the plate and it worked for me,'' said
Williams, who was 0-for-23 before Monday's game. ``(Guillen and I)
have been struggling a lot. Tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Guillen was 4 for 4, equalling the number of hits he had in his
first eight games replacing Walt Weiss in the starting lineup. He
raised his average from .141 to .183 in the process and scored
three runs in a game that ended with the announcement that Weiss
had been put on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I got four hits I think I was in Double-A,''
said Guillen, who actually now has 17 four-hit games in his big
league career. ``I got a couple lucky ones and that got me more
comfortable at the plate. I got way better at-bats today and that's
all I wanted today.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Odalis Perez, who won the game to move to 4-2, chipped
in with a sacrifice, scored a run and drove in two runs on a bloop
single to left, his second major league hit and second hit in his
last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Boone drove in his first run in 14 games to start it all
off in one of the best at-bats of the game, working a 2-2 Wilson
Alvarez pitch into center field for a 1-0 lead in the first inning,
one Atlanta would never lose.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Devil Rays, life is pretty bleak at the moment, no
matter how they slice it:
</P>
<P>
   1) They are now 0-5 in interleague play this season, 0-5 against
Atlanta all-time, and a season-worst 10 games under .500 at 24-34.
</P>
<P>
   2) The team which leads the major leagues with players sent to
the disabled list, added another one on Tuesday with Monday night's
starter Dave Eiland (back soreness). During Tuesday's game reliever
Mike Duvall left with a sore muscle in his side and Jose Canseco
left with stiffness in his back.
</P>
<P>
   3) They added two more errors - five now for the series - to
their AL worst total of 52 errors. Herbert Perry's throwing error
in the second inning fueled a four-run inning by Atlanta, which set
the tone for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
