<SLUG> BC-NY-INDIANS-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
26 ARRESTED IN DRUG SMUGGLING NETWORK USING MOHAWK RESERVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. REGIS MOHAWK RESERVATION _ Police managed to cripple but not
quite destroy the largest cocaine smuggling and selling operation
in northern New York state Tuesday in a series of rapid
early-morning raids, state and federal officials said. The raids
netted a few prize suspects, including a 24-year-old Mohawk Indian
man who, the officials said, ran the drug network from his home
here.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they were finished, shortly before 8 a.m., about 180
police officers from 13 state, U.S. Canadian, and local agencies,
including the St. Regis Mohawk Tribal Police Department, had
captured 26 suspects and charged them with possession and
conspiracy to sell cocaine and marijuana, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said 13 additional drug suspects, including a man
in a Massachusetts nursing home, were still at large late Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials described Tuesday's raids as the culmination of
a yearlong investigation into the network that controlled hundreds
of pounds of South American cocaine, worth millions of dollars,
that they said flowed over the border each week in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the most common route for this and other
contraband, including liquor, cigarettes and approximately 300
illegal immigrants, most of them Chinese, runs through the
14,000-acre St. Regis Mohawk Reservation, which reaches from the
northern edge of New York over the St. Lawrence River and into
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant step in dealing with the drug
trafficking problem'' in northern New York, Thomas Maroney, U.S.
attorney for the Northern District of New York, said in a telephone
interview from Albany on Tuesday afternoon. Maj. William Warburton,
commander of a State Police Troop in Ray Brook, 60 miles southeast
of the reservation, called Tuesday's action ``certainly the largest
drug investigation and arrests that we've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The raids were coordinated by the New York State Police, and
most of them were at the private homes of suspects, many of whom
live on or near the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials, who gathered in Ray Brook to announce the
arrests, were pleased that the raids were swift and without injury
but they stressed that the roots of the cocaine trade ran deep.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Schrader, the district attorney for Franklin County,
which abuts the reservation, expressed caution. ``I don't pretend
that we've wiped out drug activity in Franklin County,'' he said.
``We've made a major dent'' he said, but ``we definitely did not
get everybody out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hebert, a special agent with the Albany office of the
federal Drug Enforcement Administration, added, ``It's just a
matter of time before someone else picks up the ball again and runs
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrests started shortly after midnight, when undercover
agents' tried to buy cocaine from Jason Anderson, the man suspected
of running the drug network, State Police Capt. Peter Person said.
When the purchase broke down, Anderson went home in an extremely
agitated state, Person said, arousing fears that he might flee and
causing officers to decide arrest him as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the raids started as planned, at about 5 p.m., with
the arrest of another reservation resident, Peter Clute, 28, who
officials say helped Anderson bring cocaine into the United States,
mostly from South America and through Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the 26 people arrested, the police also confiscated
19 shotguns and handguns, Anderson's 1999 Cadillac and pickup
truck, $862 and a small amount of cocaine and marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Recent raids have seized far more cash and drugs. Canadian
authorities seized nearly 10 pounds of cocaine a month ago, and
last week the United States Border Patrol discovered about $330,000
in suspected drug money in a car driving down from Canada on
Interstate 87. Although the amounts of cash and drugs seized
Tuesday were negligible, the police were clearly happy to have put
Anderson behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawk tribe has an agreement with federal and state
officials that prohibits police from patrolling the miles of river
shoreline and dozens of islands and inlets inside Indian territory.
</P>
<P>
   That is the major reason why the reservation ``is one of the
most controversial pieces of real estate'' in northern New York as
U.S. Customs Agent Mike Bridgeman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Maroney noted that the reservation has been under scrutiny for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of attention to alcohol and tobacco smuggling
_ literally all the time there are aliens being smuggled through
Akwesasne,'' said Maroney, using the Mohawk name for the souther
half of the reservation, the part in the United States. ``Drug
trafficking is obviously one more of these areas of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The police lured Anderson and other suspects from Montreal to
the portion of the reservation that is in United States territory.
</P>
<P>
   On the reservation, few people even knew that heavily armed
officers in as many as 40 patrol cars and four-wheel-drive trucks
had even been there, blocking off roads and hauling away suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beautiful, let them do it,'' John Bigtree, whose trailer home
sits on a patch of grass beside St. Regis Road, said shortly after
7 a.m. when he heard about the raids. He said it was clear to him
that the reservation has become increasingly troubled with ``a lot
of marijuana, a lot of cocaine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to clean them out,'' Bigtree said, waving a large,
weathered hand across his chest. ``They're ruining our little
kids.'' Drugs, he added, ``are really dividing this reservation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
