<SLUG> BC-EDIT-THIRDWORLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HALF-MEASURES FOR POOR NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, June 9:
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund began
a program that was supposed to help the world's poorest nations
escape their debt traps. Dozens of nations spend up to 60 percent
of their budgets for interest on foreign debt that will never be
retired _ leaving little for the basic health care and education
needed to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But the debt reduction program has been too stingy. This month
the world's richest countries will decide how much to increase it.
The proposals offered fall far short of real relief.
</P>
<P>
   Debtor countries, mostly African, largely owe money that lenders
pushed on eager governments decades ago, in part to cover
commercial loans. The current relief program has several problems
that the wealthy nations, known as the G-7, say they want to fix at
their summit meeting in Cologne, Germany, on June 18. One is that
the standards for qualifying _ six years of adherence to an IMF
reform and austerity plan _ are so strict that only Uganda and
Bolivia have seen any reduction in their payments, and that has
been negligible. Another is that the IMF's austerity requirements
have forced countries to cut basic social services.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's limited plan, which will probably win support from
the other G-7 countries, would allow countries to qualify for debt
relief more quickly, focus the IMF on the importance of spending on
the poor, and allow several new countries to qualify. The
administration says a wider plan is unlikely to win over Congress
or other nations _ Japan and France are the biggest creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Congress may be more supportive than the administration thinks.
About 50 House members from across the spectrum back a plan
sponsored by Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, to provide deeper relief and
help insure that the money is better used. A Harvard economist,
Jeffrey Sachs, argues that the World Bank and IMF have the reserves
to forgive all they are owed by poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   Debt forgiveness must go to those who earn it through sound
economic policies and well-targeted social programs, but the
administration's proposal would allow only a handful of countries
to spend more on basic health and education needs. It is heartless
to argue that the United States or the IMF cannot afford to lift a
burden now borne by the children of Mali or Zambia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-08-99 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990608.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-08 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NY     06-08 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BLOW 5-RUN LEAD, LOSE TO PHILLIES, 11-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If the Yankees had won Tuesday night, they would
have looked at this game as a turning point in their season.
Remember that game when Hideki Irabu outpitched Curt Schilling,
they would say. Remember how we shuffled the lineup and everybody
relaxed and hit better, they would say.
</P>
<P>
   But now they will try to forget Tuesday night's game, in which
the Yankees blew a five-run lead and suffered a horrible, wrenching
defeat, 11-5, their third consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, could be seen muttering in
frustration in the dugout during the disastrous seventh inning,
when the Phillies scored nine runs, and who could blame him. There
was so much to gain on this night: Irabu had pitched well (two runs
in five and one-third innings), the Yankees had beaten on Schilling
for five runs in six innings with their former patient approach,
and for the third straight day, they could have edged past Boston
and into first place in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the evening ended with the Yankees' middle relief in
complete shambles and with New York once again on the verge of
being swept at Veterans Stadium. The Phillies took three straight
from the Yankees here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a lineup that Torre shuffled, Derek Jeter and Tino Martinez
slugged two-run home runs and the Yankees led, 5-0, going into the
bottom of the sixth inning. Irabu typically wilts in the sort of
scorching heat that hovered over this city Tuesday evening, and
when he allowed a pair of doubles in the sixth inning, Torre
relieved him with Ramiro Mendoza, probably figuring that it was
best to remove Irabu with his confidence soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza allowed another hit and a walk in the sixth, but still,
the Yankees held a 5-2 lead going into the seventh, and with the
closer Mariano Rivera ready for the ninth inning, they seemed to
have the game under control.
</P>
<P>
   But they were shattered in the seventh, which began with Jeter
fumbling a ground ball. Mendoza allowed a hit and then walked the
pinch-hitter Rob Ducey, who had been 0 for 12 coming off the bench.
Torre replaced Mendoza with Jason Grimsley, a right-hander coming
off a brutal outing Monday, when he walked five in one and
one-third innings and fired his final pitch to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley walked Doug Glanville to force home a run, and then
Marlon Anderson bounced a two-run single to center field, tying the
game. After Scott Rolen's sacrifice fly allowed Glanville to jog
home with the go-ahead run, Grimsley nearly threw another pitch to
the backstop. Grimsley was out and Dan Naulty was in.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley's recent disintegration is devastating to the Yankees.
The journeyman pitcher, who has a history of wildness, had been
dominant, and when Jeff Nelson suffered an elbow injury last week,
Torre spoke confidently of moving Grimsley into that role. In the
wake of two horrendous outings, Yankee officials must evaluate
whether Grimsley's failure was an aberration _ or whether his
success was.
</P>
<P>
   Naulty, who had pitched three innings over the previous two
games, allowed two singles, a walk and then hit a batter to force
home another run. The nine runs were the most allowed in an inning
by the Yankees since May 31, 1998, when they surrendered 11 to
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 32-24. Last year, they did not have their 24th
defeat until July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't had that extended period of time where we've
played really well,'' Paul O'Neill said before the game. ``Whether
we're flat, or whatever, I think it's official: We're not going to
do what we did last year, so let's get rid of that and go on from
there.
</P>
